<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Colombia-Elections, 2nd Ld,0317 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Successor of scandal-scarred president tied in presidential race quote and ADDS that Serpa resigned as interior minister last year. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with Sanin winning three largest cities, with Serpa
AP Photos BOG101-6
By FRANK BAJAK
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) _ Despite widespread disillusion with the
scandal-tainted administration in which he was a key player,
Horacio Serpa was headed Sunday for a runoff with a Conservative
Party challenger who painted himself the candidate of change.
	   With 97 percent or 10.6 million votes counted, Serpa of the
governing Liberal Party had 34.6 percent against 34.3 percent for
the Conservatives' Andres Pastrana, a former Bogota mayor in his
second straight run for the presidency.
	   Noemi Sanin, a former foreign minister who had hoped to break
the traditional parties' century-old monopoly on power, had 27
percent, official results showed.
	   Sanin's independent campaign had surged in recent days and she
won in Colombia's three biggest cities _ Bogota, Medellin and Cali,
splitting the protest vote amid a record voter turnout.
	   Both the Sanin and Pastrana candidacies were spurred by
rejection of the four-year presidency of Ernesto Samper, in which
Serpa was interior minister until stepping down last year to launch
his candidacy.
	   ``Today Colombians defeated indifference but, more than anything
else, we defeated business as usual,'' Pastrana told supporters.
	   But Serpa, a populist who appeals to the poor and billed himself
as the best chance for peace with leftist rebels, benefited from a
well-greased political machine that dominates Congress and has held
presidency for the past 12 years, trading patronage for voter
support.
	   ``The people are always wise,'' Serpa declared, promising that
peace would bring true change.
  ``The machinery, 8th graf pvs
</TEXT>
