r f     BC-Malaysia-Economy     06-01 0267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Finance minister: Bad stats won't change growth forecast 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Malaysia will not change its
projection of 2.5 percent growth for this year, despite new figures
that show the economy is in worse shape than previously thought,
the finance minister said Monday.
	   The Central Bank's announcement Saturday that Gross Domestic
Product shrank by 1.8 percent in the first quarter this year was
the worst sign yet of the country's economic problems, said Anwar
Ibrahim.
	   But Anwar said the news would not prompt the government to
change its forecast for this year, citing positive growth in April.
	   Malaysia's central bank, Bank Negara, is forecasting that
exports would grow, boosting the economy, even though regional
currencies have dropped dramatically in value since the onset of
the Asian financial crisis.
	   Anwar also said Malaysia would continue to allow market forces
determine interest rates. ``I have asked Bank Negara to give an
explanation on the interest rate policy today,'' he said.
	   He denied that there was a conflict between Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad and the central bank on the issue of interest
rates.
	   Over the weekend Mahathir had said the government was
considering lowering interest rates, currently at about 15 percent.
The central bank, however, was committed to maintaining rates that
were comparatively high by recent standards in Malaysia.
	   Mahathir and his closest economic adviser, Daim Zainuddin, have
both warned that a tough monetary policy could derail Malaysia's
recovery efforts.
</TEXT>
