r i     BC-Japan-Politics     06-01 0310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan's governing coalition breaks up four-year alliance 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photo TOK101
<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's three governing coalition parties
officially broke up their alliance Monday, bringing to an end four
years of legislative cooperation ahead of parliamentary elections
this summer.
	   Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, meeting with Takako Doi, head
of the Social Democratic Party, and Masayoshi Takemura, chairman of
New Party Sakigake, accepted the two parties' departure from the
ruling bloc.
	   The breakup, however, was seen as unlikely to have much impact
on Hashimoto's administration as his ruling Liberal Democratic
Party dominates Parliament's powerful lower house and should have
little trouble gaining support from other parties when needed.
	   ``Over the past year, the coalition was mainly driven at the
LDP's pace and that left it in bad shape,'' Takemura said.
	   The one-time finance minister also said that Sakigake will
remake itself as a party focusing on environmental issues as its
most important political issue.
	   Doi's party decided Saturday to end its alliance with the LDP,
citing disagreement with Hashimoto's party on two key issues,
including political ethics and Japan-U.S. defense ties.
	   Hashimoto said in a nationally televised interview Monday that
his party will continuously respect ``a history of working
together,'' indicating that the LDP will continue to seek
cooperation from the former partners on some issues.
	   The pro-business LDP has 261 seats in the powerful 500-member
lower house. But with 118 seats in the less powerful upper house it
still needs support from the 21-member Social Democratic Party and
three-member Sakigake to gain a majority in the 252-member body.
	   Half of the upper house seats will be at stake in elections
slated for sometime in July.
  (km)
</TEXT>
