w2233  wstm-
r i     BC-China-Dissidents     06-01 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Dissidents </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chinese dissidents call on public to pressure government 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Their previous attempts to seek government
redress having failed, Chinese dissidents have urged citizens
nationwide to press for democratic reforms, a rights group reported
Monday.
	   In a bold open letter, the former secretary to one of China's
leading reformers and 11 other democracy campaigners appealed to
the public's growing sense of rights and lingering outrage over the
military's bloody quelling of the Tiananmen Square democracy
demonstrations.
	   The ninth anniversary of the June 4, 1989, crackdown falls on
Thursday and police have stepped up detentions and surveillance of
dissidents to prevent any challenges to Communist Party rule. By
one Hong Kong-based monitoring group's count, police have arrested
or detained more than 20 dissidents to prevent public
commemorations.
	   Chinese leaders have refused to provide a full accounting of the
military's armed sweep through central Beijing. The death toll,
believed to number in the hundreds if not thousands, has never been
divulged.
	   In their open letter, the 12 democracy campaigners noted that
ordinary citizens and the families of victims have repeatedly asked
the government for a reassessment of the crackdown.
	   ``These legally reasonable appeals have never obtained a
well-intentioned response. To the contrary they have been met with
ceaseless suppression and some people who have issued appeals have
been sent to labor camps,'' said a copy of the open letter dated
Sunday and released Monday by New York-based Human Rights in China.
	   Chinese leaders' unwillingness to adopt democratic and legal
reforms have allowed official corruption _ a key concern of the
1989 student-led movement _ to worsen, the letter said.
	   ``This is an evil consequence produced by the suppression of the
`89 democratic movement and the obstruction of democratization,''
the letter said.
	   The dissidents called on the people to push Chinese leaders to
re-examine the 1989 crackdown, join ``the worldwide wave of
democracy,'' protect civil liberties and adopt legal reforms.
	   The appeal was led by Lin Mu, once the secretary to Communist
Party General Secretary Hu Yaobang. Hu was ousted by party elders
in 1987 for having failed to stop an earlier wave of student-led
protests.
	   His death in April 1989 sparked student demonstrations that
eventually brought more than a million people to Tiananmen Square. 	   
</TEXT>
