<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Pakistan-Nuclear, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Foreign minister again denounces nuclear tests 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: RECASTS; UPDATES with new denunciation of nuclear tests
<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ Australia does not accept that a
nuclear arms race is the way to solve the problems of South Asia,
Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said Monday.
	   Australia has called for a special session at the U.N.
Disarmament Conference in Geneva to discuss the detonation of 11
nuclear devices in India and Pakistan in the past few weeks, Downer
told Parliament.
	   The special session Tuesday will allow the international
community to express its abhorrence of nuclear testing and the
desire for India and Pakistan to join the global non-proliferation
regime, he said.
	   ``I met the Australian High Commissioner to Pakistan, Geoff
Allen, this morning and discussed the government's handling of the
serious security implications of Pakistan and India's actions,''
Downer said.
	   ``Australia has long accepted that South Asia presents
particular security challenges, but we resolutely do not accept
that a nuclear arms race is the way to address these challenges.
	   ``Once again Australia calls on India and Pakistan to
immediately sign and ratify the comprehensive nuclear ban treaty,''
Downer said. 	   
</TEXT>
