w2240  wstm-
r i     BC-Afghanistan-Quake 1stLd-Writethru   06-01 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-Quake, 1st Ld-Writethru,0735 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Aid supplies begin to reach quake-stricken area in Afghanistan site, more quotes from head of U.N. humanitarian office 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with international aid workers trying to get aid to
AP Photos LON108-109
By PHIL GOODWIN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   FAISABAD, Afghanistan (AP) _ Aircraft laden with emergency aid
flew Monday to northern Afghanistan to help the victims of a
weekend earthquake that buried as many as 3,000 people, many still
struggling from a temblor that struck the region three months
before.
	   The powerful magnitude-6.9 quake wiped out entire villages,
sliced mountains and triggered landslides. While initial estimates
are putting the death toll at 3,000, aid workers and local
officials in the area believe it could rise to 5,000. There are
thousands of people still missing and thousands more homeless.
	   ``This is a mountainous region and the force of the earthquake
sent houses crashing down the hillsides toward the valleys below,''
said Alfredo Witschi-Cestari, head of the U.N. humanitarian aid
office in neighboring Pakistan.
	   ``We saw a couple of villages that had been completely
flattened, but there were probably more,'' he said after visiting
the site on Sunday.
	   Cargo aircraft packed with emergency supplies in neighboring
Pakistan were expected to reach the region Monday, aid workers
said.
	   Tons of food, blankets, tents and plastic sheeting were to be
loaded onto cargo helicopters Monday in the Pakistani capital of
Islamabad and were to be sent to the mountain capital of Faisabad.
From there, the supplies will be forwarded to the areas that
suffered the greatest damage.
	   When Saturday's quake hit, many of the people affected were
living in tents, not having had the time, money or materials to
rebuild their homes that were destroyed in February's earthquake.
	   Among those killed were 140 school children in Rostaq, the site
of a Feb. 4 earthquake that killed as many as 2,300 people and left
another 8,000 homeless.
	   Witschi-Cestari said this quake was more devastating. While the
first struck a region with about 30,000 people, the second hit a
hilly, rugged area that is home to about twice that population.
	   The area's sun-baked mud homes, already weakened by the February
temblor, crumbled like dry dust in Saturday's violent shaking. The
homes had been made more vulnerable by the relentless rain that
battered the region in recent days.
	   ``We need help desperately. Thousands of people are dead,'' a
spokesman for a northern alliance fighting Afghanistan's Taliban
government said from the stricken area, near the border with
Tajikistan.
	   Opposition soldiers already had recovered 1,650 bodies, Shamshul
Haq Arianfar said.
	   Witschi-Cestari's helicopter swooped in low over several
villages Sunday, opening a view onto horrific scenes. Hundreds of
homes were shattered and completely flattened. U.N. officials said
4,100 houses were destroyed.
	   U.N. officials flew over some of the most desolate and
hardest-hit regions Sunday, setting down briefly near the quake's
epicenter in Shari Basurkh, about 50 kilometers (30 miles) from
Faisabad, capital of the Badakhshan province.
	   They delivered tents and plastic sheeting as well as materials
for an emergency clinic to be set up in Shari Basurkh for the many
wounded.
	   Aid organization officials in neighboring Tajikistan were told
by the Afghan ambassador that 5,000 people were killed. The Red
Cross said it was not able to confirm the figure.
	   According to the report, the dead included 3,000 killed in Shari
Basurkh, almost 1,900 in a settlement on the outskirts of Faisabad,
the 140 children in Rostaq and 124 people in Chaib, on the
Tajikistan border.
	   Arianfar, spokesman of the anti-Taliban alliance, described
images of utter devastation. Eight villages simply disintegrated,
he said in the town of Chaib.
	   The French Foreign Ministry plans to send on 35 tons of
humanitarian aid to Duchambe, Tajikistan, where it will be
transported to the disaster area by a non-governmental
organization.
	   The International Red Cross got one plane into Faisabad on
Sunday and was preparing to set up a clinic in the area.
	   The United Nations still has about dlrs 1.2 million in its
emergency fund left over from a massive response to the appeal
after February's earthquake.
</TEXT>
