w2241  wstm-
r i     BC-India-Budget     06-01 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Budget,0409 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
India's government faces budgetary woes 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ India's business press fretted Monday
over how the government's new budget would cope with anti-nuclear
sanctions, a widening deficit, rising inflation and a failing
rupee.
	   Finance Minister Yashwant Sinha was to present the budget to
Parliament in a speech Monday evening.
	   His government has promised to revive India's economic growth,
which faltered to 5 percent in the fiscal year 1997-98, the lowest
rate in the last five years. To do that, experts say, Sinha will
have to spend on infrastructure and encourage investment. His
revenue options have been reduced since the United States,
Australia, Japan and other nations cut off loans and all but
humanitarian aid to punish India for conducting five nuclear tests
May 11-13.
	   ``Investors are likely to think twice before they commit their
hard-earned money here,'' The Economic Times said in an editorial
Monday.
	   The Financial Express, saying Sinha's budget was shadowed by
``nuclear clouds,'' speculated he would hike taxes and speed up the
sale to private investors of state-owned industry to raise funds _
some of which might be spent on a bigger defense allotment ``in
wake of the deteriorating security environment in the region.''
	   The Bharatiya Janata Party-led government's first budget ``comes
at a time when the country is reeling under a prolonged low growth
phase and has to stand up to international criticism,'' said The
Business Standard.
	   The government's pre-budget economic assessment, presented to
Parliament last week, was bleak. In addition to the falling growth,
it said the deficit rose to 6.1 percent of gross domestic product,
the total value of goods and services produced by the economy,
exceeding the target of 4.5 percent.
	   A 6.35 percent inflation rate was reported Sunday, up from 5
percent during 1997-1998.
	   The full impact of the nuclear sanctions was not yet clear, but
they were already having a chilling effect.
	   The rupee slid last week when Standard and Poor's financial
rating agency revised its India rating outlook to negative from
stable. A few days later, the World Bank postponed consideration of
more than dlrs 800 million in development loans to India because of
its nuclear tests, prompting a further slide in the rupee.
	   The rupee opened Monday at 41.74 to the U.S. dollar; it was
39.73 at the beginning of May.
</TEXT>
