<HEADER>
w2244  wstm-
u i     BC-Malaysia-Nuclear     06-01 0323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Nuclear </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Malaysia criticizes nuclear adventurism in Asia 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ With three nuclear powers now in
the region, Asian nations must halt moves toward nuclear
adventurism, Malaysia's deputy prime minister said Monday.
	   ``We must oppose opportunistic politicians who fan the flames of
jingoism, be it in the name of religion or state,'' Anwar Ibrahim
said in an speech at a regional meeting on confidence building and
conflict reduction.
	   Anwar's comments reflected the growing concern over Indian and
Pakistani nuclear tests among Asian nations that do not have huge
armies or nuclear programs.
	   Malaysia has opposed the tests and urged India and Pakistan to
refrain from entering into a regional nuclear arms race. India
conducted five nuclear tests last month and Pakistan, its archenemy
to the West, last week replied with five tests of its own.
	   ``We must constantly remind ourselves that in any conflict it is
always the people, not the state, who pay the price,'' he was
quoted as saying by the national news agency, Bernama.
	   Anwar said although Asia had three nuclear powers now, the
region that is home to half of the world's population remained
mired in poverty and destitution.
	   Diplomacy in Asia must go beyond conventional confidence
building measures to finding remedies to remove suspicion and
distrust and heal the wounds of history, he said.
	   ``Confidence building has not worked precisely because we have
not probed into the roots of suspicions and distrust between
states,'' Anwar said.
	   Asia's economic crisis was in part a result of a mismatch
between the old-fashioned national systems and the global system in
an information age, he said.
	   Asian minds were still trapped in the second industrial
revolution which was the age of automobiles and airplanes, he said.
	   ``Thus, we have become T-Rex, trying to live beyond the Jurassic
Age.'' 	   
</TEXT>
