w2249  wstm-
r i     BC-Japan-FoodProduction     06-01 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Food Production </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Reports: Japan to abandon food self-sufficiency target 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The government has decided not to set a food
self-sufficiency target when it revises agricultural guidelines
next year, despite fears of overdependence on imports, news reports
said Monday.
	   Japan produces only 42 percent of the food it consumes, down
from 52 percent self-sufficiency in 1985 and 79 percent in 1960.
The country is self-sufficient in rice, however, its traditional
staple.
	   The decline has sparked fears that dependence on imports could
make Japan vulnerable to food shortages if bad weather, war or
blockage of trade lines should cut off supplies.
	   But the changing Japanese diet has made it difficult for
officials to impose restrictions on agricultural imports or compel
consumers to eat domestically grown produce, the Mainichi newpaper
reported, citing Agriculture Ministry sources. Per capita rice
consumption is dropping.
	   Japan is also under pressure from trading partners to dismantle
government subsidies for agriculture, which critics say inflate
food prices and keep cheaper foreign products out.
	   The ministry is planning to revise the basic guidelines for
agricultural policy next year for the first time since 1961, and
there has been speculation that it would impose a self-sufficiency
target.
	   Shirara Shiokawa, of the Agriculture Ministry's planning
division, said the government does not have a target in place now
and has not decided whether to implement one.
	   However, he said a government forecast shows food
self-sufficiency rising over the next few years to reach between 44
percent and 46 percent by 2005.
	   In a bid to fend off overseas pressure on Japan to further open
its agricultural market, the government may set an item-by-item
target for self-sufficiency in staple foods, such as rice and
wheat, instead of an overall food target, Kyodo News quoted
government sources as saying.
	   Kyodo News reported Monday that the government also plans to
lift a ban preventing companies under stock ownership from
acquiring farmland, in a bid to make farming corporations more
competitive through stock ownership. 	   
</TEXT>
