<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Olympics-1956 Film-Legal Battle </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Court battle begins over 1956 Olympic footage 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ A battle over the rights to footage of
the 1956 Melbourne Olympic Games started in the Federal Court on
Monday.
	   Australia's Olympic Committee (AOC) and American sports film
company The Big Fights Inc. are arguing over the footage, which
features the opening ceremony and finals of all major events.
	   United States cable television giant, ESPN, was also has been
named as a respondent in the case, with the AOC claiming The Big
Fights had on-sold the copyright to the cable network.
	   Produced by the late documentary film producer Peter Whitchurch
as head of the 1956 Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games
(OCOG) film unit, the footage is being held in court-ordered safe
storage until the dispute is resolved.
	   The court was told Whitchurch had been hired by OCOG to produce
three films totaling more than 10 hours.
	   It heard that between 1992 and 1996, Whitchurch's daughters
Lynette June Benson and Diane Yvonne Talbot entered into agreements
with The Big Fights, effectively selling copyright of the films for
Australian dlrs 10,000 (U.S. dlrs 6,200).
	   The AOC alleged that ESPN had bought the rights to the Olympic
footage from The Big Fights.
	   AOC attorney Anthony Bannon told Justice Kevin Lindgren that
Whitchurch was an employee of the OCOG and, subject to a granting
of residual rights to the films to him in 1960, ``the physical film
was the property of OCOG''.
	   ``Clearly the work was done by employees of OCOG,'' Bannon said.
``At the very least OCOG was a co-owner. We seek a declaration that
we (the AOC) own the copyright.''
	   The hearing is scheduled for five days.
  (tjh)
</TEXT>
