<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Student Protest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Student protests against local officials erupting across Indonesia 
</HEADLINE>
With BC-Indonesia
Eds: Many Indonesians use one name
By ANDY JATMIKO
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   UJUNGPANDANG, Indonesia (AP) _ More than 800 students demanding
the resignation of a provincial governor on Sulawesi island faced
off Monday with 200 members of a Muslim youth group who support
him.
	   Despite relative calm in the capital of Jakarta, demonstrations
targeting allegedly corrupt local leaders continued to erupt across
Indonesia in recent days.
	   Student protests helped force then President Suharto to step
down after 32 years of iron-fisted rule on May 21. But governors
and other local administrators appointed by Suharto are still in
place.
	   Soldiers and police quickly positioned themselves between the
opposing groups in South Sulawesi province. The demonstrators lined
up about ten paces apart and traded shouts and epithets on the
grounds of the local legislature buildings in the provincial
capital of Ujungpandang.
	   Monday was the fourth day the students had occupied the
buildings. They have vowed not to leave until Gov. Palaguna, whom
they accuse of corruption and nepotism, steps down.
	   The students carried banners calling for reform. Their
opponents, members of the youth wing of Indonesia's largest Muslim
organization, Nadhlatul Ulama, wore green camouflage t-shirts and
held posters saying ``Reform Is Already Underway.''
	   The Indonesian capital of Jakarta has remained generally quiet
since May 22 when soldiers evicted 2,000 students from Parliament
without bloodshed.
	   After helping to force Suharto's ouster, the students demanded
the resignation of new President B.J. Habibie. The president has
called for elections in 1999 and many of Indonesia's 202 million
people appear willing to grant him a grace period as long as he
follows through on political and economic reforms he has pledged.
	   However, protests against local leaders have been breaking out
like brush fires in several cities across the archipelago during
the past week.
	   Several hundred students have taken over the local legislature
in the eastern Javanese city of Surabaya demanding the local
governor resign.
	   The Jakarta Post reported Monday that nine soldiers have been
disciplined with two weeks of detention for using excessive force
in dealing with the students.
	   More than a hundred students have also entered their fifth day
occupying the local legislature in the city of Jambi in central
Sumatra, the official Antara news agency reported Monday.
	   The students, from the Sultan Thaha Saifuddin Institute for
Islamic studies, have accused local officials of allowing gambling
to flourish in the district, and say they won't leave until all
slot machines are burned down.
	   Last week, a riot broke out in the northern Sumatran city of
Tanjungbalai, when the local governor walked out of a meeting with
demonstrators who accused him of corruption and insisted he usher
in reforms.
	   At least 20 people were arrested and dozens of shops, homes and
automobiles burned in the ensuing violence. 	   
</TEXT>
