w2266  wstm-
r u     BC-WorldNewspaperAssocia     06-01 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-World Newspaper Association </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Vietnamese journalist awarded for devotion to free press 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   KOBE, Japan (AP) _ Vietnamese journalist Doan Viet Hoat,
currently in prison for publishing pro-democracy newsletters, was
awarded Monday the 1998 Golden Pen of Freedom for his commitment to
a free press.
	   The award, given by the World Association of Newspapers at its
51st annual meeting, held in this western Japan city, was accepted
by Hoat's wife, Tran Thi Thuc.
	   Hoat, currently serving a 15-year jail term for his writings
published in the pro-democracy newsletter Dien Dan Tu Do, or
Freedom Forum, has spent much of the past three decades in
re-education camps and prisons for calling for greater civil rights
and democratic reform in Vietnam.
	   He continues to call for the changes from his prison cell.
	   ``All that Doan Viet Hoat did was to write several articles
calling for freedom of expression, freedom of speech, freedom to
think for oneself, and freedom to exercise one's basic human
rights,'' Thuc said.
	   Hoat was first arrested in 1976 when he was a professor of
English literature. He was accused of being a ``Lackey of American
imperialism'' for calling for greater civil liberties in postwar
Vietnam. He spent 12 years in re-education camps, without trial.
	   Hoat then created a small underground magazine. He was arrested
again in 1990, imprisoned for 28 months without charge, then
sentenced to a 20-year term for publishing ``anti-communist''
articles. The prison term was later reduced to 15 years.
	   Also Monday, the first day of the associations's three-day
congress, participants agreed that industrialized nations and
international aid agencies should provide greater support to
independent newspapers in developing countries, where a free press
is crucial for sustainable development.
	   ``There simply is no real and durable development without
transparency and a free flow of information,'' association
president Jayme Sirotsky said.
	   The World Association of Newspapers represents 15,000 newspapers
around the world. The meeting was being co-sponsored by the Japan
Newspaper Publishers and Editors Association.
  (may)
</TEXT>
