w2271  wstm-
r i     BC-Asia-Communications     06-01 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asia-Communications </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV, telephone, computer developments in Asia discussed 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ While the latest telephone, computer and
broadcast gadgets and systems went on display Monday at a huge
exhibition, Asian telecommunications ministers talked about
regulation and privatization of the new technologies.
	   ``Governments are very concerned about what it means to be
giving away to the private sector ownership and management of
broadcasting,'' said Derek Nicholas, a consultant for the
CommunicASia/NetworkAsia conference. ``This may well act as a
retarding effect on using all this super technology we've seen.''
	   Nicholas spoke at the opening press conference of the conference
and exhibition which covers 22,490 square meters over two sites and
is Singapore's second largest trade fair.
	   Displays at the booths for NetworkAsia, CommunicAsia,
BroadcastAsia, CableSat98 and MobileCommAsia show how the different
communications sectors are increasingly interrelated. The
exhibition, in its 12th year, is attended by 1,800 companies from
46 countries.
	   For the first time at a international trade fair, the three
different high definition television systems, developed separately
by the United States, Japan and Europe, are on display at the same
show, said Stephen Tan, managing director of Singapore Exhibition
Services.
	   ``Many countries, including Singapore, are in the process of
deciding which (of the HDTV systems) to adopt,'' Tan said. Japan
and Australia have said they will put HDTV into operation for
national broadcasting by 2000-2001.
	   In conjunction with the trade fair, 11 ministers from countries
of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation group are gathering to
discuss liberalizing the telecommunications business across borders
and oceans. On the agenda for the Pacific Rim is a decision to
simplify certification of communications equipment to allow foreign
manufacturers greater access in the region, Japanese officials said
ahead of the meeting.
	   Currently, communications equipment such as cellular phones,
modems, and fax machines must meet technological standards and be
certified in each of the countries in which they will be used, said
an official in charge of electronics equipment at the Ministry of
International Trade and Industry in Tokyo.
	   If approved, the new system would allow manufacturers to have
their equipment certified by agencies in their own countries, which
would lower costs and boost efficiency.
	   The United States and the European Union already have a similar
agreement. 	   
</TEXT>
