r i     BC-Colombia-Elections 3rdLd-Writethru   06-01 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Colombia-Elections, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0504 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Protege of scandal-plagued president heads for runoff with rival 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: RECASTS and UPDATES with 98 percent of votes counted.
AP Photos BOG118-120,122
By STEVEN GUTKIN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) _ A protege of President Ernesto Samper
narrowly won the first round in Colombian's presidential race, but
his ties to the scandal-plagued leader could lead to defeat in the
runoff.
	   With 98 percent of the vote counted in Sunday's presidential
race, Horacio Serpa of the governing Liberal Party had 34.6 percent
to 34.3 percent for Andres Pastrana, a former Bogota mayor.
	   Both Serpa and his Conservative Party rival will compete in the
June 21 runoff for millions of votes cast for an independent
candidate who sought to break the traditional parties' century-old
monopoly on power.
	   Independent Noemi Sanin, a former foreign minister, won 27
percent of the vote. Sanin's campaign took off in recent days, and
she won by large margins Sunday in Colombia's three biggest cities:
Bogota, Medellin and Cali.
	   During victory speeches, both winning candidates tried to court
her supporters.
	   ``Nobody ever fails when they follow their ideals,'' Serpa said
of Sanin's failure to make the runoff.
	   Serpa, interior minister until last year, appears to have
benefited from a well-greased political machine. He also sought to
distance himself from Samper, who many blame for Colombia's
tarnished international image and economic malaise.
	   ``They tried to paint him (Serpa) as an accomplice to drug
trafficking,'' said Rosa Sierra, one of thousands of Serpa
supporters who celebrated at a Bogota hotel Sunday night.
	   Ties with the United States were badly strained over the
acceptance by Samper's 1994 campaign of dlrs 6 million from the
Cali drug cartel. Washington stripped Samper of his visa and U.S.
officials have privately called Serpa a criminal for allegedly
covering up the scandal
	   Nevertheless, Serpa will seek ``harmonious relations with the
United States'' if he becomes president, campaign adviser Carlos
Ossa told The Associated Press.
	   ``They (the United States) think that Serpa is an extension of
Samper, but he is not,'' the adviser said.
	   Whoever wins will inherit a country in political and economic
crisis.
	   Leftist rebels have filled a power vacuum left by a weakened
government, dominating huge swaths of territory. Inflation and
unemployment have risen sharply. The flow of illicit drugs out of
Colombia has remained steady.
	   Pastrana narrowly lost to Samper in 1994.
	   In this year's unpredictable race, Colombians voted in record
numbers. Turnout was roughly double the votes cast in the first
round of the 1994 elections.
	   At least 11 people were killed Sunday in a sabotage campaign by
guerrillas. At least 21 election officials were abducted over the
weekend.
	   Attacks and ballot-burning by rebels forced the cancellation of
voting in at least 63 towns and villages.
</TEXT>
