<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar rises, stocks plunge in Tokyo trading prices 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with closing Nikkei, mid-afternoon dollar and bond
<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Tokyo share prices finished sharply lower Monday
amid renewed worries about the health of Japan's economy. The U.S.
dollar rose against the yen.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 349.75 points,
or 2.23 percent, to close at 15,321.03 points. On Friday, the index
had lost 125.77 points, or 0.80 percent.
	   Traders said selling of blue chips by overseas investors pushed
the Nikkei average sharply lower. Domestic institutional investors
later joined in the selling.
	   Hurting sentiment were recent signs that Japan's economic woes
have deepened. On Friday, the government said Japan's unemployment
rate hit a record 4.1 percent, up from 3.9 percent in March.
	   On Monday, the Japan Automobile Dealers' Association said sales
of new cars, trucks and buses fell in May from a year earlier for
the 14th consecutive month as the sluggish domestic economy
continued to keep consumers from dealer showrooms.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was down 24.79 points, or 2.03 percent, to 1,196.70.
The TOPIX fell 2.24 points, or 0.18 percent on Friday.
	   In mid-afternoon trading, the dollar bought 139.14 yen, up 0.42
yen from late Friday in Tokyo and also above its late New York
level of 138.90 yen Friday.
	   The slide on the Tokyo Stock Exchange pushed the dollar through
the 139.00 yen level, traders said.
	   ``The weak stock and bond market is making it that much easier
to buy the dollar and break through resistance,'' said Eji Takane,
deputy general manager of foreign exchange at Asahi Bank.
	   Japanese investors and interbank players bought the U.S.
currency against the yen, lifting the dollar's value.
	   Uncertainty in South Asia following Pakistan's sixth nuclear
test Saturday along with the weakness in the Japanese economy
continued to draw investors to the dollar.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond fell to a record of 1.165 percent from Friday's
finish of 1.205 percent, driving its price higher to 112.33 yen
from 112.04 yen.
	   The yield on the benchmark bond touched a record low of 1.190
percent on Friday.
  (km-dj) 	   
</TEXT>
