<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Pittsburgh Seniors,0448 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nelson Easy Winner in Pittsburgh Senior Classic 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BELL ACRES, Pennsylvania (AP) _ Even after consecutive
record-tying rounds of 65, Larry Nelson was worried.
	   ``It was a little more difficult than I thought it would be,''
Nelson said after a 2-over-par 74 on Sunday, giving him a
five-stroke victory in the Pittsburgh Senior Classic with a 204
total.
	   ``It was kind of an uneventful day,'' Nelson said. ``I just
wanted to not embarrass myself.''
	   It helped that Nelson blistered the tournament with consecutive
65s over the Sewickley Heights Golf Club.
	   Following an opening-hole bogey on Friday, Nelson played 40
straight bogey-free holes, finally running into trouble Sunday at
the par-4, No. 6 as the wind gusted to 35 mph (56 kph) and his
red-hot putter began to cool. His second shot landed on the green
about 25 feet (7.5 meters) from the hole, but Nelson three-putted.
	   Nelson also bogeyed back-to-back holes on the back nine, but
followed those with a 15-foot (4.6-meter) birdie putt at the par-5
No. 15. He played even-par the rest of the way, never letting
runnerup Bob Duval get closer than the final five-stroke margin of
victory.
	   ``It was a pretty good tournament, except for one person,'' said
Duval, who was followed by Jay Sigel at 72-210 and Al Geiberger,
who was another stroke back after a 72. Seven other players were
tied at 212, including Gary Player and Ray Floyd.
	   The tournament was never close, thanks to Nelson's blazing start
on Friday and Saturday, twice tying the course record that stood
unmatched since 1977. When Nelson finished the front nine on
Sunday, he still led by eight strokes.
	   ``He could have stumbled into the clubhouse and he still would
have won,'' said Duval, who finished second in the Pittsburgh
Senior Classic for the second straight year. Last year, Duval lost
to Hugh Baiocchi in a playoff.
	   Nelson, who joined the Senior Tour last September, won for the
second time, matching the wire-to-wire victory he posted at the
American Express Invitational in Sarasota, Florida, in February. He
has now finished in the top 10 in 10 of the 16 Senior Tour events
he has played. The first-place check for dlrs 165,000 was the
second-largest Nelson has collected in his career, and it pushed
him over the dlrs 1 million mark for Senior Tour earnings.
	   Nelson also scored his second professional win at a Pittsburgh
area course. One of Nelson's most memorable days as a golfer came
nearby, at Oakmont Country Club, where his 62-foot (19-meter)
birdie putt at the 16th hole sealed his dramatic 1-stroke win over
Tom Watson in the 1983 U.S. Open.
</TEXT>
