<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Finance Chief: Recession unlikely this year drop, further quotes 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with union chief predicting record layoffs, market
By JONATHAN DRAKE
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Singapore's economy is unlikely to slip into a
recession this year despite a trend toward negative growth in
Southeast Asia, Finance Minister Richard Hu told Parliament on
Monday, but the market was unconvinced.
	   Meanwhile, the government minister who heads the national trade
unions said layoffs this year would exceed the 20,000 who lost
their jobs during the 1985-86 recessions.
	   ``The overall picture of the Singapore economy is one of
uncertainty,'' Hu told Parliament. But he stood by an earlier
government forecast of 2.5 percent to 4.5 percent in economic
growth this year.
	   Some private analysts and economists have begun predicting
Singapore's economy would contract this year with a GDP of no more
than 1.5 percent. Three major international investment houses have
predicted recession.
	   Singapore's already bearish market fell on recession jitters,
with property stocks fueling the sell-off after the government said
it would do nothing drastic to stimulate construction or cushion
the tax and interest bite for those with undeveloped land and
untenanted units.
	   The benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index fell 1.3 percent
by midday.
	   ``Because we do a lot of trade with our neighbors, demand drops,
and I think if the second half of this year is worse, some
companies will have to trim costs by cutting down the work force,''
said Lim Boon Heng, who is secretary-general of the National Trade
Unions Congress and also a minister without portfolio in the
government. He said the number of layoffs could exceed the 20,000
record.
	   Finance Minister Hu said off-budget measures to stimulate the
economy would be decided on in late June or July.
	   ``As the Singapore economy is fairly well diversified, we are
unlikely to slip into negative growth this year as our growth will
be supported by the relatively healthy performance in the U.S. and
(European Union) economies,'' Hu said.
	   But Hu indicated that downward growth might necessitate special
economic measures ``sooner rather than later.''
	   ``We will not wait for GDP growth to go negative before we do
something,'' he said. ``If the trend is clearly going to head in
that direction we will try to do something.''
	   Hu said that by mid-June the government would have a clear
picture of second-quarter economic developments and could react
with tax cuts or rebates.
	   The finance minister also said trade figures in the second
quarter would show a 6 percent year-on-year decline.
	   Meanwhile, Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong said that
Singapore is still offering up to dlrs 5 billion in financing of
Indonesian trade through Singapore, despite the abrupt change in
government in Jakarta.
	   Lee told Parliament that the money, which is supplemental to a
rescue plan put together by the International Monetary Fund,
wouldn't be released until IMF funding is reinstated. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Singapore-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:f; 
