<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup-Gascoigne Out, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gascoigne's erratic play on and off pitch costs him World Cup spot conference beginning at 1130 GMT 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: ADDS Steven quote; WILL be updated after Hoddle news
<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Paul Gascoigne's socializing, erratic play on and
off the soccer field, and lack of fitness finally caught up with
him.
	   In one of the biggest World Cup-related stories in the country
since 1966 _ when England won its lone World Cup _ the 31-year-old
Gascoigne was left of this year's World Cup team named Sunday by
coach Glenn Hoddle.
	   As well as Gascoigne, Hoddle also dropped five other players _
Tottenham goalkeeper Ian Walker, Manchester United's Phil Neville
and Nicky Butt, Coventry's Dion Dublin and Everton's Andy
Hinchcliffe _ to get down to the final 22-man team.
	   Gascoigne, a key figure when England reached the World Cup
semifinals in 1990 in Italy, returned to England after the shock
announcement at the La Manga resort in southeastern Spain where the
team is training prior to the World Cup, which opens June 10 in
Paris.
	   ``I can't believe this has happened. This is the worst thing
that has ever happened to me,'' The Sun newspaper quoted Gascoigne
as saying.
	   The Sun said Gascoigne _ rated as one of the country's best-ever
at midfield _ broke down in tears when Hoddle told him Sunday that
he was not going to France and that, after a flare up with Hoddle,
Gascoigne fled the team's training camp, leaving his luggage
behind.
	   Hoddle made his announcement a day early when a tabloid
newspaper got wind of Gascoigne's absence. Hoddle, who is reported
to have warned Gascoigne about his lack of fitness and slack
training habits, was scheduled to hold a press conference in Spain
at 1130 GMT Monday to explain his decision.
	   The unexpected gamble by Hoddle, the No. 1 news item Monday
across England, was surprisingly supported by more than 75 percent
of callers to a popular London morning radio show.
	   The story dwarfed news that Geri Halliwell was leaving the
English all-girls pop group the Spice Girls.
	   Gascoigne, who has played for Newcastle, Tottenham, Lazio,
Glasgow Rangers and Middlesbrough, seems to have lost the ability
to win games with his magical passing and dribbling. He has also
suffered numerous injuries and attracted the wrong kind of
publicity off the field.
	   Ankle and groin injuries sidelined him for much of last season
and, although he played 90 minutes of England's 0-0 tie with Saudi
Arabia and the 1-0 victory over Morocco on Wednesday, he managed
only half of the game against Belgium and limped off with a leg
injury.
	   In those three matches he looked ineffective, a shadow of the
creative player that made him a one-of-a-kind on previous English
sides.
	   Some of the tabloids newspaper have been gunning for Gascoigne,
accusing him of late night drinking with his showbiz friends and
castigating him for smoking 20 cigarettes a day.
	   Although Gascoigne was reported ruled out for his lack of
fitness, Hoddle kept the faith with Les Ferdinand and Darren
Anderton, two Tottenham players who have been short on fitness and
form this season.
	   The move leaves England without a player with World Cup
experience. The club failed to qualify for the 1994 World Cup in
the United States and reached the semifinals in 1990 in Italy.
	   Trevor Steven, a former England teammate, criticized Hoddle's
decision.
	   ``There's still two and a half weeks before kick off. Paul has
something that nobody else can offer the team and I would have just
given him that time.
	   ``As an England fan I would have loved to have seen him do well.
But the decision has been made and I think our squad is poorer for
the lack of Paul Gascoigne.''
	   Gascoigne's manager at Middlesbrough, Bryan Robson, was also
critical.
	   ``I'm surprised,'' admitted Robson. ``When Gazza's fit, he's the
one who can do it at the highest level. He was all right when he
was with us at Middlesbrough. He helped us win important games and
could do that for England.''
	   The squad:
	   Goalkeepers _ David Seaman (Arsenal), Tim Flowers (Blackburn),
Nigel Martyn (Leeds),
	   Defenders _ Sol Campbell (Tottenham), Tony Adams (Arsenal),
Martin Keown (Arsenal), Rio Ferdinand (West Ham), Gareth Southgate
(Aston Villa), Gary Neville (Manchester United),
	   Midfielders _ Darren Anderton (Tottenham), David Beckham
(Manchester United), Graeme Le Saux (Chelsea), Robert Lee
(Newcastle), Steve McManaman (Liverpool), Paul Ince (Liverpool),
David Batty (Newcastle), Paul Merson (Middlesbrough), Paul Scholes
(Manchester United),
	   Strikers _ Les Ferdinand (Tottenham), Alan Shearer (Newcastle),
Teddy Sheringham (Manchester United), Michael Owen (Liverpool).
	   (scw)	   
</TEXT>
