<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ecuador-Elections,0463 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mayor, business magnate headed for runoff in Ecuador presidential race 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photos
By MONTE HAYES
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) _ The Harvard-trained mayor of Quito and
Ecuador's wealthiest man will square off in a runoff to determine
the new president of the Andean nation, which is racked by
instability.
	   Quito Mayor Jamil Mahuad collected 35.4 percent of the votes
Sunday while business magnate Alvaro Noboa, who boasts of owning
105 companies ranging from banana plantations to banks, won 26.8
percent, according to an exit poll sponsored by seven television
stations.
	   They led a field of six candidates competing to replace interim
President Fabian Alarcon. But since neither received a majority of
votes, they will meet in a second round runoff on July 12.
	   Congress appointed Alarcon president in February 1997 after
deposing President Abdala Bucaram for ``mental incapacity.''
Bucaram fled to exile in Panama and is being tried in absentia on
corruption charges, but has vowed to return to politics in Ecuador.
	   Despite his absence the fiery-tongued populist, who is known as
``El Loco,'' overshadowed the voting. Many Ecuadoreans fear he is
behind Noboa's candidacy and will return if Noboa wins.
	   ``Bucaram's phantom is hovering over the campaign,'' the Quito
newspaper Hoy said last week.
	   Ecuadoreans, fed up with corrupt and ineffective governments,
were hoping the elections would produce a leader who can end the
country's political and economic instability.
	   Mahuad, who has a master's degree in public administration from
Harvard University, predicted that in the second round he would
receive the support of ``people who are against corruption, who are
against what Bucaram and Noboa represent.''
	   ``We have defeated the biggest fortune in Ecuador,'' he said.
``We have won despite slanderous attacks.''
	   Responding to Noboa's denunciation last week that his campaign
was financed by drug traffickers, Mahuad said: ``Noboa has taken
off his mask. He has sold his soul to Bucaram.''
	   Mahuad, a 48-year-old centrist, is boosted by his reputation as
an effective, honest mayor. He has pledged to improve health
services and education and to combat rising crime.
	   ``He's honest and he has kept his promises to Quito. You can see
his work everywhere,'' Mauricio Fiallos, 38, a computer tecnician,
said after he left a voting booth at a school in a middle-class
Quito neighborhood.
	   The 47-year-Noboa is running as an independent. But despite his
wealth he has the backing of Bucaram's Roldosista party, which dubs
itself ``the force of the poor.'' Resorting to Bucaram's populist
style, he promised to create 1 million jobs and build 200,000 homes
for the poor.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Ecuador-Elections; CT:i; 
