w2318  wstm-
u s     BC-Sports-Cricket-NewZea     06-01 0250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-New Zealand </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sri Lankan press praises New Zealand spinners 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) _ Sri Lankan newspapers on Monday
praised New Zealand spinners for pulling off a 167-run victory over
home team in the first cricket Test.
	   ``Sri Lanka's quest to fix New Zealand on a slow turning pitch
totally back-fired as the Kiwis turned the table,'' said the
English language Island newspaper.
	   The test that ended over the weekend was a big disappointment
for this cricket-crazy nation of 18 million people. Though one-day
world champions, Sri Lanka has been trying to prove its credentials
as a good test side.
	   The team didn't distinguish itself on the recent tour of South
Africa where it lost both the tests and couldn't make it to the
finals of a triangular series involving host South Africa and
Pakistan.
	   On Sunday, Sri Lanka chased a victory target of 465 in 134 overs
but it succumbed tamely to New Zealand's spin attack and was bowled
out for 297 runs. Spinners Daniel Vettori and Paul Wiseman shared
eight of Sri Lanka's second inning wickets.
	   Wiseman, a 28-year-old off-spinner from Auckland, returned a
match figure of 46.5-17-82-5 on his Test debut.
	   ``Sri Lanka's top order batting once more crumbled to
pressure,'' said The Daily News.
	   The tourists will now travel to the southern city of Galle, 110
kilometers (68 miles) from Colombo to play the second Test of
three-test series, beginning Wednesday.
	   (dg-ne-aks)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Cricket-New Zealand; CT:s; 
