<HEADLINE>
Prime minister of breakaway Georgian province killed in southern Russia 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Unidentified gunmen shot and killed the prime
minister of Georgia's separatist region of South Ossetia, a Russian
news agency reported Monday.
	   The attack in the southern Russian city of Vladikavkaz killed
Prime Minister Valery Khubulov along with a Russian businessman,
Sergei Zlenko, the Interfax news agency reported.
	   The two gunmen escaped in a car, which they later blew up, the
report said.
	   South Ossetia, populated mostly by ethnic Ossetians, broke away
from Georgia in 1990 when it was still part of the Soviet Union,
calling for unity with ethnic brethren in Russia's North Ossetia.
	   The fighting ended after Russian peacekeepers were deployed in
the region in 1992, but talks on political settlement have stalled.
	   Khubulov was head of South Ossetia's armed forces during the
conflict, Interfax said.
	   Investigators are being sent from Moscow to Vladikavkaz, the
capital of North Ossetia, Interfax said.
