<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asian Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong, Tokyo stock markets drop sharply 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Hong Kong and Tokyo stocks were down sharply
Monday amid rising fears of recession.
	   After a battering last week, capped by the government's
announcement late Friday that the economy contracted 2 percent in
the first quarter, Hong Kong's benchmark Hang Seng Index headed
down again. It dropped 224.36 points or 2.5 percent in the morning
session, finishing at 8,710.20.
	   Enthusiasm over the government's new economic recovery program
unveiled Friday drove the index to a high of 9,089.41 points in
early morning.
	   But overseas fund managers began selling heavily, an indication
that they did not believe that the government's measures would lead
to economic recovery soon.
	   The contraction in the first quarter was the first in 13 years.
Officials and analysts expect more bad news, with the possibility
of growth picking up again sometime in the second half of the year.
The government countered Friday with a seven-point economic program
to strengthen the economy.
	   Meanwhile, Singapore's main index closed down 1.2 percent at
midday. Tokyo share prices finished sharply lower amid renewed
worries about the health of Japan's economy.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 349.75 points,
or 2.23 percent, to close at 15,321.03 points. On Friday, the index
had lost 125.77 points, or 0.80 percent.
	   Traders said selling of blue chips by overseas investors pushed
the Nikkei average sharply lower. Domestic institutional investors
later joined in the selling.
	   Hurting sentiment were recent signs that Japan's economic woes
have deepened. On Friday, the government said Japan's unemployment
rate hit a record 4.1 percent, up from 3.9 percent in March.
</TEXT>
