<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Earthquake </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mild quake shakes Mito 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A mild earthquake with a preliminary magnitude of
5.9 shook Tokyo and wide areas of northern Japan at 4:36 p.m.
(0736GMT) Monday, but there were no immediate reports of damage and
injuries.
	   The Central Meteorological agency said the quake registered an
intensity of two on a Japanese scale of seven in Tokyo and
Fukushima, 239 kilometers (149 miles) northeast Tokyo.
	   The tremor was strong enough to rattle doors. It also forced a
shinkansen, or bullet train, to stop for 12 minutes near the
central Japan city of Nagoya because of a power outage, a
spokeswoman for Central Japan Railway said.
	   The agency placed the focus of the quake about 400 kilometers
(240 miles) underground in Mie, central Japan.
	   Four minutes earlier, another quake with a preliminary magnitude
of 4.2 shook Mito, 100 kilometers (63 miles) northeast of Tokyo.
The agency said that quake registered an intensity of one on the
Japanese scale.
  (sk)	   
