<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian students rally against U.S. policy outside embassy 
</HEADLINE>
With BC-Indonesia
AP Photo available
<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ About 50 students rallied peacefully
Monday outside the U.S. Embassy against what they said were U.S.
attempts to delay foreign loans to Indonesia.
	   Flanked by soldiers in camouflage uniforms, the protesters sat
down at the gates and chanted slogans against U.S. intervention in
the affairs of their economically-shattered country.
	   They accused the United States of conspiring to stall the
disbursement of aid tied to a dlrs 43 billion rescue package led by
the International Monetary Fund. The loans were suspended amid
political turmoil that led to the May 21 resignation of President
Suharto.
	   The demonstrators stuck posters in the embassy gates that read:
``America, don't intervene in our country,'' and ``IMF, give your
loan package immediately.''
	   Women at the rally wore Islamic shawls and the men were in red
university jackets. The protesters, members of a Muslim students'
association, accused the United States of religious discrimination
against Indonesia, which is overwhelmingly Muslim.
	   A top IMF official, Hubert Neiss, left Indonesia on Saturday
after a visit to assess when the IMF should release its next dlrs 1
billion loan to the nation of 202 million people. He was scheduled
to report to the IMF directors later Monday.
	   The United States is a key player in the 182-nation lending
agency, which is based in Washington.
	   ``We really want support from America because this country is
very dominant in the negotiations between Indonesia and the IMF,''
said Irwan Badillah, a protest organizer.
	   Student protesters helped hasten the downfall of Suharto, who
rose to power in the 1960s, but lost his authoritarian grip as
discontent grew over deepening economic hardship.
</TEXT>
