u f     BC-Japan-Markets 3rdLd-Writethru   06-01 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tokyo stocks tumble amid deepening worries over economy, dollar rises 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photos available
Eds: Wraps up with late dollar, closing bond prices, comments
By KOZO MIZOGUCHI
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Deepening worries over the state of Japan's economy
triggered a 2.23 percent decline in the Tokyo Stock Exchange's main
index on Monday and drove the U.S. dollar higher against the yen.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 349.75 points,
closing at 15,321.03 points. On Friday, the index had shed 125.77
points, or 0.80 percent.
	   In late afternoon, the dollar bought 139.12 yen, up 0.40 yen
from late Friday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of
138.90 yen Friday. During Tokyo trading, the dollar rose as high as
139.33 yen, a level not seen since early July 1991.
	   ``The state of the economy is extremely bad,'' said Sachio
Ishikawa, general manager at Chuo Securities.
	   Selling of blue chips by overseas investors pushed the Nikkei
average sharply lower, traders said. They said hedge selling of
stock futures contracts by domestic institutional investors also
contributed to the decline.
	   On top of continued weakness of other Asian economies, a series
of bleak economic indicators recently have signaled that Japan's
economic woes have deepened.
	   On Friday, the government said Japan's jobless rate hit a record
4.1 percent, up from 3.9 percent in March.
	   On Monday, the Japan Automobile Dealers' Association said sales
of new cars, trucks and buses fell in May from a year earlier for
the 14th consecutive month as the sluggish domestic economy
continued to keep consumers from dealer showrooms.
	   Trading remained thin, with an estimated 320 million shares
changing hands on the first section, down from Friday's 346 million
shares. Retreating issues outnumbered advances by 889 to 222, with
135 issues unchanged.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was down 24.79 points, or 2.03 percent, to 1,196.70.
The TOPIX fell 2.24 points, or 0.18 percent on Friday.
	   The sharp slide in the Tokyo stock market drove the dollar above
139.00 yen, a level that dollar bulls had recently found difficult
to break, traders said.
	   ``The weak stock and bond market is making it that much easier
to buy the dollar and break through resistance,'' said Eji Takane,
deputy general manager of foreign exchange at Asahi Bank.
	   Uncertainty in South Asia following Pakistan's sixth nuclear
test Saturday along with the weakness in the Japanese economy
continued to draw investors to the dollar.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond fell to a record low of 1.155 percent from Friday's
finish of 1.205 percent, driving its price higher to 112.41 yen
from 112.04 yen. 	   
</TEXT>
