w2359  wstm-
r i     BC-Russia-Economy     06-01 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian markets lower despite U.S. support 
</HEADLINE>
By MAURA REYNOLDS
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia's nervous markets sank farther in early
trading Monday despite U.S. promises to support new loans by
international lenders.
	   In a brief statement issued Sunday, President Bill Clinton
expressed U.S. support for aid to Russia from such multinational
institutions as the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund.
	   Nonetheless, by midday the stock market was down an additional
4.5 percent, although traders said there was little panic selling.
	   ``We are seeing a manageable fall,'' said Robert Devane, head of
fixed-income trading at Moscow's Troika-Dialog brokerage. ``We are
not yet at a critical point like last week.''
	   Russian leaders have been working to stabilize the financial
markets after a wave of panic selling last week caused the stock
market to plummet and threatened a run on the national currency,
the ruble.
	   Altogether the stock market is down 40 percent since April. The
Central Bank has intervened to prop up the ruble and raised
interest rates to 150 percent to convince investors to stay in
Russia.
	   The ruble was weaker in trading early Monday, but had fallen
only a few cents on the dollar.
	   Before the crisis, Russia's economic prospects had been looking
somewhat brighter, having kept a lid on inflation and recording its
first economic growth since the Soviet collapse.
	   But the government has been unable to solve a years-long
payments crisis, caused by its inability to collect taxes and
therefore to pay wages to state workers. Many workers and
pensioners have been unpaid for months on end.
	   Russia's new tax chief, Boris Fyodorov, said in an interview
Monday that the country's 35 percent tax rate must be lowered but
enforcement strengthened.
	   ``The rate should be 20 percent, but then those who do not pay
must in effect be put into prison,'' he told the NTV network.
	   He also said Russians must get used to the idea of paying taxes.
Only a small percent of Russians file income tax.
	   ``Individual taxes constitute the lion's share of the taxation
base in any normal country...'' he said. ``Where there are incomes,
there are taxes.''
	   Russian leaders have said that the crisis was triggered by a
combination of forces, including a sharp fall in world prices for
gas and oil, the financial crisis in southeast Asia, and social
unrest including a recent wave of coal miners' strikes.
	   Russia has said it is not seeking a bailout package, but it is
eager to get the latest installments of a dlrs 10 billion loan from
the IMF.
	   IMF officials have said that they will recommend releasing a
delayed dlrs 700 million loan installment.
	   (dj/mr)
</TEXT>
