<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian president names new advisers to help battle economic crisis 
</HEADLINE>
With BC-Indonesia
<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Enlisting reinforcements to battle
Indonesia's most daunting economic crisis in 30 years, new
President B.J. Habibie has named a fresh team of economic advisers,
State Secretary Akbar Tanjung said Monday.
	   The team includes economist Widjojo Nitisastro, who headed a
team of advisers set up earlier this year by former President
Suharto, former Finance Minister Frans Seda, and Ali Wardhana, also
formerly an adviser to Suharto.
	   Akbar said the new team will advise the president on all
problems affecting the crisis-ridden Indonesian economy and on the
government's negotiations with the International Monetary Fund.
	   Their advice will supplement the work of Habibie's economic
ministers, led by Coordinating Minister for the Economy, Industry
and Finance Ginandjar Kartasasmita.
	   Ginandjar and his team met last week in Jakarta with Hubert
Neiss, the IMF's director for Asia and Pacific Affairs. They
predicted the economy will contract by at least 10 percent this
year.
	   Neiss said Indonesia's economic and political situation merited
the resumption of the dlrs 43 billion bailout package that the
agency is supervising for Indonesia.
	   The IMF suspended disbursements last month because of political
turmoil that led to the resignation of President Suharto after 32
years of rule.
	   Neiss was scheduled to report to other IMF officials on the
visit at the agency's Washington headquarters later on Monday.
</TEXT>
