<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Syria-Prisoner Release </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Assad frees political prisoners, says rights group 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ The government of Syrian President Hafez
Assad has released some 30 political prisoners and human rights
activists jailed for opposing the regime, a human rights group said
Monday.
	   Some of the activists freed this week have spent 18 years
without trial, said Haitham Manaq, a spokesman for the exiled
Organization of Defense Committees for Democratic Freedoms and
Human Rights in Syria.
	   Among them were Riyad al-Turk, a leader of the opposition
Communist Party who was jailed in 1980, and Akram Nuais, a leading
human rights activist imprisoned since 1991, Manaq said.
	   He said the rest are members of opposition and human rights
groups and Kurdish activists who have been jailed without charges
or trial for lengthy periods.
	   ``We welcome the release, but we believe it is only a partial
move, '' he told The Associated Press by telephone from his Paris
headquarters.
	   Assad's government has long been criticized by human rights
groups who claim it holds thousands of political prisoners. It was
unclear why prisoners were freed now, but could be a gesture ahead
of a visit Assad plans to France later this year.
	   Syria is still believed to hold some 2,500 political prisoners
including two who have been in jail for nearly 28 years. Khalil
Berayez and Moustafa Falah were imprisoned immediately after Assad
came to power in a military coup in September 1970.
	   Since 1995, Syria has been quietly releasing political
detainees, including some who took part in a 1982 revolt against
Assad's rule.
	   Manaq urged Syria to free the rest of the detainees, especially
those who are seriously sick or have spent long terms in jail.
  sn-ggl
</TEXT>
