w2365  wstm-
r i     BC-Yugoslavia-Montenegro 2ndLd-Writethru   06-01 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Montenegro, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0736 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Wild gunfire greets victory by Milosevic foe quotes, Bulatovic accepts results, updated results. 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photos
Eds: RECASTS and UPDATES throughout with celebrations, Djukanovic
By ALISON SMALE
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Wild gunfire erupted Monday as
revelers celebrated the victory in Montenegro's parliamentary
elections of the biggest challenger to Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic.
	   With 72 percent of the vote counted, the Election Commission in
the smaller of Yugoslavia's two republics said Montenegrin
President Milo Djukanovic's coalition had captured 50.4 percent of
the ballots compared to 34.3 percent for Milosevic protege Momir
Bulatovic.
	   Djukanovic's triumph was a new blow to Milosevic's 11-year rule,
already dented by a virtual war in the Serbian province of Kosovo
in which ethnic Albanian militants are gaining ground against
police.
	   Djukanovic addressed several hundred wildly cheering supporters,
some of them firing guns in the air, and all singing patriotic
songs.
	   ``Montenegro has again shown that it has the wisdom, courage and
resolve to resist those who decided to enslave Montenegro,''
Djukanovic said.
	   ``This is not our final victory,'' he added. ``Our final victory
will be when democracy wins throughout Yugoslavia.''
	   Milosevic took command of Serbia in 1987 and set a nationalist,
autocratic course, spurring wars that helped unraveled the former
Yugoslav federation.
	   Djukanovic, 36, is the first man with executive power to
challenge him.
	   ``This is a major victory for democracy _ and light at the end
of the tunnel,'' said Novak Kilibarda, leader of one of the parties
making up Djukanovic's ``For a Better Life'' coalition.
	   Serbia and Montenegro are the two remaining republics in
Yugoslavia.
	   Despite widespread fears that Milosevic's supporters would not
recognize the results, the camp of his protege Bulatovic said they
would abide by the outcome, and called the elections free and fair.
	   Only three parties _ Djukanovic's coalition, Bulatovic's and the
Montenegrin separatist Liberal Party _ made it into the 78-seat
republican parliament.
	   Among those who surprisingly missed the 3 percent barrier was
Serbia's ultranationalist Radical Party. Its leader Vojislav
Seselj, a partner of Milosevic in Serbia's government, expressed
surprise at the margin of Djukanovic's triumph.
	   If the trend shown by partial results is confirmed, Djukanovic's
coalition should be able to form Montenegro's government without
partners.
	   More important, Djukanovic could name the bulk of Montenegro's
deputies to the federal Yugoslav Parliament, which elects and can
unseat the Yugoslav president.
	   If those deputies teamed up with lawmakers from Serbia's
opposition, they could vote Milosevic out of office.
	   For that reason, Sunday's election was keenly contested _ with
Milosevic's camp denouncing Djukanovic as a criminal and suggesting
it would not accept a win for the Montenegrin rebel.
	   The 54-nation Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe dispatched some 120 monitors to Sunday's election, and was
to declare Monday whether it considered the vote free and fair.
	   Djukanovic has won strong support from the United States and
western Europe for his defiance of Milosevic, his pro-Western
reformist policies and inclusion of minority ethnic Albanians in
his previous government.
	   Both he and Bulatovic rose in the late 1980s under the patronage
of Milosevic. But Djukanovic turned against his former mentor
during massive anti-Milosevic protests in the winter of 1996-97.
	   Montenegro, a republic of 630,000 people, has a tradition of
settling scores with the weapons that many keep at home. Hospital
officials said four people were wounded during gunfire late Sunday.
	   Tensions between the rival camps soared as polls closed when
riot police loyal to Djukanovic were deployed to block off
Bulatovic's party headquarters.
	   Police sources said they had acted to prevent planned violence
by Bulatovic supporters.
	   Hours earlier, Bulatovic threatened to shoot at police outside
the apartment house where he and Djukanovic still are neighbors,
local independent media said. Bulatovic later issued a statement
saying he became angry because the police had harassed his wife and
children.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yugoslavia-Montenegro, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
