<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Summary,0704 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
An overnight summary of Caribbean news GUYANA: Jamaican prime minister visits as country braces for audit results 
</HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
	   GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) _ As shopkeepers fearing race riots
began covering windows with protective shutters, Jamaica's leader
visited Guyana on Sunday to urge calm before the release of an
audit of December elections.
	   Jamaican Prime Minister P.J. Patterson said he had come to show
international backing for the results of the audit, which was done
by a team of Caribbean Community election experts. The results are
expected Tuesday.
	   The elections divided Guyanese of East Indian descent, who
mostly back the ruling People's Progressive Party, and those of
African descent, who identify with the rival People's National
Congress.
	   ``Guyana cannot be allowed to slip into a state of ethnic
division or social polarization,'' Patterson said Sunday.
  TRINIDAD: Government expels 20 Chinese construction workers
	   PORT-OF-SPAIN, Trinidad (AP) _ Responding to complaints from
labor officials, the Trinidad government said it will expel 20
Chinese construction workers this week because their work could be
done by local residents.
	   The Chinese men, including carpenters, masons and electricians,
were working on three primary schools being built by the China
Jiang Sue International Economic Cooperation construction company.
The company is affiliated with the Chinese Ministry of Foreign
Affairs.
	   The 20 workers have been ordered to leave by Friday, a statement
from the Trinidadian government said Saturday.
	   In March, the government turned down work permits for 24 of 36
Chinese hired to work on the dlrs 51 million project after labor
leaders accused immigration officials of letting construction
workers slip in.
  TRINIDAD AND TOBAGO: Researchers to test AIDS vaccine
	   PORT-OF-SPAIN, Trinidad (AP) _ Researchers in Trinidad and
Tobago said they will begin injecting volunteers with an
experimental AIDS vaccine that has caused controversy in Uganda,
another test site for the formula.
	   Doctors at the Medical Research Foundation of Trinidad and
Tobago said last week they will begin testing ALVAC-HIV, a vaccine
developed at the Pasteur Institute in Paris, on 20 virus-free
people to see if it will prompt creation of antibodies to fight the
disease. Trials will begin in 2000.
	   Tests of the vaccine in Uganda last year were delayed after some
politicians voiced unfounded worries that the formula might create
another, stronger strain of the virus that causes AIDS. Opponents
of the trials also accused researchers of using residents of
lesser-developed countries as guinea pigs for the drug.
  BAHAMAS: Police catch two of five escaped prisoners
	   NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) _ Two of five prisoners who escaped from
prison Saturday by chiseling through a concrete roof were captured
hours later, police reported Sunday.
	   Police warned residents the other fugitives were still free and
were armed.
	   The five prisoners squeezed through the hole in the maximum
security section of the prison sometime after the 7 a.m. roll call
Saturday. Officers caught Melvin Saunders, serving a 25-year
sentence for rape, and Wade Higgs, who was awaiting trial for
murder, in downtown Nassau a few hours later.
	   The other fugitives were identified as convicted robbers Douglas
Cleare and Kevin Roker, and manslaughter convict Vaughn George.
  UNITED STATES: Publicist confirms Cindy Crawford's Bahamas
marriage
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) _ Supermodel Cindy Crawford married longtime
friend Rande Gerber in a ceremony on a beach in the Bahamas, her
spokeswoman confirmed Sunday.
	   The couple was surrounded by family and close friends during
Friday's wedding at The Ocean Club Resort on Paradise Island,
publicist Annett Wolf said in a statement.
	   Friend and songwriter Bruce Roberts sang ``Have a Little Faith
in Me,'' accompanied by Jed Leiber.
	   Gerber owns the celebrity bars The Whiskey in New York and
Skybar in Los Angeles.
	   Crawford was previously married to actor Richard Gere.
</TEXT>
