w2373  wstm-
r i     BC-Asia-Communications     06-01 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asia-Communications </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV, telephone, computer developments in Asia discussed 
</HEADLINE>
By BETH DUFF-BROWN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Pacific rim countries could sign an agreement
this week that would simplify certification of communication
equipment and allow foreign manufacturers greater access to Asia, a
U.S. official said Monday.
	   Communications equipment such as cellular phones and modems
currently must meet technological standards and be certified in
each of the countries where they'll be used.
	   The Mutual Recognition Agreement would allow manufacturers to
get their equipment certified by agencies in their own countries,
lowering the cost to consumers and getting the products to market
faster, said Larry Irving, assistant secretary of communications
and information at the U.S. Department of Commerce.
	   The United States and the European Union already have a similar
agreement.
	   ``It'll make things easier. If you make a handset in one market,
it won't be as difficult to jump over hurdles to have that handset
used in other markets,'' Irving said.
	   Irving was attending a meeting of ministers of the Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation to discuss liberalizing the telecommunications
business across borders and oceans.
	   The MRA agreement could go into effect by July 1999.
	   Irving told reporters that the U.S. was still ``bullish'' on the
Asian market, despite the regional economic crisis that has led
many investors to flee.
	   ``While people may be stretching out investment, and that's
real, you're not seeing anyone saying they're going to halt
investment,'' he said.
	   APEC ministers were also to discuss the expansion of the
Asia-Pacific Information Infrastructure and Internet ``domains,''
the three-letter address endings such as .com.
	   In conjunction with the APEC meeting, the latest telephone,
computer and broadcast gadgets and systems went on display at the
CommunicAsia/NetworkAsia conference.
	   ``Governments are very concerned about what it means to be
giving away to the private sector ownership and management of
broadcasting,'' said Derek Nicholas, a consultant for the
CommunicASia/NetworkAsia conference.
	   ``This may well act as a retarding effect on using all this
super technology we've seen.''
	   Nicholas spoke at the opening press conference of the conference
and exhibition which covers 22,490 square meters over two sites and
is Singapore's second largest trade fair.
	   Displays at the booths for NetworkAsia, CommunicAsia,
BroadcastAsia, CableSat98 and MobileCommAsia show how the different
communications sectors are increasingly interrelated. The
exhibition, in its 12th year, is attended by 1,800 companies from
46 countries.
	   For the first time at a international trade fair, the three
different high definition television systems, developed separately
by the United States, Japan and Europe, are on display at the same
show, said Stephen Tan, managing director of Singapore Exhibition
Services.
	   ``Many countries, including Singapore, are in the process of
deciding which (of the HDTV systems) to adopt,'' Tan said. Japan
and Australia have said they will put HDTV into operation for
national broadcasting by 2000-2001. 	   
</TEXT>
