<SLUG> BC-China-Earthquakes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
After three small quakes, experts say no big one for Beijing 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ After three mild earthquakes bumped Beijing,
government seismologists insisted Monday that the Chinese capital
would not be struck by a big quake.
	   The three tremors _ the largest of which had a preliminary
magnitude of 3.4 _ hit the capital Sunday night and early Monday,
state-run media reported. All were centered in Beijing's
southwestern Fengtai district and could be felt in the western half
of the city.
	   Government seismologists, paraded by state media to squelch any
panic in rumor-filled Beijing, called the quakes aftershocks from a
magnitude-6.2 earthquake that struck farming villages 250
kilometers (150 miles) to the north Jan. 10.
	   The tremors in Beijing do ``not mean that bigger, destructive
ones will follow,'' the Xinhua News Agency quoted Ding Jianhai, who
heads the government's earthquake warning center, as saying.
	   Ding pledged to issue timely warnings in the future if experts
predict a magnitude-5 or stronger quake will hit Beijing.
	   Chinese for centuries have seen earthquakes and other natural
disasters as portents of political change. North China's last major
quake killed 240,000 in Tangshan city on July 28, 1976. Within six
weeks, revolutionary leader Mao Tse-tung was dead. 	   
</TEXT>
