r i     BC-AirFrance-Strike     06-01 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Air France-Strike,0456 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Passengers stranded as Air France strike begins 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Passengers were stranded Monday at airports across
France after Air France pilots began a strike that threatened to
disrupt travel plans during the World Cup soccer games.
	   Monitors at Paris' main airports offered a bleak sight for
passengers: ``annule,'' _ canceled _ written in red next to almost
all international and domestic flights.
	   The strike began at midnight after Air France failed to reach an
agreement with pilots seeking to block wage cuts.
	   Air France set up special telephone lines for passengers seeking
information on flights. There was no immediate indication of how
many flights were canceled or which routes were most affected.
	   Most of the company's aircraft _ many of them decorated with
players representing the 32 World Cup teams _ remained grounded
Monday. Air France is the official carrier for the World Cup.
	   The World Cup, held every four years, will attract an estimated
one million people to France. The tournament kicks off June 10. A
combined audience of 40 billion is expected to view the four-week
soccer bonanza.
	   Air France expects to cancel 90 percent of long-haul flights for
the coming week. About 25 percent of short- and medium-haul flights
out of Paris' Charles de Gaulle airport are likely to fly as
planned, the company has said, as are about 20 percent leaving from
Orly airport.
	   The spokesman for the leading union in the strike, the SNPL,
apologized to customers.
	   ``We have no other choice,'' Christian Paris said on France Info
radio on Sunday.
	   Transport Minister Jean-Claude Gayssot, speaking on French
television, urged both sides to ``take up the path of discussion.''
	   Fearful that France's image could be tarnished when the soccer
matches begin, one leftist lawmaker, Georges Sarre, denounced the
pilots as ``the damned of the Earth.''
	   Sarre, speaking Sunday on French television, said the pilots
were ``practicing blackmail on the company.''
	   The SNPL union has called a 15-day renewable strike starting
Monday. Three smaller unions called for a strike from Monday to
Thursday. Most of the state-run carrier's 3,200 pilots were likely
to take part.
	   The pilots are asking the carrier to abandon a plan to save dlrs
83 million a year by cutting into their salaries, currently among
the highest in their field in the world. The cost-saving measure
also calls for pilots hired after June 1997 to begin at a lower
salary than their predecessors did.
	   Air France President Jean-Cyril Spinetta sees the plan as
critical to keeping the airline profitable. Air France reported
strong 1997 earnings after years of crippling debts.
</TEXT>
