<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Bosnich </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serie A an option for Bosnich says manager 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Aston Villa goalkeeper Mark Bosnich was
wanted by former AC Milan manager Fabio Capello and Italy's Serie A
remained an option, his manager said Monday.
	   Villa manager John Gregory is trying to tie Bosnich to a
long-term contract but the Australian left England for a holiday in
the United States this week without making a decision.
	   ``Mark is not dissatisfied with Aston Villa and has been very
happy in his six years at the club,'' said Bosnich's Sydney-based
manager Leo Karis. ``Money is not an issue. Mark wants to know
about the club's recruitment strategy, how he would fit in and
whether it will be a competitive side.
	   ``There was also an approach by AC Milan last week but they
sacked (Capello) a few days ago and this option is up in the air.
	   ``However, Capello has always had an eye on him and indicated
wherever he takes a coaching position he will still be interested
in Mark.''
	   Bosnich has a year to run in his contract and has said he was
not in a hurry to sign until he has had time to relax.
	   He went to Aston Villa six years ago at the age of 20 and has
played over 200 league and Cup games with the club.
	   Karis said Bosnich was disappointed at the manner in which his
talks with the club had been portrayed by the English media.
	   He said there was never an ultimatum given to the keeper of sign
or be sold and the talks with Gregory had been friendly and
positive.
	   ``Mark just wants to be part of a highly competitive side and
had a good year in goal in the season just finished,'' said Karis.
	   ``He also put in star performances for the Socceroos in the
Confederation and World Cup matches as well as being named Oceania
Player of the Year. His future will be resolved over the next few
weeks after his much deserved holiday.''
