<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Church Burnings </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesia's Christian clergy complains to president about church burnings 
</HEADLINE>
By HARIS SYAMAUN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Eight leading Christian clergymen
appealed Monday to President B.J. Habibie to investigate the
burning of churches during riots in 1997.
	   In a meeting with the new president, they asked him to help
Christian communities rebuild their houses of worship.
	   The delegation, split evenly between Catholics and Protestants
and led by Bishop Jos Suwatan, chairman of the Indonesian Churches
Association, and Cardinal Julius Darmaamadja, conferred with
Habibie for nearly three hours.
	   ``The president responded positively and asked the Christian
community to work with the government,'' Darmaamadja said.
	   Indonesia's Christians are mostly members of the ethnic Chinese
minority, which makes up about 4 percent of the country's 202
million people. Muslims comprise 87 percent of the population.
	   The ethnic Chinese, who have generally been more economically
successful than the Muslims, were targeted by mobs that rampaged
through several Indonesian cities last month.
	   The rioters were angry over rising food and fuel prices, a
byproduct of the country's worst economic crisis in 30 years. Shops
and homes belonging to Chinese were burned and looted.
	   There were no reports of church burnings in the recent violence.
But churches were attacked in riots last year in Surabaya,
Indonesia's second-largest city, and several other towns in Java
island.
	   Last month's rioting, coupled with student protests over
political stagnation and corruption, helped force President Suharto
to step down May 21 after 32 years of autocratic rule.
	   Since assuming office, Habibie has strived to placate the
Chinese community. He visited burned out shops and told merchants
there was no place in Indonesia for prejudice and racism.
	   Chinese merchants control a good part of the country's
distribution system, which has been in a shambles since the riots.
Many entrepreneurs fled and have not returned.
	   Government and aid officials have warned of imminent food
shortages resulting from the wrecked distribution network.
	   ``The people are suffering from great misery,'' Suwatan said.
</TEXT>
