<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Stocks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Share prices tumble 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) - Share prices in Hong Kong tumbled Monday,
pushed down by worries that the territory's economic downturn could
last for some time.
	   The Hang Seng Index, the market's key indicator of blue chips,
fell 322.55 points, or 3.6 percent, to close at 8,612.01.
	   Trading volume was 6.52 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 835
million), up from Friday's 5.06 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S.
dlrs 648).
	   Investors were concerned over the government's announcement late
Friday that the economy contracted 2 percent in the first quarter,
brokers said.
	   The contraction in the first quarter was the first in 13 years.
Officials and analysts expect more bad news, with the possibility
of growth picking up again sometime in the second half of the year.
	   Investors don't expect government measures to stimulate the
economy to have an effect in the near future, said Ben Kwong,
research director at Dharmala Securities Co.
	   Among property shares, Cheung Kong fell 2.30 Hong Kong dollars
to 39.60, and Sun Hung Kai Properties fell 1.80 dollars to 35.60.
	   In the banking sector, HSBC Holdings fell 3.00 dollars to
185.00, and Hang Seng Bank also fell 3.00 dollars to 54.75.
	   Elsewhere, Hutchison Whampoa fell 3.40 dollars to 37.10, and
Swire Pacific ``A'' fell 1.90 dollars to 26.75.	   
</TEXT>
