<HEADLINE>
Deputy prime minister of breakaway Georgian province killed Ossetia confirming the attack, CORRECTS that victim was deputy prime minister sted prime minister, TRIMS. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPGRADES attribution, UPDATES with officials from South
<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Unidentified gunmen shot and killed a deputy prime
minister of Georgia's separatist region of South Ossetia, Russian
and Georgian officials said Monday.
	   The attack in the southern Russian city of Vladikavkaz killed
Deputy Prime Minister Valery Khubulov along with a Russian
businessman, said Irbek Khudov, a spokesman for the Interior
Ministry.
	   The two gunmen escaped in a car, which they later blew up, he
said.
	   Officials inside South Ossetia confirmed that the deputy prime
minister had been killed, but provided no details.
	   South Ossetia, populated mostly by ethnic Ossetians, broke away
from Georgia in 1990 when it was still part of the Soviet Union,
calling for unity with ethnic brethren in Russia's North Ossetia.
Khubulov was head of South Ossetia's armed forces during the
conflict.
	   The fighting ended after Russian peacekeepers were deployed in
the region in 1992, but talks on a political settlement have
stalled.
	   The Russian businessman who also died in the attack was
identified as Sergei Zlenko, a metals trader, according to the
Interfax news agency.
