w2393  wstm-
r i     BC-Japan-Politics 1stLd-Writethru   06-01 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan's governing coalition breaks up after four year alliance 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: RECASTS; Updates throughout with background; ADDS byline.
AP Photo TOK101
By CHESTER DAWSON
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's governing coalition officially broke up
Monday ahead of parliamentary elections this summer, bringing an
end to a four-year alliance between formerly bitter rivals.
	   In a widely expected move, Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto
accepted the decision of the Social Democratic Party and New Party
Sakigake to withdraw from the government, allowing his Liberal
Democratic Party to formally reclaim its position as sole ruling
party.
	   It ended an oddball marriage between the conservative LDP and
left-leaning Social Democrats, formerly Japan's socialist party.
Previous to linking up in June of 1996, the two parties had been
political enemies for most of the post-World War II era.
	   The coalition's demise was seen as unlikely to have much impact
on Hashimoto's administration. The Liberal Democratic Party has
already assumed all Cabinet posts and enjoys a majority in the more
powerful of Japan's two legislative chambers.
	   ``Over the past year, the coalition was mainly driven at the
LDP's pace and that left it in bad shape,'' said Masayoshi
Takemura, chairman of New Party Sakigake.
	   Social Democrat head Takako Doi said her party decided to end
its alliance with the LDP over disagreements with Hashimoto's party
on key legislative issues such as more stringent political ethics
and the strengthening of U.S.-Japan defense ties.
	   But the withdrawal was also viewed as a tactical move before
elections slated for sometime in July. Half of the seats in the
upper house of parliament will be up for grabs.
	   The pro-business Liberal Democratic Party has 261 seats in the
powerful 500-member lower house. With 118 seats in the less
powerful upper house, it still needs support from the 21-member
Social Democratic Party and three-member Sakigake to gain a
majority in the 252-member body.
	   The Social Democrats and Sakigake party were expected to
continue to vote with the LDP on a case-by-case basis. And the
Social Democrats have pledged to support Hashimoto's administration
if opposition parties submit a no-confidence vote against the
government.
	   Hashimoto said in a nationally televised interview Monday that
his party will respect the ``history of working together'' with the
two parties, indicating he will seek cooperation from them on some
issues.
	   Still, Hashimoto may need to court additional support from
independent lawmakers and non-aligned parties such as a lay
Buddhist political group which once had close ties to the LDP.
	   In June of 1996, the LDP joined hands with the Social Democrats
in what was dubbed an ``unholy alliance,'' producing Japan's first
socialist prime minister in 46 years.
	   While the two parties had long been rivals, they buried their
enmity in a bid to keep from power a reformist coalition made up of
political renegades from both parties.
	   The LDP was toppled from power by this reformist coalition in
July of 1993 after four decades as Japan's sole ruling party.
  (cd-km) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Japan-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:ASIA;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
