<HEADER>
w2397  wstm-
u f     BC-AsiaBusinessBriefs     06-01 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asia Business Briefs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Some of these stories also moved earlier today as separates. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: Contains items from Japan, Malaysia, Singapore and Vietnam.
<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's sales of new cars, trucks and buses fell in
May for the 14th straight month as the sluggish domestic economy
continued to keep consumers out of dealer showrooms.
	   Sales fell 8 percent in May from the year-earlier month to
294,211 units, the Japan Automobile Dealers' Association said
Monday. The sales are measures by new registrations.
	   Sales dropped 2.8 percent compared with April.
	   The sale of passenger cars was up slightly, 0.1 percent to
294,211, compared with the year before. Truck sales, however,
plunged 23.9 percent to 82,614 sold the year before. Sales of buses
were also down, falling 1.1 percent to 784.
	   While demand for Japanese cars remains robust in North America,
domestic Japanese consumption has lagged since a sales tax increase
last year. Exports to Asia have also fallen because the financial
crisis there sent local currencies into a tailspin.
	   ___
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A month after Japan's foreign currency supply
dipped due to intervention in support of the battered yen, the
Japanese Finance Ministry said Monday that the nation's exchange
reserves rose by dlrs 1.22 billion in May.
	   Japan's reserves totaled dlrs 206.98 billion last month, the
ministry said, giving it the world's largest supply of foreign
currency.
	   The increase comes after reserves in April declined by dlrs
17.84 billion compared to the previous month.
	   Supplies fell that month as the Bank of Japan waged an
aggressive campaign to prop up the weakening Japanese currency by
selling dollars and buying yen.
	   ___
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Malaysia will not change its
projection of 2.5 percent growth for this year, despite new figures
that show the economy is in worse shape than previously thought,
the finance minister said Monday.
	   The Central Bank's announcement Saturday that Gross Domestic
Product shrank by 1.8 percent in the first quarter this year was
the worst sign yet of the country's economic problems, said Finance
Minister Anwar Ibrahim.
	   But Anwar, who is also Malaysia's deputy prime minister, said
the news would not prompt the government to change its forecast for
this year, citing positive growth in April.
	   Economists regard two successive quarters of negative growth as
the criteria for a recession.
	   ``The worst is over for the country's economy,'' he said. The
figures for January to March 1998 ``shouldn't be taken out of
context.''
	   Malaysia's central bank, Bank Negara, is forecasting that
exports would grow, boosting the economy, even though regional
currencies have dropped dramatically in value since the onset of
the Asian financial crisis.
	   ___
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Singapore's economy is unlikely to slip into a
recession this year despite a trend toward negative growth in
Southeast Asia, Finance Minister Richard Hu told Parliament on
Monday.
	   ``The overall picture of the Singapore economy is one of
uncertainty,'' Hu told Parliament. But he stood by an earlier
government forecast of 2.5 percent to 4.5 percent in economic
growth this year.
	   Some private analysts and economists have begun predicting
Singapore's economy would contract this year with a GDP of no more
than 1.5 percent. Three major international investment houses have
predicted recession.
	   Meanwhile, the government minister who heads the national trade
unions said layoffs this year would exceed the 20,000 who lost
their jobs during the 1985-86 recessions.
	   ___
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ While the latest telephone, computer and
broadcast gadgets and systems went on display Monday at a huge
exhibition, Asian telecommunications ministers talked about
regulation and privatization of the new technologies.
	   ``Governments are very concerned about what it means to be
giving away to the private sector ownership and management of
broadcasting,'' said Derek Nicholas, a consultant for the
CommunicASia/NetworkAsia conference.
	   Nicholas spoke at the opening press conference of the conference
and exhibition which covers 22,490 square meters over two sites and
is Singapore's second largest trade fair.
	   Displays at the booths for NetworkAsia, CommunicAsia,
BroadcastAsia, CableSat98 and MobileCommAsia show how the different
communications sectors are increasingly interrelated. The
exhibition, in its 12th year, is attended by 1,800 companies from
46 countries.
	   For the first time at a international trade fair, the three
different high definition television systems, developed separately
by the United States, Japan and Europe, are on display at the same
show.
	   In conjunction with the trade fair, 11 ministers from countries
of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation group are gathering to
discuss liberalizing the telecommunications business across borders
and oceans.
	   ___
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ Prime Minister Phan Van Khai has decided
to allocate 1.5 trillion dong (dlrs 120 million) in preferential
bank loans for several key industries, the Dau Tu (Investment)
newspaper reported Monday.
	   The government originally set aside 6.6 trillion dong (dlrs 510
million) in preferential bank loans for priority projects, but the
garment, textile, footwear and machinery industries were not on the
list.
	   The interest rate will be 0.81 percent per month for loans in
dong and 8.5 percent per year for loans in U.S. dollars, with a
maximum payback period of 10 years.
	   Longer-term loans must seek approval from the prime minister.
	   Khai recently told government agencies to cut back inefficient
investment projects in sugar processing, breweries and hotels and
increase funding for projects which can find markets such as
bicycles, garments, textiles and footwear. 	   
</TEXT>
