<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Election, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Deposed co-premier registers to vote in Cambodia's elections conquered, grafs 4-6 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with Ranariddh fearing opposition will be divided,
<TEXT>
	   KOMPONG CHAM, Cambodia (AP) _ Prince Norodom Ranariddh
registered to vote Monday in upcoming elections, backing off
threats to boycott if the polls are unlikely to be free and fair.
	   But Ranariddh, deposed as co-prime minister last year in a
bloody coup, said that his FUNCINPEC party may push to postpone the
July 26 vote to reduce the advantage held by his archrival,
strongman Hun Sen.
	   ``We should not talk about a boycott,'' Ranariddh told reporters
after receiving his voter registration card. ``But we should talk
about the possibility of postponing the election.''
	   Ranariddh expressed fears that the opposition vote would be
badly divided and ballots cast for his chief opposition rival, Sam
Rainsy, would ultimately benefit Hun Sen's powerful Cambodian
People's Party.
	   ``When the CPP wins, they will form a government with Sam
Rainsy, leaving us as an opposition party,'' Ranariddh said.
	   Sam Rainsy, once a leading light in FUNCINPEC who now heads his
own party, has voiced similar fears about Ranariddh, pointing up
the deep division and mistrust in the opposition to Hun Sen.
	   The opposition has accused Hun Sen of stacking the electoral
process in his favor to win the polls, which he hopes will restore
international legitimacy and aid lost due to his violent takeover
11 months ago.
	   As many as 90 of the prince's supporters were killed after the
coup and no one has ever been arrested. The opposition accuses Hun
Sen of intimidating opposition workers and coercing voters into
pledging support for his Cambodian People's Party.
	   Ranariddh said that if fewer than 80 percent of the 5.5 million
eligible voters register _ down from 90 percent who cast ballots in
the U.N.-brokered 1993 elections _ FUNCINPEC should ask to extend
the month-long registration process, now set to end June 15.
	   The prince reiterated concern about the opposition's limited
access to Hun Sen-controlled radio and television, calling a
present plan to allocate each political party only five minutes a
day to broadcast messages ``unacceptable.''
	   ``People must be informed about each of the parties' ...
political programs and platforms,'' Ranariddh said.
	   Last month, a coalition of opposition parties, including
FUNCINPEC, said it would boycott the elections unless conditions
were put in place to ensure the polls were credible and the
election date was pushed back.
	   The threat was largely intended to lure the international
community into helping pressure Hun Sen to comply with a minimal
criteria for fair elections.
	   But foreign diplomats, who have shown decreasing sympathy for
the opposition or its demands, have brushed the threat off as a
gimmick. 	   
</TEXT>
