URGENT
<TEXT>
	   Also freed by Judge Japhet Banda was Moyce Kaulungombe, a senior
bodyguard of Kaunda, 74. Both men were charged with concealing
prior knowledge of an Oct. 28 coup attempt by junior military
officers that was quickly crushed by loyal troops.
	   Attorney General Bonaventure Mutale told Banda the state entered
a plea of ``nolle prosequi,'' the legal term for ``no
prosecution,'' a procedure normally used when the state lacks
sufficient evidence or does not wish to proceed with its case.
	   ``This means the state doesn't wish to proceed further. You are
discharged so you are free men,'' Banda told Kaunda and his
bodyguard.
	   Kaunda, wearing a long white beard grown since his arrest on
Christmas day, was mobbed by hundreds of cheering supporters
outside the court before being driven off to an unspecified
destination.
	   The drama came on the first day of the trials of 81 suspects _
most of them soldiers _ who were arrested after junior officers
stormed the state broadcast center and claimed to have overthrown
the government of President Frederick Chiluba.
	   Kaunda repeatedly denied charges against him that carry a
penalty of possible life imprisonment. Most of the other suspects
are charged with treason and face the death sentence.
	   Kaunda, head of an 11 party opposition alliance, was out of the
country during the coup attempt and accused the government of using
it to crush political enemies.
