<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Israel </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hezbollah threatens attacks, Israeli warns of harsh response 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Hezbollah guerrillas have threatened
retaliation for an Israeli missile strike that hit civilians in
south Lebanon, while Israel warned of a tough response if shells
fall in Israeli territory.
	   The twin warnings raised fears in Lebanon of a new round or
cross-border fighting in which far more Lebanese die than Israelis.
In Israel, newspapers reported Monday that residents of northern
Israel spent the night in shelters in fear of a possible Hezbollah
attack.
	   ``The resistance ... cannot keep quiet in light of what has
happened,'' Sheik Nabil Kaouk, Hezbollah commander in the south,
told reporters Sunday night after weekend Israeli rocket attacks
killed a Lebanese shepherd and wounded his brother and another man.
	   In Israel, radio reports quoted the Israeli army's northern
command as warning it will respond ``harshly'' if rockets fall on
northern Israel.
	   The Israeli army also suggested Monday that the harm to
civilians was unintentional.
	   ``Israel has no interest in attacking citizens,'' an army
statement said, adding the targeted area ``is an open space and
anyone in it is suspected of being a terrorist or protecting
terrorists.''
	   Cross-border guerrilla rocket attacks triggered major fighting
in 1996 in which at least 175 people, mostly Lebanese civilians,
were killed.
	   Since then, Hezbollah has targeted the occupied zone and
occasionally Israeli positions along the international border for
retaliation.
	   On Sunday, Israeli troops fired a missile near a village in
southern Lebanon, killing a Lebanese shepherd and wounding his
brother, security officials said. On Saturday night, an Israeli
rocket attack injured a guerrilla near another village.
	   The Lebanese security officials, speaking on condition of
anonymity, originally said two brothers were killed in the rocket
attack Sunday. But they later said one of the brothers had only
been wounded and was hospitalized.
	   Both targets hit by Israel are in a guerrilla mountain
stronghold on the edge of the Israeli-occupied border zone in the
south.
	   Hezbollah is leading the fight to oust some 1,500 Israeli troops
and 2,500 Lebanese militia allies from the occupied zone. Israel or
its allies have controlled the zone for over 20 years, maintaining
the occupation is needed to guard against cross-border guerrilla
raids.
