<SLUG> BC-Sports-RugbyU-Australia-England </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
England gambles on young stand off 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BRISBANE, Australia (AP) _ England has topped Australia's
fly-half gamble with one of its own for the one-off rugby union
test match at Suncorp Stadium on Saturday.
	   Australia will pitch Stephen Larkham in at fly-half for the
first time in a test after his outstanding form as fullback last
year.
	   England's choice, Jonny Wilkinson, will play in the key position
in his test starting debut after just four minutes of test
football.
	   Like Larkham, Wilkinson does not play at fly-half for his club
team, having spent all season outside Rob Andrew as a center with
Newcastle.
	   ``I realize the fact that I'm young and there's a lot of
pressure,'' Wilkinson said Monday. ``I'm going to go in there with
the self confidence just like any fly-half would need. You are
going out there to play for the team and enjoy yourself, that's my
attitude. Everyone's come here with the right attitude, ready to
take on the challenge.''
	   England is a 7-1 outsider after sending a squad with 20 uncapped
players.
	   Larkham's selection was considered a calculated risk by
Australian selectors still trying to fill the void left when
Michael Lynagh retired in 1995.
	   England captain Matt Dawson does not believe Larkham will prove
a Wallaby weak point.
	   ``I wouldn't call it a weakness because across the board in
Australia they can all play in most positions, that's what can be a
strength for them,'' said Dawson.
	   ``This Larkham might be an answer, they might be looking
somewhere else. They've got players who can play in different areas
so they've got a few combinations.''
	   Larkham has confessed to having reservations about his new job.
He hopes two weeks of training will help him settle in.
	   ``That's all I'm concentrating on, getting used to the role,''
Larkham said. ``We've had two weeks until the first test which I'm
probably going to be using as a warm-up. Hopefully two weeks into
the test season I should be right.'' first Test together in a long
time and some of them are carrying injuries.''
	   Wallaby captain John Eales got through two full sessions at the
Caloundra training camp Monday despite tendinitis in a wrist. He
took part in scrummage, lineout and kickoff drills without any
problem.
