<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippines stocks decline; peso edges higher 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Philippine stocks fell for a seventh
straight session Monday, with regional uncertainties and a lack of
positive domestic news discouraging buyers, traders said.
	   The 30-share Philippine Stock Exchange Index fell 15.40 points,
or 0.8 percent, to 1,996.05 after slipping 2.78 points Friday.
	   The index now has lost 152.56 points, or 7 percent, since May
22.
	   ``Foreign investors aren't in the market and in most of the
region since there's really no reason to invest,'' said Noel Reyes,
vice president for research at Anscor-Hagedorn Securities Inc.
	   Reyes expects the market's lethargic trading, due to the absence
of foreign investors, to continue for at least six months.
	   Traders said the Dow Jones Industrial Average's 70.25-point drop
to 8,899.95 Friday added to the market's selling mode, with local
investors cashing in their blue chips.
	   The poor, but largely expected, first-quarter economic growth
figures released last Friday were discounted by the market days
before their announcement, traders said. However, they continued to
cast a shadow over market sentiment.
	   ``The latest data raise concerns that the government won't even
meet its gross national product growth target for the year,'' said
Reyes. He said the government's optimism may be a ``state of
denial.''
	   GNP growth was 2.5 percent in the first quarter. The government
is targeting GNP growth at 3 percent to 4 percent for the full
year.
	   Losers trampled gainers, 67 to 13, while 46 issues closed
unchanged.
	   In currency trading, the peso closed slightly higher against the
dollar, with slack demand for the U.S. currency helping to buffer
the peso from the weaker regional currency trend.
	   But with the peso's last trade at a session-low of 39.240 pesos
to the dollar, the Philippine currency is likely to weaken in early
transactions Tuesday, dealers said.
	   The dollar averaged 39.072 pesos for the day, down from 39.127
pesos Friday.
	   Dealers said falls on regional stock markets, coupled with the
likelihood of contractions in a number of regional economies,
pressured Southeast Asian currencies.
	   Dealers said the peso is likely to continue tracking the
regional currency trend in coming sessions. 	   
</TEXT>
