<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Zambia-Kaunda, 2nd ADD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUSAKA: political enemies 
</HEADLINE>
URGENT
<TEXT>
	   Kaunda led Zambia to independence from British rule in 1964 and
held presidential office for 27 years until he was ousted by
Chiluba in the first democratic elections in 1991.
	   He briefly quit public life after that poll but staged a come
back he said was at the request of his supporters.
	   His outspoken attacks angered the government. In 1995, he was
arrested twice this year for addressing unauthorized political
meetings and ruling party lawmakers passed a constitutional
amendment disqaulifying him from running again for presidential
office on grounds his parents were born in neighboring Malawi.
	   Kaunda had vowed to regain power, and his oppositon alliance
boycotted elections a year later that easily retained Chiluba's
Movement for Mulitparty Democracy party in office.
	   The amendment targeted at Kaunda limited the presidency to
second generation Zambians.
	   Kaunda, a former teacher and lay preacher, has never disputed
his parents were immigrants from eastern neighbor Malawi, where
they were born.
	   Facing trial in Lusaka for alleged links to the failed October
coup are Dean Mung'omba, head of the small Zambia Democratic
Congress party and Nakatindi Wina, a wealthy businesswoman and
tribal princess from western Zambia who headed the women's wing of
Chiluba's ruling party.
	   Wina and Mung'omba, a former banker and finance ministry
official in Chiluba's government, were alleged to have plotted with
rebel army officers and bankrolled the coup attempt.
	   Mung'omba's lawyers have alleged he was severely tortured by
police to make him confess.
	   The government has promised Western donors it will investigate
allegations of torture by several coup suspects.
	     (as-tl) 	   
</TEXT>
