<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Markets plunge on recession fears; inflation at three-year high 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Thai stocks and the currency took a
beating Monday on fears of a deepening recession in Asia, while new
inflation figures showed the country is suffering the stiffest
price hikes in three years.
	   The Stock Exchange of Thailand fell 11.35 points, or 3.5
percent, to 314.24 at midday as investors sold shares in banks and
finance companies, which are struggling to recapitalize after the
government said last week the economy could shrink 5.5 percent this
year.
	   The baht slid past 41 to the U.S. dollar for the first time
since March 18. The dollar had strengthened to 41.25 baht by
midday, up from 40.33 at the close Friday.
	   The Thai government revised its recession estimates downward
last week under its latest talks with the International Monetary
Fund on the dlrs 17.2 billion IMF-managed economic rescue package
for the country.
	   Among conditions Thailand is supposed to meet for IMF help is to
keep inflation at an average of 10.5 percent this year, but some
analysts predict the average is likely to be 12 percent.
	   The Commerce Ministry released figures Monday showing that
consumer prices rose 10.2 percent year-on-year in May, marking the
biggest increase in more than three years.
	   Inflation has been rising since July 1997, when Thailand
abandoned its fixed-exchange rate system after foreign reserves
were drained in a futile defense of the baht.
	   The weakness in the economy revealed by the de facto devaluation
sparked a chain reaction of economic meltdowns across Asia. 	   
</TEXT>
