</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Zambia-Kaunda, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kaunda freed as state withdraws coup allegations 
</HEADLINE>
URGENT
Eds: COMBINES urgent series, ADDS byline
By ANGUS SHAW
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) _ Former President Kenneth Kaunda was freed
by a court Monday after spending five months under house arrest for
allegedly knowing about plans for coup by junior military officers
last year.
	   Kaunda, 74, waved to supporters on the steps of the Lusaka High
Court after state prosecutors dropped the case against him,
apparently on lack of evidence.
	   Also freed by Judge Japhet Banda was Moyce Kaulungombe, a senior
bodyguard of Kaunda, 74. Both men were charged with concealing
prior knowledge of an Oct. 28 coup attempt by junior military
officers that was quickly crushed by loyal troops.
	   Attorney General Bonaventure Mutale told Banda the state entered
a plea of ``nolle prosequi,'' the legal term for ``no
prosecution,'' a procedure normally used when the state lacks
sufficient evidence or does not wish to proceed with its case.
	   ``This means the state doesn't wish to proceed further. You are
discharged so you are free men,'' Banda told Kaunda and his
bodyguard.
	   Kaunda, wearing a long white beard grown since his arrest on
Christmas, was mobbed by hundreds of cheering supporters outside
the court before being driven off to an unspecified destination.
	   The drama came on the first day of the trials of 81 suspects _
most of them soldiers _ who were arrested after junior officers
stormed the state broadcast center and claimed to have overthrown
the government of President Frederick Chiluba.
	   Kaunda repeatedly denied charges against him that carry a
penalty of possible life imprisonment. Most of the other suspects
are charged with treason and face the death sentence.
	   Kaunda, head of an 11-party opposition alliance, was out of the
country during the coup attempt and accused the government of using
it to crush political enemies.
	   Kaunda led Zambia to independence from British rule in 1964 and
held presidential office for 27 years until he was ousted by
Chiluba in the first democratic elections in 1991.
	   He briefly quit public life after that poll but staged a come
back he said was at the request of his supporters.
	   His outspoken attacks angered the government. In 1995, he was
arrested twice this year for addressing unauthorized political
meetings and ruling party lawmakers passed a constitutional
amendment disqaulifying him from running again for presidential
office on grounds his parents were born in neighboring Malawi.
	   Kaunda had vowed to regain power, and his oppositon alliance
boycotted elections a year later that easily retained Chiluba's
Movement for Mulitparty Democracy party in office.
	   The amendment targeted at Kaunda limited the presidency to
second generation Zambians.
	   Kaunda, a former teacher and lay preacher, has never disputed
his parents were immigrants from eastern neighbor Malawi, where
they were born.
	   Facing trial in Lusaka for alleged links to the failed October
coup are Dean Mung'omba, head of the small Zambia Democratic
Congress party and Nakatindi Wina, a wealthy businesswoman and
tribal princess from western Zambia who headed the women's wing of
Chiluba's ruling party.
	   Wina and Mung'omba, a former banker and finance ministry
official in Chiluba's government, were alleged to have plotted with
rebel army officers and bankrolled the coup attempt.
	   Mung'omba's lawyers have alleged he was severely tortured by
police to make him confess.
	   The government has promised Western donors it will investigate
allegations of torture by several coup suspects.
	     (as-tl)
</TEXT>
