<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Markets plunge as Taiwan fears impact of Asian crisis 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Currency and share prices both fell
sharply on Monday as investors worried that Asia's financial crisis
will have a widening impact on Taiwan.
	   The Taiwan dollar fell 24.1 cents to 34.23 to one U.S. dollar.
That is the lowest point in almost five months and a 20 percent
plunge since the Asian crisis began last summer.
	   Traders said the Central Bank spent between U.S. dlrs 70 million
and dlrs 80 million to support the local currency and prevent its
free fall.
	   But selling pressure was heavy. Foreign stock funds bought huge
amounts of U.S. dollars after they sold shares in the stock market,
one dealer at a European bank said.
	   The Weighted Price Index of the Taiwan Stock Exchange fell
297.09 points, or 3.75 percent, to close at 7,606.25. It was the
stock market's worst tumble this year, following declines last week
as investors bailed out because of worries over the local
currency's depreciation.
	   Traders also attributed the market's plunge to concerns over the
slowdown in the economy, citing a 4.56 percent fall in export
orders in April.
	   Taiwan has so far escaped the Asian financial crisis largely
unscathed. Economic growth has been sustained by increased spending
on infrastructure projects despite a 5.6 percent fall in exports in
the first three months this year.
	   But business people are concerned exports could drop further
because of economic troubles in Hong Kong and Japan, Taiwan's two
major trading partners.
	   ``The impact on the stock market is largely psychological,''
dealer Yeh Shun-tai said. ``But it is very likely that Taiwan's
industries and property markets could feel the brunt sooner or
later.''
</TEXT>
