<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Center-right rebuffs leaders rebuff more talk on Italian reform 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Leaders of the center-right opposition headed by
media mogul Silvio Berlusconi have rebuffed calls to put off a key
parliamentary vote on political reform, state radio reported
Monday.
	   Premier Romano Prodi's center-left coalition has made the
reforms a major goal of the two-year-old government, and some
parliamentary leaders last week raised the prospect of early
elections if 17 months of legislative efforts to change the system
yield nothing.
	   RAI radio said Gianfranco Fini, a right-wing leader and
Berlusconi's main ally in the opposition Freedom Alliance, turned
down a proposal from Franco Marini, an ex-Christian Democrat within
the alliance, to postpone the vote, which is set for Tuesday in the
Camera of Deputies.
	   Marini had suggested putting off the vote for a while so
politicians could search for a compromise.
	   The process stalled over a demand by Berlusconi, a former
conservative premier, that the figure of the president be granted
power to dissolve Parliament at any time, not just when the premier
resigns.
	   Under the draft of proposals presented to Parliament by a
70-member multiparty committee, the president would be directly
elected instead of chosen by Parliament, as is the case now.
	   Italy's leftist parties strongly oppose increased presidential
powers.
	   After the downfall of Fascist dictator Benito Mussolini, writers
of the new constitution purposely created a weak central executive.
	   The reform committee also drew up plans to reshape the
legislature, grant more regional autonomy and create a greater
division between judges and prosecutors.
	   (fd)
</TEXT>
