<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Quake </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Strong earthquake strikes Russian Far East; no injuries 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A strong earthquake struck Russia's Far Eastern
Kamchatka peninsula on Monday, emergency officials said. There were
no immediate reports of damage or injuries.
	   The quake, which measured at magnitude 6.3, struck at 5:40 p.m.
local time (0540 GMT) was centered 100 kilometers (60 miles)
southeast of the region's capital of Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky, said
Vasily Yurchuk, spokesman for Russia's Emergencies Ministry. The
epicenter was below the Pacific Ocean, at a depth of 25 kilometers
(16 miles).
	   The peninsula, part of the Pacific Ring of Fire, is more than
7,000 kilometers (4,000 miles) east of Moscow.
	   Monday's quake followed eight temblors that struck the same
region on May 28, registering a high as magnitude 7, Yurchuk said.
	   (mr)
</TEXT>
