w2432  wstm-
r i     BC-SKorea-Labor 1stLd-Writethru   06-01 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Labor, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Militant labor group likely to cancel nationwide strike consultative body, CORRECTS president's visit to June 6-14 
</HEADLINE>
EDs: UPDATES with mainstream labor group's decision to join
By KYONG-HWA SEOK
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Bowing to public pressure, South
Korea's militant workers appeared ready Monday to withdraw their
strike threats and negotiate their differences with the government.
	   Reversing its previous stance, the Federation of Korean Trade
Unions said it will join a government-proposed consultative
committee to discuss ways to salvage South Korea's battered
economy.
	   The federation claims 1.5 million members in white-collar and
small-business jobs.
	   Meanwhile, the Korean Confederation of Trade Unions, a smaller
but more militant labor group, indicated it may call off a
nationwide strike scheduled for next week during President Kim
Dae-jung's visit to the United States.
	   The confederation, which claims a membership of 500,000 in auto,
shipbuilding and other heavy industries, had planned to cap a
recent series of labor strikes and protests with a large-scale
strike on June 10 to protest growing layoffs.
	   ``A much feared government-labor confrontation may be averted,''
the all-news cable television network, Yonhap TV, reported.
	   The government has been trying to lure union leaders into a
consultative body of representatives from the government, labor and
management to resolve labor problems through dialogue.
	   A similar body, formed in January, succeeded in adopting a pact
that made layoffs easier, a major concession by workers accustomed
to lifetime employment during South Korea's boom years.
	   But labor leaders later accused the government and management of
laying off workers en masse while dragging their feet on
implementing promised benefits to the unions.
	   Critics warned that a new strike could hurt efforts by President
Kim to attract foreign investment during his June 6-14 visit to the
United States.
	   ``We intend to fully cooperate (with the government) so that
President Kim Dae-jung's state visit to the United States will be
successful,'' a statement from the confederation said.
	   The confederation said it already has formed a high-ranking
negotiating team and urged the government to ``appear at the
negotiation table and make serious efforts to resolve pending
problems.''
	   A confederation official, requesting anonymity, said it was
possible that the strike could be canceled or delayed, depending on
``the attitude of the government.''
	   Officials at the Labor Ministry refused to discuss details but
acknowledged that both sides have been meeting to break the
stalemate.
	   State KBS-TV reported that the government has made fresh
promises to minimize layoffs, significantly increase unemployment
benefits and accelerate restructuring of South Korea's bloated,
family-oriented conglomerates, or chaebol _ key demands of labor
unions.
	   Thousands of workers clashed with riot police on May Day,
resulting in dozens of people injured. Protest rallies and street
demonstrations have since become almost a daily event.
	   Prosecutors are pushing criminal charges against more than 100
labor leaders for alleged involvement in a two-day strike by
autoworkers and other laborers last week.
	   Government figures show that the number of jobless people has
doubled to nearly 1.5 million and may top 2 million by the end of
this year. 	   
</TEXT>
