<SLUG> BC-Russia-Mir, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mir computer failure threatens U.S. shuttle launch successfully running first tests, UPGRADES attribution. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with crew trying again to restart computer,
AP Photos planned
By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ After running smoothly for months, Mir's skittish
central computer was out of order for a third day Monday,
threatening to postpone the Russian space station's last rendezvous
with a U.S. shuttle.
	   U.S. space shuttle Discovery is scheduled to lift off Tuesday
and dock with the station on Friday to pick up astronaut Andrew
Thomas, the seventh and last American to live on the Russian
outpost.
	   But that trip to the Mir is now in doubt since the shuttle can
only dock if the station's computer-controlled steering system
properly aligns it for the docking.
	   ``We hope that the crew will finally resolve the problem later
today,'' said Valery Lyndin, a spokesman for Russian Mission
Control.
	   He said space officials have not yet determined why Mir's
computer broke down on Saturday. Russian cosmonauts Talgat
Musabayev and Nikolai Budarin replaced it with another unit, but
the new unit failed on Sunday when they tried to switch it on.
	   ``They still have a lot of spares to fix the problem,'' Lyndin
told The Associated Press.
	   The crew resumed attempts to restart the computer later on
Monday and were running the first tests successfully. They will try
to put it back on line in the next few hours, Lyndin said.
	   During a chat with ground controllers, Musabayev said the
situation on board ``isn't bad'' but added that he was concerned
that it occurred on the eve of the shuttle's launch. ``I'm worried
not for myself, but for the flight program,'' he said.
	   Mir's computer repeatedly failed last year, prompting Russian
space officials to send up a replacement on a shuttle ferry flight
in January. That unit failed on Saturday after five months of
trouble-free operation. The station's crew has replaced it with a
back-up computer brought up by a Russian cargo ship.
	   Mir's main computer operates the station's motion control
system, and when it fails, the station's energy supply is
threatened because it can't keep its solar panels in optimum
alignment with the sun.
	   Depending on how much energy was lost, it can take from one to
three days to get the orientation system fully on-line.
	   Fortunately, when the latest trouble occurred, the station was
on the so-called solar orbit, which puts it in direct sunlight
round the clock. As a result, the Mir's solar panels have remained
in full sunlight.
	   The crew also shut down some systems to save energy, and as a
result Mir's batteries were full on Monday, which will make it
easier for the crew to restore the orientation system, Lyndin said.
	   (vi/mr)
</TEXT>
