<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Smuggling </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China reports smuggling by sea up 81 percent 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Smuggling autos, cashmere and other commodities
by sea in China increased 81 percent in the first quarter of the
year compared with the same period last year, state news media
reported Monday.
	   Chemicals, oil, autos and spare parts, cashmere, edible oil,
steel and computers were the main items smuggled, the government's
Xinhua News Agency reported.
	   By sneaking goods into China, smugglers hope to avoid paying
import tariffs and thus to pocket larger profits.
	   The report quoted Outlook, a state-run magazine, as saying 1,229
smuggling cases were uncovered in the first quarter of the year,
mostly in the south. It did not give a reason for the increase.
	   Most of the seizures were in the southern province of Guangdong;
Beibu Gulf in Guangxi, west of Guangdong; Haikou, the capital of
the southern island province of Hainan; Xiamen, Quanzhou and
Fuzhou, cities in southeastern China's Fuzhou province. Another
major smuggling point was Dalian in northeastern China's Liaoning
province.
	   China plans a national meeting about fighting smuggling in June,
Outlook reported. 	   
</TEXT>
