w2448  wstm-
r i     BC-Taiwan-China-Military     06-01 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-China-Military </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwan spy chief warns of Chinese invasion capability 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Redeployment and renewal have made China's
forces capable of invading Taiwan, and its military is devoted to
training for the task, Taiwan's spy chief said Monday.
	   New weapons and advances in electronic warfare have vastly
increased the threat to Taiwan from China's military, Yin
Tsung-wen, director of the National Security Bureau, said in a rare
public appearance.
	   Meanwhile, the reduction of other defense concerns has allowed
the People's Liberation Army to train exclusively for an invasion
of Taiwan, Yin told an audience of university students in a pitch
for new recruits.
	   Yin's comments reflect the seriousness with which Taiwan's
leaders view the military threat from China, and their
determination to keep the public focused on defense.
	   Two years of military service are required of all Taiwanese
males, but the services have difficulty recruiting professional
soldiers. The government also has difficulty persuading the public
to remain vigilant. Business clamors for closer economic links with
China.
	   China claims sovereignty over Taiwan, and threatens to invade if
the island declares formal independence. Taiwan was ruled for 50
years as a Japanese colony until 1945, and split from China again
in 1949 at the end of the Chinese civil war.
	   Most foreign observers discount China's ability to launch a
full-blown invasion, citing deficiencies in its air and sea lift
capacities. Taiwan also has its own formidable defenses.
	   But officials here refer to the Chinese threat in dire terms. A
Defense Ministry white paper issued in March warned China is now
capable of at least a partial blockade of Taiwan, and said China's
missiles could cripple its military and civil institutions.
	   Yin said a Chinese invasion would begin with an electronic
assault on Taiwan's communications and financial networks, followed
by missile attacks, a fight for control of airspace and coastal
seas, and finally a ground invasion.
	   The Soviet Union's breakup allowed China to move forces
stationed on its northern border into coastal provinces opposite
Taiwan, Yin said. Missile tests and war games held near Taiwan in
1995-96 were examples of the PLA's single-minded devotion to an
invasion, Yin said.
	   China staged those exercises, which included firing missiles
just 35 kilometers (21 miles) from Taiwan's coast, in an attempt to
intimidate those advocating the island's independence.
	   Yin said the major intelligence threat to Taiwan came not from
Beijing's spies here, who he said number less than 100, but from
Taiwanese who visit China. His bureau has stepped up surveillance
of Taiwanese suspected of funneling military and technological
secrets to China, he said. 	   
</TEXT>
