w2452  wstm-
r i     BC-SKorea-Trade     06-01 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Trade </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Korean exports decrease for first time in four months 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Exports, the engine of South Korea's
economy, decreased slightly in May for the first time in four
months, dimming hopes for a fast economic recovery.
	   Exports in May dropped by 2.6 percent to dlrs 11.4 billion from
the same month last year, the first monthly drop since January, the
Ministry of Industry and Energy said Monday.
	   Imports in May also fell 37.5 percent to dlrs 7.7 billion from a
year ago, mainly because of depressed domestic consumption and
facility investment and falling oil prices.
	   That created a dlrs 3.7 billion trade surplus in May, the
seventh straight monthly gain, and pushed South Korea's total trade
surplus so far this year to dlrs 16.1 billion.
	   But analysts said the continuing trade surplus is unhealthy
because it results from sharply decreasing imports rather than
increased exports, which have led the country's economic expansion.
	   Officials attributed the decreased May exports to the financial
difficulties in Asia, where many currencies were sharply devaluated
in recent months.
	   Asian countries have traditionally consumed about half of South
Korean exports. But Korean exports to the region fell by 10 percent
between January and April.
	   ``I believe the incentives of the weak Korean won, or price
competitiveness of Korean products by currency devaluation, are
already gone,'' said Lee Pil-sang, an economics professor at Korea
University.
	   The Korean won has lost nearly half of its value since late
1996. But other Asian currencies were also devaluated, ranging
between 16 percent for Japan and 80 percent for Indonesia.
	   The weak currencies, especially the Japanese yen, hurt Korean
exports in the international markets as the nation's key exports
such as semiconductor, steel, ships, and home appliances compete
with Japanese exports.
	   Lee also said that the decreasing South Korean imports of raw
materials could affect future South Korean exports.
	   ``Fewer imports of raw materials now means fewer exports in the
future. The impact has been little so far, but it will be bigger
and bigger,'' Lee said. ``Considering all, the prospect for our
exports in coming months is quite gloomy.''
	   South Korea began to post trade surpluses in November when the
surplus reached dlrs 120 million. It reported a record trade
surplus of dlrs 3.91 billion in April.
	   The nation recorded a trade deficit of dlrs 528 million in May,
last year. The total 1997 trade deficit reached dlrs 8.5 billion.
	   South Korea called in the International Monetary Fund in
December to bail out an economy on the verge of collapse under the
weight of over dlrs 150 billion in foreign debts. 	   
</TEXT>
