u i     BC-Israel-Palestinians     06-01 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cabinet meeting ends without decision on West Bank withdrawal 
</HEADLINE>
By DINA KRAFT
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Despite growing U.S. pressure on Israel to make
a decision, Israel's Cabinet on Monday again failed to reach
agreement on the the scope of a West Bank troop withdrawal.
	   Israel's continued indecision is likely to further strain ties
with the United States which reportedly has demanded an Israeli
answer within several days to its proposal for a pullback from 13
percent of the West Bank.
	   However, U.S. ultimatums to Israel have come and gone in the
past month without repercussions for Israel, and it appeared Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was more concerned about the survival
of his government than about possible U.S. censure.
	   A U.S. official said Monday he did not expect the Clinton
administration to make good on veiled threats to announce the
failure of the U.S. peace initiative and blame Israel. Instead,
Washington will give Israel more time to reach a decision, said the
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
	   Far-right Cabinet ministers have threatened to topple the
government if Netanyahu agreed to a 13 percent pullback.
	   ``A 13 percent withdrawal would be a disaster for Jewish
settlements,'' Transport Minister Shaul Yahalom from the National
Religious Party told Israel radio Monday. ``We cannot agree. We
were assured by the prime minister that there would be no troop
redeployment that will hurt the settlements.''
	   The Jewish Settlers' Council on Monday launched a campaign to
turn Israeli public opinion against a 13 percent troop pullback.
Recent polls have suggested that a large majority in Israel want
Netanyahu to forge ahead with the peace negotiations and agree to a
troop withdrawal. In the settlers' campaign, brochures were mailed
to 1 million homes in Israel, with maps illustrating the settlers'
arguments that a pullback would endanger water resources, Israeli
security and control over Jewish holy sites.
	   U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has been trying for
months to break the deadlock between Israel and the Palestinians on
the pullback. The Palestinians have accepted the U.S. proposal for
an immediate 13 percent pullback, to be followed by another
significant withdrawal whose scope has not been determined.
	   Israel radio and the Maariv daily reported Monday that Netanyahu
was considering a 15 percent pullback in three stages. Netanyahu's
adviser, David Bar-Illan, was not immediately available for
comment, but the radio said Netanyahu denied the report.
	   On Monday morning, Netanyahu first met with Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai and Infrastructures Minister Ariel Sharon, and
the three failed to reach agreement on a troop pullback, Israel
radio said. Sharon, a former defense minister, insists that handing
over more than 9 percent would endanger Israel's security.
	   Mordechai told the daily the Yediot Ahronot daily before the
meetingt that ``the time has come to make decisions on everything
connected to the peace talks and the Palestinians.''
	   After consulting with his ``kitchen Cabinet,'' Netanyahu
convened all of the ministers to discuss the pullback. The
two-and-a-half hour meeting produced no result.
  kl
</TEXT>
