<HEADER>
w2459  wstm-
r f     BC-Singapore-Economy 2ndLd-Writethru   06-01 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Economy, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Finance chief: recession unlikely this year exports. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: RECASTS throughout with updates, quotes; UPDATES with market
figures and reaction; CORRECTS figure in graf 14 is for May non-oil
By JONATHAN DRAKE
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Singapore's economy is unlikely to slip into a
recession this year despite a trend toward negative growth in
Southeast Asia, Finance Minister Richard Hu told Parliament on
Monday, but the markets were unconvinced.
	   ``The overall picture of the Singapore economy is one of
uncertainty,'' Hu told Parliament. But he stood by an earlier
government forecast of 2.5 percent to 4.5 percent in economic
growth this year.
	   Meanwhile, the government minister who heads the national trade
unions said layoffs this year would exceed the peak of 20,000 who
lost their jobs during the 1985-86 recession.
	   Some private analysts and economists have forecast Singapore's
economy slowing this year to about 1.5 percent GDP growth. Three
major international investment houses have predicted recession.
	   Singapore's already bearish market fell on the recession
jitters, with the benchmark Straits Times Industrial Index falling
1.6 percent to close at 1,234.57 points. Also, Singapore's currency
fell against the U.S. dollar to 1.69 in late trading.
	   Dealers said Hu's assurances that Singapore won't slip into a
recession this year run counter to growing pessimism among some
private economists and fears of recession elsewhere in the region.
He failed to calm market nerves.
	   ``Because we do a lot of trade with our neighbors, demand drops,
and I think if the second half of this year is worse, some
companies will have to trim costs by cutting down the work force,''
Lim Boon Heng, who is secretary-general of the National Trade
Unions Congress and also a minister without portfolio in the
government, said Sunday. he predicted record unemployment by the
end of the year.
	   Finance Minister Hu said off-budget measures to stimulate the
economy would be decided on in late June or July.
	   ``As the Singapore economy is fairly well diversified, we are
unlikely to slip into negative growth this year as our growth will
be supported by the relatively healthy performance in the U.S. and
(European Union) economies,'' Hu said.
	   But he indicated that signs of a contraction might necessitate
special economic measures ``sooner rather than later.''
	   ``We will not wait for GDP growth to go negative before we do
something,'' Hu said. ``If the trend is clearly going to head in
that direction we will try to do something.''
	   Hu said that once the May figures are available in mid-June, the
government would have a clearer picture of second-quarter economic
developments and could react with tax cuts or rebates.
	   ``We would like to look at the May figures before we react,'' Hu
said in response to questions from members of parliament over
whether the government was responding quickly enough. ``Certainly
its not too long to wait for a few weeks.''
	   The finance minister also warned preliminary data showed non-oil
domestic exports dropping by 6 percent in May.
	   Meanwhile, Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong said that
Singapore is still offering up to dlrs 5 billion in financing of
Indonesian trade through Singapore, despite the abrupt change in
government in Jakarta.
	   Lee told Parliament that the money, which is supplemental to a
rescue plan put together by the International Monetary Fund,
wouldn't be released until IMF funding is reinstated. 	   
</TEXT>
