<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Heat Wave,0330 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Devastating heat wave starts ebbing in India 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ The severe heat began abating Monday in
northern India after killing a reported 800 people across the
country last month.
	   Light showers and dust storms on Sunday brought some relief to
people in parts of Jammu-Kashmir state and New Delhi.
Meteorologists said the day temperatures were unlikely to rise any
further.
	   Temperatures on Sunday hovered between 108-120 degrees (42-49
degrees Celsius) in several parts of the country.
	   The first monsoon showers were expected to hit the southern
state of Kerala on Monday. Pre-monsoon thundershowers were expected
to cool some northern regions on Monday or early Tuesday, according
to the New Delhi weather office.
	   In the western desert province of Rajasthan and the northern
states of Uttar Pradesh, Bihar, Orissa and Madhya Pradesh, this
year's summer has been the hottest in three years. The highest
temperature of the season _ 120 degrees (49 degrees Celsius) _ was
recorded in Rajasthan nearly two weeks ago.
	   Local news agencies put the heat-related death toll over the
last month at least 800. A meteorologist argued the blistering
summer was not all that unusual.
	   ``The normal temperature this time of the year was 44 Celsius
(111 Fahrenheit) and a five degrees rise on a few occasions is not
wholly unexpected,'' United News of India news agency quoted D.S.
Desai as saying.
	   Indians had to bear with frequent power outages and insufficient
drinking water in most cities and towns. Protester came out on the
streets and burned police vehicles in New Delhi.
	   The upper house of Parliament decided Monday to discuss next
week the shortage of power and drinking water after some members
complained that parts of the federal capital have been without
power for days.
	   Hospitals overflowed with victims of heat stroke, dehydration
and flu in various parts of the country, officials said.
</TEXT>
