r i     BC-Germany-Iran     06-01 0353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Iran </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German, Iranian foreign minister to meet June 10 in New York 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ The German foreign minister and his Iranian
counterpart are to meet June 10 at a U.N. gathering in New York in
efforts to improve relations between their two countries, the
Foreign Ministry said Monday.
	   The meeting is the latest sign of European interest in resuming
full ties with Tehran since moderate Mohammad Khatami was elected
as Iran's president last summer.
	   Germany's Klaus Kinkel and Iran's Kamal Kharrazi also had a
``detailed'' telephone conversation late Sunday on bilateral
relations, the ministry said, declining to provide details. The two
ministers also spoke about the Pakistani and Indian nuclear tests
ahead of Kharrazi's trip this week to Pakistan, the ministry said.
	   Two German envoys traveled to Teheran May 11-12 in what was
believed to be the first visit there by foreign ministry officials
in 2 1/2 years.
	   In addition to diplomatic relations, they discussed the case of
German businessman Helmut Hofer. He was sentenced to death in
January under Islamic law for having sex with a 26-year-old medical
student, because she was Muslim and he was not. He has appealed the
sentence, claiming he converted to Islam several years ago.
	   Kinkel has said that executing Hofer would damage relations with
Iran.
	   An appeals court in Teheran last month sent the case back to the
original court. Foreign Ministry officials have said it is not
clear what effect that development would have on Hofer's appeal.
	   Iran's relations with the European Union are recovering from
last year's strains over a German court ruling that implicated
Tehran's highest rulers in the 1992 assassination of an
Iranian-Kurdish opposition figure at Berlin's Mykonos restaurant.
	   The verdict led the European Union to suspend its ``critical
dialogue'' policy of maintaining contacts with Iran, and all EU
countries except Greece recalled their ambassadors from Tehran.
	   A diplomatic thaw began late last year with the return of the
ambassadors.
	   (im)
</TEXT>
