<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asian Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Most Asian stock markets close sharply lower 
</HEADLINE>
EDS: ADDS Singapore closing figures
<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) - Most Asian markets tumbled Monday, pushed down
by rising fears of a recession and falling regional currencies.
	   In Taiwan, the key index fell 3.8 percent as investors feared
Asia's financial crisis will have a widening impact on the island's
economy.
	   Meanwhile, the Taiwan dollar fell 24.1 cents to 34.23 against
the U.S. dollar. The Taiwan currency has lost 20 percent of its
value since the regional economic crisis began last summer.
	   In Thailand, both shares prices and the currency slumped.
	   The Stock Exchange of Thailand index fell 12.55 points, or 3.8
percent, to 313.04, a new low for the year.
	   The Thai baht slid past 41 to the U.S. dollar for the first time
since March 18. The dollar had strengthened to 41.25 baht by
midday, up from 40.33 at the close Friday.
	   According to the latest government inflation figures, Thailand
is suffering the stiffest price hikes in three years.
	   Malaysian shares closed sharply lower, with the key index
falling 3.76 percent on the back of a weak currency.
	   The Kuala Lumpur stock Exchange's Composite Index closed at
518.00 points, down 20.24 points.
	   In currency trading, the dollar was quoted at 3.9275 ringgit,
compared to 3.8739 late Friday.
	   The Weighted Stock Price Index slumped 297.09 points to close at
7,606.25.
	   In Hong Kong, the Hang Seng Index fell 322.55 points, or 3.6
percent, to close at 8,612.01.
	   Investors were concerned over the government's announcement late
Friday that the Hong Kong economy contracted 2 percent in the first
quarter, brokers said.
	   The contraction in the first quarter was the first in 13 years.
	   Deepening worries over the state of Japan's economy triggered a
2.23 percent decline in the Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index on
Monday and drove the U.S. dollar higher against the yen.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 349.75 points,
closing at 15,321.03 points. On Friday, the index had shed 125.77
points, or 0.80 percent.
	   In late trading, the dollar was quoted at 139.12 yen, up 0.40
yen from late Friday in Tokyo and also above its late New York
level of 138.90 yen Friday. The dollar rose as high as 139.33 yen,
a level not seen since early July 1991.
	   On Friday, the government said Japan's jobless rate hit a record
4.1 percent, up from 3.9 percent in March.
	   The market was closed in New Zealand for a holiday.
	   Elsewhere:
	   SINGAPORE: Shares closed mostly lower in line with regional
markets. The benchmark Straits Times Industrial Index closed down
20.34 points, or 1.6 percent, to 1,234.59.
	   JAKARTA: Share prices closed lower on worries over the
Indonesian economy. The JSX Composite Index fell 1.5 percent, or
6.386 points, to 414.079.
	   MANILA: Philippine share prices closed lower for the seventh
straight session, with foreign investors remaining sidelined due to
political and economic concerns in Asia. The Philippine Stock
Exchange Index of 30 selected stocks fell 15.40 points, or 0.7
percent, to 1,996.05.
	   SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed lower in sluggish trading
on renewed investor nervousness over Asian markets. The All
Ordinaries Index fell 26.6 points, or 0.9 percent, to 2,689.1.
	   SEOUL: Share prices closed higher as worries about labor unrest
in the country eased. The Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose
4.67 points, or 1.4 percent, to 336.70. 	   
</TEXT>
