<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Congo-Rebel Surrender </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Defense ministry: 500 rebels surrender in Congo's east 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) _ As many as 500 ethnic Mai-Mai rebels have
surrendered in northeastern Congo after a series of government
military operations against their bases, the Ministry of Defense
confirmed Monday.
	   The mass surrender follows a series of government military
operations to clear out the Mai-Mai rebels and their allies from
the area around the town of Goma, near the Rwandan border.
	   ``We launched these operations along the border between the
Democratic Republic of Congo and Rwanda,'' said Maj. Ande Kanou, a
commander with Kabila's forces in Goma. ``The results you will see
are the young Mai-Mai who came out.''
	   After toppling the late dictator Mobutu Sese-Seko and coming to
power a year ago this month, Kabila has been struggling to quell
growing unrest among the Mai-Mai rebel forces in eastern Congo _
formerly Zaire.
	   State-run television over the weekend said the Mai-Mai had been
used for cover by military operatives from Rwanda, but did not
elaborate.
	   The Mai-Mai reportedly draw strength from the former Rwandan
Armed Forces along with support from militia groups elsewhere in
Rwanda and neighboring Uganda.
	   The Mai-Mai, whose name in Swahili means `magic water,' are made
up of fighters from tribes in eastern Congo who joined the Kabila
rebel alliance that ousted Mobutu.
	   They subsequently turned against Kabila, mainly in protest
against the presence of ethnic Tutsis from neighboring Rwanda and
eastern Congo in the new army and local administration.
	   Tutsi fighters from Rwanda played an important role in Kabila's
rebel war last year, but also stand accused of widespread massacres
against Rwandan Hutu refugees in Congo.
	   Kanou said Congolese forces had launched several attacks on
camps in North Kivu province used by the Mai-Mai and their allies
along the border with Rwanda. Few details of the operations were
made available.
	   Security in eastern Congo has been steadily deteriorating with
reports of Mai-Mai fighters joining other disgruntled groups in
staging sporadic attacks against road convoys and populated areas.
  (km/ids)
</TEXT>
