r i     BC-Afghanistan-Quake 2ndLd-Writethru   06-01 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-Quake, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0589 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Aid supplies begin to reach quake-stricken area in Afghanistan 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: EDITS throughout to trim.
AP Photos LON108-109
By PHIL GOODWIN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   FAISABAD, Afghanistan (AP) _ Aircraft loaded with emergency aid
left Pakistan on Monday for remote northern Afghanistan, where
soldiers dug through the rubble of villages leveled by a powerful
earthquake in search of buried victims.
	   The quake, which hit Saturday with a preliminary magnitude of
6.9, flattened entire villages, sliced mountains and triggered
landslides. Thousands are feared dead.
	   ``We saw a couple of villages that had been completely
flattened, but there were probably more,'' said Alfredo
Witschi-Cestari, head of the U.N. humanitarian aid office in
neighboring Pakistan.
	   ``This is a mountainous region and the force of the earthquake
sent houses crashing down the hillsides toward the valleys below,''
he said after visiting the site Sunday.
	   While initial estimates are putting the death toll at 3,000, aid
workers and local officials in the area expect it may rise to
5,000.
	   Among those killed were 140 schoolchildren in Rostaq, the site
of a Feb. 4 earthquake that killed as many as 2,300 people and left
another 8,000 homeless.
	   Many of the people affected were living in tents because they
lost their homes in the February quake.
	   Cargo aircraft in neighboring Pakistan, packed with emergency
supplies, were expected to reach the region later in the day, aid
workers said.
	   Tons of food, blankets, tents and plastic sheeting also were to
be loaded onto cargo helicopters Monday in the Pakistani capital of
Islamabad to be sent to Faisabad. From there, the supplies will be
forwarded to the areas that suffered the greatest damage.
	   The French Foreign Ministry also plans to send about 35 tons of
humanitarian aid to Dushanbe, Tajikistan, where it will be
transported to the disaster area.
	   The international Red Cross got one plane into Faisabad on
Sunday and was preparing to set up a clinic in the area.
	   ``We need help desperately. Thousands of people are dead,'' a
spokesman for a northern alliance fighting Afghanistan's Taliban
government said from the stricken area, near the border with
Tajikistan.
	   Opposition soldiers already had recovered 1,650 bodies, Shamshul
Haq Arianfar said. Speaking from Chaib, the alliance spokesman said
eight villages simply disintegrated.
	   U.N. officials flew over some of the most desolate and
hardest-hit regions Sunday, setting down briefly near the quake's
epicenter in Shari Basurkh, about 30 miles (50 kilometers) from the
Badakhshan provincial capital of Faisabad.
	   They delivered tents, plastic sheeting, and materials for an
emergency clinic to be set up in Shari Basurkh for the many
wounded. The officials said 4,100 houses were destroyed.
	   The area's sun-baked mud homes, already weakened by the February
temblor, crumbled like dry dust in Saturday's violent shaking. The
homes were more vulnerable by the relentless rain that battered the
region in recent days.
	   Aid organization officials in neighboring Tajikistan were told
by the Afghan ambassador that 5,000 people were killed. The Red
Cross said it was not able to confirm the figure.
	   According to the report, the dead included 3,000 killed in Shari
Basurkh, almost 1,900 in a settlement on the outskirts of Faisabad,
the 140 schoolchildren in Rostaq and 124 people in Chaib, on
Afghanistan's border with Tajikistan.
</TEXT>
