<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Telecommunications </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Major telecommunications conference opens 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ The number of telephone lines in the
Asia-Pacific region grew by a whopping 27 percent, making it the
fastest growing telephone market in the world, according to a
leading telecommunications expert.
	   Still, the Asia-Pacific region only accounts for 20 percent of
the world's telephone lines, though 53 percent of the world
population lives in this region, said Deputy Secretary-General of
the International Telecommunications Union Henry Chasia.
	   Chasia spoke at Monday's opening of the CommunicAsia
98/NetworkAsia98, a massive trade show with the latest telephone,
computer and broadcast technology on display. The annual show is
Singapore's second largest trade fair.
	   ``In 1997 teledensity was two times that of any other region,''
he said, adding that the cellular phone market had also grown by 70
percent.
	   ``This community is fighting back with new and innovative
changes that have been made possible by digital technology,'' he
said. ``This technology allows for the expansion in voice, data,
facsimile and audio visual technology that has previously been
confined to restrictions and national borders.''
	   The ITU suggests private investors, global organizations and
governments will be responsible to meet the monetary needs of the
expanding Asia-Pacific region.
	   This deregulation process will give the Asia-Pacific region 35
percent of the global wireless market by the year 2000, Chasia
said. By the year 2007, Singapore likely will have 50 percent of
the world pager market since it already has the highest pay-phone
density in the world.
	   Displays at the booths for NetworkAsia, CommunicAsia,
BroadcastAsia, CableSat98 and MobileCommAsia show how the different
communications sectors are increasingly interrelated. The
exhibition, in its 12th year, is attended by 1,800 companies from
46 countries. 	   
</TEXT>
