<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0781 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 1100 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   HONG KONG (AP) - Most Asian markets tumbled Monday, pushed down
by rising fears of a recession and falling regional currencies. In
Taiwan, the key index fell 3.8 percent as investors feared Asia's
financial crisis will have a widening impact on the island's
economy. Meanwhile, the Taiwan dollar fell 24.1 cents to 34.23
against the U.S. dollar. The Taiwan currency has lost 20 percent of
its value since the regional economic crisis began last summer. In
Thailand, both shares prices and the currency slumped. The Stock
Exchange of Thailand index fell 12.55 points, or 3.8 percent, to
313.04, a new low for the year. In Hong Kong, the Hang Seng Index
fell 322.55 points, or 3.6 percent, to close at 8,612.01. Investors
were concerned over the government's announcement late Friday that
the Hong Kong economy contracted 2 percent in the first quarter,
brokers said. (ASIAN MARKETS)
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Enlisting reinforcements to battle
Indonesia's most daunting economic crisis in 30 years, new
President B.J. Habibie has named a fresh team of economic advisers,
State Secretary Akbar Tanjung said Monday. The team includes
economist Widjojo Nitisastro, who headed a team of advisers set up
earlier this year by former President Suharto, former Finance
Minister Frans Seda, and Ali Wardhana, also formerly an adviser to
Suharto. Akbar said the new team will advise the president on all
problems affecting the crisis-ridden Indonesian economy and on the
government's negotiations with the International Monetary Fund.
Their advice will supplement the work of Habibie's economic
ministers, led by Coordinating Minister for the Economy, Industry
and Finance Ginandjar Kartasasmita. Ginandjar and his team met last
week in Jakarta with Hubert Neiss, the IMF's director for Asia and
Pacific Affairs. They predicted the economy will contract by at
least 10 percent this year. (INDONESIA-ECONOMY)
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia's nervous markets sank farther in early
trading Monday despite U.S. promises to support new loans by
international lenders. In a brief statement issued Sunday,
President Bill Clinton expressed U.S. support for aid to Russia
from such multinational institutions as the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund. Nonetheless, by midday the stock
market was down an additional 4.5 percent, although traders said
there was little panic selling. Russian leaders have been working
to stabilize the financial markets after a wave of panic selling
last week caused the stock market to plummet and threatened a run
on the national currency, the ruble. Altogether the stock market is
down 40 percent since April. The Central Bank has intervened to
prop up the ruble and raised interest rates to 150 percent to
convince investors to stay in Russia. (RUSSIA-ECONOMY)
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Singapore's economy is unlikely to slip into a
recession this year despite a trend toward negative growth in
Southeast Asia, Finance Minister Richard Hu told Parliament on
Monday, but the market was unconvinced. Meanwhile, the government
minister who heads the national trade unions said layoffs this year
would exceed the 20,000 who lost their jobs during the 1985-86
recessions. ``The overall picture of the Singapore economy is one
of uncertainty,'' Hu told Parliament. But he stood by an earlier
government forecast of 2.5 percent to 4.5 percent in economic
growth this year. Some private analysts and economists have begun
predicting Singapore's economy would contract this year with a GDP
of no more than 1.5 percent. Three major international investment
houses have predicted recession. (SINGAPORE-ECONOMY)
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Pacific rim countries could sign an agreement
this week that would simplify certification of communication
equipment and allow foreign manufacturers greater access to Asia, a
U.S. official said Monday. Communications equipment such as
cellular phones and modems currently must meet technological
standards and be certified in each of the countries where they'll
be used. The Mutual Recognition Agreement would allow manufacturers
to get their equipment certified by agencies in their own
countries, lowering the cost to consumers and getting the products
to market faster, said Larry Irving, assistant secretary of
communications and information at the U.S. Department of Commerce.
The United States and the European Union already have a similar
agreement. (ASIA-COMMUNICATIONS)
</TEXT>
