<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0743 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>

</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ India on Monday denied Pakistani
allegations that it plans to continue the nuclear test tit-for-tat
that has raised tensions in this already volatile region. Foreign
Ministry spokesman K.C. Singh said a statement from Pakistani
Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan that India was surreptitiously
preparing to conduct more tests next month was ``surprising.''
``India has declared a moratorium on testing and this has been
reiterated by the prime minister himself,'' Singh said. India was
the first to escalate the long-standing Indo-Pakistan rivalry to
the nuclear level with five tests May 11-13. In response, Pakistan
claimed to have detonated six nuclear devices last week. Pakistan
has not said whether it would test again. U.S. intelligence sources
said over the weekend they had detected no signs that either
Pakistan or India was readying new tests. (INDIA-PAKISTAN)
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ India's business press fretted Monday
over how the government's new budget would cope with anti-nuclear
sanctions, a widening deficit, rising inflation and a failing
rupee. Finance Minister Yashwant Sinha was to present the budget to
Parliament in a speech Monday evening. His government has promised
to revive India's economic growth, which faltered to 5 percent in
the fiscal year 1997-98, the lowest rate in the last five years. To
do that, experts say, Sinha will have to spend on infrastructure
and encourage investment. His revenue options have been reduced
since the United States, Australia, Japan and other nations cut off
loans and all but humanitarian aid to punish India for conducting
five nuclear tests May 11-13. (INDIA-BUDGET)
	   FAISABAD, Afghanistan (AP) _ Aircraft laden with emergency aid
flew Monday to northern Afghanistan to help the victims of a
weekend earthquake that buried as many as 3,000 people, many still
struggling from a temblor that struck the region three months
before. The powerful magnitude-6.9 quake wiped out entire villages,
sliced mountains and triggered landslides. While initial estimates
are putting the death toll at 3,000, aid workers and local
officials in the area believe it could rise to 5,000. There are
thousands of people still missing and thousands more homeless.
``This is a mountainous region and the force of the earthquake sent
houses crashing down the hillsides toward the valleys below,'' said
Alfredo Witschi-Cestari, head of the U.N. humanitarian aid office
in neighboring Pakistan. (AFGHANISTAN-QUAKE)
	   PARIS (AP) _ Passengers were stranded Monday at airports across
France after Air France pilots began a strike that threatened to
disrupt travel plans during the World Cup soccer games. Monitors at
Paris' main airports offered a bleak sight for passengers:
``annule,'' _ canceled _ written in red next to almost all
international and domestic flights. The strike began at midnight
after Air France failed to reach an agreement with pilots seeking
to block wage cuts. Air France set up special telephone lines for
passengers seeking information on flights. There was no immediate
indication of how many flights were canceled or which routes were
most affected. Most of the company's aircraft _ many of them
decorated with players representing the 32 World Cup teams _
remained grounded Monday. Air France is the official carrier for
the World Cup. (AIR FRANCE-STRIKE)
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Mexico's government seized the nation's
largest airline on Monday after 1,033 unionized flight attendants
walked off the job. Members of the Unionized Association of Flight
Attendants went on strike at midnight, saying Aeromexico was
unwilling to negotiate better working conditions and benefits. The
government, saying national security was at state, temporarily
seized Aviacion de Mexico, which runs Mexico's largest airline, and
appointed an acting general administrator for the duration of the
strike. Under Mexico's constitution, the government can temporarily
seize companies considered vital to the nation's economy or
security so that they can continue to operate during emergencies.
Thousands of passengers were left in limbo, as the secretariat
official conceded that most of Aeromexico's 300 daily flights
wouldn't leave the ground. (MEXICO-AIRLINE STRIKE)
</TEXT>
