u i     BC-Saudi-OIC 1stLd-Writethru   06-01 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Saudi-OIC, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Islamic organization urges India-Pakistan talks after nuclear tests transition. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: INSERTS 5th graf with Bahrain statement; minor editing for
<TEXT>
	   JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) _ A leading Islamic organization on
Monday expressed ``deep concern'' over nuclear tests carried out
this month by India and Pakistan and urged immediate talks by the
two nations.
	   The Jiddah-based Organization of the Islamic Conference said in
a statement from its secretary-general, Azeddine Laraki, that it
had wanted the establishment of a nuclear weapon-free zone in South
Asia.
	   ``Following the latest nuclear explosions carried out by India
and Pakistan, the secretary-general of the Organization of the
Islamic Conference expressed his deep concern over this serious
development,'' the statement said.
	   ``In the wake of these nuclear explosions, the international
community must seriously encourage both India and Pakistan to
expediently conclude a non-aggression agreement with the aim of
ensuring the promotion of peace and security in the region,'' it
said.
	   The Gulf nation of Bahrain also urged both India and Pakistan to
exercise restraint to ensure peace and stability in the Indian
subcontinent. Government-controlled newspapers reported Monday that
Bahrain issued such a statement during Sunday's weekly cabinet
meeting.
	   India exploded five nuclear devices two weeks ago, prompting
Pakistan to follow suit despite warnings from the U.N. Security
Council, the United States and other nations.
	   Pakistan said it detonated five nuclear devices on Thursday and
another one Saturday.
	   India has fought three wars with Pakistan since both countries
gained independence from colonial British rule in 1947.
	   The 55-member Organization of the Islamic Conference said in its
statement that it hoped Pakistan's nuclear explosions would not
fuel anti-Muslim sentiment.
	   It urged ``international public opinion to foil every biased
attempt aimed at using the latest nuclear explosions as a pretext
to launch an unjustifiable offensive against the Islamic (world).''
It added that Islamic states have always supported elimination of
nuclear arms.
	   Pakistan is the only Muslim nation known to have developed a
nuclear bomb.
