w2488  wstm-
r i     BC-Thailand-ChildAbuse 1stLd-Writethru   06-01 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Child Abuse, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Globalization worsens child sexual abuse; clean governments needed 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: Notes Anand spoke in keynote address in 4th graf; ADDS quotes
from other speakers in grafs 10-16; name Ofelia is cq in 10th graf
By GRANT PECK
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Globalization is turning the world into
a more dangerous place for children to be exploited for sex, making
clean government and uncorrupt officials ever more necessary to
protect them, a former Thai prime minister said Monday.
	   ``It has become easier for the traffic in children by means of
abduction, tricks and enticements both within countries and across
borders,'' said Anand Panyarachun, opening a Asia-Pacific
conference on human resources development for youths.
	   The week-long conference, hosted by the United Nations' Economic
and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific, was told an
estimated 10 million children worldwide were working as
prostitutes, with some 1 million being added every year.
	   Meanwhile, the Internet has put a tool into the hands of
pornographers to spread thousands of sexual pictures of children
around the world at ``the push of a button,'' Anand said in a
keynote address.
	   ``Children are dealt with as commodities, traded and exchanged
as part of an increasingly borderless world,'' said Anand, who led
reformist governments in 1991 and 1992 in a country notorious for
child prostitution.
	   Currently the United Nations Children's Fund ambassador to
Thailand, Anand said that trafficking was abetted by governments
that allow corruption enabling law enforcement officials to turn a
blind eye to _ or help for profit _ gangs exploiting children.
	   Government transparency and enforcement of what Anand called
``child-friendly laws'' would go a long way toward cleaning up an
environment that allows the ``dark forces'' of corrupt police and
criminals exploiting children to thrive.
	   Anand suggested a series of measures to promote child rights and
good governance, including improved screening and training of law
enforcement personnel, more support and incentives for good law
enforcement and greater penalties for corruption.
	   Poverty breeds abuse and exploitation, Anand said, while lack of
access to education renders children more vulnerable to the sex
market. Family disintegration, migration and negative traditional
practices are also factors.
	   ``We cannot be forever insensitive to the cries for help of
these children,'' Ofelia Calceta-Santos of the Philippines, a
special U.N. investigator into the sale of children said at a panel
discussion.
	   To tackle the problem, she said, ``We need a wedding to have
good children, a wedding between governments and non-governmental
organizations.''
	   The head of a private multinational organization against child
sex abuse said there were perhaps as many as 1 million children
under the age of 16 held in virtual slavery in brothels in Asia.
	   ``Many of the children in brothels die quite young, of AIDS,
drugs, suicide,'' said Ron O'Grady, chairman of ECPAT _ End Child
Prostitution, Child Pornography and Trafficking.
	   O'Grady also warned that child pornography on the Internet is
widespread, easy to find, and cruel and insidious in its effects.
	   He said that foreign sex tourists often take videos of photos of
themselves abusing children, and can post them around the world on
the Internet within 24 hours.
	   ``The internet goes beyond national boundaries, breaking down
national laws,'' he said. ``In the 21st century national laws and
boundaries will become increasingly irrelevant.'' 	   
</TEXT>
