<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Corruption Probe </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian corruption probe to include Suharto businesses 
</HEADLINE>
With BC-Indonesia
<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Authorities have launched an
investigation of government corruption under ex-President Suharto
but have no plans to target the former leader, the attorney general
said Monday.
	   The inquiry is expected to encompass business dealings of
Suharto's family, which used its connections to make billions of
dollars from a wide range of industries during his three decades in
power.
	   As part of the general investigation, Attorney General Sudjono
Atmonegoro said he had received guarantees from Suharto's family
members that they would not leave Indonesia.
	   The probe will not specifically target Suharto and his family
although the former president may be summoned to check evidence, he
said at a news conference.
	   Critics say nepotism, corruption and cronyism that thrived under
Suharto contributed in large part to Indonesia's economic woes.
Suharto quit May 21 following riots over price increases and under
pressure from student protesters who occupied Parliament.
	   A leading opposition figure has called on Suharto to donate the
bulk of his wealth back to the country. Amien Rais, a prominent
Muslim leader, said that with the money Indonesia would not have to
beg for assistance from international agencies to prop up the
economy, which is in its worst crisis in 30 years. 	   
</TEXT>
