<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Religion </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Conservative leader hails co-ed prayer service as precedent 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ A decision by police to let men and women pray
together at the Western Wall despite violent protests by
ultra-Orthodox Jews set a ``historic precedent,'' the leader of the
Conservative stream of Judaism said Monday.
	   The Western Wall is Judaism's holiest site, and men and women
pray in segregated areas, in line with ultra-Orthodox practices. In
the past, police routinely moved followers of the more liberal
Reform and Conservative streams away from the Wall if they wanted
to hold co-ed services.
	   However, on Sunday, the Jewish holiday of Shavuot, police acted
as a human buffer to allow some 300 Reform and Conservative
worshippers to hold a two-hour prayer service at the Wall. Hundreds
of angry ultra-Orthodox Jews cursed the Reform and Conservative
worshippers and threw garbage and bags of chocolate milk over the
police barrier.
	   Rabbi Ehud Bandel, president of the Conservative movement in
Israel, said Monday that police set a ``historic precedent'' by
protecting the Conservative and Reform worshippers.
	   It was not immediately clear whether police had adopted a new
policy. Jerusalem police spokesman Shmuel Ben-Ruby said police had
decided conditions Sunday morning made the co-ed worship possible.
	   The Reform and Conservative movements are dominant among U.S.
Jews, but tiny in Israel, where the Orthodox establishment has a
monopoly over religious affairs, including marriage and divorce.
	   The Chief Rabbinate in Israel had asked police that the liberal
Jews be barred from praying at the Western Wall, warning that a
co-ed service was provocative and could lead to violence.
  ga-kl
</TEXT>
