<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kenya-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Moi leads Kenya in celebrating independence 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photos NAI101-102
By GEORGE MWANGI
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ President Daniel arap Moi, celebrating
steps toward independence 35 years ago, Monday called on Kenyans to
work together to find solutions to problems including corruption,
poverty and unemployment.
	   ``Among the many challenges we face, the most critical are
poverty and unemployment,'' Moi said. ``The war on poverty has yet
to be won.''
	   Moi addressed a crowd of thousands which gathered for Madaraka
Day, the 35th anniversary of when Kenya gained the right to
self-government from British colonialists. Kenya became fully
independent on Dec. 12, 1963.
	   For the national holiday, the capital was decorated in the
black, red and green of the Kenyan flag. At an open-air ceremony in
Uhuru (Freedom) Park, troops marched past Moi, politicians and
diplomats, church choirs sang, and traditional dancers performed.
	   Last Madaraka Day, Moi dismissed opposition demands for
constitutional reforms ahead of elections, while police confined
opposition leaders to their homes to prevent them from disrupting
Moi's speech. Donor countries subsequently forced Moi to make some
compromises before the election in December, which he won for a
fifth, five-year term.
	   On Monday, Moi, 74, expressed thanks to those parties which are
cooperating with the ruling Kenya African National Union, whose
leadership he vowed to retain even after he retires from the
presidency.
	   ``I do hope that other political parties will see the need to
join hands ... peace and unity for the development and prosperity
for this nation.''
	   Opposition leader Mwai Kibaki, who was in the audience,
condemned Moi's remark, asking ``How can we cooperate with a
government which send people with bows and arrows to disrupt our
meeting?'' Last weekend, one man was killed and 20 injured when
thugs disrupted an opposition meeting in rural Kitale.
	   To fight the country's economic problems, Moi said he would try
to bring down ``excessively high interest rates,'' now at 27.97
percent.
	   Also, he promised to strengthen Kenya's tax collection system
and crack down on ``unpatriotic Kenyans who deny the government
revenue.''
	   Moi condemned corruption, saying it has undermined the
efficiency and effectiveness of public sector operations. Many
donor countries have blamed Moi for allowing corruption to thrive
in Kenya.
	   Shifting to Swahili, Moi, sounding a familiar theme, condemned
foreigners who ``come here to tell us how to live. We know
ourselves that if we don't unify the future will be difficult.''
	   (kjd)
</TEXT>
