u i     BC-Israel-Palestinians     06-01 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians,0425 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cabinet meeting ends without decision on West Bank withdrawal 
</HEADLINE>
By DINA KRAFT
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Despite growing U.S. pressure on Israel to make
a decision, Israel's Cabinet on Monday again failed to reach
agreement on the the scope of a West Bank troop withdrawal.
	   Israel's continued indecision is likely to further strain ties
with the United States, which reportedly has demanded an Israeli
answer within several days to its proposal for a pullback from 13
percent.
	   However, U.S. ultimatums have come and gone in the past month
without repercussions for Israel. It appeared Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu was more concerned about the survival of his
government than about possible U.S. censure.
	   A U.S. official said Monday that he did not expect the Clinton
administration to make good on veiled threats to announce the
failure of the U.S. peace initiative and blame Israel. Instead,
Washington will give Israel more time to reach a decision, said the
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
	   Far-right Cabinet ministers have threatened to topple the
government if Netanyahu agreed to a 13 percent pullback.
	   ``A 13 percent withdrawal would be a disaster for Jewish
settlements,'' Transport Minister Shaul Yahalom from the National
Religious Party told Israel radio Monday. ``We cannot agree. We
were assured by the prime minister that there would be no troop
redeployment that will hurt the settlements.''
	   Recent polls have suggested that a large majority in Israel want
Netanyahu to forge ahead with the peace negotiations and agree to a
troop withdrawal.
	   The Jewish Settlers' Council on Monday launched a campaign to
turn Israeli public opinion against a 13 percent troop pullback. It
mailed brochures to 1 million homes in Israel, with maps
illustrating the settlers' arguments that a pullback would endanger
water resources, Israeli security and control over Jewish holy
sites.
	   U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has been trying for
months to break the deadlock between Israel and the Palestinians.
The Palestinians have accepted the U.S. proposal for an immediate
13 percent pullback, to be followed by another significant
withdrawal whose scope has not been determined.
	   Israel radio and the Maariv daily reported Monday that Netanyahu
was considering a 15 percent pullback in three stages. Netanyahu's
adviser, David Bar-Illan, was not immediately available for
comment, but the radio said Netanyahu denied the report. 	   
</TEXT>
