w2517  wstm-
r i     BC-Russia-Impeachment     06-01 0241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Impeachment </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian hard-liners to push impeachment motion 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian hard-liners will try to get an impeachment
motion against President Boris Yeltsin put on parliament's agenda
during a scheduling session next week, a prominent hard-liner said
Monday.
	   Nikolai Kharitonov, leader of the hard-line Agrarian faction,
said Yeltsin opponents will ask members of the agenda-setting Duma
Council on June 9 to formally file the motion and set up a
committee to study the proposal. His comments were reported by the
Interfax news agency.
	   Impeachment proceedings are long and complex, and it would
likely take months before the motion is actually debated by
parliament's lower house, the State Duma.
	   Communists and their allies, including the Agrarians, launched
the latest impeachment campaign last month, gathering 205
signatures in the 450-seat Duma.
	   They have accused Yeltsin of a range of transgressions,
including instigating the Soviet collapse, launching the botched
war in Chechnya and ruining the country's economy.
	   Their frustrations intensified in April during a long test of
wills with Yeltsin, who threatened to disband the legislature
unless lawmakers approved his candidate for prime minister.
	   Several previous impeachment drives have fizzled, in part
because Russia's Constitution gives the president the upper hand in
confrontations with parliament.
	   (mr)
</TEXT>
