w2523  wstm-
u i     BCArabs-Summit     06-01 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC Arabs-Summit,0524 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Arab leaders confer on planned summit, differ on meeting's goal BY SALAH NASRAWI 
</HEADLINE>
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Arab leaders are holding intensive talks on
a proposed summit aimed at reviving the Middle East peace process,
but they reportedly disagree over what direction the summit should
take and whom to invite.
	   Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah held talks on a summit with Syrian
President Hafez Assad on Sunday and will meet Monday with Jordan's
King Hussein. Arab foreign ministers were expected to discuss the
issue Tuesday in Beirut at a meeting on Arab ties to Europe.
	   The summit would be a follow-up to a convening of Arab leaders
in 1996, shortly after Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's
election, that warned of a harsh reaction if Netanyahu failed to
fulfill pledges in peace pacts.
	   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, who has been pushing for the
summit, has urged the Arabs to take a tougher stance toward
Netanyahu since peace talks have deadlocked.
	   Talaat Hamid, spokesman for the 22-member Arab League, said
Monday that the proposed meeting would try to forge a unified Arab
position ``against the obstacles Israel erects in the face of
peace.''
	   He told The Associated Press that consultations are under way
over the time and place for the summit, but he gave no details.
	   Osama el-Baz, a senior adviser to Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak, was quoted Monday in Cairo newspapers as saying the
leaders also were trying to agree on who should attend and the
meeting's agenda.
	   Last week, Arafat said the conference should work out a unified
Arab strategy to ``confront Israeli arrogance.'' He made visits to
Saudi Arabia and the Gulf states to convince their leaders to
attend such a gathering.
	   The move reflects his frustration with U.S. mediation, which has
failed to convince Netanyahu to accept a compromise of a further 13
percent pullback in the West Bank to restart talks. Arafat, who
wanted 30 percent, has accepted.
	   Arab diplomats, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Jordan's King Hussein is reluctant to attend a conference in Syria,
where he expects Assad to push for a hard-line stance against
Israel.
	   Syria has been calling to activate a resolution by the 1996 Arab
summit to suspend ties with the Jewish state if progress was not
made toward peace.
	   Jordan's foreign minister, Jawad Anani, told The Associated
Press that Jordan supports holding a summit ``as long as it
produces the right results.''
	   He did not elaborate. But Jordan, the strongest advocate of
peace with Israel, would likely oppose any more to express outright
hostility.
	   Another hurdle to the summit is who to invite. Most Gulf states
still oppose asking Iraqi President Saddam Hussein because of his
1990 invasion of Kuwait. Syria says Iraq's presence is needed for a
united stance against Israel.
	   Several Arab countries also are unwilling to attend a summit on
the Palestinian issue while the United States still is mediating.
Once Washington announces its efforts have failed, Arafat would
likely meet less resistance. 	   
</TEXT>
