<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Sony-Justsystem </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sony to acquire 6.7 percent stake in Japanese software company 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Sony Corp. will acquire a 6.7 percent stake in
Justsystem Corp., a major Japanese software maker suffering a slump
in sales, a spokeswoman for the software maker said on Monday.
	   Sony hopes to take advantage of Justsystem's software
development skills to stengthen its position in the market for
digital consumer appliances _ electronic gadgets that incorporate
computer functions _ a Sony employee said.
	   Under a basic agreement between the two companies, Sony will buy
the entire block _ 2 million shares worth 1.27 billion yen (dlrs
9.16 million) _ of a new stock issuance by Justsystem scheduled for
July, said Kyoko Kamata, spokeswoman of Justsystem.
	   Justsystem, based in Tokushima, 515 kilometers (322 miles),
southwest of Tokyo, suffered a 5.19 billion yen (dlrs 37.34
million) net loss for the year ended March 31 on sales of 21.77
billion yen (dlrs 156.61 million), down 30.2 percent from a year
before.
	   It was the first time that the company posted a loss since its
foundation in 1981.
	   Justsystem is popularly known for its ``Ichitaro''
Japanese-language word-processing program, but its sales suffered
last year because of the slumping domestic economy and Microsoft
Corp.'s penetration into the Japanese market.
	   The Japan Securities Dealers' Association said it suspended
trade of Justsystem shares Monday as officials needed time to
verify a newspaper report on the planned tie-up with Sony.
  (km)
</TEXT>
