<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Zambia-Kaunda, 2nd Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kaunda freed as state withdraws coup allegations prosecution'' procedure that can have case reopened 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with Kaunda quotes, reaction, color, more on ``no
By ANGUS SHAW
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) _ Former President Kenneth Kaunda was freed
by a court Monday after spending five months under house arrest for
allegedly knowing about plans for coup last year by junior military
officers.
	   Kaunda, 74, waved to supporters on the steps of the Lusaka High
Court after state prosecutors dropped the case against him,
apparently on lack of evidence.
	   ``I feel great,'' said Kaunda, wearing a thick white beard he
has grown since his arrest on Christmas day. Supporters waved
two-finger victory salutes and cheered.
	   Jubilant supporter Christopher Malama described Kaunda's release
as a triumph for their opposition party.
	   ``Our father is out. We are very happy today,'' he said.
	   Also freed by Judge Japhet Banda was Moyce Kaulungombe, Kaunda's
bodyguard. Both men were charged with concealing prior knowledge of
an Oct. 28, 1997, coup attempt by junior military officers that was
quickly crushed by loyal troops.
	   Attorney General Bonaventure Mutale told Banda the state entered
a plea of
	   ``nolle prosequi,'' the legal term for ``no prosecution,'' a
procedure normally used when the state lacks sufficient evidence or
does not wish to proceed with a case that can be reopened later.
	   ``This means the state doesn't wish to proceed further. You are
discharged
	   so you are free men,'' Banda told Kaunda and Kaulungombe.
	   But Kaunda was defiant, saying he was not satisfied with the
case being dropped.
	   ``I want a complete acquittal. I am very clean,'' he told
reporters.
	   Kaunda dismissed reports that President Nelson Mandela of South
Africa asked President Frederick Chiluba for his release in return
for Kaunda retiring from politics.
	   ``I am going to listen to the people who have been discussing
this, then I'll decide,'' Kaunda said.
	   Kaunda drove through downtown Lusaka, waving his trademark white
handkerchief, and was scheduled to meet with supporters and
colleagues at the headquarters of his United National Independence
Party, the main opposition group.
	   The drama came on the first day of the trials of 81 suspects _
most of them soldiers _ who were arrested after junior officers
stormed the state broadcast center and claimed to have overthrown
Chiluba's government.
	   Kaunda repeatedly, 8th graf pvs
	   (as-aos)
</TEXT>
