<HEADLINE>
Russian border guards detain North Korean fishermen as reason for detention. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with new grafs 3-4, violations in catch records cited
<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian border guards detained 13 North Korean
trawlers Monday suspected of illegal fishing in the Bering Sea in
the Russian Far East, a news report said.
	   The boats have been escorted to the regional center of
Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
	   It said Russian border guards and sea inspectors boarded the
North Korean vessels, where they found numerous violations of catch
records and decided to detain the flotilla.
	   The main vessel, a floating fishing factory, had a crew of 196,
ITAR-Tass said. It said the North Koreans did not resist the
Russian border guards. The report didn't say how the trawlers
managed to reach Russia's waters.
	   North Korea is suffering from a deep famine, but tight border
controls in the totalitarian state make it extremely difficult to
leave its territory.
	   Many North Korean defectors are living illegally in Russia with
the hope of reaching capitalist South Korea.
	   (ad/jai/mr) 	   
