<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Japan </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia and Japan plan joint naval exercise 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photo MOSB101
<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia and Japan will hold a joint naval exercise
for the first time in the Pacific Ocean in July, the chief of the
Russian General Staff said Monday.
	   Gen. Anatoly Kvashnin met with his Japanese counterpart, Admiral
Kazuya Natsukawa, to discuss upgrading military contacts between
Russia and Japan as part of an effort to conclude a peace treaty by
2000.
	   Five decades after World War II, the two nations have yet to
sign a treaty, mainly because of a territorial dispute over four
tiny islands in the southern Kuril chain that Soviet troops seized
from Japan in the closing days of the war.
	   Kvashnin said no deadline has been set for demilitarizing the
islands as part of military reforms that envisage cutting Russia's
armed forces from 1.8 million servicemen to 1.2 million by 1999,
the ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
	   ``The deadlines depend on political agreements, but there are no
specific documents on this issue,'' he said.
	   The naval exercise will involve two Russian and three Japanese
warships in a simulated sea rescue, Kvashnin said.
	   He said he would visit Japan next October or November at
Natsukawa's invitation as part of the program to improve military
ties initiated by President Boris Yeltsin during an April summit in
Tokyo with Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto.
	   Natsukawa arrived in Moscow Sunday on an eight-day visit. He was
scheduled to spend the first five days of his Russian tour in
Moscow, then travel to the Pacific port of Vladivostok.
	   (jai/mr)
</TEXT>
