<SLUG> BC-Spain-Blast </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two police officers slightly injured in small bomb blast 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ A package bomb believed planted by a
shadowy leftist group exploded in central Madrid on Monday slightly
injuring two police officers and causing minor damage to a private
employment agency's offices.
	   Minutes before the packet bomb exploded at 11.30 a.m. (0930
gmt), police received a warning call from a person who claimed to
speak on behalf the armed leftist group GRAPO.
	   The group, whose name is a Spanish acronym for October First
Antifascist Resistance Group, is blamed for killing 60 people in
infrequent bombing and shooting attacks since it first appeared in
the early 1970s.
	   The two police officers suffered slight injuries when the bomb
exploded while they were evacuating the building.
	   As in previous GRAPO attacks, police were unsure what the motive
behind the blast was.
	   GRAPO has claimed responsibility for minor blasts at an
insurance company and two government tax offices so far this year.
	   (cg) 	   
</TEXT>
