<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Yamaichi Liabilities </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Collapsed Yamaichi Securities debts even more than claimed 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Collapsed Yamaichi Securities Co. said Monday its
liabilities exceeded assets by 22.51 billion yen (dlrs 162 million)
as of March 31, suggesting the broker doesn't have enough money to
repay all its debts.
	   The report contradicted a claim by the Finance Ministry which
said after Yamaichi collapsed last November that the broker had
enough capital to meet all its liabilities.
	   Yamaichi collapsed under the weight of more than 274 billion yen
(dlrs 1.97 million) in the off-the-book losses _ Japan's biggest
corporate failure ever.
	   In Yamaichi's earnings report for the term ended March 31,
Yamaichi suffered a net loss of 460.33 billion yen (dlrs 3.3
billion) as it wrote off 410.9 billion yen (dlrs 2.96 billion) as
special losses following the collapse.
	   Yamaichi's income including trade commission fell by 30 percent
from a year earlier to 147.488 billion yen (dlrs 1.061 billion),
but expenditures for business operations were 201.080 billion yen
(dlrs 1.446 billion).
	   Yamaichi's balance sheet as of March 31 showed that the overall
liabilities totaled 600.227 billion yen (dlrs 4.318 billion),
including 43 billion yen (dlrs 309 million) in subordinated loans,
against overall assets of 577.721 billion yen (dlrs 4.156 billion).
	   A Yamaichi official said Yamaichi is negotiating with the life
and casualty insurers which made the subordinated loans because
Yamaichi is unable to repay nearly half of what it owes them.
	   Yamaichi, one of Japan's ``Big Four'' brokerages, failed after
trying for years to juggle trading losses stemming from the
collapse of real estate and stock markets earlier in the decade.
	   It closed the last of its branches on March 31, lowering the
curtain on 101 years of businesses.
  (sk) 	   
</TEXT>
