<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Swimming-Mexico-Cuba,0219 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Australian swims from Mexico to Cuba 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   HAVANA, Cuba (AP) _ Australian Susie Maroney was believed to
have become the first person to swim from Mexico to Cuba when her
latest long-distance epic ended early Tuesday.
	   Maroney, 23, touched Cuban soil at 5:03 a.m. (0903 GMT) after
swimming approximately 197 kilometers (122 miles) from Isle Mujere,
Mexico in 38 hours and 33 minutes.
	   Her support team reported she was in fair condition but being
treated for dehydration. Maroney walked onto land in a remote part
of Cuba after being pointed towards a lighthouse by the coast
guard.
	   The distance was less than the 233 kilometers (145 miles)
Maroney had been aiming for, which would have given her an absolute
world record for the farthest any one has ever swum in the ocean.
	   According to the Maroney team, the 197 kilometers (122 miles) is
the farthest any person has swum in the ocean without the aid of
flippers and she will claim it as a new ``honest distance'' world
record.
	   After being treated by the team physician, Maroney was expected
to be taken by boat to Havana, where Cubans who have followed her
latest swim were to welcome her.
	   Last year Maroney became the first person to swim from Cuba to
Florida.
</TEXT>
