r i     BC-NorthernIreland     06-01 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Northern Ireland </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sinn Fein stands up Prince Charles _ saving some British blushes 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) _ In a double-edged snub, leaders
of the IRA-allied Sinn Fein party have turned down an invitation to
a royal garden party because Prince Charles will be there.
	   The announcement Sunday saved the host, Britain's Northern
Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam, from some awkward maneuvering. Now,
she won't have to worry about keeping the Sinn Fein leaders away
from Charles _ whose much-loved great-uncle Lord Mountbatten was
assassinated by the Irish Republican Army in 1979 _ when guests
mingle Wednesday in the grounds of her Hillsborough Castle
residence.
	   Sinn Fein said that leaders Gerry Adams and Martin McGuinness
will boycott the party because Charles holds the ceremonial
position of colonel-in-chief of the Parachute Regiment whose
members were involved in Bloody Sunday in 1972. Thirteen Catholic
marchers were shot dead in the British army's worst shooting in
this province.
	   Adams, Sinn Fein's president, and McGuinness, the party's chief
negotiator in the peace talks, won't show up ``due to unresolved
circumstances surrounding the murders,'' party chairman Mitchel
McLaughlin said.
	   After a long campaign by relatives of the victims, British Prime
Minister Tony Blair this year authorized a new investigation into
Bloody Sunday, which is being carried out by an international panel
of judges.
	   Leaders of pro-British Protestant parties accused Mowlam of
blundering and insensitivity by inviting Sinn Fein to the party,
being held to mark the 50th anniversary of the state-funded
National Health Service in Northern Ireland.
	   Before Sinn Fein said it wouldn't be going, Mowlam promised to
make sure Charles didn't meet Adams and McGuinness, who hold two of
the 18 Northern Ireland seats in the 659-member British House of
Commons.
	   ``That won't happen. I can guarantee that,'' Mowlam said of the
possibility.
	   ``It will be I who will escort the royal round, and I will make
very sure who he meets,'' she added in a BBC television interview.
	   David Trimble, leader of the largest Protestant party, the
Ulster Unionists, said Mowlam ``must be mightily relieved that her
grave error of judgment has not led to worse consequences.''
	   Charles' office made no comment. But Blair's press spokesman,
Alastair Campbell, said Charles' staff knew Adams and McGuinness
were being invited.
	   (mj-kg)
</TEXT>
