<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Arabs-Media </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New editor of Al-Hayat promises no change in paper's policies 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ The new editor-in-chief of the leading
Arabic daily Al-Hayat on Monday promised to continue its policy of
independent and fair journalism.
	   George Semaan, who assumed his post Sunday, wrote in today's
issue that the Saudi-owned paper will stay true to its policy of
``objectivity in news coverage and analysis.''
	   His statement came amid speculation that the paper's publisher,
Prince Khalid bin Sultan, was reorganizing the paper to promote a
more pro-Saudi stance.
	   Semaan said ``we will stick to our fixed principles of
independence and fairness'' in reporting.
	   Semaan, a journalist with Al-Hayat before the promotion, was
named as editor in March by the paper's publisher, Prince Khalid
bin Sultan. He takes over from Jihad al-Khazin, who edited the
prestigious daily for a decade.
	   Although the paper is owned by Saudis, most of its journalists
hail from other Arab countries _ mainly Lebanon. Two Lebanese
journalists were appointed as deputies to Semaan.
	   Former editor Al-Khazin will work as information adviser to
Al-Hayat's publishing company and will continue to write his daily
column in the paper.
	   Al-Hayat, first issued in Beirut in 1946, was forced to close
after its owner, Kamil Mroue, was assassinated in 1966. The paper
began publishing again from London in 1988.
