<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Nicholas Green </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italian appeals trial begins for slaying of American boy 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   CATANZARO, Italy (AP) _ Prosecutors are trying a second time to
convict two Italian men of the 1994 highway slaying of a 7-year-old
American boy whose parents then donated his organs, inspiring a
country where donation rates are low.
	   The appeals trial began in this southern city Monday for the men
acquitted in January 1997 of slaying Nicholas Green during a
robbery attempt as he and his California family drove down a
Calabrian highway while on vacation.
	   The lower court jury had ruled there was no evidence to convict
Francesco Mesiano, 23, and Michele Iannello, 28, of murder,
attempted murder and armed robbery, but Italian law allows the
acquitted to be retried by an appeals court for the same crime.
	   Prosecutor Salvatore Murone told the court that since the first
trial a pistol was found in the house of Iannello's mother, and
that the discovery questioned the credibility of the defendant, who
had earlier testified he had no other weapons, the Italian news
agency AGI reported.
	   As Nicholas' father, Reginald Green, drove faster to try to
break away from the highway bandits, the boy, sleeping in the back
seat, was shot in the head and was declared brain-dead.
	   His parents donated his organs in an act that saved seven other
lives and inspired a temporary surge of organ donations in a
country where many relatives of accident victims, especially of
children, refuse to allow removal of organs.
	   Italy has one of the lowest donor rates in Europe.
	   Reginald Green testified in the first trial that he could not
identify the masked assailants.
	   Mesiano and Iannello had denied involvement in the death, even
though Iannello admitted to four gangland murders.
	   The prosecution said statements recorded by telephone taps
implicated the pair, but the defense disputed the meaning of the
conversations in dialect.
	   The appeals trial is expected to take about a week.
	   (fd)
</TEXT>
