<HEADLINE>
Yugoslavia's twenty two-men World Cup roster now final 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Yugoslav Coach Slobodan Santrac on
Monday dropped striker Anto Drobnjak and midfielder Albert Nadj
from Yugoslavia's 22-man World Cup squad.
	   Drobjak of French champion's Lens and Nadj of Betis, Spain, will
not travel to the tournament in France, where Yugoslavia faces the
United States, Germany and Iran in qualification Group S.
	   Nadj reportedly had a row with Santrac before Yugoslavia's
friendly warm-up with Nigeria last Friday which the Yugoslav team
won 3-0.
	   Nadj had allegedly refused to start the game on defense, rather
than his usual position in the midfield.
	   Santrac had a large choice of strikers and Drobnjak lost his
place in competition with Predrag Mijatovic and Darko Kovacevic.
	   ``It wasn't easy to shorten the list by two names,'' Santrac
told reporters Monday.
	   ``Nadj was not ready to play the position I intended for him and
Kovacevic had the advantage over Drobnjak, being both younger and
having completed the whole cycle of qualifications,'' he said.
	   Dragoslav Jevric was chosen as third goalie but will not travel
to France unless one of the two main goalkeepers is injured.
	   Santrac's final roster:
	   Goalkeepers: Ivica Kralj, Dragoje Lekovic.
	   Defense: Zoran Mirkovic, Goran Djorovic, Miroslav Djukic, Sinisa
Mihajlovic, Nisa Saveljic, Slobodan Komljenovic, Zeljko Petrovic.
	   Midfield: Dragan Stojkovic, Dejan Savicevic, Slavisa Jokanovic,
Dejan Govedarica, Vladimir Jugovic, Miroslav Stevic, Branko
Brnovic, Dejan Stankovic, Ljubinko Drulovic.
	   Forwards: Predrag Mijatovic, Savo Milosevic, Darko Kovacevic,
Perica Ognjenovic.
	   The Yugoslav team left Monday for preparations in Switzerland,
on its way to France.
	   (ds/kk/dc)
