<SLUG> BC-Spain-Mexico-Banker's Extradition, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Spain gives final approval to extradition of Mexican banker 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with banker being extradited
<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ Spain on Monday extradited fugitive Mexican
banker Angel Rodriguez Saez, who fled his home country in 1994
after allegedly swindling banks out of dlrs 4 million.
	   Spanish police handed Rodriguez Saez over to their Mexican
counterparts at Madrid's Barajas airport where he boarded a midday
flight to Mexico City, said National Police spokesman Antonio
Nevada.
	   Rodriguez Saez, a flashy businessman known as ``El Divino'' _
The Divine One _ built a banking empire during the privatization of
the industry in Mexico in the early 1990s.
	   His Banpais entity, however, was taken over by regulatory
authorities in 1995 after they discovered capital shortfalls and
``irregularities'' in the bank's bookkeeping.
	   His extradition will make him the first major player in Mexico's
1994 banking and political scandals to be returned to his home
country.
	   Mexican officials have failed to win extradition of former
Assistant Attorney General Mario Ruiz Massieu from the United
States, while financier Carlos Cabal Peniche _ the most important
figure in the 1994 banking scandals _ is still at large.
	   Rodriguez Saez was arrested July 29, 1996, after he attempted to
flee Spanish police by diving off his yacht while sailing near the
Spanish Mediterranean island of Ibiza.
	   Despite successive appeals, Spanish judicial authorities agreed
to his extradition on February 22, 1998. On April 20, Rodriguez
Saez dropped his objections to the ruling.
	   The conservative Spanish government of Prime Minister Jose Maria
Aznar finally approved the extradition on May 22.
	   (cg) 	   
</TEXT>
