<SLUG> BC-San Marino-Elections </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Christian Democrats confirmed as top party in San Marino 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   SAN MARINO (AP) _ The Christian Democrats and the Socialists,
who have governed this tiny, land-locked republic since 1993,
grabbed the largest share of the vote in parliamentary elections,
final results showed on Monday.
	   The Christian Democratic Party won 40 percent of the vote, while
the Socialists captured 23 percent, the ANSA news agency reported.
	   Some 22,670 percent voted on Sunday, or about 75 percent of the
30,000 eligible to vote.
	   Founded in the year 301, San Marino calls itself the world's
oldest republic, with an unbroken line of elected government
officials since at least 1244.
	   The 23-square-mile (60-square-kilometer) republic, located in
northeast Italy, depends on tourism, postage stamps and financial
services for income.
