r i     BC-Bulgaria-Canada-Stole     06-01 0366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bulgaria-Canada-Stolen Cars </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police break ring smuggling stolen Canadian cars 
</HEADLINE>
With AP Photo SOF101
<TEXT>
	   SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) _ Police arrested a dozen people and
impounded as many luxury vehicles in a crackdown on a ring
suspected of smuggling cars stolen in Canada, officials announced
Monday.
	   ``All the cars, brand new and at an average price of dlrs
60,000, have been stolen from car dealers or parking lots in Quebec
province,'' said Kiril Radev, head of a special police unit dealing
with organized crime.
	   Bulgarian police began the arrests last week, and still are
seeking the man believed to have masterminded the ring, 41-year-old
Hristo Ivanov Iliev. He is a Bulgarian who emigrated to Canada and
now has Canadian citizenship, Radev said.
	   Iliev is thought to be hiding somewhere in Bulgaria.
	   He had been convicted of theft three times before moving to
Canada in the 1970s, the state news agency BTA reported.
	   Canadian authorities have arrested an unspecified number of
suspects after being being contacted by Bulgarian police three days
ago, Radev said.
	   The seizure includes a Mercedes Benz 600 SEL, a Cadillac
Fleetwood, a Volvo G70, a Nissan Infinity and a Dodge Durango
four-wheel drive.
	   The cars were shipped in containers from the Canadian port of
Halifax to the Greek port of Piraeus, then transported to two
automobile dealers in Sofia. Two unnamed transport companies _ one
Canadian and one Bulgarian _ were involved.
	   Radev said smugglers falsified the cargo papers, saying the
containers were full of fiberglass. As transit freight, the sealed
containers wouldn't be opened by customs officers.
	   Radev didn't disclose how police were tipped to the smuggling
ring.
	   Some of the cars were slated for re-export to former Soviet
republics. Others were to be sold to Bulgarians who had made
deposits on the vehicles. The Bulgarians weren't aware of the
vehicles' origins, he said.
	   ``So far we have no evidence that the local car dealers realized
they were offered stolen cars,'' Radev said. Police still were
investigating, however, because only one of the cars had documents,
and those were fake.
	   (vz/vt/scl) 	   
</TEXT>
