r i     BC-Singapore-DeathPenalt     06-01 0313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Death Penalty </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore gives death penalty for `ice' trafficking 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Parliament imposed the death penalty on Monday
for trafficking in methamphetamine, and introduced corporal
punishment and long jail terms for repeat drug offenders.
	   When the amendments to the Misuse of Drugs Act are published in
a week or so, anyone convicted of dealing in more than 250 grams
(8.75 ounces) of methamphetamine, a designer drug known as ``ice,''
will go to the gallows.
	   Traffickers in 167-250 grams (5.85-8.75 ounces) of ``ice'' face
life in prison and 15 strokes of the cane, while lesser amounts are
punishable by up to 20 years in prison.
	   Singapore law automatically considers anyone possessing large
amounts of drugs as a trafficker. Under existing law, adults caught
with more than 15 grams (0.5 ounce) of heroin, 30 grams (1 ounce)
of morphine, half a kilo (1.1 pounds) of cannabis, or 1.2 kilograms
(2.6 pounds) of opium face the death penalty.
	   Also under the new law, users and dealers convicted a third time
will be imprisoned five to seven years and face three to six
strokes of the cane. Those found guilty of a further offense will
be jailed seven to 13 years and receive six to 12 strokes.
	   The tougher punishment ``is for these people who just simply
refuse to change,'' Home Affairs Minister Wong Kan Seng argued in
Parliament. ``We have decided that the only way to treat these
addicts is to imprison them for a long time.''
	   The previous law dictated sentences of less than two years in
drug rehabilitation centers for repeat offenders.
	   The small Southeast Asian island republic has some of the
world's strictest drug laws. More than 180 people have been hanged
for drug trafficking since 1975, when the mandatory death penalty
was imposed.
	   Singapore no longer makes public the number of people hanged. 	   
</TEXT>
