w2587  wstm-
u i     BC-India-Budget 1stLd-Writethru   06-01 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru,0567 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New budget addresses economic woes pickup. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with Sinha introducing budget. ADDS byline. No
By ASHOK SHARMA
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ India's finance minister, who promised
firm action to deal with anti-nuclear sanctions that have battered
an already weak economy, introduced a budget Monday that included
increased spending in the infrastructure and nuclear energy
sectors.
	   The Bharatiya Janata Party-led government's commitment to
``swadeshi,'' which the BJP has defined as ``economic nationalism''
had worried foreign investors. But Finance Minister Yashwant Sinha
said ``swadeshi does not mean isolation, swadeshi means making
India strong and self-reliant.''
	   Sinha said he believed the nuclear sanctions ``will not have any
significant impact on our economic development,'' in part because
he believed countries like the United States, Australia and Japan
who cut loans and all but humanitarian aid in the wake of India's
five nuclear tests last month would ``moderate'' their opposition
in time.
	   ``On our part, our policies have to be clearly directed and
firm,'' he said.
	   Sinha's government, presenting its first budget, has promised to
revive India's economic growth, which faltered to 5 percent in the
fiscal year 1997-98, the lowest rate in the last five years.
Experts say that requires spending on infrastructure and
encouraging investment. His revenue options have been reduced by
the sanctions.
	   Sinha announced a 35 percent increase in spending on what he
called the key infrastructure areas of energy, transportation and
communications, and a 16 percent increase in allocations to the
Rural Infrastructure Development Fund, under which, among other
measures, farmers can obtain loans for expanding their enterprises.
The exact spending levels, and his plans for raising revenue, were
to be outlined later Monday.
	   Spending on developing nuclear energy _ an area that also has
defense ramifications _ was increased 68 percent, and for the space
department _ which has an important role in developing missiles
that could carry nuclear weapons _ 62 percent.
	   Minor concessions, likely to include tax breaks, were offered to
get Indians living abroad to invest in their homeland
	   He also promised a ``hassle-free procedure'' for foreign
investors who have complained that bureaucratic red tape presents a
huge obstacle to doing business in India.
	   The government's pre-budget economic assessment, presented to
Parliament last week, was bleak. In addition to the falling growth,
it said the deficit rose to 6.1 percent of gross domestic product,
the total value of goods and services produced by the economy,
exceeding the target of 4.5 percent.
	   A 6.35 percent inflation rate was reported Sunday, up from 5
percent during 1997-1998.
	   The full impact of the nuclear sanctions was yet unclear, but
they were already having a chilling effect.
	   The rupee slid last week when Standard and Poor's financial
rating agency revised its India rating outlook to negative from
stable. A few days later, the World Bank postponed consideration of
more than dlrs 800 million in development loans to India because of
its nuclear tests, prompting a further slide in the rupee.
	   The rupee opened at 41.74 to the U.S. dollar Monday; it was
39.73 at the beginning of May. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-India-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
