<SLUG> BC-Israel-MIA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Parents of Israeli MIA to examine captured Israeli tank in Moscow 
</HEADLINE>
By MASHA HERBST
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ The father of an Israeli MIA said Monday he
would go to Russia, accompanied by a forensics expert, to examine
an Israeli tank on display at a Moscow military museum for evidence
of human remains.
	   The soldier, Zachary Baumel, along with the other members of the
three-man tank crew, went missing after a battle with the Syrian
army at Sultan Yakoub in Lebanon on June 11, 1982.
	   An Israeli tank which was identified as having been captured at
Sultan Yakoub is now being kept at the Moscow military museum.
Russian media reported last month that the tank contained the
remains of Israeli soldiers, but that has been denied by the
Russian government.
	   The Israeli army confirmed Monday that the tank on display in
Moscow was captured at Sultan Yakoub, but said all its crew members
survived the 1982 war and were back in Israel.
	   Baumel's father, Yona, on Monday met with the Russian ambassador
to Israel, Mikhail Bogdanov. The ambassador told Baumel that he
would make arrangements for Baumel and his wife, Miriam, to fly to
Moscow this summer, accompanied by a forensics expert, and gain
access to the museum which has been closed since the news reports
on the alleged human remains in the tank.
	   The forensics expert would examine the tank for any remains that
would make possible DNA testing, Baumel told The Associated Press.
The Baumels, who moved to Israel from New York in 1970, made
tentative plans to fly to Moscow in July.
  mh-kl
</TEXT>
