u i     BC-Ethiopia-Eritrea     06-01 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ethiopia-Eritrea </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ethiopian and Eritrean troops clash at border area 
</HEADLINE>
By ABEBE ANDUALEM
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) _ Ethiopian and Eritrean troops have
clashed in a disputed border area, and both sides suffered an
undetermined number of casualties, a reliable source said Monday.
	   The source, who could not be further identified, said the clash
took place early Sunday near the village of Alitena in the
foothills of the Asimba Mountains, about 600 kilometers (372 miles)
north of Addis Ababa.
	   A reporter for the Amharic language service of the Voice of
America who was in the region said she heard artillery fire
throughout the day Sunday.
	   According to the source, the clash area is located 20 kilometers
(12 miles) inside Ethiopian territory.
	   Since its first public comment on the border dispute May 13,
Ethiopia has repeatedly claimed that Eritreans have made incursions
into Ethiopian territory.
	   Eritrea denies the claims and has suggested international
mediation. Ethiopia rejects direct negotiations until Eritrea
withdraws and threatened to use force if it did not.
	   U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for African Affairs Susan Rice
returned to Addis Ababa Sunday evening and will continue
``facilitating dialogue,'' a U.S. Embassy spokeswoman said Monday.
	   Rice spent a week shuttling between Addis Ababa and the Eritrean
capital, Asmara, after Ethiopia first accused Eritrea of border
violations.
	   A State Department team remained in the region, meeting with
officials from both nations as well as from Djibouti, the
Inter-Governmental Authority on Development (IGAD) and the
Organization of African Unity.
	   The State Department issued a second travel advisory Friday
warning American citizens to stay away from the border regions and
has pulled U.S. government employees and Peace Corps volunteers
away from border areas in Eritrea.
	   In a speech Monday in Nairobi, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi,
a former chairman of IGAD, expressed concern over the rising
tension between the two countries and said he was already
coordinating between current IGAD chairmain President Hassan Gouled
Aptidon of Djibouti and other parties ``to settle this problem in a
peaceful manner.''
	   Although no figures have been made public, military sources in
Eritrea say at 200,000 Eritreans _ including regular army, veterans
and youths doing cumpulsory military service _ have been mobilized
since May 13.
	   On Friday, staff at Asmara University were asked to contribute
10 percent of their monthly salaries to the mobilization effort.
	   Eritrea has an estimated population of 3.67 million, compared to
about 57 million in Ethiopia.
	   Seven years ago, Eritrean and Ethiopian rebels forces united to
overthrow Ethiopia's 17-year military regime in 1991. Two years
later, Eritrea gained independence.
	   Ethiopia claims that Eritrea is illegally occupying a 400-sq.
km. (160-sq.-mile) area known as the Yigra triangle in northwestern
Ethiopia as well as other areas in the northeast.
	   Eritrea says that according to the Italian colonial boundaries
that are still binding, the areas are Eritrean.
	   In the past five years, Eritrea has had border disputes with
Sudan and Djibouti as well as with Yemen over control of the Hanish
Islands in the Red Sea. The International Tribunal in The Hague is
expected to decide that dispute in July.
	   (aa/js/sl)	   
</TEXT>
