r i     BC-Indonesia-CorruptionP 1stLd-Writethru   06-01 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Corruption Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian corruption probe to include Suharto businesses 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: RECASTS to ADD quotes, details throughout
With BC-Indonesia
By ALI KOTARUMALOS
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Authorities have launched an
investigation into government corruption under ex-President
Suharto, the attorney general said Monday.
	   The broadly-based inquiry is expected to encompass business
dealings by Suharto's family, which critics say used its
connections to make billions of dollars from a wide range of
industries during his three decades in power.
	   However, the investigation's general focus is likely to
disappoint many Indonesians who have been loudly calling for a fast
probe to target the Suharto family's wealth specifically.
	   ``The investigation is underway,'' Attorney General Sudjono
Atmonegoro said at a news conference. ``This investigation is a
process that will need time. It cannot be completed in just one or
two days.''
	   Sudjono said the inquiry was the government response to calls
for an investigation into the conduct of ``government officials.''
He did not specifically name Suharto.
	   Critics say nepotism, corruption and cronyism that thrived under
Suharto contributed in large part to Indonesia's worst economic
crisis in decades.
	   Suharto quit May 21 following riots over price increases and
under pressure from student protesters who occupied Parliament.
	   A leading opposition figure has called on Suharto to donate the
bulk of his wealth back to the country.
	   Amien Rais, a prominent Muslim leader, said that with the money
Indonesia would not have to beg for assistance from international
agencies to prop up the economy.
	   Sudjono said the corruption inquiry would be carried out on the
principle of ``presumption of innocence'' and would involve many
government departments and outside agencies.
	   As part of the probe, Sudjono said he had received guarantees
from Suharto family members that they would not leave Indonesia.
	   ``There have been guarantees from them that they will not leave
our beloved country,'' he said.
	   He said there were no plans to question Suharto, although the
former president might be asked to check evidence from others, at a
later stage.
	   The head of the powerful military, Gen. Wiranto said recently he
was opposed to a specific investigation into the Suharto family
fortune, saying that it could only worsen national disunity.
	   The military played a key role in Indonesia's recent political
crisis. It quelled riots by putting thousands of soldiers and
dozens of tanks on the street.
	   Some claim it also was instrumental in persuading Suharto,
himself a retired army general, to quit in favor of new President
B.J. Habibie, a civilian and Suharto loyalist who has promised
political and economic reforms.
</TEXT>
