<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Portugal-Child Labor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Portugal sets up council to crack down on child labor 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ The government Monday announced the
creation of a national council to crack down on child labor,
estimated to involve some 50,000 children in this country of 10
million.
	   Describing child labor as ``a worrying fact,'' Employment
Minister Eduardo Ferro Rodrigues said the council will include
representatives from trade unions, employers, the government and
civic institutions. Its chief task will be to monitor and recommend
action.
	   Stamping out child labor will require cultural and social
changes, as well as cooperation between public entities, Ferro
Rodrigues said.
	   The General Confederation of Portuguese Workers estimates that
almost 50,000 children under the age of 16 are working in Portugal
_ about the same as a decade ago.
	   Most of the children work in the construction and textile
industries in the north of the country, the confederation said.
	   Government figures do not give overall estimates, but last year
167 cases of child labor were detected by the General Labor
Inspectorate in a survey of 26,424 workers.
	   (bh/cg) 	   
</TEXT>
