w2600  wstm-
r f     BC-Indonesia-AirlineClos     06-01 0320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Airline Closes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sempati Air, owned by Suharto son, closes because of weak rupiah 
</HEADLINE>
With BC-Indonesia
<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Indonesia's third largest airline,
controlled by ex-President Suharto's youngest son, closed down
Monday, crippled by the collapse of the rupiah, the government
said.
	   ``Because current conditions are so heavy, it is not possible
for Sempati to continue its operations and activities,'' said
Transportation Minister Giri Suseno Hardi Hardjono.
	   Indonesia's airlines have registered enormous losses because of
Asia's economic crisis and the weak rupiah, which has lost more
than 70 percent of its value since July 1997.
	   Most of them, including national airline Garuda, have
drastically cut services.
	   Much of the costs borne by the airlines are in dollars but their
revenue is mainly in rupiah.
	   Sempati's shareholders include Suharto's son Hutomo ``Tommy''
Mandala Putra as well as a military foundation. The airline, which
operated mostly on domestic routes with several international
destinations, is run by Tommy.
	   An economic crisis, riots and student unrest induced Suharto to
resign on May 21 after 32 years of autocratic rule. Since then, a
groundswell of support has built for the government to try and
recover billions of dollars his family allegedly siphoned off the
economy through corruption and nepotism.
	   The government has already canceled many contracts with firms
linked to the former first family, and on Monday announced it has
launched an investigation of government corruption under his rule.
	   Indonesia's attorney general said investigators have no plans to
target the former leader, but will look into business dealings of
his family.
	   As part of the general investigation, Attorney General Sudjono
Atmonegoro said he had received guarantees from Suharto's family
members that they would not leave Indonesia.
</TEXT>
