w2605  wstm-
r i     BC-Thailand-StrayDogs     06-01 0324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Stray Dogs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bangkok plans bounty for those bringing dogs for neutering 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Seeking to control the burgeoning
population of stray dogs, Bangkok city officials have decided to
pay residents 50 baht (dlrs 1.22) for each dog they bring in for
neutering at public health centers.
	   The policy was announced at a public hearing attended by 300
people on the question of how to control strays, Supong Limtanakul,
an advisor to the city's governor, said Monday.
	   The incentive would be paid for both people's pets and any
strays they might bring in, he said. But the bounty would be paid
only for female dogs of puppy-bearing age.
	   Supong estimated that there are as many as 1 million stray dogs
in the capital alone.
	   He said the hearing was held because of complaints from joggers
as well as foreigners who visited Buddhist temples, which
traditionally shelter stray dogs. The foreigners' complaints could
have a negative impact on tourism, he noted.
	   He said some animal lovers at the hearing suggested the city
government provide a budget to feed the strays, while others _
including relatives of dog-bite victims who had succumbed to rabies
_ wanted to get the strays off the city's streets altogether.
	   Last year about 80 people died of rabies, 10 of them in Bangkok,
Supong said.
	   ``Stray dogs is not the problem, the problem is people, people
who have no responsibility,'' he said, noting that people abandon
their canine pets at temples when they grow up, have too many
puppies, or simply cease being cute.
	   He also said the city is considering an idea to implant
microchips in dogs which would contain their owners' names and
other information.
	   The scheme, to cost about 100 baht (dlrs 2.44) per dog, would
help make owners more responsible because they could be traced, and
also could be used to see whether a dog who bit someone had been
vaccinated, he said.
</TEXT>
