<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Settlers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Settlers launch campaign to turn public against pullback 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Jewish settlers mailed one million brochures to
Israeli homes Monday in hopes of turning public opinion against a
U.S. proposal that Israel withdraw from 13 percent of the West
Bank.
	   The campaign came as Israel's Cabinet again failed to reach a
decision on the scope of the pullback. The United States reportedly
wants an Israeli answer within the next few days. Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu initially said he could hand over no more than 9
percent without compromising Israel's security, but media reports
said Monday he was considering a larger pullback.
	   The brochures sent out by the Jewish Settlers' Council warned
that a 13 percent pullback would endanger Israel's water resources,
its hold over Jerusalem and its control over holy sites as well as
jeopardize the future of the 144 Jewish settlements.
	   ``We can not surrender to American pressure!'' the brochure said
in bold letters.
	   Aharon Dombe, a settler spokesman, said the campaign cost 1.5
shekels (dlrs 405,000) and was paid for by supporters.
	   Netanyahu last year committed to three troop pullbacks in the
West Bank, but none have been carried because of disagreement with
the Palestinians over the scope of each withdrawal.
	   A majority of Israelis support the land-for-peace negotiations
with the Palestinians, according to various surveys.
  ga-kl
</TEXT>
