u i     BC-Egypt-Libya     06-01 0350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Libya,0350 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gadhafi to visit Egypt for talks on trade, investment 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi is making a
nine-day visit to Egypt starting Tuesday that will focus on trade
relations with Egypt and likely will touch on Libya's feud with the
West over the 1988 bombing of an American airliner.
	   Gadhafi's visit to Egypt, the second in two years, can be
expected to upset the United States, which has sought to isolate
Libya because of the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am jet over Lockerbie,
Scotland, that killed 270 people.
	   Banned from international flights under United Nations
sanctions, Gadhafi is expected to travel by land over the
Libyan-Egyptian border to the town of Saloum and then go on to
Cairo.
	   He will be arriving with an entourage including nine ministers
and a team of businessmen. The team will discuss potential Libyan
investments in Egypt, especially in the vast Toshka irrigation
project in southern Egypt.
	   The two countries are to sign seven trade, investment and
manufacturing agreements, according to Egyptian news reports. The
Libyans want to boost trade with Egypt, which now officially totals
492 million Egyptian pounds (dlrs 144 million) annually.
	   Despite U.S. complaints, Egypt has sought to maintain good
relations with its oil-rich neighbor. Gadhafi is likely to raise
the Lockerbie issue in talks scheduled Tuesday with President Hosni
Mubarak.
	   Lockerbie will also be on his agenda with Arab League Secretary
General Esmet Abdel-Meguid, who is to meet with British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook on June 14.
	   Both the United States and England have sought to isolate Libya
because of Gadhafi's failure to turn over for trial two Libyans
charged with the Lockerbie bombing. Gadhafi says they cannot get a
fair trial in either country and wants them tried in a neutral
state.
	   In an effort to force Libya to turn over the suspects, the U.N.
Security Council imposed sanctions in March 1992 that ban
international air travel, refuse arms sales to Libya and call for
limiting diplomatic contacts with the country. 	   
</TEXT>
