<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Montenegro, 2nd Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Wild gunfire greets victory by Milosevic foe 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photos
Eds: UPDATES with newer vote count.
By ALISON SMALE
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Wild gunfire erupted in downtown
Monday as revelers celebrated the victory in Montenegro's
parliamentary elections of the biggest challenger to Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic.
	   With 94.2 percent of the vote counted, the Election Commission
in the smaller of Yugoslavia's two republics said Montenegrin
President Milo Djukanovic's coalition had captured 49.5 percent of
the ballots compared to 36 percent for Milosevic protege Momir
Bulatovic.
	   The Montenegrin separatist Liberal Alliance _ the only other
party to clear the 3 percent vote threshold to get into parliament
_ received 6.2 percent of the vote.
	   Announcing those returns, commission chairman Stevan Damjanovic
said votes from 40 polling stations, where about 26,000 voters were
registered, were still not counted.
	   He expected those results to be in by Monday evening but said
voting would have to be repeated in two polling stations on
Wednesday, delaying an absolutely final count until later in the
week.
  Djukanovic's triumph, 3rd graf pvs
