<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG
</HEADLINE>
Thousands march to mark June 4, HONGKONG STANDARD  
   xfdws THOUSANDS-MARCH-TO-MARK sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THOUSANDS of pro-democracy activists held a protest on Sunday to
mark the ninth anniversary of the June 4 Tiananmen crackdown, the
first under Chinese rule.
	   But on the mainland, police temporarily detained about 20
dissidents from the eastern Shandong province and also warned
another 10 not to leave their homes ahead of the annual
demonstration over the 1989 Tiananmen Square incident, a banned
opposition party said.
	   In Hong Kong, an estimated 3,000 demonstrators, carrying black
and white banners, demanded the mainland government revise its
verdict on the brutal military crackdown.
	   The protesters marched from Victoria Park in Causeway Bay to the
SAR Government Headquarters, but unlike previous years they did not
pass the offices of the Xinhua News Agency.
	   They chanted slogans calling for the release of all dissidents
on the mainland and for democracy and human rights.
	   The radical April Fifth Action Group carried a symbolic coffin
with the slogan ``a political power that kills stinks for 10,000
years'', and put it outside the foreign ministry's Office of the
Commissioner.
	   The group carried banners and chanted slogans demanding the
resignation of President Jiang Zemin and National People's Congress
Chairman Li Peng, who they hold directly responsible for the
massacre.
	   A police spokesman said no arrests were made.
	   The protesters later said they hoped their demonstration
yesterday on Chinese soil could pave the way for more freedom to
demonstrate on the mainland.
	   Cheung Yiu-tong, a volunteer with the Hong Kong Alliance for the
Support of Patriotic Democratic Movements of China, said: ``Now
that we are under Chinese rule it is a lot more meaningful for Hong
Kong people to fight for democracy in China.'' Other demonstrators
were worried the Hong Kong government had plans to curb their
ability to hold protests in the future.
	   Alliance general secretary Albert Ho Chun-yan, a newly elected
legislator, said he feared a new law would be passed during the
next session of the Legislative Council on sedition and subversion
to limit protests.
	   Democratic Party vice-chairman Yeung Sum said the high turnout
for the demonstration showed people still cared about fighting for
democracy.
	   
</TEXT>
