u i     BC-India-Budget 3rdLd-Writethru   06-01 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Budget, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0680 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New budget addresses economic woes 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: ADDS defense spending increased, taxes steady. No pickup.
By ASHOK SHARMA
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ India's finance minister, who promised
firm action to deal with anti-nuclear sanctions that have battered
an already weak economy, introduced a budget Monday that included
more spending on infrastructure, defense and nuclear energy.
	   Finance Minister Yashwant Sinha also offered reassurance to
foreign businesses, whose investment he will need to jump-start
India's economy.
	   The Bharatiya Janata Party-led government's commitment to
``swadeshi,'' which the BJP defined as ``economic nationalism''
worried foreign investors. Sinha said ``swadeshi does not mean
isolation, swadeshi means making India strong and self-reliant.''
	   Sinha said he believed the nuclear sanctions ``will not have any
significant impact on our economic development,'' in part because
he believed countries like the United States, Australia and Japan
who cut loans and all but humanitarian aid after India's five
nuclear tests last month would ``moderate'' their opposition in
time.
	   ``On our part, our policies have to be clearly directed and
firm,'' he said.
	   The new government, presenting its first budget, has promised to
revive India's economic growth, which faltered to 5 percent in the
fiscal year 1997-98, the lowest rate in the last five years.
	   Sinha announced 611 billion rupees (dlrs 1.5 billion), a 35
percent increase, would be spent on what he called the key
infrastructure areas of energy, transportation and communications.
	   He also announced a hike of about 51 billion rupees (dlrs 1.2
billion), or about 14 percent, on defense. Military experts have
said much of the defense budget, which has been declining in recent
years, goes to maintaining conventional weapons.
	   ``There can be no compromise in defense preparedness,'' Sinha
said as lawmakers thumped their desks in appreciation.
	   To tap the financial capacity of the millions of Indians living
abroad, Sinha offered them educational, cultural and economic
concessions. He did not give details.
	   He also promised a ``hassle-free procedure'' for foreign
investors who have complained that bureaucratic red tape presents a
huge obstacle to doing business in India.
	   In a significant move, Sinha said he will open the
government-owned insurance sector to competition from private
Indian companies. He did not say foreign insurance companies would
be allowed in.
	   The government said it would sell off its interest in Indian
Airlines and several state-owned energy companies to raise funds.
But individual and corporate taxes were to remain steady because,
Sinha said, consistency in this area was needed to encourage
Indians to pay.
	   The previous government cut tax rates from 15 percent to 10
percent for those earning between 60,000 and 100,000 rupees (dlrs
1,540 to dlrs 2,560); from 30 to 20 for those earning between
100,000 and 150,000 rupees (dlrs 2,560 to dlrs 3,850); and from 40
to 30 for those earning more than 150,000 rupees (dlrs 3,850).
Those earning less than 60,000 rupees (dlrs 1,540) pay no taxes.
	   Sinha repeated the previous finance minister's argument that
Indians would be more likely to pay their taxes if they were not
burdensome. And, like the previous minister, he promised a
crackdown on evaders.
	   ``In a country of our size, it's a matter of great anxiety that
the total number of taxpayers constitutes less than 1.25 percent of
our population,'' he said.
	   Sinha said he decided to hold firm on taxes despite a great
temptation to raise them.
	   The government's pre-budget economic assessment, presented to
Parliament last week, was bleak. In addition to the falling growth,
it said the deficit rose to 6.1 percent of gross domestic product,
the total value of goods and services produced by the economy,
exceeding the target of 4.5 percent.
	   A 6.35 percent inflation rate was reported Sunday, up from 5
percent during 1997-1998. 	   
</TEXT>
