w2626  wstm-
r w     PROPERTY-TAM-AND-MARTINs     06-01 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> PROPERTY-TAM-AND-MARTIN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG
</HEADLINE>
Property market rebounds, HONGKONG STANDARD  
   xfdws PROPERTY-TAM-AND-MARTIN sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE property market has perked up, with transactions almost
trebling just days after the government announced a package of
measures to stabilise prices.
	   Real-estate agents on Sunday said the lifting of
anti-speculation measures and the pledge to boost liquidity for
banks to assist homebuyers has rekindled buyer sentiment.
	   ``After Mr Tung's announcement on Friday, total transactions
have jumped two to three times higher than before,'' said Louis
Chan, director of Centaline Property.
	   But not everybody was happy _ more than 200 buyers of pre-sale
flats marched in Central on Sunday to protest against measures they
said were of no use to them.
	   They marched from Statue Square to the SAR Government
Headquarters waving banners and chanting slogans: ``Step down,
Chief Executive'' and ``Chief Executive is in good shape but we are
in poor shape''.
	   Although transactions have risen, prices have not changed, Mr
Chan said.
	   Chi Cheung Property director Ivan Lo Chi-kai said the measures
would stabilise the primary market and, as a result, the
second-hand one as well.
	   ``Tierra Verde and the remaining units of other new projects
would benefit the most from these measures,'' he said.
	   The measures, according to Mr Lo, would enable developers to
establish a flexible sales policy.
	   Buyers fear they might be left out if developers were given more
flexibility and could opt not to rush in to sell their flats.
	   Choi Ai Min, managing director of Hong Kong Property, said the
measures marked the government's determination to manage the supply
of residential flats in a flexible manner.
	   In addition, prices of first-hand properties have already
bottomed, so the prices in the second-hand market will stabilise
shortly.
	   Midland Realty managing director Cheung Kam-shing said the
satisfactory results of the sale of Tierra Verde was good for
market in the short term.
	   He expected transactions in the first and second-hand market
this month to be 20 and 30 per cent higher, respectively.
	   ``Property in Tsing Yi, as affected by Tierra Verde, has
obviously stabilised,'' Mr Cheung said.
	   But he said investors should not be too optimistic as the
government measures were short-term and intended only to stabilise
the current market.
	   Yesterday's demonstrators mostly claimed to have bought property
last year as the market reached its peak.
	   They said the measures unveiled on Friday came too late,
claiming the prices of their units had plunged 30-40 per cent.
	   A Mrs Wu, 70, burst into tears during the demonstration and
wailed: ``I have lost all my savings.'' The unit she and her sons
purchased last May was in May Wood Court (Kingswood Villa).
	   ``When we bought the unit last year, it was worth $2.8 million
but now the banks estimate it to be worth less than $2 million,''
her son said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
