u i     BC-Kenya-WildlifeDirecto     06-01 0396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kenya-Wildlife Director </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dismissal of Kenya wildlife director blocked dlrs 400 million 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ David Western, fired by the government,
returned to the helm of the Kenya Wildlife Service because donor
countries withdrew critical financial support, a newspaper said
Monday.
	   A day after Western was fired on May 21, European donors
canceled dlrs 400 million in aid earmarked for salaries and other
crucial expenditures within the wildlife service, The East African,
a respected weekly reported.
	   Government and diplomatic offices were closed for a holiday, and
could not be reached for comment.
	   The cash-strapped, government-owned wildlife service has been
working closely with organizations including the World Bank,
coordinator of the Protected Areas Wildlife Service program, the
European Union, and British, Dutch, German and U.S. development
agencies.
	   Sources, who were not identified, told the newspaper the
decision to withhold funding was made soon after Western complained
at a news conference was ousted because he resisted ministerial
pressure to allow more mines in one park and to reallocate parts of
other parks for private use.
	   President Daniel arap Moi dismissed Western's allegations as
``cheap.'' Nonetheless, the government on Thursday extended
Western's contract until the end of the year ``so that proper
arrangements may be made for a takeover by (a new) director.''
	   The government has not explained why Western was dismissed nor
why his contract was extended.
	   On Friday, donors released dlrs 180 million to the wildlife
service. Hit by a devastating slump in tourism due to political
violence and floods, the wildlife service has been forced to make
massive layoffs and huge spending cuts.
	   Western has said he was pleased with his reinstatement, though
it cuts short his tenure by a year.
	   ``It will enable him to oversee the implementation of the
ongoing restructuring exercise at KWS, and allow him to pursue
funding options from both government and donors,'' the wildlife
service said in a statement issued on Western's behalf.
	   Western has held the post for more than four years.
	   Western's predecessor, Richard Leakey, resigned twice within
days in 1994, complaining of nepotism and corruption. He rejected a
presidential order to resume his duties.
	   (kjd)
</TEXT>
