<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 09:12:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2629  wstm-
r w     HASINA-LAUNCHES-OLDsked     06-01 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> HASINA-LAUNCHES-OLD sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANGLADESH
</HEADLINE>
Hasina launches old age allowance proramme, THE INDEPENDENT  
   xfdws HASINA-LAUNCHES-OLD sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   In a noble move to help the elderly people and remove poverty
from rural areas of the country, Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina today
launched the old age allowance programme.
	   ``We are determined to remove all sorts of discrimination,
exploitation, poverty and hunger from the society,'' she said
before handing over the pass hooks of the allowance programme to
the elderly people of Tungipara thana.
	   The government has undertaken the humanitarian programme to help
the aged but poor people of the country as per political commitment
of Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina.
	   Under the programme, 10 old distressed people from an ward that
means 90 people from each union will receive Tk 100 each per month.
	   Meanwhile, the government has enlisted some 4,03,110 people,
including 50 per cent women, from 4,479 unions under 461 thanas of
the country to bring them under the scheme.
	   On the inaugural day of the countrywide programme, nearly 450
old people of Tungipara thana received their allowances.
	   The Prime Minister handed over pass books, allowance of two
months and conveyance Tk 20 to 60 old men of the area to inaugurate
the noble programme.
	   ``I pray for her so that she can help more poor like us .. .. I
pray for her every success in her every effort,'' said Kasem
Sikder, a 75-year old man after receiving the first installment of
his life long allowance.
	   Kasem, a father of three sons, came from nearby Bhagerkul
village, said his sons give him foods, ``but that is not always
enough for me''.
	   ``I am very much happy as I have been able to take the chance to
receive the money from the Prime Minister herself.. ..from now on I
will buy an adequate amount of food for me,'' said a beaming Kasem
wearing a blur lanced obstacles.
	   Bijoy Krishna Mandal, aged about 80, came from Patgati village
to receive the allowance. He said, ``I pray for the 'Bangamata'
(mother of Bengal) so that she can serve thousands other poor
people.''
	   Shashi Charan Mandal, seemed to be 80 years old, said he will
spend the money for treatment of his eyes. ``I will buy medicine
for my eyes as I have become almost blind,'' said the old man
hailing from Chingari.
	   ``May Allah save our Prime Minister as she can do more for our
people,'' prayed the old man, a father of two sons and three
daughters.
	   Fulmala Biswas, a sixty-year old woman, also hailing from
Patgati village, said she will buy cloths and medicine for herself
by the money.
	   ``For a long time I could not buy medicine for want of money
although I have been suffering from various diseases,'' said
Fulmala in a jubilant mood. ``Now I will consult a doctor and buy
medicine.''
	   Another sexagenarian woman Devrani Roy said she had lost her
only son in the Liberation War, but now there is none to look after
her. ``I am just pulling on my life with the help of my
neighbours,'' she said adding that the money will help her a lot.
	   Earlier, addressing the gathering of the old men and women at
the Thana complex premises, the Prime Minister said the government
has taken up such a programme so that the neglected rural poor can
be benefited directly.
	   ``We are trying to help a little those poorest of the poor who
feel neglected during the last days of their lives as they are
considered burden of the society,'' she said.
	   The money, even though a very little, will help them raise their
status in the family and society, and make them feel that they are
still important, Hasina said.
	   ``This will have a positive impact on poverty alleviation
programmes of the government,'' she said adding that the main
target of the present government is to build up a poverty and
hunger free nation by ensuring a better life for the downtrodden.
	   Hasina said Father of the Nation Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur
Rahman was assassinated at a time when he started working for
economic emancipation of the people.
	   ``Now as the follower of the ideals of Bangabandhu I have
started various programmes to ensure economic freedom of the
people,'' she said. ``If we can bring back smile on face of the
downtrodden, the soul of Bangabandhu will get peace.''
	   The old aged allowance programme was inaugurated on the death
anniversary of the mother of Bangabandhu, Sayera Khatun.
	   ``We have started this noble programme on the death anniversary
of such a great lady who gave birth to the Father of the Nation,''
the Prime Minister said.
	   She said Bangabandhu had fought throughout his life for
establishing rights of the people and also sacrificed his life for
the people of the country.
	   ``Being the daughter of Bangabandhu, I'm also ready to sacrifice
everything for the countrymen,'' the Prime Minister said seeking
blessings from the people so that she can fight for the poor.
	   Finance Minister SAMS Kibria, State Minister for Social Welfare
Dr Mozammel Hossain, Gopalganj district Awami League general
secretary Sheikh Abdullah, Social Welfare Secretary Nurul Abedin,
DG of Social Welfare Directorate Meer Shahabuddin and Gopalganj DC
Nasiruddin also spoke on the occasion.
	   From the programme the Prime Minister went straight to her
ancestral home and offered fateha at the Mazar of Bangabandhu and
the Mazars of Bangabandhu's father Sheikh Lutfur Rahman and mother
Sayera Khatun.
	   Later, a milad mahfil was held at the mazar premises of the
Father of the Nation, which was attended, among others, by the
Finance Minister, Awami League leader Abdul Mannan, Col (retd)
Farrok Khan MP, Sheikh Helal Unddin MP and local people.
	   
</TEXT>
