<BODY>
<SLUG> WAR-ON-GRAFT-INTENSIFIES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG
</HEADLINE>
War on graft intensifies as deep-rooted malaise emerges, HONGKONG STANDARD  
   xfdws WAR-ON-GRAFT-INTENSIFIES sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   PREMIER Zhu Rongji has ordered a more intensive war on
corruption after nation-wide investigations into financial
institutions uncovered far more irregularities than expected.
	   In Guangdong alone, bad debts and non-performing loans were
found to have increased substantiallly since early this year _ in
spite of widespread awareness of the dangers posed by such
irregularities in light of the regional financial crisis.
	   Worse, more irregularities were found during the detailed
scrutiny of the province's banks and other financial institutions.
	   Similar discoveries have been made in other provinces, leading
to the growing view that the mainland's true situation is worse
than expected.
	   Initial reports suggest that many state corporations based in
the coastal regions have invested heavily in Southeast Asia. While
known, the extent is only now coming to light.
	   It is likely to lead to a thorough re-assessment of the impact
of the regional crisis on the mainland.
	   These discoveries have led Mr Zhu to order more intensive
investigations and more severe punishments.
	   It is understood that officials will be kicked out and barred
from the civil service, no matter how minor their misdeeds, a
mainland source said, quoting a recent speech by Mr Zhu that was
recently circulated internally.
	   Mr Zhu has also urged the media to give publicity to all such
misdeeds in the crucial business sector.
	   He also encouraged journalists to direct more energy and
criticism to the war on graft and the crackdown on irregularities.
	   Central investigators were asked to work closely with the media.
	   ``We should mobilise all the forces in the society in the fight
against these evils, especially those wrongdoings in the financial
and banking sectors, which are crucial to a healthy and stable
economic development,'' he said, pointing out that corruption,
cronyism and irregularities are key reasons behind economic
collapses in neighbouring countries.
	   He said it was not enough to rely solely on law enforcement
bodies.
	   A Guangdong official, admitting more instances of serious
irregularities have been uncovered, said officials in the whole
province have become fidgety as a result.
	   
</TEXT>
