<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Conservatives </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tories appoint right-wing anti-abortionist as health spokesman 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Conservative Party leader William Hague on Monday
appointed a right-wing legislator who opposes abortion as the
party's spokesman on health.
	   Ann Widdecombe, a staunch Roman Catholic who left the Anglican
Church because she also opposes women priests, has risen to
prominence as one of the Tories' most effective parliamentarians
since the party lost power a year ago.
	   Her appointment was part of a shakeup by Hague of the Tory
spokesmen in parliament, a group known as the Shadow Cabinet.
	   Another right-winger, Peter Lilley, who was Social Security
secretary in the previous Conservative government, was named deputy
leader of the party _ a post not filled under former prime minister
John Major, who led the party to a devastating defeat.
	   Miss Widdecombe, 50, was the only new appointee to the Shadow
Cabinet. Her colleagues in the group include Michael Howard, the
current foreign affairs spokesman, with whom she fell out when she
was his deputy in the previous government.
	   After the party's defeat, Miss Widdecombe effectively stymied
Howard's bid for the Tory leadership by saying there was
``something of the night'' about him.
	   There was no immediate sign Miss Widdecombe's strong views would
affect her position as health spokesman. Abortion is effectively
available on demand in Britain, and there is no significant public
demand for less liberal laws
	   ``This is the team that is going to hold to account the
government that is increasingly breaking its promises to the
country, and is going to generate ideas for the future,'' Hague
said as he left Tory party headquarters.
	   After a year in power, Labor Prime Minister Tony Blair holds
record popularity ratings, while opinion polls indicate
Conservative support stuck around 28 percent _ worse than the 30.6
percent than the party got in the May 1997 national election.
	   (mj-kg)
</TEXT>
