w2634  wstm-
r w     DEADLY-VIRUSsked     06-01 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> DEADLY-VIRUS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG
</HEADLINE>
Nothing to fear from deadly virus say officials, HONGKONG STANDARD  
   xfdws DEADLY-VIRUS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   HEALTH officials on Sunday gave the assurance that the
intestinal disease which killed at least 17 newborn babies and
young children in Taiwan was not likely to hit Hong Kong because of
the clean drinking water and environment here.
	   President of the Hong Kong Medical Association Dr Lo Wing-lok
said there were no signs indicating the presence here of the killer
virus _ entero-virus type 71.
	   Director for Health Margaret Chan Fung Fu-chun promised her
department would follow the situation closely.
	   But no special working group would be set up at the moment, a
spokeswoman for the Health Department confirmed last night.
	   Dr Chan said symptoms of the virus were similar to most
gastro-intestinal diseases, although type 71 could develop into a
dangerous condition and be fatal in the worst case.
	   ``A patient with the disease will develop fever and diarrhoea.
	   ``If his heart is also infected, he will have shortness of
breath and heart failure.
	   ``If a patient (with a gastro-intestinal condition) has heart
failure and shortness of breath or other serious complications,
then we can tell that he is infected with the type,'' the health
spokeswoman said.
	   The spokeswoman said the virus was spread through food and close
contact or touching of an infected person's faeces and body fluids.
	   It is believed there were occasional cases here.
	   Dr Lo said children and infants were more vulnerable to the
virus than adults.
	   He said the virus would not pose a great threat to adults with a
strong immune system, but children under two years of age and who
had no immunisation could be infected more easily, he said.
	   The virus can infect the intestinal system and other organs,
including the heart.
	   But there was no evidence an outbreak would hit Hong Kong due to
its clean drinking water and environment, Dr Lo said.
	   To prevent young children from being infected, parents and
nursery staff should be cautious about hygiene, he added.
	   Meanwhile, the health spokeswoman said young children who caught
any infectious disease should be suspended from school.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
