w2635  wstm-
r i     BC-AirFrance-Strike 3rdLd-Writethru   06-01 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Air France-Strike, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Passengers stranded as Air France strike begins France's biggest strike in 27 years, smaller airlines increasing flights 
</HEADLINE>
EDS: UPDATES with quote from SNPL pilot union, ADDS it is Air
AP Photos PAR101-104
By CHRISTOPHER BURNS
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Thousands of frustrated passengers were stranded at
airports across the country Monday, after Air France pilots began a
strike that threatened to disrupt travel plans during the World
Cup.
	   Monitors at Paris' main airports offered a bleak sight for
passengers: departure screens read ``canceled'' in bright red
letters next to nearly all Air France flights nine days before the
soccer championship begins.
	   The jets of the official airline for the World Cup, many
decorated with players representing the 32 teams, sat idle at
terminals. Their 3,200 pilots sought to block wage cuts aimed at
keeping the newly profitable state-owned airline out of the red.
	   The walkout, Air France's biggest in 27 years, was a serious
embarrassment to the leftist government of Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin, and train workers were also threatening to strike later in
the week.
	   Frustrated passengers lined up at Air France ticket counters at
Charles de Gaulle Airport in Paris, hoping to switch their tickets
to other carriers.
	   Nicolas Minvelle, hoping to leave on vacation to Senegal, said
it wasn't fair the pilots were striking ahead of the World Cup,
being played in 10 cities across France.
	   ``They use an international event to bother everyone, it's too
bad. That's not the image of France, it should be avoided. You can
say they are not civic-minded,'' he said.
	   Yelena Panteley, a Russian student from California, was on her
way to see her mother in Saint Petersburg, hoping to catch an
alternate flight. ``There is hope, but nothing's sure.''
	   Under normal circumstances, around 100,000 people would have
used Air France on Monday.
	   Air France assured that it would make good on its commitment to
fly World Cup teams.
	   But the airline expected to cancel 90 percent of long-haul
flights for the coming week. About 25 percent of short- and
medium-haul flights out of Paris' Charles de Gaulle airport are
likely to fly as planned, the company has said, as are about 20
percent leaving from Orly airport, in south Paris.
	   During the World Cup, fans will travel across France regularly
since their teams will rotate between several venues. In addition,
there are 9,000 journalists accredited to cover the event.
	   Christian Paris, spokesman for the main union in the strike, the
SNPL, admitted the consequences were ``disastrous.''
	   ``But when you're confronted by an attack you have no choice but
to defend yourself. And that's what the pilots are doing as of
today,'' he said in an interview on television channel France 2.
	   In contrast to past conflicts when ground crews blocked airport
runways, the pilots kept a low profile and simply didn't show up
for work. Other airlines quietly went on with their flights and
some increased flight quotas in some parts of the country to cope
with demand.
	   Transport Minister Jean-Claude Gayssot, speaking on French
television, urged both sides to ``take up the path of discussion.''
	   Fearful that France's image could be tarnished when the soccer
matches begin, one leftist lawmaker, Georges Sarre, denounced the
pilots as ``the damned of the Earth.''
	   The SNPL union has called a 15-day renewable strike starting
Monday. Three smaller unions called for a strike from Monday to
Thursday.
	   On Thursday, French industry will slow, with the CGT union
calling for a strike which is expected to affect most public
services, as well as the energy and construction sectors.
	   (ip-cb)
</TEXT>
