u i     BC-Kuwait-DeportationCen     06-01 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kuwait-Deportation Center </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Newspaper reports deportation center to be closed in two weeks 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ Kuwait has temporarily released hundreds of
detainees from a controversial deportation center and is hoping to
close the facility in two weeks, Al-Watan daily reported Monday.
	   The Talha Deportation Center was set up after Kuwait was
liberated in 1991 from a seven-month Iraqi occupation. But scores
of inmates have since gone on hunger strikes or attempted suicide
to protest detentions as long as five years.
	   Kuwaiti Interior Minister Sheik Mohammad al-Khaled al-Sabah said
that 250 people were freed on bail for six months to allow them to
solve problems preventing them from leaving the country, Al-Watan
reported.
	   Talha's inmates are generally debtors or or so-called stateless
Arabs that the government is seeking to deport. However, the
debtors are expected to pay what they owe before being deported,
and some of the others have nowhere to go.
	   Interior and Justice Ministry officials have met with each of
the center's inmates to ensure that their problems were solved and
that they could leave the country, Sheik Mohammad told Al-Watan.
	   Many of the stateless Arabs, which the government says number
about 120,000, maintain they have lived in Kuwait for decades, but
have been denied citizenship. The government argues most have other
passports but have destroyed them seeking Kuwait citizenship.
	   An estimated 600 people were reported detained in Talha last
month. But after the releases, only 163 people are being held at
Talba, Mohammad al-Zobi, a public prosecutor told Al-Watan. He said
that they have been there for no more than one month.
	   Al-Zobi said the debts of more than 60 inmates had been
forgiven, and hundreds of others have already left the country.
	   Human rights groups have criticized the detentions at the
center, arguing that they are protracted and sometimes done without
court order.
	   Two years ago, the government promised to shut down the
facility, which served as a school before the 1990 Iraqi invasion
of Kuwait. It did not deliver on the promise.
  de-tt-ggl
</TEXT>
