<SLUG> BC-Greece-Bank Crisis </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government to proceed with bank sale despite union opposition 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ The government said Monday it will go
ahead with the sale of Greece's fourth largest bank, bringing it
onto a collision course with Socialist-controlled labor unions.
	   Ionian Bank employees walked off their jobs on May 8 protesting
plans by the Socialist government to sell the state-owned bank,
part of a broad-ranging plan to streamline the economy in view of
European monetary union.
	   Workers ignored a court decision Wednesday declaring the strike
illegal, forcing Premier Costas Simitis to hold an emergency
Cabinet meeting to review government privatization plans.
	   Efforts to unload Ionian have created one of the strongest trade
union backlashes against the government. Simitis still faces
problems with restructuring Olympic Airways, the debt-ridden
national carrier.
	   Protests are also expected over future plans to cut costs at the
post office, public buses and the national railroad.
	   ``We have unanimously agreed to proceed with the government's
decision to privatize Ionian Bank,'' said National Economy Minister
Yannos Papantoniou after the emergency Cabinet meeting.
	   His statement tried to allay fears of a looming split in the
governing socialist party, or PASOK, caused by the privatization
plan.
	   But the socialist-dominated Federation of Greek Bank Employee
Unions, an umbrella union, vowed to strike indefinitely unless the
government revokes the bank's sale.
	   Ionian's management has asked a court to declare the
federation's strike illegal.
	   In an attempt to defuse the situation and calm tempers,
Papantoniou invited workers and unionists for talks. He has already
pledged that no jobs will be lost in the first few years after the
sale.
	   Simitis has been struggling to keep the party united following
the death of its populist founder Andreas Papandreou two years ago.
Large portions of the party's grass roots followers believe his
free market policies contradict its socialist welfare-state
ideology.
	   ``It's a shame that a necessary policy began in a way which in
the end undermines its importance and effectiveness,'' said
European Commissioner Christos Papoutsis, a PASOK member, in an
interview with the Athens daily Ta Nea.
	   (eb-pq) 	   
</TEXT>
