r w     PRO-BEIJINGERS-STRESSske     06-01 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> PRO-BEIJINGERS-STRESS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG
</HEADLINE>
Pro-Beijingers stress action on economy, HONGKONG STANDARD  
   xfdws PRO-BEIJINGERS-STRESS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   MEASURES to revive the economy, not debates over the
democratisation of Hong Kong, should top the legislative agenda,
pro-Beijing leaders say.
	   Speaking at Sunday's City Forum, Hong Kong Progressive Alliance
vice-chairman Carson Wen said legislators should act on people's
prime concerns.
	   Hong Kong people were mainly worried about stimulating the
economy to overcome the current slump and improve their livelihood,
they said.
	   Mr Wen cited a survey that found most people considered the
economy, unemployment and welfare as the most urgent matters facing
Hong Kong.
	   Those more concerned with boosting democracy were in the
minority, the survey showed.
	   Mr Wen's views were echoed by Chan Kam-lam, a legislator-elect
and core member of the pro-Beijing Democratic Alliance for the
Betterment of Hong Kong.
	   Mr Chan, who won his seat through the 800member Election
Committee, said economic development and people's livelihoods
should get a higher priority than democratisation.
	   He stressed that legislators elected through the Election
Committee and the functional constituencies could ably represent
the people.
	   Mr Chan also described as ``reckless'' current calls to amend
the Basic Law as to speed up democratic reform.
	   But Selina Chow Liang Shuk-yee of the pro-business Liberal Party
disagreed with the two, saying democratisation and economic
development were not mutually exclusive.
	   ``Democracy and the economy can't be separated,'' Mrs Chow said,
explaining that democracy did not mean giving up economic
development.
	   But she stressed that Hong Kong should maintain a healthy
environment for economic development, which was the key to its
success.
	   Owen Wong, a senior lecturer of the University of Hong Kong's
School of Professional and Continuing Education, also said the
economy and democracy were closely related.
	   He explained that people's right to vote and how they exercised
that right constituted a governing force of economic development.
	   Democratic Party vice-chairman Anthony Cheung Ping-leung said
only direct elections could guarantee that the people's calls to
revive the economy would be heeded.
	   ``If politicians failed to give you a satisfactory report card,
they have to step down, this is the promise of democracy,'' he
said.
	   Independent Andrew Wong Wang-fat cited the case of former
Indonesian president Suharto and how he had to step down.
	   Mr Wong said the pace of democratisation must be stepped up and
the Basic Law amended.
	   He criticised the government and some conservatives for trying
to scare the people by leading them to believe the economy would
worsen in a democracy.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
