r w     TRANSIT-VISIT-TO-HKsked     06-01 0333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> TRANSIT-VISIT-TO-HK sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG
</HEADLINE>
Transit visit to HK `not practical', HONGKONG STANDARD  
   xfdws TRANSIT-VISIT-TO-HK sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE new immigration scheme of allowing Taiwanese travellers to
the mainland seven days transit in Hong Kong is impractical, a
legislator-elect charged on Sunday.
	   Howard Young of the Liberal Party, who represents the tourism
functional constituency, said the scheme had a flaw that could
diminish its effectiveness in boosting tourism.
	   ``The Immigration Department is willing to grant the transit
privilege to a holder of a valid (mainland travel) permit, but the
permit must also have a valid entry-exit endorsement.
	   ``Under the current operating system, this is not practical for
the return journey back to Taiwan from the mainland, and will not
encourage stopovers in Hong Kong on the way back,'' he said.
	   Entry-exit endorsements are currently made on a permit issued by
China Travel Service (CTS) on behalf of the mainland authority each
time the Taiwanese visitor leaves the mainland.
	   This is done by either the Taiwanese visitor going to a CTS
officer in Hong Kong, or sending the permit to CTS through an agent
in Taiwan after he has returned home.
	   ``So how can the visitor get the endorsement from CTS in Hong
Kong if he isn't allowed to enter Hong Kong to do it in the first
place?'' he asked.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
