w2647  wstm-
r w     STOCK-OF-UREA-WILLsked     06-01 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> STOCK-OF-UREA-WILL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANGLADESH
</HEADLINE>
Stock of urea will be raised to 5,20,000 MT by next month, THE INDEPENDENT  
   xfdws STOCK-OF-UREA-WILL sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   After meeting the total domestic demand, the present stock of
urea of 4,13,000 metric tons (MT) will be raised to 5,20,000 MT
worth Taka 250 crore by the next month.
	   This was disclosed at a meeting of the Advisory Committee on
fertiliser at the conference room of the Ministry of Industries, an
official press release said Sunday.
	   Convenor of the Advisory Committee and advisor to the Prime
Minister on Agriculture and Food M Anisuzzaman presided over the
meeting.
	   Commerce and Industries Minister Tofail Ahmed and Food and
Agriculture Minister Motia Chowdhury attended the meeting.
	   The projected demand of urea during the next financial year
(July 98-June 99) has been estimated at 21 lakh MT.
	   The six urea fertiliser factories under Bangladesh Chemical
Industries Corporation (BCIC) are expected to produce 20 lakh MT in
the next financial year making a stock of 25,20,000 MT in the
country.
	   After meeting the projected demand of 21 lakh MT, the BCIC
factories and buffer godowns will have a closing stock of 4,20,000
MT at the end of June 1999, the press release said.
	   The Bangladesh Fertiliser Association's leaders informed the
meeting that, at present they have a stock of about 1,50,000 MT.
So, all these indication shows that at the end of next financial
year country will have a total stock of 5,70,000 MT of urea.
	   The revised demand of urea for the current fiscal is 21 lakh MT.
But the country till now consumed 17,78,000 MT of urea and by the
end of June it will be 18,18,000 MT.
	   The 28 buffer godowns and godowns of six fertiliser factories
having capacity of 2,26,000 MT and 3,00,000 MT respectively are now
packed up with urea and no space left to accommodate further stock.
	   In this backdrop, the Advisory Committee has decided to export
30,000 MT of urea immediately. The committee will sit again within
a month to review the overall stock, production and supply
situation and explore possibility of further export.
	   While taking the decision the requirements of urea in the next
mini-peak (October-December) and main peak (January-March) have
also been taken care of.
	   The meeting was informed that after the next mini peak period,
5,86,000 MT of urea will be in the godowns after meeting country's
demand while the stock remain at 3,10,000 MT after meeting the
demand of the main peak period besides the stock at the dealers'
level.
	   The meeting also reviewed stock of the Triple Super Phosphate
(TSP) and Di-Ammonium Phosphate (DAP) manure and urged the
Agriculture Extension Department to expedite the publicity to
generate more interest amongst the farmer to use DAP as a balanced
fertiliser containing sulphur and phosphorous, contents of the
soil, which could help reduce ecological imbalance of using
chemical fertiliser.
	   The meeting expressed satisfaction over the stability in price
at the retailers level.
	   Commerce Secretary Sayed Alamgir Farrouk Chowdhury, BCIC
Chairman M Anwarul Haq, acting President of BFA Kafiluddin Ahmed
and other officials of the concerned ministries and agencies were
present in the meeting.
	   
</TEXT>
