r w     LIFT-PROPERTY-SLUMPsked     06-01 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> LIFT-PROPERTY-SLUMP sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG
</HEADLINE>
Help needed to lift property slump says Loh, HONGKONG STANDARD  
   xfdws LIFT-PROPERTY-SLUMP sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE ailing property market must be given a timely overhaul,
legislator Christine Loh Kung-wai urged on Sunday.
	   A profit-based tax should be imposed on property developers to
replace the current lump-sum premium, she said.
	   She said this would open up the market beyond its current
dominance by large developers, and encourage competition.
	   Property-price forecasts, currently published after three
months, should be released sooner in order to give the market a
boost, she added.
	   ``Prompt and accurate information should be a stabilising
factor,'' she said.
	   And she gave her support to the lifting of pre-sale restrictions
in the property market.
	   ``Speculators are nowhere in sight but developers need to speed
up cash flow at this difficult time,'' she said.
	   Her remarks came a day after the rush for Tsing Yi flats, which
saw 1,400 units sold in one day, following the government's lifting
of restrictions on the resale of unfinished apartments.
	   The Citizens Party chairwoman said the property market must be
given all possible help and at the same time urged that Hong Kong
be less dependent on property.
	   The government should act as a guarantor for small and
medium-sized businesses otherwise unable to secure bank loans, she
said.
	   With 60 per cent of the workforce employed by small and
medium-sized businesses, and with these businesses comprising 98
per cent of Hong Kong enterprises, the government must step in to
help them during difficult economic times.
	   A pilot scheme could be set up to provide loan guarantees for
businesses having difficulties securing finance from cautious
banks.
	   Loans would be granted on the basis of industry, type and size,
and on the soundness of the business plan.
	   The legislator deplored the executive-led government of the SAR,
and the lack of public consultation on matters of policy.
	   She cited as an example the 70 per cent home-ownership target.
	   ``Just how did Mr Tung come up with 70 per cent? Why not aim for
65 or 80 per cent? '' 
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
