<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
While students protest, Indonesia government launches graft probe 
</HEADLINE>
EDS: RELEADS with updates throughout
AP Photos
By GEOFF SPENCER
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Facing increased pressure to clean up
past misdeeds, Indonesia's new government announced a broad-based
inquiry Monday into corruption under ex-President Suharto.
	   However, it stopped short of meeting demands by student
protesters and others who want the wealth of Suharto and his
super-rich family specifically targeted.
	   Critics say the Suhartos blatantly used their power and position
to amass billions of dollars by dominating the now ailing economy.
	   Thousands of students staged peaceful protests in several cities
Monday calling for an end to both local and national graft.
	   In Jakarta, about 50 students rallied outside the U.S. Embassy
against what they said were American attempts to delay foreign
loans to Indonesia.
	   Flanked by soldiers, the protesters sat down at the gates and
chanted slogans against U.S. intervention in the affairs of their
economically-shattered country.
	   They accused the U.S. of conspiring to stall the disbursement of
aid tied to a dlrs 43 billion rescue package led by the
International Monetary Fund. The loans were suspended amid
political turmoil that led to the May 21 resignation of President
Suharto.
	   The IMF is expected to deliberate Monday on whether to resume
aid.
	   Meanwhile, a leading opposition figure has called on Suharto to
donate the bulk of his wealth back to the country as it battles its
worst economic crisis in decades.
	   Amien Rais, a prominent Muslim leader, said that with Suharto's
money Indonesia would not have to beg international agencies to
prop up the economy.
	   Rais said that if Suharto did that ``the Indonesian people could
find it in their hearts to pardon him.''
	   Rais and others have called for an inquiry into Suharto's
business empire and have also demanded that the former first family
be barred from leaving the country.
	   Attorney General Sudjono Atmonegoro said the corruption inquiry
had been set up in response to public anger over the conduct of
``government officials.'' He did not specifically name Suharto.
	   ``The investigation is underway,'' he said. ``This investigation
is a process that will need time. It cannot be completed in just
one or two days.''
	   Sudjono said the inquiry would be carried out on the principle
of ``presumption of innocence'' and would involve many government
departments and outside agencies.
	   As part of the probe, Sudjono said he had received assurances
from Suharto family members that they would not leave Indonesia.
	   While there were no plans to question Suharto, the former
president might be asked to comment on evidence from others, he
said.
	   The head of the powerful military, Gen. Wiranto, said recently
he was opposed to an investigation into the Suharto family fortune
because it could cause national disunity.
	   The military played a key role in Indonesia's recent political
crisis. It quelled riots by putting thousands of soldiers and
dozens of tanks on the street.
	   Some claim it also was instrumental in persuading Suharto,
himself a retired army general, to quit in favor of new President
B.J. Habibie, a civilian and Suharto loyalist who has promised
political and economic reforms.
	   Also on Monday Habibie appointed three former Suharto advisors
to help steer the economy through its crisis.
	   The economic crisis claimed another casualty Monday when
Indonesia's third largest airline, controlled by Suharto's youngest
son, closed down.
	   The government said the carrier registered enormous losses
because of a 70 percent drop in the value of the currency, the
rupiah, since July 1997.
	   Much of the costs borne by the airline were in dollars, but its
revenue was mainly in rupiah.
	   Sempati's shareholders include Suharto's son Hutomo ``Tommy''
Mandala Putra as well as a military foundation. 	   
</TEXT>
