<HEADLINE>
BANGLADESH
</HEADLINE>
Forex market moderately active, THE INDEPENDENT  
   xfdws FOREX-MARKET-MODERATELY sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   The trading in the local foreign exchange market was moderately
active Sunday. In the interbank market demand for US dollar was
high triggered by fear of further depreciation of Taka and also the
depreciating trend of Pakistan and Indian rupee, says a Standard
Chartered Bank market commentary.
	   But due to the closure of the international markets the
nationalised banks were reluctant to sell dollars. However, US
dollar traded in small volume and is
	   reported to have traded between Taka 46.4550 and Taka 46.4650.
The call money rate eased due to maturity of treasury bills worth
Taka 343 crore and
	   is reported to have ranged between 5.5 per cent and 6.5 per
cent. Bangladesh Bank accepted 30 days treasury bills worth Taka
242.90 crore at 8.43 per cent and 1 year treasury bills worth Taka
247 crore at 10.25 per cent.
	   International foreign exchange markets remain closed on weekend.
However, on Friday, in New York trading the US dollar continued to
crash upward against the Japanese yen on hack of fragile Japanese
economy. The yen came under pressure as Japan's unemployment rose
from 3.9 per cent in March to 4.1 per cent in April and weaker than
expected Japanese retail sales data. But dollar's rise was capped
due to fears of intervention by the Bank of Japan. The DEM on the
other hand ended lower against the US dollar due to Germany's heavy
exposure in Russia. New York closing on Friday for US dollar
against DEM was 1.7855/65, yen was 138.81/86, and GBP was at
1.6295/1.6305 against US dollar.
	   
</TEXT>
