r w     NO-TOBACCO-DAY-OBSERVEDs     06-01 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> NO-TOBACCO-DAY-OBSERVED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANGLADESH
</HEADLINE>
No Tobacco Day observed, THE INDEPENDENT  
   xfdws NO-TOBACCO-DAY-OBSERVED sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   No Tobacco Day was observed in the country as elsewhere in the
world with a commitment to build a tobacco-free life for all.
	   To mark the day, various anti-tobacco groups including Life and
United Nations Information Centre organised different programmes.
	   President Justice Shahabuddin Ahmed and Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina gave separate messages on the occasion.
	   In the capital, the day's event began with a colourful rally in
the morning. The rally began from in front of the National Museum
and rounded up at Osmani Memorial Hall.
	   Attending a signature campaign on the occasion at his office,
State Minister for Information Prof Abu Sayeed declared his
ministry a tobacco free zone from yesterday.
	   The programme was organised jointly by Life and UNIC.
	   Speaking on the occasion, the State Minister emphasised on the
need for creating awareness among the people against the bad impact
of tobacco.
	   He said offering of bidi and cigarette to the voters during the
election campaign should be discouraged.
	   Among others, Information Secretary M Akmal Hossain, Director
General of BTV Syed Salahuddin Zaki, UNIC Information Officer Kazi
Ali Reza, Advisor of Life Mahbubuddin Ahmed were present.
	   Dhaka Ahsania Mission organised a discussion meeting on the
occasion at its auditorium. Prof Nazrul Islam Miah, Consultant of
Ahsania Mission Cancer Hospital, presented a paper there.
	   MANOS
	   Meanwhile, MANOS, an anti-smoking and anti-drug organisation
arranged a discussion at the National Museum auditorium yesterday
to mark the Day.
	   Participants at the discussion said that at least 80 crore of
the total 110 crore smokers aged 15 years and above were living in
the developing countries.
	   They quoted a WHO report as saying that 47 per cent males and 12
per cent females of the world are smokers. They said 17 per cent of
the deaths globally in 1995 was caused by tobacco.
	   The discussants anticipated an increased trend in tobacco
related deaths in future which would be 22 per cent by the year
2020.
	   Chief Election Commissioner Abu Hena was the chief guest on the
occasion while Prof Kabir Chowdhury was the special guest with
MANOS President Dr Arup Ratan Chowdhury in the chair. It was also
participated by Prof Madhushree Bhadra, film actor Ilyas Kanchon
and Lalon sangeet artiste Farida Parvin.
	   
</TEXT>
