<BODY>
<SLUG> LEECH-SHAU-KEI-WAN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG
</HEADLINE>
Leech found in tap in Shau Kei Wan, HONGKONG STANDARD  
   xfdws LEECH-SHAU-KEI-WAN sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   A LEECH has been found in tap water of a Shau Kei Wan public
housing unit.
	   A woman in Yiu Tung Estate said she found the leech in water
being used to make soup on Friday night.
	   ``I knew it was a leech because I saw one and was bit by one
when I worked on a farm as a girl,'' said the woman, who wouldn't
give her name.
	   As she was about to prepare a Tuen Ng Festival dinner for her
husband, daughter and son, who have been living in the flat for a
little less than three years, the woman said she filled a pot with
water from the tap.
	   ``I saw the leech in the pot when I was about to put it on the
stove top,'' she said.
	   She said the critter was black and four to five centimetres in
length.
	   She said she put it in a bowl to show to the Housing Department.
	   But the staff members reportedly told her their superior was on
holiday and would not deal with the matter until Monday.
	   A spokesman said it could not confirm whether the worm indeed
originated from the tap at this point as investigations were still
going on.
	   The woman called the Water Services Department, who also
promised to investigate.
	   The woman said no sand, rust, or any other particles had been
found in the family's tap water before.
	   In the meantime, the family is filtering the kitchen tap water
through a thin cloth.
	   ``I have to do something,'' the woman said. ``My two children
refused to drink the soup after they learned that a leech was found
in the tap water.'' A biologist said leeches suck blood when
attached to the skin, but cannot survive hot water and soap, and
are not poisonous.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
