u i     BC-Pakistan-Iran-Nuclear     06-01 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Iran-Nuclear,0464 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Muslims worldwide ''happy'' Pakistan tested nuclear devices: Iran 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photos ISL101
By KATHY GANNON
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Iran's Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi _ the first visitor to Islamic Pakistan since it exploded
six nuclear devices _ said Monday that Muslims worldwide welcomed
the nuclear tests.
	   It is particularly so in the Middle East, where Muslims believe
their traditional adversary, Israel, possesses the ability to make
nuclear bombs, he said.
	   ``Until now, they felt in ... the Middle East that only Israel
had the capability ... now they feel confident,'' because a
fellow-Islamic country also possesses the ability to make nuclear
weapons, Kharrazi told reporters at a brief news conference upon
his arrival in the Pakistani capital Islamabad.
	   Kharrazi, however, dismissed suggestions that Iran was preparing
to follow Pakistan down the nuclear road.
	   ``We don't have any nuclear weapons program ... what we have is
for peaceful purposes,'' and all Iran's nuclear facilities are open
to international inspectors, he said.
	   Last Thursday, after Pakistan tested five nuclear devices,
Pakistan's Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif promised to safeguard the
nuclear technology and vowed not to share it with any other
country.
	   Pakistan tested a sixth nuclear device on Saturday, one-upping
rival neighbor India, which detonated five nuclear devices three
weeks ago.
	   Kharrazi said India left Pakistan with no choice of whether to
test or not.
	   ``As a matter of its national security and to create a balance
in the region, Pakistan had no choice,'' he said.
	   While in Pakistan, Kharrazi said he will try to cool tempers and
ease tension in the Asian subcontinent.
	   ``We understand the security concerns of Pakistan, but at the
same time we think there should be more restraint and a relaxation
of tensions,'' he said.
	   Pakistan and India have traded a war of words since the first
nuclear test by India on May 11. India has threatened to step up
its military activity on its side of the troubled Kashmir border _
the flash point of two previous wars between the two nuclear
powers.
	   They fought a third war in 1971 over Bangladesh or what was then
East Pakistan.
	   In 1990, the specter of war surfaced and many people here feared
a fourth _ possibly nuclear _ war between the uneasy neighbors.
	   Pakistan accused India of preparing to attack its nuclear sites
last week, scrambled its own air force and put its soldiers on
alert.
	   The latest accusation came from Pakistan's Foreign Minister
Gohar Ayub who said his country had ``credible evidence'' that
India was preparing a second site to test nuclear weapons. India
denied the accusation. 	   
</TEXT>
