	   MACAU criminal investigation chief Antonio Marques Baptista
returned at the weekend from a three-week working visit to
Portugal.
	   The Judicial Police director went to Lisbon on 9 May _ nine days
after he had personally arrested alleged triad leader Wan Kuok-koi
at the Lisboa Hotel.
	   Wan's May Day arrest came about 12 hours after Mr Baptista's car
was bombed.
	   While in Lisbon, Mr Baptista announced that he would recruit
Portuguese police experts on organised and violent crime.
	   The specialist crime-fighters, including 10 criminologists, were
expected to arrive in Macau in the next few weeks.
	   Mr Baptista _ nicknamed Rambo by admirers for his frequent
participation in high-risk anti-triad swoops _ had said Macau
police officers were in an ``unequal fight'' against organised
crime. The Judicial Police force that he heads, which is the
enclave's criminal investigation department, has a strength of
about 300.
	   Mr Baptista, who was a public prosecutor in Portugal, had also
vowed to be relentless in the fight against organised crime in
Macau. ``He is back to beat the tiger,'' a Judicial Police
detective remarked yesterday.
	   Beijing was apparently stepping up its interest too. Tian Qiyu,
a vice-minister of state security, was reported to have paid an
unheralded two-day visit to Macau in mid-May to get first-hand
information about the enclave's security woes.
	   The governor, General Vasco Rocha Vieira, as well as Mr Baptista
was in Lisbon at the time of Mr Tian's visit.
	   Special legislation to prepare the way for the creation of a
task force to deal with organised and violent crimes was scheduled
to be gazetted on Monday.
	   
