w2672  wstm-
R I     BC-Britain-Wool     06-01 0311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Wool </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World wool production estimated at lowest since World War II 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Revised estimates released Monday showed world
wool production falling for the eighth successive year to a
post-World War II low.
	   But the International Wool Textile Organization said prices
remained weak because of Australia boosting supplies by selling
from a stockpile and demand depressed by financial problems in
Asia, particularly Japan.
	   A report by the agency, which represents the wool industry in
exporting and importing countries, also cited poor retail wool
sales in Europe and ``deteriorating consumer and business
confidence'' in China.
	   It said the decline in production was due largely to farmers
switching from sheep to products with better returns.
	   The Brussels-based body's new estimate put global wool
production in the 1997-98 (July-June) season at 1.429 million
metric tons (clean basis), compared with 1.438 million tons
previously forecast and 1996-97's clip of 1.474 million tons.
	   In 1989-90, output hit a record 2.01 million tons. Since then,
the agency's figures have shown declines every season _
particularly in the territories of the former Soviet Union and
Australia.
	   The 1997-98 production falls more than offset a record clip in
China.
	   The breakdown of the IWTO's latest 1997-98 global clip estimate
-- in thousands of metric tons (clean basis), with 1996- 97
comparisons in parentheses -- included Australia 442 (457), New
Zealand 201 (203), China 156 (149), former Soviet Union 83 (100),
Uruguay 55 (60), Britain 40 (42), Argentina 37 (41), Turkey 36
(36), South Africa 34 (37), India 28 (28), Iran 23 (23), Pakistan
23 (23), Irish Republic 17 (17), Spain 16 (16), Morocco 14 (14),
United States 13 (14), Brazil 11 (11), Mongolia 11 (11), Romania 11
(11) and France 10 (10).
	   (rs-mj)
</TEXT>
