BANGLADESH
</HEADLINE>
President calls for stepping up anti-smoking movement, THE INDEPENDENT  
   xfdws PRESIDENT-CALLS-FOR sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   President Justice Shahabuddin Ahmed yesterday called for
intensifying anti-smoking movement across the country comprising
representatives from all sections of the society.
	   ``It's very difficult to free the nation from the problems
caused by smoking without an all-out effort of the government and
the private sector and strong cooperation of the people,'' he said
inaugurating a seminar at the Osmani Memorial Hall yesterday
morning.
	   Ministry of Health and Family Welfare organised the seminar in
collaboration with ADHUNIK (Amra Dhumpan Nibaran Kari), Addiction
Cure Centre and Health Education Bureau on the eve of ``World
No-Tobacco Day '98.''
	   ``Growing up without tobacco'' is the theme of this year's No
Tobacco Day.
	   Chaired by national Professor Nurul Islam, the founder President
of ADHUNIK, the function was also addressed by Health and Family
Welfare Minister Salahuddin Yusuf and Health Secretary Muhammad
Ali.
	   ``When the trend of smoking has declined in the developed
countries following world-wide anti-smoking drive by the WHO and
UNESCO, the tendency is gradually increasing in the developing
countries,'' the President told the function.
	   In Bangladesh, he said, the number of smokers were 2 crore in
1988 which seemed to be increased by this time. ``The habit mostly
exists in the poor section of the people.''
	   President Shahabuddin said anti-smoking movement was not
vigorous in the country before 1987. In this regard, ADHUNIK has
played a pioneering role, he added.
	   The President said various steps like announcement of smoking
free zone, imposition of tax on tobacco and inclusion of
anti-smoking issues in the text books have already been taken to
discourage smoking, but expected success has not yet been achieved
in this regard.
	   ``It would be wise to prefer phase-wise pragmatic steps rather
than closing the tobacco industry at a time to avert any economic
disaster as thousands of people are involved in the industry,'' he
said.
	   The President also called for discouraging tobacco cultivation
by bringing the tobacco fields under cultivation of other cash
crops. He also suggested to discourage manufacturing and marketing
of bidi and cigarettes, and intensify campaign about the adverse
affects of smoking.
	   ``The severity of smoking will be minimised if the anti-smoking
movement can be turned into an active social movement,'' he said
calling on the doctors, teachers, engineers, journalists, writers,
poets, litterateurs and social workers to come up to supplement the
effort.
	   Health and Family Welfare Minister Salahuddin Ahmed sought
cooperation of the people of all strata for a tobacco free society
as it's not possible for the government alone to get the job done.
``Youths should be refrained from tobacco to make a tobacco-free
society.''
	   He assured the anti-smoking organisations of all possible
cooperation of the government.
	   In his welcome address, Prof Nurul Islam said some 10,000 people
in the world are losing their lives everyday due to smoking.
	   Quoting WHO statistics, he said there are 60 per cent male and
7-10 per cent female smokers in Bangladesh.
	   But he assumed that the female smokers in our country is about
30 per cent.
	   Prof Islam said of the smokers 80-90 per cent are from the poor
section of the society while 23.3 per cent are school students.
	   He strongly pleaded for steps to increase tax on tobacco in the
coming national budget. ``The opposition will not protest the
increased tax,'' he hoped stressing the need for discouraging
tobacco ads in the mass media.
	   President Shahabuddin Ahmed also distributed prizes and
certificates among individuals and organisations for their
contributions to anti-smoking movement and the winners of essay
competition.
	   The awardees are: Alhaj M Nurul Amin, Sayeed Salahuddin Zaki, Dr
AKM Kafiluddin and eminent artiste Asaduzzaman Noor. Bhorer Kagoj,
Hamdard Bangladesh and ADHUNIK Chittagong Medical College branch
also received awards.
	   Ayesha Akther, Masuma Ahmed and Taslima Zaman were the winners
of essay competition.
	   
</TEXT>
