<HEADLINE>
Swiss bank's Singapore officials sue The Economist magazine 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Two Singapore branch officials of the Union
Bank of Switzerland said Monday they have filed defamation suits
against The Economist magazine for accusing them of poor risk
management.
	   An article in last week's edition of the London-based magazine
said relaxed controls at the Singapore branch led to massive losses
that threaten to block the bank's merger with Swiss Bank Corp. That
merger is awaiting U.S. regulatory approval.
	   UBS branch chairman Lim Ho Kee and senior vice president James
Loh told Dow Jones Newswires that they filed writs in a local court
Monday. ``We absolutely refute all allegations made in The
Economist article,'' Lim said.
	   Bill Emmott, editor of The Economist, told Dow Jones Newswires
in a telephone interview from London, ``The Economist stands by the
article published in its issue dated May 30. If we receive a writ
for defamation, we will contest it with all due vigor.''
	   In response to the magazine article, the UBS head office in
Zurich had previously issued a statement saying that the Singapore
branch ``is and always has been integrated into the independent
centralized risk management processes for all credit and market
risks. UBS Singapore was continuously respecting these procedures,
especially the clear separation of duties.''
	   The statement said the UBS Singapore branch reported after-tax
profits of 29 million Singapore dollars (dlrs 17.17 million) last
year. 	   
</TEXT>
