<SLUG> CITY-POLICE-LAUNCH sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
City police launch blitz against errant motorists, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws CITY-POLICE-LAUNCH sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sun. - City traffic police conducted their biggest
enforcement operations this year with an eight-hour blitz against
errant motorists.
	   Police issued 1,579 summonses to motorists for various offences
including driving with expired licences. Eighty motorcycles and
five cars were also seized during the operation.
	   The operation, conducted jointly by Selangor traffic police,
City Hall, the Road Transport Department and Welfare Services
Department, was led by Federal traffic chief Datuk Supian Amat.
	   Some 800 officers and men from both the city and Selangor
traffic branch, Criminal Investigation Department, Anti-Narcotics
Department and another 200 from the other government departments
took part in the operation.
	   A total of 22 youths, nine of them below 18, were detained under
section 42 of the Road Transport Act 1987 for reckless driving, 47
motorists were detained under section 45 of the same Act for
driving under the influence of alcohol while six motorists were
detained under section 45(c) of the Act.
	   Speaking to reporters later, Supian said the joint operation was
conducted mainly to curb illegal racing in the city and its
outskirts.
	   Also present was city traffic chief Superintendent Mohd Zain
Ismail.
	   Supian said police were concerned over the increasing number of
motorcyclists detained for involvement in illegal racing.
	   ``This year alone, some 388 have charged for reckless driving
and involvement in illegal racing and the number keeps
increasing,'' he said.
	   Supian said while police would continue with the enforcement,
the whole community must help to stop the menace.
	   
</TEXT>
