r w     TITANIC'-PRODUCER-URGESs     06-01 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> TITANIC'-PRODUCER-URGES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANGLADESH
</HEADLINE>
Titanic' producer urges Bangladesh govt to take action against piracy of films, THE INDEPENDENT  
   xfdws TITANIC'-PRODUCER-URGES sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   A spokesman of the Twentieth Century Fox International, producer
of the world block-buster film 'Titanic' yesterday urged the
Bangladesh government to take action against piracy of films.
	   Michael J Werner, Director, Special Project-Asia of Twentieth
Century Fox International, was speaking at a press conference at
the Jatiya Press Club organised by Modhumita Group which released
the film in the country. Managing Director of Modhumita Group
Ziauddin Aslam and Director Iftekharuddin Naushad also spoke.
	   Michael J. Werner said since Bangladesh was a signatory to the
World Copy Right Convention it should take stern action against
piracy of films.
	   He said Titanic had set a record by doing a world-wide business
of 1.2 billion US dollars so far.
	   Iftekharuddin Naushad said pirated copies of many world famous
films were shown in cinema halls in Dhaka changing the names of the
films.
	   Ziauddin Aslam said they got 15 prints of the film ``Titanic''
and those were being shown in Dhaka and other cities and towns in
the country. He said they received the right to show ``Titanic' in
Bangladesh for US $ 10,000 from its producing firm.
	   Replying to a question why the price of tickets for ``Titanic
has been increased, Ziauddin Aslam said as the film was of more
than 3-hour length they had to cut the number of daily shows. He
said they had also installed modern world-class sound technology in
Modhumita cinema hall and renovated the hall which forced them to
increase the price of the tickets for ``Titanic''.
	   He said ``Titanic'' will be shown for an indefinite period,
perhaps for about 3 months.
	   
</TEXT>
