w2679  wstm-
r w     DP-REFORM-IN-THE-REGIONS     06-01 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> DP-REFORM-IN-THE-REGIONS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG
</HEADLINE>
DP urges reform in the regions, HONGKONG STANDARD  
   xfdws DP-REFORM-IN-THE-REGIONS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   ALL appointed seats in the municipal councils and district
boards should be abolished but the number of elected deputies
sitting on them should stay the same, a Democratic Party leader has
suggested.
	   Party vice-chairman Anthony Cheung Ping-leung put forward the
plan in a regional organisation structure streamlining proposal to
be announced on Monday.
	   Mr Cheung said although the number of directly elected seats in
the legislature had been reduced, they should not be reduced in
regional organisations.
	   He reiterated that his party supported a merger between the two
municipal councils but opposed mergers between the district boards
and the two councils.
	   Ada Wong Ying-kay, Liberal Party Provisional Urban Councillor,
had a different opinion.
	   ``Streamlining the regional organisations to make the district
bodies more efficient and better co-ordinated is more important
than the number of seats,'' she said.
	   Ms Wong suggested that if members of the future regional
organisations could be more powerful, more politicians might be
lured into joining the new organisations.
	   She urged the public and the government to not only focus on the
merger proposal, but to pay attention to the functions and
responsibilities of the regional organisations.
	   Improving co-ordination within the organisations, as well as
that with the government departments, was more important.
	   She criticised the existing system, saying it only allowed the
regional organisations to tackle some trivial matters, and members
of the district boards were toothless, that the government did not
consider them as important.
	   The municipal councils' responsibilities should not be
restricted to culture, recreation and health matters, Ms Wong said.
City councils in some foreign countries handled education and
transport issues, she said.
	   Professor Lau Siu-kai, of the Chinese University's Hong Kong
Institute of Asia-Pacific Studies, believed the government had the
determination to reform the existing regional organisations, but
there would be pressure from the political parties on the issue.
	   He said under the current arrangement, the district boards had
no significant duties and the morale of their members was failing,
while the many duties of the municipal councils were overlapping
with that of government departments.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
