<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 09:35:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2684  wstm-
r w     ONLY-NPC-CAN-CHANGEsked     06-01 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> ONLY-NPC-CAN-CHANGE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG
</HEADLINE>
Only NPC can change vote system says law chief, HONGKONG STANDARD  
   xfdws ONLY-NPC-CAN-CHANGE sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   ANY amendment to the Basic Law to achieve a ``one man, one
vote'' electoral system must be done by the National People's
Congress, according to Solicitor General Daniel Fung Wah-kin.
	   While last week's election result proved Hong Kong people wanted
to exercise their right to vote, Mr Fung said a more democratic
election must be achieved through the Basic Law.
	   He made the remarks while completing a seven-day visit to the
United States where he spoke to senior government officials,
business leaders, politicians, scholars, think-tanks and
commentators in four cities on the east and west coasts.
	   Mr Fung said the 53.5 per cent voter turnout in geographical
constituencies and 63.5 per cent in the functional constituencies
were higher than the United States presidential election turnout
rate of 30 per cent.
	   ``This means Hong Kong people want to participate in a
democratic election system,'' Mr Fung said.
	   But he said the speeding up of democracy must be carried out
according to the Basic Law.
	   ``Basic Law is the foundation of our mini-constitution,'' he
said. ``It has a timetable. And there is no restriction on how to
handle the question (of improving democracy) after 2007.'' Hong
Kong people have the right to push for a ``one person, one vote''
system after 2007, Mr Fung said.
	   ``Before any amendment to the Basic Law, that is before 2007, we
must abide by the Basic Law,'' he said.
	   Moreover, it would be the job of a sovereign power's body to
decide whether a change were appropriate.
	   ``Amendment to the Basic Law must, of course, be carried out by
the National People's Congress,'' Mr Fung said.
	   His hosts agreed that the transition of Hong Kong's sovereignty
had been a smooth one.
	   Such issues as human rights and right of abode had been dealt
with by the courts, he said, noting that the judiciary had remained
independent without any government influence.
	   Mr Fung said US officials praised Hong Kong for its ability to
maintain a common law jurisdiction ``according to international
standards''.
	   He said the SAR also demonstrated to the world its stability
with the lowest crime rate _ 3.5 per cent _ in the region.
	   According to Mr Fung, Hong Kong's freedom of assembly and
freedom of speech is exemplified by the approval of 1,260
demonstrations and protests since the handover.
	   ``None of these was rejected,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
