<TEXT>
	   NEITHER former Legislative Council president Andrew Wong
Wang-fat nor his successor Rita Fan Hsu Lai-tai will be backed by
Frontier in their bid for the presidency of the Legislative
Council.
	   Mr Wong, a lecturer from the Chinese University who won by
direct election as an independent, and Mrs Fan, an independent who
won through the Election Committee, are the front-runners in the
race for the top Legco post.
	   Emily Lau Wai-hing, convenor of the political group, said she
was displeased with Mr Wong's decision before the handover to join
the Provisional Legislative Council, which her group had considered
illegitimate. As for Mrs Fan, the Frontier leader said her switch
of position during the run-up to the handover was ``disgusting''.
	   But Ms Lau stressed Frontier legislators were not interested in
the Legco presidency, and their votes would depend on the options
available.
	   The Frontier fielded three candidates and all won seats by
direct election.
	   They are Ms Lau, social activist Cyd Ho Sau-lan and unionist Lee
Cheuk-yan.
	   Mr Wong wouldn't be drawn into an argument over Ms Lau's
comments.
	   ``I have already explained my entry to the interim legislature
at those election forums, I don't want to argue with her any
more,'' he said.
	   He said he was willing to serve as president if his fellow
legislators supported him.
	   Mrs Fan, president of the interim legislature, also said if
elected, she would be willing to serve the legislature.
	   But she was not available to comment on Ms Lau's comments last
night.
	   
</TEXT>
