<TEXT>
	   PETALING JAYA, Sun. - Golf, considered a game for the rich and
famous, has now been transformed to one where even the
middle-income group can enjoy, Selangor Menteri Datuk Abu Hassan
Omar said today.
	   ``This is made possible with the opening of the Seri Selangor
Golf Club at Damansara Indah, considered to be the first of its
kind in the Klang Valley and in the country,'' he said when
officiating the soft-launch of the club.
	   Abu Hassan, a golf enthusiast himself, added that since the
``golf boom''
	   in the early 90s, an increasing number of people had picked up
the game.
	   ``Golf clubs have mushroomed but many people cannot afford the
high membership fees imposed. It is as if one has to be `licensed'
to play in these expensive golf clubs,'' he said.
	   On the new 18-hole golf course, run by ASK Golf Management for
Persatuan Golf Melayu Selangor, which was given the land lease by
the Selangor State Development Corporation, he said: ``This is the
first golf club in the Klang Valley open to everybody.'' He added
that the club offered ``homeless golfers'' a place to call their
base.
	   It does not require membership fee.
	   
</TEXT>
