<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo,0526 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
More deaths reported in Kosovo; hundreds flee 
</HEADLINE>
By ISMET HAJDARI
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Heavy fighting in Serbia's explosive
Kosovo province prompted reports Monday of more than a dozen new
deaths and sent hundreds of people fleeing into Albania.
	   Conflicting accounts of casualties in the blocked-off areas
could not immediately be sorted out. But the bloodshed appears to
be the worst since early March when Serbian police killed more than
80 people in a crackdown on militants and their families.
	   A day after Serb authorities claimed to have killed several
dozen militants in four villages in the Decani region of western
Kosovo, ethnic Albanian officials said 37 Albanians had been killed
over the weekend.
	   Twenty-seven died in clashes in Decani, while 10 were killed
when Serb police stormed a village elsewhere, they said.
	   Two Serb policemen also died in the fighting around Decani, 75
kilometers (45 miles) west of the regional capital Pristina, Serb
sources said.
	   The latest fierce fighting prompted about 1,000 Kosovo
Albanians, mostly women, children and elderly, to leave the
troubled region and cross over into Albania's Troboja region Sunday
and Monday, Albanian authorities said.
	   Interior Ministry spokesman Artan Bizhga said in the Albanian
capital, Tirana, that the refugees, many of whom walked for as many
as 10 hours, were being accommodated in local homes and a school.
Local authorities were providing free food and clothes.
	   Authorities in Serbia, which with Montenegro comprises all that
remains of the Yugoslav federation, claim that thousands of Kosovo
Albanians are staying in the province illegally.
	   They are trying to block Kosovo's independence bid and are using
the police and army to try to crush militants and maintain control
over the province, where 90 percent of the population of 2.2
million is ethnic Albanian.
	   More than 200 people have died in Kosovo clashes since the
beginning of March. An estimated 50 percent of the Serbian province
is controlled by militant Albanians and many regions are blocked
off, either by Serbs or Albanians.
	   The Kosovo Information Center, close to the ethnic Albanian
leadership, released the names of the 10 people it said were killed
Sunday when Serb police stormed the village of Poklek, 25
kilometers (15 miles) west of Pristina. It said one had had his
throat slit.
	   According to the Albanians' account, Serb police burst into
Poklek houses, pulled out villagers and told them to ``go to
Albania and never return.''
	   Afterward, Serb police allegedly set 26 homes ablaze.
	   All phone lines remained disconnected Monday between Pristina
and the hot-spots of Decani, Klina and Djakovica, where fierce
battles were reported Sunday.
	   Yugoslavia's state-run daily Politika on Monday blamed ethnic
Albanian ``terrorist groups'' for numerous deaths. It said that in
their efforts to cross into Albania, they shelled several villages
near Junik, ``a border town known for resisting militant
enlistings, killing several of their countrymen, including
children.'' 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo; CT:i; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:ASIA;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
