<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Ministry plans to set up Mara education fund, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws MINISTRY-PLANS-TO-SET-UP sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   MALACCA, Sun. - The Entrepreneur Development Ministry plans to
set up a Mara education fund to help the agency disburse loans to
poor Bumiputera students who intend to pursue tertiary education.
	   Its Minister, Datuk Mustapa Mohamed, said the proposal had
already been approved by the Mara Board of Governors and the
ministry. It is awaiting approval from the Finance Ministry.
	   ``The ministry is submitting the proposal for the formation of
this fund to the Finance Ministry. Upon gaining approval the fund
will be set up next year,'' he said.
	   He was launching the MRSM Graduates Association's Education
Programme and Fund at MRSM Terendak.
	   Mustapa expressed hope Mara could raise enough funds to help
students.
	   Also present were MRSM Graduates Association president Mirzan
Mahathir, Mara deputy director-general Mydin Shariff, Third Army
Division commandant Major General Datuk Mohd Zaini Mohd Said and
Alor Gajah MP Datuk Abu Seman Mohd Yusoff.
	   Mustapa added that the ministry also hoped that contributions to
the fund could be raised from former Mara students who had either
received loans or scholarships in the past.
	   ``I think it is timely that these recipients be among the first
contributors to the fund,'' he said.
	   He added that the ministry hoped to raise between RM3 and RM4
million initially.
	   Mara had already sponsored 118,000 students to pursue higher
education either through full or partial scholarships and loans.
	   He said the additional RM101 million allocated by the Government
to Mara would enable Mara to sponsor at least 25,000 students in
local higher institutions.
	   Previously, he said the agency could only sponsor slightly more
than 11,000 students to pursue tertiary education with an initial
allocation of RM63 million.
	   Meanwhile, Mirzan said he hoped to collect as much money as
possible from the MRSM Graduates Association's Education Fund to
finance its activities.
	   
</TEXT>
