<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
`UM's explanations causing more confusion', NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws UM'S-EXPLANATIONS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sun. - Universiti Malaya's Academic Staff
Association said UM's response to its allegations that it had
deceived students and by-passed procedures in its science
matriculation programme was ``superficial''and did not address key
issues.
	   It described university's public relations officer V.T. Ratnam's
explanation to issues raised by the association as creating more
confusion instead of resolving problems.
	   The association reiterated that it was against the franchising
concept which neglected a big group of science matriculation
students, saying that it wanted all students be brought back to the
main campus.
	   The association had recently alleged that the university's
franchise programme for matriculation of science students lacked
transparency.
	   Association president Associate Professor Datuk Mahadzir Mohd
Khir had said the programme was causing confusion on two matters.
	   Firstly, neither the university's prospectus nor its
advertisements advised students of the possibility that they might
be placed in private institutions instead of the university.
	   Secondly, it was understood that the franchise scheme was to
accommodate the overspill from the university.
	   Mahadzir said only 300 places of the 2,000 places in the
university's science faculty had been filled.
	   The association, in a faxed statement, also questioned the
university's decision to choose certain private colleges, many of
which were located in shophouses and lacked sufficient science
laboratories, libraries, accommodation facilities and trained
teachers.
	   It said the association was against the university's decision to
place science matriculation students in private institutions of
higher learning under the franchise programme.
	   It further added the unversity could accommodate 2,000 science
matriculation students in its main campus.
	   Education Minister Datuk Seri Najib Tun Razak had said on
Saturday that the local public universities franchise programme
with private institutions of higher learning was to provide more
places for students locally.
	   He said the private institutions selected for the franchise
programme were carefully scrutinised.
	   Najib said places for students to do their matriculation had to
be increased as many students had obtained good Sijil Pelajaran
Malaysia results as well as to help those who were unable to study
abroad.
	   He was speaking to reporters after launching a collection of
novels titled Koleksi Novel Lambaian Hijrah by four blind authors
at the National Library.
	   
</TEXT>
