<HEADER>
w2720  wstm-
r w     JAMUNA-BRIDGE-WORKsked     06-01 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> JAMUNA-BRIDGE-WORK sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANGLADESH
</HEADLINE>
Jamuna bridge work ends June 20, THE INDEPENDENT  
   xfdws JAMUNA-BRIDGE-WORK sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   The multi-million dollar Jamuna Multipurpose Bridge, renamed as
the Bangabandhu Bridge, conceived in the late sixties will be
opened for traffic from June 23 after a gala inaugural function.
	   Work on the bridge, now going on in full swing, will come to an
end by June 20, Deputy Project Manager Brig AHM Abdullah told The
Independent yesterday at the project site.
	   The bridge, which has been named after Bangabandhu Sheikh
Mujibur Rahman, is a prestigious project of the country, for which
all the successive governments after the independence of Bangladesh
contributed a lot.
	   The bridge could have been completed by December last if the
bridge authority had not taken up the construction of the dual
gauge railway system at the northern side of the bridge along with
the construction of the main bridge, a source said.
	   The 12 metre radius curved bridge which looks like a crescent
from its southern side, connects Kalihati of Bhuapur with Saydabad
of Sirajganj linking the eastern part of the country with the west.
The curve shape of the bridge, which was designed to protect
drivers of vehicles from reflection of light, increased the length
of the bridge by 31 metres.
	   The multipurpose bridge, which is unique in the world by for its
multipurpose use, including rail movement, gas and electricity
transmission, and four-lane road, is learnt to be the 11th longest
bridge in the world with its 4.8 kilometre long pathway and 18.5
metre deck width and 1200 metre radius of carvature of bridge. The
life span of the bridge is estimated at 100 years, but engineers
said that it may be much higher if it is maintained properly.
	   Almost all the works has been completed except the setting up of
the expansion joint (the joint needed to cope with the expansion of
the bridge due to humid weather), parapet wall and barrier and
construction of some structures for laying the railway track.
	   The total estimated cost, including the escalated cost due to
delay and price hike of materials used in the bridge, is Tk 3,742
crore including Tk 163 crore for the rehabilitation of the
displaced people of the area. Of the total cost, the World Bank,
the Asian Development Bank and the OECF, Japan, provided $200
million each the total amount of which in taka terms stood at 2400
crore. The rest of the amount was provided by the Bangladesh
government. The other integrated constructions like rail, gas, 232
k.v electricity lines and telelinks required additional resources
which would be provided by the respective departments, a bridge
authority source said. The dual gauge railway system - broad gauge
and metre gauge - will require more than Tk 100 crore.
	   The eight components of the bridge such as the main bridge
(contract-1) ,river training (contract-2), East and West approach
roads (contract 3 and 4), rail approach for east and west (contract
5 and 6), the flood control embankment on east side (contract no 7)
and flood control embankment on the western side (contract no 8)
have been completed barring some finishing work. Apart from all
these major works, the government has also carried out some small
constructions for the protection of the bridge.
	   Of the total cost for the bridge, about $300 million was used
for river training to stop the shifting tendency of the river.
	   A total of 2552 local workers and about 300 expatriates were
employed during the peak period of the construction of the bridge,
i.e from October 1995 to July 1996, according to the project
authority source.
	   A five kilometre cross dam on the west side has reduced the
width of the river to almost half at 4.8 km, i.e the actual length
of the bridge. The engineers said that the 4.8 km width of the
river was sufficient to facilitate the flow of the total amount of
water through the river.
	   The first work of the bridge began in October, 1994. To begin
the work the government had to spend an amount of Tk 400 crore
which was obtained through the imposition of a surcharge on
different services. The source said the total collection of
surcharge was about Tk 560 crore. The surcharge was imposed during
the Ershad regime.
	   The bridge was conceived in 1966 and later Bangabandhu Sheikh
Mujibur Rahman first initiated a dialogue with Japan for the
construction of the bridge after independence. The donors agreed to
provide resources during the BNP regime led by Begum Zia. The
bridge was completed during the period of the present government.
	   Three international contractors, Hyundai Construction and Samwan
Corporation of South Korea and Hamban Ward Zevi of Netherlands
executed the project. The design of the bridge was done by T.Y Lin
of USA on behalf of Rendel Palmer  Tritton and NEDECO and
Bangladesh Consultant Ltd. The RPT also did consultancy work for
Hardinge Bridge in 1912, which is still in operation. Sir Willium
Hallcrow, Prize Water House, EPC and Rahman Rahman Haque have
worked as managerial advisers to the government for the
construction of the bridge. A panel of experts led by Professor of
BUET Jamilur Reza Chowdhury also advised the government and donors.
	   There was no major problems during the construction of the
bridge. The only problems the contractors said they faced was that
they had to be very tough to maintain the work schedule. The other
problem was the numerous cracks that had developed in the hinges of
the bridge, which were mended by injecting Epoxy Resin into the
cracks so that water did not harm the iron rod of the bridge. The
other problem was the presence of solid rock at the bottom of the
river which gave the contractors a lot of trouble during the piling
work.
	   Project source said that all the work would be completed by June
20 and the bridge will be opened for a marathon race by freedom
fighters prior to its formal opening.
	   Meanwhile, a 20-member national committee headed by the
Secretary of the Jamuna Bridge Authority, Abdul Muyeed Chowdhury
has been formed to supervise the gala opening ceremony. Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina will inaugurate the bridge. It is learnt the
opposition leader General Ershad, will also be present at the
function. There will be two meeting places during the inaugural
ceremony at the two ends of the bridge. Sheikh Hasina will travel
through the bridge by road from the Kalihati side and return from
Sayedabad by train. The train service may not be commissioned
before the construction of railway line upto Joydevpur. However the
construction of railway line upto Joydevpur has been taken up.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
