<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Africa-Briefs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tanzania, Mozambique 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: Contains items on Congo, South Africa, Kenya, Lesotho,
By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
	   ------
	   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) _ Congo's President Laurent Kabila accused
unnamed military officers of illegally smuggling gold, diamonds and
rare wood from Congo's northeastern forests.
	   Speaking to journalists on Sunday, Kabila promised that anyone
caught unlawfully buying or selling the country's resources will be
severely punished.
	   ``Nobody is above the law,'' the president said. ``The era of
institutionalized theft is over.''
	   Kabila made the statement several weeks after his minister of
economy and
	   petrol, Victor Mpoy, accused Ugandan government officials of
illegally trafficking in Congo's natural resources.
	   The accusations prompted cooler relations between Congo and
Uganda, which
	   strongly backed Kabila in his rebellion to oust the late
dictator Mobutu Sese Seko.
	   More than three decades of corrupt rule by Mobutu has left the
economy in
	   this central African country in a state of decay.
	   ------
	   PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) _ Former Civil Co-Operation Bureau
agent Ferdi Barnard was on Monday convicted of murdering
anti-apartheid activist David Webster and attempting to murder
Justice Minister Dullah Omar.
	   Barnard worked for the now-defunct Civil Cooperation Bureau, an
apartheid-era government unit that attacked anti-apartheid groups.
	   Barnard was convicted in Pretoria High Court on 25 charges,
including two murder charges, two of attempted murder and illegal
possession of weapons and ammunition.
	   He was acquitted on a further nine charges, including two
attempted murder charges, because of a lack of evidence.
	   Barnard would be returning to Pretoria maximum prison, where he
was already serving a 10-year sentence.
	   In court, Barnard for the first time admitted that he knew all
along that
	   the purpose for his monitoring Omar was to have him killed.
	   College professor Webster was shot to death outside his
Johannesburg house in 1989.
	   In February, Barnard was sentenced to 10 years for the armed
robbery of diamonds worth 10 million rand (dlrs 2 million).
	   -----
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ Three police officers were fired for
fleeing when raiders broke into the jail they were guarding and
freed 42 prisoners, a newspaper reported Monday.
	   They were fired for cowardice, negligence and abandoning
firearms while on duty, the Daily Nation reported, quoting unnamed
sources.
	   At least 30 armed men, some of them in camouflage uniforms,
attacked Changamwe police station, near the Indian Ocean port of
Mombasa, at dawn May 25. They stole three guns and killed a
watchman at a shop next door.
	   One of the stolen guns was recovered at Kaya Tsoba forest along
with 22 rounds of ammunition during an ambush on Saturday evening,
police said. No arrests were made.
	   Last August, raiders struck Likoni police station just south of
Mombasa, killing six policemen and making off with dozens of guns
and thousands of rounds of ammunition at the beginning of a wave of
attacks that claimed at least 88 lives and displaced 200,000
people.
	   Opposition, human rights and religious leaders said the attacks
were instigated by people close to President Daniel Arap Moi and
targeted people on the Indian Ocean coast who came from other parts
of the country known to support opponents of Moi.
	   The attacks ended before the general election in December, but
tension has remained high in areas where the raiders took cover,
especially in caves in the forests around Mombasa.
	   ------
	   ZANZIBAR, Tanzania (AP) _ Zanzibar's first international film
festival will take place July 11-18 and will feature films made in
Africa, Iran, India, Pakistan, the Gulf States and the island
communities of the Indian Ocean.
	   Yusouf Mohammed, a British volunteer working on the festival,
says films will be shown in Zanzibar's famous Stone Town in the
refurbished Old Fort, the House of Wonders, the Palace Museum and
Victoria Garden.
	   Organizers are also planning to set up a mobile screening unit
to take the films to 26 villages on the islands of Zanzibar and
Pemba so the estimated 300,000 Zanzibaris can also see the films.
	   The embassies of France, Switzerland, Poland, Oman, India,
Spain, Egypt and South Africa have volunteered financial support
for the festival, whose cost organizers estimate at dlrs 200,000.
	   ------
	   MASERU, Lesotho (AP) _ Seven workers of the Lesotho National
Development Corporation died in a crash in the northern Leribe
district when they were returning from a funeral, officials said
Monday.
	   A spokesman for the LNDC on Monday said six of the victims died
instantly in the weekend crash and the seventh perished in a
hospital. Two of six survivors are reported to be in critical
condition.
	   The accident happened in the Relebe district when the minibus in
which they were travelling overturned and collided with another
vehicle after a tire burst.
	   ------
	   PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) _ South Africa on Monday announced a
travel ban on members of the former Angolan rebel movement UNITA.
	   Senior UNITA officials and their adult family members would be
refused admission of transit through the country, Home Affairs
Minister Mangosuthu Buthelezi said in a statement. The sanctions
were imposed in a United Nations resolution against UNITA for
failing to finish complying with a 1994 peace accord.
	   In compliance with the U.N. sanctions, South Africa would also
refuse all
	   applications by UNITA members or their families for visas,
immigration permits or the extension of temporary residence
permits.
	   ------
	   MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) _ The government says the country's
inflation rate is dropping.
	   The deputy minister of planning and finance, Luisa Diogo, put
the inflation rate from January to April at 1.4 per cent, compared
to 5.7 per cent in the same period of 1997.
	   In 1997, Mozambique achieved a one-digit inflation for the first
time since the introduction of a World Bank - International
Monetary Fund-supervized adjustment program more than 10 years ago.
	   Inflation was 54 percent in 1995, 16.3 percent in 1996 and 5.8
per cent in 1997.
	   (aos)
</TEXT>
