Najib: Islamic teaching in schools ineffective, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws ISLAMIC-TEACHING sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   PENANG, Sun. - Ineffective methods of imparting Islamic values
in schools have been identified as one reason why pupils are easily
influenced by negative elements.
	   Education Minister Datuk Seri Najib Tun Abdul Razak said one way
to rectify the situation was by reviewing Islamic education
curriculum in schools.
	   ``We can also combat negative elements by increasing Islamic
religious teachers who are able to impart knowledge of Islam in an
interesting manner to pupils,'' he said last night at Universiti
Sains Malaysia.
	   Najib was speaking after presenting prizes to winners of the
Education Ministry's Tilawah Al-Quran at the university's main
campus at Minden.
	   ``The Ministry's Islamic and Moral Education Department has been
directed to identify and formulate effective programmes,'' he said.
	   The event was also attended by USM vice-chancellor Datuk
Professor Ishak Tambi Kechik and State deputy education director
Ahmad Farouk Abdul Majid.
	   Earlier, Najib presented prizes to Mohd Salleh Saidi from Johor
and Abdul Ghani Hashim from Perak.
	   In the Qariah section (women's category), Sabariah Abdul Hamid
emerged winner with Sharifah Ainun Syed Idrus (Perlis) as runner-up
and Che Eshah Che Omar from Sabah in third place.
	   
