<SLUG> BC-Finland-Russia-Latvia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia, Finland urge Latvia to respect minority rights 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photo HEL101
<TEXT>
	   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) _ Russian-Latvian relations can be
restored to normal if the Baltic state adopts measures to improve
the status of minorities, Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov
said Monday.
	   ``Our aim is not to break the camel's back and especially not
the back of a state,'' Primakov told reporters. ``But the ball is
in Latvia's court.''
	   Angered by alleged discriminations against Latvia's 700,000
Russian speakers, Moscow in April threatened sanctions against the
Baltic state of 2.6 million.
	   Finnish Foreign Minister Tarja Halonen urged Latvia to adopt
measures proposed by the Organization for Security and Cooperation
in Europe for the treatment of minorities.
	   ``Finland hopes Latvia, with the help of an efficient program,
will further the integration of her Russian speaking population,''
she said.
	   Halonen said that Latvia's possible future membership in the
European Union would ``constitute the best and strongest guarantee
for the future and position of the Russian speaking population.''
	   But, she added, that Finland ``as a member of a small language
area, supports the strengthening of the position of the Latvian
language.''
	   At the end of his three-day visit to Helsinki on Monday,
Primakov flew to Switzerland. Earlier, he met with President Martti
Ahtisaari and Prime Minister Paavo Lipponen.
	   (mhh/ls)
</TEXT>
