<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Conglomerates Merger </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two Singapore conglomerates plan merger 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Hoping to capitalize on the bigger-is-better
approach, government-linked conglomerates Singapore Technologies
Industrial Corp. and Sembawang Corp. said Monday they would merge
in order to compete more profitably in Asia.
	   The new group, which will be named SembCorp Industries, will
focus on infrastructure projects, marine engineering, information
technology ventures and the leisure industry.
	   The two conglomerates said the merger will create a company with
the resources and financial strength to compete for larger projects
in the increasingly competitive markets in Asia.
	   It will have a market capitalization of 2.01 billion Singapore
dollars (dlrs 1.19 billion), making it the 22nd largest company on
the Stock Exchange of Singapore.
	   The move must get shareholder, government and stock exchange
approval before it can proceed.
	   ``Individually, while both companies are profitable, there is a
limit to their growth potential given their current size,'' said
Wong Kok Siew, chairman of STIC and deputy chairman of Sembawang.
``In deciding to merge, both companies have significantly increased
their chances of becoming a leading Asian corporate sooner rather
than later.''
	   While the move was generally seen as positive, analysts said
investors will withhold their support until they see what concrete
steps the new group will take.
	   ``If the management delivers what they say they will deliver, it
will be good for the new company on a longer-term basis,'' said Ang
Lay Pheng, head of research at Goldman Sachs Securities. ``The
proof is in the pudding.''
	   Trading in shares in Singapore Technologies Industrial Corp. and
Sembawang Corp. was suspended on the Stock Exchange of Singapore
Monday pending the announcement.
	   STIC closed Friday at 1.66 Singapore dollars (98 cents) a share,
and Sembawang at 3.08 Singapore dollars (dlrs 1.82).
	   Under the merger plan, 1,000 shares of STIC would be exchanged
for 1,475.6 shares in the new group, and 1,000 Sembawang shares
would be exchanged for 2,543.1 SembCorp Industries shares. 	   
</TEXT>
