<SLUG> DROP-JUVENILE-CRIME-RATE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG
</HEADLINE>
Drop in juvenile crime rate, but police will stay alert, HONGKONG STANDARD  
   xfdws DROP-JUVENILE-CRIME-RATE sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   TSEUNG Kwan O police will continue their close watch on the new
town's neighbourhoods despite a decline in the juvenile crime rate,
a senior officer said on Sunday.
	   Chief Superintendent Tam Kwok-wing revealed that the number of
youths under 21 arrested last year had declined 13.7 per cent from
278 in 1996 to 240.
	   ``However, police are concerned about the fast-growing youth
population in the district, which may lead to a rise in youth
problems,'' Chief Supt Tam said at a Fight Crime Publicity Day
speech in Tseung Kwan O.
	   He attributed the downward trend in youth crimes to two videos
outlining the serious consequences of shop-lifting and other
offences involving youngsters.
	   The videos were produced by the Sai Kung Provisional District
Boards and the Sai Kung District Fight Crime Committee (DFCC).
	   ``The anti-shop theft video was shown at schools and shopping
centres in the district early this year,'' Mr Tam added.
	   But there should be no room for complacency even though the
situation was under control, he stressed.
	   ``Looking ahead, police officers from the Kwun Tong District
will step up patrols at juvenile crime blackspots.
	   ``We aim to strengthen co-operation with the Social Welfare
Department, the Education Department, social workers and schools,
organise anti-crime seminars and video shows for parents and
teachers, and set up police outreach teams to prevent juvenile
involvement in crime.'' More Junior Police Call (JPC) members were
recruited at Sunday's Fight Crime Publicity Day, held at the East
Point City residential complex in Tseung Kwan O.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
