<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Rubber </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Natural rubber is in deficit 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Despite record output in Thailand, Indonesia,
India and China, demand for natural rubber outstripped production,
the International Rubber Study Group said Monday.
	   The deficit was made up by drawing on world stocks for the first
time since 1993.
	   The synthetic rubber market was also in deficit in 1997, the
London-based intergovernmental agency said. Its latest estimates
put global natural rubber output last year at a record 6.370
million metric tons _ 40,000 higher than the previous peak in 1996.
	   Consumption _ 70 per cent of which is for tires _ rose from
6.130 million tons in 1996 to a record 6.580 million tons last
year.
	   The group's new estimates showed 1997 global synthetic rubber
production at 10.110 million tons (9.780 million tons in 1996) and
consumption at 10.150 million tons (9.590 million tons).
	   (rs-mj)
</TEXT>
