r w     DIGITAL-SIGNATURE-ACTske     06-01 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> DIGITAL-SIGNATURE-ACT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Digital Signature Act taking shape, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws DIGITAL-SIGNATURE-ACT sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE Digital Signature Act 1997 will come into immediate effect
once the Government establishes the framework in two months' time.
	   The Act, which is one of the six cyberlaws designed to
facilitate electronic commerce (e-commerce), will enable businesses
and the community to use electronic signatures instead of their
handwritten counterparts in legal and business transactions.
	   According to Energy, Telecommunications and Posts Minister Datuk
Leo Moggie, the framework will define the various details to
regulate the digital signature certification authorities (CAs).
	   ``These include items like the level of expertise an
organisation needs to have in the field of digital signatures
before being registered as a licensed CA,'' he said.
	   Moggie said towards that end, the Government has identified a
transitional controller of digital signatures who will primarily
license the CAs and monitor the activities of these authorities.
	   ``There are things that need to be clearly spelt out so that
people who think they have the expertise to be registered as CAs
have to satisfy all the requirements. As it is a new thing, we need
to be cautious. We will look at examples of how digital signatures
function, especially in the United States and Europe, when drawing
up the regulations,'' the Minister added.
	   On when the transitional controller will be replaced by a
permanent body, Moggie said it will depend on how the movement of
the Multimedia Convergence issue materialises.
	   ``This will be guided by the proposed Multimedia Convergence
Act. It will be part and parcel of the function of the commission
we are planning to have. Pending that, we need to have something
else in place,'' he said.
	   The Digital Signature Act defines digital signature as a
transformation of a message using an asymmetric crypto system.
	   Under such a system, only the combination between a person's
initial message and the public key belonging to the person who
signs can accurately decrypt the system.
	   The CAs appointed to monitor and supervise the use of digital
signatures must be licensed under the law. Those convicted of
operating or submitting a certification authority without valid
licences are liable to a fine of up to RM500,000 or 10 years jail,
or both.
	   In the case of a continuing offence, offenders are liable to a
daily fine not exceeding RM5,000 for each day the offence
continues.
	   Moggie also mentioned that the Government is also in the process
of drafting the Data Protection Bill which is targeted to be tabled
in Parliament by the end of this year.
	   The Act, when introduced later, is expected to give a boost to
electronic transactions as it will ensure that all data including
those of a personal nature are fully protected.
	   Moggie said the right to privacy must be protected and the
appropriate legal protection must be accorded to individuals.
``Legal provision will make it very difficult for other people to
attempt to have access to personal data on the network knowing that
there are penalties for the offence,'' he said.
	   ``However, we're still not yet ready with what would need to be
fully covered by the Act and also the deterrent level that needs to
be imposed.
	   We are still trying to draft and think through this and have it
finalised by year-end in time for the Parliament session,'' he
added.
	   Moggie had earlier witnessed the signing of an agreement between
Silicon Navigator Sdn Bhd and Internet Security Systems Inc (ISS)
for the master distributorship and sequentially launched the
latter's Internet security products and solutions locally.
	   Under the agreement, Silicon Navigator will distribute ISS
products and provide security consultancy services for Malaysia,
Indonesia and Brunei.
	   Silicon Navigator will tackle the local market through its
value-added resellers, Extol Corp Sdn Bhd and Comwise Internetwork
Sdn Bhd.
	   ISS Southeast Asia's channel manager of the company's Asia
Pacific division Raymond Cushman expressed interest in the
Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC) project.
	   ``We will investigate in the area of gaining MSC status,'' he
said, after representing ISS at the signing ceremony. Silicon
Navigator meanwhile was represented by its chief executive officer
Kho Han Mien.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
