<BODY>
<SLUG> KMB-TUEN-MUN-RIDERS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG
</HEADLINE>
Too few KMB buses for Tuen Mun riders, HONGKONG STANDARD  
   xfdws KMB-TUEN-MUN-RIDERS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   DEMOCRATIC Party members handed a petition to Kowloon Motor Bus
(KMB) on Sunday demanding more buses for Tuen Mun passengers
missing out through diversions to the newly opened Route 3.
	   The demands included new bus routes to serve passengers
travelling from Piung Shan to Tuen Mun.
	   It was the party's first demonstration since last week's
Legislative Council elections.
	   The Democratic Party will meet KMB and Transport Department
officials on Tuesday to discuss the routing problem.
	   And Democrat legislator-elect Albert Ho Chun-yan will put the
question to Legco when the new term starts next month.
	   After the opening of Route 3 last week some commuters had to
wait up to 40 minutes for buses 68M and 68X.
	   KMB re-directed nine bus routes to the new Tai Lam Tunnel,
avoiding the congested Tuen Mun Highway.
	   The new route cuts down travel time by up to 30 minutes.
	   But passengers last week complained of long waits due to all
buses being full.
	   Following complaints, KMB promised to put more buses on the new
routes.
	   The Democratic Party claims 102 buses have been cut, including
those on the cancelled 68 and 68A routes.
	   Routes 64M, 68M, 69M, 68X and 69X have been re-routed through
the tunnel.
	   The party also says that with the loss of the 69X, residents in
the Castle Peak Road-Lingnan College area will no longer have a
direct link to Tsim Sha Tsui.
	   And residents along Tuen Mun Road are losing four routes, they
claim.
	   
</TEXT>
