w2743  wstm-
r i     BC-Portugal-EastTimor     06-01 0285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Portugal-East Timor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nobel laureate foresees protests if no progress on E. Timor issue 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ A Nobel peace laureate said Monday the
resignation of Indonesian dictator President Suharto had brought
little change for East Timor and he predicted street protests soon
unless steps were taken to resolve the dispute over the troubled
territory.
	   ``There's been no let-up in the intimidation or repression of
the East Timorese'' said Jose Ramos-Horta, an East Timorese exile
and a leading spokesman for pro-independence forces in the
half-island territory.
	   He said government troops continued their repressive tactics
despite the fact that separatist guerillas operating out of the
territory's highlands had halted attacks. He said the guerillas
number ``a few hundred'' against more than 20,000 Indonesian
troops.
	   In a telephone interview in Portugal, Ramos-Horta said that for
the moment the East Timorese were waiting patiently for political
developments in Jakarta but added that ``if there is no substantial
improvement (in East Timor), people could soon take to the
streets.''
	   Nonetheless, he said he was hopeful of ``significant progress''
within two or three months.
	   Ramos-Horta is co-winner of the 1996 Nobel peace prize and has
close contacts with the underground resistance movement in East
Timor which Indonesia invaded in 1975, shortly after the departure
of Portugal's colonial administration. Indonesia annexed East Timor
a year later.
	   The United Nations still recognizes Portugal as the legitimate
administrative authority in East Timor and has been brokering talks
between Lisbon and Jakarta over the territory's future.
	   (bh/cg)	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Portugal-East Timor; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
