<SLUG> BC-Japan-Politics, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan's governing coalition breaks up after four year alliance 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with quote from Hashimoto in 5th graf; EDITS to trim
AP Photo TOK101
By CHESTER DAWSON
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's governing coalition officially broke up
Monday ahead of parliamentary elections this summer, bringing an
end to a four-year alliance between formerly bitter rivals.
	   In a widely expected move, Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto
accepted the decision of the Social Democratic Party and New Party
Sakigake to withdraw from the government.
	   Hashimoto's Liberal Democratic Party has already assumed all
Cabinet posts and enjoys a majority in the more powerful of Japan's
two legislative chambers, so the coalition's demise was seen as
unlikely to have much impact on the government.
	   It ended an oddball marriage between the conservative Liberal
Democratic Party and left-leaning Social Democrats, formerly
Japan's socialist party. Previous to linking up in 1996, the two
parties had been political enemies for most of the post-World War
II era.
	   ``I value our shared history of having been able to work
together,'' Hashimoto told reporters after meeting with heads of
the two former partner parties.
	   Social Democrat head Takako Doi said her party decided to end
its alliance with the LDP over disagreements with Hashimoto's party
on key issues such as proposals for more stringent legislation on
political ethics and the strengthening of U.S.-Japan defense ties.
	   Masayoshi Takemura, chairman of New Party Sakigake, said ``Over
the past year, the coalition was mainly driven at the LDP's pace
and that left it in bad shape.''
	   The withdrawal was viewed by many as a tactical move before
elections slated for sometime in July. Half of the seats in the
upper house of parliament will be up for grabs.
	   The pro-business Liberal Democratic Party has 261 seats in the
powerful 500-member lower house. With 118 seats in the less
powerful upper house, it still needs support from the 21-member
Social Democratic Party and three-member Sakigake to gain a
majority in the 252-member body.
	   The Social Democrats and Sakigake party were expected to
continue to vote with the LDP on a case-by-case basis. The Social
Democrats have pledged to support Hashimoto's administration if
opposition parties submit a no-confidence vote against the
government.
	   Hashimoto has indicated he will seek cooperation from the two
parties on some issues. Still, he may need to court additional
support from independent lawmakers and non-aligned parties such as
a lay Buddhist political group which once had close ties to the
LDP.
	   In June of 1996, the LDP joined hands with the Social Democrats
in an ``unholy alliance,'' producing Japan's first socialist prime
minister in 46 years.
	   While the two parties had long been rivals, they buried their
enmity in a bid to keep from power a reformist coalition made up of
political renegades from both parties.
	   The LDP fell from power by this reformist coalition in July of
1993 after four decades as Japan's sole ruling party. 	   
</TEXT>
