<HEADLINE>
BANGLADESH
</HEADLINE>
Ruling party out to destroy country: B Chowdhury, THE INDEPENDENT  
   xfdws RULING-PARTY-OUT sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   Deputy Leader of the Opposition Prof. AQM Badruddoza Choudhury
said that the ruling party is out to destroy the
country.''Bangladesh is not a subservient country and it will in no
way follow the dictates of others'', he said.He was addressing a
public meeting at Madhabdi SP High School ground in the district on
May 22.Badruddoza Choudhury said that signing of the CHT accord had
deprived the Bengali-speaking people living there from utilising
natural resources in the hill districts.
	   On the other hand, the accord ensured all facilities for the
tribal people . He criticised the provisions of the CHT
accord.Blaming the government for severe power cricis he said that
the government could not ease the situation even after dropping the
Energy Minister. He said that the electricity crisis forced closure
of many mills, industries and factories throwing lakhs of workers
out of job.The BNP leader blamed the government for not fulfilling
its election pledges, particularly those made to the farmers .
	   ``Instead of increasing the price of jute to Tk 500 per maund,
the government has increased the prices of agricultural inputs'',
he said. Law and order situation has deteriorated alarmingly, the
BNP leader said adding that the government has failed to curb
terrorism in its two years rule.
	   Killing and rape have become a everyday affair, he said adding
that some 350 political leaders and workers were killed during the
tenure of the present government. The meeting , presided over by
Amanullah, was addressed , among others, by Lt Col (Rtd) Akbar
Hossain MP, Dr. Moyeen Khan MP, Shamsuddin Ahmad MP, Goyeswar
Chandra Roy, DUCSU GS Khairul Kabir Khokan, Abdul Hannan, Abu Saleh
Choudhury and Shamir Bhuiyan.
	   
</TEXT>
