<HEADER>
w2750  wstm-
r w     BRING-JOY-TO-A-TEACHERsk     06-01 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BRING-JOY-TO-A-TEACHER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Even a `bunga hidup' can bring joy to a teacher, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws BRING-JOY-TO-A-TEACHER sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   I AM saddened by C.L. Goh's advice to teachers not to ask
presents from pupils and not to punish them or treat them
differently when they cannot bring a gift on Teachers' Day (NST,
May 26).
	   Teachers do not need such advice which diminishes their dignity,
least of all on an occasion society has set aside to acknowledge
their special role and contribution.
	   In spite of relatively low remuneration, lack of opportunities
for advancement, the difficult circumstances brought about by the
rapidly changing curricula, a new generation of students and
parents who do not seem to have much regard for the teaching
profession and the many frustrations within the education system
itself, teachers valiantly struggle on. Teachers' Day brings a
little consolation and encouragement.
	   Goh's account of a colleague's dilemma reveals a typical lack of
understanding of what is really going on in schools and the
problems faced by teachers and headmasters.
	   Although I do not know which school the particular child is in,
I can understand how a problem such as the bunga hidup could have
come about.
	   Teachers and headmasters are faced with the problem of pupils
trying to out-do each other in bringing presents for their teachers
on Teachers' Day.
	   To avoid the situation where the rich ones bring embarrassingly
expensive gifts and the poorer ones try to buy presents they cannot
afford, and situations where some form teachers are heaped with
presents and the non-form teachers, though not less dedicated are
neglected, some schools have standardised the gifts to a meaningful
and relatively inexpensive bunga hidup (which can even come from
the child's own garden) or perhaps to a simple card made by the
child.
	   An additional little note of appreciation from the parent would
have also gone a long way to impart some needed joy to the
teacher's heart.
	   Teachers are not asking for presents, they are asking for
understanding and trust.
	   The source of the child's distress may have nothing to do with
the fear of punishment or rejection by teachers but from the
disapproval of his peers.
	   Nonetheless, parents need to appreciate that teachers and
schools have a tremendous impact on the shaping of the mind,
character and values of their children.
	   They should seek to understand what is going on in their
children's schools and to work hand in hand with teachers in
educating the young.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BRING-JOY-TO-A-TEACHER sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
