<HEADER>
w2757  wstm-
r i     BC-Russia-KGBReturns?     06-01 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-KGB Returns? </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin moves to strengthen government _ with help of former KGB agents 
</HEADLINE>
By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ When Boris Yeltsin was fighting communism, the KGB
dogged his every step. But now that he wants to bring some order to
his unruly government, he's turning to his former enemies for help.
	   In the past week, Yeltsin has appointed three former spies to
key jobs in his administration dealing with Russia's far-flung
regions, where the Kremlin has suffered several recent setbacks.
	   Yeltsin has not commented publicly on the appointments. But
critics say the former KGB agents, trained in the repressive Soviet
system, abhor civilian control over government and are generally
anti-democratic and opposed to reforms.
	   ``They seem to be out of their mind at the Kremlin,'' says
Yevgenia Albats, a prominent Russian commentator who has followed
the KGB and its successors' activities since Soviet times.
	   First, Yeltsin appointed Vladimir Putin, 45, a former KGB
intelligence officer posted to Germany during the 1970s, as his
first deputy chief of staff in charge of relations with Russia's
regions.
	   Then he named Gen. Viktor Zorin, former deputy chief of the
Federal Security Service _ the KGB's main successor agency _ head
of the darkly named Department for Special Programs. Little is
known about the department, although it is believed to be involved
in regional issues.
	   On Monday, Gen. Nikolai Patrushev, 46, another high-ranking
Federal Security Service official, was appointed head of the
presidential Main Control Directorate _ the department controlling
how regional officials spend money from Moscow.
	   Analyst Andrei Ryabov of the Carnegie Endowment for Peace said
the appointments were made to tighten Yeltsin's control over the
recently disobedient regions.
	   Regional officials have been blamed for misspending the federal
funds allocated to the regions _ thereby contributing to the
chronic problem of unpaid wages and pensions that touched off
recent strikes and protests.
	   Despite strong opposition from the Kremlin, voters in the rich
Krasnoyarsk region of Siberia last month elected as their governor
Alexander Lebed, a former general and national security chief with
presidential ambitions.
	   In another embarrassment, a convicted embezzler was elected
mayor in Nizhny Novgorod, Russia's third largest city. Election
officials invalidated his victory after Yeltsin expressed concern
about the balloting results.
	   Ryabov, who studies Russia's domestic policy, said Yeltsin may
also be trying to recruit officials with no ties to any of the
powerful business clans vying for control over government.
	   ``Yeltsin has obviously sought to find a counterbalance to the
growing pressure of the powerful financial groups,'' he said in an
interview.
	   Ryabov cautioned against interpreting the appointments as a sign
of growing clout for the former KGB, saying today's security
officers are politically neutral bureaucrats.
	   Albats, the journalist, disagreed, saying disdain for Yeltsin's
free market reforms is widespread among the former KGB, and their
loyalties doubtful.
	   ``It's not that they are all bad guys, but they have been
brought up in the system based on violence and lawlessness,''
Albats said.
	   ``KGB people generally got a very good training, but their
skills were intended for another system and hardly suitable for the
democratic environment.''
	   The KGB was disbanded in 1991 shortly before the Soviet collapse
and divided into several successor agencies. Many former spies have
found their way into Russia's banking and business sector, while
others entered politics.
	   (vi/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
