<BODY>
<SLUG> 3+0-PROGRAMMES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Clarification on advertisements of 3+0 programmes, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws 3+0-PROGRAMMES sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE report on the approval of 3+0 programmes (NST, May 10),
quoted me as saying ``while we do not encourage such
advertisements, we will allow them if the college can furnish us
with a satisfactory reason for publishing them''.
	   This statement and the subsequent three paragraphs in the report
were taken out of context. I was clarifying on advertisements
already made concerning the 3+0 programmes by private colleges and
indicated that they are required by Department of Private Education
(JPS) to answer or explain their actions.
	   If their answers are satisfactory, they may/will be given a
warning. If not, stern action can be taken against them.
	   It is implied in the article that those advertisements are
allowed or condoned by the Ministry as long as the private colleges
have satisfactory explanation or justifications.
	   Certainly the Ministry does not allow or encourage such
advertisements merely because the colleges can provide/give prior
justifications. It contradicts the whole spirit of the article
which emphasised the need to get the Ministry's approval to run the
3+0 programmes.
	   The National Accreditation Board objects to such advertisements
and acknowledges that such matters are within the jurisdiction of
JPS.
	   It is for the Minister of Education to decide on the approval of
3+0 programmes and the issues pertaining to the applications are
within the purview of JPS.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
