<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG
</HEADLINE>
Policeman dies in MTR track jump, HONGKONG STANDARD  
   xfdws POLICE-DIES-IN-MTR-TRACK sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   A POLICE officer committed suicide by jumping into the path of a
Mass Transit Railway train on Sunday morning.
	   Sergeant Chan Wai-man, 49, was seen jumping onto the Kwun
Tong-bound tracks in Wong Tai Sin MTR station about 7.50 am.
	   He died shortly after arrival at Queen Elizabeth Hospital.
	   A suicide note, together with the officer's warrant card and
$300 in banknotes, was found on him.
	   A police spokesman said the man was seen jumping onto the tracks
as the train approached.
	   The case was classified as suicide.
	   The victim had been with the police for 30 years, and had just
been transferred to Sha Tin from the Island District two weeks ago.
	   It was learnt that he had been telling his family and colleagues
lately that he was under tremendous stress, and wanted to commit
suicide.
	   The man, together with his wife and son, lived in a flat in Tse
Wan Shan.
	   His son, who is studying Journalism in Chu Hai College, also
worked in a television station as a freelance researcher.
	   The police said they were still investigating the motive for the
suicide.
	   The MTR said they were testing the use of glass screens on both
sides of the tracks to prevent people falling.
	   The incident interrupted the train service for about 15 minutes.
	   
</TEXT>
