<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG
</HEADLINE>
Pools to kick off in a week, HONGKONG STANDARD  
   xfdws POOLS-TO-KICK-OFF-A-WEEK sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   CASINO mogul Stanley Ho Hung-sun announced on Sunday the
enclave's international football pools would be officially launched
on 8 June, just in time for the 1998 World Cup in France.
	   Mr Ho, 76, made the announcement during Macau's international
dragon boat races.
	   According to a spokesman for Mr Ho's casino company Macau
Tourism and Amusement Company (STDM), the lottery will be run by
Slot - a subsidiary of the company.
	   Slot will accept bets on the results of selected soccer matches
drawn from national leagues, regional cups and international
matches from all over the world, providing odds and handicap-goal
for the selected matches.
	   Bets can be placed in STDM betting centres in Macau, including
the Macau Jockey Club and greyhound canidrome, and by telephone.
	   Gamblers from Hong Kong and elsewhere in the region can avail
themselves of telephone betting accounts.
	   Slot's first scheduled betting game will be the World Cup
opening match between Brazil and Scotland on 10 June, a public
holiday in Macau in celebration of Portugal's national day.
	   STDM subsidiaries hold all the enclave's government-franchised
lotteries, namely the traditional Chinese ``Pigeon'' lottery. The
STDM spokesman stressed that Macau's football pools would be the
first of its kind legally franchised in Asia.
	   Mr Ho reportedly chose 8 June as the lottery's official launch
day because the date is considered to be auspicious.
	   
</TEXT>
