<SLUG> A-GOOD-NEWS-FOR-50MILL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
A good news for 50 million asthma patients worldwide, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws A-GOOD-NEWS-FOR-50MILL sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   In todays' medical scenario, asthma is turning out to be one of
the most serious health problems plaguing almost all countries,
both developed and under developed. According to the National
Heart, Lung and Blood Institute in the US, asthma affects
approximately 15 million Americans, four million of whom are under
18. In fact, over the last decade, there has been a 91 per cent
increase in asthma-related deaths in the US alone.
	   On global basis, at least 50 million people worldwide suffer
from asthma and allergies. Studies conducted in different cities of
India about the prevalence of asthma are quite horrifying. Case
studies in Bangalore in India among 15,556 children revealed that
instances of asthma rose from 9 per cent in 1979 to 24.5 per cent
(almost one out of every four children) in 1994. ``Among adults it
is now known that every tenth Indian sufers from asthma'', says Dr.
Rajesh Chawla, senior consultant at Apollo Hospital and President
of the Delhi Chest Forum.
	   In Jaipur, a study among 4,000 people showed that 15 per cent of
children in the age group 5 to 11 had asthma. In Delhi, the figure
is about the same. The statistics revealed in the case of India,
our closest neighbour and with enviromnental and economic condition
of people almost similar, put us pondering that situation in our
country might appear to be not very much different from India.
Statistics available from the premier hospital for chest diseases
in Dhaka revealed that asthma-related diseases and allergic
infections registered a sharp rise from its previous figure of 5
per cent in early 1990s to about 15 per cent in recent times.
	   The number of patients is on the upswing. Asthma is a chronic
disease in which airflow in and out of the lungs may be blocked by
muscle squeezing, swelling and excess mucus. Symptoms vary from
person to person, but usually include coughing, wheezing, shortness
of breath, chest tightness or producing a lot of mucus.
	   Physicians don't know the basic cause of asthma or why one
person gets asthma and another doesn't. They do know that heredity
plays some role, meaning asthma often runs in families, especially
in families who have a lot of allergies. It is known that asthma is
not caused by emotional factors such as a troubled parent-child
relationship, although emotions may affect pre-existing asthma.
Though there are no nationwide studies, doctors confirm that the
number of patients is on the upswing for reasons like an enormous
increase in air pollution, usage of common drugs like aspirin and
pain killer and an increasing list of allergens. Anyone can get
asthma but it is most likely to occur in children by age 5 and in
adults in their 30s. Even older people can develop asthma: about 10
per cent of new asthma cases are diagnosed in people who are 65
years or older.
	   Certain factors increase in people's chances of developing
asthma. For example, if one of the victim's parents has the
disease, he is more likely to get it. People having allergic
syndrome are more likely to develop asthma other than the heredity
factor. (As a matter of fact, research data have revealed that at
least 80 per cent of children and 50 per cent adults with asthma
have allergies). The factors that cause this allergic syndrome
still elude physicians. Studies have shown that the job of immune
system cells is to identify foreign substances (such as viruses and
bacteria). Normally this response protects us from dangerous
diseases. Anybody having allergies would have a super-sensitive
immune system which reacts to harmless substances like plant
pollen, dust mites, or animal dander, saliva of animals with fir or
feathers, cockroaches and their waste, stinging insects such as
bees, wasps, hornets and red ants, foods such as eggs, milk, nuts
and sea food, ingredients found in dyes, cosmetics, perfumes and
latex. These substances are called allergens.
	   And our immune system's ``overreaction'' is what causes our
allergy symptoms. What causes asthma other than these allergens is
still not known to experts even. Says an expert, ``The exact cause
still eludes us''. But what is clear is the mechanics of asthma - a
Greek word that simply means ``breathing hard''. It begins when the
body's immune system becomes so sensitized to an allergen, mainly
through heavy exposure in childhood, that it starts treating it as
a threat. When the allergen enters the body the renegade immune
system triggers the release of proteins called IgE antibodies in
response to the allergen. These antibodies surge through the blood
stream fastening themselves to cells which react by pouring out
inflammatory chemicals.
	   Confined to the nose at first, this reaction only leads to a
runny nose. But when it extends down to the lungs, the result
becomes lethal. The bronchioles (small airways) fill up with mucus
leading to laboured breathing. As more airways get choked, the
attack becomes severe. Leaving aside the family history in which
case either of the parents carrying the disease leaves the
offspring more prone to attack at certain stages of life, in most
cases the allergens trigger the attack. Topping the list of
villains mentioned earlier, air pollution these days poses the
menacing threat. Says Dr. H. Paramesh, a paediatric pulmonologist
and the Principal Investigator of the Bangalore Study, ``The risk
in asthma is directly proportional to the number of automobiles,
density of population and industrial growth.'' Ozone, diesel fumes
and suspended particles all act as irritants to the air passages.
	   Other new factors include, as already mentioned, drugs like
aspirin and Brufen (mostly pain killer). ``The indiscriminate use
of these drugs very often triggers asthma'', says Dr. Prem Sobti,
President of the Asthma, Bronchitis and Cancer Lung Foundation of
India. Doctors caution that anyone having anyone of the following
symptoms for the past 12 months should seek the advice of a doctor
to ascertain if he is heading for asthma attack:   )
If you have had a sudden severe episode or recurrent episodes of
coughing, wheezing (high-pitched whistling sounds when breathing
out) or shortness of breath.   ) If you have had cold that go to the
chest or take more than l 0
days to get over.   ) If you have had coughing, wheezing or
shortness of
breath in certain places or when exposed to certain things (e.g.
animals, tobacco smokes or perfumes).   ) If you have had used any
medications that
helped you breathe better.	   
	   Today an entire generation is learning to cope out with the
ailment. Doctors these days advise asthmatic people to carefully
select exercise activities such as walking, light jogging, leisure
biking and hiking rather than strenuous outdoor running sports.
Swimming is often recommended for asthmatics because of its many
positive factors: a warm, humid atmosphere, year-round
availability, and the body's horizontal position which may help
mobilise mucus from the bottom of the lungs. In fact, some Olympic
swimmers have severe asthma. Other activities recommended include
sports that involve short bursts of energy, such as baseball,
football, wrestling, short distance track and field events,
golfing, and gymnastics. Cold weather events such as cross-country
skiing and ice hockey or long distance non-stop activities like
basketball, field hockey or soccer are not recommended as they are
likely to aggravate airways.
	   However, childhood asthma differs from adult asthma in that
infants and small children may not show the usual signs of asthma.
Instead, asthma in children may appear as rapid respiration, noisy
breathing, retraction and chest congestion. Parents can help the
doctors better in recognising if their children are suffering from
asthma. Parents may notice that their child has less stamina during
active play time than his or her peers, or the child may try to
limit physical activities to prevent coughing or wheezing. More
subtle signs of asthma, such as chest tightness, may be overlooked
or the child does not have the capability to identify them as
asthma.
	   Recurrent or constant coughing spells may be the only common
observable symptom of asthma in young children. Though majority of
the children who get asthma grow out of it in their teens, doctors
feel that may be reversing with a lot of them retaining it through
adulthood. An asthma-trigger control plan is an important part of
controlling asthma. Most asthmatics, with inhalers or a peak flow
meter, the most recent device with a plastic contraption at close
reach, swap information and moral support. A peak flow meter is a
device that measures how well air moves out of your lungs. During
an asthma episode, the airways of the lungs begin to narrow slowly.
The peak flow meter can be used to find out if there is narrowing
of the airway hours - even days before you have any symptoms of
asthma.
	   By taking medicine early (before symptoms), one may be able to
stop the episode quickly and avoid a serious asthma attack. In an
effort to avoid serious asthma attack, families have got rid of
their pets, done away with carpets that attract dust and even
shifted residence to less polluted suburbs. Fortunately, these days
the drug and the devices arsenal to deal with asthma are quite
effective and easy to use. Only a few years ago arduous breathing
meant frequent puffs of an inhaler. Today doctors have shifted the
pattern of medication giving drugs only on emergency situation and
in most cases pattern of treatment has been more proactive relying
more on prevention. Bronchodilators are given to the asthmatics
having only a tight feeling after running a flight of stairs.
	   But an asthmatic who wheezes regularly needs a stronger drug
support.Today steroid inhalers have become first line of drugs
against asthma and in an inhaler form have little side effects.
CFC-free ``Azmacort'' introduced in the market in the last part of
1997 after a series of clinical studies done by Dr. Jacques
Caldwell, Medical Director of the Halifax Clinical Research Centre
in Daytona, Florida, and Dr. Paul Chervinsky, President of the New
England Research Centre in Darmouth, Massachusetts relieved
asthmatics quite profoundly. Bringing further relief to the
patients, researchers at the 1998 American Lung Association and the
American Thoracic Society International Conference announced on
April 28 this year, the results of the Azmacort built-in-spacer
inhaler system using PET (Positron emission tomography) imaging
technology - a device designed to enhance drug delivery and
minimise local side effects.
	   The NIH (National Institute of Health) in the US has recommended
spacer use with inhaled corticosteroids to improve inhalation
technique and reduce local side effects. So says Edward F. Haponik,
Clinical Director of the Section on Pulmonary and Critical Care
Medicine and Professor of Internal Medicine, Wake Forest University
School of Medicine, Winston-Salem, North Carolina in a recently
released (April 28, 1998) study conducted on patients, ``By showing
patients that a spacer helps to get more medication to the lungs,
rather than the mouth or stomach, patients may have a better
understanding of the role of the spacer''.
	   He further adds, ``Triamcinolone acetonide manufactured by Rhone
Poulenc Rorer, under the brand name Azmacort, is an
anti-inflammatory medication for the preventive management of
asthma and the only inhaled bronchial steroid clinically tested and
approved with a built-in-spacer.'' Doctors have cautioned that the
increase in asthma attacks these days is linked to the fact that
after a while, once the patient is a little better, the inhaler is
put aside without completing the prescribed course. ``There is a
feeling among patients that inhalers are bad and become a life-long
addiction'', says Dr. Deepak Sehgal, a senior consultant
pediatrician, at the Escorts Hospital in Delhi.
	   With preventive drugs most asthma patients can start an exercise
regimen. Doctors these days emphasise that with drugs most patients
can pretty well lead normal lives. But the only thing that stands
in the way is that the cost of medication is still quite
prohibitive and seems to be a burden on poor and middle class
families.
	   
</TEXT>
