<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Dilemma of pensioners over free medical treatment, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws FREE-MEDICAL-TREATMENT sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   ARE government pensioners entitled to free medical treatment and
medication?
	   On the one hand we read that ``All government pensioners are
eligible for free medical treatment ...'' (NST, May 21) as stated
by the Honorary Secretary of the Malacca branch of the Malaysian
Government Pensioners Association. He even quoted General Orders
Chapter F and the procedure whereby one can claim reimbursement.
	   Now the Health Minister says that ``Pensioners appealing for the
continuation of free medication at Government hospitals have been
told to submit a memorandum'' (NST, May 27). If the free treatment
is already enshrined in the General Orders, then why the
memorandum? Does this mean that the benefits have been withdrawn
and we have to wait for the outcome of the memorandum?
	   This contradicts the statement made by the Director of Hospital
Kuala Lumpur, Dr Lim Kuan Joo, who assured all patients under its
care that medication prescribed by its doctors ``will be honoured
and filled accordingly'' (NST, May 26).
	   Then there is the question of getting a letter from a doctor (to
apply for reimbursement) stating the reason why he could not get
the treatment or medication. A recent case of a pensioner seemed to
show that there is still no co-ordination among the various
departments. When the pensioner asked the doctor at HKL for a
letter, the doctor said that he had no authority to give one. So
where do we stand?
	   We are honoured that the Health Minister ``regards pensioners
very highly'' and that they do not ``face undue difficulties in
terms of medical and health care'' (NST, May 27).
	   But the situation is still the same, and most of us are still
having difficulties. This is not something we can wait. Old and
sick people have no time to wait.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
