<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian markets lower despite U.S. support staff by one-third. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with new 10th graf, Kiriyenko orders Cabinet to cut
By MAURA REYNOLDS
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The government has enough cash reserves to protect
the ruble against devaluation, but additional help from the
International Monetary Fund would help calm jittery investors,
Russia's new tax chief said Monday.
	   Boris Fyodorov, who was appointed by President Boris Yeltsin on
Friday, said another dlrs 5 billion would be enough to reassure
investors shaken by last week's wave of panic selling that caused
the stock market to plummet.
	   Despite U.S. promises to support new loans by international
lenders, Russian markets sank further in early trading Monday.
	   In a brief statement issued Sunday, President Bill Clinton
expressed U.S. support for aid to Russia from such multinational
institutions as the World Bank and the IMF.
	   Nonetheless, by midday the stock market was down an additional
4.5 percent, although traders said there was little panic selling.
	   ``We are seeing a manageable fall,'' said Robert Devane, head of
fixed-income trading at Moscow's Troika-Dialog brokerage. ``We are
not yet at a critical point like last week.''
	   Altogether the stock market is down 40 percent since April. The
Central Bank has intervened to prop up the ruble and tripled a key
interest rates to 150 percent to persuade investors to stay in
Russia.
	   The ruble was slightly weaker in trading early Monday.
	   In a move to ease the crisis, IMF officials said Friday that
they will recommend releasing a delayed payment of dlrs 700
million, the latest installment of an existing dlrs 10 billion
loan.
	   Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko, moving to cut government
spending, Monday ordered a 30 percent reduction in Cabinet
personnel, the ITAR-Tass news agency said. Cabinet staffing will be
cut from 1,450 people to 1,015, the report said.
	   Before the crisis, Russia's economic prospects had been looking
somewhat brighter, with the government having kept a lid on
inflation and recording its first economic growth since the 1991
Soviet collapse.
	   But the government has been unable to solve a years-long
payments crisis, caused by its inability to collect taxes and
therefore to pay wages to state workers. Many workers and
pensioners have been unpaid for months.
	   Fyodorov said in an earlier television interview that the
country's 35 percent tax rate must be lowered but enforcement
strengthened.
	   ``The rate should be 20 percent, but then those who do not pay
must in effect be put into prison,'' he told the NTV network.
	   Russian leaders have said that the economic crisis was triggered
by a combination of forces, including a sharp fall in world prices
for gas and oil, the financial crisis in southeast Asia, and social
unrest including a recent wave of coal miners' strikes.
	   (dj/mr/jai/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
