<SLUG> HSI-HOUSING-POLICY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG
</HEADLINE>
HSI to get temporary lift from housing policy, HONGKONG STANDARD  
   xfdws HSI-HOUSING-POLICY sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   RENEWED interest among potential homebuyers after the lifting of
anti-speculation measures could help Hong Kong's financial and
property stocks when they resume trading on Monday, following a
lacklustre show last week, analysts said.
	   However, they added, the market still expected an uncertain week
after the government's announcement of seven emergency measures to
help revive the economy.
	   These are aimed at reversing the massive slump in consumer
spending, which the government blames for the contraction in the
first quarter.
	   The decision to relax anti-speculation rules introduced in 1994
was an attempt to stabilise the property sector and boost the
economy, analysts said.
	   ``The measures in the short term will ease the credit crunch and
will stimulate consumption,'' Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa said.
	   On Friday, Hong Kong stocks rose for the first time in six days,
led by property shares, on the expectation that the government
would ease the measures it imposed several years ago designed to
curb speculation in Hong Kong's booming real estate market.
	   The Hang Seng Index (HSI) gained 56.62 points, or 0.6 per cent,
to 8,934.56, led by Sun Hung Kai Properties and Henderson Land
Development.
	   The index had fallen about 678.04 points or 7.1 per cent in the
days before the announcement.
	   However, gains were expected to be short-lived as, just after
the market closed on Friday, the government reported that first
quarter gross domestic product contracted by 2 per cent. Some
analysts expect the economy to shrink as much as 3 per cent for the
year.
	   ``The reversing of the 1994 anti-speculation package in an
attempt to stabilise prices is a potential disaster,'' said
Christopher Tinker, regional head of economics and debt research at
ING Barings.
	   ``By pursuing this line, the government is clearly backing down
on its housing policy, to the detriment of the man in the street.''
But the HSI is expected to respond favourably to the measures that
include an extension of the pre-sale period of uncompleted flats
from the current 15 months to 20 months and limiting flat sales to
companies to the last 15 per cent of each batch.
	   
</TEXT>
