w2780  wstm-
r w     UNSC-WANTS-PAKsked     06-01 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> UNSC-WANTS-PAK sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANGLADESH
</HEADLINE>
UNSC wants Pak moratorium on nuclear test, THE INDEPENDENT  
   xfdws UNSC-WANTS-PAK sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   The UN Security Council has rebuked Pakistan for defying the
world in conducting another underground nuclear test on Saturday,
amid growing fears that an arms race with neighbouring India could
escalate out of control.Japan called an emergency session of the
15-members body on Saturday to present a resolution it had drafted
with Sweden and Costa Rica to keep pressure on the two south Asian
rivals, which between them have conducted 11 underground nuclear
explosions in the past month.
	   President Bill Clinton and UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan also
condemned Pakistan, adding their voices to an international chorus
of criticism and of appeals to the two nations to calm the tension
created by their nuclear tests. Pakistan, in a robust defence of
its actions, said its tests had achieved strategic stability in the
region and told its people to tighten their belts to counter
expected cuts in foreign aid. Security Council President, Njuguna
Mahugu, of Kenya told reporters often the closed-door session, that
the 15 members ``deeply deplored'' Pakistan's latest test--carried
out only hours after the council had criticised Islamabad, for its
first set of five nuclear tests conducted on Thursday.
	   India conducted five tests on May 11 and 13, its first since it
detonated one bomb in 1974. 'The council also called on the
government of Pakistan to issue a public declaration announcing a
moratorium on future tests and experimentation on delivery
systems,'' Mahugu said. India announced a moratorium on future
tests after completing its recent test programme. The council made
its comments to the media rather than issuing a formal statement
that carries the weight of international policy. But it is
considering a resolution threatening further unspecified measures
against both India and Pakistan.
	   ``The council expressed its increased concern at the risk of a
nuclear arms race escalating in south Asia and urged India and
Pakistan to accede to the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty
(CTBT), that was negotiated two years ago, `` Mahugu added. Japan's
draft resolution 'encourages'' nations to stop supplying India and
Pakistan with equipment and technology that could be used to
develop nuclear weapons.
	   Annan, in a separate statement, called Pakistan's action ``a
further dangerous and senseless escalation of tension which could
lead' to a nuclear arms race with incalculable consequences.'' He
appealed to the Prime Ministers of India and Pakistan to
demonstrate leadership and reduce tensions between them, and
repeated his offer to help mediate on the disputed region of
Kashmir. President Clinton condemned Pakistan's new nuclear test
and said, India and Pakistan were contributing to a 'self-defeating
cycle of escalation
	   '' 'These tasts can only serve to increase tensions in an
already volatile region,'' he said in a written statement, 'both
India and Pakistan need to renounce further nuclear and missile
testing immediately and take decisive steps to reverse this
dangerous arms race,'' he added. Clinton also signed documents
setting in motion economic sanctions he-imposed against Pakistan
that put in jeopardy billions of dollars in loans from multilateral
lending institution.
	   Sanctions have also been imposed against India.Japan,
Islamabad's biggest aid and trade partner, has recalled its
ambassador to Islamabad in protest, frozen new yen loans and
suspended most fresh united loans--as it did to India after the
Indian tests. Australia has suspended non-humanitarian aid. But
Russia, China and most west European states have not followed suit,
which means the same countries would likely block any punitive
action in the United Nations. Pakistani leaders remained defiant in
the face of international criticism. Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
said that government expenses-would be halved as part of austerity
drive to offset the likely impact of sanctions.
	   
</TEXT>
