<HEADER>
w2783  wstm-
r w     MERGER-MAY-SAVE-S.AFRICA     06-01 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> MERGER-MAY-SAVE-S.AFRICA sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Merger may save S. Africa's NP from going way of the dodo, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws MERGER-MAY-SAVE-S.AFRICA sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   IS the once all-powerful National Party about to disappear from
the political scene. Are those dinosaurs who formerly led the cruel
racial tyranny of apartheid about to leave, finally, the green
benches of Parliament? It seems - on the face of it - possible.
	   The party which used to be a byword for organisation, for
knocking on doors and getting the vote out at election time is now
a shadow of its former self.
	   A series of local by-elections has seen the once great party
humiliated by the cheeky liberals of the Democratic Party. In the
Cape, in KwaZulu Natal, in Gauteng - especially in Gauteng, the
commercial and industrial heartland of the country, NP local
councillors have been ousted in favour of Democrats.
	   Rosettenville in the south of Johannesburg, once the rock solid
constituency of the fragrant Sheila Camerer, former junior Justice
Minister, swung impressively to the DP. Most of the seats snatched
by the DP have been in historically white areas, but in a mainly
black squatter seat on the edge of Cape Town, the NP lost to the
ANC - as well it might -but its vote dropped from 22 per cent to
two per cent.
	   In addition there has been a steady stream - and a swelling one
- of defections from the National Party to the Democratic Party.
There have been a swathe of councillors defecting in the Eastern
Cape, where the NP has got into serious bother with its Coloured
members. Former ministers have been knocking at the door of the DP
leader Tony Leon and converts to liberalism now include such as
Rina Venter, former Health Minister, and Tertius Delport, former
Minister for Constitutional Development.
	   But two weeks ago came a major blow to the new leader of the NP,
Marthinus van Schalkwyk. For the first time one of his sitting MPs
has defected. He is a Coloured former headmaster from the Eastern
Cape, and the importance of his defection is that he must
immediately lose his parliamentary seat.
	   The new Constitution contains a rigorous anti-defection clause.
If an MP is elected on one party's ticket he loses his seat if he
loses the ticket.
	   It is a powerful device for keeping petulant MPs in line. And
not many people in their middle years - as MPs mostly are - can
afford to lose the comfortable salary that goes with the job.
	   Reaction from NP stalwarts to the party's troubles has varied.
The rock- ribbed nationalists say pooh! We've had worse times.
Remember the 1980s, when the Conservative Party was defeating NP
candidates around the country? We recovered. The more nervous say
the time has come to consider merging the opposition parties.
	   One senior man - a former minister and a provincial leader -
confided that defecting at a time like this is like rearranging the
deck-chairs on the Titanic. What is needed now is a thorough
reorganisation and realignment. The urge to merge is very strong.
	   The National Party has always had a distinctly off-putting
attitude to merger. It has always meant an alliance on NP terms,
with it as the umbrella under which lesser parties could shelter.
It is already too late for that.
	   But even on kinder conditions, the Democratic Party would not
have much to gain from a merger. It would be nice to be enriched by
some of the prime city centre properties currently owned by the NP.
But the price to pay in an indiscriminate acquisition of
Nationalists and their principles might be hard for delicate
liberal sensibilities.
	   And in any case the Democratic Party does not truly need to
merge now.
	   There is no advantage in an electoral pact for except in local
councils all national and provincial assemblies are elected on a
proportional list system.
	   But Leon is happy to say that his door is always open.
	   The latest opinion poll figures are not reassuring to the NP. In
1994 the party gained 20 per cent of the votes nationwide. In an
opinion poll last November that figure was down to 12 per cent. But
last month it fell again to 10 per cent.
	   By contrast the Democratic Party got 1.73 per cent in the
general election. The November opinion poll gave them three per
cent. By last month they were on five per cent.
	   Things are not looking all that brilliant for the ruling ANC
though.
	   Much fuss has been made over statements from party leaders that
it is looking to gain a two-thirds majority in next year's
elections. This would enable it to rewrite the country's
Constitution.
	   It failed narrowly to do so in 1994 when it won nearly 63 per
cent.
	   According to November's poll that figure dropped to 58 per cent.
By last month it fell to 54 per cent. And cynics point out that if
it carries on at this rate, it would fall short of the 50 per cent
it needs to form a government on its own.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
