r w     CHIRAC-URGES-ISRAELsked     06-01 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> CHIRAC-URGES-ISRAEL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANGLADESH
</HEADLINE>
Chirac urges Israel to leave Lebanon, Golan, THE INDEPENDENT  
   xfdws CHIRAC-URGES-ISRAEL sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   French President Jacques Chirac called on Israel on Saturday to
leave both occupied south Lebanon and Syria's Golan Heights, saying
it must understand it cannot have security without Middle East
peace.''Israel must withdraw from Lebanon in accordance with (U.N.)
Resolution 425 and without any conditions. Syria has the right to
see the Golan Heights returned,'' he said from the steps of the
French ambassador's residence in Beirut.''In return, Israel, like
all other states in the region, has the right to full and complete
security.''The French leader then diverted from the printed text:
``But Israel must understand that her people will not know security
if there is no peace.
	   ``His call for an Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon triggered loud
applause from the 4,000 invited guests, including Lebanese
political, military and religious leaders.Chirac, on his third
visit to Beirut in just over two years, has been trying to boost
France's role in Middle East peace making, and proposed earlier
this month that an international conference be convened to
resurrect the U.S.-brokered peace talks.In Arab countries France is
seen as more even-handed than the United States, which is Israel's
key ally and has failed to press Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu into advancing the peace process.In south Lebanon,
Israeli troops are locked in a war of attrition with pro-Iranian
Hizbollah guerrillas.
	   Israel, after heavy losses last year, has offered to leave south
Lebanon on condition the Beirut government gives security
guarantees against cross-border guerrilla attacks on northern
Israel.Lebanon and Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, have
rejected the proposal on the ground that the 20-year-old U.N.
resolution 425 calls for an immediate and unconditional
withdrawal.Damascus, after seeing Israel reach separate peace
treaties with Egypt and Jordan, opposes negotiations with Lebanon
that ignore its demand for return of the Golan Heights.
	   Netanyahu has vowed to keep the plateau, which Israel captured
in 1967 and which dominates nearby areas of both Israel and
Syria.Chirac said Paris was prepared to help guarantee border
security: ``France is prepared to participate with others, if the
parties concerned make a request, to guarantee your borders.''''I
believe that once the Israelis have retreated as part of a global
peace, the Lebanese army, along with the internal security forces,
should be the sole upholders of the authority of the state in all
your territory,'' he added.Chirac earlier discussed Middle East
developments with Lebanon's top leaders, President Elias Hrawi,
Prime Minister Rafik al-Hariri and Parliament Speaker Nabih
Berri.The French leader's 43-hour visit to Beirut, which ends on
Sunday, has been rich in symbolism of the French legacy and hopes
for the future.
	   He stayed at the elegant Ottoman-era residence of the French
envoy in the heart of Beirut that was heavily damaged in the
1975-1990 civil war and formally re-opened when Chirac
arrived.Chirac recalled the dark days of the civil war, in which a
French ambassador and a defence attache were assassinated, but
spoke of a bright future in a Lebanon undergoing multi-billion
dollar reconstruction.He made clear his sympathy for Lebanese
civilians who have fallen to Israeli attacks, sending Air Force
Colonel Daniel Bastien, deputy to the head of his personal military
staff, to the southern town of Qana.He placed a wreath with a
ribbon marked ``The President of the French Republic'' in a
graveyard that has become a national shrine since 100 Lebanese
civilian refugees were killed by Israeli shells in a 1996 military
offensive.
	   
</TEXT>
