w2785  wstm-
r w     NIPPING-A-PROBLEMsked     06-01 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> NIPPING-A-PROBLEM sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Nipping a problem in the bud, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws NIPPING-A-PROBLEM sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE unusually high number of unsuccessful university
applications in spite of the applicants' good results has raised
several questions regarding Unit Pusat Universiti's selection and
administrative process. There is, undoubtedly, a strong case for an
overhaul of the process. It should be thinking hard on the reasons
which led to the dismal failure of the process when it appeared to
be working effectively in the past. As such, its proposed
post-mortem on the process is a welcome move.
	   Arguably, the department must also deal with the contentious
issue of whether there had been any extraneous element that can be
attributed to the shambles. The scenario where a successful
applicant is instructed to register at a private college, a
franchise holder of a university's franchise programme, is
disturbing. Imagine the shock of both parents and applicants to
receive an envelope and letter, bearing the name of a public
university, instructing them to enrol at a private college where
the fees are far higher compared with the university.
	   Granted, miscommunication could be a reason for the confusion
that arose. We are not hurling wild accusations. Such cases also
point to the possibility of a university picking up more than the
number of students it can accommodate for its matriculation
programme with the ultimate aim of re-routing the excess to various
franchise-holder colleges. If it had not recruited beyond the
number it could accommodate, the students would be picked up by the
institutions of their second, third and fourth choices.
	   But the practice of accepting beyond the number of available
places is, in effect, depriving the students of the chance to be
enlisted by the other universities. Neither can they gain admission
into Institut Teknologi Mara since under the UPU rules, ITM is
prohibited from accepting students who have been admitted into
other universities and their franchise programmes.
	   That there is an element of commercial interest - the five
universities with franchise programmes will obtain a certain
percentage for every enrolment in the programmes - lends a
disturbing dimension to the scenario. If an attempt to force the
students into the programmes had transpired, we can only describe
the action as unconscionable. The public has the right to question
the morality of such an action. A situation where universities act
as recruitment agents for their franchise holders should be
avoided. Lest the relationship between the universities and
franchise holders be deemed as incestuous.
	   Education Minister Datuk Seri Najib Tun Razak had told students
allocated places in these franchise programmes not to worry about
the high fees since Mara would provide sponsorship for most of
them. But the good minister misses the point if he treats the issue
as merely a question of funding. The franchise programme is an
excellent idea since it allows people to pursue their education at
a higher level. But universities should not behave or be seen to
behave in a manner which suggests they may be tinkering with the
admission process to profit from the franchise programmes.
	   Accepting students but only to have them re-routed to franchise
holders is unwarranted. Neither should the franchise holders have
access to the list of applications meant for UPU and the
universities for the admission process into the public tertiary
institutions. UPU must ensure its process is not open to such
abuse.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:NIPPING-A-PROBLEM sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
