<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG
</HEADLINE>
China Development in US foray, HONGKONG STANDARD  
   xfdws CHINA-DEVELOPMENT-IN-US sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   CHINA Development Corp says it will buy a leasehold property in
Honolulu, Hawaii, at a cost of US$68 million (HK$526 million) from
US firms SHC-Realty and MKS Executive Partners.
	   It's the first major foray by the investment group into US real
estate.
	   Of the total amount, HK$302 million is to be paid in cash.
	   The firm will pay a second instalment of HK$108 million through
an issue of 140 million new ordinary shares at 40 cents each to the
owners at the price of HK$0.78 per share. This represents a premium
of about 204 per cent to the average closing price of the company's
shares over the 10 previous trading days.
	   The balance of HK$116 million is to be satisfied through the
issue of a zero-coupon note.
	   About HK$271 million of the cash consideration will be sourced
through bank borrowings, while the balance of HK$31 million will
come from internal resources.
	   Lee Howe-yong, China Development Corp director, said the
purchase should benefit and increase the value of the company. He
said the firm intends to hold the property as long-term investment.
	   ``Hawaii has historically lagged behind the mainland of the US
in terms of economic growth.
	   However, in view of the robust and thriving US economy, it is
anticipated that Hawaii's economy should see a turnaround and enjoy
good growth prospects,'' Mr Lee said.
	   The 577,124 square-foot property, the Executive Centre, is a
leasehold condominium project.
	   The project comprises 511 residential and office, penthouse,
town house, and commercial units, as well as 864 parking spaces.
	   
</TEXT>
