<SLUG> PALESTINIAN-CABINET sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANGLADESH
</HEADLINE>
Palestinian cabinet calls for int'l sanctions against Israel, THE INDEPENDENT  
   xfdws PALESTINIAN-CABINET sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   The Palestinian cabinet called on Saturday international
sanctions to be slapped on Israel to punish it for its hard line in
the deadlocked Middle East peace process. 'We ask that the
international community take economic and political measures
against Israel to penalise the arrogant policy of its government,''
the cabinet said in a statement after its weekly meeting. The
statement was issued as Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat was
holding talks with leaders of the United Arab Emirates as part of a
diplomatic push to gain support for an Arab summit on the
deadlocked peace talks.
	   'European, American and Arab efforts to revive the process have
led nowhere because of the Israeli government's policy, which does
not respect international resolutions and accords signed with the
Palestinians.'' The statement also lambasted Israel for its
continued settlement polices, particularly in annexed east
Jerusalem, saying they would 'lead to an explosion.'' Israel's
decision in March last year to start work on a large new Jewish
settlement in east Jerusalem, which the Jewish state occupied and
annexed in 1967, led to the current impasse in peace negotiations.
	   In a bid to break the deadlock, Washington is pushing Israel to
hand over another 13 per cent of the West Bank to Palestinian rule,
in tandem with Palestinian measures against terrorism, but Israel
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said a troop withdrawal of that
size would threaten Israel's security. 'The Israeli government has
shown its true face by refusing the proposals of the Untied States,
which is much closer to (Israel's) stance than ours,'' the
Palestinian cabinet said. Netanyahu returned to Israel on Friday
after his visit to China, and is due to hold a cabinet meeting on
Monday to re-examine the US proposals. And in a continuing
Palestinian push to garner support for an Arab summit designed to
pressure Israel, Arafat was in Abu Dhabi for talks with UAE
President Sheikh Zayed Ibn Sultan Al-Nahayan.
	   Their discussions will cover 'the possibility of holding an
urgent Arab summit to scrutinise the stalled peace process and
efforts to tighten Arab ranks,'' the official Wam news agency said.
The UAE on Wednesday renewed its call for the 'urgent'' convening
of such a summit to try to break the 14-month deadlock, while
Arafat warned of an new outbreak of violence in the occupied
territories over Israel's hardline stance. 'A summit has become a
national necessity to protect the right and the interests of our
Arab nation,'' he said.
	   Palestinian leaders believe the coming week will be decisive for
the success of the eight-month-old US drive to unblock the peace
process, saying Washington knows it cannot ask for more time
without serious resistance form the Arab side. 'The Untied States
knows perfectly well that the Palestinians and Arabs will not agree
to continue any longer with the current situation of uncertainty,''
Arafat's spokesman Nabil Abu Rudeina told agency. The Palestinians
hope the US initiative will end with Israel accepting US proposals
for a partial pullback form the West Bank or, if Israel continues
to resist, that Washington will make its proposals public and
explain why they have not worked.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
