<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 10:17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2793  wstm-
r w     RESTRUCTURE-TARIFFSsked     06-01 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> RESTRUCTURE-TARIFFS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Restructure tariffs to keep water flowing, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws RESTRUCTURE-TARIFFS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE shortage of potable water and the resulting need to ration
has been attributed to nature and is thought to be a short-term
problem. Once the weather turns around, it is argued, we will have
plenty of rain in the catchment areas and households will once
again have abundant supply to use as they please.
	   In many cases there may be more than enough water and it is
justified to waste the resource because it is free and a gift from
God and no government has the right to charge more than a nominal
fee for its use.
	   Some countries that promoted this ideology now find themselves
with inadequate supply because of increased salinisation and
alkalisation of water.
	   While raw water is free, treated water is not. Raw water is
generally not fit for consumption because if it is, we will not
have a water crisis.
	   We have a crisis because we are short of treated water.
	   While the supply of raw water is driven by nature, that of
treated water is not necessarily so. Otherwise countries like the
Maldives and Dubai, which have low levels of rainfall would be out
of treated water.
	   The first thing to do to get out of the crisis is to distinguish
between raw and treated water.
	   We can have adequate supply of treated water even in an
environment where there is very little rainfall provided we are
able to manage water resources efficiently. The crisis is not due
to nature but to the ``command and control'' type of water
management we have inherited from the colonial days.
	   We would not be facing a shortage if we had an efficient system
of capturing, storing, treating and distributing water. As it is
about 40 per cent of treated water is lost because the distribution
pipes are old or leaking.
	   We may even have problems locating these pipes because of the
absence of maps. If this ``lost'' water was distributed to
households we may not have such a severe crisis.
	   However, to repair or replace the pipes requires money and the
present water charges may be inadequate to cover the costs. Just
like the modernisation of our electricity and telephone industries
and transport system, we need to invest in the water treatment and
distribution system to insure against a recurrence of the crisis.
	   There may be some protests about raising water rates considering
the current economic situation, but if you ask people who have been
without water for 17 days how much they are willing to pay for
treated water, they will tell you ``quite a lot''.
	   Maybe we should base rates on people's ``willingness to pay''.
Some Malaysians have been paying as much as RM20 for a day's supply
of treated water during the crisis while others have been giving
the Waterworks Department only RM21 for two-month supply. This is
definitely inequitable.
	   It is obvious that those not affected by the crisis are deriving
a surplus - i.e. the difference between what people are ``willing
to pay'' and what they are ``actually paying''. Therefore, it is
time to negotiate a new social contract between the Government and
people to ensure predictable and reliable supply of treated water
based on rates or prices that reflect the scarcity of the resource.
The contract will have to be consistent with the sustainable
development of water resources.
	   To sustain the development of water resources there must be
enough money. Some will argue that the Government can rely on taxes
but as the crisis amply shows, tax revenues are insufficient to
meet this need.
	   To treat and distribute water involves several costs. These
include the purchase of capital goods, labour, materials and also
environmental costs.
	   These are all opportunity costs because the same resources can
be used to build schools, universities, hospitals and a host of
other things that can enhance the standard of living.
	   There is therefore a need to recover the costs of developing
water resources through pricing. Otherwise there will not be enough
funds to maintain, renew and expand facilities for an expanding
population.
	   To ensure an adequate and reliable supply of treated water, it
may be necessary to have a self-financing water resources
development policy rather than rely on dwindling tax revenue.
	   Efficient allocation will equate the price of a unit of water
with the extra cost incurred in producing it. In the economist's
jargon, marginal cost must be equated with marginal revenue. If
marginal revenue is less than marginal cost then the Government
will have to subsidise water supply and we may run into problems
again if tax revenues fall below expectations.
	   However, in a caring society this type of economic calculation
may not be acceptable. The poor may not be perceived as able to pay
as much as is needed to ensure predictable supply of treated water.
To safeguard their needs, a ``lifeline'' rate can be introduced.
	   What can be done is to estimate the minimum consumption of a
family of five or six - the ``lifeline'' requirement. A low rate,
even a subsidised one can be charged for this minimum essential.
	   However, consumption beyond the lifeline requirement may be
heavily taxed on a steep tariff structure. This way those who waste
treated water or use it for non-essential purposes are heavily
penalised and made to subsidise the consumption of the poor. This
tariff structure can be designed to recover all the costs of
developing water resources and at the same time generate sufficient
revenue to promote sustainable development.
	   Such a tariff structure will also provide incentives to conserve
because it will become more and more expensive to waste treated
water. Thus, there may not be a need to build more dams, reservoirs
and treatment plants.
	   This will not only preserve the environment from depletion and
degradation but also save the taxpayers' money.
	   Maybe it is time to think of treated water as a scarce commodity
having attributes that are desired and valued and that are
necessary to develop a healthy population. It is also time to
discard the old view that treated water is free, cheap, in abundant
supply and can be wasted.
	   It is also time to manage it as a scarce commodity and to price
it according to how much people are ``willing to pay''. A good time
to evaluate the population's ``willingness to pay'' is when there
is a crisis.
	   In a number of countries where surveys have been done, the
people's estimate of their own ``willingness to pay'' for treated
water has been much higher than the politicians'. It is also time
to get the community actively involved in planning and designing
its treated water supply requirements to ensure that the crisis
does not recur.
	   (The writer is a professor at the Faculty of Business,
Universiti Malaya) 
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT
TIMES all rights reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
