<SLUG> BC-Zimbabwe-Ex-President on Trial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former Zimbabwe president goes on trial on sex charges 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ Former President Canaan Sodindo Banana
went on trial Monday on two charges of sodomy, three charges of
attempted sodomy and six of indecent assault.
	   Prosecutor Augustine Chigumira claimed Banana repeatedly lured
soldiers, aides and security men to his quarters for sex, and had
them punished if they rejected his overtures.
	   Banana, 62, an ordained Methodist minister and ceremonial head
of state from 1980-1988, pleaded not guilty.
	   Wearing a green ``Mao'' suit he adopted in his heyday as a
radical black liberation theologian, Banana arrived at the High
Court in a chauffeur-driven purple Mercedes Benz limousine with his
wife Janet.
	   Carrying a walking stick painted with the Zimbabwean national
colors of red, green, black and gold, Banana smiled for cameramen
and took his place impassively in the dock.
	   The case poses political embarrassment to his successor and
associate, President Robert Mugabe. Before the scandal broke last
year, Mugabe said gays are ``lower than pigs or dogs'' and should
have ``no rights at all'' in Zimbabwe.
	   The prosecution claims top political figures and military
commanders covered up Banana's homosexual indiscretions.
	   Vice President Simon Muzenda and Justice Minister Emmerson
Mnangagwa are expected to testify.
	   Defense attorney Chris Andersen asserted that any sexual
intimacy took place with consent.
	   But the prosecutor said the opposite occurred. He said one young
guard, ordered to escort Banana on a tour of the grounds of the
presidential residence, threw the president into the swimming pool
to escape his advances.
	   Eleven people will be alleging at the trial they were victims of
Banana's advances, court officials said.
	   (mh-aos)
</TEXT>
