<BODY>
<SLUG> AFTER-THE-TESTS... sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANGLADESH
</HEADLINE>
After the tests..., THE INDEPENDENT  
   xfdws AFTER-THE-TESTS... sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   Now that both India and Pakistan have emerged as nations with
demonstrable nuclear capability, the task before the international
community is to bring them back to the path of sanity. India's five
tests and Pakistan's six in defiance of the universal call for
exercising restraint have turned the region into a fertile ground
for using the weapons of mass destruction, which can only mean
incalculable misfortune for their impoverished people.
	   So the reality is that the world will have to live with two more
countries having the ability to mop up millions in a few minutes if
they ever decide on doing so. That alone should suffice to remove
all doubts that anyone might still have regarding the need for
preventing the proliferation of nuclear weapons. But when the cloud
is already looming large on the horizon, the only way to avert a
major disaster is to defuse tension. Both India and Pakistan should
be persuaded to sign the CTBT which should help eliminate the
possibility of a nuclear conflict and prevent further advancement
of the two countries' weapons programmes
	   That might sound like setting too modest and limited an
objective; but as things stand now, it is difficult to see how else
the threat of a nuclear conflagration can be dealt with. The Indian
argument that the CTBT is discriminatory in the sense that it does
not cut both ways has its point, since it can stop only horizontal
expansion of the nuclear armoury, giving the countries already in
possession of nuclear arms an undue advantage. If a nuclear-free
world is what we are striving for, the rules should apply equally
to all .Then come the punitive sanctions already imposed by the
United States and Japan. These will, of course, hit the economies
of India and Pakistan rather hard. And the poor people will have to
bear the brunt of it all.
	   True, the donor countries have few options, but ordinary people
should not be made to pay a high price for the decisions made by
their governments. The stirred up popular sentiments are by no
means an indication that people have lost faith in peace, rather
the celebrations in India and Pakistan following the nuclear tests
only showed that plebeians, blinded by gut patriotism, were indeed
not capable of judging everything critically.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
