w2797  wstm-
r w     DEPLETED-FISH-RESOURCEsk     06-01 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> DEPLETED-FISH-RESOURCE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANGLADESH
</HEADLINE>
Depleted fish resource, THE INDEPENDENT  
   xfdws DEPLETED-FISH-RESOURCE sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   A number of reports published in newspapers coming from various
coastal districts of Bangladesh suggest that our fishermen living
off the sea are experiencing a unique situation of elusive catches.
The coastal waters appear to have been emptied of fish
population.Many thousands of fishing boats and trawlers are
returning empty from the sea after days spent on the waves.
Trawlers fishing in deep sea waters are also complaining that
catches are becoming alarmingly rare.
	   Loss of living spells disaster for lakhs of idle
fishermen.Coastal sea-beds and estuaries provide breeding grounds
for much of the fish population of the Bay. According to reports,
one of the major causes for the vanishing trend of mature fish
catches is the irresponsible netting of fish fry for culture
fishery all along the coast-line. Inadmissible types of nets are
being used for rogue fishing, and fish fry is being caught by
mosquito nets on a massive scale, irreparably impeding the growth
of mature fish population. What is more regrettable is that the
crude methods of catching fish fry for culture is wasteful to the
extent of 80 per cent of the fry being spoilt in the process.
	   The demand for fry could be easily met by adequate hatcheries
that could ensure efficient and adequate supply for the culture
fisheries, if properly set up in appropriate places. Appropriate
management of the economy and environment of our coastal land and
waters in the long belt from Teknaf to Dublar Char, that is capable
of providing among other opportunities a valuable resources of
extensive capture fishing, is a must for our sustainable
development.
	   Besides pollution from sea-lane traffic abuses, it is
irresponsible depletion of immature fish stock and fry that poses a
major threat to the coastal economy. The authorities ought to take
special care to implement laws about breeding season bans on
sea-fishing, to penalise harmful netting practices, and to ban
commercial catching of fry altogether, in addition to stricter
implementation of pollution controls along and off the coast.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
