<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Survey </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government survey shows most people worried about jobs 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) - Most Hong Kong people listed unemployment as
one of their main concerns, a government survey said Monday.
	   The survey also showed that only 44 percent of the 1,553
respondents said they were satifised with Hong Kong's present
situtation, the lowest figure ever recorded since the government
began conducting opinion polls in 1983.
	   It said labor-related issues were the main preoccupation of 54
percent of the people interviewed over the telephone in the poll.
	   Housing, which used to be the main concern, was mentioned by
only 30 percent of the people in the latest survey.
	   The poll, which was conducted last month, did not give any
margin of error.
	   On Friday, the government announced that the economy contracted
by 2 percent in the first quarter, the first contraction in almost
13 years. Unemployment is at a 14-year high of 3.9 percent. 	   
</TEXT>
