w2801  wstm-
r w     SUPERMARKETS-GET-SPAREDs     06-01 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> SUPERMARKETS-GET-SPARED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG
</HEADLINE>
Supermarkets get spared, HONGKONG STANDARD  
   xfdws SUPERMARKETS-GET-SPARED sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE supermarket business remains a bright spot in an otherwise
gloomy retail market.
	   Sales continue to clock positive growth even as the economy
shrinks. After all, there are essentials in life.
	   Although the Hong Kong economy has registered negative growth _
the first time in 13 years _ neither of Hong Kong's two biggest
supermarket chains, Park 'N Shop and Wellcome, are about to scrap
plans to open more big stores this year.
	   The basic cause of the first-quarter slump has been less
consumer spending, which accounts for nearly 60 per cent of Hong
Kong's gross domestic product.
	   Despite the downturn, Park 'N Shop managing director Logan
Taylor believes this is the time for investment in the future.
	   The chain, he said, was opening five more ``Super Stores'' this
year as part of an expansion program that would see the present
chain of 173 stores expanding to 180.
	   Rival Wellcome is similarly on a course of expansion. Marketing
manager Lewis McMullen said the firm would open 10 more stores this
year.
	   Wellcome currently has 120 stores and employs 5,000. More staff
would be needed for the expansion, he said.
	   Economic gloom had no direct negative impact on business growth,
he said. Indeed, he added, because the prices of the company's
products were already very low, it was a good time for increasing
market share.
	   Also, the economic slump has brought massive cost reductions in
terms of rents.
	   Retail analyst Debbie Lau said both supermarkets were expanding
to take advantage of low rents that have significantly reduced
operating costs.
	   The retail sector slump has meant rents plunging up to 30 per
cent in prime locations.
	   Yet rents continued to account for a huge chunk of Park 'N Shop
operating cost, Mr Taylor said.
	   Benefits of lower rents varied from place to place, he said.
	   The super-store trend, Mr Taylor said, was to meet the demand
for one-stop shopping. The range of products offered in a Super
Store would range from daily grocery needs to wet-market features
with seafood and freshwater fish.
	   The new stores were long-term investments that promised solid
returns, according to Miss Lau.
	   The supermarket sector was more stable than other retail
sectors. She noted that while other businesses were slumping,
supermarkets had seen constant sales growth of 7 per cent to 8 per
cent in recent years.
	   ``We anticipate, for instance, that Wellcome supermarket will
see a 7.6-per-cent sales growth in the next two years despite the
downturn,'' Ms Lau said.
	   And the Asian financial crisis has had only a minimal effect on
the supermarket sector. ``After the regional turmoil, the
supermarket sector is more competitive than other retail sectors,
such as fashion,'' Mr Taylor said.
	   ``The crisis had less of an effect on food retailers than other
retailers, but it has changed the consumption habits of grocery
buyers.'' Shoppers were now focusing more on basic commodities
rather than on luxury or snack foods, Mr Taylor said.
	   And the slowdown has meant people are dining out less.
	   The Super Store approach was the way of the future for Park 'N
Shop, as Mr Taylor saw it.
	   By the end of this year, 25 per cent of sales revenue would be
generated by Super Stores, he said.
	   ``We will open one store in Lam Tin's Sceneway Plaza with a size
of 30,000 square feet, a 35,000-sq-ft store in Festival Walk,
Kowloon Tong, and a 30,000-sq-ft store in the former Wing On store
basement in the Hopewell Centre.'' Opening a 25,000-sq-ft store
would mean an investment of $15 million to $20 million, Mr Taylor
said. And total investment for the current expansion plan would
amount to about $75 million.
	   Profit margins at super stores were lower than at at regular
supermarkets, Mr Taylor added, because of the extensive range of
products, but super stores produced bigger turnover and economies
of scale.
	   Park 'N Shop is also set to undergo an image overhaul with the
arrival of a new company logo.
	   The logo change cost several million dollars, Mr Taylor said,
and it's expected to cover all branded lines within two years.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
