w2802  wstm-
r w     EL-NINO'S-DROUGHTSsked     06-01 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> EL-NINO'S-DROUGHTS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANGLADESH
</HEADLINE>
El Nino's droughts, THE INDEPENDENT  
   xfdws EL-NINO'S-DROUGHTS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   El Nino, the warm ocean current that triggers extreme changes in
weather, is bringing about world-wide droughts that are a worry to
farmers and the general consumer. Latest research reveals El Nino
has been a regular feature of the past, occurring in periodic
cycles.
	   This particular El Nino is so turbulent probably for the global
warming caused by the hole in the ozone layer. Since last year due
to El Nino's influence a drought has been raging in Indonesia.
Man-made fires to clear forests went out of hand with awesome
conflagrations. Numerous precious flora and fauna have perished and
are still perishing. Some, like Borneo's orangutans, survived the
fire to die of starvation, lacking food because of the drought and
the fire.
	   Smoke hung in a haze for months over the region from Singapore
to Borneo, forcing motor vehicles in even teeming metropolitan
cities to use headlights to grope through low visibility. A similar
disaster is befalling the region this year too. And now Mexico,
which has not seen a rain cloud for months, is in the grip of a
fire whose smoke is reaching out in a haze from Houston to Denver
in the USA.
	   The El Nino fallout in Mexico itself is of similar nature: for
instance, millions of Monarch butterflies, who regularly migrate to
Mexico in the winter, are in danger of being wiped out. In
Bangladesh there is the likely onslaught of El Nino on the coming
Aman crop. What is needed in all these countries is regional and
global cooperation for timely weather forecasts alongside disaster
management measures in accordance with the magnitude of the
calamity.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:EL-NINO'S-DROUGHTS sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
