<HEADER>
w2806  wstm-
r w     IN-WAR-OR-INVESTINGsked     06-01 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> IN-WAR-OR-INVESTING sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG
</HEADLINE>
Whether in war or investing, it sure pays to know yourself, HONGKONG STANDARD  
   xfdws IN-WAR-OR-INVESTING sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   LAST week, I discussed the different factors that affect risk
tolerance and profiled the characteristics of an aggressive
investor.
	   This time, we'll look at the three other investment
personalities: dynamic, moderate and conservative, and how they
approach investment risk.
	   Dynamic Jason Won is a 32-year-old bachelor with a monthly
income of $40,000 who lives with his parents in a 700 sq-ft flat in
Tai Koo Shing. Jason is one of the lucky people who can live
comfortably with his parents.
	   But Jason is well aware of the need to save for his future.
Because he is young, affluent and has virtually no financial
responsibilities, he could probably be categorised as a dynamic
investor who would select high-to-moderate risk investments with
the potential for high return over the long term.
	   This type of investors tends to favour a mix of investments that
offers different risk levels and returns.
	   They buy stocks in emerging markets such as South America and
Southeast Asia, and stocks in developed markets such as the United
States and Europe.
	   They usually have invested in individual stocks and mutual funds
and are knowledgeable about financial markets.
	   Moderate David So is a 39-year-old restaurant general manager
with a monthly income of $30,000. He has just paid off his mortgage
on a 650 sq-ft apartment in Lam Tin, Kowloon, where he lives with
his wife and their two children, aged 10 and five. To supplement
his income, David occasionally works part-time as a taxi driver.
	   Now nearing middle age. David is well aware of the need to save
for retirement. As the family's sole breadwinner, he probably isn't
keen on taking big risk.
	   Thus, he could be categorised as a moderate investor who would
adopt a middle-of-the-road strategy that will protect him but not
make him wealthy.
	   He categorises his investments into short term-high risk and
long term-low risk. He accepts moderate changes in the value of his
investments and takes calculated risk.
	   People like David prefer a balanced mix of investments that
includes blue-chip stocks, bonds and mutual funds.
	   These investments generally provide a moderate return over the
long term, and David likes the sense of security and stability his
investments bring.
	   Conservative James Chan is a 47-year-old supermarket manager
with a monthly income of $35,000. He owns a 450 sq-flat in Tai Po,
in the New Territories, which he bought more than 20 years ago.
Recently widowed, James has three teenage children, aged 13, 14 and
16, to support.
	   Because of his age, his moderate income and financial
responsibilities for his children, James should adopt a
conservative, or risk averse, approach to investing.
	   His savings should be put into low-risk but safe investments.
	   But James is by nature a risk taker and a gambler. He bets on
horses and regularly visits casinos in Macau. When he invests, he
buys highly speculative stocks such as little-known mainland
industrial stocks and Indonesian mining and energy shares.
	   James made money during the Hong Kong stock market bull run of
1993, but lately he has been hurt by the market downturn.
	   It is people like James who especially need the discipline of a
provident fund scheme.
	   I hope he will select one that will provide solid management to
help him save for his retirement because he'll probably need it.
	   Now that we've looked at the four types of investment
personalities, maybe you can decide your type.
	   There is a Chinese saying: ``Know yourself and your enemy and
you will win every battle.'' And knowing your investment
personality will help you in your retirement plan. As with most
things, you need to plan ahead to get ahead and achieve the results
you want.
	   In retirement planning, you need to ask yourself: ``How much do
I need to retire comfortably?'' That depends on a lot of factors _
current salary, lifestyle, how many working years you have before
retirement, assets, the rate of your investment return, your
philosophy toward risk. We'll start talking about these next week.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
