w2810  wstm-
r w     POLICY-OF-HELPINGsked     06-01 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> POLICY-OF-HELPING sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Policy of helping Bumiputeras to continue, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws POLICY-OF-HELPING sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   BANGI, Sun. - The Government will continue the policy of
intervention in market forces to help Bumiputera businessmen,
Entrepreneur Development Minister Datuk Mustapa Mohamed said today.
	   He said the policy of intervention by providing funds and
awarding licences and contracts to Bumiputera entrepreneurs would
be continued to ensure fair distribution of wealth.
	   The policy was necessary as Bumiputeras were still handicapped
in business and would be marginalised if left to market forces, he
told reporters after launching the Kelab Wawasan Melayu Malaysia.
	   Also present at the launch were pro-tem club president Datuk
Shukor Raja Idris, deputy president Datin Faridah Mohd Said and
about 200 members.
	   Mustapa said in the 1960s and 1970s, such interventions were
necessary as Malays were not able to compete with non-Malays due to
low income and lack of a level playing field.
	   In education, he said, similar interventions had caused
Bumiputeras to be on par with other races, but the 30 per cent
share equity for Bumiputeras in business had yet to be achieved.
	   On business opportunities in the face of the negative growth of
1.8 per cent announced by by Bank Negara for the first quarter of
this year, Mustapa said this was only short-term.
	   He said the Government was consolidating the national economy
and was confident it would recover in the long term.
	   The long-term prospects for recovery were good and entrepreneurs
should not be discouraged by the figures, added Mustapa.
	   Shukor, who is group executive chairman of Warga Mantap Group,
said the club, with an estimated membership of 3,000 nationwide,
would act as a voice for entrepreneurs in small- and medium-sized
businesses.
	   He said the club would assist Malay entrepreneurs aged 18 and
above deal with problems in their businesses brought about by the
economic slowdown.
	   A businessman based in Australia, Shukor said he decided to
return home to invest in Malaysia and expressed confidence the
economy would recover.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
