<HEADER>
w2813  wstm-
r w     NUCLEAR-ONE-UPMANSHIPske     06-01 1679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> NUCLEAR-ONE-UPMANSHIP sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANGLADESH
</HEADLINE>
Nuclear one-upmanship: Spectre of a sub-continental Armageddon?, THE INDEPENDENT  
   xfdws NUCLEAR-ONE-UPMANSHIP sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   As part of the race for nuclear superiority in the
sub-continent, Pakistan detonated a total of six nuclear devices on
Thursday and Saturday - five on Thursday. BBC television showed
pictures of excited people eating sweetmeat on the streets of
Pakistani towns and villages and celebrating as Nawaz Sharif
addressed the nation on Thursday saying: ``We have settled the
account of the nuclear blasts by India. Today we have successfully
carried out five tests.'' He went on to add that Pakistan had to
carry out the nuclear tests because the world community had ``...
not done anything effective to make India realise its mistake.''
	   Predictably enough Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee
said that these tests by Pakistan had vindicated' India's decision
to test its nuclear devices. Immediately after Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif's announcements, the Pakistani President announced a State
of Emergency suspending the Pakistani Constitution. All these chain
of events leading from the testing of Pakistan's missile Ghauri,
India's nuclear tests, and now Pakistan's nuclear tests, with its
declaration of emergency points definitely to a situation of
belligerent confrontation between India and Pakistan.
	   In fact Saturday's test by Pakistan came as an anti-climax, with
Pakistan claiming all these to be part of a complete series
comprising six detonations.Both Nawaz Sharif, on his election in
February '97, and Atal Behari Vajpayee on becoming the Prime
Minister of India in March, had stressed the importance of
normalising relations between the two countries. In fact, when
Sharif assumed Prime Ministership, it was seen that the voters were
clearly in favour of better relations between the two countries and
that they wanted to see India and Pakistan as trading partners
rather than warring neighbours. In Pakistan 54% of the country's
voters were below 40, and animosity towards India and memories of
the partition are a matter of the history books to them in this age
of liberalisation.
	   However both Indian and Pakistani citizens were seen rejoicing
after the tests, irrespective of age. The latest situation has
raised concerns in the SAARC countries and the rest of Asia
including China. President Jiang Zemin of China is supposed to have
written to Nawaz Sharif to refrain from nuclear tests. Indian tests
have been on a circumspect note, but now the news that the
Pakistani missile Ghauri would be deployed with nuclear warheads
makes that country a step ahead in the chessboard moves of
belligerence. Can the two countries be now prevailed upon not to
deploy these weapons?
	   Bangladesh has forcefully stated its commitment to the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, and its belief that the security of
the region lies in its economic strength rather than military
power, and now nuclear power. Bangladesh and the other SAARC
countries now have the responsibilities to bring back India and
Pakistan from the brink of war, whether conventional or nuclear,
for the sake of real economic and social development in the region.
The impending SAARC summit in Colombo-advanced by about ten
days-may well serve as an important forum for a positive defusing
of the situation.
	   On the other hand if the efforts of the SAARC leaders cannot
modify the stance taken by India and Pakistan, this will be a very
dangerous situation spelling future complications in the region as
well as for the alliance. In case of an actual war between India
and Pakistan the physical well being of Bangladesh and the
remaining SAARC nations will be, needless to say, greatly
endangered. Reference is always made in international situations of
this seriousness and urgency, to the need of the United States to
exercise leadership in the world community, to assume its
leadership role. For decades the Indian sub-continent had been on
the back burner of America's external concerns.
	   Now President Bill has turned the heat up, by his stern approach
to sanctions against both India and Pakistan. The tense situation
now because of the nuclear tests and that in Kashmir are now
definitely seen as urgent problems, and a time for activism in
South Asia. Clinton had also in the past referred to the Kashmir
problem between the two countries in his UN speech in September
1993, when he said: ``Bloody ethnic, religious and civil wars
raging from Angola to the Caucasus to Kashmir.'' However both
Indians and Pakistanis have slated the US attitudes as being
favourable to the opposing side. The attention of the largest and
the militarily most dominant of the former imperial powers,
naturally arouses the fears of some imperial residuum. In 1994,
after the testing of India's missile Prithvi, Bill Clinton sent his
diplomatic trouble-shooter, deputy secretary of state Strobe Talbot
to broker deals that could begin to curb the nuclear arms race in
the sub-continent.
	   At that time neither the Pakistanis, nor the Indians bought
Talbot's line completely. But both responded in a sufficiently
positive manner for the American to say before leaving for the US
from Islamabad: ``Much remains to be done on non-proliferation, but
much was accomplished.'' Pakistan was then amenable to the US
proposals on the non-proliferation conference and the
non-deployment of the missiles. But while Islamabad seemed
agreeable to a cap on production of missile material, it would not
concede on-site inspections of its nuclear facilities.
	   As for India, it did not respond immediately on the missile
deployment issue, but Indian officials agreed in private to the
non-proliferation talks. In only four years since April 1994, the
situation has moved beyond the ambit of that bid of the US to
defuse Indo-Pakistani nuclear tensions. In the case of India
military decisions such as the present one of exploding nuclear
devices is mainly in the hands of its political leadership. In
Pakistan the military and the establishment has also an important
say besides the politicians, and add to that the elements of it
being the smaller country also wrestling with the contentious bone
of Kashmir, and the US and the other developed countries may find
it more difficult to convince Pakistan than India in turning back
from the preparations and exercises of a nuclear confrontation.
	   Analysts have also indicated an interesting angle inasmuch as
the development of the nuclear bomb by Pakistan maybe the
indications of a future Islamic' bomb which may present a threat to
Israel. The UN, while deploring the tests by both India and
Pakistan have offered personal mediation through Kofi Annan.
Britain, the current chairman of G-8 has called an emergency
meeting of the group, and included-significantly enough-China as a
special guest in the deliberations on the nuclear scenario in the
sub-continent. It is also time that both the remaining SAARC
countries, possibly at the behest of Bangladesh, and the
Non-Aligned Movement countries take emergency steps.
	   The power of the military to assert need and acquire the
requisite financial support is evident in a great measure in the
legislative branches of both these countries. There, subject to
minor symbolic changes, the military budget is voted automatically,
and in recent years with annual increases. It is not even thought
necessary that some military needs-intelligence operations,
sophisticated nuclear weapons-be known to the legislative body as a
whole and thus to the public at large. More important, perhaps, and
particularly in the present case, is the reassuring manifestation
of patriotism in supporting the armed forces. The authority of the
military in establishing national military priorities has thus
become complete. This is a circumstance that has to be conceded and
considered in any approach towards a negotiated cessation of
hostilities and the arms race.
	   Furthermore the State of Emergency in Pakistan will preclude any
overt domestic discussion and debate about this nuclear war
preparations. Whether India will follow suit in like manner is yet
to be seen. However Vajpayee has again reiterated his offer to hold
talks with Sharif on all issues including nuclear arms and Kashmir.
Above all this, on the domestic scene in both the countries, there
were and there remain the insistent claims of the poor and the
impoverished, in the cities and the villages. Whatever the external
threats, there was and there is still the danger of an abrupt and
violent challenge to domestic tranquillity if military needs
continue to control the resources that, if used for basic income
support, job creation, housing, education, health and social care,
would ease the crisis within the countries.
	   It has been said about the Soviet Union that it was impoverished
precisely because it concentrated its resources on preparing for a
war that would never be fought. If they had been used on public
welfare, then the country may have shown the world the superiority
of its socialist way of life. A couple of years back, Sherbaz
Mazari commented on Zulfiquar Ali Bhutto: ``He was more anti-Indian
than pro-poor.'' Now we have to see whether Sharif and Vajpayee are
more anti-each other, or pro-poor in their respective countries.
	   
</TEXT>
