<BODY>
<SLUG> RECEIVE-WARM-WELCOME sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG
</HEADLINE>
Expatriates still receive warm welcome in Britain, HONGKONG STANDARD  
   xfdws RECEIVE-WARM-WELCOME sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   BRITAIN'S Labour Party, when in opposition, was very hostile
towards foreign domiciliaries. Some of the often-quoted policy
documents came from the desk of Gordon Brown, now Chancellor of the
Exchequer. It was not surprising, then that many commentators were
anticipating an all-out assault on the foreign-domiciled community
in the spring Budget.
	   However, this did not materialise.
	   Even the much publicised ``anti-Robinson'' provisions appear to
leave the door open for non-domiciled beneficiaries of offshore
trusts. For the time being at least it seems as though the UK
government still wishes to lay out the ``welcome'' mat for
expatriates into the UK.
	   It is a widely-held view that tax proposals which target
foreigners in the UK are likely to be counter-productive both for
the UK economy and for the yield to the UK Exchequer.
	   There are many wealthy individuals claiming foreign domicile
with substantial private means who live in the UK through choice,
and could just as easily reside elsewhere.
	   Few of them pay significant UK taxes, unless they are poorly
advised or wish to do so, and few would remain in the UK to suffer
under an onerous tax regime.
	   The UK is a popular base for many reasons: but the idea that it
is such an attractive place that large scale tax increases would
not discourage those of foreign domicile and independent means, may
be seriously misconceived.
	   Thus a claim to foreign domicile remains a notable asset for an
individual residing in the UK. Income from foreign sources need
suffer no tax provided proper planning takes place before
importation.
	   This is economically sensible, because to discourage importation
of cash through taxation would probably be counter-productive.
Likewise, capital gains tax may, in most cases, still be avoided
and inheritance tax remains effectively optional for
non-domiciliaries.
	   There are likely to be some cases in which non-domiciliaries
will wish to pay these ``optional taxes'' if, by virtue of UK
residence and our comprehensive network of double taxation
treaties, more severe liabilities may be avoided elsewhere in the
world.
	   One area which did not come off so well is the foreign earnings
deduction, which, in the name of counter avoidance, was abolished.
	   Many representations have been made to the Treasury in respect
of this abolition, and the Inland Revenue has issued a stock draft
response. Broadly it states that the foreign earnings deduction was
introduced to create employment by boosting exports yet ``in
practice, buyers travelling abroad to source for import . . .
benefited to the same extent _ but to the opposite effect''.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
