w2817  wstm-
r i     BC-Russia-Abkhazia     06-01 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Abkhazia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Abkhazia criticized Georgian government, asserts independence 
</HEADLINE>
By ANNA DOLGOV
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The government of separatist Abkhazia lashed out
at Georgian leaders Monday, blaming them for recent clashes in the
Black Sea region and insisting that Abkhazia is independent.
	   Georgian and Abkhazian representatives held talks in Moscow
about arranging a meeting between their leaders.
	   But Abkhazian envoy Anri Dzhergenia said such a meeting would
probably not lead to a breakthrough, because Georgia is ``not
ready'' to accept Abkhazia's sovereignty and the breakaway province
would not settle for anything less.
	   Abkhazia declared independence in 1992, and separatists drove
out Georgian troops after 13 months of fighting. Violence has
broken out sporadically since then, despite the presence of Russian
peacekeepers. At least 100 people died in the latest fighting that
ended last week.
	   ``We have determined our status, and we are not going to discuss
it with anybody,'' Dzhergenia told reporters.
	   ``We are an independent state,'' he said. ``We don't need
Georgia's recognition ... but life for our people will get easier
when Georgia acknowledges our independence.''
	   Georgia has offered Abkhazia broad autonomy, but Abkhazia
insists it is an independent nation. No other country recognizes
its independence.
	   ``What inspires us is that until the 1960s, many African nations
were in the same situation,'' Dzhergenia said. ``The drive toward
the equality of nations cannot be stopped.''
	   Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze praised the Abkhazian
leadership for not allowing the conflict escalate into a full-scale
war.
	   ``The fact that the clashes in the Ghali region did not grow
into a major war is partly the achievement of the Abkhazians,''
Shevardnadze said in his weekly radio address Monday.
	   But while Shevardnadze blamed the recent fighting on ``certain
forces that want to destabilize the situation,'' Abkhazia said that
the Georgian government was at fault for years of simmering
violence, and for the recent outbreak.
	   ``Among the Georgian leadership _ despite repeated public
statements on the adherence to a peaceful settlement with Abkhazia
_ the disposition toward the use of force is rather strong,''
Dzhergenia said.
	   Dzhergenia also accused Georgia of financing nationalist
guerrilla groups, who oppose Abkhazia's secession and are blamed
for several clashes in the region. More than 150 attacks have been
carried out in the province since a 1993 truce, he said.
	   (ad/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
