<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 10:27:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2822  wstm-
r w     THE-HEALTH-SECTORsked     06-01 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> THE-HEALTH-SECTOR sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANGLADESH
</HEADLINE>
The health sector realities, THE INDEPENDENT  
   xfdws THE-HEALTH-SECTOR sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   One of the basic needs of any society is its health care
facilities. This fundamental sector remains to be elusive to the
policy planners in Bangladesh. We are born in poverty, live in
poverty and die there. We have no dearth of policies and their
proper implementation is not beyond anybody's guess. There is no
need of any foreign experts to dig out the lacunas in this sector
nor do we need their valuable advice to formulate and ensure the
appropriate implementation of such a policy.
	   Since independence, no comprehensive national health policy has
been formulated by any of the successive governments. Sources say,
a national policy in this thrust sector is on the anvil by the
present government.
	   The main focus of the health programmes has been on the
provision of primary health care services which has been recognised
as a key approach to attain health for all by the year 2000 AD.The
impediments which contributed to the non-fulfilment of the health
sector development are inefficient project management service,
delay in project management and implementation, frequent changes of
project directors, inadequate inter-project linkages, poor
institutional coordination and support within the sector, lack of
monitoring services, resource constraints etc.Proper medical
facilities do not reach the rural population; even the urban poor
and lower income groups are devoid of any significant medicare
although we have Union Health and Family Welfare Centres, Thana
Health Complexes in majority of the Thanas and hospitals at
district level.
	   In response to the changing health situation of the country,
reforms in health sector particularly in the areas of management
structure, service delivery mechanisms and utilisation of both
public and private sector resources are called for urgently.Will
you believe that there is no echocardiography and exercise
tolerance test machines in Dhaka and Chittagong Medical College
Hospitals? Is it due to negligence of the hospital administration
or paucity of funds? Besides Dhaka, there is only one CT scan
machine in Chittagong, which is also in the private sector. One
physician who had been to UK for a few months told this writer,
what we lack is advanced medical equipment and medicines probably
defending the theory that we have quality physicians in plenty.
	   We have doctors of good quality and its reverse who discharge
their duties to the best of their abilities but unfortunately fail
to satisfy the demands of the millions who look upto them as their
saviours.The medicare facilities in this country are regarded
insufficient and inefficient to the solvent or rich class who
prefer to go abroad to receive better treatment. Most of them
prefer India, Thailand or Singapore. The more solvent ones prefer
Western countries. A simple angiogram is not done skilfully here,
not to speak of a by-pass surgery.
	   Similarly a kidney transplantation is not possible in Bangladesh
for which one has to rush to India. There are other instances in
which the given facilities fail to meet the demands of the
patients. It is estimated that the total amount spent annually by
Bangladeshi patients abroad is a fabulous one which is a huge drain
on the national resources. One way to stop the seeking of foreign
treatment is to strengthen the current services in the country and
to ensure their quality so that the confidence of the citizens in
the country's health services is restored.In recent years, a large
number of private clinics have cropped up in Dhaka and other major
cities.
	   These supplement the government efforts to reach medical
facilities to the people. These clinics being expensive are not
affordable to the lower income groups and the poor segments of the
population. The private health sector is mostly staffed by the
public sector doctors and employees on part-time basis. This is due
to the shortage of medical and health professionals in the country
and to the fact that public sector professionals are allowed to
practise privately.Against this backdrop the government has
recently decided to allow foreign doctors to work in the private
hospitals having 250 beds.
	   This has generated furore among local physicians. Both
Bangladesh Medical Association (BMA) and Bangladesh Private Medical
Practitioners Association (BPMA) have strongly opposed the move to
allow foreign doctors in all disciplines in private hospitals. What
they argue is that in the absence of any proper monitoring system,
who will monitor the activities of foreign doctors? They also
apprehend that low graded doctors of foreign countries who get less
opportunities to perform in their respective countries would be
seeing patients here.
	   This theory is not wholly untrue. We do not mind having the
services of skilled foreign doctors. But chances are widely open
that poor quality doctors will come in their guise. Bangladesh
Medical and Dental Council (BMDC) should adopt stringent measures
in issuing registration to foreign physicians.We welcome this move
of the government that would deter us from going to India,
Singapore, UK and USA. A new vista will be opened in health sector
with technology transfer. One group of physicians of our country
supports foreign investment in this vital sector while the other
opposes it. Let us have no squabbling on this issue.
	   Let foreign doctors come and treat us and foreign investment
flows in resulting in the qualitative improvement in health
sector.It may be concluded by stating that the government may
induce the foreign doctors to give their expert opinion in delicate
cases in public sector hospitals in exchange of nominal fees,
enabling the insolvent section of people to have a glimpse of
modern developments in medical science.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
