<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 10:28:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2823  wstm-
r w     PDX-INFOWORLD-SHOWSsked     06-01 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> PDX-INFOWORLD-SHOWS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
PDX Infoworld shows Web-based solutions, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws PDX-INFOWORLD-SHOWS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   PDX Infoworld Sdn Bhd has come up with two Internet-based
products after investing RM2 million to develop electronic delivery
systems.
	   The products are HomeBank, which the company claimed is the
first Malaysian Web-based banking application, and i-stock, a
Web-based Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) stock quote service.
	   Both products were launched by the Multimedia Super Corridor
(MSC) status company at the Exposisi Multimedia, Telekomunikasi dan
Electronik Kelantan (EMTEK 1998) event in Tumpat last Friday.
	   HomeBank is aimed at corporate customers while the
subscription-based i- stock is for end users, said PDX Infoworld's
executive director Wong Nan Fay.
	   He said the company is currently negotiating with two local
financial institutions which have expressed interest in HomeBank.
	   According to Wong, HomeBank debut's is timely as the local
financial market is becoming increasingly competitive.
	   ``HomeBank extends secure banking conveniences to users from the
comfort of home and this can be used as a long-term competitive
advantage,'' he said in an interview.
	   HomeBank is Internet-ready but existing financial regulatory
framework does not permit Internet banking.
	   ``We are optimistic that this framework will soon be revised,''
Wong said, adding that HomeBank could be deployed in an intranet
fashion as a temporary measure.
	   HomeBank is a client extension to PDX Infoworld's PayStream
Internet bill presentment and payment solution. It is designed to
enable financial institutions to leverage on existing automated
teller machine (ATM) infrastructure to offer Web-based services.
	   ``This translates into significant cost savings for financial
institutions with relatively minor change needed to expand their
electronic banking services,'' Wong claimed.
	   He likened HomeBank's viability to the ATM in the 1970s.
	   ``The ATM has become a necessity in our daily lives but this was
not the case when it was introduced. We see HomeBank taking the
same form and shape as the ATM.''
	   The solution is expected to be priced at RM1 million per
deployment, comprising a hardware and software Web server using the
Microsoft NT or Unix platform and a database such as Microsoft SQL
or Universal Server.
	   Crucial to HomeBank is its ability to receive and transmit
secure data.
	   As such, the product incorporates authentication devices such as
card readers to receive secure data from the user. Since HomeBank
is compliant with Data Encryption Standard (DES), it is able to
accepts DES-encrypted data generated by these devices, Wong said.
	   HomeBank also transmits secure data packets in native ISO 8583
format.
	   ISO 8583 is the international standard for interchange message
specifications in financial transaction card originated messages.
Wong described HomeBank's security level as equivalent to that of a
physical ATM outlet.
	   ``Card reader devices are currently retailing between US$50 to
US$200 per unit,'' he said, adding that banks could encourage users
to generate electronic transactions by providing these devices.
	   The device is connected to a user's personal computer (PC) which
is online with a bank's ATM service via a modem and browser. As
with the use of an ATM, the user identifies himself or herself by
inserting or swiping either a smartcard or magnetic stripe card and
keys the personal identification number (PIN).
	   Once the PIN is authenticated, the account number is displayed
along with up-to-date account statements such as savings accounts
and quite possibly utility services such as telecommunication,
water, electricity in the browser, Wong explained.
	   This would enable users to settle monthly utility bills by
transferring funds from their current accounts to the utility
accounts.
	   ``This is a convenient and secure remote transaction in a
friendly drag- and-drop fashion,'' he said.
	   According to PDX Info-world's research and development (RD)
manager Teh Ah Hock, the development of both HomeBank and i-stock
was done in parallel. ``Both took a team of four and approximately
six months to complete,'' Teh said.
	   HomeBank's core RD was carried out at the PDX Infoworld
laboratory at Technology Park Malaysia (TPM) and at Fudan
University in China. ``On the other hand, i-stock was developed
entirely at TPM,'' Teh said.
	   The browser-base KLSE stock quote service can be viewed at
www.istock.
	   com.my and is now open for subscription at RM90 per month.
	   Wong said the company has appointed Valuenet Sdn Bhd as the
service provider to collect subscriptions.
	   Subscribers will be able to view a five-second delayed KLSE
stock quote.
	   ``The stock quote is almost real-time,'' said Teh who carried
out the testing in Malaysia and China.
	   Among its features are stock searching and sorting, creating a
personal stock portfolio and news.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
