</HEADLINE>
Green In Caracas For Oas Summit, The News  
   xfdws GREEN-IN-CARACAS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   THE NEWS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   Human rights, drug trafficking, corruption and terrorism issues
will be the focus of the 28th General Assembly of the Organization
of American States.
	   The meeting slated to be held in Caracas Monday through
Wednesday will include appearances by representatives from the
Western Hemisphere countries making up the OAS.
	   Representing Mexico will be Foreign Secretary Rosario Green, who
will introduce a motion to change the Inter-American System, the
OAS policy that facilitates greater cooperation among member
countries.
	   Other expected changes from this week's meeting will be seen in
motions to strengthen justice systems in member countries and to
increase cooperation for the development of North and South
America, Spanish news agency EFE reported, citing a statement
released by the Mexican Foreign Relations Secretariat. Member
countries also will work on implementing and passing accords signed
at the Second Summit of the Americas , which took place in
Santiago, in April.
	   At this week's meeting, Mexico also officially will hand over to
OAS General Secretary Cesar Gaviria its ratification of an OAS
motion to halt the manufacture and traffic of illegal firearms,
which is expected to go into effect in about 30 days.
	   
