<SLUG> BC-Russia-Mir, 2nd Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mir computer failure threatens U.S. shuttle launch 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: LEADS with new 7th graf saying the crew wrapped up loading
software into the computer, ADDS photo number.
AP Photos MOSB101,103.
By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ After running smoothly for months, Mir's skittish
central computer was out of order for a third day Monday,
threatening to postpone the Russian space station's last rendezvous
with a U.S. shuttle.
	   U.S. space shuttle Discovery is scheduled to lift off Tuesday
and dock with the station on Friday to pick up astronaut Andrew
Thomas, the seventh and last American to live on the Russian
outpost.
	   But that trip to the Mir is now in doubt since the shuttle can
only dock if the station's computer-controlled steering system
properly aligns it for the docking.
	   ``We hope that the crew will finally resolve the problem later
today,'' said Valery Lyndin, a spokesman for Russian Mission
Control.
	   He said space officials have not yet determined why Mir's
computer broke down on Saturday. Russian cosmonauts Talgat
Musabayev and Nikolai Budarin replaced it with another unit, but
the new unit failed on Sunday when they tried to switch it on.
	   ``They still have a lot of spares to fix the problem,'' Lyndin
told The Associated Press.
	   The ground controllers fully loaded the software into the
computer at around 6 p.m. Moscow time (1400 GMT) Monday and the
crew was expected to try restarting the computer. The station is
currently out of contact with the ground, so their success or
failure won't be known until about 7:30 p.m. (1530 GMT).
	   During a chat _ Picks up 8th graf previous
	   (vi/ls) 	   
