<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 10:36:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2836  wstm-
r w     KOREA-REFORMS-TAKE-HOLDs     06-01 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> KOREA-REFORMS-TAKE-HOLD sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO
</HEADLINE>
Korea Reforms Take Hold, Bring In Capital, The News  
   xfdws KOREA-REFORMS-TAKE-HOLD sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   THE NEWS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   SEOUL --The sweeping economic restructuring taking place in
Korea resulted in new mergers and acquisitions last week.
	   A.F.S., a U.S. power company, acquired power plant operations
Friday from a unit of the Hanwha Group for 874 million dollars.
This was the largest foreign investment in Korea since its currency
plunged, forcing it to seek help from the International Monetary
Fund (IMF).
	   Dongham and Kyongham banks also announced recently that they are
in the final stages of merger talks while the Koran Exchange Bank
(KEB) agreed to sell its stake in Commerzbank of Germany.
	   When completed, the merger of Dongham and Kyonham will be the
first of its kind since the Financial Supervisory Commission (FSC)
announced last month that it is encouraging non-viable banks to
merge with sound ones to avoid closures.
	   KEB's move to sell its 29.8-percent stake for 250 million
dollars to Commerzbank, the third largest bank in Germany, is an
attempt to boost its capital base, reported The Korea Times.
	   ``We agreed to sell our shares to Commerzbank to attract foreign
capital as part of our efforts to recapitalize our bank,'' Hong
Se-Pyo, president of KEB said.
	   All of these moves offer evidence of Korea's need to
recapitalize. Despite the IMF call for raising interest rates,
these measures have done little to encourage domestic savings. Bank
deposits were down 1.5-percent in the first quarter over last year.
Central bank officials link the trend to shrinking household
incomes and the continuing credit crunch in the business sector.
	   Total deposits are the sum of savings deposits, money in trust
and money market funds. To spur bank restructuring, the government
is also considering granting tax benefits to financial institutions
that take over assets and liabilities from troubled banks.
	   Much of the efforts come on the heels of Moody's Investors
Service cutting its credit ratings of five top Japanese banks last
week and putting four others on downgrade review. As a result,
Japan is now preparing the agenda for an emergency session of
parliament to work out new bank reforms to deal with outstanding
debt. Any Japanese reforms would also have a negative effect on
Korea since much of the debt is tied to Korean companies.
	   Despite the IMF call for raising interest rates, these measures
have done little to encourage domestic savings. Bank deposits were
down 1.5-percent in the first quarter over last year. Central bank
officials link the trend to shrinking household incomes and the
continuing credit crunch in the business sector.
	   
</TEXT>
