w2839  wstm-
r i     BC-Russia-Impeachment 1stLd-Writethru   06-01 0331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Impeachment, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian hard-liners to push impeachment motion backing impeachment motion, 212 signatures collected, other details. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with communist leader Zyuganov, three factions also
<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian hard-liners said Monday they will try to
get an impeachment motion against President Boris Yeltsin put on
parliament's agenda during a scheduling session next week.
	   Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov said Yeltsin opponents will
ask members of the agenda-setting Duma Council on June 9 to
formally file the motion and set up a committee to study the
proposal. His comments were reported by the Interfax news agency.
	   The motion was also backed by the Agrarian and People's Power
factions, said Agrarian leader Nikolai Kharitonov. Together, the
three factions have 210 members in the 450-seat State Duma, the
lower house of parliament.
	   Only 150 signatures are required to put an impeachment motion on
the Duma agenda, but 300 signatures are needed to actually initiate
the proceedings.
	   Sergei Reshulsky, who is in charge of organizational issues in
the Communist faction, said 212 signatures have already been
collected, Interfax reported.
	   Impeachment proceedings are long and complex, and it would
likely take months before the motion is actually debated by the
State Duma.
	   Several previous impeachment drives have fizzled, in part
because Russia's Constitution gives the president the upper hand in
confrontations with parliament.
	   Communists and their allies launched the latest impeachment
campaign last month. They have accused Yeltsin of a range of
transgressions, including instigating the Soviet collapse,
launching the botched war in Chechnya and ruining the country's
economy.
	   Their frustrations intensified in April during a long test of
wills with Yeltsin, who threatened to disband the legislature
unless lawmakers approved his candidate for prime minister.
	   (mr/ad/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
