<SLUG> MAN-HELD-AFTER-DAP sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Man held after DAP gathering gets out of hand, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws MAN-HELD-AFTER-DAP sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sun. - Police detained a man when things got out
of hand after DAP supporters were barred from organising a
gathering to show support for Kota Melaka Member of Parliament Lim
Guan Eng, today.
	   The man, whose identity is being withheld, was detained for
allegedly using derogatory words against and pushing Dang Wangi
police chief Senior Assistant Commissioner (II) Zainal Abidin Ali.
	   The man is believed to have acted in that way after police took
away a loudhailer from DAP secretary-general Lim Kit Siang when he
tried to use it to speak to about 150 people who had turned up for
the ``Gathering of Legal Eagles'' at the Federal Hotel.
	   Zainal Abidin had earlier asked Kit Siang to ask those gathered
outside the function room to disperse as they had not heeded
repeated police appeals to do so.
	   When Kit Siang spoke to the crowd using the loudhailer, it burst
out into applause and shouts of support for DAP.
	   About 30 policemen, led by Zainal Abidin, had arrived at the
hotel about 9.30am to disperse the crowd as the gathering was
considered illegal.
	   Speaking to reporters at the scene, Zainal Abidin said police
were forced to disperse the gathering as the organisers did not
possess or apply for a permit to hold such a function.
	   Guan Eng, 37, son of Opposition leader Kit Siang, is facing an
18-month imprisonment for two counts of publishing false news.
	   He has since filed an appeal against the sentence imposed by the
Court of Appeal on April 1.
	   Speaking to reporters after the gathering was dispersed at
10.35am today, Kit Siang called the incident a ``black day for
democracy in Malaysia'' and ``a day of shame for the police''.
	   ``We have held about 40 such gatherings in the country as a show
of support for Guan Eng.
	   ``For the gatherings before this, we did not have to apply for a
permit.
	   ``If the police want to change everything and say we have to
apply for a permit, they should have at least given us ample
notice,'' Kit Siang said.
	   He added the DAP would now apply for a permit to hold the
gathering at a later date.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
