<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Taking good care of Sri Medan's basic amenities, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws TAKING-GOOD-CARE-OF-SRI sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   SRI Medan State Assemblywoman Puan Sri Atkah Abdullah says the
Education Ministry should do more to provide schools with
computers.
	   ``Sometimes when I attend Parent-Teacher Association meetings,
the schools request for computers.
	   ``As a State Assemblywoman, my financial allowances are limited.
I can only give one computer to selected schools,'' said Atkah, who
is also an executive council member of Wanita Umno.
	   She, however, said that one computer per school was not
sufficient.
	   Atkah said she was grateful to the relevant government agencies
which have helped her look into and address the grievances of her
constituents.
	   ``I am very grateful to these agencies. Without them, it would
not have been possible for me to solve the problems of my
constituents,'' said the bespectacled wakil rakyat.
	   The Sri Medan constituency covers areas bordering Pekan Yong
Peng to Chaaah towards Labis and Parit Mustafa at the west coast.
	   She said the perennial problem faced by her constituents were
floods as the area was low lying.
	   A former teacher who retired as a district education supervisor
in 1989, Atkah can now confidently claim that most areas were now
free of floods.
	   ``Under the Kumpulan Prasarana Rakyat Johor and Johor Barat
projects, the flood problem has been overcome,'' she said, adding
that both projects were initiated by the State Government.
	   She said now the people want tarred roads in the villages. There
were still some untarred stretches in the hinterland.
	   ``We hope to do that soon,'' she said, adding that these
villages had other basic amenities such as water and electricity
supply.
	   Atkah said as the majority of her constituents were farmers and
smallholders, she, with the assistance of the relevant government
agencies, encouraged womenfolk to actively participate in cottage
industries to help supplement their income.
	   ``This is the best way to increase their income given the
present circumstances. They can produce temperek, keropok pisang,
tapioca fries and much more.
	   ``Their products can also be easily transported for sale
elsewhere as there is an excellent road network linking Sri Medan
to other major towns,'' said Atkah.
	   Atkah said although Sri Medan was not as developed compared to
its neighbours, the constituency has sufficent schools and health
facilities.
	   ``We will be building a new market and a multi-purpose hall in
Parit Sulong. We have received allocations both from the Federal
and State authorities and hope that work can commence soon,'' she
said.
	   Constituents who wish to meet her can call her at her home in
Batu Pahat.
	   
