<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA
</HEADLINE>
Look how cute this baby is..., JAKARTA POST  
   xfdws LOOK-HOW-CUTE-THIS-BABY sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 31, 1998
   JAKARTA POST
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   Bowo must be brilliant. Yes, he is. Just two days prior to his
graduation from Narish Banking Academy and a foreign bank offered
him an apprenticeship in management.
	   Damn, didn't we all dream of that happening to ourselves? Of
course, it is all due to his buddy; the guy's father is the
director of human resources. Hey, Bowo, tell your friend to tell
all his friends, and they should tell all their friends. Prita was
so excited.
	   Prita and Bowo then pledged that they would get married within
two years. Hey, they usually put the guy first ... And you people,
get your handkerchiefs ready. To be exact, it would fall exactly
when Bowo finished his apprenticeship at the Bank of Ougabouga.
	   Both of their parents agreed that their children would cement
their four-year relationship with a marriage in two years. Really?
Some Romeos can date more than 48 women in that time, you know.
	   ``You'll both wear engagement rings next year. But for now,
Prita will continue with her studies, and you'll continue with your
promising job.'' Prita's father said to the two lovers. Dear
ol'Daddy Cool.
	   Lovers? Yes. It was not uncommon for them to watch movies
together. The hell with the movies, they were playing with their
noses. Dinner by candlelight in a restaurant? Yes, but not that
often. Most of the time they helped each other in finishing a big
tin of cookies together, lip to lip. ``Ouch!'' How dare they do
that to that poor cookie tin. No wonder they threw the tin away.
Sweet Jesus! Poor tin, why were you there when they were alone
together? If only you had the power of Rambo.
	   Hey, you're mean not to warn them of the consequences. Shame on
you!
	   ``What are we going to do Bowo? I can feel it kicking.''
	   Bowo looked up at the gigantic chandelier. It was worth looking
at. It floated like an upside-down mushroom, and it shone brightly,
making the night envious. No, don't worry night sky, the chandelier
is afraid of you. See, it hides in the dome shape of that Gatsby
restaurant. See?
	   ``Oh God, I think its time for us to see Dr. Syamsul.''
	   God, can you believe it? He said God!
	   Oh look! I think the fairy agrees. Prita looked at him. She said
something, hold on, hold on, she said something.
	   ``Well, we have no other choice.''
	   Hey, she stared deep into the window. Damn right you have no
choice! What are you thinking about, Mama? Don't look so gloomy,
woman. You've got someone gorgeous there to take care of you. So
don't look so sad.
	   ``If anybody we know finds out, it'd be catastrophic.''
	   You bitch! A human being is about to begin its journey here. You
say it's catastrophic. Hey, where do you both think you're going?
To Dr. Syamsul's place? He lives in Tebet, but it's too late for
his counseling. Leave everything behind and let's follow these two
sorry people.
	   Dr. Syamsul's clinic is located deep inside the alleyways. Bowo
and Prita's car moves along and soon reaches the alley that leads
to the clinic. Damn, it really looks like those alleys are
especially made for snakes, curves and curves.
	   ``Well, we're here darling,'' said Bowo.
	   The sign on the board states that Dr. Syamsul's hours end at 6
p.m.. Man, I think it's too late for them to deliver the baby. Bowo
looked around to make sure that not even the soul of a lizard was
around, and knocked lightly on Dr. Syamsul's door.
	   ``Well, well, my dear Bowo, how are you?'' Dr. Syamsul asks
after recognizing the two lovers, one with a big tummy.
	   ``Fine, doctor. I need you to check on Prita's condition. If
possible, we'll deliver this baby tonight, Doc.''
	   Dr. Syamsul whispers ``Alright, come right in.''
	   People, I think you can now use your handkerchiefs. Prita, Oh
Prita. You people should have seen how she struggled between life
and death. Oh, she sighed so massively that it forced her eyes
closed. It must have felt like rusted daggers were hacking through
her limbs. Dr. Syamsul, why did you keep on pushing her? Didn't you
hear her screaming the song of the wounded, and see her perspiring,
like a dying wolf at night? Bowo, what is the matter with you?
Don't malfunction like a robot. Tell the doctor to take it easy
with your precious there. Oh, finally, the squeal of a soft cry.
	   ``Congratulations, it's a girl. Strong and healthy.''
	   ``Well, you know what to do, Doc. Besides, I just wrote you a
seven-digit check. You can cash it at the Bank of Ougabouga.''
	   The doctor wrapped the newborn in white cloth as though she was
a delicate birthday present. But suddenly, a knock on the door
struck all present like a bolt out of the blue, including the
frail, lovely Prita.
	   ``Damn!'' muttered Bowo as he heard the knock. ``Who could that
be?''
	   ``I don't know, but from the window it looks like the RT. Here,
you and Prita can hide in my bedroom. You take the baby first till
I get rid of whoever it is.'' The doctor locked the bedroom door.
	   ``Good evening Mr. RT, what can I do for you?''
	   ``Some neighbors told me that they heard a woman screaming in
your clinic, so I thought I'd just check it out.''
	   The doctor raised his eyebrows and opened his mouth.
	   ``Scream? Woman? Good gracious. Oh, they must have mistaken the
sound of my new electric drill. I was just testing it.''
	   The RT look taken aback.
	   ``What are you doing with an electric drill in the clinic, Dr.
Syamsul?''
	   ``Well... well, I just use it for placing some wall hangings. I
apologize for the noise. You know how it is, I don't have any free
time during the day.''
	   At that moment, Bowo opened the door slightly and peeked out.
Even though the slight sound of the door opening would not be
noticed by the RT or the doctor, it was sensed by the young child,
who let out a cry.
	   ``What's that noise?'' The RT sounded alarmed.
	   Bowo felt thousands of ice daggers pierce his heart and he
rushed to the window with the baby.
	   ``People are still roaming around,'' thought Bowo.
	   ``I think I saw a man jumping out of the clinic's window, Bu,''
said one among the crowd.
	   ``Ah, Ibu, don't be nasty,'' her friend said.
	   ``Thank God,'' thought Bowo.
	   Hey, hey, that's a garbage dumpster, Bowo. What are you doing?
What! Hey! No! What in the name of God are you doing? Look! Look at
the baby, what kind of sin did this little one commit to deserve
sleeping on a bed of garbage? How could you do this? What kind of a
father are you? You moron!
	   ``What noise?'' Asked Dr. Syamsul in a mixture of irritation and
bewilderment.
	   The RT moved his head around like an antennae.
	   ``Well, I must be going now, Doctor. Sorry to bother you.'' And
he disappeared quietly into the night.
	   ``Where's the damn child?'' asked the doctor.
	   ``I've thrown it away in the garbage.''
	   ``Oh, thanks. But you and your Prita must get the hell out of
here. I've had enough trouble. Prita is still weak, but she'll
manage it. Now, out! But don't forget my check.''
	   Finally they were in their car and cruising down the road. The
couple felt a sudden relief.
	   ``Where are we going now?'' asked Prita.
	   ``Well, since you are still weak, dropping you at your house
means questions. So, I guess we'll visit my newlywed cousins on Jl.
Radio Dalam, you can stay there till morning. They can be trusted.
But we don't have to tell them what we've been through. We'll make
a call to your parents, telling them we just arrived and are
exhausted from a friend's party.''
	   ``What about you, Bowo?''
	   ``I'll go straight home. You know my parents don't like the idea
of me staying overnight.''
	   ``Hello, Prita, Bowo, come in, come in. Mas, we have guests from
far away.''
	   ``Thank you, Mbak Renni.''
	   ``Oh Prita, you seem to have lost weight. Have you been sick?''
	   ``Yes, Mbak Renni, I've just recuperated from fever. Nothing
serious though.''
	   As soon as they all reached the living room, Bowo and Prita told
them of the party at a friend's house and their intention of
dropping by. Bowo asked permission to use the phone and told
Prita's parents their made up story.
	   ``We've also just arrived from shopping.'' said Mbak Renni's
husband.
	   ``And, guess what? We have a surprise we'd like you to see. Hold
on.''
	   Renni got up and went to her bedroom. She brought a bundle back
into the room with her. A miniature hand with a miniature glove
peeked out of the bundle.
	   ``Oh, Mbak Renni, it's cute. But I didn't know you just had your
first child,'' said Bowo. ``Isn't it cute, Prita.''
	   ``Yes, you should still be in the hospital, you're too weak, you
know.'' Prita continued.
	   ``Oh, who said I gave birth to this baby? God gave it to us
through a young street singer in Tebet.''
	   A dark, silent cloud covered Bowo and Prita. Even fingernails on
a blackboard would be music to them.
	   ``What?'' They both asked in unison.
	   ``We were checking out this new mall down in Tebet, and as we
were about to go home, two street singers approached us in the
parking lot. They said they wanted to sell the baby. They said they
needed money. I asked where the baby's parents were, and they said
they had no idea because they found it in a garbage dumpster. I
cursed the parents who threw or almost killed their own baby. So,
Mas Ato gave them Rp 50,000, at which they were overjoyed. And so
was I.''
	   As she was talking, the two lovers felt the dark cloud hanging
over them blacken further. And Renni held the baby toward Prita,
who took her gently.
	   ``Oh look, it's as though the baby knows you, Prita. Look how
cute this baby is. I'm going to name it Sinta. Look Sinta, Sinta,
this is Aunt Prita. Oh... you seem to be comfortable with Aunt
Prita.''
	   Long live poor cookie tin! Un! Dos! Tres! Ole! Ole! Ole!
...Rujak Ulek. Rujake wong lagi judek ...I'm a Barbie girl, in a
Barbie world...
	   Glossary:
	   RT: Rukun Tetangga, neighborhood unit chief
	   Bu, ibu: Term of respect for older woman, general usage
	   Mbak: Term of respect for adult female, general usage
	   Mas : Term of respect for adult male, general usage
	   Rujak Ulek, Rujake wong lagi judek (I'm getting a headache):
lines from Javanese song
	   
