<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Short of land to build enough houses, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws SHORT-OF-LAND-TO-BUILD sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   SEMERAH State Assemblyman Tan Teck Poh is in a dilemma.
	   The MCA Parit Sulong division head is aware that there is an
acute shortage of houses in his constituency, but yet he cannot
seem to find a solution to address the matter.
	   ``Now, with more people coming to work in Batu Pahat and Parit
Sulong, the demand for houses has far exceeded supply,'' said the
Parit Sulong-born businessman.
	   The Semerah State Assembly covers half of Batu Pahat town in the
south and borders Muar in the north.
	   Tan says that a sizeable portion of his constituency consisted
of Malay Reserve Land and as such it was difficult to find suitable
land for housing projects, be it medium- or low-cost.
	   Citing an example, he says the entire stretch of Jalan Muar is
Malay Reserve Land and apart from the traditional villages, there
are not many suitable areas for housing.
	   ``I have brought up the matter at the Johor State Assembly
meeting and I hope the State Government will come up with a
solution,'' he said.
	   Tan said previously his priority was to solve the flooding
problem.
	   ``Previously, each time it rained, several low-lying areas in
the town centre such as Jalan Sultanah, Jalan Rogayah, Jalan Mohd
Salleh, Jalan Mohd Akhir and Jalan Parit Dobi would be flooded,''
he said.
	   He said that a RM40 million grant from the State Government for
flood mitigation programmes had now helped solve the problem.
	   An underground monsoon drain has been constructed below Jalan
Sultanah while monsoon drains along Jalan Bakau Condong and Jalan
Parit Dobi have been widened and deepened.
	   Tan said Johor Menteri Besar Datuk Abdul Ghani Othman had also
taken a personal interest to ensure all villages had tarred roads
and other basic infrastructure facilities.
	   ``Now, about 80 per cent of the 60 parit (villages) in my
constituency have tarred roads. We are confident that within the
next two years, all villages will have tarred roads,'' he said.
	   Tan said there was also a need to bring in industries to Semerah
to create more jobs for the constituents.
	   ``There are ample jobs but most of them are in industrial areas
surrounding Semerah.
	   ``Many youths who are fed up of travelling, have migrated to
bigger towns and some have even gone to Singapore to work,'' he
said.
	   Tan said as most of his constituents were farmers or
smallholders, they were encouraged to supplement their income by
doing other activities such as aquaculture or cottage-based
industries.
	   Citing examples, he said those living in Mukim Lubok Darat were
encouraged to rear honeybees while those in Mukim Sungai Nibong
Darat were encouraged to go into fish rearing.
	   Asked on the recent controversy surrounding the renovation work
on a Buddhist temple in Muslim-majority Kampung Bintang, Tan said
he had directed the contractors to stop work.
	   ``I do not want any party to get offended,'' he said.
	   The temple is popular with followers as far as Singapore who
come here during the weekends to offer prayers.
	   Tan said the latest additions to Semerah was a RM800,000
multi-purpose hall and a RM570,000 market.
	   Tan said constituents who had any complaints could meet him at
his service centre in Jalan Jenang or his business office in Jalan
Temenggong.
	   
</TEXT>
