w2866  wstm-
r w     TO-FIGHT-DADAH-MENACEske     06-01 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> TO-FIGHT-DADAH-MENACE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Community must be galvanised to fight dadah menace, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws TO-FIGHT-DADAH-MENACE sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA Lumpur police chief Datuk Kamaruddin Ali held a meeting
recently with representatives of the Malaysian AIDS Council,
Pemadam and Pengasih (ex-addicts' association) to seek their input
on how to deal with the growing dadah problem in the city.
	   At the meeting which was also attended by representatives of the
National Dadah Agency, Kamaruddin spoke frankly about the problem
and the constraints faced by his department in tackling it.
	   He should be complimented for the initiative to have a free and
frank exchange of views with leading NGOs concerning dadah and
AIDS.
	   City folks are all too familiar with the perennial problem of
dadah addiction in the infamous Chow Kit and Lorong Haji Taib
areas.
	   In 1994, an operation code-named Ops Zombies was launched to rid
the city of addicts. Some 8,000 addicts were removed and placed in
rehabilitation centres throughout the country.
	   However, in late 1996, the areas once again became the haunt of
addicts despite police operations to nab them.
	   The problem is there are insufficient treatment and
rehabilitation facilities for hard-core addicts.
	   And it is the hard-core addicts who have to be ``tackled'' as
they are responsible for about 50 per cent of petty and property
crimes in the city.
	   Several proposals were discussed at the dialogue. These included
seeking the co-operation of the private sector to offer employment
to rehabilitated addicts in the plantation sector, encouraging the
setting up of more private rehabilitation centres, and identifying
suitable old buildings which can be used as ``drop-in centres'' for
addicts to receive meals and counselling.
	   These are proposals which will only be implemented after they
have been discussed in depth and approved by various quarters and
the authorities concerned.
	   Malaysia is fighting an uphill battle against dadah. According
to official statistics there are some 200,000 registered dadah
addicts.
	   Last year, some 36,284 dadah addicts were identified. Of these
17,342 were first-time offenders and 18,942 repeat offenders.
	   Selangor recorded the highest number of addicts with 5,536 cases
followed by the Federal Territory of Kuala Lumpur with 5,026.
	   In an effort to curb dadah abuse, the Government will embark on
a 25-year strategy, focusing efforts on schoolchildren by
inculcating values and awareness of the dangers of dadah.
	   However, government action alone is inadequate to deal with this
massive social menace.
	   What is needed is the galvanising of the entire Malaysian
community including NGOs, concerned groups, the private sector,
religious bodies and parents to mount a full-scale attack on the
country's No. 1 enemy.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
