<HEADER>
w2868  wstm-
r i     BC-Russia-Atlas     06-01 0213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Atlas </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Prosecutor defends American tour of Tibetan atlas 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia's chief prosecutor defended Monday the
legality of sending a 300-year-old medical atlas on a museum tour
of the United States despite protests from Siberian Buddhists.
	   Prosecutor General Yuri Skuratov was speaking in Buryatia, the
region of southwestern Siberia whose Buddhists leaders tried to
prevent the ``Tibetan Medical Atlas'' from leaving.
	   The feared the 17th-century atlas would not be properly
protected during scheduled exhibitions in Atlanta, Washington,
Bloomington, Ind., and Newark, N.J.
	   ``The legitimacy of the atlas being exhibited in the U.S. is
beyond doubt,'' Skuratov said, according to the ITAR-Tass news
agency.
	   Skuratov defended police who beat unarmed monks protesting in
Ulan Ude, the capital of Buryatia, the day the atlas was removed
from a local museum.
	   He said the monks ``staged not only pickets outside the museum
building, but also offered resistance to bodies of power and made
an attempt to put pressure on the authorities.''
	   The atlas is revered as part of Buryatia's heritage. It was
seized by the Soviet government in 1936 and has remained in the
Buryatia Historical Museum since then.
	   (ls) 	   
</TEXT>
