<SLUG> FUNCTIONAL-SOFTWARE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Functional Software establishes local presence, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws FUNCTIONAL-SOFTWARE sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   FUNCTIONAL Software of Australia, a system management tools and
service provider, is investing RM1 million in two Malaysian
companies this year as part of its plans to establish a direct
presence in the Asia-Pacific region.
	   The first, System Management Services (SMS) Sdn Bhd, has been
operational since February this year, and focuses on systems
management services for the local and regional markets. The second
which is in the process of being set up, will focus on providing
network management services.
	   Functional Software's director Alan Main said the company has a
45 per cent equity in the venture, while the remainder belongs to a
group of local developers.
	   ``We will provide part of the working capital and training for
SMS.
	   Skills transfer to the staff at SMS will be achieved through
three specialists from Australia, who will be based at the local
office,'' he said.
	   Main added that SMS' role will be to distribute Functional
Software's system management products and services, as well as
products from other software vendors, to its customers and
resellers around the region.
	   SMS takes over from the now defunct Singapore-based Sun Trade
Software (SEA) Pte Ltd, which has been distributing Functional
Software's products in Singapore, Malaysia, Thailand and Korea
since 1992.
	   Sun Trade's closure and its marketing methods were part of the
stimulus for Functional Software to set up a direct presence.
	   ``Sun Trade was very focused on selling products. That's not
denigrating the need for a product but you have to come at it from
the point of view of product, knowledge and expertise,'' Main said.
	   ``There is a growing awareness of this within IT management.''
	   According to Main, revenues from the local operations will not
be taken out the country, but rather reinvested in a compound
manner.
	   ``Having watched the business grow in Australia, Europe and the
United States, we believe the business model that we have is
relevant to the Malaysian economy. If it grows as expected, we will
consider relocating some of the company's research and development
(RD) activities into the Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC),'' he
said.
	   He added that the lower cost and readily available
infrastructure for conducting (RD) in Malaysia, coupled with its
intelligent workforce are some of the factors that attracted
Functional Software to the MSC.
	   ``Malaysia offers a more stable environment for skilled workers
as the threshold for a satisfactory salary in this country is
lower,'' said Main.
	   Most of Functional Software's research is currently conducted in
Australia and the United Kingdom.
	   SMS' general manager James Leong said the advantage of having a
direct presence in Malaysia also means that Functional Software's
resellers and customers are provided with local support, instead of
going to Singapore or Australia as was the case in the past. Its
current resellers are Bass Consulting Sdn Bhd and Applied Business
Systems Sdn Bhd (ABS).
	   Leong expects SMS to achieve an annual growth rate of 30 per
cent for the next five years. He said the economic downturn should
not have a serious effect on this projection, as users are looking
for ways to reduce costs in the current situation.
	   Leong added that Functional Software has developed good systems
management products for the Unix platform, such as COSduty and
COS/Manager which enable IT managers to reduce the operational
costs of their systems.
	   
</TEXT>
