<HEADER>
w2875  wstm-
r i     BC-China-Nuclear     06-01 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Nuclear,0534 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Foreign ministers of permanent Security Council to meet on South Asian arms race 
</HEADLINE>
By RENEE SCHOOF
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ China will urge the world's powers to find a way
to halt the nuclear arms race in South Asia when foreign ministers
of the U.N. Security Council's permanent members meet this week in
Geneva, a senior Foreign Ministry official said Monday.
	   China fears the recent nuclear weapons tests by India and
Pakistan will set off a chain reaction of other countries obtaining
nuclear weapons and set back disarmament, the senior official said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
	   Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan will attend the meeting on
Thursday with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and the
foreign ministers of Russia, France and Britain, the official said.
	   Tang and Albright, speaking by telephone, jointly proposed
holding the meeting, said Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao.
	   China has no proposal for how to respond to the tests, said the
senior official. ``That's why we're meeting. We have to work it
out,'' he said.
	   China does not want India, Pakistan or any other countries to
become nuclear powers, he said. ``We should urge them with one
voice and make them realize it's not in their interest,'' he said.
	   China, taking a turn leading the meeting, also will propose
talking about how to reduce tensions in South Asia, he said.
	   China is worried a South Asian arms race will destabilize the
world, the official said. China needs a stable international
environment so that it can concentrate on its economic development,
he said.
	   Elaborating on previous statements by Beijing about the tests,
he said China was ``infuriated'' when India said it needed nuclear
tests because neighboring China is its top threat.
	   ``We are not their enemy. It's not true,'' he said, adding the
accusation was an insult.
	   China had improved relations with India in recent years, the
official said. He added the two countries have many similarities,
including a history of colonialism and ``the same task to feed,
clothe, house and educate our people.''
	   China conducted its last nuclear test in 1996 and declared a
moratorium. It was one of the first countries to sign the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.
	   But even the treaty allows countries to resume testing if their
``supreme national security'' is threatened, the official said.
	   ``I'm not saying China will do it. But we have to take into
account this development. China is urging the world to do
something,'' he said.
	   The official denied China has helped Pakistan, its close ally,
develop nuclear weapons.
	   He confirmed that President Bill Clinton spoke with President
Jiang Zemin by telephone before Pakistan conducted its tests. But
he denied reports Jiang called on Pakistan to forego testing at the
urging of Clinton.
	   Jiang wrote to Pakistani Prime Minister Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif ``on his own absolutely 100 percent,'' he said. ``We don't
like to be preached to. We don't preach to others what they should
do. But we tell them how we feel. We have not minced words with our
friend Pakistan.'' 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-China-Nuclear; CT:i; 
