<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Saudi-OIC, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Islamic organization urges India-Pakistan talks month in lede; TRIMS 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with Iranian reaction; CORRECTS tests conducted last
<TEXT>
	   JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) _ A leading Islamic organization on
Monday expressed ``deep concern'' over nuclear tests carried out
last month by India and Pakistan and urged immediate talks by the
two nations.
	   The Jiddah-based Organization of the Islamic Conference said in
a statement from its secretary-general, Azeddine Laraki, that it
had wanted the establishment of a nuclear weapon-free zone in South
Asia.
	   The ``international community must seriously encourage both
India and Pakistan to expediently conclude a non-aggression
agreement with the aim of ensuring the promotion of peace and
security in the region,'' the statement said.
	   It said the OIC expresses ``deep concern over this serious
development.''
	   The Gulf nation of Bahrain also urged both India and Pakistan to
exercise restraint, government-controlled newspapers reported
Monday.
	   Iran, a leading member of the OIC, said although it is faced
with a ``new security situation'' following the tests, Tehran will
not build an atomic bomb. ``The present arena concerns only India
and Pakistan,'' Iran's Defense Minister Rear Adm. Ali Shamkhani was
quoted as saying Monday in a newspaper interview.
	   India exploded five nuclear devices two weeks ago, prompting
Pakistan to follow suit with six despite warnings from the U.N.
Security Council, the United States and other nations.
	   India and Pakistan have fought three wars since both countries
gained independence from colonial British rule in 1947.
	   The 55-member Organization of the Islamic Conference said in its
statement that it hoped Pakistan's nuclear explosions would not
fuel anti-Muslim sentiment.
	   It urged ``international public opinion to foil every biased
attempt aimed at using the latest nuclear explosions as a pretext
to launch an unjustifiable offensive against the Islamic (world).''
	   It added that Islamic states have always supported elimination
of nuclear arms.
	   Pakistan is the only Muslim nation known to have developed a
nuclear bomb.
  fsa-ggl-am/af/vj
