<SLUG> BC-Russia-Contract Killings </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Prosecutor reports progress in solving contract murders 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The number of solved contract killings is on the
rise, but Russia's most famous killing remains uncracked,
Prosecutor General Yuri Skuratov said in an interview published
Monday.
	   Skuratov told the newspaper Novaya Gazeta that his office had
solved 70 contract killings in 1996 and the number rose to 132 in
1997. ``I think we shall do a still better job this year,'' he
said.
	   Skuratov said that many top investigators had returned to the
prosecutor general's office because of improved salaries and better
working conditions.
	   He said that his office was successful in solving the killing of
investigative journalist Dmitry Kholodov, who died in October 1994
when a briefcase supposedly provided by an informant exploded in
his hands. Three suspects in the case have been arrested.
	   But the contract killing of TV host Vladislav Listyev, who was
gunned down outside his Moscow home on March 1, 1995, remains
unsolved.
	   ``The Listyev case is very hard,'' Skuratov told the newspaper.
``In no case has the Prosecutor General's Office felt so much
all-round pressure,'' he said.
	   But, he said, regardless of pressure and the cost of the lengthy
investigation, his office will take the investigation to its
conclusion.
	   (jai/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
