r w     NG-TARGETING-OVERSEASske     06-01 1544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> NG-TARGETING-OVERSEAS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Ng targeting overseas markets to fuel growth, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws NG-TARGETING-OVERSEAS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   IT is perhaps a misnomer to describe Malaysia's present economic
state as an ``economic downturn'' for not all parties involved in
the economy are facing a slump.
	   For those that are export-oriented such as manufacturing- and
plantation-based firms, the present period is as good as it gets.
	   One good example of such a company is Polymate Holdings Berhad.
	   Its main and most profitable subsidiary is Automative Battery
Industries Sdn Bhd (ABI). Presently, ABI relies on the export
market for 65 per cent of its turnover and it expects this figure
to rise another 10 per cent in the near future.
	   Furthermore, ABI's impending expansion programme to cater for
strong overseas demand will make it one of the biggest battery
manufacturers in Malaysia and this region.
	   It was the idea of Ng Kim Weng, Polymate's group managing
director and ABI's managing director, to ensure that the export
market becomes ABI's mainstay.
	   Ng had, from early on, realised that companies which rely
heavily on domestic market might find their product demand
eventually reaching a saturation point.
	   However, he explained if the company is export-oriented, then
the opportunities are limitless as the world becomes its
marketplace.
	   His foresight has since then paid handsome dividends as ABI's
expansion plan is expected to increase the group's turnover by 15
to 20 per cent to reach RM80 million for its financial year ending
Sept 30 this year.
	   Ng recently took time to speak to Management Times. From the
observation made during the interview, it was evident that he is a
leader without airs and capable of understanding his people's
viewpoints.
	   The humble characteristics can perhaps be attributed to his vast
experience in the sales line.
	   Q: How would you describe your management style?
	   A: I try to be extra careful when dealing with problems
involving human relationship especially when it concerns employees,
partners or customers.
	   Therefore, I try to put myself in their shoes before making
decisions concerning them. The other parties' feelings must always
be taken into consideration.
	   Furthermore, I personally try to and likewise expect my
employees to get things done fast and well.
	   In other words, I don't believe in procrastinating.
	   This is important for day-to-day decisions, as we can't afford
to delay decision making. Although planning is important, we can't
be in the planning stage for too long.
	   However, for long term decisions, I expect my employees to have
proper planning. They should not act rashly and make on-the-spot
decisions without having the correct information.
	   Q: Should managers then rely solely on hard facts when
formulating long- term plans?
	   A: Actually, it should be a combination of intuitive feeling and
hard facts.
	   If you do long-term planning based solely on hard facts, it can
turn out to be very misleading.
	   This is because whatever happened before might not occur again.
	   Alternatively, what has not happened in the past might happen
this time around.
	   As such, it's important that apart from relying on facts, we
also have to place confidence on our observational skills.
	   Q: In that case, what do you think of decision-making process
based on intuition?
	   A: Well, that basically involves experience.
	   Generally, people who have undergone a similar situation
previously would know what to expect and how to react.
	   For example, they would know what decisions to take to counter
problems created by the present economic downturn.
	   This is true even if the problem is not exactly similar to a
past problem. Just having that long experience in the industry
would have prepared them to handle problems better.
	   This is what separates the top level and middle level managers.
	   Q: As such, in terms of weightage, how would you rank factors
like experience, on-the-job training or formal studies in
developing an efficient manager?
	   A: I feel that observation is very important as from it, you
would be able to envision the future requirements of the company.
	   Meanwhile, on-the-job training is an on-going process that needs
to be experienced on a continuous basis.
	   However, employees without high academic qualification should
not be seen as inferior.
	   To me, what's more important is their character, how much
initiative they exhibit.
	   If they have a lot of initiative but are handicapped by the lack
of high education. I am sure they will spend much time observing
and learning, for example via on-the-job training, to overcome
their limitation.
	   Therefore, it's not surprising that they at times can perform
better than their more educated colleagues.
	   Q: Are you saying that even the top level managers don't need
proper qualification?
	   A: What I am saying is that academic qualification prepares
managers to handle problems in the theoretical sense.
	   So, if a problem occurs and graduate managers have been taught
to deal with that particular problem in university, they will be
able to overcome it.
	   But, one should not forget that managers who rose from the rank
and file too would be able to perform efficiently.
	   They, in their journey up the corporate ladder, would have
learned many things that would have helped hone their
decision-making skills.
	   Not surprisingly, at times, their solutions are considered
superior to those from the textbooks.
	   Q: You rose from rank and file. How has this, and your
background in sales, prepared you for your present post?
	   A: Basically, my sales experience has taught me to deal with
people efficiently.
	   I believe managers with sales background would have cultivated
the necessary skills to deal with the needs of different sets of
people.
	   As such, this gives them a great advantage over, say an
accountant who is purely analytical in functioning as a top level
manager.
	   Q: Are you then implying that top managers should have some
sales background?
	   A: No, that is not necessary. But let's say if you want to start
a business and you have prior knowledge on sales, that will help
you tremendously.
	   This is because, it will help you sell your products better, but
in the end, it still boils down to the character of the person.
	   Q: Being export-oriented, what kind of priority do you place on
research and development (RD) activities?
	   A: Actually, we are one of the few companies in the industry
which have invested a lot of money in RD activities.
	   We know that to increase our export market share, we have to
ensure our products meet international standards and have
consistent quality.
	   In the last year or so, we have invested more than half a
million ringgit for RD activities.
	   Q: Presently, retrenchment is a hot issue. How are you dealing
with this?
	   A: Well, for the time being, retrenchment is not something that
is in our dictionary. But hypothetically speaking, if there is a
need to exercise that option, we have to take into consideration
the individual's performance and his/her length of service.
	   Nevertheless, I don't subscribe to the ``last in first out''
idea.
	   That is not fair to the productive employees who might be
contributing more than the senior employees.
	   Q: How do you view change management in the context of our
present economic situation?
	   A: To me, we have to transform according to the changes in the
market.
	   We cannot rest on our past laurels, as success is never a
guaranteed attainment.
	   Just because you were successful before does not mean that you
will be successful later, especially if you don't change according
to the dictates of the marketplace.
	   The only way to be prepared for change is to get the proper
exposure.
	   For example, companies can send their employees overseas for
exposure and also have them attend seminars regularly.
	   Q: How do you accommodate young and ambitious employees in the
organisation without creating animosity among the senior employees?
	   A: I have on many occasions seen enthusiastic employees' ideas
given during management meetings shot down by senior managers for
no apparent reason.
	   It's my opinion that we must not discourage eager employees like
them as they are very capable in offering solid ideas.
	   Therefore, it is important that the top management let everyone
in the company know that they will support new ideas.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
