<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lithuania-Amber Room </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hunt begins for fabled czarist treasure 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   KLAIPEDA, Lithuania (AP) - German treasure hunters have begun
combing a beach in Lithuania for the famed czarist Amber Room,
allegedly buried there by Nazi forces, the Baltic News Service
reported Monday.
	   The beachcombers believe the cache includes panels from Czar
Peter the Great's famed Amber Room, an ornate hall whose walls were
made from the priceless, golden brown amber.
	   It was a gift to Peter the Great from Prussian King Friedrich
Wilhelm I, but the Nazis looted it from Leningrad in 1941.
	   For the rest of World War II, the treasure was hidden in eastern
Prussia, in the town of Kralovec.
	   The search is focused in the dunes of the Neringa peninsula, a
wind-swept sliver of land that runs parallel to Lithuania's Baltic
Sea coast for more than 100 kilometers (60 miles).
	   The German team is following leads by a former resident of the
area who says he saw Nazi officers carrying boxes off a warship in
1944 and then bury them along the shore, BNS said.
	   It did not name the resident or members of the German team.
	   The fate of the Amber Room has long been a mystery and a source
of speculation. The German government has said the panels were
destroyed during the 1945 Soviet invasion of nearby Konigsberg now
Kaliningrad, Russia. But Moscow has long insisted that the Nazis
hid the treasure.
	   (mt-mhh)	   
</TEXT>
