<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru,0508 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hundreds flee Kosovo province as dozens are reported dead number rising, calling ofr outside intervention. Trims. No pickup 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: RECASTS, UPDATES with Albania reporting 2,000 new refugees,
By ISMET HAJDARI
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Hundreds of villagers fled across
the border to Albania on Monday, trying to escape heavy fighting in
Serbia's explosive Kosovo province amid reports that dozens of
ethnic Albanians had been killed.
	   Conflicting accounts of casualties in the sealed-off areas could
not immediately be resolved. But the bloodshed appears to be the
worst since early March, when Serb police killed more than 80
people in a crackdown on militants and their families.
	   Authorities in Serbia are trying to block independence sentiment
in Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians outnumber Serbs 9-to-1. More than
200 people have died in Kosovo clashes since the beginning of
March.
	   About half of the Serb province is controlled by militant
Albanians and many regions are blocked off, either by Serbs or
Albanians.
	   Serb authorities claimed Sunday to have killed several dozen
militants in four villages in the Decani region of western Kosovo.
Ethnic Albanian officials said Monday that 37 Albanians had been
killed over the weekend.
	   Twenty-seven died in clashes in Decani while 10 were killed when
Serb police stormed another village, the Albanians said.
	   Two Serb policemen also died in the fighting around Decani, Serb
sources said. The area is 70 kilometers (45 miles) west of the
regional capital, Pristina.
	   The latest fierce fighting prompted about 2,000 Kosovo
Albanians, mostly women, children and elderly, to leave the
troubled region and cross over into Albania in the last day,
Albanian authorities said Monday. They said more were arriving by
the hour
	   Albanian authorities were providing free food and clothes for
the refugees _ many of whom walked for hours to reach safety.
	   In a statement, the Albanian government called on the United
States and the European Community to intervene ``for ending the
massacre in Kosovo.''
	   ``This is just the start of a war with tragical dimensions,''
the statement said.
	   The Kosovo Information Center, close to the ethnic Albanian
leadership, named 10 people it said were killed Sunday when Serb
police stormed the village of Poklek, 25 kilometers (15 miles) west
of Pristina. It said one had had his throat slit.
	   It said Serb police burst into homes in Poklek, pulled out
villagers and told them to ``go to Albania and never return.''
Afterward, Serb police allegedly set 26 homes ablaze.
	   All phone lines remained disconnected Monday between Pristina
and the hot-spots of Decani, Klina and Djakovica, where fierce
battles were reported Sunday.
	   The state-run daily Politika on Monday blamed ethnic Albanian
``terrorist groups'' for the deaths of several people, saying the
militants shelled villages near the border town of Junik as they
escaped into Albania. 	   
</TEXT>
