r w     IN-FOR-TRICKY-TIMESsked     06-01 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> IN-FOR-TRICKY-TIMES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
In for tricky times, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws IN-FOR-TRICKY-TIMES sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   YOUR magazine rightly suggests that the country's engine of
growth -the construction sector - will and is gradually going to
choke in the article entitled Spluttering Along In Fits And Starts
(MB, March 16 issue).
	   It also correctly points out that the onus of dragging the
sector out of the quagmire will lie heavily on the shoulders of the
three-year old Construction Industry Development Board or CIDB as
it is more locally known.
	   And boy what a task it has ahead of it! From the chart
(Performance Of The Malaysian Construction Industry 1968-1998)
which accompanied the article, it is perfectly clear that the local
property/construction cycle is no different from that of any other
country. We must, like them, go through a boom and bust period.
We've had a veritable booming era for the last 10 years or so and
will, for certain, go through a bust period. The question is, for
how long or how short. And will it be a long but relatively
painless, numbing affair or a short and excruciating period of
contraction?
	   The 12-member board was established on Dec 1, 1994 to
co-ordinate the activities of the local construction industry and
provide training and accreditation to local and foreign workers to
ease the shortage of skilled workers in the construction sector.
	   With the economic slowdown and the government's ongoing forced
repatriation of many illegal workers, CIDB's role in enhancing the
skills of both the locals and the legally employed foreign workers
is all the more vital. Born at the height of the rocketing, booming
real estate/construction development, CIDB will now have to cut its
teeth and prove its mettle in a gradually deteriorating
environment. The stormy winds of change is already being felt. Bank
Negara Malaysia has dealt the first blow by labelling the real
estate sector a non-productive sector; credit has been cut off and
demand has plummeted.
	   CIDB, to its credit, has already taken the first step in
carrying out its ambitious targets. It has already set up, or is in
the process of setting up, construction academies around the
country with the primary aim of training the relatively unskilled
workforce to meet the challenges of the millennium.
	   It has also gone boldly to where no local consortia has ventured
before ... it clinched several construction deals in Bosnia, Turkey
and India and as your article states, it is also eyeing
opportunities in Lebanon, Tunisia, etc. All this is fine and dandy
when the construction sector was booming and the local pie was too
small to be shared by so many fishes.
	   The situation has changed now and it is for the worse. CIDB must
now change track ... it must not act merely as the lynchpin for the
big and rich construction companies by clinching lucrative overseas
deals, but make a strong effort to assist the smaller fries in the
local construction sector.
	   With the local situation gradually deteriorating, many medium
and smaller construction firms will find their very existence
severely threatened. CIDB might well be their saviour in these
difficult times.
	   CIDB would do well to use this economic slowdown as a golden
opportunity to push the smaller firms, who cannot yet compete on a
global scale, into recognising the need for greater emphasis on
innovation, and accelerate the restructuring of these firms from a
labour-intensive dependency to one of high technology in line with
the country's push towards information technology.
	   For sure, it won't be an easy task but this is where the
government has placed its trust in the CIDB. CIDB, therefore, will
have to bring these small firms, kicking and screaming, into the
era of a highly competitive domestic and foreign markets.
	   It has the unenviable task of ensuring: that the local
construction industry does not allow the stormy winds of change to
go unheeded, that local construction businesses - whether
Bumiputera companies or otherwise -respond proactively to the
nation's changing circumstances, and that in order to back
Malaysia's global ambitions, Malaysian construction firms must be
determined to develop advanced strategies and technology, increase
expenditure in research and development, skills training, education
and infrastructure.
	   With its zero growth forecast for the local industry, CIDB
should see this period as the best opportunity to get its act
going, to achieve all the aims and aspirations that led to its
creation by the government and to be the catalyst in a soon-to-be
moribund industry ... oh, what a challenge! Goh Kim Leong Cheras

</TEXT>
