<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Stock Market,0252 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Karachi Stock Market falls 128.76 to record low 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) _ The Karachi Stock Market hit a record
low on Monday falling 128.76 points to close at 911.44.
	   ``There was massive liquidation by foreign investors and this
put immense pressure on the market,'' said Hasan Davar, a trader
with UBS Securities.
	   The Karachi Stock Exchange opened Monday for the first time
since Pakistan exploded five nuclear devices last Thursday and a
sixth one on Saturday, bringing global condemnation and threats of
economic sanctions.
	   Within hours of the first five explosions, Pakistan's president
declared a state of emergency and froze all foreign currency
accounts to try to prevent a panic exodus of foreign capital from
the country.
	   Pakistan's foreign reserves stand at dlrs 1.2 billion, which is
barely enough to pay for the next six weeks of imports, say
financial analysts.
	   Pakistan's Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz said last Friday that
his government was preparing an economic recovery plan that would
boost exports and reduce imports.
	   Sharif announced across the board budget cuts of 25 percent in
an attempt to reduce the impact of economic sanction.
	   The stock market began to tumble immediately after India
exploded the first of five nuclear devices three weeks ago.
	   On May 8, the last trading day before India's May 11 explosion,
the stock market closed at 1551. It has been on a downward slide
since then.
</TEXT>
