<BODY>
<SLUG> FLYING-HIGH sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Flying high, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws FLYING-HIGH sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   IT IS NOT easy to establish a market base in Malaysia for a
fledging Middle Eastern airline - especially when that airline does
not even fly to Kuala Lumpur.
	   Call it a daunting task, but that was the situation in 1991 when
Emirates, the international airline of the United Arab Emirates,
recognised Malaysia's potential and appointed a local company as
its general sales agent (GSA). Says Emirates manager Malaysia Alban
Lee, `There was much misconception and ignorance among the locals.
In 1991, marketing Emirates in Malaysia was difficult. We were six
years old. There was no flight out of Kuala Lumpur. If you wanted
to fly with Emirates, you had to go to Singapore.' Another
stumbling block was the common perception that Middle Eastern
airlines are unreliable and offer scant frills. Fortunately, there
was some consolation that many Westerners living in Malaysia
already knew then of Emirates' growing reputation for fine service.
	   `The primary aim at that time was to create awareness locally.
The approach was to tell people that Emirates was an international,
not a Middle Eastern, airline. The focus was on our services and
product features. We were considered innovative for introducing
inflight features such as a video system and a telephone for every
seat, and fax machines,' says Lee.
	   He adds that when people talked about the airline those days, it
was either with envy or curiosity, depending on whether or not they
were familiar with its service. He should know. Although he was
appointed to head Emirates' Malaysian operations only in October
1996 when it began plying the Kuala Lumpur-Dubai route with three
flights weekly, his ties with the airline extends further back.
	   He was formerly with Emirates' GSA, Maple Travel (M) Sdn Bhd,
and was its assistant general manager before joining the airline.
Seven years on, the groundwork has proved to be solid. On April 1,
the airline thickened its KL-Dubai route with a fourth frequency.
By next year, Emirates would have added another flight. It plans to
incre s frequency in the sector to daily flights in two years.
	   The sector's passenger traffic has a healthy load factor of 82
per cent, and generated about RM20 million in income for the year
ended March 31, 1998. This exceeded projections by 32 per cent.
	   With Emirates taking delivery of two Boeing 777s and the first
of 16 Airbus A330-200s by the end of the current financial year,
passenger capacity will climb 20 per cent. The passenger traffic is
forecast to grow by 25 per cent over the next financial year,
indicating the airline's confidence that its yield will remain
largely unaffected by Malaysia's economic slowdown.
	   In fact, the ringgit's depreciation has made Malaysia a more
attractive destination and has swollen demand for cargo space due
to higher exports.
	   However, as a scheduled airline, Emirates's priority is its
passenger business.
	   On the whole, Emirates' Malaysian operations contributed
approximately 15 per cent of the airline's Pacific Rim revenue. Lee
estimates that 80 per cent of Emirates' passengers in the KL-Dubai
sector are holiday- makers. Business travellers are far fewer
because trade between Malaysia and the Middle East is nominal.
	   In the beginning, Emirates in Malaysia drew a sizeable chunk of
its business from the expatriate community. Says Lee, `They
responded very well because they were already familiar with what we
had to offer.
	   Typically, they had more exposure to Emirates in their home
countries and needed less convincing. To put it arrogantly, they
had been waiting for the product and now it's here.
	   `It's more like a following. Most of these passengers fly to
Dubai and proceed to popular Mediterranean destinations such as
Turkey, Greece and Cyprus. For those who are sceptical or know
little about us, we usually surprise by delivering more than
expected. Eventually, people will learn to expect more from us.
That will be the second phase. That is why we are always
improving.' Emirates has a history of confounding the doubting
Thomases. In his message in a corporate brochure, Emirates chairman
Sheikh Ahmed Saeed Al Maktoum wrote, `The international regard in
which Emirates is held today is very different from the tolerant
scepticism which greeted its arrival on the aviation scene.' From
an airline launched on October 25, 1985, with two leased aircraft
and three routes, it has matured into the leading Middle Eastern
airline with 44 destinations, the latest (to Malta) launched on
March 30.
	   Amsterdam is served as a cargo-only destination with Boeing 747
freighter leased from Atlas Air.
	   It has gained attention in particular for its posh inflight
amenities and its lengthening list of awards (151 at last count),
mainly from trade and travel publications.
	   Fleet expansion is a key component of the airline's growth
programme.
	   Emirates currently operates a fleet of 22 aircraft: nine Airbus
A310-300s, six Airbus A300-600Rs, three Boeing 777-200As and four
Boeing 777-200Bs.
	   In November 1996, Emirates ordered 16 Airbus A330-200 aircraft,
with options on a further seven, to replace its existing Airbus
fleet.
	   Emirates will begin receiving the A330-200s from January 1999,
with deliveries to be completed in 2002. The new Airbus fleet will
be powered by Rolls-Royce Trent engines as are the Boeing 777s.
Emirates will be the only airline in the world with a fleet fully
powered by Rolls-Royce engines.
	   In August 1997, Sheikh Ahmed signed an agreement for two more
Boeing 777-200 (long-range versions) on which Emirates has an
option. The aircraft are expected to join the fleet during the last
quarter of 1998.
	   Like other carriers, Emirates also has to keep increasing its
flights and destinations to strengthen business. An airline that
aspires `to be a world-class, medium-sized airline by the year
2000' cannot afford to do less.
	   `We are a young airline. We need to add frequencies to our
destinations, including KL. We believe frequency sells,' says Lee.
`We are also working to obtain more rights into new areas, but this
can be difficult.' Fleet upgrading and award-winning service aside,
Emirates still has quite a bit to aim for in Malaysia. Heading the
agenda is making KL a mini-hub in the region. Explains Lee, `At the
moment, at least 17 Emirates flights go through Singapore weekly.
We hope to bring some of the flights to KL. Of course, the Kuala
Lumpur International Airport in Sepang has to prove that it is as
efficient and modern as it promises to be. If it can offer better
handling, more airlines will come. Our goal is to fly more people
into KL to take connecting flights to elsewhere in the region.' The
other aspect to work on is to encourage more inbound traffic.
	   According to Lee, most UAE nationals do not know much about
Malaysia although it has many plus points such as the relatively
lower costs and availability of halal food. He adds that all
Emirates online stations have been directed to sell the Far East.
In addition, Emirates in Dubai is working with Tourism Malaysia to
promote Malaysia as a holiday spot.
	   To gear up for imminent growth, the Malaysian operations will be
increasing its staff, now comprising 15 people. The airline had
planned to fly from KL to Jakarta but this has been put on hold due
to Indonesia's economic crisis. There will eventually be flights
from KL to Perth in Australia, as well.
	   Says Lee, `We are committed. We are here to stay. Our Malaysia
operations have proved to be profitable. We have as many
frequencies as several other Far East destinations that came online
earlier than did KL.' 
</TEXT>
