INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   CRUDE palm oil physicals are expected to hit a softer note this
week in tandem with the movement of crude palm oil futures prices
on the Kuala Lumpur Commodity Exchange, a dealer said.
	   Bearish market sentiment coupled with lower export data,
expected to be released by SGS (M) Bhd today, and Pakistan's recent
suspension of foreign currency transaction would continue to exert
pressure on price movements in the near term, another dealer added.
	   May South, which began declining gradually since Monday, however
rebounded on Thursday to close RM70 higher at RM2,410 per tonne.
	   But on Friday, the contract month declined to close the week at
RM2,370 per tonne, RM85 lower than the previous week's close of
RM2,465 per tonne.
	   Another factor other than Pakistan's forex suspension that will
determine prices on the trading pit this week is the expected
announcement of May's palm oil export data by cargo surveyor SGS
(M) Sdn Bhd.
	   ``The export data is expected to be lower for May,'' a dealer
said.
	   For the week just ended, spot month June fell RM88 to RM2,342,
July was RM116 lower at RM2,314 while August ended RM92 easier at
RM2,292.
	   Open positions on Friday stood at 6,836 contracts against 7,280
contracts last Friday while weekly turnover declined to 11,461
contracts from 12,961 contracts previously.
	   
</TEXT>
