<HEADER>
w2910  wstm-
r w     THE-DRIVE-TO-SUCCEEDsked     06-01 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> THE-DRIVE-TO-SUCCEED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
The drive to succeed, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws THE-DRIVE-TO-SUCCEED sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   ON THE cover of this issue of Malaysian Business is an Intel
processor.
	   Not just any old processor but the first Pentium II chip for
mobile personal computers (PCs).
	   Its introduction in April is particularly meaningful to Malaysia
for two reasons: the launch was staged in Penang, and the
processors roll off Intel's manufacturing lines in Kulim, Kedah.
Another feather planted firmly in the cap of Intel Corporation's
Malaysian operations.
	   Intel Corporation is a company that excels by pursuing the
future relentlessly, yet, its past is so rich it bears repeated
mining. Its Malaysian history alone is interesting enough to fill a
book. Actually, somebody has already authored such a tome. In 1991,
Peggy Lim, a former Intel manager, came up with a 256-page
hardcover entitled Steel: From Ashes Rebuilt to Manufacturing
Excellence. The title refers to a fire that struck at the A1
assembly plant of Intel Technology Sdn Bhd - commonly known as
Intel Malaysia - in Penang in the mid-70s. The company was just in
its third year of operations on the island state. It was
potentially an insurmountable setback.
	   Then came the fightback. T-shirts bearing the slogan Intel Still
Delivers were spotted all over Penang. Intel workers worked
feverishly, some at nearby factories that had offered space,
machinery and time slots.
	   There must have been plenty of back-slapping and handshakes when
the company shipped out crucial orders on time. The rest of Intel
Malaysia's 25-year history may never reach such stirring heights,
but it is still a colourful story of adversity, drive and
achievement.
	   It all began at the start of the 70s when Intel Corporation saw
substance in the Penang leadership's vision to make the island an
Asian Silicon Valley. When assembly operations began in 1972,
several firsts were notched up. It was Intel's entry into Asia
Pacific via its first offshore assembly plant, which cost RM4
million back then. Intel Malaysia was among Penang's high-tech
pioneers, which explains why the company is invariably mentioned
whenever government leaders speak about the state's progress and
industrialisation.
	   A few years later, Intel's senior management in Santa Clara,
California, realised (but not without some persuasion) that the
Penang operations could also handle the more complex job of testing
microprocessors. That year, 1977, saw the opening of a second
building at the Bayan Lepas site.
	   Two decades on, the number of buildings swelled to 12, including
several at Intel's test and assembly facility at the Kulim
High-Tech Park. The Kulim operations are under another company,
Intel Products (M) Sdn Bhd.
	   The importance of Intel's Malaysian operations expanded
accordingly. In July 1992, Intel Malaysia's then managing director
P Y Lai sounded jubilant when he told reporters that Intel was
transferring its entire microcontroller division in the United
States to Penang. (Microcontrollers are programmed to control
specific functions in products such as automobile engines, laser
printers, disk drives and home appliances.) This was a huge step
forward for Intel Malaysia, which was expected to rake in RM1
billion in annual turnover from the move. In Lai's words, it was `a
milestone in the local electronics industry'. He, the first local
MD of an Intel foreign unit, added, `This is probably the first
time in Malaysia that a multinational is giving its offshore plant
the total responsibility of handling the design, manufacturing and
worldwide marketing of an important product.' And when Intel
decided it was time to have a presence in China, who did it call?
Intel Malaysia, according to an August 1992 news report. It quoted
Lai as saying the headquarters directed the Malaysian subsidiary to
negotiate with Chinese authorities on investing in the
semi-conductor industry there.
	   Today, Intel Malaysia and Intel Products' operations extend
beyond testing and assembling Intel's most advanced
microprocessors. The Penang plant has a packaging technology
development lab and a design centre. In 1994, Intel transferred the
sales and marketing of its Embedded Microcontroller Division to
Penang. The Kulim plant, which opened in 1996, also churns out
computer motherboards and networking/communications boards.
	   In the mid-90s, Intel decided the time was right to have a sales
and marketing presence in Malaysia. Malaysia had the highest
consumption rate of PCs with Intel's Pentium processors. A
representative office was opened in Kuala Lumpur in December 1995.
	   These days, the sales and marketing operations are handled by
Intel Electronics (Malaysia) Sdn Bhd, which is headed by a country
manager. The company focuses on developing the domestic PC consumer
market, promoting Intel's brand awareness, and working with the
government and original equipment manufacturers or OEMs to help
grow the Malaysian computer market.
	   To be sure, Intel's Malaysian operations suffered other hiccups
apart from the Penang plant blaze. In the early days, pilferage was
an annoying and costly problem. That has since been remedied by
tightening security so much that even Intel boss Craig Barrett is
subjected to metal detector scans when he visits the plants.
	   In August 1992, a 19-year-old contract worker was found dead in
a liquid nitrogen filling station at the Penang facility. It was
the first work- related fatality in Intel's history. This prompted
Andrew Grove, the then Intel Corporation president, to issue on the
same day a five-page memo addressed to all employees, detailing
steps taken in the wake of the incident. Whatever measures
instituted since must have worked well, for in 1995, the Human
Resources Ministry gave Intel Malaysia a national award for
occupational safety and health.
	   Collecting awards seems to be part and parcel of Intel's
Malaysian operations. In 1990, Intel Malaysia was named the first
recipient of the Prime Minister's Quality Award. That year, it also
added to its trophy cabinet a regional award for human resources
development. The following year, it received The Intel Quality
Award, an in-house honour, true, but prestigious nevertheless given
the company's reputation for exacting standards. It has another
accolade from the Human Resources Ministry, The Caring Employer
Award, presented in 1993.
	   Indeed, Intel Malaysia is clearly run on the principle that a
happy employee is a productive employee. In 1991, for example, it
became the first manufacturer in Penang to have its own bas kilang
fleet by forking out several million ringgit to buy 230
air-conditioned coaches.
	   The company takes care not to call its workers `operators'.
According to a news article in April 1991, the term connotes a
lower standing. Instead workers who handle highly automated
machines are called technicians or computer programmers.
	   Another mark in the plus column for Intel Malaysia is its vendor
partnership programme, through which it helps develop its suppliers
through a combination of nurturing, tutoring and prodding.
	   
</TEXT>
