<TEXT>
	   THE decline in the futures market was mainly attributed to the
sell-off of the blue chips in the cash market as Asian markets
weakened further. South Korean shares slumped to an 11-year low
last week as foreign investors retreated on concerns of more
bankruptcies and worsening labour relations.
	   The week's chart has been marked with five black candles for
both the Kuala Lumpur Composite Index and the futures. Some
retracement is expected this week after this continuous fall but
the resistance at 580 seems very strong from this angle.
	   For the first week of June, some further decline to test the old
support levels of 515 and 500 for the KLCI and the June futures are
forseeable.
	   One of the items which is expected to affect the market is the
gross domestic product figures released last Saturday.
	   Other developments that might affect the market this week will
likely be fresh developments on the new political reforms in
Indonesia and worsening corporate results in the Asia Pacific
region.
	   Given the above, with continuous uncertainties looming on the
foreign front, the upside for the Malaysian market is expected to
be limited in the coming weeks.
	   Any rebound is expected to hinge on the performance of the yen
and positive news on the home front. Therefore, these should be
viewed as opportunities to short the June futures in view of the
weakening ringgit.
	   Fair value for June is 3.18 and for July is 7.59 
</TEXT>
