<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-LPGA Rochester, 1st Ld-Writethru,0354 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rosie Jones wins Rochester International 
</HEADLINE>
By BEN DOBBIN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   ROCHESTER, New York (AP) _ Rosie Jones reopened a four-stroke
lead, then came back to the field with back-to-back bogeys before
finally winning the rain-plagued Rochester International today.
	   Jones barely matched par on the first nine Sunday _ at which
point final-round play was halted after repeated rain delays _ but
roared back with a 35-foot (10-meter) birdie putt on No. 10 and a
12-footer (4-meter) for birdie on No. 12.
	   She dropped shots on No. 14 after getting tangled in the trees
and No. 15, where she three-putted, then steadied down to complete
an even-par round and finish at 9-under-par, or 279, at the par-72
Locust Hill course.
	   It was her ninth victory, and 126th top-10 finish, in 16 years
on tour. She took home dlrs 105,000 of dlrs 700,000 in prize money.
	   Juli Inkster vaulted into second place with a 4-under 68,
rubbing out an opening bogey on No. 14 with an 18-foot (5
1/2-meter) birdie putt on No. 16 and a 3-foot (1-meter) birdie putt
on the next hole to finish at 7-under. ``I was so wired last night,
I didn't sleep well at all,'' she said.
	   Hollis Stacy, who had halved Jones' 4-stroke lead to two on
Sunday, dropped to third place with a 70 to finish at 6-under.
Stacy, 44, captured 17 tournaments between 1977 and 1985, including
the Women's Open in 1977, 1978 and 1984. She has won just once
since then, in 1991.
	   One back were Meg Mallon, who closed with a 67, Moira Dunn and
Sherri Steinhauer.
	   The 38-year-old Jones, who won the Rochester International in
1991 and lost to Kathy Whitworth in a playoff in 1984, had opened
up a 4-stroke lead over Steinhauer on Saturday with an 8-under 64.
	   Swirling winds, flashes of lightning and heavy bouts of rain
stopped play for a total of 5 1/2 hours Sunday, eventually leading
to a postponement.
	   Defending champion Penny Hammel slumped to 4-over, one ahead of
South Korean rookie Se Ri Pak, who led the LPGA Championship from
start to finish two weeks ago.
</TEXT>
