<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 11:29:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2919  wstm-
r w     A-DEEPENING-BONDsked     06-01 1502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> A-DEEPENING-BOND sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
A deepening bond, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws A-DEEPENING-BOND sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   INTEL Corporation's top bosses love to use a photograph taken in
Penang whenever they want to illustrate how much the Asia Pacific
has progressed since the high-tech giant first ventured into the
region.
	   Chairman and chief executive officer (CEO) Andrew Grove used it
last November when delivering the keynote address at the
Asia-Pacific Information Technology Summit in San Francisco. More
recently, Intel president and chief operating officer Craig R
Barrett - who will take over as CEO later this month - found the
picture just as handy for his April 2 presentation in Penang on the
company's global business strategy.
	   Taken circa 1971 when Grove was visiting the building site of
Intel's pioneer plant in Bayan Lepas, the photograph shows a
dark-haired and bespectacled version of him sporting a moustache
and sideburns. He was standing barefoot in a muddy road with his
pants rolled up to mid-calf level.
	   What happened was Grove's car had gotten stuck in the mud. He
recalled being helped by people herding water buffaloes nearby, but
to no avail. In the end, he had to walk sans shoes to the site.
Both men followed up on the first picture with a current one
showing Intel's sprawling test and assembly complex at the Bayan
Lepas Free Industrial Zone. `Things have changed a little bit since
then,' Barrett understated.
	   Intel, whose microprocessors power close to 90 per cent of the
world's personal computers (PCs), has big plans to broaden its
presence in the Asia-Pacific region. And Malaysia looks set to
benefit, thanks primarily to the company's longstanding investment
ties here.
	   It is certainly a folly to ignore the region's rapid embrace of
IT.
	   International Data Corporation, an IT market research and
consulting house, forecasts a compounded average growth rate of 12
per cent for IT spending in Asia Pacific for the period 1997 to
2002. Last year, the region's IT spending stood at US$ 50.3 billion
(US$ 1    RM3.80) and can
reach US$ 88.2 billion in the year 2002.	   In addition, the Internet explosion (Asia has the fastest
growth), the soaring investment in IT infrastructure and the
potential to become the world's PC development centre combine to
bestow Asia Pacific with an irresistible pull. A breakdown of
Intel's revenue pretty much indicates the same upward trend. In
1987, six per cent of its income came from Asia Pacific (excluding
Japan). A decade later, the proportion has swelled to 19 per cent.
Japan's contribution for both years was 10 per cent.
	   Describing Asia Pacific as a hot area for PC consumption growth,
Barrett says Intel is increasing its presence in the region not
only through manufacturing and support, but also through sales and
marketing. Of the company's total capital expenditure of US$ 4.5
billion last year, US$ 1 billion landed in Asia. On the 1998
projections, Barrett says the global investment should be about US$
5 billion, with US$ 1.3 billion targeted for Asia Pacific.
	   This year, he added, Intel would invest between US$ 400 million
and US$ 500 million in Malaysia. The amount will be spent mainly on
upgrading and expanding its test and assembly plants in Penang and
Kulim, Kedah, and on an integrated warehouse at the Penang airport.
	   Barrett reckons that among electronics players, his company is
the number one investor in Malaysia in 1998. To date, Intel has
spent US$ 1.2 billion on capital investment here. This has fuelled
expansion of its Malaysian manufacturing operations over 25 years
to now include a dozen industrial buildings in Penang and Kulim in
which workers test and assemble microprocessors and a few other
computer components. Research and development (RD) activities are
focused on design and packaging technology. Some 7,000 workers are
employed at the plants.
	   Intel's sales and marketing operations in Malaysia started in
1995 when it opened a representative office. A current focus is to
drum up business by promoting wider IT use among small and
medium-scale industries. Another measure to increase sales is to
aggressively reduce prices.
	   It is only to be expected that Intel has signed up for a slot in
the Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC) project. It was reported in
February that Barrett had been named a member of the MSC's
International Advisory Panel.
	   He says, `We are still looking at options for being a part of
the MSC, and what makes maximum sense with our partners in this
area. We are definitely committed to having a presence there.
Perhaps, it will be in the form of a stand-alone RD facility.'
Intel's MSC-status company is registered as Intel Malaysia Design
Centre MSC Sdn Bhd. Intel Technology Sdn Bhd's (also referred to as
Intel Malaysia's) managing director Wong Siew Hai says the idea was
to set up a development centre, only that it had not been decided
what exactly would be developed. A full-time manager is working on
the venture.
	   Intel's push in Asia Pacific is not just about pouring in money.
Barrett demonstrated this with frequent trips to the region that
often include chats with government and industry leaders to propel
Intel's `New Users, New Uses' drive. The aim is to encourage people
to turn to IT and to nurture the creation of IT tools. More
computers sold equates more Intel chips sold.
	   Barrett's latest Asian tour was his third in less than a year.
Between March 30 and April 3, his whistlestops also included South
Korea, the Philippines, Thailand and Australia. `IT is the key to
competitiveness in the future. That's not a terribly hard sell. If
you come to a place like Malaysia, you don't have to talk very hard
to the government to convince it that an IT infrastructure is very
important, with the MSC and other IT projects the Malaysian
government has underway,' says Barrett, adding that South Korea and
the Philippines too have similar initiatives.
	   `So every country is, in fact, looking for opportunities to
create a strong infrastructure in IT. And I don't think they're
necessarily competing. I think they're very complementary in many
instances because one of the ways to create a strong local
infrastructure is to have the capability for both hardware and
software development in your country.' Despite these reassuring
words, the competition for foreign IT investment remains a sweaty,
high-stakes battle; the neighbours are equally eager to reap
Intel's dollars and knowhow. It was recently reported that Thailand
had persuaded Intel to provide technology to kickstart its Software
Park. There have also been reports that South Korea was
anticipating Intel to invest in a big way. Perhaps, the most
telling development came in the Down Under leg of his last Asian
tour. There, he met Prime Minister John Howard and senior ministers
reportedly to work out a financial package that might get Intel to
set up a wafer fabrication plant (or fab in industry jargon) in
Australia.
	   Such an investment is said to be worth up to A$6 billion (A$1   
RM2.50).	   Some reports characterised the meeting as something of a hard
bargaining session. `If you want to put a fab in Malaysia, you
would probably get a 10-year tax holiday,' the Australian Financial
Review quoted Barrett as saying. The question of Intel investing in
a fab in Malaysia has come up before. Wong says it is a `totally
different ball game'. He explains that fab operations have
stringent and critical infrastructural needs, including water, gas
and electricity. `With a few fabs set to operate in the Kulim
Hi-Tech Park, hopefully it can be demonstrated that Malaysia has
the capabilities to support such operations,' he adds.
	   In arriving at its upbeat outlook on the Asia-Pacific region,
Intel has not overlooked the Asian economic gloom. It is simply
that the company is often guided by the philosophy of co-founder
and chairman emeritus Gordon Moore. Barrett cites an oft-repeated
Moore dictum: `You can never recover from a recession on the basis
of the products you had when the recession started. You can only
pull out of the recession on the basis of new products.' Says
Barrett, `So if there is one message I would like to give the
industries, governments and people of Southeast Asia during this
crisis is that this is the time - probably the most important time
- to invest and move forward.' 
</TEXT>
