<HEADLINE>
Hall to step down as Newcastle chairman 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   NEWCASTLE, England (AP) _ Newcastle United announced Monday Sir
John Hall would step down as chairman, his caretaker stint complete
following the controversial resignations two months ago of Freddy
Shepherd and Douglas Hall.
	   Sir John's departure follows last week's boardroom shake-up at
parent company Newcastle United PLC when chairman Sir Terence
Harrison and non-executive director John Mayo quit.
	   In a statement, the company said it would ``consider the
structure and complement of both the PLC and the football club
boards immediately after'' new appointments were in place.
	   Former chairman Shepherd and vice-chairman Douglas Hall quit in
disgrace in the wake of well documented allegations that the pair
made derogatory comments about the club's fans, Newcastle women,
England skipper Alan Shearer and manager Kenny Dalglish.
	   Sir John was subsequently recalled as chairman to stabilize the
club but marked his return by defending his son and Shepherd for
the contribution they had made to reviving Newcastle's fortunes.
	   Those remarks sparked fears among fans that Shepherd and Douglas
Hall would eventually return to the Newcastle boardroom. Sir John's
decision to step down could heighten speculation the pair will soon
be back on the board.
	   (jp/scw)	   
</TEXT>
