<SLUG> CUPPA-DELIGHT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Cuppa delight, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws CUPPA-DELIGHT sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   SOME LIKE it hot, some like it cold. Whichever way you like your
tea, you'll be sure to enjoy your cuppa at the Ummph! Tea Shop
located in Bangsar, Kuala Lumpur.
	   Here at Ummph!, there are a variety of teas, from gourmet teas
to herbal blends, from pure garden teas to exotic spiced blends,
and not forgetting the really cooling thirst quenching iced teas.
The brainchild of Caroline Russel, Ummph! was set up over a year
ago, and also serves a wide range of sandwiches, cakes, pastas as
well as popular local fare.
	   Says marketing manager Christopher S Thiagarajah, `Customers
walk in for light lunches, snacks, tea-time, and even supper.'
According to Thiagarajah, Ummph! is modelled after the United
States's Starbuck, which contemporises coffee drinking. 'Basically,
we want to contemporise tea drinking, especially among the younger
generation which is our target market. We are, in fact, turning a
new leaf or rather stirring the tea leaves among the young ones.
They should feel that it is stylish and trendy to drink tea like
the iced teas rather than Coke or Pepsi. At the same time, they
want to be seen at Ummph! because it's the place to be,' he adds.
	   Boh's iced teas offer a refreshing alternative to quench your
thirst.
	   Lemon Lime has a natural, zesty tang and Peach is delicately
fragrant and sweet, while Orchard Splash is an invigorating blend
of fresh green guava, ripe mango, orange juice and a sharp dash of
tangerine.
	   For lovers of specialty teas, there are many flavours to choose
from - Darjeeling, Lapsang Souchong, Tippy Assam, Kenya, Java and
Ceylon.
	   Thiagarajah explains that these teas come from world-renowned
tea growing regions. Each tea is distinguished by its own special
character: champagne Darjeeling, smoky Lapsang Souchong, malty
Assam, sparkling Kenya, fragrant Java and mellow Ceylon. They are
sold in tea leaf packs as well as teabags.
	   Among the more popular ones are teas from the Seri Songket
range, says Thiagarajah. They are also sought after as gifts or
souvenirs by tourists because of the attractive Songket design
packaging. Seri Songket boasts flavours like passion fruit, earl
grey with tangerine, lemon with mandarin, lychee with rose, lime
and ginger and mango in its teabag presentations. Then you have
vanilla, cinnamon, clove and cardamon, earl grey with tangerine and
lemon with mandarin. Seri Songket's earl grey with tangerine, says
Thiagarajah, is special in a way because of its tangerine flavour,
and therefore, has an edge over other earl greys. It is among
Ummph!'s best sellers.
	   The exotic and beguiling Seri Songket flavoured teas, apart from
being named after the exquisite gold-woven songket fabric, are in
fact, a precious blend of Boh's light Sungei Palas teas.
	   For those who have developed a taste for herb infusions, calming
Camomile and spirited Peppermint are just two of the most widely
enjoyed therapeutic herbal teas. Boh has them made from the best
flowers and leaves and they are naturally caffeine- as well as
calorie-free. These are available in teabags.
	   Fruit infusions offers passion fruit orange, peach apricot and
strawberry raspberry. Perfect hot or iced, these are delightful
blends of dried fruit, flowers and peel blended with fragrant
natural essences. They are free from caffeine, artificial
preservatives or artificial colouring.
	   Tea drinkers will, in the near future, be able to sit down with
their favourite drink accompanied with a plate of savouries or a
piece of cake at other Ummph! shops as there are plans for more
outlets. `We are pleased with the response to our tea shop which
shows that ``Boh ada ummph''. In whatever we do, we certainly do
not want to loose track of our origin and heritage - Cameron
Highlands,' he says.
	   
</TEXT>
