<HEADLINE>
MEXICO
</HEADLINE>
Accused Killer Handed Over To Authorities In Coahuila, The News  
   xfdws ACCUSED-KILLER-HANDED sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   THE NEWS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   Accused killer and drug trafficker Jose Luis Lopez, alias ``El
Tamaulipeco,'' was handed over to Mexican authorities by U.S.
authorities in the border city of Hidalgo, Coahuila, official news
agency Notimex reported Sunday.
	   Lopez is wanted by two Federal District judges on organized
crime and murder charges. He is also wanted by judges in the
Pacific Coast states of Michoacan and Oaxaca and by a city judge in
Guadalajara involving murder and organized crime charges. In
concordance with the Mexico-U.S. extradition treaty, Lopez's
extradition is being handled by the Foreign Relations Secretariat,
a federal agency, and not state or city departments. Lopez and two
accused accomplices are required to make declarations before the
two Federal District judges, Cruz Lilia Romero Ramirez and Patricia
Gudino Rodriguez on murder, assault and battery and organized crime
charges.
	   The Mexico City Attorney General's Office (PGJDF) said the
42-year-old Lopez is originally from Nuevo Laredo, Tamps, the
Mexican city directly opposite Laredo, Texas, on the Mexico-U.S.
	   border. The PGJDF reported Lopez had served three years in a
prison in Huntsville, Texas, for attempted murder of his wife.
	   Lopez was handed over by Texas police at the city gate of
Hidalgo, Coahuila, a border town that lies across the Rio Grande
from Texas and which lies very close to Nuevo Laredo. Judicial
police from Mexico City and Tamaulipas took him into immediate
custody.
	   Lopez currently is imprisoned in Mexico City's Northern
Penitentiary.
	   
</TEXT>
