<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-TPC of Europe </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Westwood holds off Clarke by a stroke to win TPC of Europe 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   ALVESLOHE, Germany (AP) _ England's Lee Westwood Monday needed a
20-foot birdie putt on the 18th hole to end Darren Clarke's late
charge and capture his second title of the year at the TPC of
Europe.
	   Westwood, the 25-year-old Ryder Cup player, fired a 66 and
23-under 265 to stave off Clarke's challenge by a shot after
letting a four-stroke lead melt away at the dlrs 1.9 million
tournament.
	   Clarke charged by stringing together four birdies on his last
five holes, before Westwood shook off his first bogey of the day on
the 16th with the clutch putt.
	   ``I finally closed the door, so it's the biggest birdie of the
week,'' said Westwood. ``It's difficult when a player like Clarke
is chasing you. He can birdie every hole.''
	   Clarke, of Northern Ireland, finished with a 4-under 68 and 266
while Masters champion Mark O'Meara was third at 269 and a final
round 70.
	   The American, playing his first European tournament since
winning at Augusta, also chased Clarke but shot himself out of
contention with a double bogey on the 11th hole.
	   Westwood's title was his first in Europe this season, having
earlier won on the other side of the Atlantic at the Freeport
McDermott Classic held in New Orleans.
	   Fighting a steady wind, Westwood's 6-under 66 came after he
fired a course record Sunday with 61.
	   ``It's the first time I've ever done that _ hopefully it's not
the last,'' said Westwood of the two low rounds.
	   Bernhard Langer finished with a 68 and 271, along with Ireland's
Philip Walton. The German, a two-time winner of the tournament,
also dropped out of contention with a double bogey on his second
hole.
	   ``You just want to stick your head in the sand _ I'm very happy
with my round after that,'' said Langer, still searching for his
first title this season.
	   The scores, although low, were nothing compared to Sunday's
third round when Westwood shattered the course record and O'Meara
matched it.
	   ``I'm surprised the scores weren't better. Maybe we used up all
the birdies yesterday,'' said Walton, whose fourth-place finish
came after he missed five straight cuts.
	     (rk)	   
</TEXT>
