<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Currency review, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws CURRENCY-REVIEW sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE greenback ended stronger against the ringgit last week after
a top Malaysian official warned that the economy could go into a
recession if the tight monetary policy persisted. Ahead of the
economy's first quarter results, traders were not willing to take
positions. The greenback closed at 3.8300 on Friday, from 3.7200
the week before.
	   THE Sing dollar also weakened against the dollar last week on
news that the Singapore economy could need some stimulation soon.
But the Sing ended the week higher against the ringgit, ahead of
the release of Malaysia's first quarter growth figure. The Sing
closed at 2.2810 last Friday, from 2.2710 the week before.
	   EVEN though the Japanese yen weakened to a new low against the
greenback, it was largely unchanged against the ringgit last week.
This is because both currencies weakened together. With prospects
looking dim, the yen should dip further in the weeks ahead. The yen
ended last week at 2.7540, from 2.7470 the week before.
	   STERLING benefited from the weaker ringgit last week. There were
no major UK indicators released last week. Only the uncertainties
in Russia swayed sterling against the mark. This week, sterling
could react to the central bank's policy meeting. Sterling closed
Friday at 6.2300, up 6.0590 the week before.
	   THE Aussie dollar rebounded from its recent lows against the
ringgit.
	   News that the Aussie economy registered its fifth straight trade
deficit in April had no effect. The Aussie closed last Friday at
2.3700, up from 2.3450 the week before.
	   
</TEXT>
