<HEADER>
w2938  wstm-
r w     LEAPING-INTO-PROPERTYske     06-01 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> LEAPING-INTO-PROPERTY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Leaping into property, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws LEAPING-INTO-PROPERTY sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   MAIN board-listed Arus Murni Corporation Bhd (AMCB) is doing a
volteface, both in terms of strategy and shareholders.
	   Jettisoning finance, the company is pole-vaulting into property.
	   Specifically, AMCB is selling its crown jewel, finance company
Kewangan Bersatu Bhd (KBB), to Hong Leong Finance Bhd. The sale, of
course, was in line with Bank Negara's drive to pare Malaysia's 39
finance companies down to eight. At the time of writing, details on
price and mode of payment were not available. As of last month,
Hong Leong Bank, Hong Leong Finance's parent company, was still
conducting a due diligence audit on KBB.
	   However, would AMCB prefer cash or something else? Probably
cash, if its proposed property purchases get approved by the
authorities and AMCB shareholders. In February, AMCB announced a
series of acquisitions that would probably replace the lost income
streams from KBB. These acquisitions will be paid in cash. Notably,
AMCB will be buying a slew of Singaporean and Malaysian property
companies from parties acting in concert with Singaporean property
tycoon Eric Tan Eng Huat, also dubbed the Geylang King for his
lucrative forays into the republic's property market.
	   Torie International Pte Ltd (TIPL), which is controlled by Tan,
will emerge as a substantial shareholder in AMCB. AMCB's
controlling shareholder, Arus Murni Sdn Bhd - which is helmed by
former Idris Hydraulic company secretary Mohd Faiz Abdullah - will
sell 37.64 million AMCB shares and 9.41 million AMCB warrants. In
toto, these constitute 22 per cent of total AMCB shares in issue
and 16 per cent of warrants outstanding as at Feb 6, 1998. However,
no mention was made of the quantum or mode of payment in the
proposal. At the current price of 87.5 sen per AMCB share and 31
sen per warrant, the stake would cost TIPL RM35.9 million or about
S$15 million - pretty cheap entree for Tan into the KLSE.
	   Is AMCB getting a good deal? Overall, it seems the pre-tax
profit would get a boost. For the half year ended June 30, 1997,
AMCB suffered a group pre-tax loss of RM11.1 million on the back of
interest income of RM116.98 million. Loss per share was 8.6 sen
against earnings per share of 1.64 sen during the previous period.
At the same time, cash reserves might be eroded and leveraging may
rise.
	   All in all, AMCB will fork out an aggregate cash consideration
of RM117.4 million for the proposed Singapore acquisitions and
RM289.7 million for the proposed Malaysian acquisitions. Properties
were valued according to open market valuations as of different
dates and using different methods by independent valuers. According
to the proposal, the acquisitions are expected to be financed by
the disposal of KBB, internal funds and bank borrowings.
	   At the same time, net tangible asset per share of AMCB will
decrease from RM1.79 to RM1.33. However, this is prior to the
disposal of KBB. NTA post-KBB sale was not quantified because `the
disposal consideration has not been determined at this juncture.'
But, optimistically, earnings per share won't be diluted due to an
increase in paid-up since no new shares are being issued.
	   What was the rationale behind the proposed acquisitions? On one
hand, the Singapore properties will enable AMCB to earn foreign
exchange, a crucial consideration in the light of the ringgit's
recent vagaries. The properties in Singapore comprise mainly
completed residential and commercial units. Of course, points out a
Singaporean observer, `The Singaporean property market hasn't been
too healthy lately, so demand for the AMCB properties may not be
that stunning.' The Malaysian properties comprise commercial,
industrial, residential and recreational properties, located in
mainly Johor Baru, with the balance in central Malacca and Ipoh.
AMCB's Johor Baru jewel - the JB Waterfront City, a `self-contained
metropolis to be built on a ``above-the- water'' concept on the
Straits of Johor. Started in April 1997 and poised for completion
by December 2000, assuming no hitches, this `Waterfront' will be
Johor's new central business district.
	   To safeguard its interests, AMCB will be getting a profit
guarantee for the property companies. The vendors of the Malaysian
property companies have guaranteed profit before tax of RM18 and
RM21 million for the first and second calendar year respectively,
starting from the completion date of the proposed restructuring.
Likewise, the vendors of the Singapore property companies shall
guarantee a profit before taxation for the first year of RM17
million and the second year of RM14 million. The guarantee ensures
that the group's profit before taxation will not be less than RM35
million per annum for the two calendar years commencing from
completion of restructuring.
	   Discounting the profit guarantee, the Singaporean companies
should be profitable based on their track record. Profit after tax
and minority interests for the companies was S$13.72 million for
the period from July 1, 1996 until Sept 30 1997 as compared to
S$3.57 million for the period from July 1, 1995 till June 30, 1996.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 MALAYSIAN BUSINESS all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
