<SLUG> BC-UN-Brazil-Drought </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Brazil's food and crop situation critical, U.N. agency says 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Up to 10 million people in northeastern Brazil could
go hungry this year because of one of the worst droughts in 15
years, a U.N. agency reported Monday.
	   It said grain output will be half of normal and plantings of
some crops have been cut up to 90 percent in some areas.
	   The Rome-based Food and Agriculture Organization said up to 4.8
million people might starve.
	   Half the land in the region, which has had no rain in six
months, is a virtual desert, the FAO said, and the situation might
worsen if the drought continues through December, as forecasts say.
	   Grain production in the region is expected to reach just 4.5
tons, half the normal production, the FAO said.
	   Plantings of rice and beans, staples of the local diet, have
been cut sharply, in some locations by as much as 80 percent. Maize
plantings are down 60 percent to 90 percent in some areas, and
other crops, like coffee and sugar cane, are also severely
affected.
	   Although droughts are not unusual in the northeast, experts say
El Nino has exacerbated the situation.
	   (ar/cph)
</TEXT>
