<BODY>
<SLUG> DOWNSIDE-CONSOLIDATION sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Insight into current downside consolidation, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws DOWNSIDE-CONSOLIDATION sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   LAST week share prices on the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange closed
broadly lower with movements confined within the support and
resistance ranges on lack of fresh leads.
	   The KLSE Composite Index staged several re-tests of its 544
support but gave way in the afternoon trades on May 29, this year.
The relatively thin market volume reflected investors' current
stand of sidelining their trading activities.
	   On May 25 the KLSE CI opened on a weak note as investors felt
there were no fresh incentives to enter the market. On the regional
front, investors would like to see more stability before returning
to the market. The KLSE CI closed 6.68 points lower to 570.55
level.
	   Renewed weakness on the regional equities markets dampened
market sentiment on the domestic front. It was also affected by
news that the gross domestic product growth for the first quarter
of this year was not very encouraging.
	   Given the bearish influences on both the domestic and regional
front, the KLSE CI drifted lower to 561.34 level on May 26, 1998,
giving a loss of 9.21 points, or 1.61 per cent.
	   The KLSE CI drifted even lower on May 27 on weakness of Japanese
Yen.
	   The wide fluctuations on the New York stock market was another
contributing factor in dampening market sentiment on the local
bourse. The KLSE CI closed 9.06 points, or 1.61 per cent, lower to
552.28 level.
	   Overall market drifted lower on May 28 on continuing negative
perception of the local and regional front. Economists and analysts
were further concerned by the prospect of lower economic growth
this year than forecasted earlier. The KLSE CI dropped another 7.54
points, or 1.37 per cent, to 544.74 level.
	   The KLSE CI's technical rebound to 549.94 in the morning trades
on May 29 soon fizzled out as sellers took the opportunity to
liquidate. The overall market sentiment was still fragile when most
stocks gave up their early morning gains. It closed at the week's
lowest level at 538.24 level.
	   Reflecting the continuing weak market sentiment, the KLSE CI
fell 38.99 points, or 6.76 per cent, over the week to close at its
lowest level at 538.24 points on May 29. The KLSE All Share EMAS
Index dropped 8.41 points, or 5.80 per cent, to 136.51 level.
	   The KLSE Industrial Index lost 69.23 points, or 6.27 per cent,
to 1,035.40 level. The KLSE Second Board Index declined 4.69
points, or 4.04 per cent, to 111.47 level.
	   Chartwise, the KLSE CI traced out five consecutive trading days'
losses of 38.99 points, or 6.76 per cent. It had given up all its
gains registered during the previous week's technical rebound to
596.09 level on May 21. Since then, it was almost a straight line
decline.
	   Following are the readings of some of its technical
indicators:-Moving Averages: The KLSE CI continued to stay below
all its 10-, 20-, 30-, 50-, 100- and 200-day moving averages.
	   Momentum Index: Its short-term momentum index failed in its
attempt on May 27 to overcome its resistance at the zero reference
line.
	   On Balance Volume: Its short-term OBV trend had since turned
down below its 10-day exponential moving averages.
	   Relative Strength Index: Its 14-RSI had since reversed from its
recent peak at 46.01 level on May 21 to 31.77 level on May 29
OUTLOOK: Overall market had since weakened further on lack of fresh
leads from both the domestic and regional front. Renewed weakness
on the regional bourses coupled with the uncertainties of the
regional currencies, particularly the Japanese Yen, dampened the
market sentiment further.
	   The KLSE CI fell below this column's envisaged support levels.
It even breached the clustered support at 544 level before moving
lower to close at 538.24 points on May 29.
	   Following the KLSE CI's breakdown below the 544 support level,
the KLSE CI has tentatively resumed its downside consolidation. A
stay below the 544 level on June 1 shall confirm the resumption of
its correction from 764.94 level. How far will this downside
consolidation be?
	   Trying to find an insight into the current downside
consolidation, we have to revert to the KLSE CI's other phases of
uptrend and downtrend to locate the likely symmetry waves. With
that, we shall try to pin down the next set of symmetry wave in
determining the current retracement support.
	   The technical rebound from 470 level on Jan 12 to 764 level on
Feb 11 gave a retracement gain of 294 points. This corresponded to
the uptrend gain of 294 points, from 176 level in May 1986 to 470
level in August 1987. Thereafter, its price trend retraced from 470
level to 223 level in December 1987, giving a retracement loss of
247 points, or 84 per cent.
	   Should the 84 per cent retracement (247 points) be the next set
of symmetry wave, then the KLSE CI's current retracement will
likely to find critical support at 517 level.
	   Other Fibonacci-based ratio retracement from its recent
movements placed its clustered support around 510 to 517 levels.
Thus, the next downside critical support is at 511 to 517 levels
while its immediate overhead resistance is now at 544 level.
	   
</TEXT>
