<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup-Gascoigne Out, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hoddle says he dropped Gascoigne solely for lack of fitness Gascoigne; adds more Hoddle quotes; edits 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: ADDS bookmakers odds; bookmakers says team better without
<TEXT>
	   LA MANGA, Spain (AP) _ England coach Glenn Hoddle said Monday he
dropped controversial midfielder Paul Gascoigne from the final
22-man World Cup team solely because he wasn't fit.
	   On Sunday, Hoddle stunned England by dropping the 31-year-old
Gascoigne, rated by some as the best midfielder in English history.
	   As well as Gascoigne, Hoddle also dropped five other players _
Tottenham goalkeeper Ian Walker, Manchester United's Phil Neville
and Nicky Butt, Coventry's Dion Dublin and Everton's Andy
Hinchcliffe _ to get down to the final 22-man team.
	   But all attention Monday focused on Gascoigne, a highly skilled,
creative player who has filled the tabloid press in recent years
with reports of his fast-paced, hard-drinking life off the pitch.
	   ``He (Gascoigne) was not selected on his fitness levels and his
form over the last two or three months,'' said Hoddle, speaking at
a news conference in this southeastern Spanish resort where England
has been training.
	   ``We have run out of time getting him to the (fitness) levels I
needed,'' Hoddle added. ``I am as disappointed as Paul that he is
not with us but I have had to make a very tough decision. It was a
difficult one for me to call.''
	   Hoddle, looking composed in the face of a decision that could
backfire, recounted that Gascoigne cried after he told him the
news.
	   ``We had a chat for two or three minutes that lasted no longer
than that,'' Hoddle said. ``At the end of the day I think there
were some tears in his eyes.''
	   ``He went into his room. I think some of his friends went into
his room to console him. Paul acted as I would have expected him to
react.''
	   Britain's biggest bookmakers Ladbrokes last week lengthened the
odds on England winning the World Cup from 7-1 to 8-1 following
poor play in three matches.
	   The odds remained unchanged with Gascoigne's departure _ and
could shorten.
	   ``We believe the team is better off without Gascoigne,'' said
Ladbrokes' spokesman Sean Boyce. ``We take the attitude this is a
good thing.''
	   Gascoigne, a key figure when England reached the World Cup
semifinals in 1990 in Italy, returned to England after the shock
announcement and was reported staying with his estranged wife
Sheryl.
	   ``I can't believe this has happened. This is the worst thing
that has ever happened to me,'' The Sun newspaper quoted Gascoigne
as saying.
	   The unexpected gamble by Hoddle, the No. 1 news item Monday
across England, was surprisingly supported by more than 75 percent
of callers to a popular London morning radio show.
	   ``We've played him before when he's not been 100-percent fit,
but that's been in a one-off situation, Hoddle said.
	   ``This is different, this is going up against the best players
in the world and he just wasn't ready for it.''
	   ``I needed to have 22 players who I knew could last 90 minutes,
and Paul just didn't come into that category. The pace of the
modern game means you have to have athletes, not just technically
excellent players, but athletes as well.
	   Gascoigne, who has played for Newcastle, Tottenham, Lazio,
Glasgow Rangers and Middlesbrough, seems to have lost his dribbling
and passing touch. He has also suffered numerous injuries and
attracted the wrong kind of publicity off the field.
	   Ankle and groin injuries sidelined him for much of last season
and, although he played 90 minutes of England's 0-0 tie with Saudi
Arabia and the 1-0 victory over Morocco on Wednesday, he managed
only half of the game against Belgium and limped off with a leg
injury.
	   In those three matches he looked ineffective, a shadow of the
creative player that made him a one-of-a-kind on previous English
sides.
	   Although Hoddle said he dropped Gascoigne over his lack of
fitness, he kept the faith with Les Ferdinand and Darren Anderton,
two Tottenham players who have been short on fitness and form this
season.
	   The move leaves England without a player with World Cup
experience. The club failed to qualify for the 1994 World Cup in
the United States and reached the semifinals in 1990 in Italy.
	   Trevor Steven, Gascoigne's former England teammate, criticized
Hoddle's decision.
	   ``There's still two and a half weeks before kick off. Paul has
something that nobody else can offer the team and I would have just
given him that time.
	   ``As an England fan I would have loved to have seen him do well.
But the decision has been made and I think our squad is poorer for
the lack of Paul Gascoigne.''
	   (scw)	   
</TEXT>
