<BODY>
<SLUG> IN-FOR-THE-LONG-HAUL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
In for the long haul, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws IN-FOR-THE-LONG-HAUL sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   MALAYSIA, with its extensive oil and gas reserves, is home to
three petrochemical centres. While Kerteh, Terengganu, is the
acknowledged ethylene hub of the east coast, Pasir Gudang, Johor,
is an alternative option for chemical and petrochemical investors.
The Gebeng Industrial Estate in verdant Pahang has developed as a
propylene centre and is attracting heavyweights in the global
industry.
	   With the economic downturn looming over the region, many
companies are embarking on affirmative measures to ensure they not
only stay afloat but thrive in rough weather. Likewise for
petrochemical giant, BASF (M) Sdn Bhd.
	   BASF is intent on staying focused and continuing to invest in
the country. The company has investment interests in two of the
three emerging petrochemical sites in the country. Its site in
Pasir Gudang is a stand-alone manufacturing facility churning out
plastics and specialty chemicals.
	   Total investments at the site amount to RM200 million. The site
at Bukit Jelutong, Shah Alam, is a tailor-made stand alone which
concentrates on blending and mixing facilities and will house
BASF's new headquarters. To date, BASF has poured in RM40 million
in its polyurethene system blending facility and more investment
ringgit is expected to flow in by the end of the decade. The
company is looking at investing RM80 million before the year 2000
for the facility at Bukit Jelutong. The Gebeng site in Pahang is
the company's integrated site and represents a joint-venture with
Petronas, concentrated on producing acrylic acid. This facility
involves the heftiest investment sum, running up a RM2.5 billion
bill.
	   The chemical market generally consists of two varieties:
commodity and speciality. These can be further broken down into
their smaller components. Commodity chemicals consist of
petrochemicals, which holds the biggest market share at 40 per
cent, inorganic chemicals (eight per cent), and textile chemicals
(10 per cent). Specialty chemicals are broken down into performance
chemicals (16 per cent of market share), pharmaceutical (16 per
cent), agrochemicals (10 percent), and fine chemicals also known as
pure chemicals (one per cent).
	   Overall, commodity chemicals make up 60 per cent of the world's
market and specialty chemicals make up the remaining 40 per cent.
Both markets are still growing. However, the market for chemicals
have not been sustaining growth other than pharmaceuticals and
performance chemicals.
	   The impact of these growing markets is significant; the bulk of
BASF's manufactures are speciality chemicals. BASF's array of
chemicals reads like an index list. The company classifies its
products into four broad areas: health and nutrition, colourants
and finishing products, chemicals, and plastics and fibre raw
materials.
	   BASF markets and sells nearly 850 products and more than 100 of
those are produced locally. By end of last year, BASF Malaysia's
sales turnover amounted to RM412 million. By the end of next year
it is expected to be between RM700 million and RM800 million while
by the year 2002, sales are estimated to hit RM1.3 billion to RM1.5
billion.
	   Of the company's total sales, 30 per cent is sourced from local
production and by the end of 1999, this will increase to 50 per
cent.
	   Juergen Knust, chairman of BASF Malaysia, says local production
will further increase when the joint-venture with Petronas fully
comes on stream. The business venture bodes well for BASF as
worldwide demand for acrylic acid is growing at a rate of four per
cent and the company is one of biggest producers in world.
	   In Malaysia, says Knust, the big industries are the electrical
and electronic industries and the related packaging industry, which
is driven by the company's Styropor production, which has the
largest turnover of production among all BASF's products. Up to
1997, the company imported 90 per cent of its raw materials. Since
end of last year, this 90 per cent has been reduced to just below
50 per cent due to increased production capacities anticipated in
the country.
	   Knust cites both the electrical and electronic industries as
BASF's strong markets. Other markets which the chemical giant has
its fingers in include the automotive, textile and construction
industries. Contrary to popular belief, Knust says the company
still supplies to the construction industry as it is the only
producer of Tamol, a super plasticiser used in the industry. About
70 per cent of BASF's clients in Malaysia are situated in the Klang
Valley.
	   Knust contends that, `Whilst there might be lesser volume of
products needed in Malaysia, we are undertaking greater exports,
especially to Asean where there is no major competitor producing
this material.' Knust cites two major factors as to why BASF is
doing well in the region. `We have our own production and 80 per
cent of this goes into the export market to Asean and other
countries. This market is doing well.
	   Another reason is because we have enough customers who are
export-oriented and that is why the company and the chemical
industry can sail relatively unscathed.' On the current domestic
market, there is no doubt that there is a slowdown, and Knust feels
that any company needs the export activities to balance out. `You
need this balancing act and a lot of effort to swing around your
marketing endeavours to be even more export-oriented as compared
with the past and I think we are into that mode.' And if the
downturn continues, the export figure will see a further increase
of another 10 per cent.
	   There comes a note of caution, however, as both BASF and most in
the industry did not expect the crisis to be so severe and not to
last for so long. `Until now we have not changed our plans because
overall we are doing very well. But as this situation carries on,
let's say into mid- year, then we'll have to revise down some of
our prospects. We are waiting and are being optimistic, but there
will be lesser gowth if this downturn continues.' Sales turnover
for Malaysia in the first quarter of this year increased 30 per
cent and if it continues on the uptrend, the company's plans remain
unchanged. New projects for the year will amount to RM150 million,
and if everything goes to plan, BASF will release three new
projects within the next three to six months. However, future
investments will have to be revised should the economic slowdown
continue into the year. `Looking back, we can only be glad that we
planned the buildings so much ahead of time,' says Knust while
reflecting on the increased costs nationwide. `There are certain
effects (from the economic slowdown) as we supply both the
automotive and construction industry. We are experiencing lesser
sales in these industries,' he acknowledges.
	   Delving into the subject of BASF's projects, Knust says that all
the company's projects are for the long term and based on long term
strategies. Everything is full steam ahead. This is possible, Knust
feels, as the current economic situation aids in weeding out
competition: `You get more and better suppliers.' He divulges that
there will be more projects to be announced this year and in due
course. The Bukit Jelutong plant is a medium-sized engagement and
will produce polyurethene. The investment cost for this runs up a
RM10 million price tag. By the end of the first quarter of 1999,
Knust hopes to transfer BASF's headquarters to the site. The
company's warehouse and domestic distribution centre will also be
in place by then. The master batch production is slated to be
running by mid-1999.
	   Generally, a sense of commitment is prevalent in the air. Of
BASF's investments, Knust says, `We have committed beforehand and
we've invested beforehand. Of course, certain services may be
cheaper now but we are here for the long term.' 
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998
MALAYSIAN BUSINESS all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
