<HEADER>
w2960  wstm-
u i     BC-Arabs-Summit 1stLd-Writethru   06-01 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Arabs-Summit, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede CAIRO Abdullah in Jordan to resolve differences over Arab summit new quotes; changes byline 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Saudi crown prince in Jordan;
By JAMAL HALABY
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah arrived in
Jordan Monday for talks aimed at resolving differences between key
Arab leaders on a proposed summit on the Middle East peace process.
	   Abdullah came from Damascus where he met at least twice with
Syrian President Hafez Assad to persuade him to accept an open
agenda at the proposed summit, Arab diplomats said.
	   Such a demand also has been made by Jordan and some Gulf
nations. But all agree that the summit should forge a unified Arab
position against Israel.
	   Talaat Hamid, spokesman for the 22-member Arab League, said in
Cairo that consultations are under way between Arab leaders over
the time and place for the summit. He gave no other details.
	   An Egyptian weekly newspaper reported that Morocco, Saudi Arabia
and Egypt have offered to host the summit.
	   The meeting was proposed by Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat who
wants the Arabs to take a tougher stance toward Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu since peace talks have reached a
complete stalemate.
	   Syria has taken this one step further, insisting that the summit
should put the brakes on normalization of Arab ties with Israel,
said the diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity.
	   Jordan, Israel's closest Arab ally, apparently balks at that.
	   Deputy Prime Minister Jawad Anani declined to comment on the
hard-line Syrian position, saying ``they are free to say what they
want.''
	   But, he added, the summit should ``evaluate the situation and
(allow) each to express his opinion .. to agree and reach a
consensus.''
	   A senior Jordanian government official said that Jordan
``prefers that no conditions be placed prior to convening the
parley.'' The official spoke on condition of anonymity.
	   Anani said the summit's agenda will figure high in talks during
the two-day visit by the Saudi prince.
	   Emphasizing the importance of his visit, Abdullah was received
at the airport by King Hussein in a rare protocol gesture reserved
only for heads of state. The two leaders are scheduled to meet
privately.
	   Abdullah is the first top Saudi official to visit Jordan since
1990 when relations strained over Amman's perceived tilt toward
Iraq following its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
	   Meanwhile, the issue of Iraq is causing problems for the summit
too.
	   Most Gulf states oppose inviting Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
to the summit because of Gulf War rivalry. Syria says Iraq's
presence is needed for a united stance against Israel.
	   Several Arab countries also are unwilling to attend a summit
while the United States still is mediating on the Palestinian
issue. Once Washington announces its efforts have failed, Arafat
would likely meet less resistance.
	   Arafat began pushing for the summit after the United States
failed to convince Netanyahu to accept a compromise of a further 13
percent troops pullback in the West Bank to restart talks. Arafat,
who wanted 30 percent, has accepted.
  sn-ggl/jjh/vj
</TEXT>
