<BODY>
<SLUG> SMALL-INDUSTRIES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Big focus on small industries, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws SMALL-INDUSTRIES sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   ALMOST every major information technology (IT) vendor is now
targeting the small and medium-sized industries (SMIs) with a
variety of offerings. Ask the people at IBM, Hewlett-Packard,
Compaq, Digital and others, and they will talk about their plans
and programmes to make headway in the SMI market. For them, this is
where their growth, or a sizeable portion of their business, is
going to come from this year.
	   Yes, size does matter and in this case, it's the small that is
expected to present the ``huge opportunity'' long sought by IT
vendors. The vendors, after taking a good look at what they have,
are packaging and re-packaging their products and services
specially to meet the needs of the SMIs.
	   Among the latest was Computer Associates which has packaged its
enterprise management offering Unicenter TNG into so-called
no-frills workgroup edition products. These are designed to be the
entry point into the company's extensive offerings, and aimed at
customers with less than 250 desktop clients. With the products
broken up into modules, customers only buy what they need and cost
is, of course, very much lower.
	   Based on research carried out by the US-based Aberdeen Group,
there is an untapped worldwide market of 1.5 million workgroup
units, and this is probably what CA is going for with its workgroup
edition products.
	   The SMI market, according to market researcher IDC Malaysia,
represents ``growth potential'' for IT vendors, especially when the
region is experiencing an economic downturn. The percentage of IT
usage in this sector is still considered low, as it was estimated
that 90 per cent of the companies have yet to computerise or still
require some form of computerisation. Most of those which have
computerised have employed IT mainly to process data. IT is used to
support operations, in areas such as accounting, human resource and
inventory management, and purchasing.
	   But IDC believes that IT usage is still remarkably low and these
companies will still have to spend on technology to save on
operational costs, and improve productivity in order to compete
effectively.
	   IDC Malaysia conducted a survey on the IT spending of local
companies, dividing them into small, medium and large. It was
interesting to note that 23.9 per cent of the small companies plan
to increase their IT spending this year. Even more encouraging was
that 26.5 per cent of the medium-sized companies which responded
also want to spend more on IT.
	   Under the current situation, large businesses are more likely to
leverage on their existing IT infrastructure. Instead of replacing
or increasing the IT equipment they have, they are more likely to
maintain what they already have. Here, there's still an opportunity
in the need for extended services and support. However, 34.6 per
cent of the large companies that took part in the IDC survey
informed that they intend to increase their IT spending this year.
So, not everyone is going to hold back.
	   Another trend noted in the survey was that 39.9 per cent of the
small companies and 35.4 per cent of the medium-sized were still
unsure whether to invest in IT. There is therefore a need to
promote awareness among SMIs on how they can use technology to make
their business more efficient.
	   Here's an opportunity for them to raise their level of
operations, and look into how local area networks (LANs), the
Internet and intranets can help them. They should be more willing
to invest, not just to survive but to plan ahead.
	   No wonder most of the vendors are already looking eagerly at the
SMIs.
	   Here's a growing opportunity to present new technologies and
products and services that could make a difference. In light of the
emphasis on SMIs, the grant scheme announced recently by the Small
and Medium Industries Development Corp (Smidec) to introduce a
grant scheme to promote greater adoption of IT by SMIs is a move in
the right direction.
	   Under the programme, SMIs are able to obtain financial
assistance in the purchase of manufacturing software. Smidec
proposed to finance 50 per cent of the total cost of the
manufacturing solutions purchased. Hopefully, the programme can be
expanded so that more small and medium-sized companies can reap the
benefits, and in the process become bigger.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
