r w     HOW-THEY-FAREsked     06-01 2952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> HOW-THEY-FARE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
How they fare, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws HOW-THEY-FARE sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   Amway (Malaysia) Holdings Bhd is one of the top direct selling
companies in the country. Based on its 1997 annual report, the
company has fixed deposits of RM162.84 million, banker's
acceptances of RM114.74 million and cash balances of RM4 million.
It has a relatively clean balance sheet but its exposure to the US$
may be a cause of concern as the goods the company deals with are
mostly imported. Despite its US$ exposure, some analysts are upbeat
that the cash pile will not erode significantly.
	   DETERMINING the cash surplus of a public listed company is not
easy.
	   Based on the best available published figures and feedback from
research houses, we have attempted to compile a list of companies
with favourable cash positions. However, in evaluating the strength
of a company it must be remembered that there are several other
factors to consider as well, such as their long- and short-term
loans, the nature of business they are in and where they propose to
eventually invest this cash. Below are some companies with at least
RM150 million and above, based on latest published reports.
	   Amway (Malaysia) Holdings Bhd is one of the top direct selling
companies in the country. Based on its 1997 annual report, the
company has fixed deposits of RM162.84 million, banker's
acceptances of RM114.74 million and cash balances of RM4 million.
It has a relatively clean balance sheet but its exposure to the US$
may be a cause of concern as the goods the company deals with are
mostly imported. Despite its US$ exposure, some analysts are upbeat
that the cash pile will not erode significantly.
	   Datuk Keramat Holdings Bhd: Based on its 1997 annual report, the
company has deposits, bank and cash balances totalling RM595
million, mostly generated from the sale of its stake in the then
UMBC Bank to the Sime Darby Group. With short term borrowings of
RM150 million, the company appears to have a net cash holding of
about RM450 million. But much of it will be utilised to finance its
acquisition of a Swiss bank.
	   Golden Hope Plantations Bhd: After Kuala Lumpur Kepong Bhd, this
PNB-linked plantation counter is perhaps the second most cash-rich
company in that sector with about RM400 million in cash and short
term deposits. With palm oil prices soaring with the depreciation
of the ringgit, Golden Hope is expected to further enhance its cash
position.
	   The only setback is the exposure of its 61 per cent subsidiary
Negara Properties to the real estate sector. With its healthy cash
position, Golden Hope may be called upon to play the role of a
white knight.
	   Genting Group: Even after subsidary Resorts World bought a 20
per cent stake in Star Cruises Plc for about RM950 million, the
group (which derives its main source of income from its gaming and
resort operations at Genting Highlands, Pahang) still has a cash
pile of RM2.5 billion left.
	   With so much cash, analysts feel the group is finding it harder
to make investment decisions. Among its investments in the past,
only the power project in Genting Sanyen seems to have paid off so
far. Even the Star Cruises investment is viewed with some sceptism
as the cruise business in general is affected by an economic
downturn.
	   The group does not have any substantial liability at the moment
but it remains to be seen if it can maintain a clean slate as the
cruise business is capital intensive and Star Cruises is expected
to add to its growing fleet in the next two years.
	   Kuala Lumpur Kepong Bhd (KLK): As of last year, the company was
sitting on a cash pile of RM400 million. This figure is expected to
rise to more than RM500 million by next year due to the healthy
prices of palm oil. The company is one of the solid plantation
stocks with conservative investment plans.
	   KLK is a 42 per cent associate of Batu Kawan Bhd, another
plantation stock. The negative element is that Batu Kawan has a 30
per cent stake in stock broking firm Smith-Zain Securities and some
exposure to property in mainland Penang. With the stock broking
industry in the doldrums, some analysts wonder if some of KLK's
cash surplus may be re-deployed elsewhere. However, analyst Liew
Kok Wai of BNP PrimeEast Research does not think such a
re-deployment will happen as Batu Kawan is conservative and
Smith-Zain Securities is well run.
	   Malaysian International Shipping Corporation (MISC): The
country's premier shipping company had RM836.96 million in cash
deposits and bank balances as of December 1997. A portion of this
is expected to go into buying ships and tankers belonging to
Konsortium Perkapalan Bhd (KPB) for cash. MISC has already entered
into an agreement with KPB to purchase PNSL Ltd for US$ 55 million
cash. Besides that MISC will also acquire a few more assets of KPB.
	   After the acquisition, MISC's gearing will go up from 0.23 to
1.26.
	   Based on the latest annual report, its long term liabilities are
RM893.81 million. With the deal, MISC will have to assume all debts
of KPB which is close to US$ 310 million.
	   Perusahaan Otomobil Nasional Bhd (Proton): According to its 1997
annual report, cash and bank balances amount to RM1.46 billion. But
short term borrowings come up to RM109 million and long term
liabilities to RM357.47 million.
	   For the current year Proton, like most other automobile
companies, is expected to see a dip in earnings. Thus the surplus
cash may come in handy. Also, Proton needs to spend about RM500
million in developing new models to replace its Iswara and Wira
models.
	   Star Publications (M) Bhd: It has a strong cash position - RM212
million in deposits and cash balances with virtually no borrowings.
Like most publishing companies, the setback is the rising cost of
newsprint due to the ringgit's depreciation. An anaylst says that
it is yet to be seen how the company manages its cash and whether
it makes a wise investment decision. So far, the company's recent
purchase of its new headquarters building in Petaling Jaya has not
been viewed favourably as some feel the company could have waited
for property prices to come down further.
	   Telekom Malaysia Bhd: Has cash and cash equivalent amounting to
RM2.35 billion. But the premier telecommunications company in the
country has total borrowings of RM6.4 billion. Of this, RM283
million is due within one year and another RM984 million due after
one year but within the next five years. The hefty cash balance
will come in handy for Telekom in its expansion plans as it gears
for foreign competition next year.
	   Sime UEP Properties Bhd: A subsidiary of the diversified
conglomerate Sime Darby Bhd, it stands out among property stocks
with a cash position of RM360 million and virtually no borrowings.
It is also noted for its prudent and conservative management style.
It has an ample, cheap yet well-located landbank with a book cost
of less than RM2.00 psf.
	   The only fear is that the parent, Sime Darby, has reported a
loss for the first time in more than a decade due to its disastrous
move into the banking sector. Though some analysts doubt that any
cash from Sime UEP will be used to help out Sime Darby with its
cash flow, the possibility still exists.
	   Berjaya Sports Toto Bhd: This number forecast operator (NFO) has
deposits worth RM213 million and cash and bank balances of RM66.52
million based on its 1997 annual report. This total of RM279.5
million is less than the other two NFO players mainly because of
its track record of high dividend payments. It is these lucrative
dividend payments that make some analysts rule out the possibility
of BToto's cash reserves being channelled to other Berjaya
companies.
	   Magnum Corporation Bhd: Cash and bank balances of this company
is estimated at about half a billion ringgit, giving it a cash per
share of about 33 sen per share. The company had even more money in
quoted investments: RM603.2 million as at Dec 31, 1996. The bulk of
this - RM430.3 million - was invested in stocks on the Kuala Lumpur
Stock Exchange directly or through unit trusts.
	   In its latest unaudited results for the year ended Dec 31, 1997,
the group admitted that the currency and stock market turbulence in
the region since last July had affected it. This has resulted in
the group having to set aside RM425.82m as provision for diminution
in value of this investment. In addition, there was a provision for
a further RM94.137 million for unrealised loss in foreign exchange
in respect of a foreign currency loan taken by a subsidiary.
Analysts say the company has foreign borrowings of about US$200
million.
	   Tanjong Plc: With about RM800 million in deposits and cash and
bankbalances, Tanjong has been one of the first few cash-rich
companies to announce what it plans to do with its money. It has
proposed to buy a 47 per cent stake in independent power producer,
Powertek Bhd, which will wipe out RM480 million from its cash
reserves.
	   If the deal goes through, it would trigger of a mandatory
general offer (MGO) for the remaining shares. This could drain
Tanjong's remaining cash and force it to take on borrowings,
thereby breaking its debt-free status.
	   Carlsberg Brewery Malaysia Bhd: This leading beer maker is not
only well known for its alcoholic beverage but also for its clean
balance sheet. A track record of keeping to its core business and
rewarding its shareholders with high dividends and bonus issues
lays to rest fears of Carlsberg using its cash reserves unwisely.
For the year ended Dec 31, 1997, bank balances and deposits were at
RM266.7 million. It is also a debt-free company.
	   Hap Seng Consolidated Bhd is sitting pretty on a cash pile of
RM256.6 million, made up of cash and bank balances and deposits
with banks. Its strong cash flow and zero borrowings puts it in a
good position to utilise its cash when opportunities present
themselves.
	   Analysts say the money could be used to expand Hap Seng's oil
palm operations or its food and beverage business, which currently
include a brewery in China and a 25 per cent stake in Carlsberg
Brewery Malaysia Bhd.
	   One worry is that controlling shareholder, Malaysian Mosaics
Berhad has the ability, through its 50.11 per cent stake in Hap
Seng, to tap into Hap Seng's cash via the injection of assets. Will
it happen? Analysts say that judging by Hap Seng's track record,
this is an unlikely prospect.
	   Matsushita Electric Company (Malaysia) Berhad was sitting on a
cash pile of RM178.5 million as at March 31, 1997, and it is likely
this money will remain with the electrical manufacturer for some
time to come. Reason: The conservative stance is traditional with
Japanese companies which only use their money as and when they need
it for expansion. Matsushita is also debt free.
	   YTL Corporation Bhd: The YTL group has two listed cash rich
entities, namely YTL Corp with RM3.63 billion and its 61-per cent
subsidiary , YTL Power with RM2.59 billion. However YTL Corp has
pledged the bulk of its cash reserves - RM2.14 billion - to a
financial institution for a bank guarantee facility granted to one
of its subsidiaries. YTL Corp also has cash balances of RM93
million but this is expected to be used to redeem bonds upon
maturity. It also has term loans of RM707.12 million payable within
one year and another RM905.86 million due after one year but within
five years.
	   YTL Power has close to RM2.55 billion in term loans, made up of
bank loans (RM1.11 billion) and fixed rate bonds (RM1.43 billion).
Most of these loans are repayable after more than a year. This is a
positive note in light of the fact that being an IPP, it is assured
of a fixed annual turnover of more than RM1.17 billion, by virtue
of its power purchase agreement with Tenaga Nasional Bhd. Analysts
believe that the YTL group as a whole has more than RM1 billion
available for investments or capital expenditure.
	   Selangor Properties Bhd is one of the few property companies
said to have huge cash reserves. As at Oct 31, 1997, this company
had cash and cash equivalents of over RM450 million and was debt
free. This gives it a cash to share ratio of RM1.30. It has a
steady stream of income from rentals from its commercial properties
which are concentrated in the Damansara area. However, its cash
pile might be reduced as the company is acquiring a piece of land
for RM335.41 million cash payable over five years.
	   Tan Chong Motor Holdings Bhd's net cash position is expected to
reach more than RM200 million by the end of this year. Analysts say
this is good for the company as it will put it in a strong position
to weather the current downcycle in vehicle sales and capitalise on
the eventual recovery of the motor industry.
	   However, the bulk of this amount may go to finance the company's
proposed share buy back scheme of 10 per cent of its share capital.
	   However, analysts add that it is unlikely the company will buy
back the shares all at once and, instead, may stagger the buy back
process. Also, some of its cash may go toward a special dividend
the company will be giving as part of its demerger exercise.
	   Sapura Telecommunications Bhd's cash reserves were boosted after
the disposal of stakes in Uniphone Sdn Bhd and Sapura Digital Sdn
Bhd to Time RM452.66 million. About half this money however was
used to retire loans.
	   Although Sapura has yet to do anything with the balance of about
RM264 million, analysts say that based on a recent increase in the
company's interest income, the money is believed to be parked in
banks and finance companies. However, at about the same time,
Sapura has proposed to acquire stakes in companies belonging to
parent, Sapura Holdings Sdn Bhd (SHSB).
	   These transactions should reduce Sapura's cash reserves.
	   As at Jan 31, 1997, Sapura's bank borrowings stood at RM266.22
million.
	   Rothmans of Pall Mall Malaysia Bhd: Known for giving out one of
the highest dividends, Rothmans has about RM560 in its bank and
cash balances.
	   This debt-free company also has bank guaranteed corporate bonds
and loan stock of RM49.6 million at cost and Malaysian government
securities of RM52.7 million at cost. Taking the latter's cash
equivalents into account, Rothmans is sitting pretty on RM662.3
million. Analysts say that based on Rothman's track record, when
its cash and bank balances reach between RM600 million and RM700
million, this would trigger off a special cash dividend. This means
Rothman's will most probably be paying back its reserves to its
shareholders.
	   Gamuda Berhad: This construction giant has about RM253.5 million
in deposits and RM12.7 million in cash and bank balances. However,
according to the 1997 annual report, its bank borrowings, made up
of term loans, overdrafts and banker's acceptances amount to RM10.5
million. The company also has issued long term bonds worth RM190
million which will expire in 2000 and 2001.
	   The company's investments amount to RM60.8 million at cost and
are mostly invested in investment management funds within Malaysia
(RM10.3 million) and outside Malaysia (RM50.4 million). This would
give it a total cash and cash equivalents of RM327 million but
total long and short term borrowings of RM200.5 million. Analysts
say that although the company has cash, much of it is tied up with
its highway projects in the city.
	   Petronas Gas Bhd: The 74.92 per cent subsidiary of Petronas sat
on a cash pile of RM898.13 million as at March 31 last year.
However, it has long term loans of RM2.31 billion including
Yen-denominated bonds. The bright spark is that Petronas Gas has an
assured earnings stream by processing gas generated from its parent
to service the loans. Also it has already paid for the bulk of its
capital expenditure to increase the gas processing facility in
Terengganu.
	   Trenergy (Malaysia) Bhd: The second board company is believed to
have close to RM300 million following the sale of its US-based
Hercules Offshore Corporation (HOC). When the company acquired HOC
in 1996, nobody thought much of it. However, it sold HOC early this
year when the US$ was at its peak against the ringgit and this
translated into a hefty extraordinary gain for Trenergy.
	   However, the bulk of the money is to be used to refurbish a
vessel into a floating, production, storage and off-loading
facility. The facility is to be leased to Petronas in a long term
contract worth more than RM500 million. Some analysts feel another
setback is that Trenergy is closely linked to the cash-strapped
Renong Group.
	   Daiman Development Berhad: This property-based company has fixed
deposits and cash balances of RM144.5 million as of June last year.
But analysts believe this cash pile may have increased to RM156
million as of December last year. However a portion of this -
RM25.7 million - is pledged to banks to secure bank guarantees and
a term loan of RM15.5 million. This still leaves it with over RM100
million in cash. Analysts who follow this counter say the company
has a good track record in terms of cash management.
	   
</TEXT>
