<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Botha Trial, 2nd-Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Truth Body says Botha knew ANC activists were to be killed apartheid-era assassin may testify 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: (AMs) UPDATES with cross-examination and possibility that
AP Photos GEO101-102
By PAUL HARRIS
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   GEORGE, South Africa (AP) _ A top official of the Truth and
Reconciliation Commission on Monday indirectly blamed former
President P.W. Botha for the killings of black activists during
apartheid.
	   Botha is on trial for ignoring a summons to appear before the
Truth Commission, which is probing apartheid-era human rights
abuses. But the trial _ the first ever of a former South African
head of state _ has focused on Botha's role as chairman of the
State Security Council, which coordinated a security crackdown on
black liberation groups.
	   Truth Commission executive secretary Paul van Zyl said minutes
from State Security Council meetings contained words like
``eliminate'' and ``neutralize'' when referring to opponents of
white rule. Botha headed the security council when he was head of
state.
	   ``It is quite clear from these documents, as we interpret it,
the word eliminate means kill,'' van Zyl said shortly after Botha's
trial resumed Monday after being postponed for six weeks.
	   In showing why it wants to question Botha, the Truth Commission
has presented the court in this southern coastal town with dozens
of documents implicating Botha, who led South Africa from
1978-1989, in atrocities.
	   Van Zyl said the Security Council had been briefed in 1979 about
plans to launch overseas operations against members of the African
National Congress, including sending bombs in the mail.
	   Wearing a dark suit and foregoing a cane which he has normally
used since a hip replacement last year, Botha impassively listened
to the testimony.
	   His lawyer, Lappe Laubscher, complained that van Zyl was
diverting the case to uncovering Security Council deeds.
	   ``Both of us are going to retire in George if you continue like
this,'' Laubscher joked.
	   Botha, 82, had greeted the supporters as he entered the court,
located near his retirement home in the village of Wilderness.
	   Prosecutor Bruce Morrison raised the possibility that Eugene de
Kock, a former police colonel who headed a group of apartheid-era
assassins, may testify.
	   De Kock, currently serving a life prison term, carried out the
1988 bombing of an anti-apartheid group's offices. Former national
police chief Johan van der Merwe has told the Truth Commission that
Botha authorized the attack.
	   Morrison said he wanted to ``consult'' with 4panel wants
to humiliate him by forcing him to appear in person.
	   He faces two years imprisonment and unspecified fines if
convicted.
	   (ph-aos)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-South Africa-Botha Trial, 2nd-Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
