<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 11:48:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2968  wstm-
r w     SINGAPORE-BUSINESSsked     06-01 1401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> SINGAPORE-BUSINESS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Singapore business, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws SINGAPORE-BUSINESS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   IT'S FUNNY how sentiment on a stock can swing so wildly in a
space of just six months. For most of last year, Singapore Telecom
(SingTel) was under tremendous selling pressure. The reasons: the
onslaught of competition in the mobile communications sector and
its high share price relative to other regional telecom companies.
	   Consequently, in the initial weeks after April 1, 1997, - the
day SingTel lost its monopoly in the mobile phone and paging
markets - its share price hit one record low after another. It sank
to a depth of S$2.05 in September. Some S$19 billion in market
capitalisation was wiped out. In the six months to September,
SingTel underperformed the entire market by 17 per cent.
	   But a twist of fortune came with the unlikeliest of events - the
regional currency crisis. With its predictable earnings stream and
huge cash pile, SingTel rose from the deep to emerge as `an island
of stability in a sea of volatility'.
	   Asian funds muscled their way onto SingTel's share register. By
March 5, SingTel shares had regained all their losses and more. In
the last six months, the share price gained S$1.21 to S$3.26 -
outperforming the Stock Exchange of Singapore's All Shares Index by
a staggering 55 per cent.
	   Analysts are now singing a slightly different tune, swayed
partly by SingTel's sterling 12 per cent growth in interim
earnings.
	   A number have since upgraded their calls: from sell to hold,
from hold to buy or accumulate. According to The Estimate
Directory, 60 per cent of analysts who track SingTel are now
recommending a buy or a hold. This compares to below 50 per cent in
November.
	   Houses which have upgraded their calls include Credit Lyonnais,
ING Barings, GK Goh, Tsang  Ong and UBS.
	   GK Goh's Alayne Wong says, `Under current market conditions,
SingTel's defensive nature overrides its premium valuation.' She
recommends SingTel as a core portfolio holding for the Singapore
market.
	   ING Barings' regional telecom analyst Gautam Kapoor argues that
although SingTel is overvalued in some parameters, these parameters
do not capture qualitative issues.
	   For example, they do not take into consideration replacement
costs, the management team and other local conditions. `At the end
of the day, it depends on the market. SingTel is operating in an
environment with more certainty. It's a safe stock with good
earnings visibility,' he says.
	   Analysts think that SingTel will continue to be a good place to
park one's money until the financial storm in Southeast Asia blows
over.
	   However, most refrain from setting a price target for SingTel.
	   So, fundamentally, compared with six months ago, what has
changed about SingTel? For one thing, the financial crisis has
jacked up interest rates.
	   SingTel, with its cash hoard amounting to some S$4 billion,
looks set to benefit in higher interest income.
	   But operationally, there will be adverse impact, as SingTel
readily admits. `Traditionally, there is a strong correlation
between our earnings and the level of economic activity both in
Singapore and the region,' says the group's investor relations
manager Karena Tay. `The current regional turmoil is expected to
impact on Singapore's economy, and telecommunications business will
likewise be affected.' The writing could already be on the wall.
Outgoing international telephone calls, which contribute 44 per
cent to SingTel's group turnover, grew by a mere 2.3 per cent in
volume terms in January this year. This pales in comparison to the
double-digit year-on-year growth the business enjoyed throughout
1997.
	   As for the appreciation of the Singapore dollar against the
regional units and its depreciation against other major currencies
in the West, they cut both ways.
	   First, on the expenses side, SingTel will now have to fork out
more to pay for traffic expenses, the fees it pays other telcos to
complete international calls. These expenses - SingTel's largest
cost component -are denominated in Special Drawing Rights (SDR)
which are pegged to a basket of major currencies. On the other
hand, income from its foreign associate Belgacom will now translate
into 10 per cent more Singapore dollars.
	   The plunge in regional currencies has also meant that SingTel's
investments in Indonesia and the Philippines are worth a fraction
of their earlier valuations. The investment cost in Globe Telecom,
for instance, was S$155.7 million. At today's prices and exchange
rates, the value is now down to a fifth at about S$31.6 million. In
Indonesia, the group has invested S$28 million as at March 31 last
year in its joint venture PT SingTel Bukaka.
	   But on the bright side, SingTel's share of Globe Telecom's
losses, too, will be very much less. The crisis could also present
SingTel with opportunities to buy up regional assets at bargain
prices.
	   Overall, analysts think SingTel will weather the storm well. The
consensus earning forecast for SingTel is still a healthy 13 per
cent growth for the financial year ending March 31, 1998, and 11
per cent for 1999.
	   Paribas Asia Equity's senior telecom analyst Neil Juggins is
more bullish. He expects SingTel to post a 15.3 per cent surge in
net profit to S$1.914 billion this year, followed by another 13.8
per cent next year to S$2.178 billion. SingTel shares, he says,
will outperform the market in the next 12 months.
	   Analysts anticipate earnings growth to come from local and
international calls as well as value-added services. ING Barings'
Gautam Kapoor sees increased profit in the cellular business as
well, despite SingTel's loss of market share. This, he said, could
be achieved with better cost control.
	   Meanwhile, SingTel has smartened up a lot after its first taste
of competition. It is more market-savvy now and its ads are being
noticed. It is assiduously building up its brand name and gearing
up for competition in the fixed-line and international calls
businesses by 2000.
	   It has stepped up efforts, and has been enjoying some success,
in pulling second or third lines to homes. There is still room for
growth as new demand will come from new homes and businesses and
new multimedia services like Magix. Last year's line growth of 9.4
per cent is the highest SingTel has had for the last 15 years.
	   And when full competition ensues, SingTel is set to be a tough
contender. Today, SingTel is as competitive as, if not more than,
any telco in the region. According to a study by the National
University of Singapore, SingTel's rates are the cheapest in this
part of the world, ahead of Australia's Telstra, HK Telecom and
Japan's KDD.
	   Beyond 2000, SingTel expects overseas investments to contribute
about 10 per cent to its bottomline. A new earnings stream is also
expected from its first satellite to be launched this year, ST-1.
The satellite could potentially rake in revenues of S$42 million a
year.
	   But a word of caution before you rush in to buy more SingTel
shares.
	   Some analysts think SingTel is only good while the going is
tough. And once the financial markets stabilise, the stock will
lose its safe-haven status.
	   At S$3.24 as at March 6 (price earnings: 26 times on expected
1999 earnings), it is one of the most expensive telecom stocks
around.
	   Merrill Lynch's Adam Quinton, who is advising his clients to
reduce holdings of SingTel shares, says the group's cashflow and
earnings growth are not compelling enough to sustain the current
price. `SingTel is going to underperform the market in the long
term.' For now, however, the fallout in the region, which could
last well into 1999, should keep SingTel in the limelight. -
Singapore Business 
</TEXT>
