Telekom wants to turn Mobikom into major earner, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws TELEKOM-WANTS-TO-TURN sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   TELEKOM Malaysia Berhad is confident of turning the Mobikom
cellular service into a profitable business with the proposed
upgrading of infrastructure and injection of expertise.
	   Its chairman Datuk Ali Hassan said with Telekom's years of
experience in the telecommunications sector, it could turn Mobikom
into one of its biggest revenue earners in future.
	   Ali said Mobikom also stood to contribute a great deal to
Telekom compared to other cellular services it operated because of
Mobikom's large subscriber base of 300,000.
	   Telekom also operates two other cellular services, the Atur 450
which has about 80,000 active subscribers and TM Touch which has
120,000 active subscribers.
	   He said this when commenting on Telekom's takeover of mobile
phone operator Mobikom Sdn Bhd for RM232.7 million on May 14.
	   Ali was speaking to reporters after launching the northern
region World Telecommunications Day celebrations at the Alor Star
telecommunications tower on Saturday.
	   Also present were Menteri Besar Tan Sri Sanusi Junid, Telekom
chief operating officer for telephony Datuk Dr Rahim Daud,
Kedah/Perlis chief business operations officer Sharoom Cha and
State executive councillors.
	   Earlier in his speech, Ali said to date Telekom had completed 92
of 200 proposed infrastructure projects in the State. This includes
84 fibre optic projects.
	   
</TEXT>
