r w     GANAD-IS-CONFIDENTsked     06-01 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> GANAD-IS-CONFIDENT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Ganad is confident of thriving in lean times, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws GANAD-IS-CONFIDENT sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   AS a sign of the difficult times, the advertising industry is
usually one of the first to be hit as companies begin to slash
marketing budgets in order to conserve cash flow.
	   The ardent television viewer will have noticed that there are
fewer commercials and that music videos have made a comeback to
fill airtime in-between shows.
	   In an increasingly competitive market, outdoor advertising firm
Ganad Corporation Bhd remains optimistic it will be able to sustain
itself during these lean times on its many long-term contracts
(usually three to five years) sealed with multinational
corporations.
	   Some of its customers include Citibank, Toyota, Samsung and
Marlboro.
	   Assistant general manager Cheng Kee How said despite a
consolidation in spending, Ganad would push for a bigger slice of
the market, targeting about a third of new business.
	   ``We are very aggressive and are discussing with some
multinational corporations for new business.
	   ``This will offset the industry slowdown and we will maintain
our business,'' he said in an interview in Kuala Lumpur.
	   Cheng said some of the multinational companies have contracts
with Ganad's associate companies abroad.
	   Ganad began regional expansion a few years ago into Myanmar,
Cambodia, Thailand and China.
	   Assessing the outdoor advertising segment, Cheng said it
remained a small portion of the entire advertising industry and had
seen a 20 per cent to 30 per cent reduction in spending.
	   The other segments of the industry comprise television, radio,
newspapers, magazines, rediffusion, video, cinema and
point-of-sale.
	   Newspapers command the largest slice of total advertising
dollars at 60 per cent, or RM1.59 billion of a total RM2.61 billion
last year.
	   Nevertheless, Cheng said there had been a shift towards more
outdoor advertising since television programming became more
cluttered.
	   With more new highways and expressways, prospects for the
outdoor advertising segment are on the rise.
	   He cited highways to the Kuala Lumpur International Airport as a
good location to project the corporate image of multinational firms
to visitors.
	   ``Visitors will also have confidence in a country when they see
the advertisements of big multinationals, and so outdoor
advertising is serving its purpose in that way.''
	   With the Commonwealth Games in September, Ganad is doing its bit
to promote the event.
	   It is sponsoring some 70 billboard sites nationwide, worth a
total of RM20,000 each. The campaign, which began six months ago,
now sees some 50 billboards erected.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:GANAD-IS-CONFIDENT sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
