<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 11:52:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2979  wstm-
r w     GAINFUL-GUIDELINEsked     06-01 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> GAINFUL-GUIDELINE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Gainful guideline, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws GAINFUL-GUIDELINE sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE inclusion of independent market research in the Securities
Commission's (SC's) requirement for listing exercises on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange in 1996 has proven to be a boon for Sofres
Group, a French-based market researcher.
	   Sofres FSA Malaysia (formerly Frank Small  Associates) managing
director Iain R Bell explains, `Companies now need to provide
market research reports on the particular industry they are
involved in, which include nature of industry, list of key players,
market size, outlook and areas of growth for the industry for the
next five years. This is where Sofres Malaysia has an advantage
with the backing of the Sofres Group. The Malaysian operations have
grown to become the largest Asia-Pacific office of the group, which
has a total of 23 offices in 12 Asia-Pacific countries,' he
enthuses.
	   `Market research in Malaysia is undergoing a renaissance of
sorts where an increasing number of local and multinational
companies are looking to the industry as an important component of
their business and marketing strategies,' he says.
	   He continues that the demand for market research services is on
the uptrend, both locally and globally, as businesses are
increasingly aware that research has a positive effect on their bid
to stay ahead. Knowledge of business markets, customer needs and
identification of new opportunities are paramount to sustaining or
expanding the business.
	   Market research plays a critical role in the success of a
company, as it assists organisations to fulfil their objectives by
providing detailed, cost-effective and timely market information,
along with quality interpretation, analysis and understanding that
form the basis for the development of optimal strategic planning.
	   In fact, this was the basis of the group's latest merger last
November with United Kingdom-based Taylor Nelson AGB, resulting in
the creation of the fourth largest market research company in the
world, which recorded a turnover of US$ 450 million for FY December
1997. The merger involved Taylor Nelson acquiring STG119 million
worth of shares in Sofres' holding company. Subsequently, it was
listed on the London Stock Exchange and is managed by directors
from both companies.
	   The new entity, Taylor Nelson Sofres (TNS), has a network of
over 4,000 professionals in 32 countries. The merger creates one of
the widest product ranges in the industry, combining Sofres' and
Taylor Nelson's combined strengths in continuous panels, databases
and branded research products. Bell expands on the operations of
Sofres Malaysia, `1996 was a good year with almost 70 per cent of
our revenue coming from market research for listing exercises. But
with the SC clamping down on new listings last year, the company
has now ventured into other areas of growth.' The total number of
companies supported by Sofres Malaysia for their listing exercise
between 1996 and 1997 stands at 23, involving a wide range of
industries. Apart from this, the company had done 19 independent
market reports for various industries in 1996, while the number of
independent market reports rose to 21 in 1997.
	   He highlights that the local market research industry in 1997
was RM52 million and this is estimated to increase to RM60 million
in 1998. Sofres Malaysia has recorded between a 15 per cent and 20
per cent revenue growth for the past five years, and is expected to
peg a 18 per cent growth in revenue this year. Furthermore, 22 per
cent of total revenue is derived from overseas clients.
	   `Sofres Malaysia has a 31 per cent market share in the industry
while Survey Research Malaysia (SRG Nielson) has a 45 per cent
market share. The remaining market share is divided among other
players in the industry.
	   There are about 12 to 15 research companies in the country, some
local while others are offices of regional companies,' he divulges.
	   A further boost to the Malaysian operations comes in the form of
being the only market research firm in Asia to achieve QCSI
(Quality Control System for Interviewing) accredition. Bell
elaborates, `Over 152,000 interviews were conducted in 1997 all on
an ad-hoc basis. In the same period, more than 450 focus groups and
550 individual jobs were also conducted.' According to Sofres
Malaysia associate director Supramaniam Letchumanan, the company
comprises 120 staff and has five core divisions -consumer, business
and property, services, media, and social and community. In
addition, there are six specialist units - healthcare/personal
care, telecommunications, food and beverage, automotive, financial,
advertising testing/ tracking.
	   `The consumer division (FMCG) forms 50.4 per cent of the total
business done, followed by high tech/telecom/business to business
research - 23 per cent, media - 9.4 per cent, corporate
communication/human resource - 8.1 per cent, and automotive - 4.2
per cent. The rest of the divisions contribute a minimal amount,'
he says.
	   Currently, Sofres Malaysia is focusing on market sectors of real
growth in terms of research and development which is in the areas
of pharmaceuticals, automotives, telecommunications, information
technology and healthcare. Bell emphasises that apart from
providing research materials for overseas companies to enter the
local market, the current trend is for more local companies to test
the overseas markets.
	   `In fact, the SC's requirement for companies to have market
research done is a boon in more ways than one. Although most of our
clients started the research for the purpose of listing, somewhere
along the line, they realised that the research was useful for many
other things,' he says.
	   In the near future, the Malaysian operations will be introducing
other products which are being marketed by the group. He cites the
financial public relations research - which is a tool to improve
share value, make it easier to raise capital in financial markets
and develop more effective corporate communications - as an
example.
	   The financial public relations research product has been
marketed in France and Europe successfully for the past five to six
years, and will be launched in Malaysia within two months. `We are
looking at a contribution of between 10 per cent and 15 per cent of
the revenue from this product in France and expect similar
contributions to the Malaysian operations once the product is
introduced here. In the course of time, other products will also be
introduced in Malaysia,' he adds. 
</TEXT>
