<HEADLINE>
Biggest mergers and acquisitions of world companies With US-Monsanto-American Home 
</HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
	   World's largest mergers and acquisitions:
	   (U.S. corporate figures are based on Friday's, May 29, closing
stock prices)
	   1. Travelers Group and Citicorp agree to a merger that values
each company at dlrs 69.5 billion, announced April 6, 1998.
Pending.
	   2. SBC Communications Inc. announces plan May 11 to buy
Ameritech Corp. for dlrs 61.7 billion in stock. Pending.
	   3. NationsBank Corp. and BankAmerica Corp. announce plan April
13 for dlrs 58.5 billion merger, becoming the No. 1 U.S. bank with
dlrs 570 billion in assets. Pending.
	   4. WorldCom Inc. agreement to buy MCI Communications Inc. for
stock valued at about dlrs 37 billion, announced Nov. 10, 1997.
Pending.
	   5. Daimler-Benz agrees to buy Chrysler Corp. for about dlrs 34.9
billion in stock, announced May 7. Pending.
	   6. Mitsubishi Bank and Bank of Tokyo agree to merger for dlrs
33.8 billion, completed in 1996. Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi is the
largest bank worldwide, with more than dlrs 720 billion in assets.
	   7. American Home Products announces June 1 it will buy Monsanto
Corp. in stock swap valued at dlrs 33 billion. Pending.
	   8. Sandoz AG agreement to merge with Ciba-Geigy AG for dlrs 30
billion, completed in 1997.
	   9. Banc One Corp. and First Chicago NBD Corp. announce plan
April 13 for dlrs 27.5 billion merger. Pending.
	   10. Union Bank of Switzerland agreement to buy Swiss Bank Corp.
for dlrs 25.8 billion. Pending.
	   11. Bell Atlantic Corp. combines with Nynex Corp. in an exchange
of stock valued at dlrs 25.6 billion, completed in 1997.
	   12. RJR Nabisco Inc. merger with Kohlberg Kravis Roberts and
Co., dlrs 25 billion, completed in 1989.
</TEXT>
