<HEADER>
w2989  wstm-
r w     REDUCING-STRESSsked     06-01 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> REDUCING-STRESS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Reducing stress at workplace, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws REDUCING-STRESS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   JARRAD, a 39-year-old computer programmer, was diagnosed with
high blood pressure. He had sought medical help for headaches,
tiredness and trouble sleeping. When his doctor asked about stress,
Jarrad initially said that everything was find. But when the doctor
probed further, about home and work, Jarrad admitted that his boss,
Bill, was a real negative person.
	   Bill only noticed the negative and never gave him any positive
feedback.
	   Jarrad never knew if his job was secure and he felt as though he
never lived up to what Bill expected. Jarrad had thought about
leaving his job many times but with the lack of hiring in his field
he never felt it was possible. Jarrad's doctor prescribed blood
pressure medication for the rest of his life.
	   Dealing with a difficult boss on a day-to-day basis can have
both physical and emotional consequences, including such diverse
problems as hypertension, headaches, stomach aches, diarrhoea,
insomnia, depression and nervousness. In addition, having problems
at work often affect a person's home life, causing increased
conflict within a marriage or with the children.
	   As a psychiatrist I've treated many people who had a difficult
boss. Job insecurity is more prevalent than several years ago which
gives many employees the feeling that they have to put up with
whatever an employer dishes out. As mental health professionals
know, however, perception is everything. When you believe that you
have to put up with mistreatment then you put up with it at
whatever personal cost to yourself. When you believe that you can
do something about a difficult situation then you generally tackle
it in a positive way. There are many tactics you can use to deal
with a difficult boss, besides blowing up or quitting. Here are
five strategies: l Clarify your job expectations. Make sure that
your work goals match what your boss wants from you. Many
disagreements between an employer and employee stem from unclear
expectations. Rather than blaming your boss for not being clear
with what he or she wants, take the initiative to clarify goals to
ensure you're on the right track.
	   l Assume the best about your boss, unless you have clear reasons
to the contrary. Bosses are people too. Most people in charge want
to do a good job and want their employees to succeed. Sure, many
supervisors or employers could do a better job or could benefit
from more management training, but most of the supervisors I've met
want what's best for their employees. When you expect the best,
your attitude and work performance improves which goes a long way
to improving your relationship with your boss.
	   l When you feel your boss is upset with you check it out. Since
employers and supervisors are in positions of authority their every
action is interpreted by those who work for them. If an employee
has `authority issues' from their past, he or she may misinterpret
the boss' attitude or actions and be upset over a misunderstanding.
I tell my patients that a negative look from a boss may mean
nothing more than constipation on his part. You don't know unless
you check it out! l If your boss throws tantrums, don't cower and
don't provoke. Some bosses are emotional and belligerent by nature,
some are that way because it gets them their way. If you cower and
give in to them when they get upset, they will bully you as a
matter of course. If you provoke them further when they're upset
you may end up fired. The best way to deal with a bullying boss is
to remain calm (even though you feel like screaming) and assert
your point in a positive way. Many difficult bosses will have more
respect for you if you stand up to them in a respectful way. If you
stay calm when the boss is out of control he or she is likely to
pull it together in order not to look like a fool.
	   l Reinforce your boss when he or she is giving you the feedback
you need to do your job. Too often employees see themselves in a
powerless `one down' position with their boss. Employees can shape
the boss' behaviour with positive reinforcement. For example, when
the boss gives you good feedback tell him or her how much you need
and appreciate it. If you notice your boss having a hard time with
his or her boss, let them know that you appreciate their efforts
and know things will work out. A kind word or a smile goes a long
way to disarming a fuming boss.
	   Using these simple strategies will give you some power in
dealing with a difficult boss. Never forget that a work
relationship goes two ways and that you have some responsibility
for shaping the relationship. Now, if the boss is totally
impossible and nothing works to turn the relationship around, look
for another job. Working for a boss you hate over a long period of
time will take years off your life. When you leave, however,
(especially during this economy) plan you exit to a timetable that
fits your needs, not the needs of your angry impulses. - UPS

</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 MALAYSIAN BUSINESS all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
