<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
The week that was, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws THE-WEEK-THAT-WAS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   MONDAY, May 25
	   THE Asia Pacific Economic Co-operation forum agreed to launch an
initiative to examine ways to improve corporate governance as a
means to avoid a repeat of the regional financial problems, said
Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim.
	   THE Malaysian Chamber of Mines will propose to the Primary
Industries Ministry for the revival of 10 tin mines to reduce the
country's dependence on tin imports, a move which can save the
country RM80 million annually in foreign exchange, said the Kuala
Lumpur Tin Market chairman Datuk Mohd Ajib Anuar.
	   MONDAY, May 25
	   THE Asia Pacific Economic Co-operation forum agreed to launch an
initiative to examine ways to improve corporate governance as a
means to avoid a repeat of the regional financial problems, said
Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim.
	   THE Malaysian Chamber of Mines will propose to the Primary
Industries Ministry for the revival of 10 tin mines to reduce the
country's dependence on tin imports, a move which can save the
country RM80 million annually in foreign exchange, said the Kuala
Lumpur Tin Market chairman Datuk Mohd Ajib Anuar.
	   THE Malaysian Franchise Association is holding discussions with
the Government on the setting up of a task force to help
franchisees which are facing problems during the economic slowdown,
said chairman Datuk Adzmi Abdul Wahab.
	   TUESDAY, May 26
	   INTERNATIONAL Trade and Industry Minister Datuk Seri Rafidah
Aziz urged investors to tap the opportunities in the steel
fabrication industry.
	   THE Government will be establishing an Independent Grid System
Operator by the end of the year to manage the transmission and
distribution of electricity, Energy, Telecomminications and Post
Minister Datuk Leo Moggie said.
	   SHANGRI-LA Hotels (Malaysia) Bhd estimated that the haze problem
last year led to a RM12 million loss in earnings, executive
director Kay Kuok Oon said.
	   THE consortium leads by Tenaga Nasional Bhd to undertake the
privatisation of the Sabah Electricity Board intends to invest
RM1.5 billion into the privatised entity over the next seven years,
Tenaga executive chairman Datuk Ahmad Tajuddin Ali said.
	   WEDNESDAY, May 27
	   ECONOMIC adviser to the Government Tun Daim Zainuddin said there
should be a clear definition of what constitutes a bailout of
companies and for the basis of such a bailout to be clearly spelled
out.
	   REFLECTING its confidence in the country's economy, The Bank of
Nova Scotia is keen to buy a Malaysian bank to expand and
strengthen its operation here. Its chairman and chief executive
officer Peter Godsoe said the bank liked to buy a majority stake
for management control.
	   PERUSAHAAN Otomobil Nasional Bhd is buying another 16.25 per
cent stake in Lotus Group International for RM100 million cash. The
stake is to be bought from Datuk Yatina Yahaya and Datuk Tik
Mustaffa, who are administrators of the estate of the late Tan Sri
Yahaya Ahmad, and Datuk Saleh Sulong.
	   INTERNATIONAL Trade and Industry Minister Datuk Seri Rafidah
Aziz leads a delegation comprising officials and 42 representatives
from 37 companies on a trade and investment mission to Saudi
Arabia, Lebanon and United Arab Emirates till June 6.
	   THURSDAY, May 28
	   BANKS, which are facing liquidity problems, have to work hard to
restore confidence in their abilities by attracting more depositors
and investors, said Deputy Finance Minister Datuk Dr Affifuddin
Omar.
	   CASH-rich Celcom (Malaysia) Sdn Bhd is scaling back its
investment for the fixed line network - due to the slowdown in the
property sector -and its parent company Technology Resources
Industries Bhd has no plans to raise new borrowings to fund capital
expansion.
	   TIME Engineering Bhd invites foreigners to take up stakes in the
company to obtain more financing to cover the increasing costs of
its telecommunication businesses, managing director Phang Shyue
Ming said.
	   SHARP Electronics (Malaysia) Sdn Bhd unveiled its first
Malaysian designed and developed large-screen television at its
headquarters in Shah Alam.
	   THE DRB-Hicom Group expects sales of vehicles and spare parts
for the export market to exceed the RM1 billion mark this year.
	   FRIDAY, May 29
	   BINARIANG Bhd is believed to have successfully wooed Singapore
Telecom Ltd to be its second foreign equity partner.
	   ANALYST supported economic adviser to the Government Tun Daim
Zainuddin's warning that high interest rates and too tight credit
may send the economy spinning in a downward spiral.
	   INTERNATIONAL Trade and Industry Minister Datuk Seri Rafidah
Aziz called for greater business networking between Malaysian and
Saudi Arabian companies in order to set up mutually beneficial
joint ventures.
	   MALAYSIA Airline System Bhd recorded a group pre-tax loss of
RM225.36 million for the year ended March 31, 1998 from a pre-tax
profit of RM349.56 million previously.
	   
