<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
More deaths reported in Kosovo; thousands flee trims. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: AMs. UPDATES with thousands marching in Kosovo; recasts and
By ISMET HAJDARI
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Refugees from Serbia's Kosovo
province streamed into neighboring Albania on Monday to escape some
of the worst fighting in months. Dozens of people were reported
killed.
	   Reports from Serb and Albanian sources often were contradictory
and could not be independently verified. But with 39 people
reported killed over the weekend, and fighting apparently
continuing, the bloodshed seemed the worst since early March, when
Serbian police killed more than 80 people in a crackdown on
independence-minded militants and their families.
	   A day after Serb authorities claimed to have killed several
dozen militants in four villages in the Decani region of western
Kosovo, ethnic Albanian officials said 37 Albanians had been killed
over the weekend.
	   Twenty-seven died in clashes in Decani while 10 were killed when
Serb police stormed a village elsewhere, they said.
	   Two Serb policemen also died in the fighting around Decani, 75
kilometers (45 miles) west of the regional capital Pristina, Serb
sources said.
	   The latest fierce fighting prompted about 2,000 Kosovo
Albanians, mostly women, children and elderly, to leave the
troubled region and cross over into Albania's Troboja region Sunday
and Monday, Albanian authorities said. They said more were arriving
by the hour.
	   Interior Ministry spokesman Artan Bizhga said in the Albanian
capital, Tirana, that the refugees, many of whom had walked for as
many as 10 hours, were being accommodated in local homes and a
school. Local authorities were providing free food and clothes.
	   In a statement, the Albanian government called on the United
States and the European Community to intervene ``for ending the
massacre in Kosovo.''
	   ``This is just the start of a war with tragical dimensions,''
the statement said.
	   Authorities in Serbia, which with Montenegro comprises all that
remains of the Yugoslav federation, are trying to block Kosovo's
independence bid. They are using Serbian police and the Yugoslav
army to try to crush militants and maintain control over the
province, where 90 percent of the population of 2.2 million is
ethnic Albanian.
	   More than 200 people have died in Kosovo clashes since the
beginning of March. An estimated 50 percent of the Serbian province
is controlled by militant Albanians and many regions are blocked
off, either by Serbs or Albanians.
	   The Kosovo Information Center, close to the ethnic Albanian
leadership, released the names of the 10 people it said were killed
Sunday when Serb police stormed the village of Poklek, 25
kilometers (15 miles) west of Pristina. It said one had had his
throat slit.
	   According to the Albanians' account, Serb police burst into
Poklek houses, pulled out villagers and told them to ``go to
Albania and never return.''
	   Afterward, Serb police allegedly set 26 homes ablaze.
	   All phone lines remained disconnected Monday between Pristina
and the hot-spots of Decani, Klina and Djakovica, where fierce
battles were reported Sunday. In Pristina, about 10,000 ethnic
Albanians, including 2,000 children, marched to protest Serbian
rule.
	   Yugoslavia's state-run daily Politika on Monday accused ethnic
Albanian ``terrorist groups'' of killing several of their
countrymen while shelling several villages near the border with
Albania whose residents do not support the militants.
	   (pvs/kk/gj) 	   
</TEXT>
