<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 12:05:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1006  wstm-
r w     NO-ASIAN-WOES-HEREsked     06-01 1514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> NO-ASIAN-WOES-HERE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
No Asian woes here, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws NO-ASIAN-WOES-HERE sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   IF MELBOURNE holds the largest Greek community outside Greece,
Perth has attracted the largest proportion of Asian settlers from
the region. And if the rest of Australia seems increasingly mired
in Asia's woes, could Western Australia also face a similar impact?
	   Most Asians in Perth don't seem particularly perturbed about the
impact from Asia's turmoil. In fact, much Asian investment still
finds its way to Western Australia. Perhaps it's because of the
Asian congeniality factor.
	   But geographical proximity to Asia also counts for a lot.
	   Still, there are the doubters. They say there is no state in
Australia more exposed to the sick economies of Asia than Western
Australia (WA).
	   So, the popular argument goes, WA must itself be about to become
a basket case.
	   Don't you believe it. WA could still grow faster than the rest
of the Australian economy in the coming financial year. Indeed, the
Court government is budgeting on it. The official forecast for
1998-99 built into the recent budget is a whopping five per cent -
almost two percentage points faster than the likely national growth
rate, and not far short of WA's average growth for the past decade.
	   On the Treasury's reckoning Asia will cost WA one percentage
point of growth, ask the Canberra-based consultant Access Economics
and it will tell you WA's forecast is a more conservative 3.5 per
cent to four per cent. That's still a good half a percentage point
above the likely national growth rate.
	   WA's growth will depend on how quickly the main economies in
Asia turn the corner. But if Asia's turnaround is reasonably rapid,
the state can expect growth to be pushed along by strong investment
in the resource sector. According to Ed Shann, director of Access
Economics, there are resource projects worth A$14 billion in the
pipeline, for which a decision on whether to proceed will be made
in the next 12 months.
	   The most important of these projects is the North-West Shelf LNG
expansion, the cheapest version of which is worth A$6 billion, and
the An Feng Kingstream steel plant which, with associated
infrastructure, is worth A$2.5 billion. That's thanks to Asian
investment, especially from Taiwan and, to a lesser extent, China
and Malaysia, all of whom realise the importance of natural
resources for fuelling their own economic growth.
	   Obviously Shann isn't worried. `If they go ahead I don't think
there's much to worry about,' he says. `There are some gold mines
that have closed; there will clearly be something taken off the top
of construction activity. But there will still be very high mining
investment in WA.' The potential for strong investment was
reaffirmed in the last Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) survey
of business investment intentions, taken in the early months of
this year. According to the ABS, business in WA is expected to lift
investment by another whopping 18 per cent in 1998-1999.
	   The state Treasury, taking a more conservative line and allowing
for some delay in the North-West Shelf project, is looking for
growth of about eight per cent. That should now be the envy of many
Asian countries whose stripes have been lifted off their 'tiger'
economies in the ongoing turmoil. But whatever the long-term
effects of the native title law in Australia, on which the Howard
government has taken a recalcitrant stance, there is no sign of it
affecting the level of investment in the short term.
	   Still, there are no guarantees that resource investment will
keep going strongly in the case of the Asian meltdown. If either
the North-West Shelf or the An Feng project were put on hold, the
outlook for WA would change considerably. However, An Feng
Kingstream director John Clark insists that work will begin in
August. The plant, he says, will be at the bottom of the world cost
curve.
	   And he's not worried that Asian investment partners will pull
out. The North-West Shelf partners seem almost as confident. While
the project's Japanese customers have yet to commit to the extra
gas sales, the project partners are confident of obtaining the
letter of intent by the end of this year, in time to meet the
project's original construction schedule.
	   Helping the North-West Shelf partners - and other resource
sector investors - make their sums work will be the depreciation of
the Australian dollar. The Australian dollar has depreciated
against the US dollar by about 11 per cent in the past six months
and almost 19 per cent since the end of 1996. This has cushioned
the Australian-dollar incomes of many Australian mining companies
against the decline of USD-denominated commodity prices.
	   At the same time, WA's mining and other commodity exporters have
been able to weather the Asian downturn more easily than exporters
of consumer goods and capital equipment. That is partly because
commodities are sold on world markets. Lost sales in Asia can be
replaced by sales (albeit at lower prices and with higher transport
costs) in other world markets.
	   When combined with the competitive dollar, the result is that
all but marginal mines can keep producing. And highly efficient new
projects, such as An Feng Kingstream, can still justify
construction. `The iron ore industry is going great because it has
had a rise in the USD contract prices,' Shann points out. `That's
one area where there is going to be a continuing run of activity.'
Nickel is likely to be another. `There's a large number of nickel
projects around,' says Shann. `There are three under construction
that will move into production this year. It's not clear if there
are going to be any replacements, although there are a lot of
projects which claim to be down in the bottom quarter of the cost
curve. Maybe some of them do get up despite the fall in the nickel
price.' But there is another important reason why the WA mining
exports and investment should come through the Asian downturn
reasonably intact. The point was made recently by the governor of
the Reserve Bank of Australia, Ian Macfarlane.
	   To some extent, Australia's food and mining commodity exports
are inputs for Asian export industries. These industries will
benefit from the big depreciation of Asia's currencies in the past
10 months. `We are probably better off in current circumstances
than most suppliers because of the weight of commodities,
foodstuffs and inputs into exports in our mix,' Macfarlane says.
`After the transitional export finance problems are solved, we
should expect to see strong growth in Asian exports as a result of
their large increase in competitiveness.' Of course, WA will not
get off scot-free. Not by a long shot. Take tourism. The tourist
industry has taken a sizable hit. So has the rest of Australia.
Takings by the West Australian accommodation industry in the
December quarter were down in nominal terms on a year earlier, with
the top-end four-star and five-star hotels suffering a 13 per cent
fall in revenue.
	   The Perth property market is also suffering from the financial
pressures on Asian investors. The news recently that Boutique Asset
Pty Ltd, a company connected with the powerful Indonesian Salim
group, was pulling out of plans to develop a A$55m residential
apartment tower in the Perth CBD (central business district)
demonstrates the direct link between sections of the Perth property
market and the prosperity of Asia.
	   Still, neither Asian investors here nor West Australian
officials are particularly worried. Looking ahead, the point to the
Western Australia Treasury forecasts, which predict strong growth
from consumer spending and a recovery in WA's housing investment.
	   Access Economics' Ed Shann, however, warns that the commercial
property market will remain fairly flat. `Basically they haven't
been having much in terms of office construction,' he says. `So,
unlike Sydney, where the property market is starting to kick in,
that won't be a helping hand for Perth. Perth is still basically
dependent on the resource sector.' So, as always in WA, it's back
to the resource sector. But if the Treasury's economists are right,
and the big projects go ahead as planned, the Western Australian
economy could be one of the faster growing economies in Asia in
1998-1999. And the Australian state most exposed to the Asian
crisis could come through with barely a bruising.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 MALAYSIAN BUSINESS all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:NO-ASIAN-WOES-HERE sked; CT:w; 
