<BODY>
<SLUG> NEW-PENTIUM-II-BASED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
New Pentium II-based notebook from Gateway, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws NEW-PENTIUM-II-BASED sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   GATEWAY Inc, the direct marketer of personal computer (PC)
products, has introduced its new entry level multimedia notebook
called Solo 2500 which is powered by Intel's Pentium II processors.
	   The notebook replaces the Solo 2300 model, and is targeted at
the heart of the mainstream portable market with its emphasis on
high performance and long battery life.
	   Gateway's marketing director for mobile systems Rick Griencewic
claimed that the Solo 2500 is the most aggressively priced
thin-film transistor (TFT) and Pentium II-based all-in-one notebook
available in the Malaysian market.
	   ``While many of our competitors are struggling to ship their
first Pentium II-based systems, Gateway is already cutting prices
and is pleased to offer a third Pentium II product in its mobile
line of PCs,'' he said.
	   Griencewic said the Pentium II technology in mobile PCs delivers
between 11 to 32 per cent better performance at the same thermal
level of a 166 megahertz (MHz) multimedia extensions (MMX)
technology.
	   Gateway's Solo notebooks may be customised to custom-configure
the central processing unit (CPU) speed, random access memory (RAM)
amount, hard drive capacity, modem and network connectivity,
operating system and applications software to meet individual
requirements.
	   ``The Solo notebooks can be upgraded or downgraded to meet
individual requirements and budget,'' said Griencewic.
	   Priced at RM8,498, the Solo 2500 is configured with a 200MHz
Pentium processor with MMX technology, 32-megabyte (MB) SD random
access memory (RAM), 12.2-inch TFT display, two-gigabyte (GB) hard
disk, fibre distributed data (FDD), 56K PC card fax modem and
lithium-ion battery. It includes a CD-ROM and floppy drive which
eliminate the need to swap components.
	   It also allows sharing of components such as docking stations,
system memory, hard disk drives, power adapters and other common
peripherals.
	   Gateway said the Solo 2500 has added manageability features to
lower the total cost of ownership through its common modularity
strategy.
	   For example, the LANDesk Client Management with Windows NT and
SM basic input/output system (BIOS) allows a company's information
systems department to manage company notebooks from remote sites.
	   In addition, users can choose between a touchpad or
stick-pointing device. This allows business users to standardise
with one portable system and yet meet their personal preferences.
	   Gateway's director of marketing for South Asia Niall O'Reilly
said by introducing the Solo 2500 to the Malaysian market via the
DirectPlus business model, Gateway has reaffirmed its commitment as
the value leader in the local notebook market.
	   The company's direct channel model strategy means that customers
deal directly with the principal manufacturer and everything is
built specifically to order, thus eliminating the middleman.
	   It also enables Gateway to offer an attractive package which
combines good pricing and the latest PC technologies available in
the market.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
