<HEADER>
w1012  wstm-
r w     MERICANS-IN-MALAYSIAsked     06-01 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> MERICANS-IN-MALAYSIA sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Mericans in Malaysia, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws MERICANS-IN-MALAYSIA sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   IT SO RANKLED this writer in school all those years ago when a
colleague, who shall remain anonymous, insisted on giving his
mouthful-of-a-name in all its `triple-barelled glory'. Nothing
really wrong with that except he was a fellow `Melayu' and to this
far-from-wordly-wise teenager then, a Malay name had to conform to
a simple convention. It was basically Abdul `this' bin Abdul `that'
or Mohamad `this' bin Mohamad `that'. The snooty friend, instead,
insisted on including a surname to his already unwieldy first and
second names. `Its my family name,' he implored earnestly, almost
on the verge of tears on being pressured by his hectoring
interlocutors. Only now, having picked up the book The Merican Clan
- A Story of Courage and Destiny which chronicles the achievements
of seven generations of Mericans, the progeney of Kader Mydin
Merican who first set foot in Penang from India in 1770, does one
appreciate his stubborn insistence. Thanks to the pride attached in
carrying the Merican family name with each succeeding generations,
the task of tracing lineage can be undertaken with a great measure
of certainty and accuracy. Forgive me, my friend?
	   This writer's first ever inkling of the existence of a Merican
was via the airwaves in the days when Radio 4 was called Rangkaian
Biru. Every Sunday, one would look forward to the afternoon radio
play and inevitably a Merican - Faridah Merican - would come on air
as a principal character.
	   Later on, news items would chronicle one achievement or other
with yet another Merican, invariably bathed in academic or
corporate glory. Names like Mahmood Merican, Malek Merican and
Ahmad Merican all hit the headlines for achieving one notable
success or another but little thought was given to the significance
of that Merican family name. After all, one came from a culture
where geneology and tracing one's family tree is limited to knowing
the name of one's moyang and no further. However, the regularity
with which this particular family name cropped up and the import of
their achievements did raise a measure of envious curiosity. Now
thanks to Datin Ragayah Eusoff, the blanket of ignorance is lifted.
(She's married to Mahmood Merican, so that explains this particular
labour of love!) Interestingly, Mahmood - the Datuk Dr Mahmood who
was once chairman of Pantai Hospital - wasn't too keen on his
wife's idea and mischievously suggested she write a book about
Mericans who were already dearly departed! With great aplomb,
Ragayah ignored his helpful suggestion.
	   Why should the reader be interested in the Mericans in the first
place?
	   We should, if only because we take vicarious delight in sharing
the success stories of others. In the case of the Mericans, the
exploits of various clan members should by now confer on them the
right to patent the formula for superachieving families - if the
bunch of medical men and learned women as well as earnest
entrepreneurs from their ranks have not already done so.
	   Patriarch Kader Mydin Merican was a trader who became one of the
richest men in the Penang of the 1830s. That he eminence grise in
the Indian Muslim community was acknowledged by the British who
appointed him Kapitan Keling. The fourth generation Merican
produced the clan's first doctor, Ali Osman Merican. `Oss', as he
was called, was in fact Penang's first Malay doctor. A sibling,
Sheikh Basha, was an educator who was instrumental in establishing
and heading Rida College, the forerunner of what is now the
Institute Teknologi Mara (ITM). Thespian Faridah Merican is his
daughter.
	   The recipe for eminence cannot wholly be explained by way of
geneology.
	   Marina Yusoff, the country's second Malay woman lawyer who at
one time landed an Umno Supreme Council seat, is a clan member. Her
mother Mona was Dr Ali Merican's adopted daughter.
	   The exploits of past and present Mericans have secured the clan
an indelible page in the annals of Malaysian history. The author
hints of more new pages to be written in her observation that there
are 16 great-grandchildren of Dr Ali Merican making up the seventh
generation Merican.
	   That they are not yet making waves is no reason why one of their
number should not start chronicling every mewling and chuckling
emanating from every crib in all the Merican households. Failing
which, there is always that famous family name one can latch on to
in future undertakings of this nature.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 MALAYSIAN BUSINESS all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:MERICANS-IN-MALAYSIA sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
