<HEADER>
w1016  wstm-
r w     MORE-JOY-WITH-BAZOOKAske     06-01 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> MORE-JOY-WITH-BAZOOKA sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
More joy with Bazooka Fighter, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws MORE-JOY-WITH-BAZOOKA sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   AS non-programmable analogue joysticks go, I have never come
across something as versatile as Rockfire's Bazooka Fighter. Though
Bazooka is not the sort of name I would have given it, the features
added to the joystick are by far some of the most innovative.
	   To begin with, the joystick is designed to be a chameleon of
sorts because it is capable of mimicking the functions or behaviour
of more than one type of joystick design. Generally speaking, it
looks like any other high-end and intermediately priced joystick,
except that is has a curious-looking function on the left side of
its solid-looking base marked Mode 1234. It is a slider switch
which allows the gamer to determine how the Bazooka is supposed to
behave.
	   In mode 1, the Bazooka mimics the functions of the ThrustMaster
FCS, from the four button fire control, to the viewfinder or hat
switch, right down to its precision handling. The joystick throttle
is disabled in order to avoid unwanted conflicts with an actual
ThrustMaster's throttle control unit. Just add a rudder control
unit to the Bazooka and ThrustMaster throttle, and the gamer should
have a combination that is ready for almost any true-to-life flight
simulator that requires high-precision handling.
	   In mode 2, the Bazooka behaves like a CH Flightstick Pro.
However, unlike the CH Flightstick, the throttle control for the
Bazooka is not at the base but at the upper right side of the
joystick grip. This would allow the gamer to fully dedicate his
left hand (the Bazooka being a right-handed joystick) to keyboard
commands.
	   It is surprising that joystick makers had not come up with the
idea sooner seeing how the need for the gamer's left hand to travel
from joystick to keyboard can be ``fatal'' in most fast-paced and
gruelling games, thus defeating the purpose of having throttle
control on the joystick. Well, not only has that problem been
solved, the Bazooka's throttle control is a special push-button
analogue unit that is not only easily accessible but can also be
``auto-centred'', a feature necessary for ensuring efficiency in
games like Descent and Descent II. No longer does a gamer have to
worry about over-thrusting using that silly old slide or rotary
switch.
	   By moving the Mode 1234 switch to any position while holding
down the throttle, the auto-centre feature would be enabled. And
moving just the Mode switch would disable that feature. It is as
simple as that.
	   The only problem I faced with the throttle design was that it
was not placed high enough, but this is not a problem that would be
shared by most gamers unless they are adults with stubby hands and
inflexible thumbs. I guess, for me, the cramps from having to bend
my thumb a little more than what feels natural, would just take
some getting use to. I just hope I do not get any bunions from it.
	   In mode 3, the Bazooka behaves like an arcade joystick with two
single fire and two turbo fire buttons capable of producing 15
signals per second, as well as throttle control. And in mode 4, the
gamer will get four single fire buttons and a throttle control.
	   Now, whilst the Bazooka is not about to replace sophisticated
game pads in modes 3 and 4, it does have an advantage over them
because of the throttle control. This feature would be most useful
in arcade games that require two joysticks. To fully enable it,
select the two joystick modes supported by the particular game and
calibrate the joystick as instructed by the game manual concerned.
Note, however, that the functioning of buttons C and D as well as
the throttle control in modes 3 and 4 are dependent on the dual
joystick mode.
	   If at any point the joystick does not respond as it should under
the various modes when playing through Windows 95, the user should
see whether the particular mode corresponds to what has been set
under the control panel of Windows 95.
	   Personally, I had not encountered such problems when reviewing
the Bazooka, but the control panel would have been the first place
that I looked at had I encountered such a problem. Apart from all
that, the Bazooka looks really chic and provides for a generally
comfortable grip.
	   Its wide handrest at the base of the grip allows for greater
precision handling as well as alleviates wrist cramps. Of course,
all this is relative to the user's general size, but as far as I
can tell, my ``kill rates'' have generally gone up.
	   So I guess this is one joystick I would be happy to have since
it distributes stress to the whole of my arm instead of
concentrating it on my wrist or elbow. I guess that is why the
Bazooka marketers referred to it as ``ergonomic in design''. It has
a wide and heavy base with no obtrusive slide controls for
alignment error correction to mar its sleekness. Those alignment
controls are placed underneath the base which not only makes the
joystick look better but ensures that any accidental adjustments
are avoided. What more, it comes with a 183-centimetre cable.
	   Now, if only someone had thought of a better name than Bazooka!

</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:MORE-JOY-WITH-BAZOOKA sked; CT:w; 
