<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-TPC of Europe, 1st ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Westwood holds off Clarke by a stroke to win TPC of Europe 
</HEADLINE>
EDS: ADDS details, prize money, quotes, byline, RECASTS in parts
By ROY KAMMERER
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   ALVESLOHE, Germany (AP) _ England's Lee Westwood Monday sank a
clutch birdie on his final hole to hold off Darren Clarke at the
TPC of Europe and capture his second title of the year.
	   Westwood, the 25-year-old Ryder Cup player, holed a 20-foot putt
(7 meters) to capture the dlrs 1.9 million event by a shot after
letting a four-stroke lead melt way.
	   ``It's the biggest putt of the week, because I finally managed
to close the door,'' said Westwood.
	   Westwood, who fired a course record 61 Sunday, finished with a
66 and 23-under 265 to win his first tournament in Europe this
season, having earlier won on the other side of the Atlantic at the
Freeport McDermott Classic held in New Orleans.
	   Clarke made a late charge by stringing four birdies together as
the Northern Ireland player finished with a round of 68 and a 266
total.
	   Masters champion Mark O'Meara, who also chased Clarke was third
at 269 and a final round 70. He shot himself out of contention with
a 11th hole double bogey.
	   After taking what seemed to be a sure four-stroke lead into the
16th, Westwood appeared to be hit by nerves as Clarke's birdie run
mounted.
	   He missed an eight-foot putt on the 16th for his first bogey of
the day, then struggled to play even on the 17th.
	   ``It's difficult when a player like Clarke is chasing you. He
can birdie every hole,'' said Westwood.
	   But Clarke failed to position himself for another birdie on his
approach shot on the par-5 17th, while Westwood launched a perfect
shot down the center of the fairway on his final hole.
	   ``That's a great drive,'' said Mark O'Meara, Westwood's playing
partner, in his first European tournament since winning his green
jacket in Augusta.
	   Westwood said final two rounds of 61 and 66 were the best of his
five-year career.
	   ``It's the first time I've ever done that _ hopefully it's not
the last,'' said Westwood.
	   Bernhard Langer finished with a 68 and 271, along with Ireland's
Philip Walton. The German, a two-time winner of the tournament,
also knocked himself out of contention with a double bogey on his
second hole.
	   ``You just want to stick your head in the sand _ I'm very happy
with my round after that,'' said Langer, still searching for his
first title this season.
	   The scores, although low, were nothing compared to Sunday's
third round when Westwood shattered the course record by two
strokes and O'Meara matched it.
	   ``I'm surprised the scores weren't better. Maybe we used up all
the birdies yesterday,'' said Walton, whose fourth-place finish
came after he missed five straight cuts.
	   Westwood took home dlrs 298,804 for his third career title on
the European tour.
	     (rk)	   
</TEXT>
