w1025  wstm-
r i     BC-Kazakstan-Germans     06-01 0337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kazakstan-Germans </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German minister says German-Russians returning home not burden 
</HEADLINE>
By BIRGIT BRAUER
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   ALMATY, Kazakstan (AP) _ Ethnic Germans returning home from the
former Soviet Union are not placing a burden on Germany's pension
system, the country's labor minister said Monday.
	   Most of the returnees are young people taking jobs that most
Germans would refused to accept, Norbert Bluem said following a
three-day visit to Kazakstan.
	   There has been heated debate in Germany about the ``Aussiedler''
from the former Soviet Union who are entitled to pensions because
of their ethnic roots, even though the never contributed to the
pension fund.
	   ``The debate about Aussiedler causing financial problems for the
German pension system is not only wrong, it it also stupid because
it nurtures resentment,'' Bluem said.
	   The German Labor Ministry says only 11 percent of ethnic German
returning from the former Soviet Union are over 60 years of age,
compared with 21 percent of Germany's total population.
	   However, 33 percent of the returnees are children or teen-agers,
compared with 19 percent of Germany's population.
	   Germans went to Russia about 200 years ago at the invitation of
the German-born Empress Catherine the Great who granted them land,
religious freedom and other special privileges in return for
helping to modernize the country.
	   During World War II, Stalin ordered all ethnic Germans in the
lower Volga region deported to Siberia and Central Asia as
potential traitors. Thousands died in labor camps or coal mines.
	   Germans started leaving the former Soviet Union during Mikhail
Gorbachev's perestroika reforms in the late 1980s. Since 1989, the
number of Germans in Kazakstan has fallen by 75 percent, from
around 1 million to 250,000 today.
	   In recent years, Germany has tried to persuade ethnic Germans to
stay where they are, because of its high unemployment rate and
ballooning federal deficit.
	   (str/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
