w1026  wstm-
r w     INVESTING-IN-AUTOMATIONs     06-01 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> INVESTING-IN-AUTOMATION sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Investing in automation, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws INVESTING-IN-AUTOMATION sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   IT is very rare to come across an organisation which can afford
to start off with a completely automated system. Hotel chains may
be able to start off with an integrated private automatic branch
exchange (PABX) system which ensures that telephone calls are
recorded, and printed rather than linked with the billing system,
and where the cash register in the restaurant downstairs is also
linked to the billing system. For most companies, however, growth
is gradual and incremental.
	   Generally, components stand alone and function individually.
Then they are pulled into a functioning system. For example, if you
are running a new company, you might plan on building an intranet
in two years' time. At the moment you can't afford to invest in all
the equipment, your staff aren't trained and you have not generated
the amount of resources (paperwork, etc.) to make it worth such an
investment in any case.
	   Therefore, you might decide to buy a PC and some software which
will help with specific jobs, such as accounting. This gives your
staff time to become used to dealing with computers.
	   When the time for building your intranet comes, you will
probably have to invest in enhancing your machines but hopefully
you will have kept staff accustomed to dealing with computers,
accumulated enough resources to make using an intranet worthwhile
and invested in enough equipment to keep development costs low.
	   When investing in standalone equipment look to your future needs
and consider investing in equipment with capabilities beyond your
present requirements. For example, when buying a cash register for
your new hotel, you might want to invest in a machine which
generates information which is not used yet, such as an electronic
cash register which is capable of integrating point of sale with
invoicing and inventory packages.
	   When automating a factory, you might choose to buy a robot which
paints cars which is capable of linking to your inventory and
production assessment systems but which for the first year is used
only for painting with human operators assessing inventory and
production schedules. The first year you will only use part of the
machine's capabilities but when it comes to pulling together your
equipment into a computer network, you will have the right tool in
place.
	   Be careful if you are investing in equipment where the
technology is changing rapidly. If standards have not been
developed you may find yourself investing in equipment which
becomes obsolete before you are ready to proceed to systems
integration. To avoid such problems, assess the current and future
situation with vendors and consultants. As a general rule of thumb,
many people recommend not to adopt technology which is less than
two years old.
	   When planning ahead, consider the facilities necessary to your
future needs. For example, if you are installing a telephone system
and investing in standalone computers, you might want to add in the
infrastructure necessary for your planned local area network (LAN).
When installing a PABX system you have to install wiring cables in
the walls and ceilings to connect each telephone. Save future
remodelling costs by installing network cable for your LAN on the
same path at the same time.
	   One of the costs of implementing information technology (IT) is
acquiring trained users. Training can be expensive and keeping
trained staff can be more difficult still in times of labour
shortages. Paying trained staff premium wages will significantly
reduce your training costs and keep your production level high.
	   With evolving technology, training has become a vital success
factor to the implementation of new systems and applications. Today
it is no longer valid to put training off until the economic
climate is more stable, nor is it cost-effective to send a large
group of employees on general training sessions.
	   Be prepared to have an ongoing training budget and use your
training provision as a selling point in your marketing or
recruitment. Consider the pros and cons of hiring staff straight
out of technical college compared to hiring staff with experience
but without the technological skills you need.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:INVESTING-IN-AUTOMATION sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
