<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 12:17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1028  wstm-
r w     AN-OFFICE-COMPUTERsked     06-01 1467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> AN-OFFICE-COMPUTER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
An office computer network of choice, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws AN-OFFICE-COMPUTER sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   DO YOU WANT everyone in your office to share information
instantly? Do you want to provide marketing and sales support,
disseminate training materials and schedules quickly and cheaply?
Do you dream about a system where collaboration means all members
share and have immediate access to all necessary resources?
	   If so, you need an office computer network. Computer networks
allow you to banish resource hogging corporate documents that are
now produced on paper like human resources guides, office and phone
directories, parts and price information, newsletters, annual
reports, maps, company facilities and product information
literature. Computer networks allow you to store, manipulate and
disseminate information quickly and cheaply.
	   Local area networks A Local Area Network (LAN) is a computer
network where computers are linked by a cable. Local area networks
are often used by companies to allow members to share files and
applications.
	   In a network one set of computers asks another computer for
files and services. The computer which asks for the files or
services is called the client. The computer which provides the
files or services is the server.
	   The Network Operating System (NOS) ties a client to a server.
Servers can provide, store and transfer files, access other
servers, organise e-mail, printing queues etc.
	   LANs allow everyone to share a printer and a file server, saving
the company considerable investment costs. Adding an application
server means everyone can share software packages. This means that
you need not invest in expensive PCs as everyone can use cheaper
'dumb terminals' - computers without memories or processors which
access the servers and keep documents stored there. With the
appropriate software, LANs also support local e-mail between users
and share modems among workstations.
	   Sounds good? There is one big disadvantage: sharing applications
can be expensive in terms of software licenses. When you use an
application server, you can either buy a licence for each client,
or you can invest in more software which regulates how many clients
can use the package. Either way, when using branded products,
licensing costs can rise very quickly.
	   Enter the intranet This problem has been overcome by newer
technology. Intranets are LANs which use Internet technology. Where
a LAN is accessed through a file manager, an intranet is accessed
through a browser. What does this mean?
	   An intranet is based on the World Wide Web (WWW) model. The WWW
categorises resources by URL, Universal Resource Locators, which
are then referred to as links within a `web page'. When you click
on a hyperlink, there is always an underlying URL that transports
you to `another place' on the web containing various resources, eg,
text, video, images etc. Your browser recognises what form
information is stored in by the MIME (multipurpose Internet mail
extensions) type and/or the file extension, and automatically does
whatever is necessary to display the contents of the document.
	   The technology used in browsers is extremely user friendly, just
requiring users to `point and click' their way to resources. HTML
(HyperText Markup Language), the `native' language of the WWW, is a
simple programming language and there are many software packages
offering shortcuts to web page design if users want to build extra
resources.
	   The web browser is, in effect, a `container' for a compound
document. A compound document has several elements, which can
include images, music, or even entire programs. The browser
co-ordinates these elements to display the document.
	   Another huge advantage is that the underlying structure of
intranets (called a platform) is very flexible. Intranets rely on
two formats which transmit data between linked computers. One is
called Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) and the other is
Internet Protocol (IP). Working together they form the TCP/IP
platform. This platform allows all different types of computers and
computer networks to communicate with each other.
	   Using TCP/IP it doesn't matter which network operating system
anyone is using as web browsers are designed to read the data on
all types of platforms. You can access information stored on a
`Mac' as easily as information stored on a Unix machine. This means
that you have no problem integrating inherited machines with newly
acquired machines in your office. Redundancy costs are reduced
significantly.
	   How to set up an intranet If you don't already have a local area
network, you need to set one up.
	   This requires computers, wiring, a NOS, and a network interface
card which connects the wiring to the NOS.
	   To turn your LAN into an intranet you need to make sure that you
have the appropriate software to display HTML files, TCP/IP
communication and, if necessary, multimedia. In other words, you
need a browser, assorted software and perhaps sound and video
cards. You can choose to invest in software or download freeware
from the internet.
	   There are two different types of wiring which can be used to set
up LANs. One uses coaxial cable which looks like the cable which
goes to your TV antenna. The other uses twisted pair wiring which
looks like fat telephone wires. The coaxial cable generally
connects all the machines on the network on a single bus or line.
This is generally called a bus.(Refer to Diagram 1.) The twisted
pair wire uses a hub, a traffic intersection which directs traffic
from one point to another in an intranet. This type of network is
generally called a star. (Refer to Diagram 2.) Bus topologies used
to be popular because they were cheaper to set up.
	   In the last few years, star topologies have become more popular
because their price has gone down and they are more flexible.
	   Connecting intranets to make extranets A strategic use of
intranets is to link your information network to that of your
business partners. This is called an extranet. To do this you need
a firewall to prevent unauthorised access.
	   A client who wants to connect to the outside world has to go
through the server to connect to the router, a traffic intersection
which directs traffic from one point to another between an intranet
and the outside world. When the server and router are configured to
examine traffic before allowing requests and information to pass,
then the client is deemed to go through a firewall. An extranet can
be defined as a firewall to firewall connection between intranets.
(Refer to Diagram 3.) In other words, requests from your sister
company will be allowed through, but requests from strangers will
not be allowed through.
	   Development considerations When taking decisions concerning
computer networks, consider the following points.
	   First, decide which materials should be put online first and
which materials can be added gradually. Everyone will have
different priorities and it may take some time to come to a
decision.
	   Second, ensure that information is not altered without
authorisation.
	   You may consider asking each author or department to be
responsible for their own set of resources.
	   Third, once the system is online, consideration must be given to
training users to develop new materials. Developing materials for
LANs will mean product training for developers. If you choose to
run an intranet you may choose to use authoring software which
converts documents automatically to HTML format. You may also ask
your technical department to make up various templates which can be
used to put new information online while keeping the same look and
feel as the existing system.
	   Templates are a particularly useful device when putting
regularly generated information online such as quarterly reports
and so forth.
	   Fourth, to ensure that the look and feel of the system remains
the same even if the original developers leave, write a highly
detailed style guide. Make sure that the style guide is adhered to
so that users can access resources easily and quickly.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 MALAYSIAN BUSINESS all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:AN-OFFICE-COMPUTER sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
AP-NY-06-01-98 1217EDT
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19980601.0787 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 12:19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1030  wstm-
r w     NO-CHANGE-IN-OUTLOOKsked     06-01 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> NO-CHANGE-IN-OUTLOOK sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
No change in outlook, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws NO-CHANGE-IN-OUTLOOK sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   MARKET sentiment remained soft as evidenced by a persistent and
slow downward push. The conclusion of the RHB-Sime Bank deal on
April 23 was insufficient for the market to recover. However, it
did allay earlier concerns on the funding aspect. RHB will purchase
Sime Bank for RM368 million after disposing six subsidiaries. The
Petronas-MISC-Konsortium deal was concluded on April 30. However,
there were also corporate deals which failed to be concluded such
as the reverse takeover of Ayamas.
	   Concerns on the uncertainties of the overall market continues to
be a nagging factor. MAS has yet to announce its restructuring as
at May 4.
	   Omega Securities has been suspended from trading until its
minimum liquid funds is fulfilled. And there is a mixed feeling on
the raising of the foreign equity stake to 61 per cent from 49 per
cent for the telecommunications sector. However, the stake must be
reduced back to 49 per cent within five years.
	   Money supply M3 for March moderated to 13.7 per cent year on
year. This slower money supply growth is worrisome as it suggests
the economy is slowing.
	   On the warrants market, an interesting development relating to
extending their expiry dates has created excitement in a rather
dull market. It started off with Apex-W, expiring on June 27 1998,
being granted an extension of another year to June 27 1999 by the
Securities Commission.
	   This was followed by the proposal for TA-W to extend its
maturity date from Nov 22, 1998 to May 22, 1999. The precedent for
extending the warrant maturity date was set by UCB-T when it was
given an extension from July 31, 1997 to Dec 17, 1997.
	   In Apex-W case, it is restoring the duration of the warrant to
the normal five years from the current four years. Similarly, TA-W
of 4.5 years is seeking for an extension to five years. However,
IOIPB-W and K HIN-W, both of four year duration, will expire on
their maturity dates with no extension as they are due to expire in
May.
	   However, it is wrong to assume that all warrants of less than a
five-year duration will automatically be extended. There may be
speculation on an extra time period for warrants currently of less
than a five-year duration. The bet is for the market to improve and
hopefully, warrants will be exercised to pay off bond holders.
Rating Agency Malaysia estimates some RM3 billion bond issues with
warrants will mature in 1998.
	   Warrants are sweeteners to attract subscribers to corporate
bonds. The idea is for investors to exercise the warrants, ie
converting to mother shares. With the cash raised, the corporation
can pay off the bond holders. The drop in the share market has
upset this idea as the warrant exercise prices are above that of
the mother shares. It is cheaper to buy mother shares than to
convert. A warrant is thus basically a bull market instrument.
	   On the extension of the existing warrants to the five-year
duration, the impact will be more on the warrant prices than on the
mother shares. This will increase the time premium component of the
warrant valuation. Based on the Blacksholes pricing model, adjusted
to five years for those of less than 4.5 years, warrant prices
improve. This would probably provide the opportunity for warrant
holders to cut losses.
	   On the technical side, the outlook has not changed as it
continues to mark time. This must be sounding wordy by now as I
continue to hold on to the bullish technical view. The slide in the
Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange Composite Index from the February high
of 764.94 points has not negated the bullish view yet as the 470.43
point low of January has not been violated; the current probability
suggests that it is unlikely to be breached.
	   On the relative strength index (RSI), it bounced off the lower
trendline support at 28; it is currently moving towards the upper
trend channel. An upside breach of the RSI resistance of 31 will
reverse the uptrend.
	   Immediate support is at 611 points. The next support is at 582
points which is a 61.8 per cent retracement from 764.94 to 470.43
points, followed by 565 points.
	   Resistance is at 647 points then 677. The next level is 742
points.
	   
</TEXT>
