<BODY>
<SLUG> WRAPPING-FEATURE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
More effects with wrapping feature, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws WRAPPING-FEATURE sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   IN the last article, we examined background printing and the
wrapping feature in Microsoft Word's Clip-Art pictures.
	   Wrapping allows you to control the text-picture alignment which
is important for the aesthetic appeal of the entire document.
Today, we will examine this wrapping feature further.
	   Once you have inserted the ClipArt picture, invoke Format -)
Picture.
	   Click on the Wrapping tab.
	   You will see the options Square, Tight, Through, None and Top
and Bottom. Below these, you will see another set of options
labelled: Both sides, Left, Right and Largest side.
	   These options help to fine tune the picture-text alignment and
set the distance of the text from the edges of the picture.
	   These options become active (i.e. can be used) only when you
choose Square, Tight and Through.
	   Let's suppose you want the text to flow in such a manner that
the distance of the text from the left edge of the picture is
greater than the distance of the text from the right edge.
	   First, create some text and then insert a ClipArt picture in the
middle of the text. Use Format -) Picture (Wrapping tab) to get
wrapping options.
	   Click on Square in the Wrapping Style options. Then, click on
both sides in the Wrap to set off options. Choose `1''' in the
spinner labelled left: this will create one inch of space between
the picture's left border and the text.
	   Similarly, use the spinner labelled right to alter the distance
between the text and the right border of the picture.
	   If you were to set the spinner at 0.3-inch, there will be
0.3-inch of space between the picture's right border and the text.
	   You can get unusual but very appealing effects by using
different settings for the right and left spinners. Sometimes, you
can get a very elegant look by adding borders around the ClipArt
Picture. Use the Format -) Picture command and click on the Colours
and Lines tab.
	   You will see three vertically stacked areas labelled: Fill, Line
and Arrows. Almost the entire dialogue box is in subdued grey
because a number of the features, such as arrows, are not
applicable to ClipArt.
	   Only the Fill (Colour) and Line (Colour) pulldown menus are
active.
	   The default settings on the Fill colour and Line colour menus
are No Fill and No Line respectively.
	   To add a blue border around the ClipArt picture, click on the
menu arrowhead in Line. Choose Blue from the colour palette.
	   This has the effect of drawing a blue border around your ClipArt
picture. When you enter a particular colour in the pulldown menu,
the rest of the features in the Line area become active because
they become relevant options. These are Dashed, Style and Weight.
	   Dashed allows you to choose a particular pattern for your
border.
	   Options include a series of little diamonds, dots, dashes and so
on.
	   If you were to choose Blue for Colour and the dots for Style,
you will get a border of blue dots. The Style menu allows you to
choose several types of patterns for the border.
	   Options include thick double lines or a thick and a thin double
line and so on. For instance, you can get a nice effect where the
ClipArt picture appears to be nestled in a frame when you choose
the last option in the Style pulldown menu, namely a thick line
nestled within two thin lines.
	   You can alter the thickness of the border by changing the
settings on the Weight menu. A larger number causes a thicker line.
	   Another trick that enhances the appearance of your ClipArt
picture is the presence of the Fill colour.
	   The colour menu in the Fill area allows you to add a colour of
your choice to the space between the Clip Art picture and the
border created by the Line menu.
	   You need to choose the appropriate colour from the Fill (colour)
menu.
	   Once you have chosen a particular colour, the small checkbox
titled semi- transparent will become active.
	   When you click on this box, the colour in the fill area will
take on a lighter, somewhat transparent hue. This hue goes very
well with darker coloured lines for the borders.
	   You can add a very classy look to your Clip-Art picture by using
the special fill effects Fill (Colour) and patterned line effects
in Line (Colour).
	   The Fill (Colour) pulldown menu has an option labelled Fill
effects.
	   This allows you to choose a combination of various hues for the
background; such as a lighter hue at the top which darkens
progressively to the bottom.
	   You can choose from several different effects. Similarly, the
Line (Colour) pulldown menu has the option Patterned Lines.
	   This allows you to choose from options such as bubbles,
crosswires, brickwalls, and so on.
	   The ClipArt feature offers numerous enhancement possibilities.
By trying out different combinations of Special Fill Effects and
Patterned Lines, it is possible to obtain outstanding results.
	   You should experiment freely with various Colours, Styles and
Weights in the Line options for the borders.
	   Then, you should experiment with the different Fill colours and
fill effects and examine your work with the semi-transparent
feature.
	   You must be careful that your choice of colours for the borders
match well with the choice of colours for the lines. For example,
dark blue borders with a light blue fill colour give a pleasant
look while dark blue borders and a dark blue fill colour may cause
your borders to become invisible.
	   The writer is academic head of the American Twinning Programme
in
	   Metropolitan College. He can be contacted at ananda  
metropolitan.edu.my. 1) Insert -) Picture -) ClipArt (Diploma) 2)
Format -) Picture (Colours and Lines) 3) In Colours and Lines tab,
choose Fill (Colour) -) Special Effects 4) Special Effects:
(Gradient tab); Colours - Two colours; Colour 1: White; Colour 2:
Black; Shading Styles: Horizontal 5) In Line (Colour) menu, choose
Black, Style: thick centre line with two thin lines on either side,
Weight: 2.5 pts 6) Times New Roman, Bold, 18 7) Times New Roman,
Italics, 12 8) Wingdings, 12, ( key 9) Times New Roman, 12
	   
</TEXT>
