<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 12:22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1035  wstm-
r w     LOFTY-AMBITIONSsked     06-01 1423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> LOFTY-AMBITIONS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Lofty ambitions, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws LOFTY-AMBITIONS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   AMONG THE 27 states in Brazil, one stands out eminently. While
the national exports grew at a rate of 18 per cent for 1996, the
industries in Rio Grande Do Sol managed better at 26.2 per cent.
	   The federation of industries (the Brazilian equivalent to the
Federation of Malaysian Manufacturers) in most states of Brazil,
with the exception of Sao Paulo, do not even have a building of
their own.
	   But in Rio Grande Do Sul, the federation of industries has a
large headquarters with a state-of-the-arts convention centre which
often attracts symphony orchestras from musically-inclined
countries like Austria. Though many industries in Rio Grande Do Sul
would prefer to attribute this success to their competitiveness,
the key to this prosperity lies with Mercosur, the incipient
customs union that stimulates trade between four countries.
	   Though not as big as the European Union (EU), Mercosur is the
most effective trade block in Latin America at present and its
objectives almost similar to the European body. Besides Brazil, the
other three members of Mercosur are Argentina, Uruguay and
Paraguay. Chile and Bolivia stand at the fringes as associate
members.
	   With the formation of Mercosur in 1990, Rio Grande Do Sul found
itself in a strategic position of being located at the hub of the
customs union.
	   Thus, the state became the gateway for the exchange of trade
between Brazil, the biggest economic power in South America and its
Mercosur partners.
	   `When the idea of Mercosur was first mooted, everyone thought
the state was doomed as it will have to compete with
agriculture-dominated economies of Argentina, Uruguay and Paraguay.
But while the argriculture sector of the state faced competition,
the other sectors of the economy like manufacturing and heavy
industries prospered,' says Florence Rosa, the director of
international affairs for the state of Rio Grande Do Sul.
	   Rosa says the formation of Mercosur enables industries in
Brazil, especially from Rio Grande Do Sul, to market their products
to more than 200 million people. The combined gross domestic
product of the Mercosur countries is more than US$1.2 billion.
	   The ultimate objective of Mercosur is to be a trade block
encompassing all the countries in Latin America. The trade block
also hopes to achieve a common external tariff among all countries
in Latin America, thus it should be able to rival other trade
blocks like the EU and the North America Free Trade Area (NAFTA).
But this grand-design, targeted to crystallise within the next 10
years, has to cross several bridges first. First it has to remove
the remaining internal tariff for certain products that are traded
between the Mercosur members itself.
	   Brazil, the dominant partner in Mercosur, has 27 products with
tariff protection, Argentina 220 products, Uruguay and Paraguay 900
products each. The tariff is to give some form of protection for
the manufacturers of these products.
	   `We hope to remove all tariff barriers between Mercosur members
by the year 2006. Then there will be an even more effective trade
flow between Mercosur members,' says Rosa. There is also a common
external tariff factor that has to be considered. Currently, the
common external tariff among the Mercosur four countries averages
12 per cent.
	   But this common external tariff has to be reduced further to
ensure uniformity with other countries in Latin America, thus
paving the way for the entry of more countries into Mercosur.
	   Chile, for instance, has plans to cut its external tariff from
11 per cent to eight per cent this year. But Brazil and Argentina
have plans to raise the external tariff of Mercosur countries from
the present average of 12 per cent to 15 per cent.
	   The proposed increase in external tariff means it will be a
longer wait for Chile to be a full-fledged member of Mercosur. The
addition of Chile into Mecosur means a lot as it will be a major
step forward in the Latin America trade block becoming a reality.
	   The move to raise external tariff is basically to add more
revenue to the coffers of both countries, especially Brazil which
is under severe pressure to reduce its public debt deficit and
devalue its currency, the real. A devaluation will mean a nightmare
for Argentina and the other two Mercosur members as these countries
will depend a lot on exports to Brazil. A devaluation of the real
will also further delay the removal of existing internal tariff
structures between Mercosur countries.
	   The formation of Mercosur also faces competition from the
all-powerful United States which has set its sights on forming a
Free-Trade Area of America (FTAA) by the year 2005. The FTAA will
encompass 34 countries from the whole continent and be even bigger
than the EU. US president Bill Clinton visited several Latin
American countries last year with the hope of securing allies for
the formation of FTAA, but his talks did not progress as expected.
	   Brazil and a few other South American countries prefer to fully
develop the Mercosur first, before even thinking of FTAA. 'We want
to see Mercosur progress. Only then will Brazil be able to focus
its attention on other trade blocks in the continent. Although
there are disputes on tariff structures, Mercosur is here to stay,'
exerts Rosa.
	   Although Brazil is resisting the formation of FTAA, it does want
to see a trade pact between all countries in the continent
eventually. This is necessary if it wants to explore new markets
for its massive economy.
	   While the development of Mercosur faces challenges at the top of
the administrative heirachy, on the ground, the trade integration
between Mercosur countries is moving well.
	   A new US$,36 million border crossing between Brazil and
Argentina was opened early this year to cut waiting time for
hauliers. Talks are also underway between Mercosur countries on
strategic government procurement of goods and services, which
amounts to about US$ 70 billion a year. The Mercosur countries have
also agreed on cross-border transfer of pension rights.
	   All the wealth in the exchange of trade between Mercosur
countries has a tremendous effect on the industries in Rio Grande
Do Sul. Out of the US$ 15.56 billion of trade flow between Brazil
and its Mercosur partners, US$ 4 billion was attributed to
industries in Rio Grande Do Sul.
	   Dr Luciano Andre, the executive secretary to the Federation of
Industries of Rio Grande Do Sul, says that more than 20,000 people
from all over Brazil use their facilities every week. Goods to be
exported to other Mercosur countries can only be done after
obtaining certificates from the Federation of Industries of Rio
Grande Do Sul. The federation issues a certificate after
ascertaining that the goods meet the local content requirement.
	   `Besides Mercosur, the state also thrives because of its
excellent infrastructure and its proximity to Sao Paulo,' says
Andre. Sao Paulo is regarded as the commercial capital of Brazil
but it is already congested.
	   `So many investors come here because the infrastructure
facilities. For instance the state has one of the best roads in the
country and it facilitates the movement of goods from one point to
another with minimum logistics trouble,' says Andre.
	   Rio Grande Do Sul's strategic position at the hub of Mercosur
and its infrastructure has enabled the state to attract
multinational companies, especially in the automobile sector, to
set up investments in the state.
	   Andre says among the companies due to start operations are
General Motors, Ford and Goodyear Tyres manufactures.
	   `The main objective of locating their operations in the state is
to tap the market of Mercosul countries. For instance more than 30
truck bodies are exported to Mercosul countries per day,' he says.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 MALAYSIAN BUSINESS all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
