<HEADER>
w1039  wstm-
r w     CLASSIFICATION-OF-DRAMsk     06-01 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> CLASSIFICATION-OF-DRAM sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Classification of DRAM chips, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws CLASSIFICATION-OF-DRAM sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   WE continue our discussion on a type of random access memory
chip, the dynamic RAM or DRAM chip. There are two types of DRAM -
the single inline memory modules RAM (SIMM RAM) and dual inline
memory modules RAM (DIMM RAM).
	   The SIMM RAM for personal computers (PCs) before the 486 have
30-pin connectors while newer PCs have 72-pin SIMM RAMs. However,
DIMM RAM comes with 168-pin connectors. Ever wonder why the SIMM
must be installed in pairs while the DIMM comes single? Well, the
answer is simple. For Pentium-based PCs, the motherboard supports
the central processing unit (CPU) at 64 bits.
	   A SIMM RAM transfers data at 32 bits. Therefore, to transfer
data at 64 bit to match the CPU's bus width, you need two SIMM
RAMs. So, each bank of RAM will consist of two slots for inserting
SIMM RAM.
	   What about DIMM RAM? Well, each DIMM RAM is able to transfer
64-bit data at one time. Therefore, its bank will consist of only a
single DIMM RAM.
	   From early last year, it gained wide usage. It is expected to be
used mainly in Pentium and Pentium II-based PCs.
	   The RAM chips come in either one of these two types: parity or
non-parity.
	   A parity RAM will check itself for errors using the ninth bit
built in the chips. The extra one bit will be used for this purpose
while the other eight bits will be used for operations. This ninth
bit will be able to prevent corrupted data from being written onto
secondary storage devices.
	   However, parity RAM chips are more expensive than non-parity
chips. Non- parity RAM chips do not have the extra one-bit chip
thus making it cheaper but without the checksum operations.
	   Most home PC motherboards are meant for non-parity chips.
	   Bear in mind that non-parity systems will support both parity
and non-parity RAM chips but not the opposite. Parity systems will
only support parity chips and not non-parity chips. RAM that is
able to fix error on data, such as error-correcting code (ECC) RAM
is used for the new 440 LX chipset in Pentium II machines.
	   The connector of a DRAM may be in chrome or gold. A gold-plated
RAM is more expensive than the tin-plated connectors as it lasts
longer and does not corrode easily. However, use RAMs that have the
same type of metal as its connectors compared to the slot on the
motherboard to avoid chemical corrosion between the two metals.
	   You must also be careful to select a RAM that suits the voltage
of your CPU as the voltage difference may burn the RAM chips on the
board.
	   Older CPUs use five volts while processors after the second
generation of Pentium (Pentium 75 above) use 3.3 volts as core
voltage. DIMM RAM uses only 3.3 volts. Refer to your PC's
documentation for more details.
	   To insert a RAM into its slot, you must follow these few steps.
First, remember to ground yourself as memory chips are prone to
electrostatic discharges. You can touch some metal objects to
de-charge yourself.
	   Insert the SIMM RAM into its slot at a 45-degree angle and make
sure that the notch near the centre of the slot fixes nicely with
the RAM, otherwise you may accidentally insert it in the opposite
direction. Make sure the connectors are firmly in the slot. Hold
the two ends of the RAM and lift it up.
	   The RAM will hold firmly upwards with one click from each side
of the tabs on the slot. That's it, you're ready to go. Switch on
the computer and observe the RAM test. If there's an error or
beeping, it means your RAM is not fixed properly in its slot or the
RAM is damaged. Consult someone with computer technical knowledge
if necessary to do it for you.
	   In contrast to a RAM, the read-only memory (ROM) offers
permanent data storage that is inalterable. ROM which has permanent
data that can be altered but is rarely done is known as
programmable read only memory or PROM. ROM that is often
reprogrammed is known as erasable read only memory or EPROM.
Simple, isn't it?
	   The writer is in the Physics Department, Faculty of Physical and
Applied Sciences, Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia. E-mail feedback
to rchee  hijau.com.my.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:CLASSIFICATION-OF-DRAM sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
