<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 12:25:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1043  wstm-
r w     WHEN-PURITY-IS-ANsked     06-01 1808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> WHEN-PURITY-IS-AN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
When purity is an obsession, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws WHEN-PURITY-IS-AN sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   LATE LAST year, Suez Lyonnaise des Eaux showed off its largest
and latest high-tech water treatment plant in Vigneux-sur-Seine,
20km south of Paris.
	   At its inauguration, French Environment Minister Dominique
Voynet was impressed with the plant's ability to remove pollutants
in water although, she said, it would be better if industries did
not cause pollution in the first place.
	   But we don't live in an ideal world: the pollution problem is
unlikely to go away. And water suppliers need to continuously
search for better ways to purify the water. Lyonnaise, which
supplies drinking water to over 70 million people world-wide,
focuses its research and development activities on new methods to
purify drinking water and protect the environment, says Jack Moss,
its international marketing director, water division. Its
activities span the entire water cycle, from water resource
management to wastewater treatment through a worldwide network of
research and expertise centres.
	   Daniel Villessot, deputy director of its technical and research
division, says Lyonnaise spends over 300 million French francs a
year on research and development. The bulk of the funds goes to
Lyonnaise's International Water and Environmental Research Centre
(CIRSEE) in Le Pecq, France, where about 300 scientists and
technicians work on new processes to purify both raw and polluted
water.
	   CIRSEE designed the Cristal (Combination of Reactors
Incorporating Separation and Adsorption of Liquids) process for the
Vigneux-sur-Seine Membrane Ultrafiltration Plant which Lyonnaise
claims is able to provide the highest quality of water possible
now. The plant is the biggest in the world to use ultrafiltration
membranes to treat drinking water. The Cristal process, according
to Lyonnaise, improves the organoleptic quality of water and
anticipates new types of pollution such as pesticides. It, thus,
enables the plant to deal with accidental pollution which is
frequent in surface water. The ultrafiltration membrane technique
is said to eliminate unwanted flavours and tastes in water without
the use of chemicals but preserves its natural mineral content.
	   CIRSEE is also working on a wastewater reuse and recycling
programme, because of limited fresh water resources and increasing
demand for water.
	   Bruno Levine, water reuse research engineer at CIRSEE, says
recycled water can be used for non-potable purposes such as car
wash, fountains, cleaning streets and flushing toilets. Other
applications are in industries, for example in air-conditioners,
and agriculture and landscape irrigation.
	   Levine says recycled water can also be used to recharge ground
water sources which can be affected by prolonged urban use. The
recycling technology will lead to a 30 per cent reduction in water
use, he says.
	   Moss feels that ultimately, recycled water can be consumed by
humans.
	   But people are not psychologically prepared to consume recycled
water. It will take a long time to convince them, he says.
	   The Northumbrian Lyonnaise Technology and Research Centre in
Newcastle, England, works on improving existing water distribution
and wastewater collection systems.
	   In Asia, Lyonnaise has set up the Asia-Pacific Technology and
Research Network (Astran). Managed from Kuala Lumpur, the network
has research centres in Macau, Sydney, Manila and Jakarta.
Villessot says Astran will concentrate on water resources and
problems specific to Asia.
	   Lyonnaise's strong focus on RD, says Villessot, is to enable
the company to maintain a competitive edge in the world market by
providing added services at declining costs.
	   Recognising the new global challenges, Compagnie de Suez and
Lyonnaise des Eaux merged in April last year to form the Suez
Lyonnaise des Eaux group. The merger, says Moss, is a `marriage of
different capabilities.' Lyonnaise was in a capital-hungry cycle of
business as the payback time of its Asian projects was over 10
years, he says. In the meantime, Suez, which had lost its
industrial base but was cash rich and strong in electricity, was
looking to refocus its activities. By coming together, the two
companies could be in the forefront of private infrastructure
services. Lyonnaise des Eaux, the water division of the group, is
the world leader in the water sector, says Moss.
	   The Fanco-Belgian group is refocusing on its three core business
of energy, water and waste services and is planning to develop its
operations outside the two countries. Last year, the group derived
30 per cent of its total revenue of 112.1 billion French francs
from France, 44 per cent from Belgium and 26 per cent from the rest
of the world. Its revenue from the Asia-Pacific region was three
billion French francs.
	   The energy sector contributed 64 billion French francs to the
group's revenue in 1997, waste services 15 billion French francs
and communications 2.4 billion French francs.
	   Revenue from the water sector was 30 billion French francs in
1997, a seven per cent increase compared to 1996. This sector
reported a profit of 1.4 billion French francs last year, an 11 per
cent increase compared to 1996.
	   With demand stabilising in Europe, the group's spotlight is
shifting to the developing countries. It's positioning to seize the
opportunities arising from deregulation of public monopolies and
the growth of mega cities in these countries.
	   The Asia-Pacific region contributes five per cent to the total
revenue of the group. `It's a small amount but we plan to increase
this to 15 per cent in five years,' says the group's Asia-Pacific
president, Martin Negre. Lyonnaise plans to invest about US$1
billion in the next five years on several build-operate-transfer
projects in the region. It already holds several water and
wastewater concessions and projects in Macau, China, the
Philippines, Indonesia, Malaysia, Australia, Vietnam, Thailand and
Cambodia.
	   Bruce W Bland, managing director of Lyonnaise (South East Asia)
Sdn Bhd, says the company is prepared to invest over RM10 billion
in Malaysia over the next two decades. It is eyeing several deals
in Putrajaya, Cyberjaya and states which have yet to privatise
their water supply.
	   Bland says Lyonnaise and its local partners have invested over
RM1 billion to supply bulk drinking water to 1.9 million people in
Perak, Johor and Sabah. In Perak, Lyonnaise holds a 34.4 per cent
stake in GSL Water Sdn Bhd, the concessionaire for supplying bulk
drinking water to Taiping, Kerian, Larut and Matang districts. Its
local partners are Gopeng Bhd (22.8 per cent), Wembley Industries
Holding Bhd (20 per cent) and Sisma Water Technology Sdn Bhd (22.8
per cent).
	   In Johor, Lyonnaise has a 25.5 per cent stake in Equiventures
Sdn Bhd which supplies drinking water to the Johor Baru district.
The local partners in the joint venture are Kembangan Dinamik Sdn
Bhd (49 per cent) and Pilecon Engineering Bhd (25.5 per cent).
Lyonnaise also owns Strategi Tegas Sdn Bhd, the operator of the
Sungai Layang Water Treatment Plant and Sungai Johor Water
Treatment Plant.
	   In Sabah, Jetama Sdn Bhd holds the concession to supply water to
the Kota Kinabalu area. It's a joint venture between Lyonnaise
which holds a 35 per cent stake, the Sabah government (20 per
cent), John Holland (Malaysia) Sdn Bhd (10 per cent) and Hume
Industries Bhd (35 per cent).
	   Privatisation doesn't necessarily lead to an increase in water
prices, says Negre. In some countries with undeveloped
infrastructure, he points out, people spend an enormous amount of
time and energy to get their daily water supply. Often, he says,
there is profiteering and the poor end up paying 10 to 20 times
more to buy water. Lyonnaise, he says, is committed to supply water
in a cheaper way for all to share.
	   `There is no such thing as a free glass of water,' adds Bland.
There are hidden costs in the water supplied by government
agencies: the water is subsidised. By delegating the job to private
companies, he says, governments can divert the money to meet other
needs such as education, health and housing.
	   Bland says governments also lack funds to improve existing
networks. `By shifting the burden from the government to private
companies, better services will be provided.' The efficiency gains
will lead to a better water system at lower prices, he says. For
example, Bland points out, three years after Equiventures took over
operations, the quantity of water supplied in the Johor Baru
district increased three times. Lyonnaise and its local partners in
Equiventures invested RM800 million to have the automated, most
technologically advanced water treatment plants in Malaysia, he
says. Its computerised predictive and preventive maintenance
programme has considerably reduced the number of plant breakdowns
and cut total maintenance costs, he adds.
	   In Macau, Negre says Lyonnaise and its partner, the New World
Group, have successfully reduced non-revenue water from over 40 per
cent to about 12 per cent after changing 70 per cent of the piping
network. (Non-revenue water is water lost during the distribution
process due to technical and non-technical factors such as leakage
and theft). In Malaysia non-revenue water is between 40 and 45 per
cent.
	   Water is basic to life. Aware of the sensitivities involved in
the business, Lyonnaise is painstaking in its choice of partners.
`We go for genuine partnerships with the locals and have a
responsible attitude to profits,' says Bland. And Lyonnaise takes a
long-term view of investments, about 20 to 25 years, adds Moss. He
says the payback time of its projects is over 10 years. Lyonnaise
seeks to support the local community leadership, not usurp its
powers, says Moss. `We advise, you decide.' Bland says Lyonnaise
prefers the delegated management concept where the government
retains ownership of assets and sets the price, quality and
quantity of the drinking water. Private companies will only manage
the utilities. Bland says the concept is successful in Malaysia due
to the advantage each partner can bring to the business.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 MALAYSIAN BUSINESS all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
