<SLUG> BC-Uganda-Rebels,0596 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ugandan government criticized for neglecting its own in favor of Sudanese rebels 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photos NAI101-103
By HENRY WASSWA
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   LIRA, Uganda (AP) _ Frightened nurses speak in low voices in the
hospital where two soldiers groan in pain from wounds received when
they stepped on a land mine.
	   Sgt. Reuben Tugineyo and Cpl. Edward Adima were among 18 sent to
protect the village of Oririm, 54 kilometers (30 miles) east of
Lira two weeks ago when Lord's Resistance Army rebels penetrated
deep into central Uganda.
	   ``We followed the rebels ... they took off, leaving behind a
land mine, which we stepped on,'' said Tuginyeo, 32.
	   At the time, the army boasted that it had the rebels surrounded
because they had ventured too far from their bases in southern
Sudan.
	   But by Friday, the rebels, operating in small units, had managed
to elude government troops, and people expressed fears that the
government of President Yoweri Museveni is on the losing end of the
11-year insurgency.
	   ``They (the government) have already lost the war. The
government is not effectively defending the people. They send a few
soldiers to fight off the rebels,'' said Opio Moro, a Lira civic
leader. ``For the war to end, there must be a mutual understanding
between Uganda and Sudan.''
	   People in Lira and Oririm believe rebel penetration south and
eastward from two northern districts has overstretched the army.
They also believe Uganda's support for rebels in southern Sudan
fighting the Islamic government in Khartoum has made it difficult
to end the war with the LRA rebels.
	   More than 10,000 people fleeing the rebel attacks have swarmed
into Lira, 370 kilometers (230 miles) north of the Ugandan capital,
Kampala. They are camped out in seven primary schools.
	   ``People are panicking as they are not sure what will happen
next. Soldiers are not permanent here. Only 18 were sent to defend
our village,'' said Silvester Otiti Akeny, a teacher whose sister
was killed in an attack during which he was briefly taken prisoner.
	   Lira administrative officer Jacob Ettedu says the rebel tactic
of avoiding major military and civilian centers to attack soft
targets like remote villages at night has paid off.
	   ``They move in very small groups. A whole government battalion
is attracted by these small numbers. If they moved in groups of,
say, 200, the army would finish them,'' he said.
	   Another local official charges that Museveni's only brother,
Gen. Salim Saleh, whom he named ``overseer'' of the Defense
Ministry, spends more time helping Sudanese rebels than engaging
the LRA.
	   ``I asked Salim Saleh to come to our area and defend us,'' said
Opio Moro. ``He told me he was going to Sudan. The army is engaged
in Sudan and fighting wars in other countries.''
	   Others believe that the northern insurgency has gone on for so
long because of the shift in Uganda's power base 12 years ago when
Museveni, a southerner, ousted a government made up largely of
northerners.
	   The argument is that northerners may not be ready to accept a
head of state from the south, and secretly sympathize with the LRA,
whose goals, other than ousting Museveni, are vague.
	   Around town, frustrated people blame the long war on the
government's refusal to negotiate a peace settlement with LRA
leader Joseph Kony.
	   ``The war will never end here,'' said school principal John
Etimu. ``Let the government talk with the rebels. Museveni's
government supports rebels against Sudan, and in the process,
neglects its people.'' 	   
</TEXT>
