<DOCNO> APW19980601.0803 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 12:27:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1047  wstm-
r w     WANTED-A-SOCIETYsked     06-01 1380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> WANTED-A-SOCIETY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Wanted: A society with a heart, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws WANTED-A-SOCIETY sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   DESPITE Finance Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim's reiteration
that layoffs should be kept to a minimum, `human bloodletting will
be unavoidable' as MB writers predict (A Merger Wager, April 16
issue). In the same issue, a team member of Andersen Consulting
cited casualty rates of between 30 per cent and 50 per cent in lost
jobs, arising from bank mergers abroad. Then, on April 15, 1998,
the president of the Malaysian Trade Union Congress reportedly
announced that the number of retrenched workers stood at around
35,000 so far. The number of jobless in the foreseeable future
seems to be headed upwards.
	   Amid this gloomy scenario, there have been concerns that some
still profitable companies may be taking advantage of the current
situation to retrench their staff. Others cite mergers or
acquisitions or plummeting demand as justifying the unkind cut.
Still, others such as financially strapped companies may feel they
have a watertight justification to cut their workforce.
	   But there is a need for some lateral thinking in this layoff
issue, specifically in tackling it. As people may be aware, the
jobless disease can exact a big toll, both at the macro and micro
levels. Rising unemployment can only mean reduced incomes, which in
turn will backfire on businesses which removed them in the first
place. But firms don't normally view things this way. They retrench
mainly because they are short-term and desperate. Sometimes, they
forget that they are in the business for the long haul. Retrenching
staff can adversely affect the morale and productivity of the
remaining staff, especially if their retrenched colleagues were to
be given a raw deal. Those who are fortunate to remain in the
payroll work under conditions of uncertainty until the economic
recovery is in sight.
	   Meanwhile, there are those who view the perceived excess staff
like a gangrenous leg - to be quickly cut off, lest it endangers
the bottomline of the companies. The business reengineering experts
often think in terms of efficiency in justifying their
recommendations to companies to remove staff from the payroll. The
have no qualms as to what their recommendations could do to human
lives who need food, drink, clothing and shelter as much as them.
They will not understand the human trauma of being out of a job
unless they experienced retrenchment themselves.
	   The consultants and their converts often and primarily think in
terms of ever-increasing improvements in corporate performance,
recommending that companies should be lean and mean in a fiercely
competitive world. This, they argue, is the stuff that business is
made of, if they want to thrive in a dog-eat-dog world.
Unfortunately, social considerations such as job security or job
stability, a clean and healthy working environment, etc, are
nowhere to be found among the higher rungs of their ladder of
priorities. Perhaps, there is a need to rethink the whole business
of being in business. Are we in business just for the sake of
profits per se?
	   Are we to think layoff at the first signs of trouble or weak
demand.
	   Let us not be quick to ape the American way of hiring when it's
fine and firing when in decline. We need to fashion our own
indigenous model -in good times, do not profligate but save wisely
for the rainy days. That way, we will have the option of retaining
jobs, instead of ruthlessly throwing people out of their jobs. We
will then prove to be business owners or managers with a heart and
a healthy social conscience, and our staff will surely love and
remember us for it.
	   This is the kind of loyalty and trust that staff are expecting
their employers to display when the going gets tough, ie, employers
remaining loyal to their staff at the time when their staff need
them the most in keeping their jobs and earning a decent
livelihood. Not only will staff love and remember them, they will
also want to be loyal and give their best to their caring employers
who stood by them.
	   Still, the critical questions remain: how can jobs be saved in
an economic and financial crisis? Can they be saved?
	   If people are willing to put on their thinking caps, it is not
difficult to arrive at a solution. Yes, we can save jobs - many
jobs in fact, for the good of our country, families and
individuals. There is no necessity to walk the path of least
resistance and let go of our staff (those leaving voluntarily are
exempted) so easily, unless of course there is a hidden agenda.
Here, the various media can help by spreading the word that it is
possible to save jobs, for example, by highlighting creative ways
and means of preventing job destruction. One of the ways is for
both the companies and unions to arrive at some amicable agreements
to save jobs.
	   Together, they can prevent the already flagging economy from
becoming worse than it needs to be. Together, they have the
capacity to restore job stability and job security before the job
situation gets worse.
	   For one thing, unions can initiate job-saving measures by laying
meaningful concessions at the negotiating table with the employers.
	   Concessions such as pay and benefit cuts can help to retain some
staff under the payroll. The non-unionised employees can also
follow the unions' example and accept lower remuneration and
benefits to save jobs. Each senior staff or manager's pay cut has
the potential of saving anything between two to four lower-paying
jobs. Just think of the possibility of enlisting the support of
more senior people in affected companies throughout the country to
willingly accept pay and benefits cuts! Apart from wage cuts,
companies should also do their part and explore innovative ways and
means of reducing non-wage costs. In this regards, the involvement
of staff in preventing their companies from declining or collapsing
is crucial. The impact on our nation would be both positive and
great if all parties concerned were to do just that. This, in turn,
will help ease the needless trauma and anxiety arising from the
possibility of losing one's job.
	   Interestingly, there is a biblical example of how caring and
concerned people helped those in need in a marvelous way. They
truly sacrificed by selling their possessions and goods and
distributing the proceeds to all, as any had need. This story is
recorded for us in the book known as Acts.
	   Likewise, those who own or run businesses can make some
sacrifices by, for example, selling some of the companies' assets
to help avoid slashing jobs at the first sign of trouble. In bad
times such as this, they could also consider trimming unnecessary
non-wage costs, postponing non-critical capital expenditures,
reducing wastage, implementing wage and benefit cuts and the like
to prevent their profitability indicators from worsening, as well
as to preserve the livelihood of their staff.
	   For employees who see their pay cheques shrink, they should see
their sacrifice as a way of helping their colleagues from being
thrown out of jobs, which may otherwise cause much hardship to the
unemployed and their dependents. For the more senior employees who
suffer bigger paycuts in absolute terms, they need not fret but
realise that they are contributing something worthwhile and
meaningful in life. After all, how much does a senior staff need to
live on?
	   In a nutshell, all the above is part and parcel of what we, as a
nation, should be striving to build - a society with a heart.
Together, let us seize this opportunity to establish such a caring
society.
	   
</TEXT>
