<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cycling-Tour of Italy, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fontanelli wins 16th stage, Zuelle keeps overall lead 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with detail, official times, quotes.
<TEXT>
	   ASIAGO, Italy (AP) _ After a long breakaway from the main pack,
Fabiano Fontanelli edged Paolo Bettini and Mario Scirea at the
finish of the Tour of Italy's 16th stage Monday.
	   That trio of Italians finished seven seconds ahead of a group of
chasing riders and nearly 12 minutes ahead of the top contenders.
But Fontanelli was in 77th place before the stage and not a threat
to the favorites for the overall title.
	   Alex Zuelle, who opened up a substantial overall lead with a
dominating time-trial performance Sunday, retained the pink jersey
heading into the toughest climbing stages.
	   Fontanelli was timed in 5 hours, 53 minutes, 53 seconds over the
227 kilometers (140.5 miles) from Udine to Asiago, into the
Dolomite mountains.
	   Zuelle was 29th on the day, 11:46 behind. Pavel Tonkov, the 1996
Giro d'Italia champion, finished 30th and remained second overall,
2:02 off the pace.
	   ``I always believed I could do it today,'' Fontanelli said after
his fourth career Giro stage triumph. ``I knew if I gave it a shot
I could pull through with a win. There's no surprise. I've won
stages before.''
	   Bettini had been the protagonist most of the day, breaking out
in front along with Javier Ochoa of the Kelme team. Bettini
repeatedly urged Ochoa to help do the work of providing a leading
draft, but the Spaniard refused and Bettini eventually took off
alone.
	   He was joined at the front by Scirea and Fontanelli with about
10 kilometers (6 miles) remaining.
	   ``I'm a little bitter. I don't know what the Kelme team was
thinking,'' Bettini said. ``Fabiano I know very well. We were
teammates last year so I know he's fast and could beat me.''
	   Tuesday's 17th stage takes the riders 217 kilometers (134.5
miles) from Asiago to Selva Val Gardena, including four tough
mountain passes in the last 100 kilometers (60 miles).
	   (hjf)
</TEXT>
