<BODY>
<SLUG> TURNING-ON-THE-STYLE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Turning on the style, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws TURNING-ON-THE-STYLE sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   FANCY A dapper look, oozing with English charm and elegance?
	   Then check out the Alfred Dunhill Spring/Summer 1998 collection,
which draws on English style to fit the corporate businessman. The
theme for this season's collection rests on slim and sleek
tailoring with comfort as an underlying factor, while ties take on
an English country garden theme.
	   `English style is currently in vogue,' says Peter Tilley, Alfred
Dunhill's international design and merchandise manager. `It's
sartorial, reflecting the art of the tailor and the traditional
English tailoring skills of London's Saville Row.' For those who
are young at heart, the slim tailoring of Dunhill's designs
emphasise cut and fit, belying a simple and understated elegance.
	   Corresponding to today's expectations, clothes are comfortable;
suits focus on lighter tones of grey and blue, and colours such as
tan, naturals and pastels are used to soften jackets. Ties are
filled with images of flowers, fruits and garden tools, swimming in
vivid shades of orange, yellow, lime and deep red.
	   The emphasis is on simple styling with soft, functional and
lightweight material such as blends of wools and cotton to render
the garments comfortable. The adventurous should find plenty of
room to experiment with the many colours and prints that this
collection offers. Tilley feels that the smartest and most
conventional chap in the corporate workplace would just as easily
and happily slip into something casual and dressed down on weekends
and evenings.
	   Dunhill's hacking jackets have a slim silhouette and come in
varying shades and patterns. A majority of the jackets come in
graphic checks in spicy mustards and browns or muted greens and
greys to classic navy blues. Try throwing together a sophisticated
look with a dark blue checked jacket with a bright blue shirt and
grey pants. A shimmering grey tie tops off the look. The art of
looking sophisticated with the many colours and designs to choose
from lies in keeping the look balanced.
	   Casual wear takes on both the sporty and the sophisticated
touch.
	   Weekend wear is a burst of colours ranging from bright hues of
crimson to subdued shades of pastel blue. Try co-ordinating a
powder blue blouson with navy blue corduroys and a blue and green
checked cotton seersucker shirt. Sports jackets are also in again
with a wider range of colours and patterns.
	   Avid golfers will find that Dunhill has their love of the sport
in mind in its golf wear collection. Golf shirts have wider
armholes and are tailored slightly longer in the back to facilitate
movement. Pants are made from Tencel and cotton, allowing for
easier surface cleaning.
	   For those who are still a mite baffled by two and three button
jackets, here's a reminder: a three-button jacket tends to favour
the slim, if your build is slightly on the tubbier side, go with
the two-button jacket. The same rule of thumb applies to blazers;
the six-button double-breasted blazer fits better on lean frames
while the four- and two-button blazers are more suitable for
tubbier frames. Also, if you prefer to follow the proper English
way, only the middle button is done up in a three-button jacket.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 MALAYSIAN BUSINESS all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
