<HEADER>
w1057  wstm-
r w     SITTING-PRETTY-INsked     06-01 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> SITTING-PRETTY-IN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Sitting pretty in Malaysia, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws SITTING-PRETTY-IN sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE RECARO name is renowned worldwide as a German product, and
holds the position of undisputed leader in car seats the world
over. The name draws covetous envy and inspires awe among the
majority of motorists. Among drivers of luxury sedans, high-end
sports coupes and `souped-up' racing or rally cars, Recaro is the
seat of choice. Indeed, Recaro has become a cult brand in car seats
worldwide, not only because of its snob value and aesthetic appeal,
but also because of its ergonomic qualities. In the words of Recaro
managing director Klaus Fricke, seats bearing the Recaro name are
`more than just a technical extra'. He says Recaro seats offer
added value, emphasising a certain zest which reflects a degree of
hedonism for drivers with discerning tastes.
	   Quietly - and with little fanfare - Recaro has come to Malaysia,
and in the process, has made this country its regional base. For
nearly a year now, Recaro seats have been made in Malaysia, and
within the next few months, will be produced with 50 per cent local
content. After overcoming initial teething technical problems, up
to 80 per cent of Recaro seats made at its plant in Shah Alam now
find their way back to Germany for the export market. This is on
top of the 8,400 seats produced in 1997 which was delivered to
Proton for the Putra.
	   A little history. Recaro comes from the combination of the first
two letters in Reutter and Carosserien. Two Reutter brothers,
Wilhelm and Albert, had in 1906 set up the Wilhelm Reutter car and
bicycle factory in Stuttgart, Germany. They gained a reputation for
engineering excellence, producing non-production line vehicles in
the Germany of the 1920s. After the Second World War, Reutter the
company produced car bodies for Opel, BMW and Porsche, among
others. When Porsche took over its operations fully in 1963,
Reutter became Reutter Carosserien - shortened to become Recaro
-producing seats for Porsche. In 1969, the brothers sold Recaro to
a group made up of suppliers and competing firms, including seat
manufacturer Keiper of Remscheid. The production base was also
moved from Stuttgart to Kircheim. In Germany, the parent company is
called the Keiper Recaro Group which has a total of nine factories
all over the country.
	   Recaro now supplies to 35 automobile manufacturers in 45
countries, and its seats are found in 50 different car brands
worldwide. Its upmarket cachet is ensured by the fact that Recaro
is the exclusive supplier of seats to Porshce.
	   Speaking during the opening of the latest Recaro showroom in
Shah Alam recently, Fricke said Recaro's international sales are
expected to total around RM760 million this year. This is a 40 per
cent increase from the RM540 million recorded last year. `Our goal
is to increase production from the current 343,000 seats to 800,000
seats per year within the next five years. I truly believe Malaysia
is part of this exciting strategy. Our growth here is based on
mutual benefit,' he says.
	   Recaro established a presence in Malaysia back in July 1997 with
the setting up of Recaro South East Asia Sdn Bhd. It was set up
with a local partner, Car Seat Malaysia Sdn Bhd which is in the
process of acquiring an equity stake in the joint-venture. Malaysia
has been chosen as its regional headquarters with the setting up of
two production lines for the Recaro SR and N-Joy seats in Shah Alam
at a cost of RM1 million. These production lines now employ 50
employees.
	   Today, Recaro's investment in Malaysia has exceeded RM4 million,
and this is expected to increase by another RM2 million with the
planned production of a range of child seats. Last year, the Shah
Alam plant produced 12,000 car seats valued at RM11.2 million for
the local and export markets. Its local production is mainly geared
to supplying seats for the Proton Putra and Proton Wira 1.8 rally
car. Exports of Malaysian- made Recaro seats, meanwhile, go to
Europe, Australia, Singapore, Hong Kong, Indonesia and Thailand.
	   Recaro South East Asia managing director Jurgen Fritz says an
increasing percentage of local components go into the manufacture
of Recaro seats.
	   `We consider Malaysia a good source of materials. We have chosen
Malaysia as our regional headquarters because it offers our company
positive prospects in terms of rich resources and world-class
facilities.
	   Furthermore, the government's open and liberal policies make
Malaysia a viable and profitable location for foreign investors
like Recaro,' he says.
	   Looking after sales in the region is Malaysian Lau Man Chong, a
25-year veteran of the automotive industry who serves as Recaro
South East Asia's regional sales manager. Lau says in the region,
Recaro seats are exported to Singapore, Australia, Indonesia, the
Philippines, Thailand and Hong Kong. `The majority of our seats end
up in the ``after-market'' segment where drivers take out their
existing seats and replace them with Recaro seats,' he says.
	   The current economic climate has not dampened Fritz's outlook on
Recaro's prospects in Malaysia. He believes there are many
challenges and opportunities still available in the region. `We
have been in the business of making seats for over 90 years and
during this time, there have been equally testing periods. We can
weather this storm,' he says.
	   Fritz says the current economic situation allows Recaro to be
more competitive, thus enabling its export products to be more
keenly priced.
	   With increased local components, Recaro hopes to develop better
pricing structures for both the local and export markets. `This
strategy should increase demand, output and ultimately profit,' he
says.
	   He adds, `It is important to emphasise that Recaro established
its operations in Malaysia as it sees the long-term growth for the
Malaysian economy as excellent. While our exports to neighbouring
countries are experiencing some current difficulties, these markets
will recover, and Recaro will be in a good position to successfully
exploit opportunities in these economies as they revive and
rebuild,' he says.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 MALAYSIAN BUSINESS all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:SITTING-PRETTY-IN sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
