<SLUG> BC-Zambia-Kaunda, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kaunda freed as state withdraws coup allegations lawyer, party officials 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: (AMs) UPDATES and recasts with background, comment from
AP Photo LON101
By ANGUS SHAW
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) _ Former President Kenneth Kaunda, freed
from house arrest when coup-related charges against him were
dropped Monday, immediately went to his opposition party
headquarters to plan his next move.
	   Kaunda, 74, walked out of the High Court in Lusaka after
Attorney General Bonaventure Mutale said the state wouldn't
prosecute Kaunda on charges he concealed prior knowledge of an Oct.
28, 1997, coup attempt.
	   ``I feel great,'' said the nation's founding father, wearing a
thick white beard he has grown since his arrest on Christmas day.
Supporters waved two-finger victory salutes and cheered.
	   Aides denied reports that Kaunda's retirement from politics was
a condition of his release.
	   ``There were no conditions. The state didn't have a case they
could win,'' said Sakwiba Sikota, a lawyer for Kaunda.
	   Kaunda drove through downtown Lusaka, waving his trademark white
handkerchief, and met with supporters and colleagues at the
headquarters of his United National Independence Party, the main
opposition group.
	   Kaunda said he was aware of pressure on him to hand over control
of his party to younger leaders.
	   ``I am going to listen to the people who have been discussing
this, then I'll decide,'' Kaunda said.
	   Party officials said Kaunda told them he wanted to convene a
party convention to decide what to do next.
	   The South African government welcomed Kaunda's release, saying
in a statement that it ``creates an opportunity for all political
parties to engage in a meaningful dialogue.''
	   Kaunda led Zambia to independence from Britain in 1964 and was
president for 27 years until he was ousted by Frederick Chiluba in
the first democratic elections in 1991.
	   Last year's coup attempt against President Chiluba by junior
military officers was quickly crushed by loyal troops.
	   Many foreign countries had pressed Zambia to release Kaunda or
give him a speedy trial.
	   Also freed was Moyce Kaulungombe, Kaunda's bodyguard, who had
faced the same charge as his boss.
	   One state witnesses was to have testified that Kaunda predicted
an ``explosion'' in Zambia days before the failed coup, said Wezi
Kaunda, the politician's second son.
	   Kaunda had spoken ``in the metaphorical, social sense. That was
the best evidence they had,'' Wezi Kaunda said.
	   Mwangala Zaloumis, an official of Kaunda's party, said Kaunda's
arrest has increased his popularity.
	   In January, Kaunda was transferred from a maximum security
prison to house arrest.
	   His release on Monday came on the first day of the trials of 81
suspects _ most of them soldiers _ who were arrested on suspicion
of involvement in the coup attempt.
	   Kaunda repeatedly declared his innocence. The charge against him
carried a possible penalty of life imprisonment.
	   Most of the other suspects are charged with treason and face the
death sentence.
	   (as-aos)
</TEXT>
