</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-Quake, 4th Ld-Writethru,0629 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Aid supplies begin to reach quake-stricken area in Afghanistan 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: Adds details from earthquake site throughout. No pickup
AP Photos LON108-109
By PHIL GOODWIN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   FAISABAD, Afghanistan (AP) _ Some hobbled on makeshift crutches,
a few carried stretchers and others broke into a run as helicopters
carrying emergency aid landed Monday in remote northern
Afghanistan, devastated by an earthquake that killed more than
3,000 people.
	   On a small distant hillock, a woman cuddled her infant, a
toddler sat nearby wailing. Crouched behind, her head buried in a
bright orange shawl, a woman sobbed.
	   The quake, which hit Saturday with a preliminary magnitude of
6.9, flattened entire villages, sliced mountains and triggered
landslides. The estimates of the dead vary from 3,000 to 5,000
people. Thousands more are homeless and missing.
	   The force of the quake literally sent houses roaring down
mountainsides into the valleys below. There are estimates of up to
80 villages heavily damaged, and another dozen completely
obliterated.
	   Aftershocks lingered in the region Monday, sending frightened
residents scrambling outdoors. Many people are refusing to return
to homes still standing, said Sarah Russell, a United Nations
spokesman in neighboring Pakistan.
	   ``The aftershocks that continue to shudder through the region,
sometimes only minutes apart, keep people from moving back into
their houses and remind a population already traumatized . . . that
another could easily strike,'' she said.
	   In Chaujan, a village near the quake's epicenter, thousands of
homes were flattened. People wandered through the rubble, dazed. In
the middle of the devastation, a lone wooden door stood erect. The
clumps of mud still clinging to it was the only reminder of the
home that once stood there. The family of four that once lived
there were dead.
	   The International Red Cross and the United Nations scrambled to
establish mobile medical units in Shari Basurkh, about 50
kilometers (30 miles), from Faisabad, the capital of northern
Badakhshan province.
	   Doctors Without Borders were operating a clinic there.
Helicopters ferried the wounded, many with broken bones. Aid
workers also distributed blankets, tents and plastic sheetings.
	   Among the hardest hit areas was Rostaq, the site of a Feb. 4
earthquake that killed as many as 2,300 people and left another
8,000 homeless. When Saturday's quake hit, many in the area were
still living in tents because they had lost their homes in the
February quake.
	   Aid workers at the site said people were traumatized, their eyes
unfocused, their hands searching through the rubble. Many of the
wounded loaded onto helicopters were old women and men and small
children.
	   Cargo aircraft from neighboring Pakistan, packed with emergency
supplies, reached the region Monday.
	   As relief workers reach the hardest hit areas, they have begun
worrying about the risk of diseases like malaria, because of the
rain, Russell said. Other health hazards include hemmhoragic fever
and cholera, she said.
	   The French Foreign Ministry also planned to send about 35 tons
of humanitarian aid to nearby Dushanbe, Tajikistan, where it will
be transported to the disaster area.
	   Anti-Taliban soldiers who control this region say they have
removed 1,650 bodies, but they said thousands more people are dead.
	   The alliance spokesman Shamshul Haq Arianfar said eight villages
simply disintegrated.
	   Many of the homes in the area, already weakened by the February
temblor, crumbled like dry dust in Saturday's violent shaking. The
homes were made more vulnerable by the relentless rain that
battered the region in recent days. 	   
</TEXT>
