r i     BC-UN-India-Pakistan     06-01 0302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-India-Pakistan,0301 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Annan encouraged by response from prime ministers of India, Pakistan 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Following nuclear tests by India and
Pakistan, Secretary-General Kofi Annan spoke by telephone with the
prime ministers of the two countries over the weekend and was
encouraged by their response, a U.N. spokesman said Monday.
	   Spokesman Fred Eckhard gave few details of Annan's conversations
with Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee and Pakistani Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif except to say they were to ``encourage
dialogue on peace and security issues including Kashmir.''
	   ``He was encouraged by their reactions and intends to continue
to engage with them on these issues,'' Eckhard said. ``He was just
encouraged by their openness with him and on that basis he is
prepared to stay in touch with them.''
	   The United News of India reported that Vajpayee rejected any
third party mediation between India and Pakistan to help resolve
the Kashmir issue.
	   Annan has offered to help the parties resume their high-level
dialogue, which broke down last year over Kashmir, the Himalayan
territory which is divided between them. India and Pakistan have
fought two wars over Kashmir.
	   The Security Council has issued statements deploring the South
Asian nuclear tests and has called on both India and Pakistan to
sign nuclear control treaties without conditions.
	   India and Pakistan have resisted such treaties because they do
not require the five permanent Security Council members _ the
United States, Britain, France, Russia and China _ to dismantle
their own nuclear arsenals.
	   Foreign ministers of the five permanent members are to meet this
week in Geneva to consider the next steps in trying to curb the
nuclear arms race on the subcontinent. 	   
</TEXT>
