w1064  wstm-
r w     SIMPLY-SMASHINGsked     06-01 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> SIMPLY-SMASHING sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Simply smashing, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws SIMPLY-SMASHING sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   LET ME confess: I am a failed business journalist as evidenced
from the months of story-lessness, the unofficial media jargon for
non-productivity. I stand now as a sucker for tales of those who
can spin a report ala Fortune from stuff that baffle me: financial
records, boardroom politics and shareholding value. That's why I
ploughed through Bloomberg by Bloomberg, the czar of the financial
information industry, with deep reverence.
	   Michael Bloomberg needs no introduction. The founder of
Bloomberg L P took an extraordinary 12 years to build a media
empire that encompasses online and wire services, radio, television
and the print media.
	   He is hailed as Wall Street's best known generic name; utter
Bloomberg and all these will come to mind - Bloomberg Financial
Markets, a top provider of online financial information; Bloomberg
News, a wire service providing news stories to leading newspapers
worldwide; Bloomberg News Radio, a 24-hour nationally distributed
news radio; Bloomberg Business News, a public television programme
for the investment community and Bloomberg Television, a 24-hour
direct satellite television network.
	   But alas, I discovered that he had never been a journalist, so
no tips to gather, no uplifting morale to pick up and no insight
into the operations of a Bloomberg editorial room. This is no Ben
Bradlee's (former managing editor of Washington Post) riveting
insight into the workings of Washington Post. But plodding on
grudgingly, I was rewarded with a powerful personality -
hard-hitting candour with arrogance and humility surfacing at
times, a patronising attitude at other times, but an unmistakable
force of energy.
	   Nothing in his early life indicates that he would one day be
playing David to the Goliaths of the media industry. Armed with an
engineering degree from John Hopkins University and a masters
degree in business administration from Harvard University, he took
up a friend's suggestion to apply for a job at Wall Street's
Solomon Brothers  Hutzler (now called Goldman, Sachs  Co) as an
equity trader. For someone who had queried 'Who are they? What
would I be doing?', he loved the job, `reveled in it every minute
of the day', and quickly rose up the ladder to become a Wall Street
star and partner of the prestigious firm. As he said, he loved Wall
Street not just for the money but the lifestyle it provided. He had
humble beginnings. His father was a dairy accountant, and his
mother, a home-maker. High-style Manhattan living enthralled him.
He remembered gawking at a French restaurant's opulent decor,
having a meal with more silverware per place setting than his
family owned in total, cruising uptown in a black limo when the
only other time he had been in such a car was at his father's
funeral, and gasping at a US$ 50 tip someone had given for a two-
dollar cab ride - an amount that would have covered his entire
week's personal, social and food budget. He fittingly called this
chapter of his early life, Capitalism, Here I Come.
	   But the good life came to an end when he was 39. The firm's
merger with Phibro Corporation resulted in the termination of
several partners, including Bloomberg. After 15 years of 12-hour
days and six-day weeks, he was told: `Here's US$ 10 million; time
for you to leave.' His initial reaction: `US$ 10 million? America's
a wonderful country.' Then, with the outgoing partners, he shot
pool, smoked Cuban cigars, played poker and laughed uproariously.
As he says, `I never look over my shoulder. Once finished: gone.
Life continues.' All the same, he was worried his wife would be
ashamed of his less visible status and he broke the news with a
style that very few can afford: he presented her a sable jacket and
champagne. His contention: a sable jacket seemed to say, 'No sweat.
We can still eat. We're still players.' Yeah, I couldn't agree
more. The end of the good life spells the beginning of an even
better life! Any gutsy entrepreneur with money can enter the news
business anytime.
	   But starting something from scratch is far from easy. Bloomberg
succeeded because he filled up a gap in the financial information
industry (in his words, `making news with numbers' - combining text
and analytics with computer-driven tours that let readers
automatically see the calculations and graphs of what was written,
and followed up with words to expand what the illustration showed)
and built up his organisation's strength from there. As he says,
`From the beginning, we tried to be different.' Much to his credit,
he instinctively knew `unless our news was impartial, free of any
outside influence, and not tied to some hidden agenda, then no
amount of money or talent would assure us success as journalists'.
He admits that one must learn what one doesn't know, and then, get
access to the people who do know. He relies on professional
journalists for Bloomberg's editorial policy and the management of
the newspeople. His natural flair for the media industry and
unshaken respect for editorial ethics explains why the Bloomberg
News rivals Dow Jones and Reuters quickly.
	   More than a piece of interesting reading, the book is certainly
engaging and packed with information on how to start a lean, hungry
company and keep it that way. The book is instructive of how he
builds up his media empire, plays catch-up with the Goliaths of the
industry, balances the dollar sign with the honour of the written
word and his management style.
	   But it's not purely a business perspective, he seems nostalgic
in recalling his childhood days and family. And for those who yearn
for words of wisdom from the czar, there's also terrific, albeit,
patronising advice on how to increase and guard your investments.
The one I love - and keep reminding my hubby and thus relieving us
of the guilt of not being able to leave dollops of cash for our
offspring - `children have no God-given right to an inheritance ...
(what matters is) the best education and a grubstake to start them
off.' Take it from Bloomberg - the emperor of the financial
information industry knows what he is talking about.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 MALAYSIAN BUSINESS all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:SIMPLY-SMASHING sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
