<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 12:36:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1065  wstm-
r w     ASMB-STRIKES-BACKsked     06-01 1581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> ASMB-STRIKES-BACK sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
ASMB strikes back, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws ASMB-STRIKES-BACK sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   WITH so many unit trust funds set up in the last few years, the
country's first Bumiputera unit trust funds must surely be feeling
the heat from new competitors.
	   Amanah Saham Mara Bhd (ASMB) has not been taking it lying down.
It plans to open up funds which have been exclusively Bumiputera
for the last 30 years to all Malaysians. Says group managing
director cum chief executive officer of ASMB, Datuk Kamaruddin
Mohammed, `We have plans to re-launch the existing Tabung Kumpulan
Modal Bumiputera (TKMB) funds and open them to all Malaysians.'
Certainly this change is a milestone. `Yes, times are different
now,' concurs Kamaruddin. If implemented, it would mean that
non-Bumis will have more choices when it comes to ASMB's funds.
Currently, only five funds out of 15 are open to non-Bumiputeras.
They are ASM FPF, ASM Premier, ASPT (only for Tenaga Nasional Bhd
staff), Dana Al-Aiman and ASM TP Balanced Fund. All TKMB funds are
open to Bumiputera investors only.
	   Kamaruddin started off in ASMB as a marketing executive in 1969,
and is recognised today as one of the longest-serving chief
executive officers in the unit trust industry in Malaysia. He has
held a Securities Institute of Australia fellowship and gained work
experience Down Under.
	   Malaysian Business caught up with him to find out about what's
in store for the funds, the unit trust industry, the economy and
more. Excepts: How about a backgrounder on ASMB, the first
Bumiputera unit trust fund in Malaysia?
	   We were established in 1967. Our first Bumiputera unit trust
scheme was set up the next year, even before Perbadanan Nasional
Berhad (PNB) and Amanah Saham Nasional (ASN). Our first fund, the
Tabung Kumpulan Modal Bumiputera 1 (TKMB1), now renamed Dana
Al-Aiman, was first launched in 1968 and relaunched last year.
Between 1968 and 1980, we launched 12 funds. But most of these -
they were mainly TKMB funds - were very small, with an authorised
size of 20 million units per fund only. They were small because the
economy during that era was not as robust as the previous decade's.
The initial investment required was only RM20-RM50. But over the
years, the value per unit has grown tremendously - from RM1 to
RM12.
	   During that time, we gave out a lot of bonus issues and
dividends. The original investors then cashed out and moved into
other funds. Therefore, the 12 funds shrunk in terms of unit
circulation. Now, they are worth about RM1-RM2 per unit.
	   (ASMB was incorporated in 1967 and is wholly owned by Majlis
Amanah Rakyat or MARA. ASMB, in turn, wholly owns ASM MARA Unit
Trust Management Bhd, which was set up in 1993 to take over the
management of trusts funds from ASMB. The 15 funds have a total
approved size of 1.2 billion units.
	   As of March 31, 1998, the number of units in circulation is
606.8 million).
	   How have your funds performed as compared to three months and
nine months ago?
	   Compared to nine months ago, when the Kuala Lumpur Composite
Index (KLCE) stood at 1,077.30 points (around June 30, 1997), our
funds have dropped by 33 per cent - the stockmarket fell by 42 per
cent during this time. However, since the stockmarket rebounded to
around the 700-point range at the end of March 1998 from a low of
about 470 points in January 1998, our funds have made a gain of 48
per cent over that three-month period.
	   What is your investment strategy in view of the current
slowdown?
	   Our strategy is to liquidate positions in the stockmarket and
invest more in money market instruments.
	   What sectors do you favour?
	   We favour sectors that are expected to be the engine of growth
for the future, for example IPPs (independent power producers). We
also like defensive stocks like food-based and consumer products,
and plantations.
	   We avoid construction, property, motor, banking and finance.
However, as long-term investors, we will not avoid all other
stocks. We have to keep our ears open, look at the balance sheet
and study the company. Some companies are not up there but could
perform. We like some Tier-1 banks and finance companies which are
priced very attractively now.
	   Who are your fund managers and what is their experience? Do you
engage foreign expertise?
	   ASM MARA has been managing the 15 funds since 1993. There are 10
fund managers in the team, including a general manager and myself.
We do not have any foreign fund managers working for us. We have an
investment panel and a syariah advisory panel comprising experts
with vast experience in the field. Aminah Jaafar, general manager
of ASM MARA, is a graduate of the Institute of Chartered
Secretaries  Administrators (UK) and has been with ASMB since
1970. Our five top management staff have clocked up more than 125
years in total service to the company.
	   After almost 30 years in the unit trust industry, what is your
opinion of the current state of affairs in Malaysia?
	   The net asset value (NAV) of the local unit trust industry,
including PNB, makes up only 8.9 per cent of the Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange's (KLSE) market capitalisation. Excluding PNB, the NAV is
around 1.7 per cent. Compare this to other countries - Thailand (16
per cent), India (25 per cent), Singapore (39.8 per cent),
Australia and the United States (40 per cent), and Japan (48 per
cent). This shows that there is tremendous potential for growth for
the unit trust industry in this country.
	   The sudden increase in unit trust management companies in the
market within a short time in the past few years should bode well
for the industry as it will help make the stockmarket more matured
and less speculative. However, the concept of unit trust investment
is still not very well known to the man in the street.
	   How do you think we could further develop the industry?
	   There should be stricter compliance rules to safeguard
unit-holders. To increase professionalism, fund managers should be
adequately trained to have a more global view. Ideally, they should
be able to analyse stocks worldwide for investment opportunities
rather than concentrate on local stocks only. The Federation of
Malaysian Unit Trust Managers (FMUTM) could provide the necessary
leadership and also oversee training programmes, say, for agents.
Agents have to be trained to be more professional so that they deal
with investors more as consultants rather than as salespersons.
	   Fund managers should also be allowed to invest in more financial
instruments, for example, the futures market. The regulatory body
should also come up with guidelines to allow sales through the
Internet.
	   Is there a shortage of fund managers and if yes, how do we
overcome the problem?
	   Yes, there is. To overcome it, we need more foreign fund
managers to train local fund managers via courses. It will also be
helpful if undergraduates were exposed to the principles and
practice of investment, especially in unit trusts. Universities
should also hold courses relevant to fund managers.
	   Why do you think investment in unit trusts has not caught on yet
with the public?
	   The Malaysian public is more used to the traditional modes of
savings, for example fixed deposits and bonds. Many of them are not
aware of the benefits/returns of investment in unit trusts as there
has not been much publicity on unit trusts until recently. Also,
there is an impression that Malaysian investors are more interested
in short-term gains and fast returns.
	   What is your advice for investors?
	   Individual investors need to map out their monthly expenses and
invest only the balance. They should diversify their investment
portfolio. Those who have already invested should keep their
investments and buy more to average out the cost. Now is the time
to invest to get better capital appreciation in the middle to long
term.
	   Time has proven that if you keep your money in unit trusts, you
will reap very good benefits. For example, if in 1968 you had
RM20,000 in unit trusts, it would have grown to close to RM1
million 25 years later. If an investment gives you a return of at
least 10-15 per cent per annum, it's a good investment.
	   Are you invested overseas?
	   No, at the moment. But we plan to in the future.
	   What is your outlook for the stockmarket and the ringgit?
	   For the short-term, the KLCI should range between 680 and 750
points. I expect the CI to hit 800 points at the end of the year.
This is because there is a lot of uncertainty in the market.
Developments in Indonesia would also impact on our economy. Ours is
basically a crisis of confidence. Sentiments of investors are
reflected in stock prices. The government has been trying its best
to show that our fundamentals are still intact but it is up to the
people to believe it or not.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 MALAYSIAN BUSINESS all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
