Rover's back on track, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws ROVER'S-BACK-ON-TRACK sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE Rover Group, Britain's leading carmaker and exporter
announced an operating profit in 1997. It made an operational
contribution of STG31 million to its parent, BMW, compared to a
loss of STG29 million in 1996.
	   The group's four brands - Rover, Land Rover, Mini and MG
generated great interest at the recent Geneva Motor Show. This year
marks the 50th anniversary of Land Rover, the world's most famous
line of four-wheel drive vehicles. Taking pride of place at the
display was the Freelander, the new and highly-acclaimed sports
utility vehicle which is currently being launched across Europe.
Available in three body styles - Softback three-door, Hardback
three-door and five-door Station Wagon - the Freelander offers the
choice of 1.8 litre K Series petrol or 2.0 litre L Series diesel
power.
	   
