w1068  wstm-
r w     RETRAINING-OF-RETRENCHED     06-01 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> RETRAINING-OF-RETRENCHED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Retraining of retrenched workers timely, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws RETRAINING-OF-RETRENCHED sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   A MID the gloom of being retrenched, there is a ray of sunshine
for retrenched workers in the manufacturing and services industry.
	   The announcement by Human Resources Minister Datuk Lim Ah Lek
that the government will fully sponsor professional and technical
courses for retrenched workers is heartening. The move is also
timely as it will ensure that the retrenched workers would be able
to acquire new skills.
	   There is no doubt that the Malaysian economy will undergo
structural changes as it recovers from the stock market and
currency turmoil. The question is, will we be ready to take on
these new challenges as the economy picks up?
	   There will obviously be many new areas of growth. Just as the
mid-eighties recession brought about a shift in emphasis to certain
sectors and industries, the current downturn will give rise to new
areas of growth and opportunities.
	   Perhaps with the emphasis on information technology and the
multimedia super corridor, this area could be a new engine of
growth. In fact, IT- related courses are among the various diploma
and certificate level courses on offer.
	   The basic conditions for workers to qualify for any of the 133
diploma and certificate level courses is also flexible. Even
retrenched workers from companies not registered with the Human
Resources Development Council can apply.
	   The Malaysian workforce has in the past been very receptive to
learning new skills. It is hoped that those laid-off and still
unable to find a job will pursue these courses.
	   Even if they manage to find a job while attending the course,
they can always continue with it on a part-time basis. This is
certainly an opportunity not to be missed.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 MALAYSIAN BUSINESS all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:RETRAINING-OF-RETRENCHED sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
