<HEADER>
w1069  wstm-
r w     METAL-RECLAMATION-TO-GOs     06-01 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> METAL-RECLAMATION-TO-GO sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Metal Reclamation to go on expansion trail, BUSINESS TIMES  
   xfdws METAL-RECLAMATION-TO-GO sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   AT A time when most businesses are consolidating, Metal
Reclamation Bhd is set to undertake a RM63 million expansion drive,
a big portion of which will be financed with internally-generated
funds and RM25 million with proceeds from its flotation exercise.
	   The flotation exercise involves a public issue of 5.97 million
ordinary shares of RM1 each at RM1.80 a share which will generate
about RM30 million for the company.
	   In an interview with Business Times, Metal Reclamation's
managing director, Mr Lim Sheng Seaw, said apart from the funds
generated in the flotation, the group will take up RM20 million in
bank borrowings to finance its expansion plan.
	   With this, he added, the group's bank borrowings will increase
to RM80 million which although looks big actually comprises largely
short-term loans for trade financing.
	   Lim pointed out that the group's borrowings for working capital
stand at only RM3 million compared with total credit facilities of
RM102 million granted by its bankers.
	   Thus, in actual fact, Metal Reclamation's debt ratio ``is very
small'' and it is in the long-term interest of the group to
partially finance its plans with proceeds from corporate exercises
because for the group to grow it is not advisable to be tied down
by huge long-term loans, he added.
	   It is for this reason, Lim said, that the company is going for a
listing as it will enable to have access to cash it needs to grow
within the reclamation and sale of lead and lead alloys industry
and to venture into other businesses that have synergies with the
group's forte.
	   ``The money that we raise from the listing exercise is for the
business which in turn will provide us with more opportunities
later,'' he added.
	   Lim said he is confident Metal Reclamation will receive
favourable response from investors when it is listed sometime in
the first half of this year since its heavy investments show the
company's strong commitment to its business.
	   Furthermore, he pointed out, the investing public should take
heart from Metal Reclamation's dominant position in the making of
lead acid batteries for motor vehicles.
	   There are four million scrap batteries in Malaysia every year
and Metal Reclamation controls close to 90 per cent of this
industry through its recycling operations.
	   Commenting on the weak sales of new cars, Lim said Metal
Reclamation will not be affected much as based on its projection at
least 150,000 new cars will be on the road this year to join the
existing four million cars already in use, providing the company
with a ready and lucrative market.
	   Even in the worst of times, he added, the company can look
forward to get the lion's share of the minimum two million
batteries a year used because car batteries last only two years.
	   In any case, Lim contended, Metal Reclamation's earnings base is
quite diversified with its batteries division contributing 30 per
cent to group turnover followed by 20 per cent from its cable
division which provides cable alloys used in the production of
paper insulated and lead covered cables, with the rest coming from
its pure lead and tin solders division.
	   For the year ended December 31 1997, the group recorded a
pre-tax profit of RM6.95 million on the back of RM203.88 million in
turnover which Lim said is expected to grow at a rate of 5 per cent
a year for the coming five years.
	   However, central to Metal Reclamation's plans to strengthen its
earnings base and its growth projection is whether it will be able
to build its proposed plant at Pulau Indah in Klang.
	   With the plant in operation, Lim said, Metal Reclamation will be
able to further diversify its business base by moving into, for
example, plastic recycling.
	   The plant, which is expected to cost RM63 million, will not only
increase Metal Reclamation's production capacity to 70,000 tonnes a
year from the current 36,000 tonnes of pure lead and lead alloys,
but will also be important in reducing usage of imported raw
materials to 30 per cent from 60 per cent.
	   It will also provide an opportunity to the group to once again
participate in the international market as it did in the early
1990s when a quarter of the group's turnover was derived from the
export market, Lim said.
	   He added that the company will not have any trouble getting into
the export market since its 99.97 per cent refined lead under the
brand name ``MRISB-MALAYSIA'' is registered with the London Metal
Exchange which enables the company to sell its products anywhere in
the world with trading conducted in US dollars.
	   Lim said this puts Metal Reclamation in an advantageous position
as the weakened ringgit has not impaired its profits since trade,
even in the country, is based on the US dollar and is only
converted to the ringgit at the point of sale.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:METAL-RECLAMATION-TO-GO sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
