<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Gazza and Spice </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Spice Girls, Gazza sensations have Britain in a tizzy 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ It was all over the tabloids Monday, and the
quality papers, too. Questions were asked in the House of Commons:
Geri Spice is out. So's Gazza.
	   Two idols fallen on a single weekend, touching on national
obsessions with pop music, soccer and celebrity.
	   Geri Halliwell, 25, was the eldest member of the Spice Girls,
the inventor of ``girl power,'' the gorgeous pouting idol of
millions of pre-adolescent girls. She quit after a series of fights
with the other four members of the group _ and after earning a
reported dlrs 20 million in the two years since ``Wannabe'' put
them on top of the charts.
	   ``What a shame,'' the Daily Star said in an editorial. ``The
very power, energy and drive that made them a world pop phenomenon
has now destroyed them.''
	   Paul Gascoigne, 31, was a sometimes brilliant soccer player who
won the nation's heart with his tears when he was ejected from the
1990 World Cup. But the nation often had to think again: Gazza
drunk, Gazza posing at a urinal on his wedding day, Gazza's wife
Sheryl _ inevitably dubbed ``Shezza'' by the tabloids _ walking out
of the marriage with a bruised face.
	   ``His graceless existence has overwhelmed his footballing
qualities,'' said an editorial in The Mirror, the
second-largest-selling tabloid.
	   England manager Glen Hoddle dropped Gascoigne from the World Cup
squad because of his poor physicial condition. ``It's a great pity
that Paul has not got himself fit. It's a pity he has so many
injuries over the last months and the injuries kept coming,''
Hoddle said.
	   Halliwell's announcement of her retirement and Gascoigne's
dismissal were front-page naturals for the popular press. They even
rated brief mentions on the front of the Financial Times.
	   In the House of Commons, Labor lawmaker Gareth Thomas urged the
government to encourage Geri ``to think again.''
	   ``Are you aware that local authority initiatives to encourage
tourism in my area may well be undermined by the need to divert
resources to fund trauma counseling for the younger members of my
constituency?'' he said.
	   But Tom Clarke, the minister for film and tourism, said the
government wasn't inclined to intervene.
	   Gazza isn't the government's problem either, but Conservative
lawmaker Anne McIntosh managed to work his sad situation into a
discussion of the ``social exclusion'' of Britain's down and out.
	   ``I wonder if you would like to comment on the impact on the
England football team of excluding Gazza from the squad?'' she
said, drawing laughter from her colleagues.
	   Sports Minister Tony Banks said he hoped Hoddle had made the
right decision.
	   ``I expect the English team to do even better now, even with the
personal tragedy surrounding the football exclusion of that great
character Gazza,'' Banks said.
	   (rb-kg)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Britain-Gazza and Spice; CT:i; 
