<HEADER>
w1080  wstm-
r w     WORLD-FREE-OF-N-ARMSsked     06-01 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> WORLD-FREE-OF-N-ARMS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Big 5 should lead way to world free of N-arms, BUSINESS TIMES  
   xfdws WORLD-FREE-OF-N-ARMS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   IN condemning the nuclear tests by Pakistan, which was
responding to the tests conducted earlier by India, the world seems
to have forgotten that the nuclear arms race actually began many
years ago.
	   If India, a poverty-stricken developing country, is rightly
proud of its scientific and technical achievement in exploding five
nuclear devices, then Pakistan should also be proud of its
brilliant scientists and engineers in building and successfully
exploding not just five, but an incredible six nuclear bombs in a
matter of days.
	   A nation can be economically poor but this does not necessarily
mean that it is poor in scientific and technical talent.
	   The myth created by those in developed countries that an
economically poor nation remains poor because of the lack of
scientific and engineering talent has been exploded with the
explosion of nuclear devices by India and Pakistan.
	   In fact, the myth was first exploded in 1964 when China, another
big but poor country, exploded its first atomic bomb in 1964.
	   From that time onwards, poor and developing countries have begun
to realise that economic poverty did not necessarily mean poverty
in scientific and engineering talent. A nation may be poor but it
can also achieve certain things which the rich and developed
countries are able to do.
	   If anything else, the nuclear tests by Pakistan constitute the
latest demonstration of how a poor and developing nation can take
pride in its scientific and technical capabilities.
	   It is blatant hypocrisy that the current five major nuclear
powers, which have among them massive stockpiles of nuclear bombs
and missile warheads which can obliterate the world several times
over, can turn around and condemn India and Pakistan for going
nuclear.
	   If they do not want the other non-nuclear countries to go
nuclear, they should have set an example a long time ago and
completely destroyed their own nuclear stockpiles so that we can
all live in a nuclear-free world.
	   Instead, what really happened was that the Big Five nuclear
powers engaged in an expensive nuclear arms race which threatened
the world and introduced more destructive and dangerous weapons
over the years.
	   Technological one-upmanship was of such a magnitude that
billions of dollars were spent and precious scientific and
engineering resources wasted just to get a minor strategic edge
over the adversary.
	   There was even a chilling strategic concept known as MAD, which
stood for Mutually Assured Destruction. The frightening thing was
that MAD was not thought up by mad men but by seemingly respectable
persons with good brains and intellect and who had received the
right kind of education to qualify themselves to lead and manage
advanced industrialised countries.
	   To the advocates of MAD, tossing around with figures of millions
of dead and injured people as a result of nuclear attacks became
just a game.
	   Killing in a potential nuclear war was of such a scale that it
degenerated into a kind of intellectual exercise in the minds of
the nuclear strategists.
	   If a few hundred or even a few thousands are killed in an
ordinary conflict, one can feel the pain and the tragedy of those
who die, but in the more tragic circumstances of a nuclear
conflict, the millions of those who are wiped out are nothing more
than statistics because they are so many of them for us to feel the
pain.
	   The major nuclear powers have for years been arming themselves
with huge stockpiles of bombs and nuclear warheads which reflected
nothing more than the murderous desire for ``overkill.''
	   Why build a few thousand nuclear bombs when a few hundreds will
be sufficient to destroy your adversary?
	   There is no rationale for this desire for overkill and yet the
major nuclear powers, with all their highly educated strategic
planners, could not resist the temptation to build more and more
nuclear weapons over the years that the nuclear arms build-up took
on a life - and a momentum - of their own until the so-called Cold
War came to an end with the break-up of the Soviet Union.
	   However, even with the Cold War being over, the stockpiles of
nuclear weapons still in the hands of the five major nuclear powers
are enormous enough to destroy the world several times over. It
looks like the major nuclear powers are still reluctant to abandon
the ``overkill'' mentality.
	   The tests by India and now Pakistan may have introduced a
dangerous nuclear arms race in the sub-continent but the world
itself is neither a more dangerous nor safer place now than it was
before the nuclear tests by India and Pakistan.
	   The culprits who started the dangerous nuclear arms race - the
US, Russia, Britain, France and China - have not got rid of their
own nuclear arsenals. Therefore, they have no moral right to stop
other countries from conducting nuclear tests nor to build their
own nuclear weapons.
	   How can the existing nuclear powers condemn India and Pakistan
for conducting nuclear tests and building their own nuclear weapons
and missiles when they themselves have been doing the same thing
for years and on a much bigger scale?
	   The major nuclear powers have subjected the world - their own
populations and the peoples of other countries as well - for the
last five decades to the threat of a nuclear world war.
	   This threat still exists because they have refused to discard
their nuclear arsenals and yet they demand that other non-nuclear
countries should not go nuclear.
	   If the world is to be truly safe from the potential threat of
nuclear destruction, then the first step should be taken by the
existing nuclear powers themselves in completely destroying their
own nuclear stockpiles.
	   The only way to achieve a nuclear-free world is for the five
major nuclear powers to first free themselves from nuclear arms.
	   
</TEXT>
