<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
3 team up to develop AGV navigation system, BUSINESS TIMES  
   xfdws AGV-NAVIGATION-SYSTEM sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   PSA Corp Ltd, DSO National Laboratories and CET Technologies Pte
Ltd signed an agreement on May 30 this year to jointly develop a
navigation system to operate automated guided vehicles (AGVs) at
PSA's container terminals.
	   This navigation system is the ``auto-pilot'' which controls the
movements of AGVs in the container yard.
	   Proven technologies for unmanned operations such as ground
vehicle control, navigation sensors, signal processing and wireless
communications will be used in its development.
	   This project is another commitment by PSA to invest in
capabilities to improve the reliability and speed of their
operations to serve their customers better.
	   It represents another phase in the automation of PSA's container
terminals, following the successful completion of the pilot testing
of AGVs last year.
	   In the next few years, PSA will implement this navigation system
to operate a small fleet of AGVs at one berth at its new Pasir
Panjang Terminal before implementing it at other berths.
	   DSO National Laboratories will design and develop the navigation
system and handle the design integration of the entire AGV system
based on the PSA's specifications and requirements. CET
Technologies will supply and integrate the components used in the
system.
	   PSA will provide the terminal operations knowledge for the
project and develop the deployment system for the AGVs.
	   In a statement released in Kuala Lumpur last Saturday, PSA group
president Khoo Teng Chye said: ``We are very pleased with our
partnership with DSO National Laboratories and CET Technologies.
	   This joint venture, he said, is an example of PSA's commitment
to invest substantially in technologies to develop pioneering
techniques in container handling that will significantly boost
productivity and service levels for our customers.
	   On safety record for 1997, PSA has reduced its injury rate by 45
per cent despite a 9.2 per cent increase in the number of
containers handled in the same year.
	   In 1997 there were 66 accidents causing injury to PSA staff and
non-PSA staff working at PSA's premises compared with 121 in 1996.
	   PSA's accident frequency rate (accidents per million man-hours
worked) was 2.5, lower than the rate of 2.6 for all industries in
Singapore.
	   In addition, PSA's accident rate per million TEUs handled was
reduced by 50 per cent from 9.4 in 1996 to 4.7 in 1997.
	   
</TEXT>
