<HEADER>
w1084  wstm-
r w     CALIBRATING-THE-LOST-OFs     06-01 1893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> CALIBRATING-THE-LOST-OF sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Calibrating the cost of IT, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws CALIBRATING-THE-LOST-OF sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   MORE AND more chief financial officers (CFOs) are embracing the
concept of total cost of ownership (TCO) for managing corporate
asset costs, with determining the cost of information technology
(IT) to your company being one of the most aggressive focuses.
While you may not be responsible for calculating IT TCO for your
entire organisation, chances are that someday soon someone will tap
your budgets under a heading that reflects IT TCO.
	   To get ready to manage relevant IT costs, a good starting point
would be to develop a working knowledge of TCO for desktop and
portable computers, and how to begin reducing PC-related costs
immediately.
	   It may surprise you to find out exactly how much PCs cost your
organisation. I know when I was first introduced to the figures for
my organisation, I was amazed, appalled and immediately suspicious
of the source of these seemingly inflated figures. However, after
seeing the strong relevance of these figures to the process of
calculating PC TCO, I was able to accurately verify these costs on
my own. Then, I was able to take action on reducing these costs for
my regional headquarters operation here in Kuala Lumpur, and other
Gateway operations in South Asia. More importantly, I've championed
efforts toward staff training to help Gateway better assist
customers in identifying TCO factors and issues to reduce customer
costs. Here's how you can get started.
	   Defining PC TCO In essence, PC TCO is all costs associated with
the acquisition and operation of personal computers; from the
initial purchase to training and support, including the cost of
downtime to your organisation. A more complete list of PC TCO
components looks like this: hardware - desktop and portable PCs and
peripherals, software -productivity software, utilities and
custom-developed applications, training - PC operation and
software-specific instruction, management -utility costs of PCs at
work, such as upgrades and enhancements, support - fixing hardware
and software problems, and downtime - lost revenue and productivity
due to system delays and failures.
	   When looking into these elements as cost centres, managers can
identify shortcomings, inefficiencies and waste associated with
PCs, whether it is for a small workgroup, department or an entire
organisation. Sometimes, these costs and potential savings can be
difficult to identify at first, yet, they can ultimately be very
dramatic.
	   Hardware myths: Cheaper is not always better To begin with, one
common misconception that I had, and many managers have, is that
hardware is the principal cost associated with PC TCO. In fact, it
is one of the smaller elemental costs, typically representing less
than 20 per cent of PC TCO.
	   Here's an example. Under hardware, one can take the original
price of a PC, then add the cost of additional peripherals, ie,
modems, printers, scanners, etc. Also included in the hardware cost
is any fee associated with delivery, set-up, and configuration for
the system and all peripherals. This is quite straight forward.
	   However, what is not so clear is the connection between a
specific hardware purchase - regardless of initial price - and the
impact on other elemental costs such as management, support and
downtime. This is where the serious TCO action often takes place.
	   Management makes it happen Management describes the cost of
leveraging PCs in the work environment.
	   This encompasses general systems administration, such as
alterations to hardware or software capabilities to suit changing
requirements. This does not, however, include repairs, which fall
under support. In some environments, management may also reflect
the cost of network management and administration, but frankly, for
workgroups and departmental managers, PC TCO is best calculated
separately.
	   The golden rule for reducing management costs for PCs is to buy
systems that support current and foreseeable future requirements.
Why? Today's cheaper PCs may be capable of handling your current
requirements, but one modest software update can easily make that
investment obsolete, requiring new systems. The result: no cost
savings on management, with often a negative and lingering impact
on support and downtime as you and your team come face to face with
the ramifications of a short-sighted purchase.
	   In today's market, here's how to avoid early PC obsolescence.
Think in terms of purchasing fresh technology. Generally, it comes
down to performance, capacity and manageability. Today's
performance desktop PCs are based on Intel's Pentium II-class
processors, where for obsolescence avoidance, I recommend systems
running at 300 MHz or more with 64 MBs of RAM and 4 GBs of hard
disk, such as Gateway's E-Series E-3110 300. The E-3110 comes with
advanced manageability features built in, giving PC users and
systems administrators the ability to diagnose and anticipate
problems before they occur, which can save downtime and money.
	   Similarly, for portable systems look at Pentium II processors
with enough RAM and hard disk space to grow on.
	   Support for office PCs Support includes all costs associated
with fixing hardware and software problems. The good news is that
PC hardware and software has become far more reliable since the
dawn of the PC revolution. The bad news is that this enhanced
reliability is most often only achieved by investing in
high-quality, brand name systems to avoid faulty components and
software compatibility issues.
	   Here again, the golden rule for reducing support costs is to
invest in quality systems from a vendor who you are confident will
be around tomorrow. Vendors must be directly accountable to both
requisitioning managers and users in providing solid warranties,
and then stand behind their products with extended support
programs. Support is a major cost centre because having a trained
professional capable of fixing most PC problems arrive at your
location costs money. But, as where there is smoke, there is fire,
when there is support, there is downtime, and that can be most
costly of all.
	   Downtime equals lost revenue and productivity Downtime cost
calculations can be somewhat tricky, but as you will see, it is one
of the most significant issues regarding PC TCO. To make this
calculation, you must first factor how much time management and
staff spend interacting with the computer to conduct their jobs.
Next, you figure the cost to your business when computers don't
work, in the form of lost revenue or sales and lost productivity.
	   It takes little imagination to consider a variety of
circumstances where PC TCO of a given computer can multiply in
hours or even minutes. Savvy managers quickly begin equating down
computers as a steady stream of revenue seeping through cracks in
the floor. You are very lucky if you are having trouble imagining
such dire circumstances. But these circumstances do not have to be
so dramatic. Intermittent failures or even slow performing systems
sap productivity, often both materially and spiritually on the part
of employees.
	   My best advice on reducing downtime is two-fold. First, invest
in quality, both in terms of hardware and software. Second, take
advantage of vendor-provided internal or external support
professionals and insist on fast, effective problem resolution.
	   Software on the rise in TCO Software continues to grow as part
of PC TCO, and in many cases, eclipses hardware and other cost
elements. This is especially true in environments with a
significant investment in customised applications software, such as
resource planning, accounting and GroupWare.
	   Reducing software TCO is best accomplished by rigorous software
asset management and training. Studies have shown that an
organisation's software costs can often be reduced by between 20
and 30 per cent or more through a more complete accounting and
administration of software licenses. For example, computers most
often come equipped with operating systems, but are regularly
reigned into corporate software licensing agreements.
	   Even more common are situations where purchased software goes
uninstalled or forgotten, delivering no value to the organisation.
	   Training is paramount The most important aspect of ensuring
returns on software investments and other elements of PC TCO is
training. Of course, some managers and staff insist that software
training is unnecessary or a poor use of time.
	   Here again, experience shows that time spent on training can
significantly boost productivity on both standard and custom
software applications.
	   You have most likely heard someone look over your shoulder and
say, `Wow, I didn't know that button could do that!,' or `That
feature certainly would have been great to know about when...'
Beyond productivity, software specific training also helps identify
what not to do, and contributes to avoiding downtime.
	   Standardisation leads to cost savings The fastest route to
reducing PC TCO is through standardisation.
	   Standardisation among hardware and software vendors and
configurations leads to savings and significant efficiencies in all
elements of PC TCO, especially in areas such as support, training
and downtime.
	   Identifying the appropriate model of desktop and portable
computers that will satisfy current and future requirements is the
first step. My company, Gateway, has implemented a global offering
called Custom Integration Service (CIS) that focuses on helping
companies identify specific requirements for desktop and portable
computers and reducing PC TCO. CIS goes steps further by building
each system's hardware and software configuration exactly to an
individual customer's specifications, then delivering the system to
the customer's door. Customers simply remove the box and plug in
the new system to start productive work.
	   PC TCO checklist Here's a checklist to help you begin to
identify and reduce PC TCO: quality products serving current and
future requirements, quality support to avoid problems and
downtime, quality training pays off in productivity enhancements,
asset management reduces redundancies, and standardisation improves
all aspects of PC TCO.
	   I look forward to answering any questions you have regarding
managing PC TCO or other topics that I've covered in this column.
Next time, I will be focusing on ways to manage repetitive stress
problems associated with computer use.
	   The writer is managing director of Gateway 2000 (South Asia).
This is the second in a series of articles on managing IT. Views
expressed are the writer's own.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 MALAYSIAN BUSINESS all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
