<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Air France-Strike, 5th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Anger, embarrassment as strike begins before World Cup TRIMS. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: AMs; RECASTS and UPDATES throughout with new quotes, color.
AP Photos PAR101-109
By CHRISTOPHER BURNS
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ In normal times, an Air France strike would merely
cause havoc.
	   But the walkout by the carrier's pilots Monday was worse: a deep
embarrassment for a country preparing to host in just nine days the
world's biggest sporting event, the World Cup.
	   Despite pressure from leftist government ministers, most of the
state-run carrier's 3,200 pilots stayed out of their cockpits to
protest 500 million francs (dlrs 83 million) in annual pay cuts.
They are threatening to stay out for two weeks or more.
	   That's well into the World Cup, which begins June 10 and lasts a
month. On just the first day Monday, 100,000 passengers were sent
scrambling.
	   And it could be only the beginning: French train workers were
planning to strike at the end of the week.
	   Desperate travelers lined ticket counters at Paris airports
Monday, while the Air France planes they were supposed to take,
many colorfully painted with soccer players for the championship,
sat idle.
	   Departure screens offered a bleak sight: they alternately
flashed ``annule'' and ``canceled'' in bright red.
	   Nicolas Minvelle, hoping to leave on vacation for Senegal, said
it wasn't fair that the pilots were striking just before the World
Cup, which is being played in 10 cities across France.
	   ``They use an international event to bother everyone. It's too
bad,'' he said at Charles de Gaulle Airport.
	   The airports in Lyon and Marseille, France's second and
third-largest cities, were virtually deserted. Rental car agencies
did brisk business.
	   Hassan Beloumi spent only a few minutes at the Marseille
airport. The 63-year-old Tunisian was supposed to fly back to
Tunis, but couldn't get any information. So he decided to stay in
France.
	   ``I'll go back to Tunis when the strike is over,'' he said. In
any case, he added, ``I'll have a longer vacation.''
	   Mark Wall, an American living in Amsterdam, had to return from
Lyon quickly for professional reasons.
	   ``No problem,'' he said at the Lyon-Satolas airport. ``They gave
me a ticket for tonight on a Sabena flight.''
	   At Paris' other main airport, Orly, Air France had arranged for
Vince Narez and his wife to take a Northwest Airlines flight back
to California.
	   ``We're not very happy about it, but we want to get home,'' said
Narez, of San Jose.
	   Passengers ``are being taken hostage,'' the French passenger
association ADUA said angrily. It called the walkout by the pilots,
among the highest-paid in the world, ``a strike by the privileged
of the skies.''
	   It said the strike was hurting France's image and offending
taxpayers who paid billions of francs (dollars) to bail out the
once-struggling airline. It called for anti-strike demonstrations
in the airports.
	   The walkout would be Air France's longest in 27 years if it
lasts the projected two weeks. It was an embarrassing blow to the
leftist government of Prime Minister Lionel Jospin.
	   The Communist transport minister, Jean-Claude Gayssot, on Sunday
made a final appeal for both sides to negotiate. But by late
Monday, no new talks were planned.
	   ``Negotiating teams are ready at Air France,'' said the
carrier's director general, Henri Gourgeon.
	   The airline said it would make good on its commitment to fly
World Cup teams.
	   But it canceled 90 percent of long-haul flights Monday, and most
short- and medium-haul flights.
	   Unlike past conflicts, when ground crews blocked runways and
clashed with police, the pilots simply didn't show up for work.
	   They are protesting plans to save dlrs 83 million through salary
cuts while offering pilots shares in the airline. They also are
angry about salary cuts for starting pilots.
	   Christian Paris, spokesman for the main union, the SNPL,
admitted the strike's consequences were ``disastrous.''
	   ``But when you're confronted by an attack you have no choice but
to defend yourself,'' he told France 2 television.
	   The union has called a 15-day renewable strike. Three smaller
unions have called for a strike until Thursday.
	   Also for Thursday, the CGT union is calling a strike affecting
most public services, and the energy and construction sectors.
	   In Paris, Michael Apstein of Boston didn't mind taking a later
connecting flight to Montpellier on another airline, Air Liberte.
	   ``It's nice to have a strike once in a while,'' he said, ``so
you can go into Paris for lunch for four or five hours.''
	   (cb-eg-parf-jn) 	   
</TEXT>
