<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 12:46:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1086  wstm-
r w     WOOING-FORIEGN-PARTNERSs     06-01 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> WOOING-FORIEGN-PARTNERS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Wooing foreign partners to survive, BUSINESS TIMES  
   xfdws WOOING-FORIEGN-PARTNERS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   IF BINARIANG Bhd, the young but aggressive telecommunications
conglomerate, can sell a huge chunk of its shares to yet another
foreign partner, there is no longer any justification to prevent
other Malaysian companies from following in its footsteps.
	   This is especially so when the foreign interest Binariang is
selling its stake to is a company controlled by the Singapore
Government.
	   Some Malaysian parties - public and private - seem to have an
aversion for all things Singaporean even though they are good.
	   Binariang, a company seen by many as enjoying a special position
in the country's corporate arena, has by its sale of shares to
Singapore Telecoms, provided others with an equally strong
justification to sell theirs to foreign parties in their desperate
efforts to stay alive.
	   Binariang, which counts among its prized possessions Maxis
cellular and fixed line telephone services and Astro satellite pay
television, is understood to have wooed the Singapore company to be
its second foreign partner.
	   Its first foreign partner is US West International, which holds
19.8 per cent of Binariang's shares.
	   While Binariang, whose literal Malay translation means ``happy
building'', declined to comment on the deal, it is understood that
Singapore Telecoms may buy as much as 40 per cent of the company's
existing paid-up capital.
	   If the figure is correct, foreign shareholdings in Binariang
will be only slightly lower than the 61 per cent maximum allowed.
The Government recently raised the maximum for foreign equity in a
telecommunications firm from 49 per cent to 61.
	   The Singapore Telecoms deal is said to be worth RM1.4 billion.
	   Several local companies have either sold substantial stakes to
foreign firms, or announced plans to sell strategic blocks of their
shares to foreign partners.
	   With many local companies facing debt and cash flow problems as
a result of the ringgit's depreciation and the sharp fall in the
prices of shares, the alternative to insolvency is to sell shares
and assets.
	   The disposal of shares and assets to foreigners is fast becoming
an imperative for local businessmen as credit dries up and interest
rates remain prohibitive.
	   Sales to local investors do not seem possible as they too face a
credit squeeze. The use of many capital market instruments to
finance share purchases is either officially curtailed or is
commercially not feasible due to the shortage of funds and the high
interest rates.
	   As it now stands, only foreign investors are capable of buying
shares and assets of local companies, and are willing to pay a much
higher price than what is currently quoted on the Kuala Lumpur
Stock Exchange.
	   With the exception of problems brought about by the sudden and
sharp depreciation of the ringgit and the ensuing credit squeeze,
many Malaysian companies remain viable.
	   This is recognised by foreign long-term investors who are keen
to take up strategic shareholdings as well as use Malaysian
companies as vehicles for regional and international expansion.
	   Unless the Government has a better and surer way of solving the
problems of these companies, it should not discourage them from
selling their shares and assets.
	   It can help speed up approvals and encourage local companies to
seek out strategic foreign partners instead of having these firms
selling their shares and assets outright.
	   Before the crisis, companies could wait for months for their
applications to be approved without major problems to operations.
Today, they need approvals more speedily as weeks or even days make
a big difference.
	   It is better to allow local businessmen, including Bumiputeras,
to divest part of their holdings instead of forcing them to retain
their shares and risk bankruptcy.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:WOOING-FORIEGN-PARTNERS sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
