<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Obit-Mexico-Pedraza,0159 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hero of 1968 Olympics dies of hepatitis 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Jose Pedraza, an army sergeant who thrilled
Mexico with a late charge for a silver medal in walking at the 1968
Olympic games here, died Monday of hepatitis. He was 61.
	   Pedraza was third as he entered University Stadium at the end of
the 20-kilometer walk. The crowd thundered encouragement as he
passed one Soviet competitor and came just short of passing the
other by the finish line.
	   Frustrated by his failure to overtake the winner despite the
spectacular finish, he repeatedly hit himself in the head with his
hands.
	   ``This was an unforgettable moment in Mexican sports,'' said
Guillermo Ochoa, presenter of the show ``Today'' on the nation's
leading television network, Televisa.
	   Pedraza continued in the military and held the rank of captain
at the time of his death, according to military officials, who
announced the death. 	   
</TEXT>
