<BODY>
<SLUG> SALE-OF-15PC-IN-MALAKOFF sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
MRCB: Sale of 15pc stake in Malakoff a `good value' deal, BUSINESS TIMES  
   xfdws SALE-OF-15PC-IN-MALAKOFF sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   MALAYSIAN Resources Corp Bhd (MRCB) sees the sale of a 15 per
cent stake in Malakoff Bhd to UK-based National Power Plc (NPP) as
necessary to maintain the group's overall financial strength.
	   Chief operating officer Izzaddin Idris said on Saturday that
MRCB is going through with the agreement as it is a ``good value
deal'' which will see the group selling part of its stake at a
premium price.
	   The sale, together with the proposed disposal of MRCB's 51 per
cent equity interest in Teknik Janakuasa Sdn Bhd, will result in
MRCB deriving an extraordinary gain of RM480 million which will be
used to pay off a substantial portion of its borrowings, which will
be reduced to RM1.2 billion from the current RM1.6 billion.
	   A huge portion of the borrowings arises from MRCB's US$250
million (US$1    RM3.89) bridging facility to finance the
subscription of 34.7
million new shares and 14.9 million warrants in Rashid Hussain Bhd.	   Thus, Izzaddin said, the deal will effectively help reduce the
group's debt ratio to 0.4 from the current 0.6 against
shareholders' funds of RM2.86 billion.
	   It is also expected to offset the translation loss of RM372.5
million (based on the assumption that the exchange rate is RM4 to
US$1), as MRCB will have an extraordinary gain of RM480 million
based on both the corporate exercises.
	   However, he said, the sale should not be seen just as a dollar
and cents deal, as MRCB stands to gain an important strategic
partner which will open many doors to Malakoff in the international
power market.
	   NPP is a renowned international player with operations in Europe
and India, and it has invited Malakoff to participate in some of
their overseas projects, Izzaddin said. ``But due to the current
economic environment, we would rather concentrate on the domestic
market first,'' he added.
	   Furthermore, MRCB sees NPP as a useful strategic partner in
Malakoff's domestic market, especially where direct foreign
investment is required.
	   Izzaddin said this when asked to comment on the rationale for
MRCB's disposal of a 15 per cent stake in Malakoff, which has been
described as a ``cash cow''. Malakoff chalked up a quadruple
increase in pre-tax profit for the half-year ended February 28
1998, to RM174.50 million from RM43.48 million.
	   He also said MRCB's results for the half-year ended February 28
1998, which saw its pre-tax profit falling 65 per cent to RM51.94
million from RM147.93 million, did not come as a surprise
considering the current situation.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
