w1094  wstm-
r w     BOLD-MOVES-DOWNsked     06-01 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BOLD-MOVES-DOWN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Bold moves down under, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws BOLD-MOVES-DOWN sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   HE IS Melbourne's most prolific CBD (central business district)
property buyer. He is managing director of one of the country's
fastest-growing listed companies. And he can sniff out a capital
gain from 100 paces.
	   But the high profile activities of lawyer Jason Yeap, a former
Malaysian citizen, are in sharp contrast to the way he likes to do
business.
	   Despite a track record of savvy counter cyclical property plays
which have put him in the limelight, the quiet Yeap and his stash
of wealthy Asian investors firmly shun the attention.
	   On a public front, however, he is willing to talk about his
latest venture with the recent relaunch of listed company Phileo
Australia. In less than two years he has increased assets from a
mere A$2 million to more than A$60 million, and has managed to
snare some of the city's prime redevelopment sites before most
people even realised they were valuable.
	   But it is Yeap's private client deals that keep the market
ticking over and the market watchers fascinated.
	   In the past five years he has spent more than A$200 million
buying properties throughout Melbourne on behalf of overseas
investors as an adviser and lawyer.
	   At the moment, interests he represents control 15 Melbourne CBD
office buildings, including seven along the prime Collins Street
office strip.
	   He also has another five or so, `I've never had to add them up
before', on city fringes to make a current portfolio of 20
buildings.
	   Making money from property involves a simple formula, Yeap says,
despite multi-billion dollar losses by the big expert banks,
institutions and developers during the last slump. `Basically, we
look for undervalued assets in the best addresses,' he tells
Malaysian Business.
	   `Of course potential capital gain is our main driving force,
either through value growth over a period of time or we improve the
assets and the value increases from that improvement.
	   `I like to pick the best address in a city and in Melbourne
that's Collins Street. Our next best would be Queen Street and then
Bourke,' he adds.
	   Melbourne's landmark former stock exchange building is to be the
next project off the starting blocks after last year receiving
approval for a new office and residential tower at 357 Collins
Street.
	   The planned transformation of the derelict drab 1960s building
includes 20,000 sq m of office space, a 130-room hotel and about 80
apartments.
	   Yeap expects to launch the project within the next couple of
months on behalf of its owner, a syndicate of Malaysian investors
called Maxicity.
	   But it is the public activities through Phileo that look set to
make the next set of headlines. After re-listing in August 1996,
the former Renak Holdings has leaped from acquisition to
acquisition. It has amalgamated a portfolio of significant assets,
including the huge General Motors Holden site in Melbourne's outer
suburbs.
	   The company plans to build one of the biggest industrial parks
in Australia, with the 41 ha property eventually to house more than
200,000 sq m of buildings space.
	   In an equally bold project, Phileo also snared the sought-after
former Tram Depot in South Melbourne last year and virtually within
hours had carved off a large slice of the site and on-sold it to
developer Central Equity - at a profit, of course.
	   On the bulk of the remaining South Melbourne site, the company
intends to build one of the first major new office projects in the
city since the market slump in the early 1990s.
	   A seven ha residential parcel in Melbourne's suburban heartland
of Box Hill is another of the group's new projects while a whole
block on prime Port Melbourne is also earmarked for about 200
units.
	   Phileo (a Greek word meaning friendship) is controlled by
Malaysian-based Phileo Land and its investment, including an A$11
million injection last year, may prove to be a good hedge against
uncertainty.
	   Despite the ongoing roller coaster in the Asian markets, Yeap
says the biggest hurdle of the meltdown has already been overcome -
`fear of the unknown'.
	   `What has happened is now already known. When the crises started
we could see no end but now we know there are some deep problems in
Indonesia, in Korea and Thailand. But because they are now known
factors we can budget and manage from here onwards,' he says.
	   `As a business person who looks forward, it should not be
something that we are fearful of, it should be something that we
must consider. Not something that we are so scared of that it
paralyses us and we get nothing done.' Few, if any, Asian-based
buyers will retreat or sell their assets because of financial
pressure. `I'm not talking about the people who may buy a A$200,000
apartment, who could be hit hard - but I'm talking about those
people who have spent A$15 million or A$20 million buying an asset
in Collins Street.' 
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 MALAYSIAN BUSINESS all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BOLD-MOVES-DOWN sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
