w1097  wstm-
r w     MIGHT-IN-AEROSPACEsked     06-01 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> MIGHT-IN-AEROSPACE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Might in aerospace inventory exercise, BUSINESS TIMES  
   xfdws MIGHT-IN-AEROSPACE sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE Malaysian Industry-Government Group for High Technology
(Might) is currently undertaking an aerospace industry inventory
exercise to identify the players in the local industry.
	   Its chief executive, Dr Ahmed Tasir Lope Pihie, speaking to
Business Times over the weekend, said the first draft of the
inventory is expected to be ready in two months.
	   The inventory exercise is among the 45 recommendations and
implementation plans outlined by Might in the Blueprint for the
Aerospace Industry in Malaysia.
	   The blueprint, which will pilot the flight of the country's
aerospace industry, outlines the key implementation programmes to
be undertaken by the public and private sectors of the industry.
	   The Government has identified the aerospace industry as a
critical constituent of the country's future industrial base. The
industry has been accorded a priority status in the Seventh
Malaysia Plan (1996-2000).
	   Both civil and military aircraft and equipment, satellites and
space equipment, and related products and services fall within the
ambit of the aerospace industry.
	   It also includes aircraft maintenance, overhaul, repair and
upgrading, manufacturing of aircraft, satellites, missiles and
space vehicles, provision of infrastructure such as airports and
launching pads for rockets, research and development activities and
systems integration.
	   Dr Ahmed Tasir said the agency is sourcing information from its
own MIGHT Interest Group on Aviation and the International Trade
and Industry Ministry, which has a cluster working group on
aviation.
	   Under the blueprint, the structure of the Malaysian aerospace
industry will see the consolidation of the efforts of the key
aerospace operators in Malaysia namely the Armed Forces, Malaysia
Airlines and Malaysia Airports Bhd together with other general
aviation companies.
	   Engineering and manufacturing activities will be anchored in
companies such as MAS Aerotechnologies, SME Group of Companies,
RMAF Engineering and Phileo Aviation.
	   ``We are not saying that there will be a physical consolidation
of the companies in the aerospace industry, but we would like to
see a consolidation in terms of efforts and resources,'' he said.
	   Among the other programmes covered under the blueprint include:
Manufacturing: Expanding parts and components manufacturing to
enable the country to be a leader in upgrading and re-manufacturing
activities.
	   General aviation: To be a regional player in general aviation
activities and a major player in the manufacture of light aircraft.
	   Space: To be significantly involved in the utilisation of space
for both commercial and strategic reasons.
	   Systems: To be a major player in aerospace systems technology
(including avionics); and Commercial aviation: Preferred
transportation hub of and for the region.
	   Among the projects to be undertaken are for technology
acquisition, human resource development, space, composite
procurement, vendor development, surveillance, defence and
satellites.
	   These programmes will, by the year 2015, enable Malaysia to have
a cohesive and developed industrial base with aerospace
capabilities, capability and competency at company and individual
levels, a degree of technological independence, savings by
obviating the need for foreign purchases, a sustainable national
defence capability and enjoy the spin-off benefits useful in other
industries.
	   Might will also undertake a roadshow to explain the content of
the blueprint to government agencies and the private sector
companies.
	   ``We have done one at Universiti Utara Malaysia, explaining the
blueprint and the respective roles of the government agencies and
the private sector in the scheme of things,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:MIGHT-IN-AEROSPACE sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
