<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 12:50:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1100  wstm-
r w     BOH-ON-THE-GOsked     06-01 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BOH-ON-THE-GO sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Boh on the go, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws BOH-ON-THE-GO sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   HAVING established itself as the tea with the ummph, Boh
Plantations Sdn Bhd intends to be the tea specialist in the market,
for everyone ranging from six-star hotels to teh tarik stalls.
	   Its executive director and general manager Caroline Russel says
Boh's mission is to be a world-class Malaysian brand, competing
against the best from anywhere in the world. According to Russel,
while Malaysians have been drinking Boh Tea since the 1930s, it was
only in the late 50s that a concerted effort was made to market the
product domestically. In the 30s, most of the tea was exported in
bulk to London.
	   Russel hails from the family of John Archibald Russel, a tea
producer and pioneer of highland tea cultivation, who established
Boh Plantations in 1929. Boh Plantations has since stopped
exporting its tea to London in bulk, and now, all the prime grades
of tea produced by the company are sold in a branded form.
	   Boh Plantations manages four estates: Boh; Fairlie and Sungei
Palas Estates in Cameron Highlands; and a lowland estate - Bukit
Cheeding - in Banting, Selangor. With a total planted area of 1,200
hectares, Boh Plantations produces 3.7 million kilogrammes of tea a
year, or approximately five million cups of tea per day.
	   As consumers become more sophisticated and discerning, Boh is
moving towards a bolder and brighter corporate image. `In addition
to increasing sophistication, the profile of the Malaysian market
is becoming much younger with 44 per cent of the population being
below the age of 19,' says Russel. `This presents a huge challenge
to marketeers, especially those of long-established brands. Brands
like Boh are in danger of being perceived as old-fashioned, boring
and irrelevant to the youth market. A product that one's
grandmother purchased may not fit in with a young person's
self-image. We see the threat of younger consumers moving away from
tea to soft drinks, as what is happening in the United States where
Coke is a regular breakfast drink. We feel there is an urgent need
to reposition tea as a healthy and great tasting refreshment, the
choice even of a generation bombarded with MTV,' explains Russel.
She adds, `So, it is also our mission to revitalise and rejuvenate
the concept of tea here in Malaysia.' The launch of Boh's new
corporate identity, according to her, is aimed at fulfilling both
the objectives of establishing Boh as a world-class brand and as
the beverage of choice for Malaysia's youthful market. `We
recognise the need to contemporise the Boh brand, refresh and
update its image while retaining its heritage and core values of
quality and value.
	   We want to re-emphasise the Cameron Highlands origin of Boh and
the unique character of our teas, embodied in the phrase ``Boh ada
ummph!''' The new identity will be reflected in all aspects of the
brand - from new products to packaging to all marketing
communication tools, from the Internet to advertising.
	   `While the typography in the brand logo type is true to the
original and remains strong, it has greater clarity and definition.
The detailing lifts the profile of the brand, and it injects a
sophistication and refinement that reinforces Boh as a brand
synonymous with fine quality tea. At the same time, a more
contemporary look has been achieved.
	   `The diagonal graphics and the brown and orange colour schemes
have always been, and will remain, strong, proprietary parts of
Boh's packaging, instantly recognisable to the consumer. Brown is
the colour of heritage and establishment, dependable and constant.
Orange is in direct antithesis, reflecting zest, innovation and
creativity.
	   `Together, they reflect the qualities of earth and nourishment,
soil and sunshine, two of the essential components in the
production of fine quality tea leaves. This unique scheme will
continue to form the visual identity of the packaging, and is the
link by which the Boh brand is, and will continue to be,
recognised,' details Russel.
	   The new packaging for products like teabags, potbags, loose
leaves and iced tea has been designed to revitalise Boh's identity.
The colours have been enhanced, new ones introduced and graphics
restyled. Product descriptions have been revised to reflect the
long heritage and unique selling points of tea grown in Cameron
Highlands.
	   Boh's new identity is also expressed in the range of products
that the company now markets. Each product is designed to cater to
the needs of specific consumer groups, from the tea connoisseur, to
the health enthusiast, to the stressed office worker, to the
overseas tourist. Its product catalogue now includes the garden
teas, Seri Songket flavoured teas, fruit and herbal infusions,
specialty black teas, iced tea and three-in-one instant tea mix.
The garden teas, targeted at the gift market and discerning tea
drinker, is a range of Boh's own-grown, pure, unblended teas from a
single tea garden.
	   Tea can be likened to wine; its character and flavour are
directly influenced by environmental conditions such as the climate
and soil of the place in which it is grown. Similarly, the range of
specialty black teas allow tea drinkers to experience selected
unblended original teas from renowned tea-growing regions of the
world.
	   Recently, Boh also launched a range of instant iced tea mixes in
Peach, Lemon Lime and Orchard Splash flavours, which are targeted
directly at the youth market.
	   
</TEXT>
