w1103  wstm-
r w     DEFENCE-OF-ONES-COUNTRYs     06-01 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> DEFENCE-OF-ONES-COUNTRY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
In defence of one's country and company, BUSINESS TIMES  
   xfdws DEFENCE-OF-ONES-COUNTRY sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   HARVARD: India evoked strong reactions from around the world
with its nuclear tests. It received adverse press and evoked the
anger of major powers and President Clinton imposed sanctions.
	   India's neighbour, Pakistan, replied with its own nuclear tests
evoking even stronger reactions. Its tests outnumbered its
neighbour, which is also being subjected to sanctions.
	   India is not being spared for setting off the ``nuclear arms''
race in Asia. But while India may have received considerable press,
the Confederation of Indian Industry (CII) sprang into action to
present India's views. It took full page advertisments, including
in the Financial Times of London.
	   The advertisment was a public relations exercise and at the same
time presented India's story and where it is heading in terms of
the economy.
	   The CII, in defending the Indian Government's nuclear tests,
said they ``
	   ... were carried out because of serious national security
concerns, especially the nuclear environment in the region''. It
added that `` ... the internationl focus must remain on Economic
Opportunities and Economic Partnership''.
	   In the advertisement entitled ``India: The High Growth Market
Opportunity'', the CII listed out the agenda for growth, the
business opportunities, economic vision and the government and
private sector consensus on economic reform.
	   The CII is not alone in adopting this strategy. Microsoft, taken
to task by the US Government which has filed anti-trust lawsuits
against the company, also ``told its story'' in a full page
advertisment in the New York Times.
	   Mr Bill Gates of Microsoft wrote an open letter to ``Customers,
Partners and Shareholders'' telling his side of the story in the
anti-trust lawsuits against his 23-year-old company.
	   He explained, in his own words, that ``This is an industry built
on innovation, competition and consumer choice - principles that
America's anti-trust laws were designed to promote, and that have
always been a cornerstone of Microsoft's business practices.''
	   Mobil outlined three steps for the US to take in dealing with
Iran, namely, allow US companies to negotiate deals with Iran,
contingent on the lifting of sanctions; allow US companies to swap
oil with Iran; and grant a limited waiver to use Iranian equipment
in the Caspian Sea.
	   This ``advice'' came hot on the heels of Washington's
announcement to waive sanctions against Petronas, France's Total
and Russia's Gazprom for investments in Iran's oil sector. Under
the Iran Libya Sanctions Act, the companies would have been
penalised for investing in Iran.
	   The three cases - CII, Microsoft and Mobil - all have one thing
in common. They were fast off the starting blocks to present their
side of the story. They did not wait for the media to pick up and
tell their story for them. They chose to do it themselves, thus
preventing any misrepresentation and misinterpretation.
	   Telling one's own story as it is, is essential. The CII, Bill
Gates and Mobil had compelling reasons to ``tell their side of the
story'' and found it necessary to take full page advertisments. The
media has its own bias and many feel that the media, both print and
electronic, may not present the facts as they should be in their
news stories.
	   Developing countries, including Malaysia and its business
community, need to learn from these companies to tell their own
story. With the incresingly biased and opinionated news and feature
stories, it is time concerted efforts are made to ``tell Malaysia's
story''. While the government leadership, Prime Minister and Deputy
Prime Minister continue to do their part, it is important for the
private sector and the business community to play a greater part in
this area.
	   While small steps have been taken with the onset of the crisis,
they are insufficient to have the required and intended impact. The
continued presence in the popular press needs to be maintained.
	   The Western media is a powerful tool, even if it does not report
accurately all the time. It is a problem for small and helpless
countries, companies and individuals in presenting their stories.
	   Thus, the collective action of the CII can and should be
emulated by organisations to present their side of the story and
that of the countries in which they operate and have their base.
	   The Malaysian Chambers of Commerce and Industry, for example,
can together with other chambers of commerce and industry groups
present the economic potential in the country. It is time the
business community and entrepreneurs ``sell'' the potential to
foreign investors and businesses.
	   Malaysia's economic fundamentals remain unchanged despite the
currency crisis. These need to be brought to the attention of the
people who matter - decision makers, businessmen and fund managers.
Who would be in a better position to speak to his counterparts, the
foreign businessmen, if not his fellow businessmen and
entrepreneurs with operations in Malaysia.
	   Thus, as the CII has shown, the situation cannot be that
hopeless. It takes courage to face the challenge, onslaught and
condemnation from the world, including the most powerful economies.
In the final analysis, it is the citizens, shareholders and owners
who have to fight for their own country and company. If they do
not, no one else will.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:DEFENCE-OF-ONES-COUNTRY sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
