<SLUG> FLATBED-COLOUR-SCANNER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Flatbed colour scanner for the SOHO market, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws FLATBED-COLOUR-SCANNER sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   HEWLETT-PACKARD Co, the well-known manufacturer of flatbed
colour scanners, has rolled out its new HP ScanJet 5100C which is
targeted at the small office-home office (SOHO) market.
	   The ScanJet 5100C uses HP intelligent scanning technology
designed to automatically detect different types of scanned items
and optimises its scan settings such as resolution, bit depth and
image type.
	   Using a single-pass for both colour and monochrome images, the
ScanJet 5100C comes with 300 dots per inch optical resolution, 300
by 600dpi hardware and 1200dpi enhanced resolution.
	   Other features of the scanner include a 30-bit converter and
36-bit colour image processor.
	   The scanner also supports a maximum document size of up to 8.5
inches by 11.7in (216 millimetres by 297mm).
	   Measuring 124.8mm, 306mm and 485.1mm (height, width and length)
in dimensions, the printer takes quite a lot of space when placed
next to the personal computer (PC).
	   The product comes with one scan button which is used for
scanning purposes. Before installing and using the scanner, do not
forget to unlock the scanhead. It is normally locked especially
during transportation to protect it from damage.
	   The ScanJet 5100C uses an enhanced parallel port interface.
Thus, connecting the scanner to the PC is as easy as connecting a
printer. All you have to do is plug the cable into the printer's
port at the back of the PC and the other end at the scanner's port.
Then plug the power cord into the electrical outlet.
	   The scanner comes with the HP PrecisionScan which is the
scanning software.
	   There are basically two resolution modes available for scanning
-default and custom. The default mode scans at 150dpi while the
latter gives you the options to choose the required scan
resolution.
	   You can also choose the scanning speed - normal or faster scan
speed.
	   The normal scan speed is a default and aimed for best-quality
photographs, text, or black and white drawings.
	   Faster scan speed comes with two more options: the first option
is to scan best-quality photographs while the latter can be used
for best-quality text and also black and white drawings.
	   A colour image was scanned in both modes of the resolution using
normal scan speed.
	   The quality of the image was good for both resolutions but it
was, of course, even better when using the 300dpi in custom
resolution. The scanner also did not make much noise during the
scanning process.
	   When scanning colour images, there were several options of
format to save them. The same also applies for the text documents,
which you can save as a text file or even in Microsoft Word or
WordPad format.
	   Speaking of text, a text document was scanned and saved in
WordPad.
	   Overall, the text was readable although there were few words
that needed to be edited manually.
	   The ScanJet 5100C comes with a one-year warranty and the package
includes the scanner, parallel cable, power cord, scanner driver
and user manual.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
