<BODY>
<SLUG> AIRBUS-SIGNS-MOU-WITH sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Airbus signs MOU with Engine Alliance for A3XX engine, BUSINESS TIMES  
   xfdws AIRBUS-SIGNS-MOU-WITH sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   AIRBUS Industrie signed a memorandum of understanding (MOU) with
the Engine Alliance to offer the GP7200 series of engines on its
A3XX family of aircraft.
	   The MOU was signed during the 4th A3XX Programme Progress Review
in Cannes, France.
	   Developed to meet the needs of the A3XX family, the GP7200 will
cover the 67,000-pound to 80,000-pound thrust range.
	   The A3XX is the first application for this new engine and for
the Engine Alliance as its supplier. It offers higher levels of
fuel efficiency and better noise characteristics than any engine in
its class flying today.
	   This agreement will provide the A3XX with a choice of engine
supplier, as an MOU had already been signed between Airbus
Industrie and Rolls-Royce for the Trent 900 engine in October 1996.
	   The 4th A3XX Programme Progress Review has gathered together
representatives of 14 airlines with members of the A3XX team,
including both engine suppliers, in the presence of Airbus
Industrie's managing director Noel Forgeard.
	   Airline focal points have been able to validate the progress
achieved towards meeting A3XX performance goals and the innovative
approach being applied to ensure that the A3XX becomes a reference
for international travel.
	   Mr Forgeard welcomed the signature of the MOU with the Engine
Alliance, saying ``Our customers expressed a preference for a
choice of engines on the A3XX programme. We are pleased to offer
that choice and encourage a healthy competition to provide the best
product to the market.''
	   The meeting demonstrates the continuing support of the world's
leading airlines for the A3XX family concept, covering capacities
of 480 to 650 seats and ranges from 7,650 nautical miles to 8,750
nautical miles (14,200km-16,200km) as well as short range, Combi
and Freighter variants.
	   The A3XX is scheduled for launch in 1999 and entry into airline
service in the third quarter of 2004.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
