w1108  wstm-
r i     BC-Macedonia-Scandal     06-01 0274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Macedonia-Scandal </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Seven people sentenced in pyramid scheme scandal 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   SKOPJE, Macedonia (AP) _ Seven people involved in last year's
failed pyramid schemes, which cost thousands of Macedonians their
savings, received sentences Monday ranging from fines to prison
time.
	   Some 23,000 Macedonians lost the equivalent of dlrs 65.8 million
in late 1996 with the collapse of so-called pyramid schemes, which
offer high interest rates and use new deposits to pay earlier
investors.
	   The biggest failure was of the Tat company, based in Bitolj,
some 100 kilometers (62 miles) south of the capital, Skopje.
	   Owner Sonja Nikolovska proclaimed her innocence and blamed the
collapse on Macedonian companies that she claimed owed her an
equivalent of dlrs 58 million. She was sentenced to eight years in
prison.
	   Four people who worked in government finance offices in Bitolj
also received prison terms. Julijana Atanasova, head of the finance
office, was sentenced to five years in prison.
	   Employees Sogka Jancevska, Jonce Bocevski and Boris Mijalcev
received sentences ranging from one year to three months.
	   Siljan Micevski, the former mayor of Bitolj, received a one-year
suspended sentence, while his wife, Violeta, was fined the
equivalent of dlrs 882.
	   All were accused of falsifying documents for Nikolovska and
helped her avoid paying taxes.
	   The scandal in Macedonia sparked fears of violence similar to
that in neighboring Albania, where the failure of pyramid schemes
led to armed insurrection last year.
	   The Macedonian government has proposed a gradual compensation
plan.
	   (str/jg/scl) 	   
</TEXT>
