<BODY>
<SLUG> LOCALLY-MADE-PRODUCTS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Locally-made products are not inferior: PM, BUSINESS TIMES  
   xfdws LOCALLY-MADE-PRODUCTS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE call to buy Malaysian is not a call to buy inferior
products, Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir Mohamad said last
night.
	   ``World-class jeans are made in Malaysia. High-quality
electronic components are manufactured in Malaysia. We can make
cars and lorries in Malaysia that can be exported,'' he told a
crowd of some 20,000 people at the ``Semarakkan Semangat Cinta
Malaysia'' performance organised by the Malaysian Chinese
Association in Kuala Lumpur.
	   Dr Mahathir said Malaysian-made goods are ``different from
before'' and the country has been making products for the world.
	   Foreign goods, he said, are not necessarily better; in fact, he
added, many foreign brands have Malaysian-made components.
	   ``When we called for buying of Malaysian-made products, we are
not urging the rakyat to buy inferior goods. We simply urge them to
buy local products as this can help to strengthen the economy.''
	   He said buying local will help reduce the outflow of the ringgit
while at the same time improve the local businesses.
	   ``It is most critical to protect our currency, and this can be
done by buying Malaysian-made products ... This gives strength for
us to fight the present economic problems,'' he said.
	   Dr Mahathir said Malaysians should support campaigns on buying
locally- made goods.
	   ``When we buy Malaysian-made products, it shows that we love the
country and willing to sacrifice to defend the nation and its
economy ... Malaysia belongs to all of us. If we don't, who else
would love this nation?''
	   Dr Mahathir said the Government will do everything it can to
defend the country and ensure it weathers the economic storm.
	   He also called on the people to act rationally and sensibly in
dealing with the problems facing them as a result of the region's
financial crisis.
	   ``In other multi-racial nations, there are problems and even
racial riots due to the crisis. In Malaysia, we do not have this.
No race in Malaysia is living in fear or feeling threatened. This
is our advantage. We must value this,'' he added.
	   The country's balanced economic development as well as the
strong unity of its multi-racial population are the country's edge
in overcoming the current downturn.
	   Dr Mahathir said the country's racial harmony is intact because
all the races in Malaysia are sensitive to one another's feelings.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
