<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Obit-Huber </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German dancer, film star, writer Lotti Huber dies at 85 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BERLIN (AP) _ Lotti Huber, a pre-World War II cabaret dancer who
escaped Nazi persecution and reclaimed fame in Germany in the 1980s
with a film career, died Sunday at age 85.
	   Huber died at a Berlin hospital after suffering a heart attack
Friday, her friend and former stage partner Thomas Nowotny said.
	   Huber's launch into cult status began at age 67 with the 1979
film ``Gigolo,'' in which she danced and appeared in a scene with
film's lead, rock star David Bowie.
	   She then netted lead roles in films during the 1980s by the
openly homosexual German director Rosa von Praunheim, including
``Our Corpses are Alive,'' and ``Horror Vacui,'' in which Huber
played a sect leader.
	   She wrote a memoir entitled ``This Lemon Still Has a Lot of
Juice.''
	   Born in 1912 in Kiel to a Jewish family, Huber became a cabaret
dancer in Berlin. Because of her relationship with a German man,
the Nazi government convicted her of ``racial disgrace'' in 1937
and imprisoned her in a concentration camp.
	   An American organization secured her release a year later, and
she emigrated to British-controlled Palestine and married a British
colonel. After her stint as a cabaret dancer in Cairo, Egypt, the
couple settled in Cyprus and ran a hotel together until their
divorce in 1955.
	   She returned to Germany in 1965.
	   There was no immediate word on survivors or funeral
arrangements.
	   (im)
</TEXT>
