<BODY>
<SLUG> BIG-AND-SMART sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Big and smart, MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws BIG-AND-SMART sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   ANYONE who's been driving on our highways for any length of time
will surely have stories to tell of lucky escapes from road
accidents. Just the very thing happened when Malaysian Business
test-drove the Ford Explorer 4-litre XLT sport utility vehicle
(it's Yankee-speak for 4WD) recently.
	   That life was spared and limb intact, was in no small measure
due to the Explorer's rugged reliability. Overcome with grateful
relief, a colleague who sat in the passenger seat chanted an
involuntary `mantra': `Thank you XLT, I'm getting home safely.'
(More about this `near-accident' later).
	   The Ford Explorer XLT is an American import first launched
locally in July last year. It comes with the reputation of being
the `World's Best-selling' 4-by-4, and is credited with creating a
huge growth in interest in the sports and recreational utility
vehicle market in the United States. This trend has been
transplanted to other markets in the United Kingdom, Australia,
Thailand, Japan and South America.
	   One would think anything stamped Uncle Sam would naturally be
big and brash. This Explorer (there is a limited, upmarket model
called the Explorer Limited) is big without being brash. Neither is
it flashy. A pair of large `wraparound' headlamps split between a
chromium-plated front grille gives it a commanding but understated
presence. Its wheelbase measures well over 4.78 metres, making it
longer than the Range Rover or many of its Japanese rivals. Yet it
is lighter, having a kerb weight of just over 1,950 kg.
	   A feature which sets the Explorer XLT apart from other 4WDs is
Control Trac - a true on-demand 'smart' 4WD traction control
system. Control Trac is operated by a simple three-position rotary
knob on the dashboard and needs no secondary levers to clutter
floor space or complicate driving routines.
	   The Explorer XLT has deep windows that afford excellent
all-round visibility. Rather than being hinged on to the rear door,
the spare wheel is stored out of sight. The vehicle boasts stylish
wheel arch flares and side sill skirts, tasteful chrome highlights
and a classy exterior colour range. Sitting high above the traffic,
yet avoiding the `tall boy' stance of many 4WD vehicles, the Ford
Explorer has a commanding presence on the highway.
	   Safety concerns are given top priority in the Explorer. All have
dual front airbags, 4-wheel disc brakes with ABS, anti-submarining
front seats, outboard seatbelt lockers, adjustable front seatbelt
upper mountings, cargo tie-down hooks and limited-slip rear axle.
The front sections of the Explorer XLT's separate chassis have
controlled collapse rates engineered to help absorb frontal and
offset front crash forces. Doors enclose side-impact protection
beams and the body incorporates a cabin safety cage, part of which
is a major composite cross car beam behind the instrument panel.
The steering wheel frame is magnesium which has crash energy
absorption and noise/vibration suppression qualities superior to
the steel usually used.
	   Internally, the dashboard controls not only look neat but they
are also well-laid out and functional to boot. The Explorer XLT has
a single stalk wiper and lamp controls to the left of the steering
wheel - no confusing which controls what.
	   On the minus side? The Autocruise control could do with a little
refinement. Looking extremely functional, the thumb-activated pads
require a degree of concentrated exertion (it feels hard to the
touch) to operate.
	   Climbing in requires some effort for those of us who are not
physically too well-endowed; the Explorer XLT could do with
side-steps. The seats are a little on the firm side, but this can
easily be remedied by placing one of those therapeutic cushions
easily available from auto accessory outlets.
	   After all that, you are now ready to hear about that
`near-accident' story. Friday afternoon on the Federal Highway and
this driver had just collected the Explorer for the weekend
testdrive. Most drivers are struggling to stay awake at the wheel
with the airconditioning turned on full-blast. The bitumen on the
road surface has a treacly appearance, having baked all day at an
El Nino-induced 37 degrees Celsius. First protaganist: a woman
driver in a shiny new compact car in the middle lane heading
towards the city. For no apparent reason, she chugs along at just
under 60kmph which riles protaganist 2 - a male driver of an
articulated lorry minus the trailer. Pulling on to her rear, he
clearly indicates his intentions: `Move aside, lady, and stop
hogging the middle lane as if you were out on a Sunday drive!'
`Miss Piggy' - that's a female road hog -doesn't get the hint.
	   Exasperated, the driver tries to pass on the inside lane, where
protaganist 3 - two men in a beat-up 1.3 litre saloon - is moving
forward, fastest of the three! The lorry grazes the car on the left
with its left front fender. The car's speed causes it to be shunted
forward and once brakes are applied, is spun 90 degrees to the
right while stuck to the front fender of the articulated lorry. The
car's front fender grazes the left rear of `Miss Piggy's' compact
which is propelled forward and spun 180 degrees. Pandemonium! The
Explorer XLT was right behind the articulated lorry. Why didn't we
become protaganist 4 - and another statistic of everyday road
mayhem?
	   Firstly, the Explorer's height affords a commanding `road ahead'
view.
	   Once the accident occurred, it bought sufficient time to hit the
brakes.
	   But had we not stopped in time, both front-seat occupants could
have relied on the dual-airbags in the Explorer XLT to cushion an
impact.
	   FORD EXPLORER XLT (AUTOMATIC) SPECIFICATIONS Engine Bore 
stroke 100.484.4 Cylinder head SOHC Displacement 4,011cc Fuel
system Electronic Fuel Injection (efi) Max power output 206/5,000
DIN PS/rpm Max torque 340/3,000 DIN Nm/rpm Cylinders V6 Steering
Power assisted, rack and pinion Lock to lock (turns) 3 Minimum
turning circle 12.4 metres kerb to kerb Steering ratio 17:1
Dimensions Overall length 4,788mm Overall height 1,717mm Overall
width 1,874mm Wheelbase 2,832mm Front track 1,494mm Rear track
1,486mm Front overhang 858mm Rear overhang 1,087mm Fuel tank
capacity 80 litres Luggage capacity 1,206 litres (with rear seats
upright) Suspension Front Short and long arm (SLA), torsion bar
springs, twin tube telescopic shock absorbers and stabiliser bar
Rear Rigid axle, leaf springs, twin tube telescopic shock absorbers
and stabiliser bar Brakes Three channel anti-lock brakes with
electronic control module and hydraulic actuator, 286mm front
ventilated discs and rear solid discs Price RM 166,888.88 excluding
insurance 
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 MALAYSIAN BUSINESS all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
