w1118  wstm-
r w     COREL-WORDPERFECT-SUITEs     06-01 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> COREL-WORDPERFECT-SUITE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Corel WordPerfect Suite 8 with speech-recognition capability, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws COREL-WORDPERFECT-SUITE sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   COREL Corp has incorporated its latest word processor, Corel
WordPerfect Suite 8, with Dragon System Inc's Dragon Naturally
Speaking continuous speech-recognition software.
	   The new bundle is called Corel WordPerfect Suite 8 with Dragon
Naturally Speaking (CWS8/DNS). By leveraging on the reputation of
Dragon Naturally Speaking as one of the industry's leading
voice-recognition software, Corel hopes to add value to its
existing word processing suite.
	   While both software have been available separately in the local
market for quite some time, this new bundle from Corel is still at
its beta stage.
	   ``The first final version of the CWS8/DNS will only be shipped
and made locally available in the next couple of weeks,'' said Kany
Chan, Corel's media relations manager for China and Southeast Asia,
at a Press conference recently.
	   CWS8/DNS runs on Windows 95 and NT platforms with a minimum of
133 megahertz (MHz) processor, 48 megabytes (MB) of random access
memory (RAM), 110 megabytes (MB) of hard disk space, a 16-bit sound
card and compact disk read-only-memory (CD-ROM) drive.
	   According to Chan, the CWS8/DNS allows users to dictate up to
160 words per minute and encompasses a vocabulary of 230,000 words,
customised abbreviations and jargon. But like all existing
voice-recognition software, it requires ``training'' to the
particular user's speech pattern, and is vulnerable to disruption
from the environment's background sound.
	   Although still unconfirmed, Corel said the price of this latest
bundling effort will range as the local recommended retail price
for the Corel WordPerfect Suite 8. CWS8/DNS is also expected to
come packaged with a headset microphone to facilitate usage of the
voice-recognition part of the word processor.
	   At the same event, Corel also launched the Corel Print Office,
an entry level desktop publishing application aimed at small
office-home office (SOHO) users.
	   The software encompasses three main components, which are: Corel
Print Office, Corel Photo House and Corel Colleagues  Contacts.
	   Chan also gave a brief insight on Corel's development of
Java-based products. ``There are three parts to Corel's Java
strategy and they are the OpenJ Development Environment, jSuite and
jBridge thin-client technology,''
	   she said. ``The OpenJ Development Environment is a professional
software developers kit for Java applications, while jSuite is for
end users who want to create lightweighted, Java business
applications.''
	   Chan added that the jBridge thin-client technology is Corel's
answer for users of 32-bit Windows applications who want to take
advantage of Java virtual machines.
	   As for the development of these Java-based products, she said
Corel worked with Sun Microsystems in the initial stages of the
development.
	   ``These three Java applications from Corel should be available
by the end of 1998,'' Chan said.
	   The local distributor for Corel products is SiS Distribution (M)
Sdn Bhd.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
