w1119  wstm-
r w     BEHIND-EVERY-SUCCESSsked     06-01 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BEHIND-EVERY-SUCCESS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Behind every success (or failure)..., MALAYSIAN BUSINESS  
   xfdws BEHIND-EVERY-SUCCESS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 16, 1998
   MALAYSIAN BUSINESS
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   `FOR BETTER or for worse, till death do us part.' How many
people actually keep to this marriage vow and stick together
through thick and thin? At a time when our economy is faltering,
let us all re-examine our matrimonial commitments to each other.
This brings me to the subject of this issue's topic - the
indispensable role of women in the success (or failure) of their
husbands.
	   The economic problems have taken its toll on many marriages,
leading to divorce. Relationships have been highly strained and
many families have fallen apart, primarily because people are not
able to have the same life-style that they had in good times.
	   I have a close friend who went through bad times recently. His
business collapsed and the loan sharks were circling. Empathising
with his plight, I introduced him to a job in another town. He
brought his wife and his son along. However, things did not work
out and the couple could not get along. My friend became unbearable
to live with and his wife's impatience with his inability to
overcome their financial woes took its toll on their marriage.
	   I admire women who go through thick and thin and stand by their
men. One such case is the wife of the Thai multi-millionaire turned
sandwich vendor, Sirivat Voravetvuthikun (he appeared in our April
issue) who was here recently to give support to our TTGG (The Tough
Get Going) Fund. His wife, Vilailuck, earned a degree from
Chulalongkorn University, Bangkok, majoring in cost accounting.
After getting married, she gave up her lucrative job to help her
husband run his condominium project when it was not running
smoothly.
	   When the stock market crashed, her husband was down by one
billion baht (RM100 million)! She stood by her husband when the
business collapsed and he turned sandwich salesman. In fact,
selling sandwiches was actually her idea! From the start of their
sandwich venture, she would wake up every morning at 3.00 am and
spend the next three hours preparing the sandwiches.
	   When I asked her why she was prepared to stand by him all the
way, this was what she said: `My husband is a good man. When he was
rich, he was not one to squander his money. He doesn't smoke,
doesn't drink and doesn't womanize. Many a time he wouldn't even
spend on new clothes for himself.
	   He would continue to invest whatever he earned into his business
venture.
	   He did his best for his family. I must now stand by my man when
the chips are down.' Yes, it is easy to stick around when the going
is good, but it is really during tough times that we need to stick
together more, to give support in whatever way we can.
	   Recently, I had the good fortune of meeting Datuk Maznah Hamid,
who rose from being a farmer's daughter to become Malaysia's top
Malay woman entrepreneur, managing director of the Securiforce
group of companies and director of Perbadanan Usahawan Nasional Bhd
(National Entrepreneur Corporation) which oversees 300 public
listed companies. Maznah (she has since earned the nickname the
Iron Lady of Malaysia) and her husband went through thick and thin
on their way to be what they are today. This is what she says: `I
would rather lose everything than to lose my husband and family.'
Couples during these challenging times should emulate them.
	   To all the women in our lives, I have this to say: `It is easy
enough to be pleasant, `When life flows along like in a song.' `But
the spouse worthwhile is the one who will smile, `When everything
goes dead wrong!' Let's adopt the stance that in life there is no
such thing as bad weather, only varying levels of good weather. A
supportive spouse is important to guide the men through rain or
shine. Women like Vilailuck and Maznah are shining beacons who
point the way out of the gloom.
	   This article is the second in a series contributed by Billi P S
Lim in his effort to expedite the recovery of the Malaysian
economy.
	   He is the author of Dare to Fail which is available in English,
Bahasa Malaysia and Chinese from major bookstores. Lim is also
involved in a Malaysian economic recovery project called TTGG (The
Tough Get Going) Fund, organised by MMM Networking Sdn Bhd and
other Malaysian companies.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 MALAYSIAN BUSINESS all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BEHIND-EVERY-SUCCESS sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
