<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Portugal-Arson Trial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Five get maximum jail terms for arson attack that killed 13 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: Meia Culpa is cq
<TEXT>
	   PENAFIEL, Portugal (AP) _ A court Monday sentenced five men to
the longest jail term allowed under Portuguese law for an arson
attack on a nightclub last year that killed 13 people and injured
22.
	   The court handed down the 25-year sentence to Jose Queiros for
contracting three bouncers from the nearby city of Oporto and
paying them 1 million escudos (dlrs 5,800) each to carry out the
attack.
	   The three-month trial heard how the three armed and hooded
bouncers doused the Meia Culpa nightclub in gasoline and set it
alight at 4 a.m. on April 16 last year.
	   The men, in their early 20s, stopped the people inside from
fleeing the fire, and shot one man in the back as he ran for a
door.
	   The bouncers, and the intermediary between them and Queiros,
also received the maximum jail term.
	   The motive was believed to be the competition for business in
Amarante, 300 miles (480 kilometers) north of Lisbon where the
recently opened Meia Culpa was rivaling Queiros's club called the
Diamante Negro.
	   Two men who stole the car used in the getaway were each jailed
for one year.
	   (bh/jt)
</TEXT>
