<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Portugal-TV Takeover </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Portuguese, Venezuelan consortium takes over private channel 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ A consortium of Portuguese and
Venezuelan companies Monday won their battle for control of private
national television channel Televisao Independente, one of the
country's four broadcasters.
	   A court approved the takeover after TVI's creditors endorsed the
consortium's proposed recovery plan for the debt-ridden channel.
	   The consortium includes retail and industrial giant Sonae, media
and entertainment group Lusomundo, both from Portugal, and
Venezuela's Cisneros Group.
	   The Cisneros Group, one of the largest corporations in Latin
America, owns businesses in communications, entertainment and soft
drinks, including Venevision, Venezuela's No. 1 TV station.
	   The consortium's plan beat two other bids for control of TVI
which was launched in 1993 by institutions and companies linked to
the Roman Catholic Church as the country's second private channel.
	   TVI has failed to secure an average weekly audience share of
more than 15 percent since its launch, and creditors reportedly are
owed 17 billion escudos (dlrs 93 million).
	   SIC, the first private channel, launched in 1992, has attained
an audience share of about 50 percent, eclipsing state broadcaster
Radiotelevisao Portuguesa, created in 1956.
	   The latest viewing figures, for the week May 18-24, gave SIC a
49.6 percent share, with 32.6 percent for RTP1, 11.3 percent for
TVI, and 6.5 percent for RTP2.
	   (bh/jt)
</TEXT>
