<SLUG> 11,000-SURGE-ACROSS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
11,000 surge across Penang Bridge, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws 11,000-SURGE-ACROSS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   PENANG, Sun. - About 11,000 people surged across the longest
bridge in Asia in the International Penang Bridge Run today, the
largest group of people ever to gather on the bridge at any one
time.
	   The run, which has been gaining popularity over the years, saw
the introduction of a 42.195km full marathon, which attracted 800
runners.
	   Most of the major titles were won by the 1,000-odd foreigners
who took six of the nine top placings in the adult categories.
	   The runners who salvaged Malaysia's pride were S. Devamani, who
won the marathon women's open - beating international marathon
favourite Sunitha Godara of India into second place; R. Muniandy
who retained his half- marathon men's open title, and Chua Say
Choon who retained his half-marathon junior veteran title.
	   Thailand, with 350 runners, did very well with Jirattigarn
Boonma and Kesinee Unsa-ard winning the inaugural marathon men's
open and marathon women's veteran events.
	   Watanabe Yuji of Japan won the marathon men's veteran event
while Lee Kar Lun of Hong Kong took the half-marathon junior
veteran title.
	   Preethida Somajit of Thailand clinched the half-marathon women's
veteran event.
	   The Yang di-Pertua Negeri Tun Hamdan Sheikh Tahir presented the
prizes to the top five winners of the marathon men's open.
	   The run was organised by the New Straits Times and Lembaga
Lebuhraya Malaysia with the co-operation of the State Government,
the State Youth and Sports Department, the Penang Amateur Athletic
Association and the Penang Bridge Sdn Bhd.
	   Works Ministry Parliamentary Secretary Yong Khoon Seng flagged
off the runners in stages from atop a Simon snorkel. With him were
New Straits Times Sdn Bhd group editor Datuk A. Kadir Jasin, LLM
chairman Datuk Yahya Yaacob and Penang Amateur Athletic Association
secretary Paul Subramaniam.
	   All the VIPs, including Chief Minister Tan Sri Dr Koh Tsu Koon,
also took part in a Celebrity Run held in conjunction with the run
to raise funds for charity.
	   Low Yong Leong of Penang won a return air ticket to Seattle, US,
donated by EVA Air, in the quiz held after the run.
	   
</TEXT>
