w1128  wstm-
r w     PLAYING-BALL-WITH-LOUISs     06-01 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> PLAYING-BALL-WITH-LOUIS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Playing ball with Louis Vuitton, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws PLAYING-BALL-WITH-LOUIS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   AFTER more than a century of churning out nothing but designer
luggage and other leather accessories, Louis Vuitton is breaking
new ground.
	   This year, the label marked its entry into the world of fashion
with the release of its ready-to-wear line and shoes for men and
women, culminating with the opening of four new stores around the
world to house the new range.
	   Despite being a virgin venture, the collection was a hit, thanks
to designer Marc Jacobs. (Incidently, LV is very proud of its new
designer's work. Says David Au, marketing and communications
director for Louis Vuitton Asia Pacific, of Jacobs: ``We love him.
He is great and fantastic and wonderful.'') More au courant, LV
came up with a range of pens, which it hopes to launch here in
July.
	   And finally, in celebration of the last World Cup of the
century, hosted by France this month, the label has come up with
limited edition luxury designer soccer balls.
	   The ball, although made of canvas and patterned with the classic
Louis Vuitton monogram, has all of the weight, bounce and size of a
normal soccer ball. Costing 2,800 French francs (about RM1,600) and
stamped with the official logo of the World Cup, it is supposed to
make a great present for the avid soccer fan.
	   It is a costly designer ball, and one would find it hard to
imagine anyone kicking this collector's item around, but Au insists
that ``... this is a real working soccer ball. You have to play
with it. I don't think we designed this to sit on a shelf and
deflate after a while.''
	   Only 3,000 balls are being issued, with 250 allocated to Asia.
	   So far, promotions have only been done in Hong Kong and
Malaysia.
	   According to Au, the response in Hong Kong has been fantastic,
with over 50 reservations made so far.
	   To obtain one of these collectibles, one has make a reservation
at any Louis Vuitton store. The balls are available now, provided
LV doesn't have any problems bringing them into the country.
	   (Au had a tough time explaining the monogram canvas football
when he checked it through our Customs.) Asked why Louis Vuitton
was venturing into new areas, Au appeared evasive.
	   Instead, he said: ``We want to create a whole new luxury
collection for Vuitton. But the spirit of travel will always be
there because we want to be close to our roots.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
