<TEXT>
	   ONE of the problems that top Singapore makeup artists Dily Wang
and Andy Lee used to face in their work was the difficulty in
finding the right shade of foundation for their predominantly Asian
clients.
	   ``Although there are a few brands catering to Asian skin, many
of the popular brands have pink tones that are more suitable for
Caucasian skin.
	   Even Japanese brands are meant for fair skin.
	   ``It has always therefore been our dream to come up with our own
brand that would suit Asian skin,'' says Lee, whose work has been
featured on the cover of virtually every Singapore and some foreign
fashion magazines. He is highly sought-after by Television
Corporation Singapore actresses as well as by visiting celebrities.
	   Lee and his former beauty coursemate Wang realised their
ambition of developing their own line of makeup and skincare 1
years ago. They teamed up with another friend and started ``i nuovi
cosmetics''. Pronounced as ``ee nu-vi'', the words mean ``the new''
in Italian.
	   ``We have four outlets in Singapore and one in Malaysia, at
Isetan KLCC (Kuala Lumpur City Centre). Our products are also
available worldwide via the Internet.''
	   Conceptualised by Lee and Wang, a beauty salon owner, i nuovi
cosmetics represents the latest in makeup innovation and
technology. The products are manufactured in advanced laboratories
in France, Italy and America, claimed Lee who was in KL recently to
train the company's sales staff.
	   Consumers have a wide range of colours to select from; there are
60 shades of lipstick colour alone. To match Asian skin, most of
the foundations have a yellow base rather than a pink base, though
the latter is also available.
	   Besides the usual range of makeup and skincare items, i nuovi
cosmetics also has trendy party makeup that is tinted with luminous
hues.
	   ``The teenagers love this new-age type of makeup,'' raves Lee,
who writes a fortnightly beauty column for a leading Chinese
magazine, Sister Pictorial. he also hosts the makeup segment of a
weekly TV programme.
	   Using simple but elegant packaging, the products are priced from
RM28 for a lipliner pencil to RM96.50 for a bottle of foundation.
	   Besides building their brandname, Lee and Wang are also in the
midst of setting up a makeup school in the island republic.
	   ``We plan to provide a comprehensive course that covers various
types of makeup including normal, bridal and stage makeup. We also
hope to publish books on the art of applying makeup,'' says Lee.
	   
</TEXT>
