      APTV 1800 GMT OUTLOOK MONDAY JUNE 1, 1998   For Planner / Newsdesk use - stories expected to move in the next 12 hours. All times are GMT.  ---- EXPECTED: ---- AFGHANISTAN: QUAKE - APTV will have further coverage of the devastation caused by an earthquake in Afghanistan. (F-l-a-s-h 1700 gmt) --- PAKISTAN: OFFICIAL - APTV has an interview in Islamabad with the U.N. humanitarian aid coordinator for Afghanistan, Alfredo Witschi-Cestari. (1945 Asia Pacific Early) --- PAKISTAN: IRAN -   A top Iranian envoy arrived in Pakistan on Monday and praised its government for their nuclear tests. APTV will have the arrival of  Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi. (1945 Asia Pacific Early) ---- US: PAKISTAN - APTV is monitoring any comment from the State Department or White House to the nuclear tests in Pakistan. (1930 North America Late) ---- INDIA: BUDGET - APTV has pictures from New Delhi where India's finance minister introduced a budget on Monday that increased spending on infrastructure, defence and nuclear energy. The package will include exteriors of parliament, Vajpayee speaking in English and a soundbite from a former defence minister in Hindi. (1945 Asia Pacific Early) ---- US: SHUTTLE - APTV will have coverage of a pre-launch news conference by the crew of the Shuttle. The crew are scheduled to take off on Tuesday and dock on Friday with the troubled Russian space station MIR. (1830 North America Update) ---- UK: SPICE GIRLS -- APTV has a new package after the split in the 'girl power' band, including pictures of the clamour for memorabilia featuring 'Ginger Spice' and a comment from an entertainment lawyer about the huge bill faced by corporate sponsors to re-shoot adverts with the band. (1830 North America Update) ---- US: BILINGUAL - California voters go to the polls tomorrow to determine the fate of bilingual education in the state. APTV has a preview look at Proposition 227 with opponents and advocates explaining their positions. (1830 North America Update) --- SALVADOR: TRAFFIC - San Salvador's roads are some of the most dangerous in all of Latin America. APTV has a special report. (1900 Latin America) ---- PERU: SMOKING - APTV reports on a government anti-smoking campaign that's working in Peru with large numbers of people giving up cigarettes. (1900 Latin America) ---- RUNNING: ---- KOSOVO: CHILDREN - Thousands of children have marched in Pristina demanding equal rights for ethnic Albanians in the province. (First Run Europe Late 1500) ---- ZAMBIA: KAUNDA - APTV has pictures from Lusaka where celebrations took place as former President Kenneth Kaunda was freed from house arrest. Supporters gathered on the steps of the Lusaka High Court after state prosecutors dropped the case against him. (First Run 1500 Europe Late) ---- PAKISTAN: AID - APTV has a package from Islamabad where Pakistani aid has left for Afghanistan. The item includes comment from Afghan's ambassador to Pakistan, speaking in English. (First run 1115 F-l-a-s-h) --- MONTENEGRO: RESULTS - First results from Montenegro's  parliamentary elections were announced on Monday. (First Run 0800 Europe Early) ---- COLOMBIA: WRAP -  APTV has a comprehensive wrap of the first round of Colombia's presidential race - narrowly won by Horacio Serpa. Includes shots of polling, a soundbite from Ernesto Samper, president of Colombia, the candidates and celebrating in the streets. (First run  F-L-A-S-H 0435) ---- FRANCE: STRIKE - APTV has pictures from Paris where Air France pilots are striking ahead of the World Cup soccer tournament. The package shows an empty runway at Charles de Gaulle airport and includes comment in both French and English from stranded passengers. (First Run 1130 Europe Update) ---- Editor of the Day: - 44 171 427 4163 Master Control Room - 44 171 427 4131 ---- APTV 
