w1148  wstm-
r i     BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 4thLd-Writethru   06-01 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 4th Ld-Writethru,0623 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
More deaths reported in Kosovo; thousands flee employees seeing fighting. Trims. No pickup 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with U.N. spokesman confirming refugee exodus, U.N.
By ISMET HAJDARI
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Thousands of refugees from Serbia's
Kosovo province streamed into neighboring Albania on Monday to
escape some of the deadliest fighting in months. Dozens of people
were reported killed.
	   Albania appealed to the United States and European Union to
intervene in what it said was a ``massacre'' in Kosovo.
	   ``This is just the start of a war with tragic dimensions,'' the
Albanian government said in a statement.
	   Reports from Serb and Albanian sources often were contradictory
and could not be independently verified. But with 39 people
reported killed over the weekend, and fighting apparently
continuing, the bloodshed appeared the worst since March, when
Serbian police killed more than 80 people in a crackdown on
militants among the ethnic Albanian majority in Serb-ruled Kosovo.
	   In New York, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard spoke of ``heavy and
indiscriminate shelling'' of some Kosovo Albanian villages near the
border to Albania. He said U.N. workers could see heavy mortars
being fired into the villages.
	   Serb authorities claimed Sunday to have killed dozens of
militants in four villages in the Decani region of western Kosovo.
Ethnic Albanian leaders put a firmer number on the toll among their
people, saying 37 had died.
	   Twenty-seven died in clashes in Decani while 10 were killed when
Serb police stormed a village elsewhere, they said.
	   Two Serb policemen also died in the fighting around Decani, 75
kilometers (45 miles) west of Kosovo's capital, Pristina, Serb
sources said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
	   The latest fierce fighting forced about 2,000 Kosovo Albanians _
mostly women, children and the elderly _ across the border into
Albania's Tropoja region on Sunday and Monday, Albania said. They
said more were arriving by the hour.
	   Local authorities were putting the refugees up in a school and
in private homes and giving them food and clothes, Interior
Ministry spokesman Artan Bizhga said in Albania's capital, Tirana.
	   Authorities in Serbia are using Serbian police and the Yugoslav
army to try to crush militants and maintain control over the
province, where 90 percent of the population of 2.2 million is
ethnic Albanian.
	   The conflict has killed more than 200 people in Kosovo since the
beginning of March. About half of the province is believed
controlled by militant Albanians and many regions are blocked off,
either by Serbs or Albanians.
	   The Kosovo Information Center, close to the ethnic Albanian
leadership, released the names of the 10 people it said were killed
Sunday when Serb police stormed the village of Poklek, 25
kilometers (15 miles) west of Pristina. It said one had had his
throat slit.
	   According to the ethnic Albanians' account, Serb police burst
into Poklek houses, pulled out villagers and told them to, ``Go to
Albania and never return.''
	   Afterward, Serb police allegedly set 26 homes ablaze.
	   All phone lines remained disconnected Monday between Pristina
and Decani, Klina and Djakovica, where fierce battles were reported
Sunday.
	   In Pristina, about 10,000 ethnic Albanians, including 2,000
children, marched to protest Serbian rule.
	   Yugoslavia's state-run daily Politika on Monday accused ethnic
Albanian ``terrorist groups'' of killing several of their
countrymen and of shelling border villages that are home to people
opposed to the militants.
	   Serbia is the dominant of two republics remaining in the
Yugoslav federation. 	   
</TEXT>
