<SLUG> FACE-ECONOMIC-PROBLEMS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
PM: Face economic problems in rational and sensitive manner, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws FACE-ECONOMIC-PROBLEMS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sun. - Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir
Mohamad reiterated his call to Malaysians to remain united and face
the country's economic problems in a rational and sensitive manner.
	   Dr Mahathir said these two qualities could help avoid possible
misunderstanding and ill-feeling which were counter-productive to
ongoing efforts to overcome the country's problems.
	   He said various steps had already been taken by the Government
to restore the economy and one of them was the ``Love Malaysia'',
``Buy Malaysia'' campaign such as the one organised by the MCA.
	   Dr Mahathir said this at a large gathering of Malaysians at
Dataran Merdeka tonight, including Bond girl Michelle Yeoh and
other artistes.
	   Also present were the Prime Minister's wife Datin Seri Dr Siti
Hasmah Mohd Ali, MCA president Datuk Seri Dr Ling Liong Sik and his
wife Datin Seri Ena Ling, deputy president Datuk Lim Ah Lek, MCA
central committee members, the party's Wanita chief Datuk Teng Gaik
Kwan and its Youth chief Datuk Chan Kong Choy.
	   Dr Mahathir said: ``In some other multi-racial, multi-religious
and multi-cultural countries, riots can be triggered by many
factors. But we are fortunate because we are more rational and
sensitive to each other's feelings and needs.
	   ``This is one of our strengths. Of course, there are certain
foreign Press which never fail to mention that there are racial
undercurrents in the country.
	   ``But tonight's gathering is a good example of how the various
races in Malaysia get together to play their part in helping the
economy. Some of the foreign reports seem to have been made by
people who have closed their eyes, ears and minds.
	   ``We can gather today without fear and tension. We must value
this. I am very happy that tonight's event once again demonstrates
the people's sensitive nature.''
	   He cited as an example of Malaysians' sensitivity the gesture by
the organisers to stop the performance for a while to observe the
isyak prayers at about 8.30pm.
	   Dr Mahathir said the country was still committed to achieving
developed nation status by 2020.
	   ``We believe that we are able to develop the country to be on
equal standing with other developed nations,'' he said.
	   He added others might want to see the country impoverished so
that they could then acquire the nation's assets. Hence, the attack
on share prices in the belief that they could then buy these
companies cheap.
	   He said these people also wanted to take over local banks and
industries. ``If we allow this, then we will be their slaves and
cannot claim to be independent,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
