<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Call to spruce up for Sukom '98, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws CALL-TO-SPRUCE-UP-SUKOM sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   WILL owners of Federal capital shophouses which have seen better
days as historical buildings, still lie low and wait for the last
minute to spruce up and paint the buildings? Their lackadaisical
attitude may mar the image of the city and its surroundings.
	   They should not wait for City Hall to slap them with summonses
before getting down to action.
	   Sukom or Commonwealth Games '98 is just around the corner.
	   The main thoroughfare leading to the prestigious Subang Stadium
is still very much in need of various facelifts, including
landscaping, which still looks miserably bare.
	   Five months from now may be a little short a time for City Hall
to have things adequately spruced up. Let us hope that with the
help of modern machinery, they will be able tackle the problem much
better.
	   It is earnestly hoped that in the coming weeks, our citizens
will be civic-minded enough to refrain from littering.
	   To create a mood of pomp and pageantry, in view of the coming
Sukom '98, it is suggested that City Hall, with the help of the
private sectors, erect colourful arches, hang banners, standards,
buntings and flags of the various local States and also illuminate
shops and houses with glittering lights.
	   It is also hoped that Tenaga Nasional will charge lower tariffs
to enable more folk to join in.
	   
</TEXT>
