<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Signboard needs to be adjusted, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws SIGNBOARD-NEEDS-ADJUSTED sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   LAST April 3, I was out walking with a friend who was back from
the United States on vacation.
	   We were walking from Jalan Chulan towards Jalan Sultan Ismail,
and on the left of the pedestrian walkway along Jalan P. Ramlee.
	   Upon crossing the road, we came across a signboard which we
believed might have been a bit too low for the safety of
pedestrians.
	   My friend suffered a cut on his left temple because he was
unaware of the signboard. The sharp edge of the signboard caused a
gash which started to bleed.
	   I imagine the walkway had been resurfaced, leading to it being
higher off the ground. The height of the signboard, however, was
not reset.
	   I recommend that the authorities re-install the signboard or
remove it before someone else gets injured.
	   
</TEXT>
