r w     BAD-DRIVING-HABITSsked     06-01 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BAD-DRIVING-HABITS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Bad driving habits causing nightmare in Subang Jaya, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws BAD-DRIVING-HABITS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   OUTSIDERS need only to take a 15-minute drive inside Subang
Jaya-USJ any day of the week to experience the notorious traffic
jams and chaotic driving habits of drivers in this township.
	   Drivers who are new to this township will certainly be shocked
and stunned upon coming across motorists who appear suddenly and
drive head-on from the opposite direction of a one-way street.
	   Yes! ``No Entry'' signs don't mean a thing to certain drivers in
Subang Jaya-USJ.
	   It's a ``free-for-all'' for all they care.
	   Knowing motorists will always anticipate and be extra careful
upon entering a one-way street, to avoid hitting someone who might
be coming at them from the opposite direction.
	   Drivers of school buses and parents fetching their children home
from schools in SS19, Subang Jaya seldom observe the few ``No
Entry'' signs in the area, especially those along roads between the
shophouses.
	   Often, there are bound to be some drivers coming from the USJ
direction, defying the traffic lights and rules at the popular SS19
Subang Jaya traffic light junction, and making U-turns into SS18.
	   This short cut is dangerous and can easily lead to a nasty
accident.
	   Although, there are two ``No Entry'' signs prominently placed on
both sides of the entrance of a narrow and short sliproad from
Jalan USL 3/1E, which directly links up with the nearby SS19 bridge
into Subang Jaya, you can still see cars coming out from that
sliproad.
	   Again this is a short cut to get on the bridge and into Subang
Jaya from USJ.
	   It's also horrifying to see motorists making U-turns at the KFC
exit.
	   There is an urgent need for strict enforcement of the traffic
laws by the relevant authorities. They should keep an eye on those
who flout the traffic rules in SS19 so that the roads can be made
safe for all motorists.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
