<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-El Al </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israel decides against selling off most of El Al 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israel decided Monday to keep ownership of 51
percent of the national air carrier El Al, despite recommendations
the unprofitable company be sold off, according to a government
statement.
	   A government panel had recommended that the airline be sold off
by this year. El Al lost dlrs 83 million in 1996 and dlrs 35
million in 1997.
	   The decision ensures that El Al flights will continue to be
grounded during the Jewish Sabbath _ from Friday sundown to
Saturday sundown. The Sabbath groundings have been cited as a
factor in the company's losses.
	   No date for selling off 49 percent of the company has been set
yet.
	   A statement from the ministerial committee overseeing Israel's
privatization plans quoted Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu as
calling Monday's decision ``important.''
	   ``It will protect out national interests,'' he said
	   Israel radio said national security and emergency situations
were key factors in the decision to retain a majority of the
airline.
	   El Al is known for its strict security checks and Israel has
used the airliner in the past for secret operations such as a 1985
airlift of thousands of Ethiopian Jews from Addis Ababa to Israel.
  dl-hla
</TEXT>
