<BODY>
<SLUG> STOP-SPREAD-OF-CHOLERA sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Quick action stops spread of cholera, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws STOP-SPREAD-OF-CHOLERA sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE Selayang Municipal Council's prompt action in tearing down
an illegal canteen in Rawang earlier this month, where a confirmed
case of cholera was reported, has prevented the disease from
spreading.
	   Council medical officer Dr Tuan Ramlah Tuan Muda said the victim
was an Indonesian worker who had eaten cendol from a stall in
Petaling Jaya.
	   ``We believe this was the source of the infection. The vendor's
wife, however, was only a carrier but did not have any cholera
symptoms,'' she said.
	   The third reported case this month involved a worker from
Selayang Bahagia whose source of infection has not yet been
identified.
	   Dr Tuan Ramlah said as a precautionary measure all cendol stalls
in the municipality would be closed with immediate effect until the
situation improves.
	   ``We are inspecting every `cendol' stall in the municipality and
are in the process of taking samples for tests,'' she said.
	   She said the council was working closely with the Gombak
District Health Office in carrying out inspections.
	   She said the message from the council was that any food operator
carrying out business under unhygienic conditions would be fined up
to RM500 under the Local Government Act.
	   
</TEXT>
