<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Pakistan-Nuclear,0341 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Pakistan feared Israeli attack hours before nuclear detonations 
</HEADLINE>
By DAFNA LINZER
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Pakistan feared an Israeli air strike on its
nuclear installations hours before it detonated five nuclear
devices last week, Israeli media reported Monday.
	   State-run Israel television said Pakistan's foreign minister
informed the United States about Israel's plans last Thursday,
hours before it carried out the tests. Pakistan believed that
Israeli planes would operate out of bases in India, the report
said.
	   The United States told Pakistan that Israel was not planning any
such attack, Israel's Channel Two Television said.
	   Israel has relations with India but not Pakistan, the first
Islamic nation to go nuclear.
	   Shai Bazak, spokesman for Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu denied an attack was planned. ``These reports are totally
baseless,'' he told Israel TV.
	   Israel, an undeclared nuclear power, has warned that rival
neighbors India and Pakistan's atomic tests could encourage nearby
Iran to follow suit.
	   Israel destroyed an Iraqi nuclear facility in 1981.
	   The Israeli Cabinet discussed the recent tests on the Asian
subcontinent on Monday.
	   Netanyahu's media adviser David Bar-Illan said in a statement
that Monday's visit by Iran's foreign minister to Pakistan
``strengthens Israel and the international community's calls to
make every effort in order to prevent Iran from gaining a nuclear
capacity.''
	   ``The international community needs to act decisively in order
to prevent Iranian capabilities,'' he said.
	   According to Israeli officials, Iran is seeking technology to
build a bomb and is close to having its own long-range delivery
system capable of hitting Israel.
	   In Islamabad, Pakistan, Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi
said Monday that Muslims everywhere welcomed the nuclear tests, but
dismissed suggestions that Iran was preparing to follow Pakistan
down the nuclear road. 	   
</TEXT>
