r i     BC-Russia-Economy4thLd-W     06-01 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian markets close in downward spiral analysis. CHANGES byline. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: AMs. RECASTS with central bank comments on defending ruble,
By JOHN IAMS
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian stocks plunged more than 10 percent Monday
in a frenzy of selling by Russian banks and a cold shoulder from
foreign investors wary of the market's turmoil.
	   The Russian Trading System index closed 10.2 percent lower after
late panic selling gripped the market and reassuring comments from
government officials failed to calm jittery investors.
	   Monday's close matched the 10-percent fall last Wednesday, when
hectic selling caused the stock market to plummet and threatened a
run on the national currency, the ruble.
	   The market has fallen 44 percent since the beginning of May,
making it the worst performing market in the world, and there are
fears of further losses before calm is restored.
	   The Central Bank has intervened to prop up the ruble and tripled
a key interest rate to 150 percent to persuade investors to stay in
Russia. A top bank official said Monday the interest rate would
remain unchanged.
	   ``At the present, there is no need (to change it),'' said
Alexander Potyomkin, the bank's first deputy chairman.
	   Potyomkin said the central bank will remain firm in its policy
to defend the ruble. ``We will do our best to escape that kind of
scenario,'' he told a news conference, referring to the possibility
of devaluation.
	   But investors are increasingly coming to believe that only an
international aid package will be able to save Russian markets from
a devaluation, that could lead to steep price hikes and social
unrest.
	   Boris Fyodorov, Russia's new tax chief, said Monday that
government has enough cash reserves to protect the ruble, which
closed relatively unchanged at 6.18 to the dollar Monday.
	   But Fyodorov acknowledged an additional dlrs 5 billion from the
International Monetary Fund would help stabilize the market.
	   Russian leaders have said that the economic crisis was triggered
by a combination of forces, including a sharp fall in world prices
for gas and oil, the financial crisis in southeast Asia, and social
unrest including a recent wave of coal miners' strikes.
	   Deputy Prime Minister Viktor Khristenko said Monday that
economic growth predicted for this year probably would not
materialize, but was optimistic that the country could cope with
the current crisis.
	   ``If the government is able to quickly and effectively eliminate
the consequences of the past week, the stability of the real sector
of the economy will be preserved,'' he told a news conference.
	   In a move to cut government spending, Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko Monday ordered a 30 percent reduction in Cabinet
personnel, the ITAR-Tass news agency said.
	   (pvs/jai/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
