<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Other matters, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws OTHER-MATTERS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE Selayang Municipal Council hopes to collect RM32.5 million
in assessment rates this year, with RM11.2 million collected over
the first four months of the year.
	   Its president Kasjoo Kadis said notices had been sent to
ratepayers.
	   He said 81 per cent of ratepayers had settled amounts owed over
the first four months of the year, compared to 93 per cent during
the same period last year.
	   Speaking at the council's full board meeting yesterday, he said
the figure received this year could not be compared with that of
last year as there were more property owners now.
	   Kasjoo was commenting on points raised by councillor and Paya
Jeras State Assemblyman Datuk Saidin Thamby on the question of
collection of assessment rates.
	   On rubbish collection and disposal in the municipality, he said
Alam Flora Sdn Bhd would take over such services from Aug 1.
	   He said the first meeting to discuss details of the takeover
would be held on Wednesday.
	   Asked if the quantum and mode of payment had been discussed, he
said this was up to the Economic Planning Unit in the Prime
Minister's Department to decide.
	   
</TEXT>
