<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
ABN Amro reports quarterly profit of RM22m, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws AMRO-REPORTS-QUARTERLY sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   ABN Amro Bank Bhd reported a pre-tax profit of RM22 million for
the quarter ended March 31, 1998, compared to a loss of RM22
million over the previous quarter ended Dec 31, 1997.
	   The strong performance was mainly attributed to a 34 per cent
growth in net interest income and 83 per cent increase in
non-interest income, while non-interest expenses fell 10 per cent.
	   In a statement, the bank said its total net non-performing loans
remained at 0.7 per cent of total loans and advances.
	   General provisions for the period under review stood at 1.7 per
cent.
	   The bank's total loan loss cover (the ratio of specific and
general provision and interest-in-suspense to total NPL) stood at
124 per cent.
	   Total shareholders' funds grew by 10 per cent to RM163.7 million
and the bank's risk weighted capital adequacy ratio stood at 14.2
per cent.
	   The bank said its Malaysian operations currently had total
assets of RM2 billion.
	   ``The bank is preparing and investing considerable time and
resources on smoothing the way for the introduction of the new Euro
currency and in ensuring that by Jan 1 the bank will offer full
banking services to make the transition to the Euro as simple as
possible,'' it said.
	   The bank will organise a Euro seminar in Kuala Lumpur to explain
the consequences and implications of the Euro to existing and
potential customers, it added.
	   
</TEXT>
