w1182  wstm-
r w     THE-SPORTS-FOOTWEARsked     06-01 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> THE-SPORTS-FOOTWEAR sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Bata eyes the sports footwear market, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws THE-SPORTS-FOOTWEAR sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   CANADIAN-based Bata Shoe Organisation Ltd, whose brand name is
synonymous with school shoes, is keen on developing a global
business in athletic shoes and accessories, its chief executive
Thomas J. Bata said.
	   The 83-year-old son of Tomas Bata, who founded the BSO, said the
athletics business complemented the company's plans for creating a
chain of bigger Bata retail and merchandise stores.
	   He added that the company might consider establishing Malaysia
as a base for the manufacture of Bata school shoes for the Asian
region following the success of the Bata school shoe in the
country.
	   However, the company's new endeavours will not change its
103-year tradition as a maker of quality affordable shoes.
	   ``In terms of positioning and quality, we would like to be seen
as the Rolls-Royce of the affordable shoe segment.
	   ``We do not aspire to be in the high-priced, luxury goods, niche
segment. We want to serve a wide consumer base with progressive and
affordable quality products,'' Bata said in an interview yesterday.
	   According to Bata, its Malaysian operations had done well in
marketing Bata shoe products and establishing the Bata school shoe
in the country, and would be backed up by bigger stores and wider
product range in the near future reflecting a global business
direction for the Bata Shoe Organisation.
	   ``We have been moving into a new development of bigger retail
stores to serve additional consumer groups and we are bringing a
big influence of sports/athletics into our stores.
	   ``Bata will broaden its merchandising, bringing in athletic
shoes and clothing as well as throwing in merchandise related to
today's craze about hiking and roller-blading,'' he added.
	   To date, Bata has acquired brands such as Power, Sparx, Marie
Claire, King Street and North Star.
	   ``This avenue is growing into a global-type business for us and
we will continually improve on it as well as on our other product
lines,'' said Bata.
	   He added that the Bata Shoe Organisation was seeing more
decentralisation of management and manufacturing, and believed it
could operate in relatively medium-sized manufacturing operations
in different locations worldwide to serve specific and localised
market segments.
	   ``We believe we can specialise in different products at
different locations. For example, school shoes in the Asean region
can be made in Malaysia.
	   ``Now there may be import-export duties to be considered but
they are coming down as well. As trade barriers become more relaxed
in Asia, it is a possibility to make best products in one place of
the region and we will consider Malaysia when the time comes,''
said Bata.
	   Bata currently operates two manufacturing plants, one each in
Seremban and Klang, which together churn out over eight million
pairs per year.
	   Last year the company achieved a sales turnover of RM249 million
of which exports to Europe and North America accounted for RM29
million.
	   On the current regional and local economic downturn, Bata said
sales in Asia had not been affected substantially but that growth
had stagnated at the moment. An average annual growth of about
seven per cent was recorded before the economic troubles.
	   ``We will continually improve on our business and grow in Asia
despite the current economic scenario, and will introduce new
activities.
	   ``Our confidence in Asia remains unchanged and as long as we are
willing to work hard to satisfy the consumer, we can survive,'' he
added.
	   Bata is in Kuala Lumpur in conjunction with the opening of Bata
Malaysia's retail outlet at the KLCC Suria today.
	   BSO claims to be the world's largest manufacturer and marketer
of footwear and operates in over 60 countries.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
