<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Azerbaijan-Plotters Sentenced </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Azerbaijan court sentences 20 in failed coup plot 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BAKU, Azerbaijan (AP) _ The Azerbaijan Supreme Court sentenced
20 people Monday to jail terms ranging from 1-1/2 to 15 years for
their involvement in a 1995 coup attempt.
	   Anvar Gafarly, once the spokesman for former Prime Minister
Suret Huseinov, was sentenced to eight years in jail. Journalist
Rasim Agayev, a former spokesman for former President Ayaz
Mutalibov, was given four years.
	   Since 1995, about 200 coup participants have been sentenced to
jail terms and about 40 others have been sentenced to death.
However, Azerbaijan suspended the death penalty in 1993, and there
have been no executions.
	   The failed 1995 coup attempt was led by former Interior Minister
Rovshan Dzhavadov, who tried to seize power in this former Soviet
republic with an elite unit of police officers.
	   Also Monday, the court opened a criminal case against former
parliamentary chairman Yakub Mamedov, who was acting president of
Azerbaijan in 1992. He was charged with failure to notify law
enforcement agencies of preparations for an earlier coup attempt.
	   (str/jai/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
