w1191  wstm-
r i     BC-France-WateringtheWin     06-01 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Watering the Wine </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fine wine fraud; water, sugar, other additives may taint a Margaux 
</HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHE HUTTEAU
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   BORDEAUX, France (AP) _ A prestigious Bordeaux wine may not be
all its label claims. Authorities have discovered water in the
Chateau-Giscours, and even some sugar, milk and acid, and taken the
case to court, judicial sources and the newspaper Le Monde reported
Monday.
	   An investigation shows that not only were water, milk and
certain acids added to the wine -- a Margaux that is one of the
most noted ``grand cru'' of the Medoc region. But there also was
allegedly a mixing of vintages and inferior wines from elsewhere,
the judicial sources said.
	   Such trickery is tantamount to treachery in the wine business,
strictly controlled to maintain the kind of quality that is
synonymous with fine French wines.
	   The judicial sources in Bordeaux, speaking on condition they not
be named, said that several officials of the domain, one of the
most imposing in the Medoc region, have been placed under
investigation, a step short of being charged, for illicit
practices.
	   The judicial sources would not identify the suspects.
	   Le Monde, which broke the story in a front-page article,
identified those placed under investigation as wine expert Regis
Froidefond and Jean-Marie Ferrandez who for four months headed the
company marketing the wine.
	   Dutch billionaire businessman Eric Albada-Jeigersma, who has
bought part of the domain, was questioned in the investigation, Le
Monde reported.
	   The Bordeaux prosecutors office opened its investigation in 1995
after complaints by a government office that oversees competition
and fraud complained. Acting on information from a former employee,
the office discovered a mixture of vintages and inferior wines, the
judicial sources said.
	   Water and sugar were also allegedly added to some vats, the
sources said. Le Monde reported that milk and certain acids were
likewise detected.
	   None of the additives makes the wine dangerous for the consumer,
the sources said, but they could ruin the chateau, disparage the
Margaux wines and there was speculation it could even shake up the
rising Bordeaux wine prices.
	   (eg-var-parf)
</TEXT>
