<HEADER>
w1193  wstm-
r w     THERE-ARE-GOOD-STOCKSske     06-01 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> THERE-ARE-GOOD-STOCKS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
There are good stocks even in a sick bourse, BUSINESS TIMES  
   xfdws THERE-ARE-GOOD-STOCKS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE situation in regional stock markets may be still uncertain
and all eyes remain focused on developments in Indonesia but on a
global perspective investors and speculators should also be keeping
a watchful eye on what's happening on Wall Street.
	   One phenomenon that an investor should always remember when
venturing into any stock market is that when almost everybody least
expects something to happen, that very thing will take place.
	   The Dow Jones average, which was reaching one high after another
some weeks ago, was supposed to continue its record-breaking run
and hit the sky by now.
	   However, what has actually happened is that the Dow has pulled
back in recent weeks and dropped by 70.25 points to 8,899.95 last
Friday -something totally unexpected by optimistic forecasters
earlier on. By all accounts, the Dow should continue to shoot up,
given the fact that the US economy is doing well and the inflation
and economic figures look good.
	   Therefore, the Dow should continue to be good as well, or so
goes the reasoning.
	   In contrast to the US economy, the economic and financial
situation in Japan, the world's second largest economic power, is
really pathetic.
	   The Japanese situation is such that whatever is being done to
stimulate its economy and get it out of the financial mess, it is
never enough and something more and much better is called for.
	   Given such an unfortunate set of circumstances, it is no wonder
that the Tokyo stock market - once even considered on the way to
becoming mightier than Wall Street - has been humbled and seems to
be going nowhere.
	   Given a choice, it would be a safe assumption to advise
investors that they should avoid Tokyo and go for stock markets
which are holding up better. However, it has been often suggested
that a seemingly sick stock market may provide potentially better
opportunities for long-term gain than healthy ones which provide
limited profit-making opportunities over the long run.
	   The more sickly stock markets are probably selling at their
historical lows and therefore an investor taking the long-term view
can expect prices to rise much higher when the stock market moves
out of its bottom and begins to take off.
	   A sick market has the potential to get well and when it does
become healthier, this will translate into higher prices and
capital gains for the investor who is courageous enough to buy
stocks when the market was ailing.
	   If a stock market is already healthy with stock prices selling
at their historical highs, there isn't much potential for profit
for the investor who picks up prices at that high level.
	   This is not to suggest that investors should only scout around
for sick companies to buy their stocks because what is being
suggested is that if they are global investors, they should not be
deterred from going into sick stock markets just because they are
unwell.
	   A stock market may be sick but there are individual listed
companies which are well managed with good assets and earnings but
whose stock prices are pulled down together with that of the bad
companies.
	   What the investor should do is to seek out the good apples from
the bad ones in an ailing stock market.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:THERE-ARE-GOOD-STOCKS sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
