<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 13:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1195  wstm-
r w     AGRICULTURAL-PRODUCTIONs     06-01 1367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> AGRICULTURAL-PRODUCTION sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Now is the time to focus on agricultural production, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws AGRICULTURAL-PRODUCTION sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   FOR decades, agriculture played a dominant role in the Malaysian
economy.
	   Rubber, palm oil, cocoa and timber products were the major
primary commodities that contributed significantly to the growth of
Gross Domestic Product, employment and export earnings.
	   The agriculture sector as a whole contributed more than 50 per
cent of export earnings during the 60s and 70s.
	   Agricultural products are subjected to price fluctuations, and
the inflexibility of demand and supply make it difficult to plan
their development. They are also subjected to tariff and non-tariff
barriers that curtail their developments.
	   The huge drop in the international prices of these commodities
in the 70s and 80s dealt a severe blow to the once striving
agriculture-based Malaysian economy.
	   This led to structural economic reforms in the 80s and beyond
and a shift in the economy from dependence on the primary sector to
the promotion of export-led manufacturing sector.
	   Guided by the First Industrial Master Plan, 1986-1995 and the
Second Industrial Master Plan, 1996-2005, heavy emphasis was given
to boosting the manufacturing and services related sectors in
Malaysia, with tremendous results.
	   The manufacturing sector is now the engine of Malaysia's
economic growth and contributes significantly to export earnings
and employment, superseding the contribution of the agriculture
sector.
	   The contributions of the agriculture sector to GDP consequently
declined to 18.7 per cent in 1990, 13.6 per cent in 1995 and is
expected to further decline to 10.5 per cent in 2000.
	   So is its contribution to employment and export earnings. Its
contribution to export earning dropped from 26 per cent in 1990 to
18 per cent in 1995 and is expected to drop further to 22.2 per
cent in 1990 and 13.1 per cent in 1995.
	   The positive aspects of these declining contributions, however,
have been the corresponding increases in agricultural value-added
products, labour productivity and land-labour ratio.
	   From a policy point of view, the structural change is a success
as it has provided Malaysia the path to faster economic development
and growth.
	   More importantly, the change will lead to Malaysia being an
industrialised country by the year 2020.
	   The structural economic reforms enabled Malaysia to experience
high economic growth of above eight per cent per year for almost a
decade, among the most vibrant economies in Asia.
	   Discriminatory policy treatment in favour of the vibrant
manufacturing and property sectors at the expense of the
agriculture sector, however, has its drawbacks. This is
particularly clear during the current economic problem.
	   The declining property market and the slowing down of
manufacturing growth and exports brought about by the financial
downturn have severely affected overall economic growth.
	   The competitiveness of Malaysian exports is questionable,
especially those with high import content of inputs.
	   More surprising is the current account deficit in the balance of
payments which, among others, can be attributed to our high bill of
food imports, which was in the region of RM9 billion last year.
	   The high bill of food imports, while acceptable in times of
prosperous growth, is unacceptable during a slowdown. Questions
have arisen as to our capability and capacity of producing our
domestic food resources.
	   With abundant land resources and thousands of plant species and
a variety of animal husbandary available, the high food import only
shows that less attention has been given to produce these food
resources in a bigger way.
	   Most alarming is that, not only human food but even animal and
fish feed are mostly imported, thus contributing to the high import
content of locally produced chicken and farm-bred fish.
	   The current economic problem is in a way a blessing in disguise.
The immediate response of both the Federal and State governments to
revert to boosting agricultural production is most welcome.
	   Indeed, there are ample opportunities for both the public and
private sectors to venture into agricultural development in a big
way to boost production, not only to provide food security but also
to boost food processing and pharmaceutical manufacturing
activities.
	   The economic problem also revealed the need to provide equal
treatment to the agriculture sector in our development process,
alongside that given to the manufacturing sector.
	   In addition to giving priority for approving land for
large-scale agricultural production, some form of fiscal and
financial incentives should be put in place.
	   Agro-based research support should be strengthened to cover
marketing aspects of agricultural produce such as processing,
handling and quality control.
	   Marketing channels should be strengthened through a more
business-like public organisation. Infrastructure support, where
necessary, should be provided.
	   Efforts should also be made to identify the type of crops with
high demand and output value.
	   In addition to rice, fruits and vegetables, attention should be
given to growing herbs, spices and ulam in a big way.
	   These plants are not only available locally for large-scale
production but also contain medicinal properties that can be used
to produce traditional medicine and other pharmaceutical products.
	   Fish production is another area with high economic potential,
yet under- exploited. The Department of Fisheries forecast that by
the year 2010, fish production will reach 900,000 metric tonnes
from inshore fisheries, 600,000 mt from aquaculture and 430,000 mt
from deep sea fisheries, with an estimated value of more than RM6
billion.
	   There are vast opportunities for utilising mining ponds and
lakes for inland aquaculture.
	   There is also great potential for deep-sea fishing particularly
in the South China Sea, which is still under-exploited.
	   What is required is the provision of financial and non-financial
incentives to attract private sector investment in the fishing
industry.
	   Now is the opportune time to give more attention to the
agriculture sector. The current economic problem has taught us a
lesson that discriminatory policy treatment in favour of a
particular sector (manufacturing) at the expense of another sector
(agriculture) does not guarantee sustainable development and
growth.
	   Agricultural and manufacturing production should therefore be
given equal treatment in our development process.
	   A thorough review of the National Agriculture Policy should be
expedited to provide an updated policy in this endeavour.
	   However, we must bear in mind two realities. Firstly, the
current economic problem is temporary in nature and the Malaysian
economy is expected to rebound in due time and secondly, we have to
accept the fact that Malaysia is fast losing her comparative
advantage in agricultural production.
	   As such, the only rational justification for increasing domestic
agricultural production is to be based on food security
consideration rather than a temporary and short-term improvement in
competitiveness due to current depreciation of the national
currency.
	   Another option is the liberalisation of agricultural trade,
particularly of products where Malaysia has no potential
comparative advantage.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:AGRICULTURAL-PRODUCTION sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
</BODY>
