<HEADER>
w1197  wstm-
r w     BANK-NEGARAsked     06-01 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BANK-NEGARA sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Bank Negara: We listen to market's views, BUSINESS TIMES  
   xfdws BANK-NEGARA sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   BANK Negara says it constantly listens to suggestions from the
market, but nevertheless prefers banks to stick to the stipulated
plan to maintain credit growth at 15 per cent by the end of this
year.
	   The credit growth plan was introduced earlier as part of
pre-emptive measures to protect soundness of the domestic banking
system amid the regional financial crisis.
	   The banking system's rapid moves to tighten credit extensions
attracted criticisms from the market, with many complaining about
difficulties in obtaining credit facilities to finance their
businesses.
	   ``We constantly receive views and comments and do so with an
open mind.
	   It is not the central bank's way to dismiss suggestions from the
market outrightly,'' Bank Negara Governor Tan Sri Ahmad Mohd Don
told newsmen at a briefing on Saturday.
	   His deputy, Datuk Fong Weng Phak, estimated that about RM60
billion should still be available within the banking system in the
next eight months, based on the present credit growth plan.
	   The money is there, although potential borrowers must do a bit
more to convince their respective bankers before they can have
access to the funds, he said.
	   While banks have been criticised for being overly cautious in
extending credit facilities, several bankers contacted in recent
weeks said they themselves are facing constraints to lend actively.
	   Although the preliminary total pre-tax profit recorded by the
domestic banking system stood at a high of RM7.9 billion for 1997,
the actual profit is expected to be substantially lower as banking
institutions have been required to provide higher provisions to
build up loan loss reserves and strengthen their balance sheets.
	   Briefing newsmen, Ahmad Don outlined immediate prospects for the
Malaysian economy, one of the determining factors for recovery
being that banks continue to lend within the credit plan figures.
	   ``Many banks over-extended themselves during the economic boom
period,''
	   said Bank Negara assistant governor Datuk Abdul Murad Khalid,
who was also present at the briefing.
	   Echoing Murad's sentiments was assistant governor Dr Zeti Akhtar
Aziz who summarised all the pre-emptive measures instituted in the
banking sector within the past year, saying they have brought
positive results to shore up banks' fundamentals in facing the
economic uncertainty.
	   The Malaysian economy charted its first quarterly decline since
the mid- 1980s when it contracted by 1.8 per cent in the first
quarter of 1998 on an annual basis compared with a 6.9 per cent
expansion in last year's fourth quarter.
	   The banking sector felt impact of the regional financial crisis
during the first quarter of this year as both deposits and loan
activities recorded declines due to both supply and demand factors.
	   The fall in domestic demand and slowing down of economic
activity adversely affected the debt-servicing capability of
debtors, resulting in some financial institutions facing a
deterioration in their asset quality.
	   ``The banking system is sound. It is under strain, but
manageable,'' Ahmad Don said, adding that the central bank will
maintain the present monetary policy and interest rates, as
inflation figures are showing a rising trend.
	   As at March 31 this year the level of non-performing loans of
the banking system stood at 9.1 per cent.
	   He also said that Bank Negara will continue with ways to
strengthen the industry further, among others by actively
encouraging merger of banks, insurance companies and discount
houses.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BANK-NEGARA sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
