<HEADER>
w1198  wstm-
r w     MOS-BURGER-COMES-KLCCske     06-01 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> MOS-BURGER-COMES-KLCC sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
MOS Burger comes to Suria KLCC, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws MOS-BURGER-COMES-KLCC sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   SABAH-based Wong Chik Lim Holding Sdn Bhd, in a tie-up with MOS
Food Services Inc of Japan, yesterday opened its flagship MOS
Burger fastfood restaurant at the Suria KLCC shopping complex in
Kuala Lumpur.
	   The joint venture company, Moriyoshi Foods (M) Sdn Bhd, now
plans to open between 10 and 15 MOS Burger outlets in Malaysia over
the next three years.
	   The second outlet is planned for The Summit Subang USJ shopping
mall in Selangor in July.
	   Moriyoshi Foods managing director Eric Wong Shew Yee said
yesterday the company expects a turnover of RM2 million this year
and up to RM6 million next year.
	   Speaking after the opening of the MOS Burger outlet, he said
Moriyoshi Foods also has the rights for Singapore and has already
opened seven outlets there since 1993.
	   The MOS Burger chain - Japan's answer to McDonald's - has been a
runaway success in Japan since it began operations in 1972 with
over 1,500 outlets there now.
	   The only burger franchise listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
since 1988, the company has also expanded to Hawaii, Taiwan and
China. Apart from burger outlets, it also operates Chirimentei
Chinese noodle restaurants.
	   MOS Food Japan vice-president Eitaro Sano, who opened the KLCC
Suria outlet, said the company plans to expand further globally
with the aim of adding 100 outlets annually. In Malaysia, each
outlet costs about RM700,000 to set up.
	   The distinctive aspect of the MOS Burger is that each is made
fresh when the customer makes the order. Also, unique to MOS Burger
is its offerings of a rice burger and a teriyaki burger.
	   MOS Burger draws its acronym for Mountain, Ocean and Sun, and
aims to promote a healthier lifestyle for the people.
	   
</TEXT>
