<BODY>
<SLUG> SOFWARE-DYNAMICS-UNVEILS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Software Dynamics unveils Y2K solutions, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws SOFWARE-DYNAMICS-UNVEILS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   SOFTWARE Dynamics Sdn Bhd, a company focusing on Cobol
programming and solving Year 2000 (Y2K) problems, has announced a
new service called the Y2K Factory to provide solutions for the
millennium bug.
	   Scheduled to be launched next month, Y2K Factory is aimed at
sparing companies the trouble of recruiting extra personnel to deal
with the Y2K problem, hence allowing them to concentrate on
business more effectively.
	   According to Software Dynamics' business development executive
Amran Ariffin, the company uses two main software programs, the
SoftFactory/2000 and HourGlass 2000, to address the problem.
	   ``We are the local distributor for both software and these
complement each other to provide a complete and comprehensive Y2K
solution,'' he said.
	   Besides providing the service, the company also sells
SoftFactory/2000 and HourGlass 2000 packages to companies wanting
to develop in-house Y2K solutions. SoftFactory/2000 is a toolset
and methodology designed to enable information technology (IT)
organisations rectify the Y2K problem with a set of intelligent
rules specifically optimised for logic-based remedy.
	   Available in three modules - Revolve/2000, SmartFind/2000 and
Workbench/2000 - SoftFactory/2000 helps solve the impending Y2K
date-change crisis affecting organisations with Cobol-based legacy
systems.
	   ``Even though SoftFactory/2000 is based on Cobol, it can also
check Fortran, C++ and other basic text-written programs, except
RPG,'' said Amran.
	   Revolve/2000 is a tool designed to identify and categorise Y2K
code in several languages and the package supports multiple
Y2K-conversion methodologies. It also checks the date formats in
the program.
	   ``A lot of companies hesitate to buy the Y2K program because
they think it is a waste of money to buy solutions solely for
solving the Y2K problem,'' Amran said. ``But with Revolve/2000,
users can still use it after the turn of the century for activities
such as documentation and charting purposes.''
	   The second module, the SmartFind/2000, is a rule-based analysis
tool for identifying lines of Cobol codes that require the remedy
to become Y2K-compliant, and it is the core of the SoftFactory/2000
solution. It is optimised for Y2K conversions utilising logic-based
``windowing'' fixes to the century date-change problem.
	   Software Dynamics said the rule-based detection methodology of
SmartFind/2000 is considered to be the most effective compared to
other methods which only identify date fields and requires no
conversion and extensive manual intervention.
	   The windowing solution identifies only dates which require
fixing, such as those used in some calculations and comparisons,
and leaves the two-digit dates in place, but adds logic to
differentiate between centuries.
	   The Workbench/2000 module, meanwhile, provides a complete
personal computer (PC)-based testing environment for users'
modified code. It gives a straightforward and accurate testing
method for the Y2K program conversion.
	   To complete the checking system, the company uses the HourGlass
2000 which the company claims is the only comprehensive
date-simulation tool that lets users run specified programs, jobs
or sessions, without affecting the others. It provides
Y2K-compliance testing for in-house applications, third-party
applications and utilities, running non-Y2K- compliant applications
on the first day of year 2000, and rerunning old or future months
or year-end jobs.
	   However, the HourGlass 2000 is only available for the HP 3000
and 9000, and MVS systems.
	   As the local distributor, Software Dynamics expects to generate
RM2 million to RM3 million in sales by the end of this year. ``We
believe Y2K Factory will contribute about 80 per cent of the sales
while the rest is from pushing the boxes,'' Amran said.
	   The Revolve/2000 module carries a price tag of US$52,500
(RM199,500) whereas cost of the SmartFind/2000 depends on the
number of lines of codes used in the program and the Workbench/2000
is priced according to the number of seats.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:SOFWARE-DYNAMICS-UNVEILS sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
