<BODY>
<SLUG> PROFIT-FOR-ABN-AMRO sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
RM22 profit for ABN AMRO in first quarter, BUSINESS TIMES  
   xfdws PROFIT-FOR-ABN-AMRO sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   ABN AMRO Bank Bhd posted a pre-tax profit of RM22 million for
the first quarter ended March 31 1998 compared to a loss of RM22
million in the last three months of 1997.
	   The strong performance was attributable to a 34 per cent
increase in net interest income and 83 per cent in non-interest
income, while non-interest expense fell by 10 per cent.
	   Given the encouraging profits recorded for the first quarter,
the bank foresee its continuous commitment in the Malaysian banking
industry by expanding its business strategy as the opportunity
arises, its managing director Huibert Boumeester says.
	   Announcing its quarterly results, ABN said that its total net
non-performing loans (NPLs) remain at 0.7 per cent of total loans
and advances, while general provisions stood at 1.7 per cent.
	   The bank's total loan loss - covering the ratio of specific and
general provision, and interest-in-suspense to total NPLs - stood
high at 124 per cent. There was no new specific provision made in
the period reviewed as adequate previsions were made in the
previous quarter.
	   As at March 31, the bank's risk weighted capital ratio stood at
14.2 per cent while total shareholders' funds grew by 10 per cent
during the period under review from the previous RM148.6 million to
RM163.7 million.
	   ABN is a wholly-owned subsidiary of ABN AMRO NV and is one of
the oldest foreign financial institutions in Malaysia. Its overseas
associates, ABN AMRO Bank is one of the major banks involved in the
Euro, the single currency in Europe that will be introduced on
January 1 1999.
	   The implementations of Euro will radically change the banking
system in Europe, whereby banks will have fewer counterparts and
will choose those which sell the best products.
	   ``There will be intense competition between the biggest network
banks while the smaller ones will either enter into alliances or
come to banks such as ABN AMRO to do the processing for them,''
Boumeester said.
	   He said the bank is preparing and investing considerable time
and resources on smoothing the way for the introduction of the new
currency.
	   ``We hope by January 1 1999, we would be able to offer full
banking services for the transition to the Euro as simple as
possibele,'' he said.
	   These will range from treasury and cash management facilities
through trade and project finance, asset management and the full
menu of capital market services.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
