<SLUG> ENTERPRISE-STORAGE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Enterprise storage framework, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws ENTERPRISE-STORAGE sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE fast pace of today's businesses and the Internet explosion
are placing a heavy demand for information on networks. As a
result, there is an urgent need for new applications and a
centralised enterprise storage framework, according to EMC Computer
Systems (South Asia) Pte Ltd's general manager Paul Rath.
	   ``Enterprise storage means consolidated storage that is capable
of supporting multiple operating systems and multiple mainframes,
Unix and Windows NT servers on a single system,'' Rath said.
	   ``The need for a shared, consolidated repository of business
information has never been greater. The real value of enterprise
storage is that it stores and retrieves data from all major
computing platforms in both the mainframe and open systems
environments,'' he added.
	   Enterprise-wide connectivity is regarded as an important element
of enterprise storage as it allows information system (IS) managers
to consolidate packets of information into data centres for
competitive advantage.
	   As a result, IS managers are no longer just managing disparate
technologies and data but information which now rests in a
centralised location.
	   To address this, EMC Corp, a worldwide provider of enterprise
storage devices, is promoting the use of its architectures covering
both hardware and software. For hardware, EMC offers Mosaic:2000,
while Intelligent Storage Architecture (ISA) is used for the
software.
	   ISA is designed to create a computing environment driven by
consolidated information from across the enterprise.
	   Built on Mosaic:2000, the EMC hardware architecture is aimed at
bringing together the best disk, memory and system software
technologies.
	   ``We don't manufacture storage disks, instead we formed
alliances with popular database developers, hardware manufacturers
and systems integrators to provide best-of-breed solutions,'' Rath
told reporters in Kuala Lumpur.
	   ``With EMC solutions, we give organisations a more timely access
to information and this will lead to better business decisions.
Moreover, a good enterprise storage must be able to provide
connectivity, cascadable and information-centric solutions and this
is what EMC products address,''
	   he added.
	   On EMC business performance, EMC Computer Systems (Far East)
Ltd's country manager Zulkifli Latiff said more than 1,000 units of
EMC storage devices have been installed locally since the middle of
last year.
	   EMC claimed to be the world's largest supplier of enterprise
storage devices with a 50 per cent share of the mainframe and the
open systems markets.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:ENTERPRISE-STORAGE sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
