<BODY>
<SLUG> MAS-TO-SELL-USED-AIRCRAF sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
MAS to sell used aircraff, seek loans, BUSINESS TIMES  
   xfdws MAS-TO-SELL-USED-AIRCRAF sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   MALAYSIAN Airline System Bhd (MAS) is planning to sell its used
aircraft and borrow from a few foreign financial institutions to
raise money for its capital investments totalling RM1.81 billion
for the current year ending March 31 1999.
	   MAS' treasury manager, Mr Low Chee Teng, said the group is
negotiating with a few foreign parties for loans which MAS is
hoping to secure and these to be guaranteed by export credit
agencies in the respective institutions' countries.
	   Out of the total investment, RM1.54 billion will be used to pay
for four aircraft MAS will receive later this year and in 1999,
including spare engine payments.
	   ``Since the four aircraft are manufactured in the US and
Britain, we are hoping that the export credit agencies of the
countries can guarantee the debt acquired,'' Low said.
	   Low, however, declined to name the financial institutions
involved.
	   Meanwhile, MAS chairman Tan Sri Tajudin Ramli once again
successfully kept the group's much talked about restructuring plans
under wraps.
	   In a much eagerly anticipated briefing to the media and analysts
last Saturday, Tajudin said details on the restructuring of the
national carrier will be revealed this year.
	   Declining to answer questions on the subject, the chairman who
seems visibly upset, only said: ``We will come out with the details
later.''
	   Meanwhile, the treasury manager said actual implementation of
the restructuring exercise will take longer than a year. He said
that MAS is still deliberating on the final structure of the plan.
	   Tajudin also cleared the air over the exercise which he said is
not an attempt to satisfy the business interests of specific groups
of shareholders in MAS.
	   In a statement signed by Tajudin himself, he said, that
shareholders, regardless of the size of their investment, are
valued partners in MAS.
	   Hence, no party will be disenfranchised in any manner, Tajudin
stressed.
	   Earlier reports had said that Tajudin was planning to sell the
company's aircraft to a new company, MAS Capital, which would then
lease the aircraft back to MAS.
	   It was also said that the proceeds from the transaction would be
used by Tajudin to partly pay off his personal debts.
	   Suffering from a RM225 million pre-tax loss in its last year
ended March 31 1998, MAS has suspended flights to Madrid, Macau,
Davao, Vientiane and Pusan. It has also deferred taking delivery of
14 aircraft.
	   In addition, MAS has stopped extending the leases of its
aircraft, cancelled any option aircraft, modified aircraft orders
to save costs, and it has also offered to lease or sell its
existing aircraft.
	   Currently, 14 aircraft are being offered for lease or sale by
MAS.
	   Datuk Bashir Ahmad, the group's executive vice president, in
briefing investment analysts at the same function, mentioned that
MAS will now shift its growth emphasis to long-haul services,
expecially to North America and Europe.
	   This is as a result of the group's capacity reduction with the
selling, leasing and the delivery deferment of aircraft.
	   To concentrate on the long flight market, MAS will reduce the
frequency of flights on the Orient road, to countries such as South
Korea, Hong Kong and Taiwan.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
