<BODY>
<SLUG> MEI-SETS-UP-CONCERN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
MEI sets up concern to handle subsidiaries' funds, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws MEI-SETS-UP-CONCERN sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   MATSUSHITA Electric Industrial Co Ltd (MEI) of Japan yesterday
announced that it has established a new company in Malaysia to
specifically handle treasury management of all its 20 subsidiaries
in the country.
	   The new company, 100 per cent-owned Panasonic Financial Centre
(Malaysia) Sdn Bhd, would start operations on Monday.
	   With a paid-up capital of RM2 million, its business will be the
rationalisation and risk management of funds and foreign exchange
within Matsushita subsidiaries in Malaysia.
	   Previously, the duty was handled by each subsidiary.
	   Asia Matsushita News Centre spokesman Keiji Furukawa said the
decision was taken to ensure that the Malaysian subsidiaries could
concentrate on their respective businesses without having to worry
about currency fluctuations particularly with the weakening
ringgit.
	   ``The new company will act as a sort of a bank for all these
subsidiaries. It will manage the combined fund of these 20
companies, possibly see what the cash-rich subsidiaries can do to
assist those in need of cash.
	   ``It will also minimise the foreign exchange risk for the
group,''
	   Furukawa said.
	   The Malaysian company is MEI's seventh treasury company and
sixth outside Japan. The others are in London, New York, Hong Kong
and Singapore.
	   MEI's subsidiaries in Malaysia contributed 400 billion Yen
(RM11.2 billion) to the consolidated turnover of 7.67 trillion Yen
in 1996. For the last financial year ended March 31, 1998, MEI
recorded a 7.89 trillion Yen consolidated turnover.
	   MEI, founded in Osaka, Japan, in 1918, is one of the world's
leading producers of electronic and electric products for consumer,
business and industrial use.
	   It employs more than 275,00 employees worldwide with overseas
operations that include over 200 companies in 44 countries.
	   In Malaysia, the first MIE subsidiary, Matsushita Electric Co
(M) Bhd (Melcom), was set up in 1966 in Shah Alam, Selangor and
currently employs about 2,500 workers.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:MEI-SETS-UP-CONCERN sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
