   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   CANON Marketing (M) Sdn Bhd has launched a series of new
products under three categories of its camera/video divisions
consisting of three digital video camcorders, two Advanced Photo
System (APS) cameras and three EF lenses.
	   The new digital video camcorders - XL-1, MV-1 and MV-100 - are
the top line of Canon's digital video camcorders which were
introduced locally.
	   According to Canon Malaysia's vice chairman Shuichi Tsukahara,
the introduction of the digital video camcorders are in line with
the company's commitment to introduce advanced photographic
technology.
	   ``We introduced digital camcorders because we have the advantage
of manufacturing advanced digital technology in other Canon
products,'' he said.
	   The XL1 digital video camcorders are based on the 3CCD
technology.
	   Designed for professional film makers who need portability and
high-quality recordings, the new camcorder has a high-resolution
projection with a 16x optical zoom and SuperRange Optical Image
Stabilisation plus audio recording.
	   The XL-1 is wrapped with magnesium alloy which Canon claims is
20 times stronger and lighter than conventional camcorder casings.
	   The second model, the DM-MV1, is a mini digital-video camcorder
which incorporates the Digital ``IC'' (1-CCD chip) processing of
wide-band RGB colour filters. Canon said with its scan system, the
XL-1 is the first three mode DV camcorders in the world.
	   Aimed at advanced camcorder enthusiasts and professional users
that want a higher level of image and colour resolution, the MV1
provides two Movie Modes - Normal and Progressive Scan Mode, and a
Photo Mode.
	   Other than the user-friendly feature, it is also equipped with a
colour viewfinder and a two-inch LCD monitor. The model also comes
with a 14x optical zoom, 35x digital zoom and Canon's FlexiZone
Control and Optical Image Stabiliser.
	   The third model, the MV100 is, by Canon's estimates, the world's
smallest digital camcorder with LCD display. With a dimension of
118.5 by 85.5 by 55.7 millimetres, the camera has the ability to
give 44x digital zoom.
	   Powered by a new lithium battery pack, the digital camera is
able to project 180,000 pixel images on its 2.5-inch LCD screen.
The LCD screen can be adjusted to a variety of positions for high
or low angle shooting, playback at different angles and it can also
be lifted by 180 degrees.
	   Apart from the Easy Recording, the MV100 also includes Auto,
Sport, Portrait, Spotlight, Sand and Snow, and Low light for
customised situations.
	   For videographers, there are seven digital effects incorporated
which are fade, wipe, scroll, black and white, strobe, art and
sepia. As for accessories, the product comes standard with a colour
finder unit for bright area and a docking unit for playing on TV.
	   The two new APS cameras launched were the EOS IX7 and IXUS Z70
models.
	   The EOS IX7 is Canon's smallest and lightest SLR camera and is
the second single-lens reflex camera introduced by the company that
incorporates the benefits of EOS EF lenses and APS. It incorporates
a set of IX functions like mid-roll film change, IX data exchange
for Print Quality Improvement (PQI), drop-in loading and print
format selection. It also has nine AE modes, three point
auto-focusing features with six zone evaluative metering, automatic
or manual focus point selection, focus point indicator, automatic
exposure bracketing and a built-in retractable flash with TTL
exposure metering.
	   The IXUS Z70 model is another compact APS camera that has 3x
zoom lens and a flash. It incorporates a new Light Guide system
which is introduced for the first time as an improved flash
feature.
	   The APS features available in this model are mid-roll film
change and print quantity settings which enables users to select
the number of prints of each shots either before or after taking
the picture.
	   Another significant feature is the hybrid autofocus system which
is designed to eliminate infra-red autofocus for close range and in
low light environment.
	   The new lenses introduced are EF28-135mm f/3.5-5.6 USM,
EF22-55mm f/4-5.6 USM and EF55-200mm f/4.5-5.6 USM.
	   With the introduction of the new products, Canon is aiming to
achieve 10 per cent growth in sales compared to last year.
	   ``The market environment in Malaysia may not be good now but
Canon is positive that the setback is temporary. Canon will remain
aggressive in its approach towards addressing the Malaysian
market,'' said Tsukahara.
	   List prices of the digital video camcorders range from RM7,737
to RM25,326, the IXUS Z70 APS camera is priced at RM1,505 and
prices for the lenses range from RM1,119 to RM2,428.
	   Together with the product launch, Canon Malaysia also launched
its own home page.
	   
</TEXT>
