<HEADLINE>
World Bank loan to repair Yerevan's water and sewage system 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with heavy rains causing flooding in Yerevan.
<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The World Bank is ready to give Armenia a dlrs 30
million loan to repair the water supply and sewage systems in the
capital, Yerevan, a Russian news agency said Monday.
	   Vagram Nersesyants, the bank's representative in Yerevan, said
the credit proposal was agreed to following negotiations with
Armenia's central bank. The proposal will be submitted to the World
Bank for approval June 11, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
	   The credit, to be repaid over 35 years, must also be ratified by
the Armenian parliament.
	   The repairs are needed to prevent losses of drinking water and
to stop sewage from leaking into the water supply, ITAR-Tass said.
	   Meanwhile, about 100 homes in Yerevan have been flooded in what
officials call the heaviest rains in 20 years. Several dozen people
have been left homeless, said the head of the State Department for
Emergency Situations, Karapat Safarian.
	   (jai/ls) 	   
