<BODY>
<SLUG> SOFTWARE-ONLINE-TO-INVES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Software Online to invest RM10m in MSC, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws SOFTWARE-ONLINE-TO-INVES sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   SOFTWARE Online Sdn Bhd plans to pump in RM10 million in its
latest round of investments to support its involvement in the
Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC) initiative.
	   Software Online's general manager Hong Fan Chong said the
company is allocating RM5 million to establish its corporate office
and another RM5 million to set up a research and development (RD)
facility in Cyberjaya.
	   He said the RD plant is expected to be ready by the year 2000
and will focus on software development activities that are in line
with local market requirements.
	   According to Hong, the RD investment is the second, after a
recent allocation of RM5 million, which underlines the company's
commitment to its MSC venture.
	   Software Online, which develops specialised software solutions
for the property development industry, was awarded MSC status in
February this year.
	   On the company's financial performance, Hong said Software
Online, which is a member of the IFCA Consulting Group, is
targeting some RM10 million in sales revenue by the end of this
year.
	   He was speaking at a Press conference held in conjunction with a
seminar themed Effects of The Millennium (Year 2000) Bug On The
Property Development Industry in Kuala Lumpur last week.
	   At the event, Software Online unveiled the second version of its
property development information system called D'Developer, which
it claimed is future-proof against potential problems caused by the
Year 2000 (Y2K) or millennium bug problem.
	   ``The property development industry is a very important part of
our economy, and we believe that property developers should be
given every assistance in addressing the Y2K issue,'' said Hong.
	   He said the locally-produced D'Developer which involved an
investment of RM5 million, is capable of supporting companies with
multiple projects and property types.
	   The software functionalities include customer prospecting, sales
tracking, extra packages offering, billing, collection, credit
control, project scheduling, contractor contract and claims,
purchasing, material management, accounts payable, project costing
and corporate accounting.
	   In conjunction with the new release, Software Online, through
its distributor Project Online Sdn Bhd, is offering a promotion
valid until the end of next month. During this period, customers
will be given the software free of charge, and they need only bear
the hardware, networking and Y2K implementation costs. Depending on
the number of users, the cost ranges from RM50,000 to RM200,000.
	   Hong said even though there is a drop in demand for software
products due to the economic crisis, Software Online is still
bullish about its prospects.
	   ``For the new release, we are targeting sales revenue of between
RM4 million and RM5 million this year.''
	   According to Hong, the company plans to expand its market reach
to Africa, South America, United States and Europe.
	   He said Software Online is also looking for more distributors in
countries such as the Philippines, Indonesia, Thailand, Australia,
Papua New Guinea and the US.
	   A member of the IFCA Consulting Group, Software Online
specialises in the development of comprehensive management
information systems for hotels and clubs, real estates developers,
property management companies, financial institutions,
project-based companies, federal and Government projects,
educational institutions and data interchange industries.
	   
</TEXT>
