w1221  wstm-
r i     BC-NorthernIreland 1st-Ld-Writethru   06-01 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Northern Ireland, 1st-Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sinn Fein stands up Prince Charles _ saving some British blushes plans in grafs 9-13, edits 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with Mowlam defending invitation, detailing government
<TEXT>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) _ In a double-edged snub, leaders
of the IRA-allied Sinn Fein party have turned down an invitation to
a royal garden party because Prince Charles will be there.
	   The announcement saved the host, Britain's Northern Ireland
Secretary Mo Mowlam, from some awkward maneuvering, though she
defended the invitation on Monday.
	   Now, she won't have to worry about keeping the Sinn Fein leaders
away from Charles _ whose much-loved great-uncle Lord Mountbatten
was assassinated by the Irish Republican Army in 1979 _ when guests
mingle Wednesday in the grounds of her Hillsborough Castle
residence.
	   Sinn Fein said that leaders Gerry Adams and Martin McGuinness
will boycott the party because Charles holds the ceremonial
position of colonel-in-chief of the Parachute Regiment whose
members were involved in the so-called Bloody Sunday killings in
1972. Thirteen Catholic marchers were shot dead in the British
army's worst shooting in this province.
	   After a long campaign by relatives of the victims, British Prime
Minister Tony Blair this year authorized a new investigation into
Bloody Sunday, which is being carried out by an international panel
of judges.
	   Leaders of pro-British Protestant parties accused Mowlam of
blundering and insensitivity by inviting Sinn Fein to the party,
being held to mark the 50th anniversary of the state-funded
National Health Service in Northern Ireland.
	   Before Sinn Fein said it wouldn't be going, Mowlam promised to
make sure Charles didn't meet Adams and McGuinness, who hold two of
the 18 Northern Ireland seats in the 659-member British House of
Commons. Charles' office made no comment.
	   ``I think we've indeed been fortunate that, for wrong and
inexcusable reasons, Mr. Adams and Mr. McGuinness have declined the
Charles invitation,'' Conservative lawmaker Andrew Mackay said in
the House of Commons in London.
	   Mowlam responded that Sinn Fein was a party to Northern
Ireland's agreement on a new assembly, and that it was normal to
invite all political parties to such events.
	   ``We can't expect people to participate in the assembly together
and then say we judge for ourselves different standards,'' Mowlam
told the House of Commons.
	   Mowlam told lawmakers that both the British and Irish
Governments planned ``very soon'' to introduce bills establishing
decommissioning schemes to encourage paramilitary groups to
relinquish their weaponry, under the terms of Northern Ireland's
April peace accord.
	   ``There will then be no practical barrier to a start to
decommissioning,'' Mowlam said.
	   Mowlam said the British government will also bring in bills to
set up Northern Ireland's new assembly and the planned ministerial
council that will have members from both Northern Ireland and the
Republic of Ireland. Prime Minister Tony Blair is expected to fly
to Northern Ireland to meet with the province's political leaders
Tuesday in talks that will focus on the legislation.
	   (mj-kg-rs) 	   
</TEXT>
