<SLUG> BC-Spain-Blair </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
British premier says violence in Northern Ireland predictable 
</HEADLINE>
With AP Photo MAD106
<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ British Prime Minister Tony Blair described
the weekend's violence between Protestant marchers and Catholic
protesters in Northern Ireland as ``not wholly surprising if
regrettable,'' at the end of a flying visit to Madrid on Monday.
	   Blair said that the violence, the worst since the Northern Irish
peace agreement was reached on April 10, was instigated by people
who ``belong to the past.''
	   ``The result of the referendum (in favor of the peace accord)
showed that the overwhelming majority of people want to conduct
debate by democratic and nonviolent means'' he added.
	   The Labor Party prime minister made his comments during a joint
press conference with his Spanish counterpart Jose Maria Aznar, of
the center-right Popular Party.
	   Blair was due in Dublin later Monday in this latest stage of a
round-Europe tour to prepare for the Cardiff summit later this
month that will wind up the British term in the rotating presidency
of the European Union.
	   The Spanish and British prime ministers also confirmed plans to
hold annual bilateral summits.
	   Blair said his ``excellent'' relationship with Aznar, despite
their origins ``at opposite ends of the political spectrum,'' was
due to the dwindling importance of the ideological divide between
left and right as well as their relative youth.
	   He stressed a meeting of minds ``on the principles of how we
make our people more employable,'' underlining the need for
competitiveness and adaptability of the workforce.
	   (jt)
</TEXT>
