<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - Some 32,000 new cancer cases are reported
every year in Malaysia, making it the number two killer after road
accidents.
	   National Cancer Foundation president Datuk Mohd Farid Ariffin
said most cancer deaths among men were due to lung cancer and
women, breast cancer.
	   ``This figure is increasing because of the people's unhealthy
lifestyle,''
	   he said, adding that smokers should give up the bad habit while
women should go for regular screening. ``Men who smoke heavily are
known to have a low sperm count while women smokers have small
babies.''
	   Farid said this after a Press conference on a charity film
premiere which will be held on June 14 to raise RM70,000 to set up
a cancer institute.
	   
