<SLUG> MCA-YOUTH-PRAISED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
MCA Youth praised for its pragmatic approach, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws MCA-YOUTH-PRAISED sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - Deputy MCA president Datuk Lim Ah Lek today
praised MCA Youth for its pragmatic approach in taking up issues
directly with the relevant authorities to resolve problems.
	   ``This is not only very constructive but also an acceptable
manner to overcome issues faced by the movement,'' he added.
	   Lim, who is also the Human Resources Minister also praised its
leadership for the proactive stance in response to the economic
problems.
	   Delivering his keynote address at the movement's 35th annual
general assembly at the Tunku Abdul Rahman College, he said: ``The
movement's initiative in promoting the Love Malaysia, Buy Local
Products and other patriotic campaigns have enhanced the confidence
of people in facing the current economic downturn.''
	   Also present were Umno Youth head Datuk Ahmad Zahid Hamidi,
youth leaders of Barisan Nasional component parties, former MCA
Youth heads -Datuk Kee Yong Wee, Chew Hock Thye and Datuk Yap Pian
Hon, who is also an MCA vice-president.
	   Lim hoped that the movement would continue with its practical
political struggle and further enhance its image as a contributor
to the community and country.
	   ``Only through such `leadership by example' will the party earn
the trust and support of the Chinese community and the Barisan
Nasional Government,''
	   he said.
	   He also urged the movement to go on an aggressive recruitment
drive to get more youths to join the party.
	   ``Intensive political training must be provided so that they
will be equipped to serve the party and nation. We need both
quality and quantity in the party,'' he added.
	   On the party elections next year, he said: ``There should be
minimal contests for top positions in the movement.
	   ``However, under the democratic process, members have been given
the mandate to retain those who have performed well and to remove
those who have not.''
	   Lim also reminded members that the party was free from
factionalism and unity was prevalent and this could be attributed
to the leadership of the president Datuk Seri Dr Ling Liong Sik.
	   ``Political stability in the party has allowed the top
leadership to launch several large projects for the community and
the country,'' he added.
	   MCA Youth chief Datuk Chan Kong Choy in his speech called for
closer co- operation among the various races.
	   ``Our forefathers have laid this strong foundation of
co-operation, unity and solidarity and this has been further
strengthened by Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim when
he said `we are one family','' he said.
	   Chan, who is also the Deputy Minister of Energy,
Telecommunications and Posts, added that the spirit of co-operation
among the various races should be strengthened as we faced the
current economic problems.
	   Towards this end, Malaysians must rally and support the
country's leaders in a true spirit of `one family' to tackle the
problems.
	   
</TEXT>
