<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Number of councillors from women's wing up by 81pc, says Ting, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws NUMBER-OF-COUNCILLORS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - The number of Wanita MCA members holding
the post of local councillors has increased by 81 per cent.
	   MCA secretary-general Datuk Dr Ting Chew Peh said today 49
Wanita members had been appointed as councillors in district and
municipal councils nationwide to date.
	   There were only 27 Wanita councillors last year although 447
positions were allocated for the MCA.
	   This changed when the MCA presidential council decided last year
to allow Wanita members to take up 15 per cent of the MCA posts for
municipal and district councillors by 1999 and 30 per cent by the
year 2005.
	   Speaking to reporters after opening the Wanita MCA 23rd annual
general assembly at Wisma MCA, Ting said the aim was to give women
a bigger role in the party.
	   ``The leadership is satisfied with the Wanita members'
performance but we feel their participation in the party can be
increased.
	   ``As such, we want more Wanita members as delegates at the
annual general assembly,'' he said.
	   The 45th MCA general assembly tomorrow is expected to pass an
amendment to the party's constitution to increase the number of
Wanita MCA delegates to the general assembly.
	   The amendment is to enable every division to select at least one
Wanita delegate for the assembly. Currently, there are only 175
Wanita representatives out of the 2,502 delegates.
	   ``We expect the number will be more than 200 after the
amendment,'' said Ting.
	   Earlier in his speech, Ting urged Wanita MCA to organise
programmes to uncover potential future leaders.
	   This would ensure the party continued to have leaders of
calibre.
	   It was also important for a party to have many members and
branches.
	   Wanita MCA now has 1,415 branches and 250,000 members. The
target is 500,000 members by 2000.
	   Wanita head Datuk Teng Gaik Kwan said women had to widen their
knowledge and become involved in politics so that they could play a
role in policy- making and nation-building.
	   ``As we are entering a new era, we have to project a new image
and must have the ability. This is so that we are given the
confidence to participate in policy-making which is currently
monopolised by men,'' she said.
	   There were 23 resolutions presented for debate at the general
assembly.
	   They include children's, social, education and economic issues.
	   The resolutions included: Urging MCA to field more Wanita
candidates in the next parliamentary and State elections.
	   Urging the Government to severely punish agents who bring in
illegal foreign workers and those who rape children below 12 years
of age.
	   Urging the Government to set up a children's affairs division
under the National Unity and Social Development Ministry to address
social problems.
	   Urging the police and relevant authorities to take a serious
view of gangsterism in schools.
	   Urging the Education Ministry to review the criteria for
admission of students into local universities to ensure those with
excellent results get a place.
	   Supporting the Government in its policy to control inflation.
	   Supporting the ministries of Housing and Local Government and
Environment in the move to punish polluters.
	   The assembly was attended by 491 delegates.
	   
</TEXT>
