<TEXT>
	   THE US economy grew at 4.8 per cent in the first quarter of 1998
in spite of signs that Asia s economic troubles were slowing
exports. In addition both consumer spending and income increased by
0.5 per cent and 0.4 per cent respectively for the month of April
1998.
	   Meanwhile US imports surged by US$48 billion (US$1    RM3.89) in
the
first quarter of 1998 more than triple the $14.7 billion increase
in the last quarter of 1997 while exports dropped by $7.7 billion
for the first quarter of 1998.	   Federal policy makers have said that US economic growth must
soon moderate to a rate close to 2.25 per cent annual growth in
order to forestall monetary tightening.
	   
