Ensure good returns from investments, EPF urged, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws ENSURE-GOOD-RETURNS-EPF sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - The MCA Youth today urged the Employees'
Provident Fund to ensure that it can generate reasonable returns
through cautious, prudent and transparent handling of its various
investments.
	   It also pledged to heed the call of the National Economic Action
Council to the people to buy local products, enhancing food
production, encouraging domestic tourism, saving with local banks
and embarking on austerity drive.
	   This is to avert the outflow of the country's foreign exchange
reserves to help the nation tide over the prevailing economic
downturn.
	   These were among the resolutions adopted at its 35th general
assembly.
	   The others included: To support the Government by not allowing
any privatised project or concession from being transferred to stem
profiteering. It said that in any selection of concessionaires for
such projects, the Government should ensure that only those with
sufficient expertise, capital and management ability be given due
consideration.
	   To support the Government in intensifying the coastal patrol to
stem the influx of illegal immigrants, and to urge the people to
provide the authorities with relevant information to enable the
latter to send back the aliens; To fully support the party
leadership in launching the various information technology projects
catered to the needs of the IT era, through the implementation of
paperless administration, electronic mailing and video
conferencing; To urge the Education Ministry to tighthen the
supervision of private institutions of higher learning to ensure
that their advertisements and the standard of teaching adhere to
regulations; and, To urge the Works Ministry and respective State
Governments to view seriously the prevailing water crisis and to
address the problem comprehensively in the national perspective.
	   During the debate, Malacca representative Leong Chiew Chong
expressed dissatisfaction with the Education Ministry in allowing
only pupils whose parents were earning below RM1,000 to secure book
aid under the school textbook loan scheme.
	   ``Earning RM1,000 is no longer a big income, especially when one
is employed in big cities.''
	   Pahang representative Chim Siew Wai questioned the rationale of
the party's leadership in wanting 30 per cent of its Wanita members
to be the party's representatives in local councils by the year
2000.
	   ``Why are we implementing such a policy when all this while we
were fighting the quota system,'' he said.
	   Kelantan representative Yap Hock Onn said the packaging aspect
of local goods should be made more attractive and presentable if
the Buy Malaysian campaign were to be a success.
	   ``Unless we improve the packaging of Made-in-Malaysia products,
I am afraid we will not be able to attract customers.
	   ``I observed that even goods manufactured by the Thai cottage
industry near the Kelantan border, are far ahead in terms of
presentation compared to ours,'' he added.
	   
</TEXT>
