<TEXT>
	   HONG Kong stocks will endure another unpredictable week as
concern mounts over the state of the local economy and Asia's
financial outlook, dealers said.
	   Mr Alex Tang, research head at Core-Pacific Yamaichi Securities,
said the direction of the market will hinge on reaction to the
announcement after trading closed on Friday that Hong Kong's gross
domestic product (GDP) slumped 2.0 per cent in the quarter to
March, the first decline in 13 years.
	   The key Hang Seng index shed 621.42 points or 6.5 per cent to
close the week's trading at 8,934.56 on Friday, after gaining a
mere 0.2 per cent the previous week.
	   The average daily turnover amounted to HK$6.34 billion, against
the previous week's HK$6.719 billion.
	   
