<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Market poised to trade steadier amid low volume, BUSINESS TIMES  
   xfdws MARKET-POISED-TO-TRADE sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   INDONESIAN President Habibie has been in office for slightly
more than a week and he seems to have the situation under control.
	   Aside from the small groups, opposition seeking reforms, poll
date and other minor problems, life in Indonesia is back to normal.
The fact that large numbers of Indonesians, led by ethnic Chinese
have returned bear witness that life is slowly returning to normal.
	   The long orderly queue to withdraw money from the biggest
private bank is a contrast to the rioting mob prior to the stepping
down of President Suharto.
	   Habibie seems to have appeased the anger of the students and
have gained the support of the armed forces. This will go a long
way to help him get down to resolving the economic problems now
facing Indonesia. Stability in Indonesia will also bring stability
to its neighbours.
	   The treasury announced early last week of the possibility of a
surplus in its current account this year.
	   Critics have come out to say that this has been achieved through
the drastic cut back in the importation of goods and not through
the more positive action of more exports.
	   We feel that this is uncalled for, as the whole world knows that
we are experiencing an economic slowdown. Common sense tells us
that we should cut down on unnecessary import items, which are not
productive.
	   The Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange was traded easier for the full
five days of trading last week. Although the local bourse did make
an attempt to rally on Thursday and Friday, it was put down by
concern in the weak ringgit and warning that our economy would move
into recession if banks continue to be extra strict in their
lending policy.
	   Fears that the Hong Kong economy may slip into recession, the
weak yen and high interest rates all added to the woes of a market
that was already weak. The Dow falling to below its 9,000 point
level is another factor that contributed to the overall weak
market.
	   In the midst of these, a market observer has noted that trading
volume has been extremely low. The first three days of trading
chalked up less than a hundred million shares each day, while
Thursday and Friday just managed to move above the one hundred
million mark.
	   On the technical front, our rising Timing Device turned down
last Tuesday. The falling pace gained momentum on Wednesday and
Thursday but started to slow down on Friday.
	   We feel that the slowdown in falling pace will continue early
this week and a reversal trend is possible at the -200.0 point
level by mid-week, failing the next support level at the -400.0
point level.
	   Our O/O Indicator continues to trend up but at a slower space.
Our projection study has indicated a continuation of this uptrend.
Another slowdown of the uptrend pace can mean we are slowly working
towards a reversal in trend. An increase in its uptrend pace can
act as a catalyst for further advancement. The current low volume
favours a steadier market this week.
	   
</TEXT>
