<SLUG> PSD-NOD-FOR-SURVEY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
PSD nod for survey on effectiveness of NRS, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws PSD-NOD-FOR-SURVEY sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   IPOH, Sun. - Cuepacs has received the green light from the
Public Service Department to conduct a random survey on the New
Remuneration System for civil servants to gauge its effectiveness
and acceptance. The NRS, in its sixth year of implementation, has
been the subject of many complaints from civil servants.
	   Cuepacs secretary-general S. Siva Subramaniam said today:
``Questionnaires would be distributed to members of affiliated
bodies in a month.''
	   He said the survey was expected to be completed in one month and
its findings submitted to the PSD by the end of August.
	   Siva Subramaniam said Cuepacs hoped the survey could help
improve weaknesses in the NRS.
	   ``We found the matrix system not properly implemented but we
also have civil servants who approve of the system. That is why we
need to conduct a survey on the NRS,'' he said after attending the
opening of the Perak Cuepacs delegates' meeting.
	   Under the NRS, every employee has to be assessed annually, first
by his immediate superior and then by the head of his department on
his performance and points are given for each aspect of the
assessment.
	   The NRS is designed to get the best out of government servants
by rewarding them with salary increases based on performance. The
performance of civil servants is then classified into one of four
categories -unsatisfactory, satisfactory, very good and excellent
performance.
	   The unsatisfactory performer gets no salary increase for that
year; the satisfactory performer, a salary increase on the same
level; the very good performer, a salary increase of 1 1/2
increment and moved to the next level, and the excellent performer,
a double increment and moved to the next level.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
