<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Field Hockey-World Cup, 1st Ld-Writethru,0583 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Netherlands downs Spain 3-2 to take third World Cup 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES throughout with quotes. Will stand.
AP Photos
By MANDY MANN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   UTRECHT, Netherlands (AP) _ Teun de Nooijer scored a golden goal
two minutes from an imminent penalty shootout to secure the men's
field hockey World Cup for Olympic champion Netherlands in
sudden-death overtime Monday.
	   Cheered by thousands of frenzied home fans, De Noojier's goal in
the 13th minute of extra time helped the Netherlands beat Spain 3-2
to win the World Cup for the third time in the tournament's 27-year
history.
	   Spain, losing finalist in the inaugural 1971 World Cup, was
again left holding the runner-up trophy on its second trip to the
final.
	   It was the second time in two years that Holland shattered the
Spanish men's hopes of winning their first major title. The
Netherlands beat Spain 3-1 for the gold medal at the 1996 Atlanta
Olympics.
	   Spain showed its resolve to turn the tables this time by closely
marking the Dutch raiders and surging into the lead against the run
of play in the 18th minute through a flash strike by left winger
Javier Arnau.
	   The Spanish defense was under pressure from the Dutch raiders
when a counter attack on the first Netherlands penalty corner saw
Victor Pujol relay Juan Escarre's long pass to Arnau, who scored
with a stinging angular shot past goalkeeper Ronald Jansen.
	   Spain suffered a big blow in the 21st minute when its
center-forward Escarre limped out of the field with a pulled
hamstring, but its goalkeeper Jufresa played a brilliant game to
thwart a series of raids on the citadel.
	   Jufresa twice came between Dutch strikers and the Spain goal as
he padded away stinging shots from Jeroen Delmee and Jaap Derk
Buma.
	   Marking the Netherlands' raiders exceptionally well, Spain
seemed in control of the game when a penalty corner conversion by
Victor Pujol increased the lead in the 54th minute by deflecting
Arnau's shot past the bewildered goalkeeper.
	   Dutch captain Stephan Veen brought his team back into the game
with a 54th minute strike after dribbling into the scoring zone
past two defenders on the right flank and shooting into the far
corner of the goal.
	   Going all out into the attack, Netherlands forced a series of
penalty corners. But the Spanish defense held its ground until drag
flick specialist Bram Lomans scooped the ball into the cage in the
61st minute to make the equalizer and take the game into extra
time.
	   De Nooijer slammed a penalty corner rebound into the goal to set
off celebrations among the boisterous 15,000 capacity crowd after
goalkeeper Jufresa had blocked the shot from Lomans with just two
minutes of extra time remaining.
	   Spanish coach Toni Forrelat said his players gave away easy
penalty corners towards the end.
	   ``The better team won but we had a chance to score our third
goal, which would have finished the Netherlands,'' he said. ``It
was great to try and beat the Dutch in Netherlands but we ran out
of oxygen in extra time and were very tired.
	   ``My team had not practiced strokes before or during the
tournament so we were not playing for penalties.''
	   Roelants, the Dutch coach, said the goal from Veen was the
turning point for Netherlands.
	   ``I though it was all over when we went down 2-0,'' he said.
``The goal from Veen was very important and so was the crowd
support which lifted us.'' 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Field Hockey-World Cup, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:s; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
