<HEADER>
w1251  wstm-
r w     STOCKS-MOSTLY-LOWERsked     06-01 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> STOCKS-MOSTLY-LOWER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Stocks mostly lower throughout the week, BUSINESS TIMES  
   xfdws STOCKS-MOSTLY-LOWER sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE local stock market continued with its downward trend last
week, a situation that is most likely to persist well into this
week's trade, according to analysts.
	   With no positive local and foreign developments that could spur
the market, stocks were traded mostly lower throughout the week. As
one analyst put it aptly: ``No matter where you turn, there were
worries everywhere.''
	   Leading the worries is the anticipated low corporate earnings to
be announced this week. Last Friday, national carrier Malaysian
Airline System Bhd announced a pre-tax loss of RM225.38 million for
the financial year ended March 31 1998.
	   Then, there are the growing concerns over the country's state of
economy. Malaysia's gross domestic product figure for the first
quarter of this year is expected to be announced and already
analysts have given their lower-than-expected forecasts.
	   Adding to the weak sentiment last week was the statement made by
Tun Daim Zainuddin that Malaysia must avoid stagflation - slow
growth with high interest rates.
	   Daim has said last Wednesday that if Malaysian banks continue to
be unnecessarily strict in their lending, stagnant growth can be
expected.
	   On the foreign front, taking the cue from the sharp fall of the
Dow Jones last Wednesday and coupled with continued concerns over
the region's economies, share prices across the region fell hard.
	   Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index was the hardest hit as it nosedived
5.3 per cent or 498.78 points to below the psychological level at
8,983.43 on economic jitters. It was reported that Hong Kong chief
executive Tung Chee-hwa said the territory might post negative
growth as the economy was in a major adjustment.
	   Besides worries that Hong Kong might go into recession, the
sluggish Japan's economy and the yen depreciation against the US
dollar contributed to the lethargic sentiment over the local
bourse.
	   The yen depreciation, said anaylsts could spark US investors to
dump Japanese and other international stocks, which in turn would
affect all Asian markets.
	   Meanwhile, the political uncertainty surrounding Indonesia is
far from over and this will further dampen sentiment across the
region.
	   Back at home, sellers, led by foreign funds swarmed the local
bourse, selling down most blue-chip stocks such as Maybank,
Telekom, Tenaga Nasional and Sime Darby.
	   The week began last Monday with the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange
Composite Index (KLCI) finishing 6.68 points lower to close at
570.55. The next day, it fell again by 9.27 points to 561.28.
	   On Wednesday, as concerns on the economy grew, investors dumped
heavyweight stocks, dragging the KLCI 9 points down to close at
552.28.
	   Last Thursday saw a mild technical rebound in the early parts of
the day but was later absorbed by profit-taking with the KLCI
shedding 7.54 points to close at 544.74. Finally on Friday, selling
pressure continued prompting the KLCI to close 6.5 points lower to
538.24.
	   Overall, the KLCI lost about 38.99 points or 6.76 per cent from
the previous Friday's closing of 577.23, while the Emas Index shed
8.41 points or 5.8 per cent to 136.51.
	   In terms of volume turnover, last week saw a total of some
499.270 million shares traded valued at RM1.068 billion compared to
754.54 million shares worth RM1.550 billion the week before.
	   Main board turnover was 445.993 million shares valued at
RM993.515 million while second board saw a total of 44.195 million
shares dealt valued at RM69.517 million.
	   Off market turnover saw some 29.302 million shares done worth
RM102.420 million compared to 74.759 million shares valued at
RM161.183 million shares dealt the week before.
	   Making its debut on the main board last week was Mieco Chipboard
Bhd which was not spared from last week's bearish sentiment when it
debuted at RM1.20 over its over price of RM1.50. The stock of the
particleboard maker ended the day one sen lower at RM1.49 with
about 1.2 million shares traded.
	   
</TEXT>
