r w     ACQUITTED-OF-CURRENCYske     06-01 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> ACQUITTED-OF-CURRENCY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Muhammad acquitted of currency charges (HL), NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws ACQUITTED-OF-CURRENCY sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   FORMER Selangor Menteri Besar Tan Sri Muhammad Muhammad Taib was
acquitted yesterday on two charges of falsely declaring the money
he took into Australia in December 1996 and failing to declare more
than A$1.2 million (RM2.9 million) when he left the country.
	   District Court Judge Eric Pratt freed Muhammad after the 12-man
jury, which deliberated for almost five hours, returned a unanimous
verdict of not guilty. Pratt said he would not entertain any
reference on law by the prosecution when Crown Counsel Cate Holmes
said she might make a reference later.
	   ``You can do so before another judge,'' Pratt said, referring to
his earlier ruling on mens rea (guilty mind) which the prosecution
had to establish.
	   When court was adjourned, Muhammad said ``syukur alhamdullilah''
(thank God), rushed out of the dock, hugged his wife Puan Sri Asbi
Rohani Hasnan, his brothers and his counsel. More than 20 of his
supporters in the public gallery above the court room, hurried down
to meet him.
	   There were sounds of relief and cries of joy when the head juror
announced the verdict.
	   With the acquittal, the money involved would be returned to
Muhammad.
	   Counsel Tim Robertson said the defence received a letter from
the prosecution in the morning stating that the money would be
released before the verdict since it was not tainted.
	   Muhammad, 52, who resigned as Menteri Besar in April last year,
was charged with two counts of falsely declaring the amount of
money he was taking into Australia on Dec 16, 1996 and failing to
declare more than A$1.2 million when he left the country on Dec 22,
1996.
	   The charges were under the Australian Financial Transactions
Report Act 1988. Under the Act, all transfer of any currency into
or out of Australia in excess of A$5,000 (the limit was raised to
A$10,000 last June) must be declared to the Australian Customs.
	   Earlier, in his summing up, Pratt outlined the salient points in
the defence and prosecution's evidence, and reminded the jury to
return a unanimous verdict, one way or the other.
	   (A unanimous verdict is required for federal offences such as
those faced by Muhammad.) Muhammad, a Malaysian, should be judged
in the light of his cultural background, the judge said, referring
to Malaysians' preference to deal in cash.
	   Pratt said there was no dispute that most of the elements of the
charges were proved, but what was in dispute was Muhammad's
intention.
	   The judge said the jury should ascertain whether Muhammad had a
guilty mind (mens rea) when he failed to declare the money.
	   (The issue of mens rea was raised by the defence and Pratt had
ruled that it had to be established before Muhammad could be guilty
of the offences.) Pratt said it was rather unfair for the police
not to show Muhammad the declaration form which he filled up on Dec
16, 1996.
	   It would have been better if the form was shown to him during
the interview so that he could explain himself, the judge said,
adding that Muhammad was rather surprised when told that he had
only declared A$9,793.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
