<SLUG> BC-UN-Kosovo,0423 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rugova calls for greater UN role, independence for Kosovo 
</HEADLINE>
By ROBERT H. REID
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ The leader of the self-declared government
of the Kosovo Albanians sought U.N. support Monday for an
international civilian administration for the troubled province as
a first step toward independence from Serbia.
	   Dr. Ibrahim Rugova met Monday with Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
one day after the United Nations recorded a record number of people
fleeing from Kosovo across the Albanian border to escape fighting
which erupted in the Serb-ruled province over the weekend.
	   U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said 1,300 people arrived at the
Albanian border town of Tropoja on Sunday, the largest number in a
single day. Eckhard said an undetermined number of others were
believed trapped by the fighting and unable to cross the border.
	   ``The independence of Kosovo is the best solution,'' Rugova said
after meeting Annan. Rugova said independence for Kosovo, which has
a 90 percent majority Albanian population, would help stabilize the
Balkans, ``even Serbia, although at this stage they think in a
different way.''
	   Serbia rejects independence, considering Kosovo the cradle of
Serb culture. The United States and other major countries also
oppose independence but have called for self-rule for the Kosovo
Albanians within Serbian borders.
	   But Rugova suggested ``some kind of international civilian
administration, or a protectorate, as an interim measure'' leading
to full independence.
	   In the meantime, he called for an end to Serb military and
police operations against Albanian separatists who have been
fighting for independence for the Albanian-majority region, which
is now a province of Serbia. Serbia, together with Montenegro,
forms Yugoslavia.
	   Rugova met in Washington last week with President Clinton and
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to discuss the crisis in
Kosovo. Rugova applauded U.S. mediation to promote a dialogue
between the Kosovo Albanians and President Slobodan Milosevic.
Milosevic revoked Kosovo's autonomy in 1989.
	   ``In order for the negotiations to be successful, it is critical
that police and military operations stop,'' Rugova said. ``Serb
police and military actions have been continuing, resulting in many
people killed.''
	   He said he asked Annan for ``more support for Kosovo'' and
unspecified ``preventive measures'' to prevent further
deterioration and ``massacres and massive ethnic cleansing.''
</TEXT>
