<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
British aid to Malaysian students appreciated, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws MALAYSIAN-STUDENTS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   MALAYSIA is grateful to Britain for the assistance it has
rendered to Malaysian students whose education has been affected by
the shortage of funds following the country's economic problems.
	   Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim expressed his
appreciation to Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown during a
breakfast meeting yesterday.
	   Anwar, who is Finance Minister, said Malaysia appreciated the
initiative taken by the British Government to look into the funding
problems of its students so that they may continue their studies in
the United Kingdom.
	   It is learnt that the British Government, through its Foreign
and Commonwealth Office, has set up a fund to assist needy Asian
students unable to continue their studies in the UK because of the
region's economic situation.
	   The students requiring assistance are mainly from Indonesia,
Korea, Thailand and Malaysia.
	   The financing for the fund comes from the British Government,
the British Council, several universities and private companies in
Britain which have interests in the affected Asian countries.
	   More details on the fund are expected to be announced next week.
	   Later, speaking to Malaysian journalists at Malaysia Hall after
addressing Malaysian students on the country's economic situation,
Anwar, who was on a two-day working visit to London, expressed
confidence that Malaysia could achieve a 2.5 per cent economic
growth figure for this year.
	   He said he would announce the country's economic growth figures
for the first quarter of the year by next weekend.
	   ``Although the first two months were really drastic and will
reflect adversely on the growth, the March and April figures seem
to be reassuring as there is more positive growth and lending by
the commercial banks.''
	   Anwar also said Malaysia was prepared to liberalise its economic
policy but at its own pace and not on the terms dictated by others.
	   ``We should do it gradually and decide the pace and extent of
liberalisation and ensure we have our indigenous capacity.''
	   He said although Malaysia did not have any major debts and,
unlike some of its neighbours, could still survive the economic
crisis without depending on the International Monetary Fund, it
should learn from the experience of other countries where
corruption existed.
	   ``It is a big crisis which has hit all countries, including
Russia.
	   ``We must therefore resolve to be a united force to deal with
the problem.
	   ``We must resolve to fight corruption because it is a cancer
that can destroy us.''
	   He urged the people to be prepared for change and accept
reforms.
	   ``We do not deny that there is a problem but our fundamentals
are still strong. We need to learn from the experience of others.
Our propensity to change for the better is necessary.
	   ``I am confident that our economy will recover soon and we will
come back even stronger because I believe in the resilience of the
people.
	   ``There is creative destruction and from the ashes of the past,
we will build a new resilience for the future.''
	   Speaking to the students earlier, Anwar said there was no
necessity for a shadow Cabinet in Malaysia as the Opposition was
free to express their ideas.
	   He said although ideas by the British Government are bandied
about with the Opposition's shadow Cabinet over the media, it need
not necessarily be emulated by Malaysia.
	   ``The role of the Opposition in the West should not be
considered ideal for us.''
	   Anwar agreed on the need for transparency through the media but
cautioned against sensationalising issues which could cause tension
among the people.
	   On the prospects of more funding for students involved in
research and development, he said the Government was committed to
promoting RD and had allocated about RM400 million for the purpose
through the Intensification of Research on Priority Areas Scheme.
	   He said local universities such as Universiti Tenaga Nasional
and Universiti Petronas had been asked to provide the necessary
expertise and research centres.
	   
</TEXT>
