<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Syariah Appeals Court dismisses appointment, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws SYARIAH-APPEALS-COURT sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KOTA BARU, Sun. - The Syariah Appeals Court today dismissed the
appointment of Datuk Shukri Mohamed as prosecutor on behalf of the
Kelantan Religious and Malay Customs Council (MAIK) in a libel case
involving Pengkalan Chepa MP Mohd Amar Abdullah.
	   The ruling was on the grounds the appointment had not been made
according to procedure.
	   The court, presided by three judges - Datuk Professor Mahmood
Zuhdi Abdul Majid, former Lord President Tun Mohamed Salleh Abas
and Datuk Nik Hashim Nik Abdul Rahman - ruled that Shukri's
appointment could not be made under section 169(1) of the Kelantan
Syariah Criminal Procedure Enactment as was done by Syariah deputy
public prosecutor Abu Bakar Abdullah Kutty.
	   Mahmood Zuhdi, who led the panel of judges, said this was
because the provision in the section stated that a hearing before
the Kadi High Court should be conducted by a prosecutor or a
Syariah lawyer who had been given written permission by the
prosecutor to do so. ``In this case, Shukri is not a Syariah
lawyer.''
	   However, he said Abu Bakar could submit a fresh application to
the Kadi High Court to appoint Shukri as the prosecutor.
	   He also said that there was no need for the Kadi High Court to
get approval from the State Government to do so.
	   Section 170 states that written permission from the court is
required for a lawyer to conduct prosecution on behalf of the State
Government.
	   The ruling was made following Mohd Amar's request, made through
his lawyer, Takiyuddin Hassan for a revision on Shukri's
appointment.
	   Shukri had, on March 15, received sanction from Abu Bakar to act
as prosecutor in the case. The sanction was made under Section 169
of the Kelantan Syariah Criminal Enactment Procedure.
	   Takiyuddin, in his submission today, questioned the legality of
the procedure in Shukri's appointment saying that Shukri's
appointment to act as prosecutor in the case could not be made
under Section 169.
	   He also cited Section 167 which stated that the power to
prosecute was only bestowed on the Syariah prosecutor.
	   Mohd Amar, 34, who is Kelantan Pas Youth vice-chief, had pleaded
not guilty in the Chief Kadi's Court in April last year with
insulting MAIK over a Hari Raya Aidil Fitri sermon in his ceramah
at Jalan Dusun Raja at 10.15pm on March 8, 1997.
	   He is charged under section 121 of the MAIK Enactment 1994. If
found guilty, he can be jailed three years or fined RM5,000, or
both.
	   He was alleged to have used the words kurang cerdik (not so
intelligent) when referring to two or three MAIK officials in his
speech at the ceramah.
	   
</TEXT>
