<HEADER>
w1265  wstm-
r w     PPAS-IN-WAY-OF-LOWERsked     06-01 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> PPAS-IN-WAY-OF-LOWER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
PPAs in way of lower tariffs, says Tajuddin, BUSINESS TIMES  
   xfdws PPAS-IN-WAY-OF-LOWER sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   TENAGA Nasional Bhd (Tenaga) says a more efficient generation of
electricity that could lower tariffs is possible, but this will
require existing power purchase agreements (PPAs) with the
independent power producers (IPPs) to be ``undone''.
	   Executive chairman Datuk Ahmad Tajuddin Ali said if a trading
and settlement of electricity in a free market scheme is adopted,
consumers will benefit from lower tariffs.
	   But this scheme cannot be implemented if the PPAs are still in
place.
	   ``It would be unfair to Tenaga,'' Tajuddin said in an interview
with Business Times.
	   In an electricity trading and settlement market, the IPPs must
inform the independent grid system operator of their plants'
available capacity and their selling price daily.
	   The independent grid system operator - which will manage the
systems operations of the National Grid by the year 2000 - will
then match the demand and supply of electricity at any one time and
buy from the IPP which offers the cheapest price.
	   The electricity will then be directed to Tenaga's National Load
Despatch Centre at Bangsar, which will despatch it to the grid.
	   Tajuddin said in this case, the PPAs become a stumbling block.
	   Under the PPA, Tenaga will have to pay the IPPs an agreed amount
for making their plants available to generate electricity for the
use of the utility.
	   Tenaga is spending more than RM2 billion to buy about 30 per
cent of the electricity generated by the IPPs.
	   The agreement also acts as a guarantee, whereby the IPPs can use
the PPAs - which secure revenue to the companies - to source funds
from financial institutions.
	   Tenaga, however, does not envisioned the settlement and trading
system to be in place for quite some time. It has enough supply and
more than its required capacity.
	   Currently, the installed capacity is closed to 12,000MW while
maximum demand is 8,500 MW.
	   The Government, too, is not ready for commitments on a
settlement and trading of power as restructuring in the electricity
is still on-going.
	   ``I cannot make that commitment without being very sure,''
Energy, Telecommunications and Posts Minister Datuk Leo Moggie had
said when asked about the idea of a power trading system.
	   ``Once we make a public statement and if it is found not very
practical or workable, we will get ourselves in a jam,'' the
minister had added.
	   A cautious approach to such a system is being taken. The
Economic Planning Unit in the Prime Minister's Department is
looking at its viability and customising it to the local
electricity scenario.
	   Penjanabebas, the association for IPPs, will hold a meeting soon
to discuss the issue.
	   Its honorary president, Encik Ahmad Jauhari Yahya, said a
settlement and trading system will lower the entrance barrier and
attract the best participant for the electricity generation
industry.
	   When asked on the impact of the settlement and trading system on
the current PPA, he said ``we have been assured by the Government
that existing agreement will be honoured''.
	   Ahmad Jauhari said concerns will mainly be on industry
restructuring and the reaction from the industry as the settlement
and trading system will have to be viable to attract new
investments.
	   ``The settlement and trading system for power will result in a
liberalised market if it is to be implemented. However, the market
must be mature to accept such a system. The financial market must
also be educated and accept that it a more competitive system,'' he
said.
	   
</TEXT>
