<BODY>
<SLUG> LIBERALISATION-HELPS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
`Liberalisation helps everyone', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws LIBERALISATION-HELPS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - Developing countries should continue to
pursue the agenda for further liberalisation in world trade,
especially in manufacturing.
	   ``Such a move would only be in the interests of developing
countries, especially manufacturing into which these countries are
now in a big way,''
	   Kuala Lumpur International Airport Berhad chairman Tan Sri
Clifford Herbert said.
	   Citing Malaysia, Herbert said, about 80 per cent of Malaysia's
exports were manufactures-based and any denial of access to markets
would have deleterious effects.
	   ``Malaysia is today the 17th largest trading nation and it is in
our interest to maintain an open trading system,'' Herbert, who was
former Finance Ministry secretary general, said.
	   He was speaking at the Harvard Project for Asian and
International Relations conference titled ``Asia in Transition:
Beyond the Miracle'' at the Putra World Trade Centre.
	   Co-organised by Harvard University student organisation, Aiesec
Universiti Putra Malaysia and the International Malaysia Forum, the
conference entered its second day today.
	   The conference aims to engage future leaders in discussions that
demonstrate the complexity of international relations.
	   Speaking on ``Economic Liberalisation: Problems and Prospects'',
Herbert told the audience the recent Apec agreement in Vancouver,
Canada to liberalise trade further in 15 major sectors was a
positive development.
	   ``Malaysia participated in these discussions and the fact that
we could subscribe to this illustrates trade liberalisation is
still very much on our agenda.''
	   ``Malaysia and like minded developing countries however must
insist that liberalisation is not a one-way affair.''
	   Herbert attributed the long lasting growth in Asia to several
factors which included; Increasing trade links with the rest of the
world, with all these countries increasing their share of exports
to the markets of the developed countries, particularly in
manufacturing, and Flow of technology to these countries and high
levels of foreign investment.
	   ``Countries like Malaysia also benefited by the free flow of
labour into these countries, sometimes at costs much lower than
domestic labour.''
	   In the case of Malaysia, foreign labour now amounted to almost
two million, out of a labour force of eight million.
	   ``There is no doubt that liberalisation of markets in trade,
investment, labour and capital contributed to the rapid development
of these economies.
	   ``Strong and purposeful leadership contributed to growth in a
liberalised trading enviroment.''
	   These countries therefore, he added, had a strong commitment to
maintaining open trading systems, free flow of capital, increasing
globalisation and integration with world markets.
	   ``In fact, if the economic crisis had not occurred, a higher
level of liberalisation would have taken place.''
	   
</TEXT>
