<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Nik Aziz determined to hold on to his post, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws NIK-AZIZ-DETERMINED sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KOTA BARU, Sun. - Menteri Besar Datuk Nik Abdul Aziz Nik Mat
today brushed aside Kelantan Umno's call for his resignation,
saying that it would only strengthen his resolve to hold on to his
post.
	   ``The more Umno urges me to step down, the stronger is my
resolve to hold on to my post,'' he said.
	   Describing himself as Umno's enemy, Nik Aziz said his presence
in the State Government had caused uneasiness among Umno members.
	   As such, he said Umno would come up with various ploys to exert
pressure on him to quit.
	   ``Probably my views on different issues have placed Umno members
in a lot of trouble,'' he told reporters after opening the dadah
awareness programme for village headmen.
	   Kelantan Umno, at its convention yesterday, had passed a
resolution calling Nik Aziz to resign, saying that the State
Government's administration under his leadership was inefficient.
	   On whether the resolution was in retaliation to the recent Pas
call on Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir Mohamad to step down,
Nik Aziz said it was a political move.
	   Asked on cultural activities after he opened the 1998
International Kite Festival here, Nik Aziz said Kelantan was
drafting a bill requiring cultural performances to conform to
Islamic requirements.
	   The proposed bill was being studied by a special committee
chaired by state Culture, Tourism, Youth and Sports Committee
chairman Abdullah Ya'kub.
	   ``We expect to table the bill at the next sitting of the State
Legislative Assembly,'' Nik Aziz was quoted by Bernama.
	   The committee, comprising academicians and Culture, Arts and
Tourism Ministry officials, among others, will study the forms of
cultural shows that do not contravene Islamic teachings.
	   The proposed bill would also define in general the form of dikir
barat that can be permitted in the state.
	   The State Executive Council last week imposed a freeze on dikir
barat performances following public complaints of undesirable
features projected by the performers.
	   
</TEXT>
