<BODY>
<SLUG> ACCOUNTABILITY-VITAL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Accountability vital to good governance, says don, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws ACCOUNTABILITY-VITAL sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - For good governance, those in power must
have political legitimacy and be held accountable, Thammasat
University professor of political science, Dr Likhit Dhiravegin
said today.
	   He said the writing of a charter would help reform the existing
fledgling Thai democratic system, caught in the economic crisis.
	   Dhiravegin said reform was inevitable to curb vote-buying,
scramble for cabinet posts, corruption, interference in the civil
service and abuse of the national budget.
	   He said this presenting his paper, ``Good Governance in Asia :
Political Reform and Democratic Development in Thailand'' at the
Harvard Project for Asian and International Relations conference
entitled ``Asia in Transition : Beyond the Miracle'' at the Putra
World Trade Centre.
	   Co-organised by the Harvard University student organisation,
Aiesec Universiti Putra Malaysia and the International Malaysia
Forum, the four-day conference is the first held in Malaysia since
HPAIR's first conference in 1992.
	   Undergraduates and post-graduates from the world's top
universities including Harvard, Yale and Oxford are attending to
exchange perspectives on critical international issues.
	   A new charter would help rectify the defects of the present
system on ascension to power and to institute a control mechanism.
	   First, the ascension to power would be changed in such a way
that more capable people with integrity would be recruited.
	   Mechanisms of control through checks and balances would be
devised to prevent the breaking of laws and the like.
	   ``More importantly, the people must be given their rights and
freedom and be able to participate in the political process,'' he
said.
	   To questions from the floor, Dhiravegin added that changes also
meant the Prime Minister would be chosen by a vote count in the
House of Representatives in lieu of the existing system where the
party with the most seats in the House of Reprentatives would go
around asking other parties to join as a coalition government.
	   The process would afford more transparency.
	   On the economic meltdown, he said it was not solely for lack of
good governance but a coming together of several factors.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
