<HEADLINE>
Hundreds march against government in Belarus on Children's Day 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MINSK, Belarus (AP) _ Several hundred people rallied in Minsk on
Monday, International Children's Day, protesting against everything
from the president to the lingering health effects of the Chernobyl
nuclear disaster.
	   ``Our children are sick with cancer after the Chernobyl
catastrophe,'' said rally organizer Tatyana Vanina. A reactor at
the Chernobyl nuclear plant exploded and caught fire in neighboring
Ukraine in 1986, but much of the radioactive fallout landed in
Belarus.
	   Protesters adopted a resolution calling for the resignation of
President Alexander Lukashenko, accusing him of not being concerned
about the future of the 2.7 million children in Belarus.
	   Lukashenko is a frequent target of protest groups who object to
his authoritarian rule. However, he generally enjoys broad
popularity in the former Soviet republic.
