<BODY>
<SLUG> AMSTEEL-SECRITIES-GETS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Amsteel Securities gets SC consent to continue trading, BUSINESS TIMES  
   xfdws AMSTEEL-SECRITIES-GETS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   AMSTEEL Securities Sdn Bhd has been given written consent to
continue trading by the Securities Commission (SC), on condition
that it complies with the Minimum Liquid Fund (MLF) requirements of
the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) on or before June 5.
	   Amsteel is one of 12 stockbroking companies with an MLF deficit
reported by the KLSE on May 15. All firms on the list, except for
Amsteel, have been placed under trading restrictions by the KLSE.
	   Omega Securities Sdn Bhd has since been told to cease trading
and the dealer's licence of MBf Northern Securities Sdn Bhd has
been suspended.
	   Labuan Securities's dealer's licence is also suspended. However,
it does meet the MLF requirement.
	   According to the SC, only Omega Securities has not received
written consent to continue with its trading activities.
	   The Commission, replying to a Business Times query, said it has
given ``conditional consent'' to all the other companies (including
Amsteel) to continue with their trading.
	   ``The conditions of restricted trading of the KLSE apply to
these companies,'' the SC said.
	   To date, there has been no announcement that Amsteel is under
trading restrictions.
	   Meanwhile, according to a source, given the MLF deficit in
Amsteel, the SC had issued a ``warning'' cum show-cause letter to
the brokerage asking it to regularise its financial position or
risk being ordered to halt trading or having its licence suspended.
	   The company was also told to submit plans on how it intends to
regularise its financial position, which it replied to. Following
this, it received a letter of extension for three weeks from the
SC. Since the extension, the source said, Amsteel has been
reporting the necessary information to the SC.
	   The source said the staff of Amsteel have been on their toes
working to ensure that the company's financial position is up to
the satisfaction of the SC.
	   Daily operations of the stockbroking company have been under the
SC's watch, the source said, adding that Amsteel has been in
constant contact with the Commission.
	   ``At the end of trading every day, the stockbroking firm has to
report its financial status to the Commission, including its MLF
position,'' said the source.
	   Typically, brokerages hit with a MLF deficit must seek written
consent from the SC to continue trading as stipulated under Section
20A of the Securities Industry Act 1983.
	   What happens following the deficit is an issuance of a
show-cause letter by the SC to the brokerage.
	   The firm, in seeking written consent to continue trading, is
required to disclose to the SC the steps it plans to undertake to
regularise its financial position after which the stockbroking
house will either get conditional consent or an order to stop
trading altogether.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
