People unhappy over price hikes, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws PEOPLE-UNHAPPY-OVER sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - Operators of fast-food outlets will have to
face the Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs Ministry over
complaints of price increase since last month.
	   The ministry's parliamentary secretary Datuk Tan Chai Ho said
the ministry had been receiving many complaints and that it would
meet with the operators to clarify the matter.
	   ``People are not happy over the price hike, especially of
chicken.
	   Furthermore, the operators usually deal directly with chicken
farmers and thus are not affected by the market price,'' he told
reporters at the Putra World Trade Centre today.
	   Tan said the ministry's enforcement division had already checked
the fast-food outlets for details over the price hike but he
declined to name the affected outlets. He added the operators would
have to explain the rationale for raising the prices.
	   The ministry has been opposed to price hikes although it has
made some concessions due to the rising cost of raw materials. This
led to a corresponding rise in food prices at fast-food outlets.
	   However, consumer backlash accompanied by calls from consumer
groups to boycott chicken has led to the price of chicken to drop.
	   
