w1272  wstm-
r w     ATTRACT-CAPITALsked     06-01 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> ATTRACT-CAPITAL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Attract capital, boost confidence to end woes, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws ATTRACT-CAPITAL sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - East Asian countries need to build up
confidence and attract capital inflow in order to end the economic
problems and put the region back on track.
	   This was the view of scholars and corporate player attending the
plenary session of the Harvard Project for Asian and International
Relations Conference entitled ``Asia in Transition: Beyond the
Miracle.''
	   ``Principally, one of the solutions to end the regional economic
and financial problems is to ensure capital flow back to the
region,'' said Arab-Malaysian Securities Sdn Bhd executive director
Mustafa Mohd Noor.
	   ``And this requires a stable currency market.''
	   ``If the capital flow resumes, the problems will subside. But if
not, liquidity remains tight and it will be hard to suggest when
the problems could be over,'' said Institute of Strategic and
International Studies Malaysia deputy director-general Dr Zainal
Aznam.
	   Zainal added that tight monetary and fiscal policies, as well as
high interest rates and postponement of mega developments, could
also help end the regional problems.
	   Crawford Jameson, a senior official at Morgan Stanley
Singapore's investment and banking division, said building up
confidence was a major task in view of the battering several East
Asian countries took in the last few months.
	   ``But we somehow need to come up with terms which can restore
the loss of confidence in the region,'' said Jameson, who blamed
the regional problems on corruption, inflated assets, weak market
sentiments, ties between politics and business and ``white elephant
projects'', among others.
	   Mustafa said the Indonesian problem and the weakening of the yen
were factors currently dictating the movement of the ringgit and
other regional currencies.
	   ``Currency volatility should delay resumption of capital flows
to the region, and tight liquidity would retain pressure on
interest rates and dampen economic activity.''
	   He said the depreciation of the yen could also affect the
stability of the region's yet-to-be-affected currencies such as
that of Taiwan, China and Hong Kong.
	   ``If these currencies are not stable, the regional economic and
financial problems could prolong.''
	   He however conceded that ``the selling of assets in the United
States by Japanese investors or government to protect the yen could
in turn destabilise the US financial markets and aggravate the
situation in the region''.
	   Mustafa said at this juncture, the ringgit was still sensitive
to the external developments although it had recovered after
hitting a low of RM4.88 against the US dollar in January.
	   He also warned of a potential recession in Malaysia if there was
a delay in capital flow resumption and banks continued facing
liquidity problem.
	   ``The financial and economic problems are hurting the corporate
sector.
	   The companies which are severely affected should consolidate and
restructure and resume business from a lower base.
	   ``The move to recapitalise and retain existing size of business
may only create greater difficulties,'' Mustafa said, noting that
the regional problems were likely to become more widespread unless
global governmental efforts were taken quickly to overcome them.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:ATTRACT-CAPITAL sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
