<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Denmark-World Cup Team,0494 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Denmark's coach presents his squad for the World Cup 
</HEADLINE>
By JAN M. OLSEN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) _ Denmark's coach Bo Johansson mixed
veteran players and youthful talent in his 22-man World Cup squad
announced Monday.
	   Although Denmark, the 1992 European champions, played poorly in
two recent World Cup warm-up games against Norway and Sweden,
Johansson said there was ``nothing to be negative about.''
	   The side that will play in Group C against France, Saudi Arabia
and South Africa, included three safe bets _ brothers Michael and
Brian Laudrup, and veteran goalie Peter Schmeichel.
	   Michael Laudrup is the only survivor of Denmark's 1986 World Cup
side in Mexico. The 33-year-old will bid farewell to the national
team after the World Cup. His younger brother, Brian, was on the
team that upset mighty Germany to win the 1992 European
Championship in Sweden.
	   One of the world's top keepers, Schmeichel, has been suffering
from a minor injury but Johansson was confident that the Manchester
United's goalie would be fit in time for the World Cup.
	   Schmeichel ``wasn't 100 percent in shape'' when Sweden beat
Denmark 3-0 on May 28, Johansson said.
	   As substitute goalies, Johansson picked Mogens Krogh of the
Danish champion team Broendby, and sole newcomer Peter Kjaer of
Silkeborg, another Danish team.
	   The Danes have only qualified once before for a World Cup.
Denmark surprisingly failed to qualify for the 1994 World Cup in
the United States and a defensive-minded team flopped in the 1996
European Championship in England.
	   Johansson, a Swede, has 8 wins, 2 draws and 3 defeats since he
became Denmark's coach in 1996.
	   He selected experienced defenders like Marc Rieper, Jan Heintze,
Thomas Helveg and Jes Hoegh on the team once known as ``Danish
Dynamite.''
	   Striker Ebbe Sand, the Danish league's top scorer with 28 goals,
was also selected. His first cap was against Norway on April 22
when Denmark lost 2-0.
	   Other inexperienced players are defender Rene Henriksen who
played his first match on the red-and-white team against Scotland
in March, and forward Martin Joergensen who has played three times
on the Danish side.
	   Johansson who has opted for a 4-4-2 system, said he hadn't
decided what system Denmark would play in France, adding he wanted
to avoid ``the vulnerability of playing only one system.''
	   Before heading for France, Denmark plays a friendly against
Cameroon on Friday in Copenhagen.
	   The squad:
	   Goalies _ Peter Schmeichel, Mogens Krogh, Peter Kjaer,
	   Defenders _ Jes Hoegh, Marc Rieper, Jacob Laursen, Rene
Henriksen, Soeren Colding, Jan Heintze, Michael Schjoenberg, Thomas
Helveg,
	   Midfielders _ Allan Nielsen, Per Frandsen, Morten Wieghorst,
Stig Toefting, Bjarne Goldbaek, Michael Laudrup,
	   Forwards _ Brian Laudrup, Miklos Molnar, Peter Moeller, Martin
Joergensen, Ebbe Sand. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-Denmark-World Cup Team; CT:s; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:ASIA;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
