trouble getting loans from banks, especially during this period of
economic slowdown,'' Samy Vellu told reporters after opening the
Indian General Contractors Association's second annual general
meeting in Kuala Lumpur yesterday.
	   He added that he had brought the matter up with the Cabinet
because infrastructure projects should continue even though the
country is facing an economic slowdown.
	   The minister said there had been no offers of financial
asssistance for the other highway project. This covers the RM585
million New Pantai Highway, which stretches between the existing
intersection of Jalan Subang Utama/Jalan Lengka and the KL-Seremban
Expressway between the existing Jalan Klang Lama/Federal Highway
interchange and the intersection of Jalan Bangsar.
	   He added that it is necessary that work on these two projects
continues as they are important infrastructure schemes.
	   On the Sungai Penchala Link Highway, which is part of the Sprint
Highway, Samy Vellu said it ``is very necessary to relieve
congestion in the Damansara area''.
	   ``Even though the highway project will cut through Malay reserve
land, it is necessary because there are eight townships there, with
a population of about 400,000 people and 100,000 vehicles,'' he
said.
	   The minister added that people need to understand the need for
this highway.
	   He said that although there have been protests from those living
in the Malay reserve land area, he feels ``this highway is a
must''.
	   ``I have already explained to the Cabinet why it is so,'' he
said and added that it will help reduce the number of vehicles
using Jalan Damansara to enter the city.
	   He said that those affected by the highway project will be duly
compensated. ``If an interchange is developed, the people who own
the land there will get even better economic returns.''
	   The minister also spoke about work on seven Indian highway
projects amounting to ``billions of ringgit'' which has been
offered to Malaysian companies.
	   An initial feasibility study on the privatized infrastructure
projects is being conducted by ASS Integrated Sdn Bhd, a local
consulting engineer company. The company will then submit a report
to the Ministry of Surface Transport in India.
	   It is understood that the Construction Industries Development
Board (CIDB) Malaysia is leading the consortium which will
undertake work on some 2,000km of roads and highways.
	   ``The projects are to widen existing two-lane highways into
four-lane highways,'' Samy Vellu said, pointing out that business
is done differently in India as compared to Malaysia.
	   ``In India, the concession company only has to come up with
about 50 per cent financing for the project as the Government will
invest about 30 per cent in the project and sub-loans amounting to
20 per cent are granted,''
	   he said.
	   He added that the Indians had developed further some of
Malaysia's ideas, such as the one on toll charges.
	   Among the highways to be worked on in Andhra Pradesh are the
1,000km stretch of the national highway No. 5 (between Tada and
Ichapuram) and the national highway No. 9, stretching between
Hyderabad and Vijayawada.
	   
</TEXT>
