w1278  wstm-
r w     TIN-SECTORS-LAST-RESORTs     06-01 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> TIN-SECTORS-LAST-RESORT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Tin sector's last resort to retain its shine, BUSINESS TIMES  
   xfdws TIN-SECTORS-LAST-RESORT sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   TIN mining used to be the in thing in the country. The wealthy
were commonly referred to as tauke lombong; the title became even
more apt if the rich person wore khaki shorts which were worn by
the Mat Sallehs -Western bosses who run most of the mines in the
country then.
	   Malaysia's tin mining activities were at his height in the 1950s
and the industry provided employment to the people. The country was
then the world's largest tin producer and held the title for a long
time. Even the secretariat of the Association of Tin Producing
Countries (ATPC) was located in Malaysia due to the strengh of the
industry.
	   Tin, a non-renewable resource, however began to lose its shine
when the world tin market crashed in the mid-1980s. It marked a
turning point for the industry in the country. The world's largest
tin producer became a net importer of the metal in the early 1990s.
	   The low price of tin made mining activities unlucrative in
Malaysia and land was used for more profitable sectors such as
property and oil palm.
	   The cheap price of tin, however, has helped one sector to
prosper -the smelting industry. The two Malaysian smelters - Escoy
Smelting Sdn Bhd and Malaysian Smelting Corp (MSC) - are now
multi-million ringgit businesses.
	   Foreign exchange revenue from export of tin in 1997 totalled
RM479 million against RM533 million in 1996. However, the import of
tin-in-concentrates were valued at RM452 million compared with
RM486 million in 1996. As such, net export revenue in 1997 totalled
RM27 million against RM47 million in 1996. Malaysia exported 31,785
tonnes of refined tin last year, down 2,557 tonnes from 34,342
tonnes in 1996.
	   But even the smelting sector seems to be following the fate of
the tin mining industry. Effective last April, Escoy Smelting had
closed shop, making MSC the country's sole smelter of tin.
Nonetheless, the Malaysian Chamber of Mines had expressed
confidence that MSC can still assist the country remain as the
centre of tin smelting in years to come. With MSC's smelting
capacity of 40,000 tonnes a year, the chamber felt that the company
should have no problems in maintaining the volume of refined tin
metal exports which total some 30,000 tonnes a year.
	   Tin's only avenue for maintaining its name in the country's list
of revenue-earning industries is the Mineral Development Policy - a
policy which allows the mining industry to diversify its sources
and not limit itself to mining tin only.
	   Unfortunately, the adoption of the Mineral Development Policy by
states has been too slow for the industry's liking. Malaysian
Chamber of Mines president Abdul Sukor Shahar had said although
several roadshows had been conducted to explain the implementation
and benefits of the policy, not much progress has been made. Except
for Sarawak, which had incorporated several of the provisions into
its State Mining Enactment, the other states have remained quiet.
	   It is a sad that the new policy, which was intended to give a
needed boost to the tin mining industry, invoked only lukewarm
response from state governments.
	   The MDC aims to generate mining investments and offer
socio-economic developments to the states, especially those with
mineral potential. The earlier the states realise these advantages,
the faster the economic benefits to be reaped.
	   The year will undoubtedly see more roadshows by relevant
authorities and tin-related associations to convince state
governments to adopt and implement the MDP.
	   While the country's tin mining days are numbered, there is no
reason why it should not continue to tap its remaining tin
reserves.
	   Granted that it is not viable to solely concentrate on tin
mining, there is no harm in simultaneously mining both the metal
and other minerals such as silica, ball clay, gold and marble
stones.
	   The diversification of mining activities may in the long term
spur the sector to become a major revenue earner for the country
once again. And perhaps this time there will be more tauke lombongs
around.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
