<HEADER>
w1281  wstm-
r w     HELPING-BUMI-FIRMSsked     06-01 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> HELPING-BUMI-FIRMS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Government `to continue helping Bumi firms', NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws HELPING-BUMI-FIRMS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KOTA BARU, Fri. - Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir Mohamad
said today the Government will continue to help big and small
Bumiputera companies to enable them to compete with other races in
the business sector.
	   He said that it was the Government's responsibility to ensure
that all races share the country's wealth.
	   ``If we allow all the Bumiputera companies to collapse, we will
be placed in a situation before the New Economic Policy was
introduced, where the poor were generally the Malays,'' he added.
	   He said, however, the Government would only assist Bumiputera
companies which had the potential to succeed and that ``there is no
favouritism''.
	   Dr Mahathir said the Government's assistance to Bumiputeras was
often interpreted by certain foreign quarters as helping
``government cronies'' as if they were favoured by the Government.
	   ``Such allegations were made because they are envious of the
achievements of the Malays. They actually want the Malays to remain
the poorest race in the country. They have bad intentions and if
possible, they want us to remain stupid.
	   ``Even if a Malay businessman succeeds without Government's
assistance, he will still be labelled a government crony,'' he
added.
	   He was addressing a large crowd at the launch of the Kelantan
Multimedia, Telecommunications and Electronic Exposition (Emtek
'98) at Sekolah Menengah Chabang Empat Pasir Mas/Tumpat.
	   Dr Mahathir was accompanied by his wife Datin Seri Dr Siti
Hasmah Mohd Ali. Others present included former Deputy Prime
Minister Tun Abdul Ghafar Baba, MP for Gua Musang Tengku Razaleigh
Hamzah, Entrepreneur Development Minister Datuk Mustapa Mohamed,
Rural Development Minister Datuk Annuar Musa, Umno Youth chief
Datuk Ahmad Zahid Hamidi, Johor Menteri Besar Datuk Abdul Ghani
Othman and Umno Information chief Datuk Dr Yusof Nor.
	   Dr Mahathir said since the NEP was introduced, thousands of jobs
were created as well as scholarships given which enabled children
in the rural areas to pursue their education which later enabled
them to compete on equal footing with other races.
	   He said these efforts helped the economy and created many
millionaires and even billionaires.
	   ``We should be proud of them. We don't question who they are
because they are our representatives from among the Malays in the
country. We want all the races to be equal.
	   ``We do not want a situation where the poor are the Malays and
the rich are from other races. This is a dangerous situation and
can lead to chaos in the country,'' he added.
	   Dr Mahathir also advised the people to familiarise themselves
with information technology so that they could use IT to assist in
the nation's progress.
	   ``The use of IT is everywhere. It has created a borderless
world. But there is now an attempt to colonise nations using IT
instead of war planes or canons.''
	   He said an example of the power of IT was the transfer of
millions of ringgit from one country to another with the touch of a
button.
	   ``We now have a borderless world. The world has become as if one
country.
	   People can move anywhere without restrictions and without
respect for our borders.
	   ``I do not know if this was done on purpose to control us but
the fact is that they have succeeded in making us poor, and because
of that, they are able to control our economy. They get richer and
richer.''
	   Dr Mahathir said as the value of the ringgit depreciated, so
would the people's purchasing power.
	   When this happens, he said, the people could not buy imported
products, such as milk, wheat and medicine, and as a consequence,
the people would revolt and blame the Government.
	   ``So, they are not only creating economic problems but political
and social problems as well,'' he added.
	   Citing Indonesia as an example, he said the country with more
than 200 million people and experiencing a growth rate of seven per
cent for several years was now made poor following the fall in the
value of the rupiah.
	   ``The people have forgotten the efforts of the Government to
build the country over the past 30 years. At one stage, Indonesia
was regarded as one of the economic tigers of Asia.''
	   However, he said, when the rupiah was attacked, it caused
numerous problems, including high cost of essential items which
have to be imported, the closure of 16 banks, the closure of 10,000
companies and the loss of jobs for 20 million people.
	   Speaking to reporters later, Dr Mahathir said the development of
the Multimedia Super Corridor would proceed despite the current
economic situation.
	   He said the economic problems in the region had also affected
the finances of companies planning to invest in the MSC.
	   For example, he said, companies in Japan have slowed down their
investment abroad and this would affect the MSC.
	   Asked if the economic problems could be overcome soon, Dr
Mahathir said it could not be solved in the short term because ``we
have lost the power to dictate the rise and fall of currency''.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
