<BODY>
<SLUG> AYAMAS-PERLIS-SIGN-BROIL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Ayamas, Perlis sign broiler farm contract, BUSINESS TIMES  
   xfdws AYAMAS-PERLIS-SIGN-BROIL sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   AYAMAS Food Corp Bhd (AFCB) will jointly undertake with the
Perlis State Government a large-scale broiler contract farming
project.
	   The leading local poultry processor and retailer recently signed
an agreement with the Perlis State Government to formalise the
project which will supply an estimated one million birds every
year.
	   The project involves the construction of a 200ha broiler farm
located in Padang Besar, Perlis.
	   Signing on behalf of the Perlis State Government was its Menteri
Besar Datuk seri Shahidan Kassim and representing Ayamas was KFC
Holdings (M) Bhd executive deputy chairman Datuk Ishak Ismail.
	   ``This project marks a significant business venture for us as we
will be transferring our skills and knowledge of the poultry
industry to farmers in Perlis,'' said Ayamas chief operating
officer Ms Foo Peng Peng in a statement released in Kuala Lumpur
recently.
	   She said, a team of qualified veterinarians from Ayamas Food
will give professional advice on the raising of chicks or broilers
following strict quality control measures.
	   ``We will also be supplying quality feed to the farm to ensure
that the broilers achieve satisfactory growth during the 40 to
45-day cycle,'' she added.
	   The farm, according to her, will be supplying around 50,000
birds per cycle. This will gradually increase to 300,000 birds per
cycle in the long term.
	   The MOU she pointed out, looks toward a long-term understanding
and with time it is expected that more farmers will realise the
lucrative returns of such a joint venture.
	   In August last year, Ayamas signed an agreement with the
Selangor Farmers Organisation (LPP Selangor) to undertake broiler
contract farming for the supply of an estimated 5.4 million birds a
year.
	   At present the company's two processing plants in Bukit Mertajam
and Port Klang process around 2.2 million birds per month. With the
completion of the RM30 million upgrading exercise for the Port
Klang plant by 1999, production is expected to increase by around
50 per cent.
	   To date, Ayamas supplies fresh chicken to KFC's network of over
255 restaurants, 58 Pizza Hut restaurants and 45 Ayamas convenience
stores, as well as the open market comprising supermarkets,
hypermarkets, wholesalers, hotels and restaurants throughout the
country.
	   
</TEXT>
