<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 14:35:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1289  wstm-
r w     OPTIMISTIC-ABOUT-ECONOMY     06-01 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> OPTIMISTIC-ABOUT-ECONOMY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
BNM optimistic about economy (HL), BUSINESS TIMES  
   xfdws OPTIMISTIC-ABOUT-ECONOMY sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   BANK Negara Malaysia (BNM) remains optimistic about the
economy's outlook despite the negative growth for the first
quarter, but three factors will be crucial in determining a better
second-half performance.
	   These are a higher export level, strong fundamentals in the
banking system, and a stable ringgit.
	   Its governor, Tan Sri Ahmad Mohd Don, elaborated on these
factors at a press briefing last Saturday when asked for the bank's
economic outlook for the second half of the year.
	   He had just announced a negative 1.8 per cent growth in the
gross domestic product (GDP), the country's first negative
quarterly growth in over a decade.
	   In terms of export, Malaysia recorded a large external trade
surplus of RM8.8 billion during the first quarter due to a a
sharper decline in imports in US dollar terms. The surplus for the
corresponding period of last year was RM1.7 billion.
	   Official statistics, however, show that on a quarter-to-quarter
basis, the country's export has seen a sharp increase to RM69.8
billion in January-March 1998 from RM49 billion in January-March
1997.
	   Ahmad Don said whether the country is able to increase its
export level for the rest of the year is, therefore, paramount.
	   ``But I must also say that other (countries) affected in the
regional economic turmoil will also be trying their best to export
themselves out of the problems,'' he added.
	   Maintaining the fundamental strengths in the banking system is
an ``all- important'' factor, the governor said.
	   This is why the central bank has to ensure that financial
institutions must continue to strive to achieve the 15 per cent
loan growth target by year-end as stipulated in its credit plan, he
added.
	   Another important factor is the exchange rate of the ringgit.
	   ``In the past few months, the ringgit has been relatively
stable, although it remains vulnerable,'' Ahmad Don said.
	   The ringgit has lost 33.5 per cent of its value against the US
dollar since July last year.
	   Last Friday, the ringgit ended at 3.89 against the greenback,
compared with 2.52 at the end of June 1997.
	   The local currency has also lost significantly against the
values of other major currencies.
	   Ahmad Don said the first quarter's contraction in GDP growth
will have to be taken into account in making a forecast for the
entire 1998.
	   ``At some point in time, we may have to relook at these
numbers,'' he added.
	   The Government had announced last March a revised GDP growth
figure of between 2 per cent and 3 per cent amid the weakened
Malaysian and regional economies.
	   The January-March negative growth was attributable to various
factors.
	   On the supply side, decline in output was most apparent in the
construction, manufacturing and agriculture sectors, given the
sluggish external demand especially from the Asian market.
	   On the demand part, negative wealth effects due to asset
deflation and the rising inflation rate led to more cautious
consumer sentiment, which adversely affected private consumption.
	   Output in the manufacturing sector declined 2.4 per cent on an
annual basis compared with a 10.9 per cent growth in the last
quarter of 1997.
	   The decline was broad-based, affecting both the domestic as well
as the export-oriented industries.
	   For the construction sector, sharp slowdown in construction
activity led to the sector recording a 10 per cent decline.
	   This was due to a slowdown in implementation of the existing
infrastructure and non-residential projects and also completion of
projects associated with the forthcoming Commonwealth Games.
	   Meanwhile, inflation rose significantly in the first quarter of
1998 with the higher import prices due to the weaker ringgit being
passed down to domestic price levels, pushing the consumer price
index up by 4.3 per cent (1994  100) against 2.7 per cent increase
in the last quarter of 1997.
	   At producer level, the producer price index (PPI, 1989    100)
also
rose significantly by 14.9 per cent reflecting the higher prices of
both domestic and imported inputs.	   The overall position of the Federal Government remained in
surplus. The current and overall accounts recorded larger surpluses
of RM5.4 billion and RM4.2 billion respectively.
	   The Government's total debt declined by 2.4 per cent from the
level as at the end of 1997 to RM87.8 billion at the end of March
this year, attributed to reductions in both the domestic and
external debts.
	   
</TEXT>
