<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 14:36:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1291  wstm-
r w     HEADLINE-GRABBINGsked     06-01 1426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> HEADLINE-GRABBING sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Social impact of bail-out efforts lost in headline-grabbing figures, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws HEADLINE-GRABBING sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   WORLD Bank president James D. Wolfensohn began his Press
conference by first apologising to the journalists present for the
criticism he was about to make of the media for being too
simplistic in its reporting of the Asian financial problem.
	   The media, it seems, likes figures too much. The international
bail-out efforts of Indonesia, South Korea and Thailand have been
summarised in dollars and cents - US$45 billion here, US$50 billion
there - and not much of anything else.
	   Its pre-occupation with headline-grabbing figures, and the
righteous calls for economic and political reforms, led to the
media's inability to look into the social consequences of the
financial trouble and the bail-outs.
	   The millions who were suffering, for example, as a pre-requisite
to participation in the International Monetary Fund programmes,
were somehow lost in the debates on whether to extend loans to the
troubled economies.
	   Speaking at the Asia Pacific Economic Co-operation forum Finance
Ministers Meeting that ended in Kananaskis, Canada last week,
Wolfensohn told of the millions in Indonesia who would fall into
poverty, and whose lives would be greatly affected by food and
medicine shortages. The number of those joining the ranks of the
unemployed was also expected to balloon in the near future.
	   In Thailand, he said, the poor state of the economy was breaking
down the traditional support system resulting in the millions
returning to their villages from the cities not receiving the help
they would have had from their families. As a result, crime and
child prostitution were now on the rise, he said.
	   In South Korea, the fragile truce between the trade union,
government and businesses needed for the implementation of the IMF
programme was showing signs of cracks. That could lead to social
chaos.
	   While the economic woes in these countries were the root of the
problems, they nevertheless could be alleviated if the
international efforts to rescue them had spared some thought to
people on the street.
	   Debates on the pros and cons of giving the loans took the high
ground, criticising governments for the way they do things and
demanding reforms before help could be given, while in the lower
rung of society, the people suffered.
	   In Indonesia, for example, the IMF insistence that the food and
fuel subsidies be removed, as they were economically unsustainable
and unsound, resulted in rioting in the streets that saw about 500
people dead.
	   Regardless of whatever romantic notions one might have on the
uprising - that people took to the streets to rid the country of
cronyism, nepotim, collusion or corruption - it was food and fuel
that led to the burning and looting.
	   A hungry mob, after all, is an angry mob.
	   Wolfensohn was not alone in expressing his regret. The cool
setting at the lodge in Kananaskis at the foot of the Canadian
Rockies where this year's meeting was held could not escape the
rioting and death in Indonesia. They served as constant reminders
that, in the end, decisions in high places, no matter how noble,
sometimes have their own peculiar spin on the masses.
	   Apec Finance Ministers in their final statement recognised that
any rescue effort has to have a heart. It must be tempered with the
need to take care of the poor and needy who were already badly hit
by any economic trouble, and would suffer more in any adjustment
programme.
	   Even the IMF agreed that some of its measures were harsh, said
Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim who represented
Malaysia at the meeting.
	   Camdessus, he said, agreed that IMF would continue to be
flexible with its programmes to make sure that the hardest hit
would not be much worse off.
	   It was not as if the IMF was extracting its pound of flesh from
the Indonesians, it was just that no one foresaw how bad the effect
of the measures, as they trickle down the system, would be on the
people.
	   They nevertheless served as sombre reminders that while bitter
medicine might sometimes be called for, to quote Camdessus who was
also at the meeting, the treatment must not be so harsh as to wreak
havoc on the body.
	   The medical anology had been used many times to justify the
actions taken by the IMF. It is true that within its own field of
competence such harsh measures were the only recourse. But care
must be taken to make the medicine go down easier.
	   Nevertheless, Anwar said the international community must assist
the IMF, either through bilateral measures or through agencies like
the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank, whose functions were
more suited for social programmes, while it was the IMF's job to
help turn around economies.
	   Anwar also took to task countries like the US, that wanted to
see more being done in Indonesia before it could support the
resumption of IMF loans, which had since been suspended, to the
country.
	   The Deputy Prime Minister, who became the unofficial spokesman
for Indonesia at the meeting since the country was only represented
by its ambassador to Canada, said he believed there was a genuine
attempt by President B.J. Habibie to undertake economic and social
reforms, and he should be given as much support as possible.
	   The US should not expect immediate reform from Indonesia; it
took the US more than 100 years to carry out similar reforms, he
said.
	   While the situation in Indonesia dominated the meeting, the
general financial health of Apec member economies was also
discussed at length, including trying to identify ways to minimise
the possibility of the Asian financial downturn recurring.
	   It was generally agreed that, currency speculators and
manipulators notwithstanding, the slowdown was caused by the weak
macroeconomic environment in the affected countries. Unsustainable
policies coupled with poor governance and the dependence on foreign
money made them vulnerable.
	   The Kananaskis meeting agreed that increased surveillance of the
macroeconomic conditions of countries be established, either
through peer pressure, or a regional or global monitoring body. The
ministers also agreed to continue looking at how best to deal with
the influx of short-term capital flows. Though welcome, they had
the tendency to disrupt economies as was seen in the days leading
to the regional financial difficulty.
	   The Finance Ministers also agreed to look at an initiative of
the Apec financiers, made up of the private sector of member
economies, for the development of domestic and regional bond
markets as an alternative to raising funds for business and
development.
	   The over-dependence on short-term debts, where credit lines were
easily recalled, had been the downfall of many business in the
region. Long-term debts like bonds were less likely to be withdrawn
and would be more consistent.
	   Incidentally, there are two versions of how Kananaskis got its
name.
	   The first, rather appropriately, means a meeting place in the
local Indian dialect.
	   The other, the fable goes, the place is named after a Indian
named Kananaskis. Apparently, while chopping wood he injured
himself badly in the head and people thought he would not make it.
But he miraculously recovered, and in honour of the magical
recovery, they name the river and lake nearby after him.
	   Perhaps the Canadians were thinking of the good vibes of the
place, rather than its beautiful setting, in deciding to hold the
meeting there.
	   Some of the injuries to the troubled Asian economies seemed
self-inflicted, but many believe that they would emerge stronger
over time.
	   For that no miracle will be necessary, only hard work.
	   
</TEXT>
