<SLUG> BC-Venezuela-OAS,0364 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Citing `new climate,' OAS president says Cuba could be readmitted ANA CAROLINA GRIFFIN 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photo CAR102
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) _ A ``new climate'' created by Pope John
Paul II's visit earlier this year to Cuba is making it more likely
that the communist-run island may rejoin the Organization of
American States, the OAS secretary-general said Monday.
	   ``It's clear for everyone that since the visit of John Paul II
to the island a new climate has been created in which this issue
can be addressed in a more constructive manner,'' Cesar Gaviria
said in opening the OAS' 28th general assembly.
	   If economic and political liberties and respect for human rights
are broadened on the island, ``it will be possible to consider the
return of Cuba to the Inter-American system,'' said Gaviria, the
former president of Colombia.
	   Mexico's foreign secretary, Rosario Green, suggested that a
``group of friends'' of Latin American nations be formed to help
resolve the issue.
	   Cuba was thrown out of the OAS in 1962 after strong pressure
from the United States, which accused Castro of supporting leftist
rebel groups in Latin America.
	   While not mentioning the United States directly, Gaviria seemed
to criticize the U.S. hard-line stance against Cuba.
	   ``Many of us would like to see applied to this problem the type
of diplomacy, negotiation and gradualism that have been effective
in other regions,'' he said.
	   U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, a fierce critic of
Cuban President Fidel Castro, is scheduled to attend the OAS
meeting Tuesday.
	   Delegates cannot make a decision on the issue because Cuba has
not requested readmission to the OAS. However, pressure could be
built up for later addressing the issue officially.
	   Castro has enjoyed a string of recent political victories,
including the visit of Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien and
the re-establishment of diplomatic ties with the Dominican Republic
and Guatemala.
	   The three-day OAS meeting also is expected to address subjects
including poverty, drug trafficking, corrupt justice systems and
consolidating democracy. 	   
</TEXT>
