r w     SINGTEL-TO-TAKE-UP-40PCs     06-01 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> SINGTEL-TO-TAKE-UP-40PC sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
SingTel `to take up 40pc stake' in Binariang, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws SINGTEL-TO-TAKE-UP-40PC sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   BINARIANG Bhd, in a surprise move, is believed to have
successfully wooed Singapore Telecom Ltd to be its second foreign
equity partner.
	   The deal - which was to be deliberated on by the Binariang board
of directors yesterday evening - is said to be worth about RM1.4
billion.
	   Officials at Binariang declined comment on the deal - which is
expected to see SingTel taking up a 40 per cent stake in the
telecommunications firm.
	   As existing foreign partner US West International will still
hold its 19.8 per cent stake in Binariang, this deal will be the
first to see foreign equity in a local telecommunications firm
exceed 50 per cent.
	   This is however subject to there being no change to Binariang's
paid-up capital.
	   Should there be new issue of Binariang shares to SingTel, the
overall foreign equity structure could be lower and the existing
local majority shareholder - Tunku Burhanuddin's Trust Fund - may
still remain the single largest shareholder.
	   The Government recently raised the maximum for foreign equity in
a telecommunciations firm to 61 per cent, up sharply from the
previous cap of 49 per cent.
	   However, the 61 per cent cap is subject to total foreign equity
being scaled back to 49 per cent within a five-year period.
	   Analysts said the deal could be good for Binariang as it
represents much-needed cash infusion into the company - believed to
have been facing cash-flow problems in terms of funding capital
expansions.
	   Despite a strong revenue base from its Maxis cellular subscriber
base - which passed the 360,000 mark early this year - Binariang
had to suspend its fixed-line expansion plans this year due to the
property sector slowdown.
	   This fixed line expansion represents a long-term growth strategy
for Binariang and also for its sister company, Measat Broadcasting
Sdn Bhd, which operates the cable television network Astro.
	   With the fixed-line infrastructure - including fibre optic cable
connections -Astro programmes can be pumped directly into
subscribers' homes without need for the VSAT (very small aperture
terminal) dish.
	   The analyst said SingTel's involvement could further assist
Binariang in expanding its subscriber base for Astro to Singapore
and the rest of the region.
	   Also, SingTel has a number of investments in foreign
telecommunications firms abroad and the tie-up could see more
optimum usage of Binariang's two communications satellites - Measat
I and II.
	   
</TEXT>
