<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Good money in dried squids business, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws GOOD-MONEY-IN-DRIED sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   PROFITABLE ENTERPRISE ... Not many people realise that dried
squids which are considered delicacies by some, are produced mostly
in Terengganu, mainly in Marang, Kuala Terengganu and Besut.
	   Mohd Yusof Muda, 45, a dried squid producer and supplier in
Kampung Air Tawar, Kuala Besut, said unlike fish which are caught
only at certain times of the year, squids are available year round
even during the wet seasons.
	   His son-in-law, Fadzil Zabidi Zakaria (picture), helps him in
the business.
	   ``There's hardly a time where we cannot get squids and that is
why I have sufficient supply to meet the customers' demands,'' Mohd
Yusof said.
	   During the peak season, he would process up to 300 kilogrammes
of squids daily. That happens between January and October when
fishermen will have abundant harvests of squids.
	   Each kilogramme of squid normally costs between RM7 and RM8
while the dried ones cost RM40 per kg, he said.
	   He said that to produce dried squids, one only had to cut and
clean them before putting them to dry.
	   ``However, to retain their natural flavour, the squids must be
thoroughly washed with sea water before being dried,'' he added.
	   Mohd Yusof, who has been in the business for 13 years, said
during the rainy season, the squids would be processed in a smoke
house where they were left to dry over a slow fire.
	   He said besides selling the product in the district, he also
supplied the dried squids to Penang, Malacca, Johor and Negri
Sembilan.
	   
</TEXT>
