<BODY>
<SLUG> RE-TRAINING-PROGRAMME sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Re-training programme `only for contributors to fund', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws RE-TRAINING-PROGRAMME sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - The Human Resources Development Council's
re-training programme is meant strictly for workers retrenched or
expected to be laid off by employers who have contributed to the
fund, Human Resources Minister Datuk Lim Ah Lek said today.
	   ``There is no move by the HRDC to expand the programme to those
who have not joined the work force yet,'' he told a Press
conference after he opened the MCA Youth 35th annual general
assembly at the Tunku Abdul Rahman College.
	   He said the council had set aside RM5 million for the
re-training programme and those who had lost their jobs or were
about to be retrenched could apply for re-training.
	   ``These programmes would give the retrenched workers added value
to their careers,'' he said, adding that it would be unfair to open
it up to everyone.
	   The Human Resource Development Fund was set up whereby
participating companies, particularly manufacturers, contributed
one per cent of their payroll to the fund.
	   ``As trustee, our concern is to ensure that those affected by
the economic problems would be given priority,'' said Lim.
	   Lim also reiterated that the ministry would review the ``no levy
collection'' for six months for the fund which took effect from
March, this year.
	   He said since the HRDF was set up, more than 1.7 million workers
had been re-trained to upgrade their skills.
	   ``We are also getting a lot of applications from training
providers to take part in training programmes,'' he added.
	   Lim said even the World Bank had acknowledged that the HRDF was
an important component in helping to upgrade workers' skill and to
help improve career prospects.
	   He reiterated that the highly-disciplined workforce in the
country had helped the country in facing the economic problems.
	   ``Credit must also be given to the trade unions who prefer to
settle disputes and problems through negotiations,'' he added.
	   Unlike other countries facing the same problems, Lim said, there
were no industrial disputes to disrupt the Government's move to
tackle the economic downturn through various tough measures.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
