<HEADER>
w1313  wstm-
r w     TRAINING-SCHEME'S-SUCCES     06-01 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> TRAINING-SCHEME'S-SUCCES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Support of construction sector vital to training scheme's success, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws TRAINING-SCHEME'S-SUCCES sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE move by the Construction Industry Development Board to
provide free short-term courses to Sijil Pelajaran Malaysia
students who failed to obtain a place in institutions of higher
learning is commendable and timely.
	   With thousands of SPM holders failing to get a place in local
higher learning institutions, the courses come as a ray of hope for
several hundred students interested in a career in building
construction.
	   Although CIDB can only offer its scholarships to fewer than 500
students, it is still an effort as it will have to spend about
RM3,000 per trainee or about RM150,000 from its own funds.
	   The objective of providing free courses is multi-pronged. The
main intention is to attract SPM school-leavers who have an
interest in building construction but do not have the qualification
to pursue their ambition in higher learning institutions.
	   The second objective is fulfilling its social obligation. By
holding such courses, CIDB would be doing its part in attracting
youths into a sector (building construction) which provides a lot
of job opportunities rather than allowing them to loaf or be
engaged in other unproductive activities.
	   Thirdly, CIDB hopes the course could provide the foundation for
these trainees to pursue higher professional courses related to
building construction, including civil engineering.
	   Finally, CIDB also hopes to build a register of skilled building
construction workers. This will enable the board to become a
reference centre or an employment agency for the construction
sector which could supply skilled workers to contractors.
	   CIDB chief excutive Datuk Abdul Rahman Abdullah said under the
training programme, which is expected to be introduced early next
year, selected students would be trained at six of the Akademi
Binaan Malaysia (ABM) training centres located in Selangor, Perak,
Johor, Terengganu, Sabah and Sarawak.
	   Trainees would have to go through three to six months of basic
building construction courses. They have a choice of 58 modules,
including how to operate mobile cranes, brick laying and handling
scaffolding.
	   ``The students will be given certificates. With it, the trainees
will have a better chance of securing jobs in the construction
sector. It will also enable them to pursue higher education in
related fields.
	   ``If we do not offer this course, the students will have to seek
jobs in the construction sector first and hope that their employers
will send them for training at ABM later.''
	   At the moment, CIDB accepts employees in the construction
industry for training at ABM. The training fee, ranging from
RM2,000 to RM3,000, is paid by the employers. Those who complete
the course are given competence certificates to acknowledge the
level of professionalism in the respective fields.
	   Although the facilities at the ABM training centres are still
inadequate, they are more than sufficient to meet the requirements
for basic training.
	   In this respect, CIDB is also working closely with other skills
training centres in the country such as the Terengganu Advance
Training Institute in Kemaman and the Terengganu Skills Development
Centre in Kuala Terengganu.
	   ``We need all the help we can. We have to put on hold our plans
to provide tower cranes or other expensive equipment at the ABM
training centres at the moment due to the current economic
situation.
	   ``But this does not mean that we don't have any training
equipment at the ABM training centres. In fact, our plan to
co-operate with skills training centres is aimed at overcoming this
problem in the short term.
	   ``We also plan to provide twinning programmes with local and
foreign higher learning institutions to ensure that our trainees
get the best in skills training.''
	   On paper, the plans by the CIDB look realistic as it involves
the development of manpower from the basic stage to the
professional stage, as well as registration of manpower for the
construction sector.
	   However, to be successful, it has to receive the support of
players in the the construction sector. They could at least share
the cost of providing the training equipment and machines used by
workers.
	   The industry has to realise that what CIDB is doing is for the
sake of the industry, especially in improving the professionalism
and skills of manpower required in the construction sector.
	   With more trained and skilled manpower, industries will no
longer have to look abroad for good workers, reducing foreign
exchange loss. The CIDB will have a registry of local workers that
it can supply to contractors.
	   Another training programme which deserves to be commended is the
one endorsed by the Electricity and Gas Department, which involves
the training of chargemen by industries.
	   Under this programme, the State Economic Planning Unit
shortlists the candidates for training and pays part of the
allowances during the six-month training period.
	   Industries which accept these trainees will provide on-the-job
training and those who excel are given certificates endorsed by the
department.
	   In Terengganu, companies such as Perwaja Steel, Metro Pacific,
Permint Plywood, The New Straits Times Press (M) Berhad, Gunawan
Iron and Steel and the Marang Safari  Resort, have participated in
such training schemes and benefited from them.
	   ``Those who received the certificates but declined the offer to
work with their host companies can easily secure a job as chargeman
in other companies as there are over 5,000 vacancies,'' said
director-general of the department, Datuk Mohd Anas Mohd Nor.
	   
</TEXT>
