<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Brewery logo doesn't promote beer, says RTD, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws BREWERY-LOGO-PROMOTE sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - The Road Transport Department today said
using the name of a brewery in a Commonwealth Games publicity
campaign on buses and taxis, would not promote drinking.
	   Its director-general Datuk Pahamin Rajab said: ``It is not an
advertisement for alcoholic drinks but just one which carries the
name of the Carlsberg company, which is one of the sponsors of the
Games.
	   ``As you notice, there is no picture of a bottle of Carlsberg or
any word extolling its superiority or that drinking is good,'' he
said, adding that the company also produces non-alcoholic drinks
like Nutrimalt.
	   Personally, Pahamin said he did not think that one would
immediately turn into an alcoholic after looking at the
advertisement.
	   He was speaking at a Press conference called to clarify the
controversy which arose following objections from several quarters,
including the Malaysian Youth Council, over the move by Sukom
Ninety Eight Bhd to collaborate with Carlsberg in promoting the
September Games.
	   Pahamin hoped the issue would not be politicised as the decision
to allow the advertisement did not mean that the Government, RTD,
Sukom or the Youth and Sports Ministry were encouraging people to
drink.
	   Yesterday, Sukom Ninety Eight Bhd executive chairman Tan Sri
Hashim Mohd Ali and Games village mayor Datuk Dr Ibrahim Saad said
the advertisement did not contravene any law as it was aimed more
at promoting the Games and not the company's products.
	   On whether the guidelines on advertisement on commercial
vehicles were vague and needed to be reviewed, Pahamin said
coincidently, a review was expected to be completed within three
months.
	   He said the department planned to turn the guidelines into
rules, which would enable stricter action to be taken against cases
of non-compliance like offenders being slapped with compounds.
	   At present, the department can only direct advertisements on
commercial vehicles to be withdrawn if they fail to follow
procedures.
	   He said views and response from the public and non-governmental
organisations, especially following this latest controversy, would
be considered in the review.
	   On action against Singaporean drivers who failed to settle their
traffic summonses, Pahamin said RTD was studying the best way to
handle the matter.
	   When it was pointed out enforcement could be made more effective
by linking up the RTD computers with those at the Immigration
Department, Pahamin said this would be the ideal solution.
	   However, he said this could not be realised at the moment as the
Immigration Department was not fully computerised yet.
	   
</TEXT>
