<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Argentina, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Argentina seeks contracts under Iraq's U.N. oil deal 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: CORRECTS Argentine official's name throughout
<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Argentina is seeking contracts to sell Iraq
food items under the U.N. approved oil-for-food deal, the official
Iraqi News Agency reported Monday.
	   It said a senior Iraqi foreign ministry official, Marcelo
Avogadro, met with Iraq's Trade Minister Mohammed Mehdi Saleh on
Monday to discuss ways of expanding bilateral trade.
	   ``The possibility of Argentine companies getting contracts under
the next phase of the oil-for-food deal was reviewed,'' INA said.
	   The deal allows Iraq to sell a limited quantity of oil every six
month to help it overcome shortages caused by U.N. economic
sanctions imposed after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait. Iraq can sell
up to dlrs 5.2 billion worth oil in the latest phase beginning June
3, instead of dlrs 2 billion worth permitted in previous phases.
	   Iraq plans to use dlrs 3 billion for buying food, medicines and
other humanitarian goods from the oil revenue, up from dlrs 1.3
billion it used to spend every six months in the earlier phases of
the deal.
	   INA quoted Avogadro as saying that Argentina want contracts to
supply Iraq with wheat, maize and cooking oil. Avogadro is the
undersecretary for trade relations in his ministry.
	   According to U.N. figures Argentina sold commodities worth dlrs
7 million to Iraq in the past 18 months.
  lb/vj
</TEXT>
