<BODY>
<SLUG> MINISTRY-TO-INTENSIFY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Ministry to intensify organ pledge campaign, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws MINISTRY-TO-INTENSIFY sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - The Health Ministry will intensify its
campaign for more organ donation pledges from Malaysians while
working out legal and ethical issues surrounding the process.
	   Health Minister Datuk Chua Jui Meng said today lack of donors
was hampering the development of an effective national organ
transplantation programme, although the country had the capability
to conduct such ``miracle'' operations.
	   ``We have received more than 10,000 organ donation pledges from
the public, of which more than 8,000 were made through the National
Kidney Foundation and the rest with the Kuala Lumpur Hospital's
Organ Transplantation Resource Centre.
	   ``However, our cadaveric kidney donation rate is still low -
less than 0.5 per million population in Malaysia,'' he said when
opening the Malaysian Society of Transplantation's third annual
meeting at the National Heart Institute.
	   Comparatively, he said, the rate was about 40 per million
population in countries such as Australia, Belgium, Spain and
Portugal, and about 30 per million in the United States and United
Kingdom.
	   Chua said the Ministry's National Transplantation Co-ordination
Committee during a meeting last March 5, had set up five
sub-committees, to handle professional issues, public education,
ethics and law, registration as well as planning and promotion.
	   Chaired by Health director-general Tan Sri Dr Abu Bakar Suleiman
and supported by professional groups, non-governmental
organisations, universities, private hospitals and religious
groups, the committee will next meet on June 18.
	   Chua said the country had seen 663 local kidney transplants
carried out from 1975 to the end of last year, 25 liver transplants
performed since 1995 and three heart transplants as of April this
year.
	   ``Organ transplants have dramatically improved the quality of
life for end-stage organ failure patients,'' he said, adding that
they freed patients from tedious and expensive treatments such as
dialysis, daily injections and intravenous feeding.
	   However, he said the Government would strive to ensure donated
organs do not become a commodity here as opposed to how organ
transplants have become a commercial activity in certain countries.
	   Chua said information of potential donors would eventually be
forwarded to Kuala Lumpur Hospital to be compiled in a centralised
database, to prevent the organ donation process from experiencing
``hiccups.''
	   On rumours that Viagra pills were available in Malaysia, Chua
advised the public to be careful as the pills being sold locally
were probably fake and could have harmful effects.
	   He said the Pharmaceutical Services Division was compiling
information about the drug, which is reported to address the
problem of impotence but is not yet registered in Malaysia.
	   He said if and when Viagra was to be registered, it would only
be dispensed by prescription, enabling the physician to monitor the
patient's condition as well as any other medication he might be
taking.
	   
</TEXT>
