<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Isetan braves the slowdown, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws ISETAN-BRAVES sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   DESPITE discouraging retail sales, Japanese department store
Isetan is opening a five-floor outlet at the newly-opened Suria
Kuala Lumpur City Centre shopping mall.
	   Even in these gloomy times, this flagship store aspires to be
international in its outlook, offering ``a total lifestyle
experience'' to trendsetting 20 to 34-year-olds.
	   From fashion and accessories, household and food to books and
stationery, Isetan says it believes in ``celebrating the individual
and offering something for everyone in every aspect of their
lives.''
	   Among the interesting labels to look out for, which
unfortunately are rather pricey, are funky fashion by New
York-based Korean designer Anna Sui, Alberta Ferretti's Philosophy
from Milan, Lawrence Steel from London and Hackett. Other leading
labels available are Donna Karan's DKNY, Gianni Versace's Versus,
Calvin Klein's cK and Polo Ralph Lauren.
	   Joining these notable names are the store's in-house brands like
Gillian Hung, Total Women, Crescendo, Cicada, City, Generation X
and Cultivation.
	   One of the sought-after names in professional make-up, Bobbi
Brown, has set up a reasonably big counter in the store's cosmetics
section. Brown, whose make-up principle is about looking pretty,
naturally has a cult following worldwide. But Brown's beauty comes
with a price - it's said that her stick foundation sells at US$30
each in America.
	   Another big name is professional skincare and bodycare brand
Biotherm from France. It is said to be between 10 and 15 per cent
cheaper than a leading American label, one of its main rivals.
	   With five floors covering 77,000 square metres of retail space,
Isetan KLCC is twice the size of its Lot 10 store in Jalan Sultan
Ismail, Kuala Lumpur.
	   Ladies' apparel is on the concourse floor, designer boutiques,
sundries and cosmetics are on the ground floor while men's wear,
sundries and sportswear can be found on the first floor.
	   On the second floor, there are a variety of items like
children's apparel, jewellery, watches, optical articles, gifts,
books and stationery. At the top level, the third floor, shoppers
will find the supermarket and household items. Having this section
on the top floor is unique to Isetan since its survey showed that
customers usually shop in this department last.
	   Shoppers are offered services such as alterations, laundry, gift
wrapping, photo processing and a duty-free shop.
	   Facilities include a golf practice range, nursery room as well
as The Gallery on the first floor which promotes local artwork.
	   
</TEXT>
