<SLUG> HIJACKED-SHIP'S-CREW sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Hijacked ship's crew sails home, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws HIJACKED-SHIP'S-CREW sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - Seven Malaysians, part of a 21-man crew
onboard a Malaysian-registered ship, Petro Ranger, sailed home
yesterday, about a month after the vessel was detained by Chinese
authorities in connection with an alleged pirate attack in the
South China Sea.
	   The fuel tanker was held at the Haikou Port since it was
intercepted by the Chinese maritime authorities on April 26.
	   Following the vessel's release, the Malaysians and other crew
members left the port in Hainan island for Singapore about 4pm.
	   The Malaysians crew members were identified as Saravanan
Subramanian, Mohamed Nazri Selamat, Abdul Kadir Soad, Sani Anak
Ugie, Mohd Faizal Mohd Ghazali, Mohd Shizul Khan M. Razali and Mohd
Samsuri Abdul Kadir.
	   The other crew onboard the vessel were six Indonesians, four
Bangladeshies, a Ghanaian, a Filipino, a Myanmar and the ship's
captain, Kenneth Blyth, an Australian.
	   Chinese authorities reported they had detained a gang of 12
Indonesians - believed to have boarded the vessel off the coast of
China -in connection with the hijack of the ship to smuggle its
cargo into the country.
	   When contacted at his office in Beijing today, Malaysian
Ambassador to China, Datuk Abdul Majid Ahmad Khan, said the ship
and the crew set sail for Singapore yesterday.
	   ``All the crew aboard the vessel, including the Malaysians, were
released by the Chinese authorities,'' he said.
	   The International Maritime Bureau had sought the assistance of
the Malaysian Embassy after the bureau's officials and the ship's
agent, Petroships of Singapore, were denied access to board the
vessel.
	   The crew members were also barred from leaving the vessel
although they were allowed to post letters to their families,
through the embassy.
	   On April 16, the Petro Ranger disappeared during a voyage from
Singapore to Ho Chi Minh City in Vietnam after it was alleged to
have come under pirate attack.
	   It was transporting 11,000 tonnes of diesel and kerosene when
the incident occurred.
	   Meanwhile, Petroships of Singapore's maritime superintendent,
Capt Johnny Liew, when contacted in Singapore, said Petro Ranger
was expected to arrive in the republic by the middle of next week.
	   He said the 12 Indonesians, arrested by the Chinese authorities,
were being held to assist in the probe.
	   
</TEXT>
