<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Consumers International criticises labelling body, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws CONSUMERS-INTERNATIONAL sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   PENANG, Fri. - Consumers International today criticised the
Codex Food Labelling Committee, a body of the United Nations Codex
Alimentarius Commission that sets food standards, for failing to
ensure labelling of genetically engineered food.
	   It said the four-day committee meeting held in Ottawa, Canada,
that ended today was important to consumer organisations concerned
about such food in the world market.
	   Its regional director for Asia and Pacific, Josie Fernandez said
this meant that much of the genetically modified food sold in
supermarkets would not have to be labelled as such.
	   Genetic engineering can change nutritional value or create
problems that offend religious obligations, she said.
	   She said, for example, Muslims could not eat lamb or other food
products containing pig genes and vegetarians wanted to know
whether such food contained genes from animals and Hindus would
want to ascertain whether they contained genes of cows.
	   Josie said most consumers would certainly want to know if human
genes were used in any of the food they ate.
	   ``In this context, the Malaysian Ministry of Health needs to
state the actions being taken with regard to inter/cross-splicing
of animal, human, virus, bacteria and plant genes into various
food, crops, and drugs.''
	   
</TEXT>
