<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Mir, 5th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mir computer working again steering system. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with crew trying to reactivate
AP Photos MOSB101,103.
By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The central computer on board Mir was working
again Monday night, after a three-day breakdown that threatened to
postpone the Russian space station's last rendezvous with a U.S.
shuttle.
	   That enabled the Mir crew to begin the long process of
reactivating the station's automatic steering system, said Valery
Lyndin, a spokesman for Russian Mission Control. The shuttle can
only dock with Mir when the steering system keeps it properly
aligned.
	   The space shuttle Discovery is scheduled to lift off Tuesday and
dock with the station Friday to pick up astronaut Andrew Thomas,
the seventh and last American to live on the Russian outpost.
	   Lyndin said space officials have not yet determined why Mir's
computer broke down on Saturday. Russian cosmonauts Talgat
Musabayev and Nikolai Budarin replaced it with another unit, but
the new unit failed on Sunday when they tried to switch it on.
	   Ground controllers fully loaded the software into the computer
Monday night, and the crew was able to get it working again within
about 90 minutes. Reactivating the steering system can take an
entire day.
	   During a chat with ground controllers during the repair process,
Musabayev said the situation on board ``isn't bad'' but added that
he was concerned that it occurred on the eve of the shuttle's
launch. ``I'm worried not for myself, but for the flight program,''
he said.
	   Mir's computer repeatedly failed last year, prompting Russian
space officials to send up a replacement on a shuttle ferry flight
in January. That unit failed on Saturday after five months of
trouble-free operation. The station's crew has replaced it with a
back-up computer brought up by a Russian cargo ship.
	   Mir's main computer operates the station's motion control
system, and when it fails, the station's energy supply is
threatened because it can't keep its solar panels in optimum
alignment with the sun.
	   Depending on how much energy was lost, it can take from one to
three days to get the orientation system fully on-line.
	   Fortunately, when the latest trouble occurred, the station was
on the so-called solar orbit, which puts it in direct sunlight
round the clock. As a result, the Mir's solar panels have remained
in full sunlight.
	   The crew also shut down some systems to save energy, and as a
result Mir's batteries were full on Monday, making it easier for
the crew to restore the orientation system, Lyndin said.
	   Russia plans to bring down the 12-year-old Mir at the end of
1999 after the first parts of the international space station are
in orbit.
	   A Russian-manufactured propulsion system, is supposed to be
launched in November. But Russia's contributions to the station
have been delayed repeatedly because of financial problems.
	   A service module for the station to be supplied by Russia is
nearly ready for testing, the Interfax news agency reported.
	   A satellite communications system and a computer will be
installed in the module before it is sent to the Baikonur launch
site in Kazakstan, where it will be launched in April of next year,
the report said.
	   (vi/mr/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Russia-Mir, 5th Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
