w1333  wstm-
u i     BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 5thLd-Writethru   06-01 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 5th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
More deaths reported in Kosovo; thousands flee 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with scene in Tropoja, refugee quotes; trims
By ISMET HAJDARI
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Refugees from Serbia's Kosovo
province streamed into neighboring Albania in unprecedented numbers
on Monday amid reports of dozens of people killed and some trapped
by the worst fighting in months.
	   With 39 people reported killed over the weekend, and fighting
apparently continuing, the bloodshed seemed the worst since early
March, when Serbian police killed more than 80 people in a
crackdown on independence-minded militants and their families.
	   In New York, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard spoke of ``heavy and
indiscriminate shelling'' of some Kosovo Albanian villages near the
border to Albania. He said U.N. workers could see heavy mortars
being fired into the villages.
	   Refugees talking to The Associated Press on the Albanian side of
the border said one three-year old had died on the way and that
they had heard second hand of infants inadvertently suffocated by
parents who had covered their mouths and noses to stop them from
crying and giving away their location to Serb forces.
	   Ethnic Albanian officials said 37 Albanians had been killed over
the weekend. Twenty-seven died in clashes in Decani while 10 were
killed when Serb police stormed a village elsewhere, they said.
	   Two Serb policemen also died in the fighting around Decani, 75
kilometers (45 miles) west of the regional capital Pristina, Serb
sources said.
	   The latest fierce fighting prompted about 2,000 Kosovo Albanians
to leave the troubled region and cross over into Albania's Tropoja
(pronounced Tro-POH-yah) region Sunday and Monday, Albanian
authorities said. They said more were arriving by the hour.
	   In Tropoja, some of the hundreds of refugees in the town itself
_ most of them old, young or women _ said they had walked for up to
20 hours to reach the Albanian town. They said Serb tanks were
positioned inside Decani, and said some of the Serb forces
besieging the town wore black uniforms.
	   Tropoja, although some 5 kilometers (3 miles) inside Albanian
territory, resembled a community under siege, with most of the men
carrying rifles or other weapons.
	   Some of them displayed the insignia of the Kosovo Liberation
Army, the militant Kosovo organization spearheading the fight
against Serbia.
	   Andrew Harper, the representative of the main U.N. refugee
agency, said he had purchased three tons of flour, rice and other
basics on the local market to provide for the refugees, and more
aid was expected from Tirana, the Albanian capital, on Tuesday.
	   Still, some questioned if it would be enough.
	   ``I am very worried about providing for all these people,'' said
Isa Memia, the town leader. ``We have grave (supply) problems
ourselves, but they are our kinsmen, and we will help them.''
	   Eckhard, the U.N. spokesman, called the refugee flow ``the
largest such exodus to date.''
	   He said that 1,300 people fled to Tropoja town on Sunday alone
and cited reports that some people were ``trapped and cannot cross
the border.''
	   Refugees already in Tropoja said about 1,000 more were still on
the Kosovo side of the border hills and were expected to cross
Tuesday.
	   In a statement, the Albanian government called on the United
States and the European Union to intervene to end ``the massacre in
Kosovo.''
	   Authorities in Serbia, which with Montenegro comprises all that
remains of the Yugoslav federation, are trying to block Kosovo's
independence bid. They are using Serbian police and the Yugoslav
army to try to crush militants and maintain control over the
province, where 90 percent of the population of 2.2 million is
ethnic Albanian.
	   More than 200 people have died in Kosovo clashes since the
beginning of March. An estimated 50 percent of the Serbian province
is controlled by militant Albanians and many regions are blocked
off, either by Serbs or Albanians.
	   The Kosovo Information Center, close to the ethnic Albanian
leadership, released the names of the 10 people it said were killed
Sunday when Serb police stormed the village of Poklek, 25
kilometers (15 miles) west of Pristina. It said one had had his
throat slit.
	   According to the Albanians' account, Serb police burst into
Poklek houses, pulled out villagers and told them to ``go to
Albania and never return.''
	   Afterward, Serb police allegedly set 26 homes ablaze.
	   All phone lines remained disconnected Monday between Pristina
and the hot-spots of Decani, Klina and Djakovica. In Pristina,
about 10,000 ethnic Albanians, including 2,000 children, marched to
protest Serbian rule.
	   (pvs/md/gj) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 5th Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
