<HEADER>
w1334  wstm-
r w     ENSURING-ENOUGH-WATERske     06-01 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> ENSURING-ENOUGH-WATER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Ensuring enough water supply for all, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws ENSURING-ENOUGH-WATER sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - The Selangor Waterworks Department today
said it would further improve the water distribution process under
the current rationing scheme to ensure supply reached everyone.
	   ``We will try to do this by opening valves to higher areas first
before opening those to the low-lying areas,'' said the
department's deputy director V. Subramaniam during a Press
conference at the department headquarters.
	   As a result, he urged people who do not receive water through
their pipes continuously to report the matter to the department so
that it could rectify the situation.
	   Subramaniam said although this would create a lot more work for
his staff, who were already stretched to the limit, the move was
necessary to ensure that everyone got their supply.
	   Such adjustments have been successfully implemented for
residents in Bukit Gasing and Puchong Jaya in Selangor, who are now
getting water as scheduled.
	   Besides valve manipulation, Subramaniam said repairing broken
and leaking pipes could also help increase the efficiency of water
supply.
	   He said the department had managed to improve its response time
to reports of damaged pipes.
	   He said the public should not damage the department's
installations or use more water than necessary because this might
prevent areas on higher grounds from getting water.
	   ``Unlike electricity, water takes time to travel when the valves
are opened. Low lying areas will have to be satisfied first,
including filling up all the pails and tanks, before it moves to
higher ground.''
	   Subramaniam also said the levels at the Semenyih and Langat dams
had dropped further as water had been released to maintain water
production at the Sungai Semenyih, Sungai Langat, Cheras and Ampang
intake treatment plants at 70 per cent.
	   ``We will keep monitoring the situation and will inform the
public of any decisions.''
	   Subramaniam said the department was still considering the steps
to be taken under the contingency plan if the water levels at the
dams fell to ``critical''.
	   ``We are looking at other options besides just cutting down the
rationing hours,'' he said.
	   Meanwhile, Selangor State Information and Information Technology
Committee chairman Datuk Sharif Jajang, said the forum to be held
on June 3 would only create more confusion over the issue among the
public. The seminar was organised by the Federation of Malaysian
Consumers Associations on the water crisis Sharif, who is also the
Industry and Investments Committee chairman, said the public
already had adequate information on the facts of the water problem
and as a result, need not attend the forum.
	   ``This is especially so when the Selangor State Government,
Selangor Waterworks Department and Puncak Niaga (M) Sdn Bhd are not
attending the forum,'' he said at the same Press conference.
	   He said all three parties were not attending although Fomca had
claimed that the representatatives of the three parties and Indah
Water Konsortium Sdn Bhd would attend the forum.
	   He said the department would meet with Fomca on June 2 to
discuss issues relating to the water problems and seek ways in
which the organisation could help under present circumstances.
	   
</TEXT>
