<TEXT>
	   SEREMBAN, Fri. - Pupils of SK King George V became a privileged
lot when they received 50 copies of the New Straits Times in
conjunction with the Kuala Lumpur Mutual Fund Future Grads contest.
	   The school was among those selected to be the recipient of
copies of the NST, the official newspaper for the contest.
	   KLMF Seremban senior branch manager Chooi Chan Yen handed over
the newspapers to the senior assistant of the school, Maria Teoh,
and her Standard Five and Six pupils at the school.
	   ``The contribution will encourage the younger generation to get
into the habit of reading English newspapers so that they can have
a better command of the language,'' he said.
	   The school's English teacher Caroline Wood said her pupils had
shown keen interest in taking part and more than 200 of them had
asked for the entry forms.
	   ``This contest would enrich the pupils' knowledge and keep up
with the latest news,'' she said, adding that the contest would
also help them to improve their English.
	   Also present were KLMF Seremban group agency manager Lee Ban
Chuan and NST circulation executive Asim Mohamed.
	   Under the contest, three questions on mathematics and science,
history, geography, sports, entertainment and current affairs will
be printed in the newspapers together with the contest form.
	   Participants must answer all 15 questions and write a slogan.
	   Twelve participants will be selected for the finals to be held
at the Subang Parade shopping complex in Subang Jaya on July 5.
	   
</TEXT>
