<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 15:07:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1351  wstm-
r w     IBIQUITOUS-SIGNSsked     06-01 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> IBIQUITOUS-SIGNS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Ubiquitous signs of the times, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws IBIQUITOUS-SIGNS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THERE is no escaping them. Like a modern-day ``virus'', they are
virtually everywhere.
	   Shopping complexes, bus stops and taxi stands, inside LRT
trains, along the highways and byways. They leap at you, envelop
you and even if you don't pause for a second look, they insidiously
wend their way into your mind.
	   These are the posters - undoubtedly the most powerful tool of
publicity, persuasion and propaganda in modern times, since Jules
Cheret created the first four-colour posters in the late 19th
century! Not meant to last, the posters have become one of the
greatest signposts of the times with many of the more memorable
images assuming iconic status.
	   Some of the greatest original posters of all times are featured
in The Power of the Poster exhibition at London's Victoria and
Albert Museum in South Kensington, on until July 26.
	   With a broad overview reflecting the social history of the last
120 years, the exhibition is neatly arranged under three categories
- Pleasure and Leisure, Protest and Propaganda, and Commerce and
Communication.
	   The 300 posters on display are culled from the museum's own
extensive collection of more than 10,000 original posters, and this
exhibition is the most ambitious of its scale since 1931.
	   The great appeal of posters is their effectiveness, their
incredible outreach and mobility, and economy of production.
	   They also reflect the changes in styles from Art Nouveau, Art
Deco, Bauhaus and Russian Constructivism to the '60s psyche delia
and Pop.
	   The exhibition includes posters of Oskar Kokoschka, David
Hockney, Richard Hamilton (This Is Tomorrow exhibition at the
Whitechapel Art Gallery in 1965); Roy Lichtenstein (Crak! Now, Mes
Petits ... Pour La France!, 1963), and Keith Haring.
	   They are invaluable publicity for the latest plays, operas,
concerts, even movies.
	   Famous music posters include the album cover of punk rockers Sex
Pistols' Never Mind the Bollocks by Jamie Reid and John Varnam
(1977) and Martin Sharp's Mister Tambourine Man (1967).
	   As propaganda, they have inspired revolutions, evoked
nationalist fervour and boosted conscriptions.
	   Savile Lumley's Daddy, What did YOU do in the Great War? is both
an appeal to the conscience and national pride as well as a biting
ridicule of the draft dodgers.
	   Fougasse's Careless Talk Costs Lives brings home the importance
of secrecy to overcome the enemy.
	   Posters from the Bolshevik Revolution in the Soviet Union,
American anti-war protests in Vietnam, the suffragette movement,
``ban the bomb''
	   campaign, the overthrow of Communism in Eastern Europe in
1989-90 have become key documents of some of the most tumultuous
events of this century.
	   Tomosz Sarnecki's High Noon 4 June 1989 election poster for
Solidarity marks the political turning point in the former Eastern
bloc enclave.
	   There's also Ron Haeberie's photograph of the massacre with dead
bodies strewn along a footpath with the terse captions: Q. And
Babies? A. And Babies.
	   Campaigns against VD and AIDS exhort machismo restraint or at
least discreet precaution.
	   The ubiquitous posters are also dominant in sports for
mega-events such as the Olympics and the World Cup.
	   One impressive work is that on mercurial former Manchester
United striker Eric Cantona. Done with a twist when most Britons
would be thinking of England wresting the World Cup, it says: ```66
was a great year for English football. Eric was born.''
	   Posters are at their most sophisticated in advertising. Some of
the most provocative involve the Wonderbra and of course,
Benetton's controversial and exploitative slew of confrontational
realism.
	   Besides Cheret, other big names in poster designs featured
include the Beggarstaffs (Don Quixote, 1895), Frank Brangwyn,
Cassandre (exponent of Art Deco), Ludwig Hohlwein, Tom Purvis,
Graham Sutherland, and McKnight Kauffer.
	   To mark the exhibition, a two-day conference, Posters:
Persuasion and Subversion, will be held at the museum on June
12-13.
	   For more information, visit the museum's website at
http://www.vam.ac.uk The exhibition is open Tuesdays to Sundays
from 10am to 5.45pm, and Mondays from noon to 5.45pm.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
