<HEADER>
w1354  wstm-
r w     UNIT-TRUST-FUNDSsked     06-01 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> UNIT-TRUST-FUNDS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Allow EPF members to invest more in unit trust funds, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws UNIT-TRUST-FUNDS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   LAST Wednesday's report that the Employees' Provident Fund might
declare a lower dividend this year is not exactly good news to its
over seven million members.
	   Coming in the wake of last year's dividend of 6.7 per cent, the
report, which cited Deputy Finance Minister Datuk Dr Affifuddin
Omar as saying the EPF dividend payout this year might be affected
by lower returns from its stock market investments adds more gloom
to contributors who perceive their retirement nest-egg shrivelling.
	   That gloom would be laced with pangs of frustration as members
are painfully aware that savings in financial institutions yield
much higher returns. Fixed deposits with finance companies for
periods longer than a year earn more than 12 per cent per annum.
Even commercial banks are providing interest as much as 10 per cent
for one-month fixed deposits.
	   Just as every cloud has a silver lining, EPF has provided that
silver lining to its members to seek higher returns on their EPF
savings but at their own risk.
	   In 1996, the Fund introduced the Members Investment Savings
Scheme that enables members to withdraw a portion of their savings
to invest in approved unit trusts.
	   As all EPF members know by now, savings with the Fund are
trifurcated into three accounts. Account I, which is for
retirement, captures 60 per cent of all savings. It is from this
account that contributors can withdraw to invest in unit trusts.
	   But members must have more than RM50,000 in Account I to be
eligible to withdraw for investment. Even then, contributors can
only take out 20 per cent of the amount, in multiples of RM1,000,
that is in excess of RM50,000 in the account. Simply phrased,
members must have at least RM55,000 in Account I to be eligible to
withdraw the minimum of RM1,000 under the scheme.
	   Which brings us to the logical question: how many among EPF
contributors have RM100,000 or more in savings? The Fund, however,
has never been keen to reveal any statistics. What we do have is a
relatively old set of statistics on the savings profile of members
as at the end of 1994.
	   Those figures show about 33 per cent of 3.8 million active
contributors had more than RM100,000 in savings with the EPF. At
the other end of the scale more than 100,000 members have more than
RM1 million in savings with the Fund.
	   These statistics are not very significant to the primary aspect
of this article, which is simply: how many EPF members have, so
far, availed themselves of the the latest benefit provided by the
Fund?
	   Inquiries with three of the 30 approved unit trust managers
reveal the response has been ``encouraging.''
	   Kuala Lumpur Mutual Fund Bhd, which manages 10 unit trusts, has
so far attracted RM250 million from EPF members.
	   OSK-UOB Bhd, which launched two unit trusts, has also secured
funds from EPF members, though not in the scale of KL Mutual Fund
which is the largest private unit trust managers in the country.
	   Another fund manager, who declined to be named, expressed
similiar views saying that it has attracted ``several millions''
from EPF members.
	   These facts show that many members invest a portion of their
savings in approved unit trusts. And a salient fact is that these
members are willing to take the risk of transfering their savings
in EPF to unit trusts in these difficult times.
	   But they know that investing in unit trusts would yield higher
returns than EPF could possibly declare. For instance, Permodalan
Nasional Bhd, one of the approved fund managers in the EPF savings
investment scheme, which manages the Amanah Saham Bumiputera has
consistently declared dividends above 12 per cent. Even in the
worst year, so far, in 1997, it gave 11.8 per cent.
	   KL Mutual Fund, for another, has a distinguished record of
providing an average of 10 per cent dividend on its income
generating unit trusts over the last 30 years. Even late-comer,
OSK-UOB is investing 72 per cent of the RM10 million it has so far
attracted in fixed deposits that would yield 10 per cent or more in
interest.
	   Clearly then, EPF's savings investment scheme can increase the
quantum of members' retirement nest-egg. But the amount they could
invest in unit trusts, under current rules is relatively paltry.
	   So the question is why should the Fund place a 20 per cent cap
on the amount members could transfer to unit trusts. In drawing up
this scheme, EPF realised that members who have substantial savings
are mature enough to decide how their monies should be invested.
	   The Fund has realised that despite its huge resources, it cannot
give even the eight per cent dividend it once declared over four
years in the early 90s. Since then the dividends has been 7.5 per
cent (1995), 7.7 per cent (1996) and 6.7 per cent (1997).
	   Surely then, EPF should allow members who have substantial
savings in the fund to withdraw as much money as they can to
substantiate their retirement nest-egg.
	   Let them withdraw the total amount they have in excess of
RM50,000 in Account I. The returns on investments in unit trusts
will then truly be significant.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:UNIT-TRUST-FUNDS sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
