<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Hunter Douglas picks Malaysia, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws HUNTER-DOUGLAS-PICKS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   HUNTER Douglas, a multinational industrial group engaged in the
manufacture of ceilings and claddings, has made Malaysia the hub of
its Asian operations covering 12 countries.
	   It has invested RM65 million in Malaysia to set up three
factories to produce metal ceilings and claddings and to assemble
window furnishing products.
	   Hunter Douglas Manufacturing (Malaysia) Sdn Bhd exports 50 per
cent of its production of metal ceilings and claddings to countries
such as Japan, China, South Korea and India.
	   Its general manager (architectural products division) Azeman
Ghazali said the company's marketing strategy was focused on the
replacement market where metal ceilings could be used to replace
the conventional mineral fibre and gypsum or plaster board which is
currently supplied for most offices.
	   In a statement, Azeman said the local market for metal ceiling
products had been growing at a rate of seven to eight per cent
since the early 1990s.
	   ``We estimate the metal ceiling market to be equivalent to
380,000 square metres this year - about 10 per cent of the total
market for ceilings.''
	   As office buildings move towards higher technology materials to
achieve durability and lesser maintenance, easier integration and
better acoustic properties, more people will turn to aluminimum
ceiling systems.
	   Developed countries in Europe, the United States, Singapore and
Hong Kong have been the leading users of metal ceiling products.
	   ``In Malaysia, we will be looking at the renovation market where
we have a small share.''
	   Hunter Douglas has gained a lot of experience since its
establishment in Malaysia in mid-1979.
	   It has completed its supply and installation of the ceiling
system at the Kuala Lumpur International Airport's main satellite
building, measuring 100,000 square metres.
	   The design and development of the wood grain finish and the
printing technology took six months.
	   
</TEXT>
