<HEADER>
w1360  wstm-
r w     ENHANCE-RISK-MANAGEMENTs     06-01 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> ENHANCE-RISK-MANAGEMENT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Urgent need for local firms to enhance risk management, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws ENHANCE-RISK-MANAGEMENT sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   LOCAL corporations, which had been complacent in managing their
risks in the past, need to `urgently' enhance their financial risk
management capabilities to protect themselves against volatile
market conditions.
	   Malaysian Monetary Exchange Bhd general manager Mohd Azwar
Mahmud said in times of market turbulence, such as that experienced
by the regional and local market recently, managing risk in passive
and reactive ways could no longer be adequate for them.
	   Mohd Azwar said corporations have to be more proactive and
prudent in managing risk and one of the ways to do it is by using
hedging activities in their operations.
	   ``If they do not hedge, they will be caught by surprise should
there be any sudden moves in the market. Eventually, if the moves
are adverse it will be calculated in their bottom line (earnings).
	   ``This was seen with the results of corporations which suffered
unbelievable magnitude of losses due to the volatility in the
market.''
	   Mohd Azwar said the financial market in this country would
``never ever''
	   be the same again.
	   ``The rules of the game have changed and it is now about
exposure to financial risk by choice and not by chance,'' he told
reporters at the Corporate Treasurers' Colloquium in Kuala Lumpur
yesterday.
	   The event was jointly organised by MME and the Malaysian
Association of Corporate Treasurers. Mohd Azwar added that unless
these corporations changed their attitude and adapted to the
changes in the market, it would destroy them.
	   ``Even if the environment is stable and there is no compelling
reason for them to manage their risk, they still need to be more
proactive and prudent,'' he said.
	   He pointed out that the application of derivative instruments in
general requires a comprehensive training programme at all levels
to ensure it is being managed professionally.
	   The professionals must be willing to take more proactive role
towards minimising risk exposures for the corporations, he added.
	   He said MME in its efforts to promote the usage of derivative
products as risk management tools, has been working together with
financial institutions as well as corporations to set up their
derivative desks.
	   ``What we are doing now is getting local corporations to be more
adventurous and aggressive by shifting and expanding their risk
management capabilities,'' Mohd Azwar added.
	   
</TEXT>
