<BODY>
<SLUG> MATRICULATION-FRANCHISE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
UM refutes claims over matriculation franchise, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws MATRICULATION-FRANCHISE sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - Universiti Malaya today refuted claims by
its Academic Staff Association that the university's franchise
programme for the matriculation of science students lacked
transparency and that applicants had not been made aware of the
programme.
	   The university's public relations officer V.T. Ratnam, in
dismissing claims of the programme's haphazard implementation, said
all students had been informed in advance of the private
institutions they would be placed with once all places at the
university were filled.
	   He said this would have been done either by letter, telegram or
telephone prior to registration.
	   Ratnam, however, admitted that there had been a small number of
students who had turned up at the university not knowing where they
would be placed.
	   But this was due to miscommunication, he said.
	   On the association's claim that students placed in private
colleges might have to pay between RM8,000 and RM12,000 annually
compared to the much-lower UM fees of RM3,000 per year, Ratnam said
UM had made arrangements to ensure the fees at the private colleges
would not exceed RM2,500 per semester.
	   He said the colleges had also been instructed not to charge more
than RM500 in registration fees.
	   He also said the association's claim that UM's fees per year
were RM3,000 was incorrect.
	   The actual sum, he said, was RM8,000, after factoring in other
costs such as lecturers' fees and science equipment.
	   On the association's claim that the proper channel was not used
in the selection of private colleges, Ratnam said all colleges
selected under the franchise programme had been scrutinised
thoroughly to ensure their suitability.
	   The colleges had not only been visited but also had all their
facilities (such as science laboratories and accommodation) checked
and certified as up to standard, not just by UM but by the
Education Ministry as well.
	   The selection of private institutions, he added, had been
supervised using the highest standards by a task force.
	   The task force is registered with the Private Education
Department of the Education Ministry.
	   Also involved in the selection process was a UM advisory
committee chaired by vice-chancellor Tan Sri Dr Abdullah Sanusi
Ahmad.
	   UM is one of five universities which have franchise programmes
with private colleges.
	   The other universities are Universiti Putra Malaysia, Universiti
Kebangsaan Malaysia, Universiti Sains Malaysia and Universiti
Malaysia Sabah.
	   The 10 private colleges under UM's franchise scheme are Kolej
Mara, Banting, Kolej Yayasan Pelajaran Mara, Kuantan, Kolej
Matrikulasi Terengganu, Kuala Terengganu, Institut Kemajuan
Ikhtisas Pahang, Kuala Selangor, Institut Goon, Kuala Lumpur,
Institut Maxisegar, Bukit Sentosa, Kolej Uniti, Port Dickson and
Kolej Cempaka, Kuala Lumpur.
	   
</TEXT>
