<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-WC98-World Cup Growth,0809 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREVIEWING THE WORLD CUP As it grows, World Cup finds new markets, problems AP Sports Writer 
</HEADLINE>
RETRANSMITTING to all needing
By LARRY SIDDONS
<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ The force that rocks the world occurs for one
month every four years _ and it gets bigger and bigger each time
they put up the nets.
	   When the World Cup is held for the 16th time this summer, more
teams will play before more people and generate more money than
ever before. Even grander things are up next _ a cup staged by two
nations and earning billions of dollars in TV and sponsor fees.
	   Its world championship puts soccer on an even higher stage than
normal. By the time the title is decided in the new Stade de France
outside Paris on July 12, a total audience of more than 17 billion
is expected to have watched World Cup matches on TV, more than any
other event by far.
	   But there are fears that what one official calls ``the No. 1
passion event in sports'' may be getting too big and that
fundamental changes are needed to protect its global stature.
	   ``We are running out of countries capable of hosting the cup,
and the more teams you add, the lower the common quality of the
field,'' said Kier Radnadge, editor of World Soccer magazine.
``Probably the highest quality of the tournament was back in
1970.''
	   Seventy years ago, there was no World Cup. The title of soccer's
best went to the winner of the Olympic tournament. But on May 26,
1928, a group of officials led by Jules Rimet of France agreed to
stage a World Cup, and later awarded the first tournament to
Uruguay, the reigning Olympic champ, for 1930.
	   Of the 13 entries in that initial edition, only four came from
outside the Western Hemisphere. A total of 435,000 fans watched the
games, all but a couple played in a single stadium. There was no
TV, of course, and organizers were pleasently surprised that they
could pay all their bills.
	   When defending-champion Brazil and Scotland kick off France '98
the evening of June 10, they will lead a field stretching from
South Africa to South Korea. The 32 teams, double the number of
just 20 years ago, will play in 10 stadiums, total capacity 1.81
million. Television networks around the world paid approximately
dlrs 450 million dollars in rights fees to FIFA, soccer's world
governing body. Organizers are confident of covering their dlrs 270
million budget from private funds.
	   Two things spurred this growth _ TV and the emergence of sports
as perhaps the single largest unifying force of late-20th century
life. Starting with the first satellite transmissions of live
matches in 1970, the World Cup became a truly worldwide event.
	   ``It's always been that soccer was the most popular sport,''
said Jim Trecker, deputy secretary general of the U.S. Soccer
Federation. ``But it was in the 1970s and '80s, through television,
that the World Cup was universally disseminated and allowed all
people to participate.''
	   ``Everything that's happened technically and socially in the
last half-century has suited the game exactly,'' said Radnadge, who
has covered the Cup from his London base since 1966. ``Sport has
become one of the great movements of the 20th century.''
	   That universal audience _ not even moon landings, the Olympics,
or even Princess Diana's funeral come close in sheer numbers _ has
attracted commercial sponsors with wide-open checkbooks to the
World Cup.
	   ``It's just so big that you can't afford not to be involved in
it,'' Radnadge said.
	   So rich is FIFA that every four years it gives each of its 198
national members dlrs 1 million to help develop soccer in their
country.
	   ``To stretch the math a little, that's a 200 million-dollar
giveaway,'' Trecker said. ``That's pretty good.''
	   And that number is set to explode. Next year, a new TV contract
kicks in, worth a total of dlrs 2.5 billion for the World Cups in
2002 and 2006.
	   FIFA will use a good deal of that money to promote grass-roots
soccer programs and boost particiation and fan programs for women's
soccer, a rapidly growing element of the sport.
	   ``In terms of both the potential number of participants and the
potential market, it makes perfect sense,'' Trecker said.
	   But with growth and success have come increased demands and
expectations.
	   Radnadge said the list of countries that can realistically stage
a World Cup now is down to a half dozen _ the United States,
France, Germany, England, Italy and Spain.
	   Trecker said it's time for FIFA to consider spending some of its
money to ease the financial burden of local organziers, especially
with talk about holding the tournament one day in South Africa or
China.
	   ``It think it might be wise to change the equation so those
countries that are economically challenged can still play host,''
he said.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-WC98-World Cup Growth; CT:s; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
