w1367  wstm-
r s     BC-Sports-Soccer-WC98-Bo     06-01 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-WC98-Bonuses,0681 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREVIEWING THE WORLD CUP World Cup mixes lure of the goal with that of cash 
</HEADLINE>
RETRANSMITTING to all needing
By CIARAN GILES
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   For some soccer players, just reaching the World Cup is prize
enough. For others, it is also the gateway to a lucrative feast.
	   And where money lurks, controversy is bound to be close by.
	   Over the decades, financial bonuses for World Cup performances
have soared to such an extent that many national federations now
prefer to remain tightlipped regarding the matter.
	   Fearing a repeat of disputes with players that bonus
negotiations triggered in previous tournaments, record four-time
champion Brazil, backed by multinational sports product giant Nike,
claims there will be none this time round for the big `R's _
Ronaldo, Romario, Rivaldo, Roberto Carlos _ or their teammates.
	   But few believed them, especially after it was added that the
bonuses wouldn't be revealed even if they did exist.
	   Most suspect the South Americans' compensation will tally
closely with that being promised to their Italian counterparts, for
whom a a fourth championship would land a tidy sum of dlrs 278,000,
nearly dlrs 80,000 more than squad members earned for winning the
1982 World Cup.
	   But news reports say the Italian stars, including Roberto Baggio
and Alessandro Del Piero, have been warned they won't get a single
lira unless they reach the semifinals of the 32-team competition.
Once there, however, each player stands to receive dlrs 55,500 each
while even a place in the final would garner them dlrs 195,000.
	   A little less demanding is host France, whose federation has
reportedly set a quarterfinal threshold before unleashing the
centimes. A place in the final eight would merit a dlrs 50,000
reward for each player and that figure will quadruple should they
get to the final.
	   Germany admits it is offering incentives from the start.
Federation spokesman Michael Novak said each player would receive
dlrs 270,000 for winning the title but also will get dlrs 25,000
just for getting beyond the first round.
	   Neighboring Netherlands averted a repeat of the dispute that
marred its run-up to the 1994 Cup by agreeing to a bonus package
``that satisfies both parties,'' according to team captain Frank de
Boer.
	   Reports said the KNVB originally offered a dlrs 70,000 bonus for
winning the Cup _ less than what was agreed to for winning the
European Championship in 1996 _ but eventually agreed to increase
it to dlrs 100,000.
	   Meanwhile, some teams are offering more for getting to the
second round than others can for winning the trophy.
	   Playing in its third World Cup, the United States, reportedly
has pledged a whopping dlrs 250,000 to its players who have been
with the team all the way through qualifying if the side manages to
emerge from the three-game first round, in which it faces Germany,
Yugoslavia and Iran.
	   Some teams at the other end of the scale, however, are still
squabbling over payments from the 1994 Cup.
	   Just last month, FIFA was warning modest Cameroon that unless it
paid former keeper Joseph Antoine Bell dlrs 74,000 owed him since
1994 it could be disqualified from the tournament in France.
	   Bell caused a rumpus in the United States when he led a team
revolt prior to its game against Brazil demanding Cameroon pay
promised bonuses. Cameroon has pledged to resolve the matter.
	   Neighboring Nigeria also found itself embroiled in a row the
same month as players demanded their bonus be increased from dlrs
6,000 to 8,000 per game.
	   Such disputes have led some to argue that team performances are
too dependent on the dollar awards.
	   ``Spain can't be world champions because we don't earn the most
money. Brazilians earn much more,'' said cynical Spanish coach
Javier Clemente.
	   For him, eighth place would suffice for Spain, for which players
would receive dlrs 73,000 each. The team's members have nonetheless
been pledged a total of 280,000 dlrs each if they were to win the
gold statuette.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-WC98-Bonuses; CT:s; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
