<BODY>
<SLUG> CAPITAL-INVESTMENTS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
MAS allocates RM2.78b for capital investments, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws CAPITAL-INVESTMENTS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   MALAYSIA Airlines has allocated capital investments of RM2.78
billion for the current financial year and subsequent financial
years until 2000 of which the bulk will be for the payment of
aircraft and spare engine.
	   Of the amount, RM1.54 billion would be utilised for aircraft and
spare engine payment and another RM749.1 million would be used for
the second financial year.
	   For the year ending March 31, 1999, the company plans to spend
RM1.8 billion while another RM971.6 million is earmarked for the
year ending March 31, 2000.
	   Executive vice-president of group finance S. Suppiah said the
airline has allocated a total amount of RM130.8 million which would
be spent on projects at the Kuala Lumpur International Airport.
	   ``We have also set aside RM360 million for both financial years
for other capital expenditure which include replacement of
equipment with the move to the new airport,'' he said.
	   Suppiah said this at a briefing for analysts, bankers, employees
and the media on Malaysia Airlines' results in Petaling Jaya on
Saturday.
	   The airline has recorded a group pre-tax loss of RM225.36
million for the year ended March 31, 1998, compared to a profit of
RM349.56 million previously.
	   The 164.5 per cent drop was largely due to the weakening ringgit
against the the US dollar with the company suffering a foreign
exchange loss of RM718.4 million.
	   Suppiah said Malaysia Airlines' current assets as at March 31,
1998, stood at RM2.3 billion against RM2.07 billion in the same
period last year.
	   Executive vice-president (airline) Datuk Bashir Ahmad said
Malaysia Airlines has taken steps in anticipation of continued
decline in traffic including the deferment on aircraft deliveries
as well as reduction in flight capacity.
	   Bashir said the airline which had originally expected delivery
of 28 aircraft by 2000, as part of its five-year expansion plan,
has defered the deliveries until 2003.
	   These include the delivery of three B747-400 and four
B777-2001GW which was initially scheduled for between 1999 and
2000.
	   ``We have been quick to inform Boeing on the deferment, so it is
not going to incur much cost,'' added Bashir.
	   He said Malaysia Airlines would not extend the lease on three
B737s and one A330 aircraft while for 1999, there would be no
extension of a A330 leased aircraft.
	   The carrier has also modified aircraft orders from B777-300 to
B777-200, he said adding that there was also an offer for sale of
its existing aircraft.
	   ``We are talking to foreign parties who are interested in buying
or leasing the B777-400. There is a demand now especially for
B777-400 series in Europe and United States,'' Bashir said.
	   Meanwhile, Malaysia Airlines chairman Tan Sri Tajudin Ramli said
the company has taken immediate steps to cut down on operations to
places which were not profitable.
	   ``When the economic downturn happened in the second half of last
year, we quickly made changes in the way we operate the airline. We
have curtailed capacity and made adjustment,'' he added.
	   
</TEXT>
