<HEADLINE>
PREVIEWING THE WORLD CUP World Cup 2006 a key factor in FIFA presidential vote 
</HEADLINE>
RETRANSMITTING to all needing
By ERICA BULMAN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ With eight years and two World Cups still to go,
the host for the 2006 tournament is likely to be decided long
before the decision is announced two years from now.
	   In the fierce competition leading up to the FIFA presidential
elections in Paris on June 8, the 2006 World Cup could figure
prominently in the outcome.
	   Both candidates have expressed support for different venues,
with FIFA General Secretary Sepp Blatter speaking out for a World
Cup in Africa and the UEFA President Lennart Johansson pushing for
its return to Europe. Votes at the presidential elections could
hinge on the issue.
	   Though the African Football Confederation (CAF) officially
supports Johansson, his backing from those nations appears to be
disintegrating.
	   Johansson's racial comments during a trip to South Africa in
November combined with his support of a European World Cup final in
2006 have endangered key African votes, with several of its 51
nations having hinted they would support Blatter in the secret
ballot among 198 members.
	   Johansson saw his election campaign take another blow when
CONCACAF announced in mid-May its decision to back Blatter.
	   Liberian player George Weah, who plays for Italian club
Internazionale of Milan and a former FIFA Player of the Year, also
has announced he will endorse Blatter and try to convince African
nations to do likewise.
	   South Africa has from the beginning benefitted from the support
of retiring FIFA President Joao Havelange.
	   Havelange, who is stepping down after 24 years as head of FIFA,
created a stir when he virtually promised South Africa the 2006
championship. Blatter has echoed Havelange's sentiments, indicating
he would strongly support an African bid.
	   Blatter said it was not right that he should promise the
competition to Africa including South Africa, Morocco, Nigeria or
Egypt.
	   But he said if they had the necessary infrastructure, they
should have it.
	   ``I cannot promise anything but I said I would work for that,''
he said. ``We must do something for African football.''
	   Johansson even has angered at least one European vote, England,
having openly endorsed Germany. It's a statement Blatter has tried
to use against him.
	   ``How can the Africans vote for someone who has already said he
would give the World Cup to Germany?'' Blatter said.
	   Once considered the front-runners of the chase to host the 2006
World Cup, Germany and England have split the European bid, only
strenghtening the prospect of having it staged in South Africa.
	   Both European countries already have hosted the World Cup,
England in 1966, and Germany in 1974.
	   Not to be overlook in the chase is Brazil, the four-time
champion, which can also expect to receive strong support. Other
competition may come from Australia which also has expressed
interest in hosting the event.
	   But clearly, staging one of the world's largest events in South
Africa, backed by President Nelson Mandela, is an enticing prospect
_ not only for FIFA but for the International Olympic Committee,
which also loudly has applauded the nation's bid to host the 2008
Olympic Games.
	   Since the first World Cup in 1930, the finals have been staged
in Europe nine times, in South America four times, North America
three times and Asia (Japan-South Korea) will be organizing it for
the first time in 2002. Africa and Oceania are the only regions to
have never hosted the tournament.
	   The decision on the host country for the 2006 World Cup will be
made by the 24 members of FIFA's Executive Committee in June of
2000.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-WC98-2006; CT:s; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
