<SLUG> BC-Rwanda-Economy,0528 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rwanda says stability in danger unless it gets debt relief 
</HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) _ Without international support, the Rwandan
government will not be able to service a dlrs 1 billion debt and
maintain economic and political stability, the finance minister
said.
	   In a speech prepared for an international meeting of donors in
Stockholm, Sweden, on Tuesday and Wednesday, Finance Minister
Donald Kaberuka appealed for dlrs 767 million in the next three
years to sustain the cost of reforms.
	   The World Bank has warned the national reconciliation and
prevention of renewed ethnic violence will depend on success of the
reforms.
	   ``Crucially, the debt relief is itself ... restricting the
ability of the government to undertake the critical social
interventions required to bring about social reconciliation,
reintegration and the necessary sustainable human development,''
Kaberuka said, according to a copy of his speech made available to
The Associated Press on Monday.
	   So far, donors have been satisfied with the government's record
in restoring peace after a 1994 genocide, resettling more than 1
million refugees and stabilizing the economy.
	   But economists say one of the key constrains lies in Rwanda's
inability to service dlrs 1.2 billion in external debt and a high
level of military spending at a time when the Tutsi-led army is
fighting Hutu rebels.
	   Rwanda has been paying dlrs 17 million each year to service the
debt, most of it to multilateral creditors such as the
International Development Association, the African Development Bank
and the World Bank.
	   The money was acquired by the former Hutu-led government
responsible for the 1994 slaughter of 500,000 minority Tutsis. In
July 1994, Tutsi rebels won power and started on an ambitious
recovery plan to sell state-owned property, restructure civil
service and reintegrate thousands of former Hutu soldiers and civil
servants to win their confidence.
	   But Kaberuka said the debt burden was too heavy too sustain and
insufficient to clear Rwanda from its debt in a foreseeable future.
	   In his speech, he appealed for a special case for Rwanda, under
which the international donor community should write off dlrs 97.5
million in debt arrears and establish a Multilateral Debt Trust
Fund to help finance the multilateral debt service until 2001.
	   Under the proposal, the trust fund would be administered by the
World Bank to ensure accountability and render reports to donors.
	   If successful, the measures would help Rwanda qualify in three
years for a debt relief.
	   Such debt relief, under a World Bank-IMF program known as Highly
Indebted Poor Countries' Initiative, has already been granted to
Uganda and Mozambique, both credited with economic reforms.
	   The amount of money used for servicing the debt would enable
Rwanda to meet urgent social needs; support the victims of genocide
and the cost of demobilization; and to finance the transition from
crisis to sustainable economic growth, the World Bank said.
</TEXT>
