SC extends deadline for disclosure, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws SC-EXTENDS-DEADLINE sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE Securities Commission has extended by a month to July 1 the
deadline for the disclosure of substantial shareholdings ``due to
overwhelming requests from parties concerned'', it said in a
statement yesterday.
	   According to the Securities Industry (Reporting of Substantial
Shareholding) Regulations 1998, a person who is a substantial
shareholder in a listed or non-listed public company shall give
notice to the SC on the particulars of the interest.
	   Also, the new section 99B of the Securities Industry Act imposes
a duty on chief executives and directors of listed firms to
disclose their interests in securities of the listed corporation or
any associated entity.
	   The securities watchdog said submissions have been slow in
coming and reminded parties involved that the penalty for
non-compliance with the regulations was a fine not exceeding
RM500,000 or five years' imprisonment, or both.
	   Any queries on the disclosure requirements should be directed to
the Corporate Affairs Department of the SC at 03-2539988.
	   
</TEXT>
