<HEADLINE>
PREVIEWING THE WORLD CUP Rimet's tournament returns, bringing back fading glory AP Special Correspondent 
</HEADLINE>
RETRANSMITTING to all needing
By MORT ROSENBLUM
<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ The 1998 World Cup brings France a last flourish of
badly needed glory in the fading millennium, and the French are
sparing no effort to wrap the games in grandeur.
	   ``The World Cup must stamp our history,'' President Jacques
Chirac said in January, inaugurating the new Stade de France near
Paris with all the pomp of a Sun King opening Versailles Palace.
	   For months now, officials have been spouting superlatives.
	   This time, 32 teams compete instead of the 24 that have taken
the field since 1982. With rebroadcasts, 37 billion people will
watch at least some play, twice the audience of the Olympics Games.
	   Over 33 days, 64 matches are scheduled in 10 stadiums from the
soccer-mad little mining town of Lens in the north to the ancient
Mediterranean port of Marseilles.
	   A half billion dollars went into the Stade de France, an
80,000-seat concrete flying saucer hovering near Paris, where play
will begin and end with elaborate fanfare.
	   Another billion was raised from commercial sponsors, tickets and
public funds for the French Organizing Committee (CFO) and
facilities. Technicians laid 2.5 million kilometers (1.5 million
miles) of fiber optic cable.
	   But for most Frenchmen, the best part of the 16th World Cup is
that it is theirs, a planetary platform to wave the blue, white and
red Tricolor and a chance to throw the biggest dinner party ever.
	   French football fans are praying for an unlikely victory for
more than the usual reasons.
	   A French journalist thought up the idea of a world federation in
1904. Two Frenchmen were behind the first Cup, in Uruguay in 1930,
and a French striker scored the first goal.
	   Michel Platini's goal in 1986 helped beat Brazil to put Les
Bleus into the semifinals. But the French have never reached the
final. A last game between, say, France and Brazil, would make
their millennium.
	   Even many who are fleeing for the duration are happy about the
venue. As France melts into a European Union and Americanisms
muscle into the culture, Paris will be the capital of the world.
	   From the opening extravaganza to the final frenzy, the
tournament promises to be distinctly French.
	   Among the official suppliers is Yves Saint Laurent. There is an
appointed purveyor of dairy products.
	   ``We did have one problem at the stadium inauguration,'' allowed
Pierre Parisot, director of the Stade de France. ``The hot dogs
were terrible. Cold, all wrong.''
	   But, he added, spectators seemed pleased with the four posh
Parisian caterers who served 11,000 meals. And patrons praised the
wine cellar of the panoramic gourmet restaurant, run by Lenotre.
	   Along the Champs Elysees, Frenchmen jostle with tourists to buy
pins, T-shirts and blue-white-red soccer balls from an official
World Cup stuff shop.
	   Upon reflection, officials withdrew the official World Cup
knife.
	   Just about every item is emblazoned with the ubiquitous mascot:
Footix, a cocky-looking little blue and red rooster with a goofy
grin.
	   Huge streetcorner posters push the slogan, ``It's not every day
that we welcome the whole world.'' On one, a come-hither beauty in
a slinky white sheath holds a tray at a lustrous Paris bistro.
	   Perhaps to add an extra French touch, truck drivers and
transport unions have threatened to strike during the tournament,
choking off access to the stadiums.
	   One popular booklet advises visitors how not to get cheated by
merchants, hotelkeepers and taxi drivers. Another instructs locals
to say ``moutchas gracias'' and its equivalent in a score of
tongues.
	   On television, talking heads give soccer new social and
political dimensions.
	   Sociologist Christian Bromberger told a colloquium he saw a
``footballization of society.'' He said, ``It is a profound game, a
condensed source of all emotions: joy, anguish, revolt,
injustice.''
	   Many fear it is also a source of violence, and police have made
complex plans to contain hooligans or rowdy fans who do not make it
into stadiums.
	   For a while, tourism officials urged Britons to come without
tickets and watch matches on outdoor screens. Someone thought about
that again and changed the message: Stay home.
	   Tickets are already a sore point.
	   After the European Union and other countries roasted France for
keeping the lion's share of the tickets for Frenchmen, organizers
scraped up 110,000 tickets for foreigners to order by phone.
	   The April day they went on sale, however, 20 million calls
swamped the 90 operators, and it took two weeks before the tickets
could be sold to the lucky few who managed to get through.
	   In London, the Daily Mirror reported that an elderly Englishman
destroyed finger ligaments by repeated dialling.
	   Of 2.5 million tickets, two-thirds were allotted to Frenchmen,
and another 12 percent to the organizing committee and commercial
affiliates. Tour operators got another 8 percent.
	   Tickets to early matches went on sale in France in 1996, and
were sold out a year ago. In December, a lottery among Frenchmen
determined who could buy tickets for the nine deciding matches.
	   For instance, real estate executive Pierre Macchi and a friend
each applied for four tickets to the finals. Both wound up with two
seats. ``You can imagine,'' he said, ``we were ecstatic.''
	   He paid dlrs 600 per ticket and could have sold the two extras
for three times that. Instead, he gave them to an equally ecstatic
friend for merely twice the face value, which reduced his cost to
zero.
	   Tickets or not, fans are swarming to France which, with annual
arrivals of 67 million, is already the world's most visited
country. By May, 360,000 hotel rooms were booked, mostly in Paris.
	   The show starts June 9 with a Festival of Football, a citywide
splash of color and sound climaxing at the Place de la Concorde, a
sweep of dramatic stone and space at the heart of Paris.
	   Details are guarded with the zeal of a state secret. Four
parades will start at classic monuments, with music and costumes of
dozens of cultures blending with a French accent.
	   In the nation of Liberty, Equality and Fraternity, the
festival's theme is Excitement, Universality, and Sharing.
	   There are some rubs.
	   None of the 12 official sponsors, and only four of the eight
suppliers, are French. The games' official restaurant is McDonalds.
	   Soccer-hating Frenchmen have formed a tongue-in-cheek
association called, ``The Cup Is Full,'' to plan alternative
activities in June and July. If popular, the group represents a
clear minority.
	   Starting June 10, first-round matches will be played in nine
provincial cities chosen for their football traditions, their ample
stadiums, and their accessibility.
	   Each has tried to outdo the other to remain in visitors'
memories.
	   The largest stadium outside Paris is the wide open 60,000-seat
Velodrome in Marseilles. But the most passionate may be in Lens,
just outside of Lille at the top of France.
	   The 47,000-seat stadium can hold 1 1-2 times the city's
population. And early in May, when Lens won the French league
title, most townsfolk were there at 3 a.m. when the team returned
home.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-WC98-The Host; CT:s; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
