<HEADLINE>
PREVIEWING THE WORLD CUP Two-time World Cup runner-up aims again for top spot 
</HEADLINE>
RETRANSMITTING to all needing
By MIKE CORDER
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) _ Another major soccer tournament.
Another talent-packed Dutch soccer side. Another near miss?
	   From trusty Ajax goalkeeper Edwin van der Sar to star strikers
Dennis Bergkamp and Patrick Kluivert, the Netherlands _ World Cup
runnerup in 1974 and 1978 _ has the quality to take the title.
	   The question _ as always _ is whether they also have the
temperament to play as a team rather than 11 talented individuals.
	   Ajax Amsterdam's Danish coach, Morten Olsen, recently said that
the Dutch do not have the character to take soccer's most
prestigious title.
	   That was evident at the last major soccer tournament, Euro 96,
when players in the fancied Dutch squad reportedly split along
black-white lines and midfielder Edgar Davids was sent home for
publicly criticizing coach Guus Hiddink.
	   This time around, Hiddink is attempting to shield his 22-man
squad from the pressures of the tournament, while giving them a
chance to let off steam during the long campaign.
	   Hiddink has commandeered a hotel in the mountains above Monte
Carlo as the Dutch base this summer. ``Players will have privacy,
but will also be able to get out and meet people. We want to avoid
them getting bored,'' he said.
	   After nearly two years on the international sidelines as
punishment for the Euro 96 bust up, Davids' form has been so good
with Italian giant Juventus that he now is a near certainty to
play.
	   Davids is likely to share the midfield with old Ajax teammates
Clarence Seedorf, now with Real Madrid, and Ronald de Boer. The
hard-working Juventus star is seen as an ideal defensive foil for
De Boer and Seedorf, who both tend to push forward looking to
create or score goals.
	   In Ajax's Van der Sar, the Dutch have one of the world's most
reliable goalkeepers. The bean-pole Amsterdammer has conceded just
20 goals in 33 league matches this season.
	   The Dutch also boast the world's most expensive defender, Jaap
Stam, the PSV Eindhoven center back who will play for Manchester
United next season.
	   Off the field, Hiddink has assembled an impressive bench of
assistant coaches with a wealth of major tournament experience.
	   Ex-internationals Johan Neeskens, Ronald Koeman and Frank
Rijkaard are key members of the Dutch party. Rijkaard's appointment
was seen as an effort to boost the morale of young players like
Seedorf, Kluivert and Davids who share Rijkaard's Surinamese roots.
In his last year with Ajax, Rijkaard acted as a seasoned mentor for
the young guns.
	   His calm head and experience could be crucial for the Dutch who
always carry a huge weight of expectation from their fanatical
orange-clad fans.
	   Not only do the supporters expect their team to win, they expect
them to win in style, playing the kind of attacking ``total
football'' that took the Dutch to two World Cup finals in the
1970s.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-WC98-Netherlands; CT:s; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
