<BODY>
<SLUG> COUNCIL-TO-STUDY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Council to study take-over offer, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws COUNCIL-TO-STUDY sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE Shah Alam Municipal Council wants to consider all
implications before accepting the Selangor Government's offer to
take over the management and maintenance of the Shah Alam
International Aquatic Centre.
	   Council president Mohamad Adzib Mohd Isa said the council had to
study, among other things, maintenance, potential profits, fees to
be charged and whether or not the centre's maintenance be
privatised.
	   His response followed councillor Mohd Zin Mohamad's query on
when the council would take over the centre and open it to the
public.
	   The centre, built by Worldwide PKNS, is owned by the State's
Sports Council.
	   It was first used during the Sukma Games.
	   ``The council has to study the matter thoroughly before
accepting the offer. The centre will still be opened to the public
even if the council declines the offer,'' he added.
	   
</TEXT>
