<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Unable to prevent overcrowded living, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws UNABLE-TO-PREVENT-LIVING sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE Shah Alam Municipal Council has no authority to stop
residents from overcrowding houses and causing poor ventilation.
	   Council president Mohamad Adzib Mohd Isa said the council could
only advise residents but not take legal action against them.
	   He was replying councillor Mohd Zain Mohamad's question on five
cases of tuberculosis in the municipality last month.
	   The meeting was informed that investigations had revealed that
poor ventilation and overcrowding in houses were factors
contributing to the occurrence of the air-borne disease. The
victims were aged between 24 and 62.
	   The houses had a certificate of fitness issued by the council.
	   Mohd Zain questioned the council's building and planning
department for approving CF for the houses.
	   Mohamad Adzib said the question of adequate ventilation was
considered when approving the CF.
	   ``But sometimes, in a small house, the occupants tend to make
use of store rooms and utility rooms for living purposes, when
these rooms are not meant for such use,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
