<HEADER>
w1387  wstm-
r w     QUALITY-SHOESsked     06-01 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> QUALITY-SHOES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Quality shoes for the people, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws QUALITY-SHOES sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   HIS name has been stepped on, dragged through the mud, and
smeared in just about every way - mostly by children.
	   But he is not some unfortunate victim of malicious mouthing - he
is in fact, Thomas J. Bata, whose name adorns every school-going
child's shoes.
	   At 83, Bata, who opened the newest retail outlet at KLCC in
Kuala Lumpur on Saturday, is a sprightly, browned version of Santa
Claus, snowy hair and all. Conspicuously absent are the elves,
dancing at his fingertips.
	   ``Yes, I wore Bata shoes as a child,'' he says, answering a
million-dollar question.
	   And now?
	   ``Now I mostly wear Bata shoes. But I also wear other shoes
because that is the only way to make a comparison,'' he says
triumphantly, neatly sidestepping what could have been an awkward
question.
	   ``And,'' he says warming up, ``sometimes I wear a different shoe
on each foot!''
	   Bata was born into a shoe-making family. Twelve generations ago,
an ancestral member of the Bata clan decided that farm prices were
too low, and that shoes were a better business.
	   In 1894, Thomas' father, Tomas, converted that hand-operated
business to a machine-manufactured one, and the Bata shoe empire
was born.
	   ``See, I have even developed a shoemaker's thumb,'' he says,
waving a thumb that curves sharply backwards, usually acquired by
cobblers who cut leather by hand.
	   Born in Prague, Czechoslovakia, just before the First World War,
Bata's childhood was filled with sporting activities like horseback
riding, skiing in the winter and swimming in the summer.
	   His early schooling took place in England and Switzerland, and
his degrees (including a Doctor of Sciences) were obtained in
Czechoslovakia.
	   At the age of 24, he emigrated to Canada, where he has lived for
the past 59 years.
	   His English, though flawless, is still heavily-inflected with an
Eastern European accent.
	   And he is still as active as ever.
	   Hours after stepping off a plane from Oslo, Norway, he entered
the interview room, leaning heavily on a cane. One could have been
forgiven for assuming that this was a sign of age. But no, the cane
was because he ``skied stupidly'' and is at the tail-end of
recovery from a broken leg.
	   As the only child, was the pressure on him to take over the
business?
	   ``I never really wanted to get out of it,'' he says, again
circumventing the real question.
	   But would his father have been disappointed if he hadn't shown
any interest?
	   ``Perhaps. But if I had wanted to become a doctor, for example,
I don't think he would have stopped me. And if I had become a good
doctor, he would even have been pleased.''
	   However, there seems to have been no danger of a lack of
interest.
	   At age 16, the younger Bata got directly involved when, on his
own drawing-board, he tried to improve the models the company was
then producing.
	   He remained as involved in designing until the age of 60, which
means that those still in school in 1975 may have worn shoes
created by the man himself.
	   Bata shoes first made their appearance in Malaya in 1930, when a
retail outlet was opened in Capitol Street, Singapore. Through many
periods of corporate restructuring and growth, Bata Malaysia, which
manufactures and retails, was established.
	   To date, school shoes remain the best-selling item.
	   Due to its ubiquitous quality here, and its seeming absence in
some Western countries, many have mistaken Bata for a local brand.
	   But although Bata may not retail under its own name in these
places, the company supplies some models to other retailers, such
as Marks and Spencers.
	   In fact, in Indonesia, Thailand and Chile, Bata also makes shoes
for Adidas, Nike and New Balance.
	   However, there is no likelihood that the Bata brand-name will be
phased out. Transcending the boundaries of icon, it has become an
institution. My wordprocessing programme which underlines Prada
with a disapproving red line, has no such trouble with Bata.
	   In the words of Thomas J. Bata: ``We do not aspire to be in a
super luxury class. Our ambition is to serve a wider range of the
population with first-class, progressive products at a reasonable
price.''
	   Bata Bites: Bata Shoe Organisation Ltd is named after its
Czechoslovakian founder Tomas Bata.
	   The company's headquarters are in Toronto, Canada.
	   The first Bata outlet in Malaysia was opened in Jalan Pudu,
Kuala Lumpur.
	   Bata has two factories in Malaysia, one in Klang, the other in
Seremban.
	   In 1997, Bata Malaysia exported 2.5 million pairs of shoes to
Europe and North America. Italy alone bought nearly 500,000 pairs.
	   In the same year, 11.5 million pairs, largely school shoes, were
sold in Malaysia.
	   Twenty-five per cent of total annual sales come from Asia.
	   There are 250 Bata stores in the country.
	   Besides Selangor and the Federal Territory, which have 60
stores, the state with the largest number of stores is Johor, with
30.
	   Sabah has the least number of outlets, at 13.
	   The latest Bata outlet which is 2,700 square metres big, opened
at KLCC in Kuala Lumpur on Saturday.
	   This year, Bata Malaysia will open more big outlets in: Miri,
Kuantan, Johor Baru, Ipoh, Malacca, Kuala Terengganu, Kota Kinabalu
and Penang.
	   Bata Malaysia also runs Athlete's World, which carries a variety
of athletic products.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:QUALITY-SHOES sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
