Council to improve drainage in flood-prone areas, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws FLOOD-PRONE-AREAS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE Petaling Jaya Municipal Council will improve drainage in
flood-prone areas.
	   Its president Mohamad Nor Bador said the council could not carry
out too many projects at the same time and needed the co-operation
of residents in keeping drains clean.
	   ``Residents should not only depend on the council to clean up
drains.
	   They should hold gotong-royong sessions to clean up their
areas,'' he added.
	   He said clogged drains could be due to complacence on behalf of
council workers who knew that Alam Flora Sdn Bhd would be taking
over drain cleaning services from July 1.
	   ``We realise the problem and the council will try its best to
accommodate the needs of the people,'' he added.
	   Meanwhile, councillor Raja Ropiah Raja Abdullah said the council
should look into the widening and cleaning of clogged drains as
preparation for the impending weather conditions, which are
expected to bring heavy rainfall to the region.
	   She said the council had to act fast as it should not be blamed
later for poor planning.
	   ``This is important as we do not want people to blame the
council later for not preparing for the floods,'' she said.
	   
</TEXT>
