<SLUG> BC-Israel-El Al,0174 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israel decides against selling off most of El Al 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israel on Monday decided to retain ownership of
51 percent of the national air carrier El Al, despite
recommendations the unprofitable company be sold off.
	   A statement from the ministerial committee overseeing Israel's
privatization plans quoted Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu as
saying the decision ``will protect our national interests.''
	   Israel radio said national security and emergency situations
were key factors in the decision to retain a majority share of the
airline.
	   The decision ensures that El Al flights will continue to be
grounded during the Jewish Sabbath _ from Friday sundown to
Saturday sundown. The Sabbath groundings have been cited as a
factor in the company's losses.
	   A government panel had recommended that the airline be sold off
by this year. El Al lost dlrs 83 million in 1996 and dlrs 35
million last year.
	   No date has been set for selling off 49 percent of the company.
</TEXT>
