w1401  wstm-
r w     TURNING-JUNKsked     06-01 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> TURNING-JUNK sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Turning `junk' into collector's items, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws TURNING-JUNK sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   R. GUNA could go on and on about Remington Steel - not the TV
sleuth, but his favourite typewriter.
	   His Remington is about 45 years old, of semi-standard issue,
weighs slightly over three kilogrammes and is silent.
	   Guna also has a Remington Rand, a portable, in his shop. Both
Remingtons can fetch up to RM1,000 each.
	   Guna loves old typewriters which others would dismiss as junk.
	   The Remington and Royal typewriters were both popular in the
1950s, he says. The American-made Royal is distinguished by its
letters on cardboard, placed on the transparent keytops. It is neat
and smaller in size, and was popular in the past with planters who
bought them for their wives to type those lengthy letters home.
	   Look around the shop and one can find names like Imperial
(British-made), Roneo (UK), Hermes (Swiss) and Olivetti (Italy).
	   The shop is a mass of old keyboards, spare parts and gadgets
haphazardly heaped along dusty shelves.
	   Guna inherited the business in 1977 after the death of his
father. As he was the only one interested in carrying on the
business, he quit his job as a costing and store clerk at
McAlister's in Jalan Kidd and, with the help of his father's friend
Khoo Swee Yong, started repairing and reconditioning typewriters.
	   His father had started the shop in 1951, servicing typewriters
for plantations, banks, Government departments and hospitals.
	   For instance, said Guna, ``we have been making office calls at
United Plantations since 1957. It was then known as Bernam Oil
Plantations.''
	   From servicing of typewriters, customers later asked him to
repair those which had broken down. A repair job could take two
months and cost from RM300 to RM600 inclusive of spare parts, he
said.
	   ``Many people opt to repair these `antiques' because they trust
these machines more than modern ones,'' he said.
	   Guna has lovingly restored, polished and fine-tuned machines
left by customers who never returned for them. Restoration work is
time-consuming and has to be done on a trial-and-error basis.
	   He said a typewriter between 30 and 40 years old can be sold for
between RM800 and RM1,000 to collectors and writers. Some banks,
for instance, still keep their old typewriters for sentimental
reasons.
	   Added Guna: ``One can ascertain a typewriter's quality by the
impression of the typewritten characters.
	   ``The old ones also tend to be rust-free since they are made of
steel.
	   The type of ribbons used also differs,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:TURNING-JUNK sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
