w1408  wstm-
r w     BEAUTIFUL-AND-BRIGHTsked     06-01 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BEAUTIFUL-AND-BRIGHT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Beautiful and bright balsam, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws BEAUTIFUL-AND-BRIGHT sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   NOTHING is more invigorating than being greeted by colourful
annuals and other garden shrubs and creepers when you step out
first thing in the morning. We complain about the warmth and
dryness outside, but this time of year - hot, dry periods - brings
out the best in summer flowering plants. Plan your planting; select
species to suit your needs. As I often say, planting garden annuals
and herbaceous perennials is not particularly difficult and
involves only digging the soil to a reasonable depth, bringing in
organic material to upgrade its organic status and moisture
retention, as well as coarse sand for all-important soil aeration
and drainage, to ensure healthy plant growth.
	   Here are some of the colourful annuals you can try your hand at.
They are not difficult to raise from packet seeds; an average of 20
or 30 seedlings are easily obtainable from one small packet of
seeds costing about RM2.50. Annual seedlings planted in a small
polybag will cost between RM1 and RM2 each, depending on variety
and species.
	   Balsams
	   This colourful annual flower is easy to grow and will reward you
with lovely blooms in about eight weeks. The plant flowers right up
to two or three weeks before it dies. Balsams love the sun and are
not choosy about soil type, provided there is good drainage,
organic matter and moisture.
	   It can tolerate a certain amount of shade.
	   Yates' Superb Double Mixture seeds, readily available in the
country, have all the finest colours and lovely blooms; an example
is the camellia.
	   The plant will grow up to 45cm high. It will do best in raised
beds prepared beforehand with a liberal dressing of well-rotted
organic manure or compost; this will provide moisture retention and
fertility. Balsams are very vigorous growers and respond well if
soil is well-prepared and mulched.
	   The mulch can be, simply, dried grass clippings. Lawn clippings
should not be discarded, as they can be useful mulching or compost
material that will eventually be returned to the soil.
	   Balsam seeds are fairly large (half the size of the green pea)
and can be sown directly into the soil (or polybag or pots - one
seed will be enough); sow seeds 3-4mm deep.
	   Seedlings should be spaced 30cm between rows and 25cm between
plants.
	   This should give the actively-growing seedlings lots of room to
develop into healthy plants, with maximum flowering capacity.
	   The plants should be well-watered twice a day; A layer of
organic mulch will help keep surface roots cool and moist.
Flowering should begin six or seven weeks from sowing. In Malaysia,
balsam has always been a popular flower, especially in school
gardens, because it is so easy to grow and has bright colours,
ranging from white to pink to wine.
	   Portulaca
	   Portulaca is another dazzling, colourful annual. Once it
matures, it will flower continuously; flowering is rather
short-lived, but there is prolific bud formation. This helps keep
up flower production, especially during the four or five hours of
the morning before the sun becomes too hot. Flowering portulaca
looks like a carpet of colours - white, pink, red, orange, lilac
and other intermediates.
	   Portulaca is a low-growing succulent annual (or perennial),
boasting lovely rose-like blooms. It is known in Malaysia as the
Japanese Rose. How this name came about is a mystery, because it is
neither Japanese nor a rose! Portulaca was originally found in
Brazil, but it soon spread to all warm parts of the world. It is an
extremely hardy plant. It is herbaceous, and is ideal for rock
gardens and low borders. Leaves are greatly modified into rod-like
structures.
	   The original portulaca is very common in rural areas, where it
is found growing in sandy soil, particularly along the coast. This
species is more of a perennial than an annual. It bears light
purple flowers and blooms during the first half of the day, after
which all its flowers fade; by morning of the next day, though,
flowers burst forth again.
	   New portulaca varieties have now appeared. These are more
colourful than the original purple. In all types, flowering is more
profuse in the late mornings, before it gets too hot.
	   Because the plants have endless flowering stems (the plant grows
in rosette form) and have flowering buds in abundance, flowering
seems to be continuous. As the short-lived flowers fade, new ones
open to take their place.
	   Portulaca is extremely hardy, even in very harsh conditions. It
is common knowledge that to encourage it to flower well, do not
pamper the plant and do not overwater. Over-watering or pampering
with nutrients will lead to a lush growth of foliage at the expense
of flowering.
	   Portulaca thrives in sandy soils and enjoys the sun - the hotter
the better.
	   The plant is propagated by stem cuttings, as well as by seeds.
	   Seeds are very fine and contained in cup-shaped structures.
	   Plants creep along the ground, protecting their roots; they are
excellent in smothering weeds. Plants should be watered in dry
weather, but do not overwater - they prefer rather dry conditions.
	   The plant has single- and double-flowered varieties.
	   Sunnybank double mixed is the most widely-planted, and boasts a
range of bright colours.
	   New varieties you can grow are the Yates' Sunnybank mixed; this
contains both doubles and singles in a wide range of brilliant
colour.
	   Yates'
	   Dazzle Doubles is a fine double-flowered strain of dazzling
colour; this grows to only 8-10cm high and is lovely in hanging
baskets, window boxes, borders and sunny rock gardens. Single mixed
is another showy plant with gorgeous colours. It grows exceedingly
well in hot, dry periods.
	   Portulaca blooms secrete honey and are insect-pollinated; there
are always bees and small insects hovering around the bright
blooms. Most species of portulaca have mucilaginous, often acidic
(malic acid) stems and foliage. Portulaca oleracea is edible and is
a pot herb.
	   Salvia
	   This is another garden annual popular in subtropical and warm
climates.
	   This brilliant bedding plant was once believed to have medicinal
properties and it derived its name from the Latin word salveo - to
heal.
	   Salvia splendens from Brazil can grow up to 30-45cm high in the
tropics.
	   Modern cultivations tend to be more compact.
	   `Blaze of Fire' is a variant of the splendens - the vivid red
bracts that hold the scarlet flowers are borne closely on long
spikes, and are spectacular in full bloom.
	   Other forms exist - white and mauve, to deep purple. These are
much sought-after for landscaped gardens.
	   Another, the blue salvia (Salvia farinacea), is another that can
be a centre of attraction amid reds. Salvia farinacea is the mealy
sage from Texas, with a flower like lavender's, of deep violet with
white wooly bracts and stems. This can grow to 60 cm high and is
ideal for cuttings for vases. It has oval, aromatic leaves, and is
excellent in open beds.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
