<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
`No problem for Muhammad to resume V-P post', NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws MUHAMMAD-TO-RESUME-V-P sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sun. - Umno secretary-general Datuk Sabbaruddin
Chik does not foresee any problem for former Selangor Menteri Besar
Tan Sri Muhammad Muhammad Taib to continue serving as the party
vice-president.
	   However, he said, the Umno supreme council which would meet on
June 8, would discuss the matter at length and decide on Muhammad's
position.
	   ``He did not resign, but merely took leave before the conclusion
of his court case in Brisbane as he did not want to tarnish Umno's
name. If that is the reason, there is no problem for him to resume
as the vice-president.''
	   He was asked about Muhammad's status in Umno following his
acquittal by a district court in Brisbane on two counts of falsely
declaring the money he was bringing into Australia on Dec 16, 1996
and failing to declare more than A$1.26 million (RM2.9 million)
when leaving for New Zealand six days later.
	   He said this after launching the local entrepreneurs exhibition
themed ``To Know Malaysia is to Love Malaysia'' at Dataran Merdeka,
organised by the MCA.
	   
</TEXT>
