<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Iraq,0507 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Butler headed for Baghdad this month for more weapons talks 
</HEADLINE>
By ROBERT H. REID
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Under pressure to speed up U.N. weapons
inspections in Iraq, the chief U.N. inspector will travel to
Baghdad this month in a renewed effort to account for all the
banned weapons Iraq reportedly held before the 1991 Persian Gulf
War.
	   U.N. sources said Richard Butler will hold talks June 13-14 with
Iraq's deputy prime minister, Tariq Aziz. Butler hopes to be
carrying a strong message from the Security Council that Iraq must
disclose more information about its weapons programs if it expects
to have crippling economic sanctions lifted.
	   But officials of the U.N. Special Commission, which performs the
inspections, admit privately they have lost ground in the political
battle to convince all 15 council members that serious gaps remain
between what Iraq is known to have held before the 1991 Gulf war
and what it claims to have destroyed.
	   The council imposed sanctions on Iraq in 1990 after President
Saddam Hussein invaded Kuwait. After a U.S.-led coalition drove the
Iraqis from Kuwait, the council decided to maintain sanctions until
the inspectors certify Iraq is free of all long-range missiles and
chemical, biological and nuclear weapons.
	   Iraq claims it has destroyed all illegal weaponry and that the
United States and Britain are manipulating the commission to keep
sanctions indefinitely. Russia, France and China are urging the
commission to accelerate its accounting of Iraqi weapons so that
sanctions can be ended.
	   Butler, an Australian, will attempt to shore up support when he
briefs the council Wednesday. U.N. officials say Butler will
present aerial photographs and other evidence to substantiate his
claims that Iraq has failed to account for significant portions of
its illegal arsenal.
	   To narrow the gap, Butler and his staff met last week at U.N.
headquarters with an Iraqi delegation which included Foreign
Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf and Lt. Gen. Amer al-Saadi, a
senior adviser to Saddam.
	   ``Basically, the Iraqis gave us the same kind of explanations
they've given in the last year,'' said a U.N. source on condition
of anonymity. ``They claim to have provided all the documents to
the commission. The commission has different ideas.''
	   U.N. and Iraqi experts have been excavating sites near Baghdad
where the Iraqis say they destroyed missile warheads capable of
carrying chemical and biological agents.
	   The source said that operation brought the two sides ``close to
a full accounting'' on missile warheads. As a result, he said, the
commission may be able to end its missile inspections in October.
	   But the source said progress in accounting for Iraq's chemical
and biological weapons programs has been slower. For example, he
said, Baghdad has offered production records for 1988 and 1989 for
the deadly nerve agent VX. But the commission suspects Iraq was
able to produce several tons of VX in 1990.
</TEXT>
