w1414  wstm-
r w     THE-PLANT-LICE-MENACEske     06-01 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> THE-PLANT-LICE-MENACE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Destroying the plant lice menace, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws THE-PLANT-LICE-MENACE sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   APHIDS, or plant lice, are small, soft-bodied insects that feed
on plants by sucking out their fluids, or sap.
	   They are about the size of a small grain of rice. They range in
colour from pale green to red. They have a white woolly coating.
	   Often named for the type of plants they destroy, aphids survive
by sucking out the plant juices of soft and fleshy new growth. This
damages the plant's ability to process food.
	   You will usually find aphids among ornamental or fruit trees by
checking newly-formed leaves and buds. Distorted young leaves with
a grayish cast are sure signs of the pest's presence.
	   Aphids also excrete a sticky coating onto leaves.
	   These insects are easy to detect; turn over a damaged leaf and
you are sure to find a cluster of the culprits.
	   How they feed Aphids feed by sucking out plant sap with their
piercing mouth parts; they use slim, needle-sharp stylets in their
beaks, with which they pierce stems, leaves, buds, roots and fruit.
	   In badly-ravaged plants, aphids may cause leaves to curl or may
stunt a plant's growth. This will hinder its production of flower
or fruit.
	   Eventually, the plant may die.
	   Aphids also introduce fungi, bacteria and even viral diseases,
that can be as damaging as the aphids themselves.
	   Aphids expel, from the end of their abdomen, a rather sticky,
sweet substance called ``honeydew'', a favourite food of some
species of ants.
	   These ants move the aphids to productive plants, thus helping
spread the pests.
	   Control The first step to controlling aphids is inspecting new
growth for any tell-tale signs. You can wash off the slow-moving
pests with a slow jet of water from the garden hose.
	   For more serious infestations, use suitable insecticides
available at garden centres. Check the label carefully.
	   Other ways to fight aphids: Destroy them by hand - Rub an
infected leaf between thumb and forefinger. Be careful not to
damage leaves.
	   Wash them away - Mix insecticide with soap and use it to rinse
away the aphid population. Mala-thion will do the job. Sometimes,
insecticidal soap can be used to good effect - otherwise, mix your
own.
	   White oil - Abarol or albolenium are formulated to destroy
soft-bodied sucking insects. Follow instructions; exceeding the
recommended dosage can cause foliage burn.
	   Ladybirds are beneficial insects which feed on aphids. Ladybirds
and lacewings are natural enemies of aphids; in Nature, they and
other beneficial insects feed on aphids and their grubs.
	   Controlling ants is another way of putting an end to the menace,
because the ants spread aphids to healthy plants.
	   Ants are said to rub the bellies of the smaller insects, causing
them to excrete the ``honeydew'' the ants feed on. Spray plants
with an insecticide against ants.
	   Systemic insecticides Use systemic insecticides to control these
sucking pests more effectively. These are most commonly used to
fight aphids. Plants absorb these chemicals into their systems.
They do not harm plants, but when the aphids suck up the sap, they
quickly die.
	   Where sucking insects are concerned, ordinary contact
insecticides that control biting insects are useless because the
pests do not eat plant tissue, they suck only the sap through their
hollow needle-like mouths.
	   Rogor or Dime-thoate is a suitable systemic.
	   Whichever insecticide you choose, follow directions closely for
safe and effective use. Then wash your hands and face with lots of
water.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
