<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Privatization </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia slashes price for oil company it couldn't sell 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The Russian government lowered the price for the
Rosneft state oil company to dlrs 1.6 billion on Monday, after
failing to sell it last week for dlrs 2.1 billion.
	   The government wants to sell 75 percent of Rosneft, both to
raise much-needed cash and to show that its privatization program
is working.
	   Several oil companies indicated interest in Rosneft, Russia's
fifth largest oil company. But Russia's young stock market has
crashed since the sale was planned last fall and the price of oil
has also plummeted on world markets.
	   The sale was seen as a major test for President Boris Yeltsin's
new Cabinet, which has said it would carry out further
privatizations without bestowing any special favors on the
country's politically powerful commercial banks.
	   The sale was suspended last Tuesday when the government received
no bids. In announcing the new price of 9.8 billion rubles (dlrs
1.6 billion), Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko did not say how long
the bidding process would remain open this time.
	   (ls) 	   
</TEXT>
