<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 15:29:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1420  wstm-
r w     NOBEL-LABOUR-OF-LOVEsked     06-01 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> NOBEL-LABOUR-OF-LOVE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Nobel laureate's labour of love, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws NOBEL-LABOUR-OF-LOVE sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   I FIRST made Professor Yuan T. Lee's acquaintance through his
five-page curriculum vitae. A notable scientist whose highest
achievement has been winning the 1986 Nobel prize for chemistry,
Lee's accomplishments consist of a seemingly endless list of
fellowships and awards, honorary appointments, academic positions
and lectureships.
	   Sixty-one-year-old Lee has recently opened a new chapter in his
life. After living in the United States for 32 years, four years
ago he gave up American citizenship and returned to his homeland,
Taiwan, and became president of Taipeh's prestigious Academia
Sinica.
	   ``I thought I would be too old if I didn't come home,'' he says,
laughing.
	   Lee left for the US to pursue a doctrate in chemistry in 1962,
and then dedicated his life to research.
	   His purpose in returning to the Far East was a noble one; he
hoped to raise the standard of research and improve the education
system in Taiwan and Southeast Asia.
	   ``If you work hard, you can conduct world-class research in
Southeast Asia,'' he says. ``I decided if I do not raise the
standard of chemistry research to the highest level in the world,
my returning to Taiwan won't mean very much.''
	   After six months as Academia Sinica president, Lee took up a new
challenge, heading the Council for Educational Reform; he has spent
two years working to improve education in Taiwan.
	   ``I believe people can be educated to change things for the
better,'' he says. ``But I can't do very much alone, and I hope to
persuade established scientists and academicians to get involved.''
	   Talking to Lee is like talking to a walking encyclopaedia. The
scope of his knowledge is vast, not limited to chemistry or
science. And he is a man of many concerns, especially in the
humanities, economics, social sciences and education.
	   He recently spoke at a seminar in Kuala Lumpur entitled ``Asian
financial shocks, high-technology and economic growth''. ``I'm not
an expert on the economy or monetary system, but I'm concerned
about the future of Southeast Asia - what we are doing and where
we're heading,'' says Lee.
	   ``Whenever I'm asked to do something, it is a challenge. I may
not know very much, but I learn. Life is a long learning process,''
he adds.
	   Lee was born in 1936 in Hsinchu, Taiwan, to an artist father and
schoolteacher mother. He had a colourful and fun-filled elementary
and secondary education in Hsinchu, where he was actively involved
in sports and music.
	   The turning point in his life came when he was 16.
	   ``I fell ill and was in hospital for a month. I was thinking to
myself what the meaning of life is and who I would become.''
	   An avid reader, Lee found the biography of Madame Curie
fascinating. It was Curie's dedication to science and her
selflessness and idealism that influenced him to study science.
	   ``For the first time, it hit me that you can achieve something
when you have ideals,'' says Lee. ``Madame Curie was a very
idealistic person who believed knowledge belongs to all
humankind.''
	   Aside from his ambition to become a scientist, Lee's other wish
was to change tradition and transform society.
	   ``China was so poor and there was much political unrest after
the war. I wasn't happy about the situation in society. I believe
there's a need to reform and change, and that we should work hard
to transform society.''
	   After completing his first and second degrees in chemistry in
Taiwan, he won a scholarship to pursue his doctorate at the
Univesity of California at Berkeley.
	   It was a very different but interesting experience for Lee and
wife Bernice Wu.
	   ``We came from closely-knit extended families. But in America,
we were uprooted and isolated; we knew nobody,'' says Lee. ``Then I
found I had all the time in the world for science.''
	   For the first four years, Lee was totally immersed in science
and forgot educational and social reformation. As there were few
Chinese students in America at the time, Lee put in his best to
prove that Chinese could do as well as Americans.
	   He developed an interest in crossed molecualr beams, studying
reaction dynamics. Upon receiving his Ph.D in 1965, he stayed to
conduct more experiments and research as a post-doctoral fellow,
under Professor Dudley Herschbach at Harvard.
	   Lee accepted a position as assistant professor in the chemistry
department of the University of Chicago in October 1968, and began
his illustrious academic career. From 1974 to 1991, Lee was
professor of chemistry there and at the University of California,
Berkeley.
	   He became an American citizen in 1974. His three children were
born in the United States.
	   In 1986, Lee won the Nobel prize for chemistry with his mentor
Herschbach and colleague John Polanyi, for the development of
chemical reaction dynamics.
	   But he confesses he never worked to win the prize.
	   ``I just wanted to be a good scientist and contribute to
society,'' he says. ``I was interested in solving problems and
doing things no one is able to. I do not believe anything is
impossible.
	   ``This is something young people do not understand. They look at
us and think we sacrifice so much time and energy. But I enjoy my
work immensely.
	   To me it is much more fun than going out and playing baseball.
When you carry out a successful experiment when no one in the world
knew it would work, it is really very exciting.''
	   Lee is one of five Chinese Nobel laureates in history and the
only one born in Taiwan and who has won in chemistry (the others
won for physics).
	   Winning the Nobel prize has changed his life.
	   ``A Nobel laureate is expected to be spokesperson for his field.
I was asked by the university, by the state of California, by the
US, and even by the government and people of Taiwan and China.''
Lee travelled around the world helping scientists in countries as
far-flung as Italy, France and Japan; he spoke at numerous
conferences and conventions.
	   ``I became very busy and was spending less time in the
laboratory,'' he says. ``On one hand I wanted to do more science,
but on the other I wanted to help people. My loyalty was even
questioned by the White House because I was helping the Taiwanese
government. Suddenly, I thought: `Jeez, things are getting so
complicated!'''
	   Lee then decided he should zero in on something, thus his plan
to leave America and return to Taiwan to promote scientific
research and education.
	   His decision was welcomed by many Asian intellectuals,
scientists and academicians.
	   ``When you work hard, it doesn't matter where you are as long as
you're contributing,'' he says.
	   ``It wouldn't make much of a difference if I serve in the United
States, as there are other great scientists. But by returning home,
my presence will make a difference in Taiwan.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:NOBEL-LABOUR-OF-LOVE sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
