<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Tokyo: Lower, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws TOKYO-LOWER sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   JAPANESE share prices closed 0.8 per cent lower yesterday with
market sentiment hit by Pakistan's nuclear tests and the yen's fall
against the dollar, brokers said.
	   The Nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange dropped 125.77 points to close at 15,670.78, while
the broader Topix index of all first section issues edged down 2.24
points to 1,221.49.
	   Turnover on the major board totalled an estimated 320 million
shares, up from Thursday's 270.2 million shares.
	   Share prices lost direction after an early round of dealer-led
activity ran out of steam, with investors sidelined ahead of the
weekend, brokers said.
	   Earlier, the yen's sharp fall past 139 against the dollar
pressured the market, together with uncertainty over the Asian
economic and political situation following Pakistan's nuclear
tests, they said.
	   But share prices closed above a low of 15,604.70 thanks to
``buying support by public sector pension funds which bought into
high-weighting issues in banks and other sector leaders'', one
broker said.
	   The release of poor employment data, which showed the nation's
unemployment rate soared to a record high of 4.1 per cent, had a
limited impact on share prices, brokers said.
	   Slowing selling by foreign investors also helped share prices
move off their lows, with some foreign investors beginning to buy
into selected blue-chip issues with good earnings fundamentals,
they said.
	   But share prices failed to move into positive territory due to a
lack of follow-through buying, with a wait-and-see mood spreading
in the afternoon session ahead of the weekend, they said.
	   
</TEXT>
