<TEXT>
	   SHARE prices closed up slightly on Wall Street on Thursday, but
gains were limited because traders were nervous about the
continuing troubles in Asia.
	   The Dow Jones index of 30 blue chips rose 33.63 points (0.38 per
cent) to 8,970.20 on bargain-hunting. Share prices rose and fell
throughout the day.
	   The market closed down 27 points on Wednesday, after sliding 175
points one day previously because of unease over Asia's economic
woes and its consequences for US companies.
	   Then on Thursday, the US government revised upward its estimate
on US economic growth for the first quarter from an annualised 4.2
per cent to 4.8 per cent as strong consumer and business spending
was offset by a weak trade sector due to the Asian financial
problem.
	   But growth is expected even as export sales to Asia shrink,
analysts said.
	   Exports have also been reduced since the dollar is at its
highest level against the yen in eight years, making Japanese goods
relatively less expensive, said John Lonski, the principal
economist for the Wall Street rating firm Moody's.
	   On the bond market, the average yield of the US Treasury
Department's benchmark 30-year bonds remained stable at 5.832 per
cent down from 5.837 per cent.
	   Among the gainers, Boeing rose 3/8 to 46-13/13 despite
announcing Wednesday that its business would be hurt by Asia's
economic woes.
	   Banking issues rose, with Citicorp up 1-1/16 to 150 and
NationsBank was up 13/16 at 76. Chrysler rose up 2-3/16 to 56-15/16
after the annual meeting of Daimler-Benz shareholders. Daimler rose
4-9/16 to 100-1/2.
	   
</TEXT>
