w1429  wstm-
r w     A-MIGHTY-SHAMEsked     06-01 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> A-MIGHTY-SHAME sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Godzie - a `mighty' shame, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws A-MIGHTY-SHAME sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THIS gargantuan film (we're talking about the hype surrounding
it, not its merit!) can be summed up in two words: physical
tragedy.
	   It has special effects that are nothing less than stunning and,
ermmm, nothing else much.
	   The story revolves around Godzilla making its way to New York,
leaving the usual, if uninspired, trail of destruction.
	   Supporting this computer-generated imagery (CGI) Godzilla are
Matthew Broderick in the lead as nuclear scientist Dr Nick
Tatopoulos; Jean Reno as French spy Philippe Roche; Hank Azaria as
a cameraman named Animal and Maria Pitillo as the pitiful Audrey -
pitiful because she is forced upon an unsuspecting audience.
	   None of these cardboard cutouts adds any originality to their
performances.
	   However - strangely - it must be confessed that Azaria has more
screen presence than Broderick. And Godzilla in turn, has more than
all of them put together.
	   Safe to say, throughout this feeding tube of a movie, the only
pondering viewers are apt to do is to ask why Godzilla chose New
York.
	   And even then, this could be easily attributed to the
re-awakening of some long dormant and ancient instinct, probably
memories of the prehistoric supercontinent, Pangaea, or something
like that.
	   Then again, it could also be the attraction of the trendy
lifestyle in the city that never sleeps and its superb skyline. One
can never be sure about these things nowadays! Anyway, for an
audience weaned on Steven Spielberg's Jurassic Park and its sequel,
The Lost World, or the CGI-laden box-office bomb Dragonheart,
there's nothing new or groundbreaking in Godzilla in terms of
special effects, except maybe for the creature, which even then
looks like a cross between the artist H.R. Giger's Alien and a
scowling T-Rex (Jurassic Park).
	   Godzilla is basically a pastiche of other blockbusters - Godzie
downtown is like Mrs T-Rex in San Diego looking for her little one
in The Lost World; Godzie underwater is like the swimming aliens in
Alien Resurrection; Godzie being target practised upon is like King
Kong, and, of course, landmarks going down is similar to what
happened in Independence Day (ID4).
	   Surprisingly, the first teasing glimpses of the gigantic CGI
creature's tail and feet as it runs swerving behind one building or
another seem so unreal and do not mesh with the surrounding.
	   Only in the darkened scenes (underground tunnels, underwater or
during nighttime) does the mighty CGI Godzilla look believable.
	   One thing that really needs saying is the mannerism of the
towering beast, which is very real, especially when its suspicions
are aroused as the humans try and bait it for the second time.
	   The single most memorable scene has to be when the creature
dives into the sea to escape its pesky tormentors, only to face
armed submarines.
	   Also striking are the scenes depicting Godzilla's flammable
breath, if that's what it is, in two incidences.
	   As for scale, this Godzilla is sometimes dwarfed by the tall
buildings in New York.
	   It does not often come across the way the hulking Godzilla of
yore did in those kitschy Japanese shows that we used to see on
television long ago.
	   It must be said that for a nation that has been tracking the
beast, the US sure is ill-prepared to grapple with the situation
when Godzilla comes a-calling.
	   And where is the camcorder brigade that is always in every nook
and cranny capturing everything on video for posterity Stateside?
The only first glimpse of Godzilla that the New Yorkers see on
their tellys are bad visuals taken by Animal.
	   For those looking for a huge dose of destruction in the exact
same vein as dished out in ID4 in 1996, it'll be good to hear that
New York's landmarks are destroyed willy nilly.
	   For dessert, there is the squadron of helicopters swarming in on
Godzilla, only to be outsmarted and crunched by the beast during
the first round of their encounter.
	   Unlike ID4 (made by the same director-producer team of Roland
Emmerich and Dean Devlin), this film's weakness is that it does not
have memorable characters with whom audiences can emotionally lock
onto.
	   Godzilla's cutesy characters spewing effortlessly-digestable
inanities pale in comparison to ID4's screen magnet Will Smith.
	   If the serious anti-nuclear message at the core of the movie
does not come across, the blame must squarely fall on the
filmmakers who have sacrificed substance (in the screenplay) for
cheesy lines.
	   It is sad that the film leaves no room for its characters to
ponder on the folly of their ways although it is firmly established
that Godzilla is the mutated result of the undersea nuclear testing
conducted by the French.
	   Everyone in the film takes Godzilla to be the bad guy who must
be destroyed.
	   The creature eats fish, for Godssake - he does not go around
chomping people. Well... except for a few misplaced stomps here and
there.
	   While we're at it, the soundtrack is not memorable at all and
neither is the creature's vocal performance.
	   Verdict: This is a morally-unsound movie - a true-blue denizen
of the 90s would be appalled when the actors on screen applaud as
Godzilla collapses at the end.
	   Folks, this year's event movie just got dumber.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:A-MIGHTY-SHAME sked; CT:w; 
