<HEADLINE>
26:22.75, fixes typos, fixes slug to fit style Gebrselassie sets new men's 10,000-meter record 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: COMBINES pvs, changes Gebrselassie's official time to
<TEXT>
	   HENGELO, Netherlands (AP) _ Ethiopian Haile Gebrselassie
bettered the men's 10,000 meter world record by five seconds
Monday, finishing in 26 minutes 22.77 seconds at the Adriaan Paulen
Memorial track meet.
	   He shattered the nine-month old mark of 26:27.85 set by Kenyan
Paul Tergat in Brussels on August 27 last year.
	   Gebrselassie ran the last ten laps of the track with only lapped
runners for company after the last of the five Ethiopian pacemakers
he'd brought along dropped back.
	   The Ethiopian clocked a half-way split time of 13:11.53 over the
first five kilometers.
	   Gerbrselassie made the most of a sunny and almost windless early
evening here, and encouragement from lapped compatriot Habte Jifar,
who chased him round the final circuit.
	   Earlier in the meet, African male athletes scored three
season-best times over the middle distances.
	   Kenyan Wilson Boit Kipketer set a 3,000-meters time of 7:36.05,
besting Moroccan Brahim Lahlafi in a close finish.
	   And there was a Kenyan 1-2-3 in the 3000 meters steeplechase as
Bernard Barmassai came home in 8:11.57, ahead of Julius Chelule and
Patrick Sang.
	   Barmassai's time sliced 8.29 seconds off American Mark Croghan's
previous best time of this season.
	   And it was the turn of Moroccan Hicham El Guerrouj to lead the
world this year in the 1,500 meters, winning in 3:31.19, some way
ahead of Frenchman Nadir Bosch and Julius Achon of Uganda.
	   The second world record attempt of the day proved a flop as
Australian Emma George failed to better her own record mark of 4.59
meters in the women's pole vault.
	   In fact, George couldn't clear the bar at all. She failed three
times at 4.30, the height she came in on.
	   And the same height won her American rival Stecey Dragila the
competition.
	   (sc)	   
</TEXT>
