r w     MAS-RECORDS-PRE-TAX-LOSS     06-01 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> MAS-RECORDS-PRE-TAX-LOSS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
MAS records pre-tax loss of RM225.36m, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws MAS-RECORDS-PRE-TAX-LOSS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   MALAYSIAN Airline System Bhd recorded a group pre-tax loss of
RM225.36 million for the year ended March 31, 1998, from a pre-tax
profit of RM349.56 million previously.
	   At the company level, pre-tax loss stood at RM226.25 million
against a pre-tax profit of RM328.23 million previously.
	   After providing for taxation of RM31.27 million, the group's
after-tax loss was RM256.64 million while group loss per share was
33.7 sen from a group earnings per share of 43.8 sen last year.
	   Group turnover grew 8.7 per cent to RM7.051 billion and
investment and other income dropped by one per cent to RM102.69
million.
	   Group cashflow per share improved by 76 sen or 52.1 per cent
from RM1.46 to RM2.22.
	   MAS said in a statement performance was affected by the decline
in traffic demand, escalation of costs and foreign exchange losses,
particularly in the second half due to the economic situation in
the region and the weak ringgit.
	   The group suffered a translation loss of RM3.487 billion
compared to a translation gain of RM164.2 million last year, on
revaluation of long-term foreign monetary assets and liabilities.
	   However, as the borrowings were mainly to finance the
acquisition of aircraft, the costs of which were denominated in the
US dollar, the appreciation in aircraft book value was
approximately RM4.8 billion at RM3.64 to US$1.
	   The statement said as only translation loss for long-term
foreign assets and liabilities were amortised, an exchange loss of
RM620.9 million was booked in.
	   During the year, the group also incurred an exchange loss of
RM97.5 million on operating transactions, provided RM165.2 million
for doubtful debts and RM48.6 million for its Year 2000 Compliance
programme.
	   The statement said in the year under review, the group entered
into sale and leaseback arrangement for 11 aircraft and seven spare
engines and sold an Airbus A300B. These transactions resulted in a
total gain of RM620 million.
	   A gain of RM136.9 million was also derived from divestment of
aircraft engine repair and overhaul business unit to an associated
company.
	   During the year under review, MAS took delivery of six B777-200,
three B747-400, one B737-400 aircraft and deferred the deliveries
of three B747- 400 aircraft.
	   The statement also said that MAS' capacity, inclusive of
freighter operation, expanded 4.3 per cent to 6,411.3 million
tonne-kilometres while traffic grew at a rate of 4.9 per cent to
3,887.7 million tonne-kilometres.
	   Overall load factor improved by 0.3 percentage points to 60.6
per cent while passenger load declined 1.7 percentage points to
67.9 per cent.
	   The airline's outlook for the current financial year was that
demand for air travel would remain weak.
	   It said the economic problems in the Asian region would affect
intra-Asian travel while outbound traffic from Malaysia and
domestic travel would drop further if the economic situation did
not improve.
	   However, the statement added, the undervalued ringgit, the 16th
Commonwealth Games in September and some other major international
events should encourage inbound traffic into Malaysia and also
enhance awareness of the country for future travel.
	   Expected keen competition will continue to exert pressure on
yield.
	   Costs are expected to remain high.
	   
</TEXT>
