<HEADER>
w1440  wstm-
r w     ASIA'S-DYNAMIC-GROWTHske     06-01 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> ASIA'S-DYNAMIC-GROWTH sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Musa: Asia's dynamic growth lulled people into complacency, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws ASIA'S-DYNAMIC-GROWTH sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sun. - Before facing the current economic
problems, Asia's dynamic economic growth, dubbed the Asian Miracle,
provided its citizens with a success which lulled them to
complacency.
	   ``It is common knowledge the manner Asians were shopping at
shopping centres of the world ... Paris, Milan, London, New York,''
former Deputy Prime Minister Tan Sri Musa Hitam said.
	   ``They were shopping like their counterparts who came from far
more developed economies with little concern for being frugal. We
didn't know how to manage monies ourselves ...'' he said.
	   ``Currently, many of us, are reeling from this trouble.
Indonesia, Korea Thailand, Malaysia and Singapore ... all of us are
feeling it,'' Musa, who is chairman of Lion Land Berhad, said.
	   He said this when closing the four-day Harvard Project for Asian
and International Relations conference at the Putra World Trade
Centre today.
	   Musa said the theme for this year's conference was apt as it
enabled the participants to understand the issues at hand.
	   ``If this (the conference) was organised several years ago ...
the theme would have been different.
	   ``Our (the nations') dynamism brought streams of people from the
international community who came and viewed us with awe.
	   ``We had people who had nothing but good things to say about us
... the Asian way.''
	   But success breeds arrogance, corruption, decadence and
failures.
	   ``We became too rich too fast ... suffering from success which
bred failures.''
	   The cultural shock from that failure was traumatic.
	   However, countries in the region had reacted with an acceptance
of responsiblity for the problem and taken remedial action
immediately.
	   ``There are some countries that indulge in the denial syndrome
... yet are forced to take remedial action grudgingly.
	   ``There are those who deal with the problem with cool acceptance
of the reality of the situation, adopting a no-nonsense approach
towards remedial action and getting on with the job at hand to put
their act together.''
	   Musa said one aspect not mentioned much in the wake of the
downturn, and which could be regarded as positive, was the human
rights issue.
	   ``Being an international activist in the cause, in the present
social, economic scenario, the human rights cause seems to be the
winner here,''
	   Musa, who heads the Malaysian delegation to the 54th session of
the United Nations Commission on Human Rights, said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:ASIA'S-DYNAMIC-GROWTH sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
