<BODY>
<SLUG> INFO-SYSTEM-READY-IN-AUG sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Info system ready in Aug, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws INFO-SYSTEM-READY-IN-AUG sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE Petaling Jaya Municipal Council hopes to get the
geographical information system (GIS) ready by August to provide
contractors with up- to-date information on underground pipes,
cables and wiring.
	   Its president Datuk Mohamad Nor Bador said the council was
currently carrying out a pilot project in Section 52 and the Old
Town area.
	   He said the pilot project would take some time as the council
was gathering information from utility departments.
	   He said the utility departments would update the council on
pipes, cables and underground wiring.
	   ``We have to get all the information first before we can provide
the GIS service. Once we know the layout of pipes and underground
cables, it will be easier for us to put all information into the
computer.
	   ``The pilot project will let us know the shortcomings of our
study. Once we have completed the pilot project in Section 52, it
will be easier for us to carry out studies in other areas,'' he
added.
	   Mohamad Nor said contractors can get up-to-date information
before carrying out excavation or drilling.
	   However, contractors will have to purchase the GIS to get the
information.
	   Kelana Jaya State Assemblyman Datuk Mokhtar Dahlan said it was
important for the council to have the GIS system as there were many
incidents of burst pipes in Petaling Jaya.
	   He said contractors were not responsible when carrying out their
work, resulting in burst pipes.
	   ``Most of the pipes are very old and slight pressure on them
will cause a major damage. With the water shortage, we do not need
another burst pipe.
	   ``The council should implement the GIS as soon as possible so
that contractors can buy the plans from us and carry out work
without problem,''
	   he added.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
