<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Three released after payment of RM14,000 ransom, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws THREE-RELEASED-AFTER sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   MUAR, Sun. - Three fishermen taken captive by armed pirates
returned to the Parit Jawa fishing village last night after a
ransom of RM14,000 was paid for their release.
	   Lim Yong Koon, Hitam Salleh and Murad Bidon, all aged 30, were
kidnapped by armed pirates in Malaysian waters about l0 nautical
miles off Parit Bulat coast in Muar at 10am yesterday.
	   The fishermen, who arrived in their village at 10pm, said they
were given boiled banana, coffee and cigarettes while under
detention in a vessel anchored about three nautical miles off
Bantan Tengah at Pulau Bengkalis off Sumatra.
	   Recalling the incident today, Lim said four pirates aged between
30 and 40, one armed with a rifle, threatened to hit him when he
negotiated to lower the RM20,000 ransom originally demanded.
	   ``One of them aimed his rifle at my chest when I tried to reduce
the ransom to RM10,000.
	   ``They finally agreed to RM14,000 after listening to Hitam.''
	   Two fishermen, Mohd Fadil Mohd Yassin, 32, and Najib Ahmad, 34,
left the fishing village at 5pm yesterday with the RM14,000 ransom
money raised by the fishermen's community. Fadil said the ransom
money was handed over to a man believed to be the pirates' leader
at 7.30pm at an area about 27 nautical miles from the Parit Jawa
coast.
	   
</TEXT>
