<TEXT>
	   THE Petaling Jaya Municipal Council will investigate the company
commissioned to construct low-cost units for the State Government
in Lembah Subang as work has been abandoned for more than two
months.
	   MPPJ senior councillor Khoo Ooi Seng said the developer
abandoned work even after the State Government had allocated 20ha
of land for social amenities.
	   ``The contractors have stopped work for more than two months. We
will hold discussions with them to identify the actual problem.
	   ``The State Government has made special allocations for low-cost
units. I do not see why the project has to be stopped,'' he said at
the council's monthly full board meeting.
	   Khoo said the project was aimed at solving housing woes among
squatters in the area.
	   The developer was scheduled to construct 2,872 low-cost units in
three 16- or 17-storey flats for 279 families from longhouses at
the former Taman Aman squatter area.
	   The Taman Aman squatter area has made way for the Light Rail
Transit Project.
	   Councillor Raja Ropiah Raja Abdullah said the abandoned project
was a serious matter as it would reflect badly on the council.
	   ``We cannot let the contractor get away by citing the economic
slowdown as a reason. There is a special allocation for low-cost
units.''
	   Raja Ropiah added that residents were not paying rent at the
moment and would only do so when the project has been completed.
	   ``We must have a meeting with the developer and identify the
actual problem. We have to solve it before the matter gets worse,''
she added.
	   
</TEXT>
