</HEADLINE>
Plans for school-level clubs to combat smoking, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws SCHOOL-LEVEL-CLUBS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sun. - The Health Ministry will recommend the
setting up of Action on Smoking or Health (ASH) clubs in schools
nationwide, starting at secondary level, where students will act as
peer leaders to combat the rising trend of smoking among the youth.
	   The ASH clubs are aimed at creating a smoke-free environment
amongst schoolchildren through discussions, counselling sessions
and poster campaigns.
	   Speaking at the launch of the National Tobacco Free month in
conjunction with World Tobacco Free Day at the Central Market
today, Deputy Health Minister Datuk Dr Siti Zaharah Sulaiman said a
national survey by her Ministry in 1996 showed that 16.7 per cent
of teenagers below 18 smoked.
	   This was an increase compared to the 1986 figure of 10 per cent.
	   The survey also showed that there was a greater tendency for
boys to take up smoking at a rate of 30.7 per cent compared to 4.8
per cent among girls.
	   She said it was imperative to educate teenagers about the
dangers of smoking whilst still in school so that they can make
responsible choices when they leave school.
	   ``Having these clubs in the schools is a good idea as it will
create a counter group among the peers to do away with the notion
that smoking is the ``in'' thing,'' she said.
	   She said the matter would be raised with the Education Minister
soon and its implementation was likely within this year. The clubs
will be formed with the help of the Public Health Committee of the
Malaysian Medical Association.
	   Committee chairman Dr Lekhraj Rampal said in his speech that
they would begin the clubs in secondary schools before introducing
them to primary schools.
	   ``We are willing to provide the technical assistance to the
education ministry such as giving talks, showing slides and
providing the peer leaders with the right information and education
on the harmful effects of tobacco,'' he said. Among the activities
for National Tobacco Free Month are a poster competition and ``Quit
Smoking For a Month'' campaign.
	   
</TEXT>
