<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Ministry to submit proposal on alternative funding, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws ALTERNATIVE-FUNDING sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sun. - The Health Ministry will come up with
proposals for the Cabinet on alternative measures of funding for
sectors, particularly sports and entertainment, which are largely
dependent on revenue from tobacco companies.
	   Deputy Health Minister Datuk Dr Siti Zaharah Sulaiman said today
the proposals will be submitted to the Cabinet in June, after the
ministry's officials have had a dialogue on the issue with
professional bodies, non-governmental organisations and other
concerned parties.
	   Siti Zaharah said this at a Press Conference after the launch of
the Tobacco Free Month in conjunction with World Tobacco Free Day
at the Central Market.
	   She said the Government had been unable to ban indirect tobacco
advertising due to the large revenue brought in by these companies.
	   One of the measures being considered by the ministry is linked
to the taxation on tobacco companies.
	   ``We feel that there is a need to be affirmative on this issue
as a concerted effort must be made to have a smoke-free
environment.''
	   However, Siti Zaharah declined to elaborate on the proposals
being considered.
	   A recent report in the New Straits Times said that tobacco
companies here spend about RM400 million in advertising annually.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
