<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
KL Hospital takes statement from father over missing baby's body, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws MISSING-BABY'S-BODY sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - The Kuala Lumpur Hospital authorities today
recorded a statement from Chandra Bos Kanniah, 52, in connection
with the disappearance of the body of his still-born son from the
mortuary last week.
	   Police have also recorded a statement from him.
	   The hospital has begun its own probe.
	   Yesterday, hospital deputy director Dr Ramlee Rahmat said action
would be taken against employees found to be involved in the
disappearance.
	   Last Saturday, Chandra Bos had lodged two police reports
claiming the body of his still-born child had ``mysteriously
disappeared'' from the mortuary.
	   His wife, Ambujam Balakrishnan, 45, had delivered the baby last
Friday.
	   However, he was informed later that the baby was still-born and
told to return to the hospital to claim the body. A medical officer
had given him the baby's death certificate which stated the cause
of death as mecerated still birth/intra utrine death.
	   The next day, when Chandra Bos came to the mortuary he was told
someone had claimed it. He also claimed that two workers at the
mortuary had offered him compensation of RM1000 and RM2000 each, to
keep the matter under wraps.
	   
</TEXT>
