<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
MTUC calls for meeting to discuss charges, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws MTUC-CALLS-FOR-MEETING sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sun. - The Malaysian Trades Union Congress feels
that a National Labour Advisory Council meeting will be the best
forum to settle once and for all allegations that MTUC
secretary-general G. Rajasekaran had been spreading lies about the
country abroad.
	   However, MTUC president Zainal Rampak said he was under the
impression that the issue had already been settled in a similar
meeting in August, 1996, but ``appeared to have resurfaced after
two years''.
	   ``MTUC has agreed that to maintain harmony, another NLAC meeting
should be convened to settle the matter,'' he said in a statement.
	   On Thursday, Human Resources Minister Datuk Lim Ah Lek made
public a video tape as proof that Rajasekaran had been spreading
lies about the country in a forum in Washington DC in the United
States two years ago.
	   Lim said Rajasekaran had been unable to substantiate his claims,
among which were that there were in Malaysia, enterprise-based or
so-called company-based unions which were created by the employers.
	   In addition to refuting these claims, Lim said, Rajasekaran had
failed to provide the names of the companies for investigation.
	   To this, Zainal said the names of the companies had been
submitted to the Ministry but if required, it would be sent again.
	   Zainal said MTUC was more concerned in helping the country
overcome its economic woes and hoped to work together with the
Government on this.
	   In light of this, he said MTUC would put forward proposals on
how best to safeguard the interests of workers and suggest the
implementation of an employees service scheme.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
