<SLUG> PACT-TO-MAKE-SHAN-ALAM sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Pact to make Shah Alam a recognised garden city, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws PACT-TO-MAKE-SHAN-ALAM sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   REFLECTING its seriousness in answering the Government's call to
``garden the nation'' by 2005, the Shah Alam Municipal Council
yesterday signed a Memorandum of Understanding with Agricultural
Chemicals (M) Sdn Bhd to transform the town into an
internationally-recognised landscaped garden city.
	   Council president Mohamad Adzib Mohd Isa said the ACM would be
providing technical know-how on plant cultivation and maintenance,
including fertilisers and pesticides, to the council's landscape
contractors.
	   ``This is to help the council's contractors learn techniques in
planting and maintaining plants so that the trees and plants will
be healthier and bear more flowers,'' he said.
	   The MoU was signed by Mohamad Adzib and ACM managing director
Hsu I-Che and witnessed by National Landscape Department
director-general Datuk Ismail Ngah.
	   Speaking to reporters after the signing, Mohamad Adzib said the
co-operation with ACM had no time limit.
	   He said that ACM had been chosen as consultants based on its
excellent track record in agricultural research and development and
official recognition by the Government.
	   Among awards won by the company were the Malaysia Industry
Excellence Award and the Merdeka Award for Corporate Excellence -
the 24th placing among top companies in Malaysia with the highest
RD expenditure in Science and Technology.
	   Mohamad Adzib said not all 28 landscape contractors with the
council would be trained by ACM.
	   ``We will choose only certain areas, with the town centre being
the first,'' he said.
	   Earlier in his speech, Mohamad Adzib said the council had so far
spent RM9 million on landscaping and RM3 million on maintenance
work.
	   The council had also obtained RM3 million from the National
Landscape Department for landscaping in view of the Commonwealth
Games.
	   Meanwhile, Hsu said the council would be paying a small amount
for consultation services.
	   ``The cost will be very cheap as this is for mutual benefit,''
he said, adding that the co-operation would be a win-win situation
for both entities.
	   ``This co-operation will be able to support our research and
development activities and more people can enjoy our technique and
approach,'' he said.
	   He added that research carried out by the company catered to the
Malaysian conditions.
	   He said the company would establish a standard operating
procedure for each of the council's contractors to monitor their
progress.
	   Hsu said the company was also negotiating with other local
authorities on the possibility of extending its services.
	   Meanwhile, Ismail said his department would provide technical
expertise to local authorities on landscaping work in preparation
for the Commonwealth Games.
	   
</TEXT>
