<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Junta accuses U.S., South Africa, Ghana of anti-Abacha plot 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Gen. Sani Abacha's ruling military junta
on Monday accused the United States, South Africa and the West
African country of Ghana of plotting to disrupt upcoming
presidential elections.
	   Although he has not officially declared his candidacy, Abacha in
April became the only candidate for August presidential elections,
rendering the poll into little more than a referendum on his
selection.
	   His supporters, however, say Washington is teaming up with
leaders from South Africa, Ghana and exiled Nigerian opposition
activists to block Abacha's president.
	   Abacha seized power in a bloodless 1993 coup and while he has
repeatedly pledged to hand over power to a civilian government, it
now seems that Abacha plans to keep the job for himself.
	   In a six-page statement issued during a press conference Monday,
the military junta said officials from the United States and South
Africa recently met in nearby Ghana to discuss coordinated
opposition to the August elections.
	   ``The issues discussed at the meeting were the strategies to be
adopted by pro-democracy and human rights groups in Nigeria to
ensure the termination of the present government,'' the statement
said.
	   The junta also said U.S.-backed pro-democracy groups were
working to restore the canceled 1993 election result, in which
opposition leader Moshood Abiola apparently won the presidency.
	   Abiola's presumed electoral victory was quashed when Abacha
stopped the vote counting and declared the poll invalid. Abiola was
later jailed and charged with treason for declaring himself
president.
	   Abacha's military supporters have repeatedly accused the United
States of funding opposition activities and say officials from
Washington discussed the use of mass protest rallies and boycotts
to block the upcoming elections.
  (fa/ids)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Nigeria; CT:i; 
