<BODY>
<SLUG> SOLVING-SOCIAL-PROBLEMS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
`Solving social problems of children is just as important', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws SOLVING-SOCIAL-PROBLEMS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   MALACCA, Sun. - Solving social problems plaguing children is as
important as overcoming the nation's economic situation, National
Unity and Social Development Minister Datin Paduka Zaleha Ismail
said last night.
	   She said if parents do not attend to the problems of their
children now, then social problems like HIV/AIDS, drugs, loafing,
pre-marital sex and abandoned babies may see a sharp increase.
	   ``This was proven when my Ministry did a survey two years back
which showed that the number of social problems in this country for
the past five years had seen a dramatic rise.
	   ``Therefore, handling the current economic situation is one
thing but families must also place emphasis on taking care and
solving the problem of their children so that they are not involved
in negative activities,''she said.
	   Zaleha said this in her keynote address at the launching of a
conference entitled `Role of the Family in the Next Millennium'
organised by the Women's Federation for World Peace at the Pan
Pacific Legacy hotel last night.
	   Also present were WFWP patron, Datuk Paduka Dr Saleha Mohd Ali;
Datin Seri Khalijah Mohd Jiddi, wife of Chief Minister Datuk Seri
Abu Zahar Isnin and organising committee chairman, Kian Sit Har.
	   Zaleha said that besides providing care, parents should also
instil a high-level of discipline and noble values in their
children.
	   She said another survey by the National Population and Family
Planning Board recently showed that a working parent only had 10
minutes a week to interact with his or her children.
	   She said working parents should find time for their children
instead of concentrating on material gains alone.
	   She urged non-governmental organisations to to assist the
Government in reducing social problems.
	   
</TEXT>
