u P     BC-Britain-Pakistan-Indi     06-01 0353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Pakistan-India </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Britain urges Pakistan and India to sign nuclear arms treaty and open negotiations 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Britain on Monday called on Pakistan and India to
sign up to nuclear arms control conventions and discuss the roots
of tension between the two countries to avoid a nuclear arms race
in southern Asia.
	   Foreign Secretary Robin Cook told the House of Commons that
Pakistan had acted in ``flagrant disregard of international
opinion,'' by carrying out two sets of nuclear tests last week. The
Pakistani tests came two weeks after India carried out five nuclear
tests, heightening tension between the two nations.
	   ``The international community is united in its insistence that
Pakistan should refrain from further tests,'' Cook said in his
first statement in Parliament since Pakistan tested its nuclear
devices.
	   Cook called on both nations to sign the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty and to halt the production of nuclear material, and said
``the need is now more urgent that ever'' for the states to open
negotiations to reduce tensions.
	   Pakistan and India are at loggerheads over the disputed region
of Kashmir, and have fought two wars in 1948 and 1965 over the
control of the Himalayan territory. Both nations won independence
from Britain in 1947.
	   Britain has canceled visits by senior Pakistani and Indian
military officials and will review trading links with both
countries, Cook said. However, the government will not halt aid
programs.
	   ``Britain's aid program,'' Cook said, '' is directly targeted on
providing help to the poorest people in the poorest regions. We
remain convinced that it would be wrong to penalize the most
vulnerable citizens in either country.''
	   Cook said that a meeting in London on June 12 of the G8, the
group of leading industrial nations that includes the United
States, Japan, Britain, France, Germany, Italy, Canada and Russia
would send a powerful signal to both south Asian nations.
	   ``The meeting will coordinate our approach to Pakistan and India
in the light of nuclear tests,'' Cook said.
	   (rs) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Britain-Pakistan-India; CT:P; 
