r w     NOT-DETERIORATE-CRISISsk     06-01 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> NOT-DETERIORATE-CRISIS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Blackouts `will not deteriorate into a crisis', NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws NOT-DETERIORATE-CRISIS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KAJANG, Fri. - The growing number of power failures reported in
the Klang Valley over the past few weeks will not turn into a
crisis as is the case with water supply, Tenaga Nasional Bhd
executive chairman Datuk Dr Ahmad Tajuddin Ali said tonight.
	   He said unlike the water crisis which was caused by inadequate
supply due to the lack of rain, power failures were caused by more
manageable problems, such as a sudden increase of outage and damage
to power cables.
	   ``These problems can be more easily remedied as we can promptly
analyse the situation and take prompt action.''
	   He said Tenaga Nasional was upgrading electrical cables which
had inadequate capacity and identified as the major cause of the
recent breakdowns.
	   ``For the past one month, TNB had spent over RM7 million to
replace these cables and taken other measures such as improving
power distribution units in certain areas in Kuala Lumpur and
Petaling Jaya.''
	   Ahmad Tajuddin was speaking to reporters after attending a
welcoming ceremony for 1,875 students of the Universiti Tenaga
Nasional who completed their orientation programme today.
	   He assured the public that the recent power failures were
confined to specific areas where the pace of development had
exceeded TNB's infrastructure, such as low voltage cable that had
been laid earlier.
	   Speaking earlier to the students, Ahmad Tajuddin called on them
to use the opportunity of their admission into Uniten to strive to
become capable professionals.
	   
</TEXT>
