</HEADLINE>
`Stamp out use of banned fishing net', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws BANNED-FISHING-NET sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   PENANG, Fri. - The Fisheries Department has been urged to step
up its enforcement to stamp out the use of pukat siput in the
inshore areas of Perlis.
	   Sahabat Alam Malaysia said the pukat siput menace had been going
on for too long and was threatening the livelihood of more than
1,000 fishermen.
	   SAM president S.M. Mohd Idris urged the department to step up
its patrols and beef up enforcement against unscrupulous trawler
boats using the pukat siput.
	   ``Stiffer penalties should be meted out to those caught using
this kind of nets which have been outlawed,'' he said.
	   Mohd Idris said the department should also determine why these
illegal activities were being carried on despite action against
some violators.
	   
</TEXT>
