r w     DESIGN-AND-BUILD-SCHOOLS     06-01 0423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> DESIGN-AND-BUILD-SCHOOLS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
`Design and build' schools soon, says Najib, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws DESIGN-AND-BUILD-SCHOOLS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUCHING, Fri. - More schools with creative and innovative
designs are expected to be built in future because the current
standard designs are hardly inspiring.
	   Education Minister Datuk Seri Najib Tun Razak said under the
``design-and-build concept'' the developers did not have to follow
any standard design.
	   Working committees, both at the federal and state levels, had
been formed to identify schools for such projects.
	   ``Under the design-and-build concept, there is no need to follow
any standard design, but the problem is the cost may be high.
	   ``This is different in the case of standard design as we can
control the price,'' he told reporters after opening Sekolah Rendah
Kerajaan Satria Jaya at Taman BDC near here today.
	   Among those present at the function were State Agriculture and
Food Industries Minister Datuk Adenan Satem, Assistant Industrial
Development Minister Sim Kheng Hui and state education director
Putit Matzen.
	   Najib commended Borneo Development Corporation (Sarawak) Sdn Bhd
for not only building a ``beautiful and cute'' school but also
donating the RM3.98 million structure to the Government.
	   SRK Satria Jaya, which sits on a 1.01 hectare plot of land and
started operation on Dec 4, 1995, has 24 classrooms, 289 pupils and
19 teachers.
	   Najib also said he was proud that the standard of education in
Sarawak was high, with students performing better than the national
average.
	   On the shortage of graduate teachers in the State, he said more
would be sent.
	   ``But whatever difficulties we may face, let us never give up
hope but continue to struggle for the good of the future
generations,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
