r w     UKM-TO-RECONSIDERsked     06-01 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> UKM-TO-RECONSIDER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
UKM to reconsider those who failed to gain admission, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws UKM-TO-RECONSIDER sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia will
consider appeals by students whose applications to pursue first
degree or matriculation programmes have been rejected.
	   UKM will, however, only consider appeals for degree programmes
in basic science and social sciences and matriculation programmes
in science and mathematics.
	   Vice-chancellor Professor Datuk Dr Anuwar Ali said the
university would accept 250 applicants for degree studies in
mathematical, life, social, as well as applied and physical
sciences.
	   ``Places for other programmes like medicine, pharmacy,
information technology, engineering, accounting and economics have
been filled up,'' he told reporters after launching the ``Home Care
Nursing'' programme at Hospital UKM in Cheras today.
	   About 200 nurses participated in the programme held in
conjunction with World Nursing Day.
	   It was organised for Cheras residents by the hospital and UKM's
faculty of medicine.
	   Anuwar said the applications depended on the places available
and the students' qualifications.
	   Yesterday, Education Minister Datuk Seri Najib Tun Razak had
said that the Unit Pusat Universiti Infoline system was reviewing
1,000 appeals by students who had obtained an aggregate of 15 and
below.
	   Anuwar said there were 100 to 200 places under the university's
franchise programme for matriculation science and mathematics at
private institutions.
	   Places for law and accounting/economic matriculation programmes
have been filled up.
	   At present, UKM has an enrolment of 2,226 students for
matriculation programmes, 19,036 for first degree and 8,000 for
distance learning.
	   Asked about the reported ragging of a first-year student, Anuwar
said deputy vice-chancellor (student affairs department) Professor
Datuk Dr Wan Hashim Wan Teh had met with the girl's parents this
morning.
	   He said the department would investigate the case and take
disciplinary action, including suspension, against those
responsible.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
