r w     OVER-RAGGING-INCIDENTske     06-01 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> OVER-RAGGING-INCIDENT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
No report filed yet over ragging incident, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws OVER-RAGGING-INCIDENT sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - The student who dropped out of Universiti
Putra Malaysia, claiming to be a victim of ragging, has still not
filed a report and this is hampering investigations.
	   UPM vice-chancellor Prof Datuk Dr Syed Jalaluddin Syed Salim
said there was no response to numerous telephone calls to his home.
	   However, university authorities are questioning his room mate,
friends and the hostel master, in an attempt to discover the
identities of the five youths behind the alleged incident.
	   It was reported last week that UPM freshie R. Prasath, 20, from
Ipoh was allegedly assaulted by five youths, believed to be
seniors, in his hostel.
	   Syed Jalaluddin also said UPM expected to submit its report to
the Education Ministry in a week, along with another report on a
student who attempted suicide a few days later after struggling to
cope with campus life.
	   He however said the attempted suicide was not caused by ragging.
	   ``The student is recovering. We hope parents will let us know if
their children find it difficult to cope so that the students can
then be given counselling and assistance,'' he said.
	   He said this after signing a memorandum of understanding with
the Commonwealth Secretariat to launch a diploma programme on youth
in development work.
	   Commonwealth secretary-general Chief Emeka Anyaoku signed for
the secretariat, witnessed by deputy secretary-general Sir Humphrey
Maud and Youth and Sports Minister Tan Sri Muhyiddin Yassin.
	   Syed Jalaluddin said the university had the power to take
disciplinary action, including expulsion, against the five youths.
	   He also said incidents of ragging had declined over the years
and are now uncommon. Ragging is not permitted.
	   On the 18-month diploma programme, he said it aimed to equip
people with skills for youth work. The first intake of 50 will be
in November. The diploma is equivalent to completing the first year
of a related degree course.
	   Anyaoku said Malaysia is the first to launch a youth diploma
programme with the Commonwealth and will be followed by another 15
universities in member countries, including India and South Africa.
	   The programme content was drawn up with input from 10 countries.
``It's a demonstration of the Commonwealth at work in a global
fashion,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
