w1503  wstm-
u i     BC-Yemen-Reforms     06-01 0339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Reforms </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yemen's new government vows to carry on economic reforms 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   SAN'A, Yemen (AP) _ Yemen's new prime minister on Monday
unveiled his government's policies, pledging to continue with the
three-year-old economic and administrative reforms.
	   But Prime Minister Abdel-Karim al-Iryani cautioned that the
Asian economic crisis and the fall in oil prices will have a
negative effect on the economy and further increase the budget
deficit to 36.2 billion rials (dlrs 275 million).
	   ``The government will continue the process of economic,
financial and monetary reforms and launch a broad national
administrative reform program,'' al-Iryani told Parliament where he
presented his policy statement.
	   The oil revenues, which represent about 40 percent of the
country's total income, are Yemen's main source for foreign
currency.
	   The 1998 budget projects oil income will increase 3 percent to
dlrs 1 billion from dlrs 970 million estimated for 1997. The
government aims to raise oil output capacity to 500,000 barrels per
day by 2000 from around 350,000 barrels daily now.
	   Al-Iryani said the country's foreign reserves have shrunk by
dlrs 142 million from dlrs 378 million in the period January-March
last year to dlrs 236 million in the same period this year. Yemen's
fiscal year begins April 1.
	   The World Bank has approved a dlrs 80 million credit to Yemen to
support its economic reform program. The government has already cut
back subsidies and stepped up privatization of state-controlled
companies as part of reforms required by the International Monetary
Fund.
	   Still suffering from a devastating 1994 civil war, Yemen has a
foreign debt of some dlrs 10 billion it cannot serve. Most of its
17 million people live in poverty.
	   Al-Iryani took office on May 17, replacing Faraj bin Ghanem who
resigned amid differences with President Ali Abdullah Saleh, the
real power in the country, over political and economic reforms.
Ghanem spent less than one year in office.
  my/vj
</TEXT>
