<HEADLINE>
Report: Pakistan feared Israeli attack hours before nuclear detonations 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with reports Pakistan believed Israeli F-16 warplanes
were in India graf 2; Pakistan also informed Kofi Annan and China
graf 3, Israeli ambassador in Washington contacting Pakistani
counterpart in graf 5
By DAFNA LINZER
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Pakistan feared an Israeli air strike on its
nuclear installations hours before it detonated five nuclear
devices last week, Israeli media reported Monday.
	   State-run Israel television said Pakistan's foreign minister
informed the United States about the plans last Thursday, hours
before it carried out the tests. Pakistan believed that Israeli
F-16 warplanes were in bases in India, and would operate from there
the report said.
	   The United States told Pakistan that Israel was not planning any
such attack, Israel's Channel Two Television said. The report said
Pakistan also informed United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan
and as well as China, where Israel's prime minister was on an
official visit last week.
	   Israel has relations with India but not Pakistan, the first
Islamic nation to go nuclear.
	   Shai Bazak, spokesman for Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu denied an attack was planned. ``These reports are totally
baseless,'' he told Israel TV. Israel radio reported that Israel's
ambassador to Washington Eliyahu Ben Elissar contacted his
Pakistani counterpart Monday to deny the report.
	   Israel, an, 6th graf pvs
