w1507  wstm-
u i     BC-Yugoslavia-Montenegro 4thLd-Writethru   06-01 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Montenegro, 4th Ld-Writethru,0705 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Reformist triumphs in Montenegro poll Djukanovic victory. STANDS as 3rd Ld-Writethru for some points. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES throughout with more results appearing to confirm
AP Photos POD105-106
By ALISON SMALE
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ In a major electoral triumph,
Montenegro's reformist president threw down a challenge to Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic on Monday that could dent or
ultimately undo the strongman's rule.
	   In true Balkan style, supporters of President Milo Djukanovic
fired guns, waved flags and honked car horns as they showed their
joy at an unexpectedly decisive win over Milosevic protege Momir
Bulatovic in Sunday's parliamentary elections,
	   With 99.7 percent of the vote counted for the 78-seat
Montenegrin parliament, Djukanovic's coalition ``For a Better
Life'' had secured 49.5 percent of ballots cast, the State Election
Commission said.
	   Bulatovic's Socialist People's Party had 36.1 percent, the
Commission added.
	   A jubilant Djukanovic, 36, told cheering supporters he hoped to
build on the triumph and use it to spread democracy throughout
Yugoslavia, which now consists of just Serbia and Montenegro.
	   ``Montenegro has again shown that it has the wisdom, courage and
resolve to resist those who decided to enslave Montenegro,'' he
said.
	   Although this mountainous republic has just 630,000 residents,
it supplies the same number of deputies to the federal Yugoslav
parliament as Serbia, with 10 million inhabitants.
	   Djukanovic and his aides are determined to stack Montenegro's
bloc with their supporters, and hope to team up with Serbian
opposition deputies to vote Milosevic out.
	   No political analyst in Yugoslavia can imagine Milosevic going
quietly. Since rising to power in Serbia in 1987, the wily
strongman has used a powerfully effective mix of nationalism, tight
media control and autocratic methods to cement his hold on power.
	   But Djukanovic and unrest in the Serbian province of Kosovo
recently have weakened his grip.
	   In Kosovo, ethnic Albanians fighting for independence appear to
be gaining ground in ever more deadly battles with Serbian police.
	   Djukanovic first threw down the gauntlet in the winter of
1996-7, coming out against Milosevic during massive protests
against his rule.
	   Last fall, the Montenegrin then narrowly beat Bulatovic _ his
former best friend _ for the republic's presidency.
	   Strongly backed by Washington and western Europe, Djukanovic
took office last January.
	   The strength of his triumph in Sunday's elections could hand him
a majority in the 78-seat Montenegrin parliament. Besides
Djukanovic's and Bulatovic's parties, only one other party _ the
Montenegrin separatist Liberal Alliance _ passed the 3 percent vote
threshold needed to get seats.
	   Djukanovic aides suggested Monday that they would insist on
Bulatovic being replaced as federal premier. Milosevic maneuvered
his protege into that office two weeks ago after the previous
premier refused to crack down on Djukanovic's pro-Western reforms.
	   The big unknown Monday was Milosevic's reaction. Typically in
such situations, he bides his time, allowing media or political
aides to speak for him before acting.
	   The state news agency Tanjug said that Bulatovic's party had
accepted Sunday's results.
	   Some 120 election monitors dispatched by the 54-nation
Organization for Security and Cooperation concluded Sunday's ballot
``was generally well conducted,'' an OSCE statement said.
	   ``I'm giving these elections a clean bill of health,'' said
Javier Ruperez of Spain, heading the monitoring team.
	   The statement urged all political parties to overcome the bitter
divisions of the election campaign and ``work now at establishing a
climate of dialogue and confidence.''
	   Media control has proven critical for all ruling parties since
the old Yugoslavia, of six republics, began its bloody break-up in
1991.
	   OSCE said Montenegrin state media were biased toward Djukanovic.
But the transatlantic organization was even more critical of
Serbian state media for its vicious attacks on the Montenegrin
president during the campaign.
</TEXT>
