<BODY>
<SLUG> FICS-EYES-BANKING sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
FICS eyes e-banking opportunities in Asia, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws FICS-EYES-BANKING sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   INTERNATIONAL financial software company FICS Group of Belgium
is positioning itself to tap the growing electronic banking market
of Asia in a bid to further strengthen its presence in Asia.
	   Its chief executive officer Michel Akkermans said the company
sees great potential for electronic banking in the region,
especially in countries like Malaysia and Singapore.
	   ``Asia contributed about 15 per cent of FICS' total revenue of
US$42 million (RM160 million) last year. This year, the percentage
is expected to grow with a global revenue projection of US$50
million,'' he told Computimes in a recent tele-interview.
	   Towards that end, the company has established a new regional
headquarters - FICS Asia - in Singapore to enhance local support
and increase technical capabilities to better service its clients.
	   For that purpose, FICS Asia's current staff strength of 20 is
expected to double by year-end.
	   ``We will also leverage on our business partners in the various
countries in the region,'' Akkermans said, adding that FICS Group
business partner in Malaysia is Solsis (M) Sdn Bhd, a subsidiary of
Dataprep Holdings Bhd.
	   The group is also setting up a FICS development centre in
Singapore which will house technical and functional expertise to
develop Asian versions of FICS' electronic banking and regulatory
reporting products.
	   This, according to Akkermans, includes developing localised
products for the Malaysian market.
	   ``Some of our electronic banking and regulatory reporting
products are already compliant with Bank Negara's guidelines. Our
electronic cash card technology is also fully compatible with the
Banksys's Proton electronic cash scheme selected as Malaysia's new
national electronic payment system,'' he said.
	   Akkermans claimed that FICS Group is the world market leader in
the electronic banking and regulatory financial reporting areas
with about 500 customers in 26 countries who have installed FICS'
solutions complying to local standards and legal frameworks.
	   FICS Group, which was founded in 1989, focuses on two core
business activities: electronic services delivery (ESD) and
financial reporting systems (FRS).
	   The ESD products and services range from Windows-based and
Internet-enabled electronic banking solutions for retail and
corporate banking to electronic commerce and electronic purse
solutions and services.
	   The FRS offering, based on a client-server reporting system
called Abacus, addresses the regulatory financial and management
reporting needs of banks, insurance companies, pension funds,
mutual funds and brokers.
	   
</TEXT>
