w1515  wstm-
r w     SIX-CLAIM-TRIAL-IN-BSNsk     06-01 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> SIX-CLAIM-TRIAL-IN-BSN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Six claim trial in BSN car loan fraud case, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws SIX-CLAIM-TRIAL-IN-BSN sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   SHAH ALAM, Fri. - A Bank Simpanan Nasional credit manager and
five others, including a Road Transport Department employee, today
claimed trial in the Sessions Courts to 100 charges of cheating the
BSN Shah Alam branch of RM3,459,208 as loans for 20 non-existent
Proton cars.
	   Shukri Fadzil, 33, car salesman Zamanhuri Ezin, 35, and office
boy E.M Balakrishnan, 31, each face 20 cheating charges while BSN
credit clerks, Baharin Abdullah, 30, and Mohd Hafid Othman, 28, are
facing 10 charges each.
	   RTD driver Abdul Aziz Kassim, 36, also faces 20 charges of
abetting them.
	   They are jointly charged with cheating the BSN into believing
that all loan documents for the purchase of the cars were genuine
and thereby inducing the bank to approve the loans, amounting to
RM3,459,208 to Syarikat Nurdin Enterprise and Cita Ulung Sdn Bhd.
	   They are alleged to have committed the offence at the BSN,
Kompleks PKNS between July 9, last year and Jan 19 this year.
	   The six, who were allowed RM100,000 bail each, were charged in
two Sessions courts.
	   They were charged under section 420 of the Penal Code which
carries a maximum sentence of 10 years jail and caning upon
conviction.
	   Baharin, Shukri, Zamanhuri and Balakrishnan pleaded not guilty
to 10 charges when they were produced before judge Mohtarudin Baki.
	   They are alleged to have cheated the bank by making it believe
that 10 documents related to the loans for the purchase of 10
Proton cars were genuine and thereby inducing the bank to release
the loans, amounting to RM400,000 to Nurdin Enterprise between July
9 and Aug 26 last year.
	   They were each allowed RM100,000 bail in one surety and also
ordered to surrender their passports to the court.
	   Mohtarudin fixed joint hearing of the charges for four days,
starting Oct 12, following an application by Deputy Public
Prosecutor Salehuddin Saidin.
	   In another Sessions Court before Zabariah Mohd Yusof, Mohd
Hafid, Shukri, Zamanhuri and Balakrishan claimed trial to 10 joint
charges of cheating the bank by making it believe that the
documents for purchase of 10 cars - five Proton Perdana 2.0, three
Proton Wira, one each of Proton Putra and Proton Satria - were
genuine and thereby inducing the bank to release the loans,
amounting to RM400,000 to Cita Ulung between Nov 1 last year and
Jan 19 this year.
	   Meanwhile, Aziz, who claimed trial to the 20 charges of abetting
them was allowed bail of RM100,000 in two sureties and ordered to
surrender his passport to the court.
	   Mohd Hafid, who was allowed bail of RM100,000 in two sureties
was also ordered to surrender his passport.
	   Zabariah fixed June 10 for the mention of Abdul Aziz's case to
enable him to engage a counsel.
	   She said she would decide then whether Abdul Aziz should be
jointly tried with the five others.
	   She allowed an application by Salehuddin for Mohd Hafid to be
jointly tried with four others.
	   Shukri, Bahrin and Hafiz were represented by Rosli Zin while
Balakrishnan and Zamanhuri were represented by Hazman Ahmad.
	   
</TEXT>
