	   JAKARTA (JP): Publicly listed plantation firm PT Astra Agro
Lestari (AAL), a subsidiary of the country's largest automaker PT
Astra International, announced Saturday that it had exported nine
metric tons of black tea worth US$18,474 to India.
	   The company said its black tea exports comprised 3.7 tons of
Broken Orange Peko (BOP) grade, two tons of Broken Orange Peko
Fanning and 3.3 tons of Broken Tea grade. India was chosen as its
main market because the country is the world's biggest tea
consumer.
	   The black tea was produced by AAL's tea plantation subsidiary PT
Bantar, which currently produces 2.7 tons of tea per day.
	   The company said that it planned to increase Bantar's production
capacity to 4.5 tons per day this year, most of which would be
exported.
	   AAL's estates cover 300,000 hectares in Sumatra, 192,758
hectares of which has been planted with palm oil, rubber, tea and
cocoa. Oil palm plantations cover 92 percent of the company
plantation area.
	   The company's net profit jumped 43 percent to Rp 90.6 billion
(US$9.06 million) last year from Rp 63.3 billion in 1996.
	   The company said that the increase in its net profit was mostly
due to the increase in the price of crude palm oil last year

