Hospital `needs respiratory unit', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws NEEDS-RESPIRATORY-UNIT sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA TERENGGANU, Fri. - Out of nearly 7,000 patients admitted
into the hospital here annually, about 35 per cent were respiratory
cases.
	   The State Environmental, Health and Consumers Affair Committee
chairman Wong Foon Meng said among the types of respiratory
problems were pneumonia (728 cases), asthma (596 cases) and other
respiratory complications (782 cases).
	   ``Based on the number of respiratory cases treated at the
hospital, we feel that it is time for the hospital to have a
special unit where patients with respiratory problems can be given
proper treatment,'' he said after receiving a RM30,000 cheque from
Esso Production Malaysia Incorporation medical adviser Dr Abu
Hassan Ahmad yesterday.
	   Wong said due to the shortage of equipment, the hospital had to
borrow the apparatus from other hospitals to treat patients.
	   To have a respiratory unit complete with equipment, the hospital
requires at least RM300,000 and is appealing to the private sector
to contribute.
	   
</TEXT>
