	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   PENANG, Fri. - At least half of the 11,000 participants
registered for the International Penang Bridge Run collected their
numbers, vests and runners' guides at the Youth and Sports Complex
in Batu Uban yesterday.
	   Most of the runners who lined up to collect their numbers were
from here and neighbouring States.
	   ``There was no rush; everything went smoothly,'' Penang Amateur
Athletic Association secretary Paul Subramaniam said.
	   The booth was operated by Penang AAA officials from 5pm to 9pm.
	   A regular participant from Sungai Petani, K. Nadarajah, said
that he was impressed with the way the numbers were given out.
	   ``There was absolutely no rush, things went on properly,'' said
the 52-year-old teachers' college lecturer from Sungai Petani.
	   Meanwhile, India's favourite runner Sunita Godara is confident
of another victory in the Open category of the women's marathon.
	   The 38-year-old Sunita from New Delhi is no newcomer to Penang
as she has won the Penang MAS International Marathon five times.
	   ``If there are runners from Myanmar and Thailand, they will pose
a stiff challenge,'' said Sunita, who arrived two days ago.
	   The full marathon, introduced for the first time this year, will
see the participation of about 1,000 runners, half of whom are
foreigners.
	   Runners from the United States, Britain, Iran, Japan, Australia,
New Zealand, Singapore, Thailand and Indonesia are among those who
have signed up for the event.
	   Meanwhile, the public is reminded that several roads leading to
the Penang Bridge will be closed to traffic on Sunday for the run.
	   Georgetown deputy district traffic chief, Assistant
Superintendent Ahmad Termizi Abdul Haq, said roads will be closed
from 4.30am to 9.30am.
	   The coastal highway leading to the Bayan Lepas Industrial Free
Zone factories will also be closed.
	   Motorists are advised to use alternative routes to reach their
destinations.
	   Participants and their supporters are advised to keep to the
runners' guide provided by the organisers.
	   About 200 police personnel will be stationed at all
intersections in Georgetown and on the mainland to assist traffic
flow.
	   Detour and temporary road closure signs will also be placed in
these areas.
	   
