u s     BC-Sports-Golf-LPGARoche     06-01 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-LPGA Rochester,0421 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jones wins Rochester International by two shots 
</HEADLINE>
By BEN DOBBIN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   ROCHESTER, New York (AP) _ Rosie Jones recovered from
consecutive bogeys down the stretch Monday to capture the Rochester
International for the second time in seven years.
	   Picking up on the back nine after thunderstorms forced the
suspension of final-round play Sunday, Jones reopened a four-stroke
lead with a 35-foot (11-meter) birdie putt on No. 10 and a 5-footer
(1.5-meter) for birdie on No. 12.
	   She bogeyed No. 14 after getting tangled in the rough and No.
15, where she three-putted, then settled down to complete an
even-par round and finish at 9-under 279, two ahead of Juli
Inkster.
	   Jones, 38, won the Rochester International in 1991 and lost in a
playoff to Kathy Whitworth in 1984. Her ninth victory in 16 years
on the LPGA tour was worth dlrs 105,000.
	   ``I cherish every win _ you wouldn't believe it,'' she said. ``I
don't get to win as much as the really great players. I have a lot
of good tournaments but I don't win as much as I'd like.''
	   Hollis Stacy, who had cut Jones' lead to two on Sunday, dropped
to third place with a 70 to finish at 6-under. Stacy captured 17
tournaments between 1977 and 1985, but she has won just once since
_ in 1991.
	   Tied for fourth at 5-under were Moira Dunn, Sherri Steinhauer
and Meg Mallon, who closed with the day's best round of 67. Another
stroke back was Alicia Dibos of Peru.
	   Jones barely matched par on the first nine Sunday, when swirling
winds, flashes of lightning and intermittent downpours stopped play
four times for a total of 5 1/2 hours.
	   Her birdie putt from just off the fringe on the 10th hole gave
her a quick boost.
	   ``I was not so nervous _ I felt pretty good _ but that just kind
of freed me up a little bit,'' she said.
	   ``It was nice that I made a couple of birdies before I made a
bogey so I felt like I had a little cushion,'' Jones said. ``I
wasn't real worried ... after two bogeys. I didn't let it get to
me.''
	   Inkster vaulted into second place with a 68, rubbing out an
opening bogey on No. 14 with a birdie putt on No. 16 and a birdie
putt on the next hole to finish at 7-under.
	   ``I was so wired last night, I didn't sleep well at all,'' she
said.
	   Defending champion Penny Hammel slumped to 4-over, one ahead of
South Korean rookie Se Ri Pak, who led the LPGA Championship from
start to finish two weeks ago.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Golf-LPGA Rochester; CT:s; 
