r w     HAVE-HEALTHCARE-FOR-LIVE     06-01 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> HAVE-HEALTHCARE-FOR-LIVE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Have healthcare for life policies, insurers urged, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws HAVE-HEALTHCARE-FOR-LIVE sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Fri. - Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs
Parliamentary Secretary Datuk Tan Chai Ho today urged insurance
companies to provide low-premium policies for lifetime healthcare.
	   Tan told a Press conference at the Putra World Trade Centre that
this was because the cost of healthcare was expected to increase.
	   ``For diabetics alone, there is an increase of 2,000 patients
per year needing regular haemodialysis,'' he said after launching a
charity art exhibition by Shirley Chu at the PWTC.
	   The exhibition, open until Sunday, is part of the National
Association of Malaysian Life Insurance Agents (Namlia)
haemodialysis charity project.
	   Tan suggested individual policies to cover single diseases which
should also meet the cost of healthcare through a patient's
lifetime.
	   Policies should distinguish between, say, heart cases which
require major surgery once or twice in a lifetime, and diabetics
who need haemodialysis three times a week.
	   Tan added he would take up the matter with relevant parties such
as associations of insurance companies and Bank Negara.
	   Namlia president Paul Naidu admitted that so far no such
policies had been introduced in Malaysia although it was common in
developed countries.
	   ``What we have so far is the critical illness policy which
covers some 30 types of illnesses,'' he said.
	   Naidu said he supported Tan's suggestion, but a policy to
support patients for the rest of their life might be unrealistic.
	   Tan suggested insurance companies work out the necessary
calculations to make the best possible policy to cover continuous
treatment.
	   ``Anyway, I think insurance companies do make a lot of money.
Why not expand it a bit for social responsibility,'' he said.
	   Earlier, Naidu said Namlia's haemodialysis centre would be
operational in two months time, starting with six haemodialysis
machines.
	   Another four would be added by the end of the year, he added.
	   Naidu said the cost of setting up the centre would be met
through a series of charity drives. Namlia had set a target of
RM1.5 million in collections, of which more than RM100,000 had been
collected so far.
	   Today's exhibition of some 80 Chinese water colours done by Chu
is expected to raise another RM100,000 as the artist intends to
donate all proceeds from her paintings to the cause.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
