<BODY>
<SLUG> GRAND-BALLROOM-LAUNCH sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Grand ballroom launch, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws GRAND-BALLROOM-LAUNCH sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   THE economic downturn may have hampered Sheraton Subang Hotels
and Towers Kuala Lumpur from organising a grand launching ceremony
for its new ballroom, but the ceremony was nonetheless an affair of
fun and good food.
	   The Selangor ballroom was officially opened on May 19 during a
cocktail reception attended by about 500 guests comprising
corporate executives, travel agents, members of a Sheraton travel
arranger programme called Choice as well as the Press.
	   On hand to greet the guests were Sheraton Subang general manager
John L.
	   Eaton, its public relations manager Stephanie Ng, its reception
manager S.
	   Puvan and Sheraton Langkawi Beach Resort sales and marketing
director Jasmine Heng.
	   The ballroom is located on ground level next to the main hotel
building on the 3.756-hectare site of Sheraton Subang.
	   It has a foyer designed like an observatory with
floor-to-ceiling glass windows, allowing maximum light to penetrate
during the day.
	   Guests were seen appreciating the new concept of the ballroom.
	   It has a unique feature of having a separate entrance and is
also accessible from the hotel lobby.
	   Eaton said the separate entrance provided convenience and
privacy to private functions.
	   He said the observatory-like design is purely for the
convenience of those using the premises.
	   ``Normally, a ballroom would either be underground or in the
centre of a hotel where it is totally enclosed.
	   ``Most people feel they are being trapped. They feel
uncomfortable and stuffy but they couldn't complain because they
think that is what a ballroom is,'' Eaton said.
	   ``With our concept, they can enjoy the sunlight and refreshing
view during a break from conference or meeting.''
	   The ballroom can seat up to 1,500 theatre-style, and 1,050 for
banquet dining.
	   It can also be divided into three smaller function halls.
	   The evening was made merrier by ``live'' performances by an
in-house band and generous offerings of Western and local food.
	   Some caricaturists were also seen going around sketching
portraits of guests while others were seen chasing their hors
d'ouevres as the tables walked away! It was, however, a gimmick. A
table was specially made and attached to a waitress and as she
walked, she carried the table with her. The table ``stopped'' when
there's a request for hors d'ouevres.
	   Also present at the function were Faber Group Bhd director Datuk
Moehamad Izat Emir and management and directors of Faber Hotels
Holdings Sdn Bhd and Renong Group of Companies.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
