w1560  wstm-
r w     HONGKONG-BANK-POSTSsked     06-01 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> HONGKONG-BANK-POSTS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Hongkong Bank posts RM118m pre-tax profit gain, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws HONGKONG-BANK-POSTS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   HONGKONG Bank Malaysia Bhd reported a group pre-tax profit of
RM118.26 million for the first quarter ended March 31, 1998,
compared to a pre-tax loss of RM60.8 million recorded in the
previous quarter.
	   The first quarter's pre-tax profit figure was lower compared to
RM138.93 million recorded for the quarter ended March 31, 1997.
	   In a statement, the bank said interest income for the period
under review was at RM526.03 million, up from RM468.82 million in
the previous quarter and RM363.44 million for the first quarter of
1997.
	   Profit after tax was at RM71.22 million compared to a post-tax
loss of RM53.01 million previously and a profit after tax of
RM95.62 million in the first quarter of 1997.
	   It said total net non-performing loans, which was at 2.5 per
cent of total loans, for the period was at RM383.79 million
compared to RM289.7 million previously and RM141.52 million in the
first quarter last year.
	   General provision stood at RM269.47 million from RM228.48
million in the previous quarter.
	   Total loans provisions surged from a mere RM1 million in the
first quarter of last year to RM122 million, but added that this
was lower than the RM207 million provision in the last quarter of
1997.
	   Interest in suspense stood at RM74.81 million compared to
RM124.86 million previously and RM113.06 million in the 1997 first
quarter.
	   Hongkong Bank deputy chairman and chief executive officer Tim
O'Brien said the bank's results fo the first quarter were affected
by a recognition of emerging credit facilities.
	   ``The current economic conditions have led to a requirement for
higher general and specific provisioning. A conservative view has
been taken on specific non-performing advances and we have
increased the level of general provisions to 1.75 per cent of
advances.''
	   O'Brien added the underlying business of the bank has been
resilient and its strength has been rewarded through market share
growth income business areas.
	   ``The bank's capital position and liquidity remain strong
enabling us to continue with the steady development of our business
in 1998.''
	   Earnings per share was at 35.61 sen compared to a loss of 26.51
sen previously and 47.81 sen in the quarter ended March 31, 1997.
	   For the first three months of this year, deposits at the bank
stood at RM17.06 billion compared to RM17.99 billion previously and
RM13.80 billion in the same period last year.
	   
</TEXT>
