<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Blind Activist,0232 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkish police returns blind human rights activist back to prison 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ Police on Monday put a blind human rights
activist back in prison after he declined to provide a medical
report for his possible pardon on health reasons, the Anatolia news
agency said.
	   Esber Yagmurdereli was released from prison last November after
the government, bowing to pressure from international human rights
activists, suspended his 22-year prison term for one year because
of his high blood pressure and other unspecified health problems.
	   But Yagmurdereli, insisting he is innocent, has refused to
undergo a medical check-up and rejected an amnesty offer on health
reasons.
	   ``Freedom of expression should not be a crime,'' Yagmurdereli
told reporters as plainclothes took him away. ``We have to fight
for it.''
	   Yagmurdereli, 52, was arrested after criticizing the government
in a live television talk show last October and imprisoned near the
town of Cankiri, 130 kilometers (80 miles) northeast of Ankara.
	   Yagmurdereli, a lawyer-turned-activist, was first imprisoned in
1978 on charges of trying to overthrow the government. He was freed
on parole in 1991, only to be arrested soon afterward on charges of
spreading Kurdish separatist propaganda. His arrest last year was a
parole violation that earned him a prison sentence.
