<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Arabs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Arab ministers seek joint strategy ahead of Euro-Med conference 
</HEADLINE>
By HUSSEIN DAKROUB
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Foreign ministers of Arab Mediterranean
countries met here Monday to chart a common strategy against Israel
at a European-Mediterranean conference this week.
	   Israel is participating along with the Palestinian territory and
10 other Mediterranean basin countries in the June 3-4 foreign
ministers' conference in Palermo, Italy. These ministers will meet
with counterparts from the 15 European Union nations.
	   In Palermo, Israel ``will definitely try'' to keep the stalled
Middle East peace process separate from economic relations so that
it can ``continue getting economic gains (from the EU) at the
expense of any political linkage,'' Lebanese Foreign Minister Faris
Bweiz told the Arab ministers.
	   Their two-day meeting is being attended by foreign ministers of
Egypt, Syria, Jordan, Morocco, Libya, Tunisia, Algeria and the
Palestinian Authority. Arab League Secretary-General Esmat Abdel
Meguid also is invited.
	   Jordan is represented by its housing and public works minister,
and Mauritania by its permanent representative at the Arab League.
The 12th Mediterranean participant at Palermo is Cyprus.
	   Bweiz later said the Arab ministers agreed that it was
``impossible to separate the political aspects of the (Middle East)
peace process from the other security, economic or social
aspects.''
	   Discussions in Palermo will focus on the Euro-Mediterranean
partnership agreement, which was launched in Barcelona in 1995 to
forge closer political, economic and social ties between the two
regions.
	   Citing its dlrs 2.3 billion annual aid to the region, including
to Israel and the Palestinians, the EU is seeking a greater role in
Arab-Israeli peace-making efforts, which have been largely led by
the United States since 1991.
	   But Israel and the United States are not in favor of that.
Israel views the Europeans, especially France, as too pro-Arab.
	   Bweiz said he supported a European role in the Mideast peace
process. ``Europe is concerned with security in this region and
with nuclear situation in this region,'' he told reporters after
the three-hour meeting. He was referring to Israel's undeclared
nuclear arsenal.
	   Local newspapers said Monday the Arab ministers would discuss a
plan for dealing with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's
hard-line policies, which have been blamed by Arab countries for
the current stalemate in Arab-Israeli peace negotiations.
	   They will try to persuade the EU to take action, mainly
economic, to force Netanyahu to advance the peace process, the
reports said.
	   Bweiz said Lebanon supported current efforts to convene an Arab
summit aimed at reviving the peace process.
  hd/vj
</TEXT>
