<SLUG> BC-Angola </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. envoy says Angolan rebels still have armed forces 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   LUANDA, Angola (AP) _ The United Nations envoy to Angola said
Monday that the country's former rebels maintain armed units in the
bush and have failed to meet the latest deadline in the delayed
peace process.
	   Alioune Blondin Beye said UNITA was hiding troops in several of
the vast southwest African nation's 18 provinces. He declined to
specify the areas, or estimate the size of the forces.
	   Sunday's deadline for UNITA to hand over to the government the
four remaining areas it still controls had also passed unfulfilled,
Beye told a news conference.
	   Under the U.N.-brokered 1994 peace pact, UNITA _ a Portuguese
acronym for the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
_ agreed to relinquish its control over more than half of the
country it seized during the two-decade civil war.
	   ``UNITA doesn't feel that the current context is favorable to
the extension of the state administration (to the final four
areas),'' Beye said.
	   The U.N. envoy said that the government had complied with his
demands to tone down hostile propaganda against UNITA and clamp
down on human rights abuses by the police.
	   UNITA has tabled a new proposal to hand over control of its four
strongholds by June 30, according to Beye.
	   He said he would travel to New York later this week to discuss
the proposal with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
	   But a speech by UNITA Deputy President Antonio Dembo on Monday
fueled uncertainty over the former rebels' stance.
	   Dembo said the government was attempting to ``wipe out'' UNITA
through ``manhunts, arbitrary detentions and the torture and murder
(of the movement's officials).''
	   UNITA's number two provided no concrete evidence for his claims
made when he formally reopened the movement's refurbished offices
in Luanda. A two-floor house that was partially destroyed in the
fighting that followed the rebels' refusal to accept defeat in 1992
elections that plunged the country back into civil war.
	   Beye said he ``disliked the tone'' of Dembo's comments.
	   UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi has refused to leave his central
highland stronghold at Bailundo, 290 kilometers (180 miles) south
of the capital, saying he fears for his safety in Luanda.
	   War first broke out after the country's 1975 independence from
Portugal.
	   (bh/jt)
</TEXT>
