<HEADER>
w1573  wstm-
r w     REMEMBER-SINATRAsked     06-01 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> REMEMBER-SINATRA sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
In a frenzy for something to remember Sinatra by, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws REMEMBER-SINATRA sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   ERNIE Country, 62, who calls himself the other kid from Hoboken
was at Pinky's, a second-hand store selling knick-knacks from
plastic toys to used cassettes at 156 Monroe Street belting out
``Come Fly With Me'', accompanied by music from his portable
cassette player.
	   He received applause as he sang a phrase or two that was
distinctively familiar. If you were to close your eyes, and let
your imagination run a bit, then you could have sworn that Ol' Blue
Eyes was back in town.
	   But that was not the case. It was the Friday when world woke up
to the news that Frank Sinatra had died. And Hoboken, a small town
in New Jersey across the Hudson River from Manhattan, was suddenly
the centre of media attention. It was here that 82 years ago, at
151 Monroe Street beside Pinky's, Francis Albert Sinatra was born.
	   The scores of television camera and journalists were parked near
an empty lot where a star with a picture of Sinatra had been placed
on the ground two years ago to mark the hallowed ground. There was
to be a tenement building there, a walk-up apartment complex
occupied by first and second-generation poor Italian immigrants who
decided to quit Manhattan to live there.
	   Country, who impersonates Sinatra for a living, got the call at
4.30am that Friday. It was a television reporter who broke the news
to him and wanted his comments. Of course he was sad, he said. The
man was his hero.
	   At six in the morning, Country, who now lives in Staten Island,
was in Hoboken. He was soon on television, one station after
another, sharing his grief with the millions watching the morning
news and singing ``In The Wee Small Hours of the Morning''.
	   He knew that while it was a sad occassion, it was also a chance
for some publicity. With Sinatra gone, some die-hard fans might
find him a good substitute.
	   Sinatra's death was not a tragedy. He had been ill for a while
and had not recorded any new tunes for years. But the mystique and
magic of the man, that oh so effortless singing that made him the
legend he was, remained. The New York tabloids ran special editions
that day; the Daily News simply said ``Sinatra Dead''.
	   At Pinky's, the girl behind the counter was apologetic. It must
have been the hundredth time that day that she had to tell
customers they had ran out of Sinatra's stuff. Since the star was
unveiled, there had been a constant flow of Sinatra fans paying
homage to Hoboken and the spot next door.
	   Ever the shrewd businessman and owner Pinky Cato, whose burly
figure seemed inappropriate for the name, decided to sell Sinatra
T-shirts, Sinatra mugs, pins and hats to the visiting fans.
	   But that Friday morning, when news of Sinatra's demise spread in
Los Angeles some 3,000 miles away, mourners started snapping
everything Sinatra, so much so that by 10am he sold everything.
	   Like Country, Cato sensed that even on that dark day there was a
silver lining for him. He called his supplier and told them to
start cranking as much Sinatra stuff as possible and bring them
over. People were dying for something to remember Sinatra by, and
he was not fulfilling their needs.
	   He would tell them that by the next day he would have them.
	   Just to remind the mourners who came, he had one last T-shirt
hung over a Sinatra shine that was soon beginning to grow around
the spot. There was an Italian flag, pictures of the young crooner,
letters to friends in the neighbourhood, flowers, candles, notes,
even a loaf of Italian bread -Sinatra was said to have liked them
so much he had them flown to California every once in a while.
	   At Picollo, a 15-minute walk from Monroe Street, there was also
a group of television reporters. On the restaurant window the owner
wrote ``We will always rememeber you Frank.''
	   Apart from its superb cheesesteak sandwich, the place had been
an unofficial home of the Hoboken Sinatra appreciation society. In
the backroom there was a rather tacky ensemble with wall to wall
pictures of Sinatra. Sinatra the teeny booper, the Swinging Frank,
the Cool Frank with the hat tilted somewhat, Frank as the leader of
the Rat Pack, Frank as the music's elder statesmen, etc.
	   The Hispanic cook and waiters, more comfortable with Spanish
than Italian, were slightly amused by the attention the restaurant
was getting.
	   But they looked more amused at the boss' wife, who that day was
in a dress too fine to run a restaurant in. The television cameras
must have done the trick.
	   But at Picollo that day, there was no music. For years, there
would be Sinatra's music daily from the time it openened its doors
in the morning right to the time it closed. No one else would
serenade its clients, but that local boy who made good. But that
day, only the sound of dishes being arranged could be heard.
	   Up in the Bronx, at the Yankees Stadium that night, there was a
moment of silence to remember Sinatra. The baseball players and
fans lowered their heads and had their caps to their chest. Sinatra
lives forever in Yankees Stadium where after each game his anthemic
``New York, New York''
	   would be played to send the fans home humming in the subway
trains and in their cars.
	   That night they had a series of songs between innings to keep
the place swinging. ``Luck Be A lady Tonight'' was blared through
the public announcement system, and in the cool night in the
expanse of the stadium, it sounded so right. But luck was not with
the Yankees that night. Even with a sign that read ``Win One for
Frankie'', they lost to the Minnesota Twins 7-6.
	   In Manhattan that Friday night, the Empire State Building had
its spire bathed in blue light in honour of Ol' Blue Eyes.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:REMEMBER-SINATRA sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
