<BODY>
<SLUG> THE-NUCLEAR-CLUB sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Disband the nuclear club, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws THE-NUCLEAR-CLUB sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   PAKISTAN has ignored world opinion not to take the same path
that India travelled two weeks ago in testing nuclear its
capability. At 5-5 in one month alone, the score is tied and honour
has perhaps been satisfied.
	   Has the detonation of nuclear devices been worth it in a
tit-for-tat grudge match? Pakistanis themselves will have to weigh
the answer against the larger risk of economic and social
repercussions, and decide if pride alone will suffice to sustain a
population of 140 million. The bite of an immediate shutdown of
external humanitarian and development aid will be felt long after
the euphoria fades. Pakistan's only consolation may be that its
erstwhile neighbour is dealing with the same fallout.
	   Not too long ago, there was a glimmer of hope that India and
Pakistan were finally meeting on common ground to resolve an enmity
that has stretched over 50 years. The nuclear tests need not mean
an end of this, but could become yet another area in which they
work towards a lasting understanding that is beneficial to both
countries. And it could begin with them signing the 1996
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.
	   India's earlier assurance that it would conduct a strategic
review of its nuclear programme must be met with a similarly
unequivocal undertaking by Pakistan. Indeed, both must further
declare a moratorium against taking that next step which would
result in nuclear weapons being designed and built. Regional
stability depends on this, as does the protection of humanity from
the disastrous outcome of playing with nuclear warheads.
	   With the latest episode, the global community can no longer
afford to dither over tough decisions. The five major nuclear
powers especially have to show greater seriousness in implementing
nuclear arms disarmament conventions. The US, Britain, Russia,
China and France can hardly preach when they have practised all
that they now seek to ban. It is time to disband the club. For so
long as this is not done, there will always be some ambitious
country or other trying to make a point, just for the sake of doing
so.
	   Pakistan and its leaders can expect to feel the same stinging
denouncement by world leaders that accompanied India's venture into
what is considered forbidden territory. As it is, the response has
been predictable and instantaneous - the US imposing sanctions,
Japan withdrawing aid, Australia cutting military ties and dropping
official visits, and Germany stopping talks on economic
development. Pakistan, now in a state of emergency, has battened
down the hatches and is looking to wait out the storm of
disapproval.
	   The nuclear arms race does the world no good at all. There are
more productive ways in which mankind can utilise resources for its
own progress, to leave a constructive rather than destructive
legacy. More is to be gained from investing in peace than preparing
for the eventuality of war. After two World Wars and numerous armed
conflicts, no further proof is needed that war is a wanton waste of
the earth's most precious resource -life.
	   If national leaders refuse to see this, then the potential
victims of aggression must claim their rights through national
democratic processes.
	   Economic, social and health arguments will prevail over military
insecurities and political posturing. Long after the dust settles
on test sites, it will be ordinary citizens who will continue to
carry the burden of the nuclear arms race.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:THE-NUCLEAR-CLUB sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
