<BODY>
<SLUG> FREEZE-ON-KL-ROADWORK sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Freeze on KL roadwork permits pending Games, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws FREEZE-ON-KL-ROADWORK sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA Lumpur City Hall, preparing for the 16th Commonwealth
Games to be held between Sept 11 and 21, has stopped issuing new
permits for road digging and other work that might mar the beauty
of the city.
	   Datuk Bandar Tan Sri Kamaruzzaman Sharif said many roads in the
federal capital, in particular those outside the city centre, had
been resurfaced.
	   He said all roads in the city will be resurfaced before the
Games.
	   He was speaking to reporters after chairing the Kuala Lumpur
City Hall Advisory Board meeting on Saturday.
	   Kamaruzzaman said contrary to criticism from the media that
Kuala Lumpur has too much built-up area and too few green lungs,
the city had more than 450ha of parks and playgrounds that were in
good condition.
	   He said Kuala Lumpur will be presented as the ``Garden City of
Lights''for the Games.
	   Kamaruzzaman said landscaping work was being carried out all
over the city with the International Garden project in Bukit Jalil
an added attraction.
	   He said he has asked the contractor for the turnkey project,
Seri Merga Construction Sdn Bhd, to finish part of the garden in
time for the Games although this was not specified in the contract.
	   He was confident that the garden, which will feature a boating
pond, an ornamental lake, a picnic site and a cascading waterfall,
will be completed in time for the Games.
	   The garden will have 28 international themed gardens with 10
expected to be ready.
	   The international gardens include those depicting English,
Japanese, Iranian, Dutch, Peruvian, Indonesian, Thai, Canadian,
Chinese and Malaysian themes and will cost a total of RM30 million.
	   Kamaruzzaman said more areas in Kuala Lumpur will be turned into
gardens under a City Hall plan to create a bigger green belt.
	   He had said a total of 400ha in several areas including Pudu
Hulu, Taman Metropolitan, Kepong, Jinjang Utara, Taman Manjalara
and Taman West Valley in Bukit Kiara had been identified for the
project.
	   He said the 400-metre long and 30-metre wide pedestrian mall
project at Jalan P. Ramlee was still on the cards.
	   City Hall is in the process of signing a privatisation agreement
with the contractor undertaking the project.
	   ``The project is very much on and we hope it will be ready for
the Games.
	   It will be an added attraction to both local and foreign
tourists visiting the city.
	   ``The mall, situated behind Holiday Inn on the Park and other
commercial buildings, will be landscaped with indigenous plants, of
both the flowering and non-flowering variety. It will also be lined
with kiosks selling refreshments and souvenirs.''
	   The mall, Kamaruzzaman said, would be an ideal place to take a
stroll.
	   He sees local and foreign tourists relaxing amidst the lush
greenery.
	   He added that the mall was unique as it would actually be
sitting on a box drain culvert covered with earth.
	   Kamaruzzaman said as part of the on-going beautification
campaign, he will launch the ``Love Your Drain and River'' campaign
on the banks of the Sungai Gombak near the Putra World Trade Centre
on Aug 8.
	   This year, City Hall has a RM53 million development budget, of
which RM11 million will be for the maintenance and upkeep of
rivers.
	   From the RM11 million, RM3 million is being spent on keeping
rivers clean while the rest is for the deepening, maintenance,
canalising and infrastructure work on eight rivers passing through
the Federal Territory.
	   Kamaruzzaman said City Hall was also intensifying efforts to get
building owners to repaint their buildings by the end of next
month.
	   Those failing to do so will be billed after the local authority
has undertaken the task for them.
	   
</TEXT>
