<SLUG> POULTRY-INDUSTRY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Poultry industry `must tackle pollution problem', NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws POULTRY-INDUSTRY sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   MALACCA, Fri. - Poultry farmers should live in harmony with the
environment and society, says Agriculture Minister Datuk Amar Dr
Sulaiman Daud.
	   He said he would like to see a commitment by the industry to
restructure itself further so that conflict could be reduced.
	   Poorly managed farms too close to housing projects made for a
negative image, as they caused pollution, he said.
	   Dr Sulaiman said the industry would have to be realistic about
the complaints of pollution and make efforts to overcome the
problems associated wth poultry farming.
	   The industry would do well to consider the possibilities of
integrating itself with other major agriculture sector activities.
	   ``For instance, poultry operations should consider relocating
their farms into the oil palm plantations.
	   ``This arrangement would not only create a more friendly
environment away from human habitat but would also provide good
protection as the trees could act as buffer zones between farms,''
he said at a dinner hosted by the Leong Hup Holdings Bhd held in
conjunction with its 10th anniversary.
	   ``In a modernising society where industrialisation and
manufacturing is in the forefront of economic growth, we should be
proud that the poultry industry has not lagged behind in the
development of its growth potential.
	   ``With no direct subsidies from the Government, the poultry
sector has the vision to seek business partners from overseas to
help build a production system.''
	   He added that from the estimated RM1.4 billion import bill for
feed ingredients, Malaysia produced RM4.18 billion ex-farm value of
livestock, of which poultry and eggs were valued at RM2.82 billion.
	   He said the ministry would continue to look for an economically
viable local substitute for expensive imported feed.
	   ``Looking into the future, the major poultry producers will have
to be more vertically and horizontally integrated. This will be a
part of the on-going transformation process of the industry.
	   ``I would also like to see a win-win situation created between
the existing small and independent scale farmers and producers and
the integrators.''
	   He said one way was for independent farmers to be clustered or
become contract growers to integrators. In the transformation, the
big producers must continue to ensure that the independent farmers
had an equal chance of continuing their operations.
	   Also present were Leong Hup Holdings executive director Datuk
Francis Lau, Veterinary Services Department director-general Datuk
Dr Hadi Hashim, Arbor Acres Asian division manager and
vice-president Gordon Lawrence and Arbor Acres Pacific Area manager
David Hutchinson.
	   
</TEXT>
