<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Don: Peg to US dollar biggest problem, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws PEG-TO-US-DOLLAR-BIGGEST sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   June 01, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sun. - The pegging of regional currencies to the
US dollar was a major contributor to the financial problems in
several Asean member states.
	   ``Pegging to the US dollar was the biggest problem,'' said Prof
Jomo K.S., of Universiti Malaya's economics faculty.
	   He added that the peg allowed foreign fund managers to gain
access to some of the economies.
	   ``This resulted in economies in the region continuing to record
positive growth rates and thrive,'' he said.
	   He was addressing international students at the final day of the
four-day Harvard Project for Asian and International Relations
Conference at Putra World Trade Centre today.
	   The conference, entitled Asia in Transition: Beyond the Miracle
saw a gathering of top students from renowned universities
worldwide to exchange perspectives on critical international
issues.
	   Another issue which should be resolved is whether current
account deficits contributed to the problem.
	   ``This is not possible as it was covered by the entry of foreign
funds,'' he said.
	   Citing Malaysia, Joko said the Labuan International Offshore
Financial Centre enabled the circulation of foreign currencies in
the country.
	   ``It allowed easy entry of foreign funds.''
	   On claims by certain quarters that ``crony capitalism''
contributed to the regional problem, Joko said this was a matter of
interpretation.
	   ``It (crony capitalism) cannot explain the crisis,'' he said,
adding that it did not undermine the rapid growth that took place
in the region.
	   
</TEXT>
