<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Speed up clearance of goods vehicles, departments told, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws CLEARANCE-OF-GOODS sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   MALACCA, Fri. - The Immigration and Customs and Excise
departments have been told to improve their services at the Bukit
Kayu Hitam checkpoint so that vehicles transporting goods are
cleared faster for entry into Thailand.
	   Deputy Transport Minister Datuk Wira Mohd Ali Rustam said he had
received complaints that enforcement officers took a long time to
inspect the vehicles.
	   ``I have been told that sometimes they take half a day to
inspect just one vehicle. Their counterparts at the Causeway take
only two hours to clear each vehicle.''
	   He was speaking after closing the orientation programme at
Universiti Telekom yesterday.
	   Mohd Ali said the departments could assign more manpower to
handle the task.
	   ``This was brought up at a post-Cabinet meeting a few weeks ago
and I hope the departments could work together to improve their
services.''
	   He also said he had not received any memorandum from the
Pan-Malaysian Lorry Association on difficulties which their members
faced in view of the economic downturn.
	   The association, who claims to have 100,000 members, had
recently stated that some of its members, had been forced to quit
due to the downturn.
	   It wanted the ministry to assist them by offering the 5,000
lorry permit holders, haulier licences.
	   Mohd Ali said the ministry could not offer such assistance.
	   
</TEXT>
