<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Airline Strike, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0419 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Flights continue as government intervenes in airline strike 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: RECASTS with new detail. Changes byline.
By KEN GUGGENHEIM
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Aeromexico flights remained on schedule
Monday after the government took over operations of Mexico's
largest airline and striking flight attendants agreed to work.
	   The government's decision to temporarily seize the airline left
the 1,033 unionized flight attendants with little choice but to
continue working and wait for negotiations to resume, said Lizette
Clavel, a spokeswoman for the Unionized Association of Flight
Attendants. But she said the move put the union at a disadvantage
in bargaining.
	   The union declared the strike at midnight Sunday, charging the
airline was unwilling to negotiate better working conditions and
pay.
	   The government responded by taking over management control and
appointing an acting general administrator. Mexico's constitution
gives the government the right to temporarily seize companies vital
to the nation's economy or security.
	   Aaron Dychter, undersecretary of transportation, said at a news
conference that the government was not taking sides in the dispute,
but was protecting the public interest in taking over an airline
that carries about 30,000 passengers a day.
	   ``We cannot allow, or think about, putting in risk the national
economy,'' he said.
	   The government had been prepared to use replacement workers and
non-union flight attendants to maintain as much of its schedule as
possible.
	   Union members decided it would be ``the lesser evil'' to return
to work, the union's secretary-general, Alejandra Barrales
Magdaleno, told the Televisa television network.
	   Although close to agreement on wage issues, the union and
airline are fighting over benefits and working conditions. Flight
attendants want a pension plan, better health benefits and
guarantees on flight staffing. Aeromexico wants to increase shifts
by two hours and reduce the time between shifts.
	   Labor problems weren't evident at Mexico City's airport Monday
morning. No pickets were in sight and television monitors listed
Aeromexico's flights as ``on time.''
	   Jose Luis Nieves, traveling on Aeromexico to Acapulco for a
business convention, said he was relieved to hear that flight
attendants were still on the job.
	   ``I hope that there aren't any last-minute surprises,'' he said.
</TEXT>
