<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
KK seeks public's help to deal with squatters, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws KK-SEEKS-PUBLIC'S-HELP sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   KOTA KINABALU, Fri. - The Kota Kinabalu Municipal Council will
seek public support in dealing with tough problems, including those
involving squatters and illegal hawkers.
	   Incoming KKMC president Datuk Dayang Adeline Leong said this
after taking over the post from Stephen Shee today. Shee had served
as the president for 10 months.
	   ``Squatters are bound to sprout anytime and anywhere but the
KKMC cannot give up on that situation.
	   ``I believe we need to get co-operation from the public,
especially on giving information on new squatter settlements.''
	   She said there was a `whole range of departments' in the KKMC
which must work as a unit to achieve goals.
	   Leong, who had been the director of the State Library for 25
years, is the first woman in Sabah to hold a municipal council
president's post.
	   She is also chairman of the Sabah Information Technology
Committee's Working Committee on IT in Social Development.
	   Leong, 48, a mother of two, obtained her Bachelor of Arts in
Asian Studies at the Australian National University, Canberra and
Post-Graduate Diploma in Librarianship at the Royal Melbourne
Institute of Technology.
	   She has headed various organisations like the Toastmasters Club,
Sabah Women Advisory Council, Sabah Women Entrepreneurs
Professional Association, Sabah Government Officers Association,
Intan Jaycees and is a member of the International Federation of
Library Association and the Institute for Development Studies
Sabah.
	   She will start work on Tuesday.
	   
</TEXT>
