<BODY>
<SLUG> SILICON-NAVIGATOR sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
Silicon Navigator distributor for US company, NEW STRAITS TIMES- MANAGEMENT TIMES  
   xfdws SILICON-NAVIGATOR sked
   Emerging Markets Datafile
   May 30, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   ENGLISH
	   COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH,
INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED
HEREIN MAY BE USED
	   IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
<TEXT>
	   SILICON Navigator Sdn Bhd has been appointed the distributor for
US company Internet Security Systems Inc's products and security
consultancy services for Malaysia, Indonesia and Brunei, following
a signing ceremony between both parties yesterday.
	   Silicon Navigator is a hub for research and development
activities within the Silicon group of companies, and began
offering internet security services 18 months ago.
	   ISS, listed on Nasdaq, focusses on protecting network and
information from any malicious intent and action.
	   Following the partnership, Silicon Navigator will provide
security consulting services based on ISS products and will be the
major distributor for SAFESuite products, namely RealSecure.
	   RealSecure is an automated, real-time attack recognition and
response system for enterprises. It protects information assets by
automatically detecting and responding to both internal and
external security breaches.
	   Potential customers include those from banking and finance,
telecommunications, internet service providers, and government
agencies which handle a lot of data and corporations with large
networks.
	   Silicon Navigator chief executive officer Kho Han Mien said
security breaches are serious as they are difficult to detect.
	   Energy, Telecommunications and Posts Minister Datuk Leo Moggie
witnessed the signing ceremony in Kuala Lumpur yesterday.
	   Later at a Press conference, Leo Moggie, citing statistics from
International Data Corporation, said electronic commerce in
Malaysia, which accounted for just US$4 million(RM15.2 million)
worth of sales in 1997, was expected to grow to US$95 million next
year, and US$1 billion by 2001.
	   He said the explosive use of the Internet had led to its
acceptance as a practical medium of communication for individuals,
corporates, and others.
	   ``As more and more people begin to conduct business on the
Internet, security has emerged as a crucial factor for the
successful conduct of electronic commerce.''
	   Last year, Malaysia pioneered the enactment of several cyberlaws
to ensure a fair, stable and secure environment free from fraud,
counterfeiting and piracy.
	   He said the Data Protection Act, being considered and drafted,
was likley to be tabled in Parliament by year end.
	   ``It is our intention to make sure that data will be properly
secured.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
