<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-Dodgers-Nomo, 1st Ld-Writethru,0340 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dodgers cut Nomo AP Sports Writer 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with background
By JOHN NADEL
<TEXT>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) _ Hideo Nomo's career with the Los Angeles
Dodgers came to an abrupt halt on Monday when the team removed the
Japanese right-hander from the roster.
	   Nomo's agent, Don Nomura, met with Dodgers general manager Fred
Claire on Sunday and asked for a move to be made.
	   Nomo, who put Japan on the U.S. major league map in 1995 when he
signed a contract with the Dodgers and became an immediate star,
was just 2-7 with a 5.05 ERA this season.
	   Los Angeles designated Nomo for assignment. The move removes him
from the Dodgers' 40-man roster immediately. The team has 10 days
to either trade or assign the 29-year pitcher, or seven days to
place him on unconditional release waivers.
	   Nomo, who became the fastest pitcher in U.S. Major League
history to record 500 strikeouts when he accomplished the feat in
444 2-3 innings 13 months ago, had gone downhill since 1995, when
he was the National League Rookie of the Year.
	   He was booed in his most recent start _ against Cincinnati on
Saturday when he allowed seven hits and six runs in 3 2-3 innings
while walking three and striking out three.
	   Nomo has lost four straight decisions, and he has allowed 18
earned runs in his last 26 2-3 innings.
	   Claire said Nomura called him Saturday night and asked for a
meeting.
	   ``Hideo had expressed the thought that it would be best to make
a move,'' Claire said at a Dodger Stadium news conference. ``This
was the best move to accommodate that request.''
	   Nomo is signed through the end of the season and is earning dlrs
2.7 million this year _ his fourth with the Dodgers. He is not
eligible to become a free agent.
	   ``Maybe a chance of scenery would be beneficial for Hideo,''
said Nomura, who cited recent trade rumors, causing his client to
want to pitch somewhere else. ``Just a change in the environment.''
</TEXT>
