<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup-Netherlands-Paraguay,0664 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Netherlands puts on powerful attacking show to crush Paraguay 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photos
By MIKE CORDER
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   EINDHOVEN, Netherlands (AP) _ The Netherlands put on a powerful
display of attacking soccer to crush Paraguay 5-1 in a clash of two
World Cup bound sides in the Philips Stadium here Monday.
	   After being criticized by coach Guus Hiddink for squandering
chances in last week's lackluster 0-0 draw with Cameroon, the Dutch
struck the target almost at will Monday.
	   ``After the Cameroon game, we needed a result like this,''
Hiddink said. ``It was important for us and for the supporters.''
	   But Hiddink said his team needed to keep its concentration in
defense even when attacking.
	   ``We gave away too many chances today,'' he said.
	   Marc Overmars scored twice and set up another goal before being
substituted to a standing ovation in the 71st minute.
	   Paraguay took a surprise lead in just the second minute when
Jorge Campos chested down a headed pass from Jose Cardozo and
immediately volleyed the ball low to Edwin van der Sar's right.
	   Van der Sar, appearing to think the ball was going wide, made no
effort to save it and watched helplessly as the shot hit the back
of the net.
	   The Netherlands gradually clawed its way back into the game as
Arsenal's Overmars repeatedly beat defenders down the left flank.
	   In the 8th minute, Patrick Kluivert tipped an Overmars cross
just over the bar and five minutes later Overmars headed on a pass
to Ronald de Boer who controlled the ball on is chest and volleyed
just over the bar in a near repeat of Paraguay's opening goal.
	   It was Overmars, the Netherlands' most dangerous player, who
scored the equalizer, shooting low into the corner of Paraguayan
goalkeeper Jose Luis Chilavert's net after a deft pass from
Kluivert in the 26th minute.
	   Kluivert and Overmars combined again in the 29th minute to give
the Netherlands a 2-1 lead. Kluivert's powerful drive was well
saved by Chilavert but Overmars was on hand to tap in the rebound.
	   And it was the same pair who teamed up two minutes later to give
the Netherlands a 3-1 lead. Overmars beat two defenders and took
the ball to the touch line before squaring it to Kluivert who shot
home from close range.
	   The Netherlands continued its trademark fluent attacking soccer
after the break.
	   Substitute Boudewijn Zenden set up the fourth Dutch goal,
crossing in the 58th minute for captain Frank de Boer to head in.
	   Paraguay should have pulled a goal back in the 67th minute when
Miguel Benitez found himself with only replacement goalkeeper Ed de
Goey to beat, but put his shot wide.
	   Zenden came close to scoring a spectacular goal in the 72nd
minute. He picked up the ball on his own halfway line and beat
tackle after tackle before unleashing a powerful shot that beat the
goalkeeper but crashed off the inside of the post and rebounded to
safety.
	   Jimmy Hasselbaink made it 5-1 in the 83rd minute, calmly sliding
in a pass from Kluivert.
	   The Netherlands takes on Belgium, South Korea and Mexico in
World Cup qualifying Group E while Paraguay has a tough task in
Group D where it meets Spain, Bulgaria and Nigeria.
	   The Dutch take on Nigeria Friday in their last warm-up match
before leaving for France.
	   Lineups:
	   Netherlands: Edwin van der Sar (Ed de Goey, 45), Michael
Reiziger, Jaap Stam (Winston Bogarde, 45), Frank de Boer, Arthur
Numan, Clarence Seedorf (Boudewijn Zenden, 45), Aron Winter,
Phillip Cocu (Edgar Davids, 45), Marc Overmars (Jimmy Hasselbaink,
71), Ronald de Boer, Patrick Kluivert.
	   Paraguay: Jose Luis Chilavert, Francisco Arce, Catalino Rivarola
(Pedro Sarabia, 45), Carlos Gamarra, Celso Ayala, Jose Cardozo
(Cesar Ramirez, 56), Carlos Paredes, Miguel Angel Benitez, Julio
Cesar Enciso, Denis Caniza, Jorge Campos (Hugo Brizuela, 63).
</TEXT>
