t i     BC-Spain-EquatorialGuine     06-01 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-Equatorial Guinea-Sedition Trial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fifteen condemned to death for sedition in Equatorial Guinea 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ A military court sentenced 15 people to
death for sedition in Equatorial Guinea on Monday at the end of a
mass trial of more than 100 people, according to Spanish news
reports.
	   The sentences were revealed in Madrid by representatives of the
opposition to President Teodoro Obiang who also reported that the
remaining defendants had received jail sentences of between six and
24 years, Spanish national radio said.
	   The charges stemmed from an attack in January on a military
barracks on the Guinean island of Bioko _ the home of most of the
ethnic Bubi minority in this tiny central west African country.
	   Many of the condemned belong to the Bioko Autonomy Movement, an
outlawed political group that strongly opposes Obiang.
	   ``The sentences are outrageous'' a spokesman for the group said
on Spanish radio, claiming that confessions had been forced out of
accused with torture.
	   ``This can only bring instability to Equatorial Guinea'' he
said.
	   The human rights group Amnesty International, along with several
European countries and the United States, has long accused Obiang's
government of human rights violations.
	   Obiang seized power in this oil-rich country wedged between
Cameroon and Gabon in 1979 by overthrowing his uncle Francisco
Macias Nguema.
	   Some 500 people, mostly Bubi, were arrested in the military
crackdown that followed the January attack, which left four
soldiers and one civilian dead.
	   Amnesty claimed four of the detained died in custody and sent
two observers to the mass trial in Malabo _ the capital of this
former Spanish colony of about 400,000 inhabitants.
	   Calls to Amnesty on Monday went unanswered.
	   Spanish journalists covering the trial were asked to leave the
country last Friday after they reported that some of the accused
had been tortured. A precise figure for the number of those tried
could not be obtained.
	   Monday's sentences prompted Spanish Foreign Minister Abel
Matutes to send a letter to his Guinean counterpart calling on
Obiang to pardon the lives of the 15 condemned to death, national
radio said. The Spanish Socialist Party issued a statement
describing the trial as ``full of irregularities.''
	   The trial was of particular interest in Madrid because four
Spaniards of Guinean origin were among the defendants. They were
absolved of all charges, the radio reported.
	   (jt)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Spain-Equatorial Guinea-Sedition Trial; CT:i; 
