<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-Dodgers-Nomo, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0377 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dodgers cut Nomo AP Sports Writer 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with additional details and quotes.
By JOHN NADEL
<TEXT>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) _ Hideo Nomo's career with the Los Angeles
Dodgers came to an abrupt halt on Monday when the team removed the
Japanese right-hander from the roster.
	   Nomo's agent, Don Nomura, met with Dodgers general manager Fred
Claire on Sunday and asked for a move to be made.
	   ``We'll be talking to many teams, perhaps all teams,'' Claire
said. There is a time frame. That being said, there is also a great
demand for pitching.''
	   Nomo, who put Japan on the U.S. major league baseball map in
1995 when he signed a contract with the Dodgers and became an
immediate star, was just 2-7 with a 5.05 ERA this season.
	   Los Angeles designated Nomo for assignment. The move removes him
from the Dodgers' 40-man roster immediately. The team has 10 days
to either trade or assign the 29-year pitcher, or seven days to
place him on unconditional release waivers.
	   Nomo said little during a brief news conference. But, through an
interpreter, he said it was true he ``definitely needed a change of
scenery, a change of environment,'' and that the boos he heard
Saturday were not significant.
	   ``I'm truly grateful for everything the Dodgers did provide me,
with an opportunity to fulfill a dream.''
	   Nomo was the 1995 National League Rookie of the Year and struck
out 500 faster than any other pitcher, accomplishing the feat in
444 2-3 innings. But he's stumbled of late and was booed in his
most recent start _ against Cincinnati on Saturday. Nomo allowed
six runs and seven hits in 3 2-3 innings.
	   Nomo has lost four straight decisions, and he has allowed 18
earned runs in his last 26 2-3 innings.
	   ``Hideo had expressed the thought that it would be best to make
a move,'' Claire said. ``This was the best move to accommodate that
request.''
	   Nomo is signed through the end of the season and is earning dlrs
2.7 million this year _ his fourth in the big leagues.
	   To fill Nomo's roster spot, the Dodgers purchased the contract
of 25-year-old left-hander Gary Rath from Albuquerque of the
Pacific Coast League.
</TEXT>
