<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugo-Kosovo, 5th Ld-Writethru,0626 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thousands of refugees flee fighting in Kosovo; dozens reported dead,0620 
</HEADLINE>
RETRANSMITTING to fix slug
Eds: UPDATES throughout with details. EDITS to tighten.
By ISMET HAJDARI
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Thousands of refugees from Serbia's
Kosovo province streamed into neighboring Albania on Monday to
escape some of the deadliest fighting in months. Dozens of people
were reported killed.
	   Albania appealed to the United States and European Union to
intervene in what it said was a ``massacre'' in Kosovo.
	   ``This is just the start of a war with tragic dimensions,'' the
Albanian government said in a statement.
	   With 39 people reported killed over the weekend and fighting
apparently continuing, the bloodshed appeared the worst since
March, when Serbian police killed more than 80 people in a
crackdown on militants among the ethnic Albanian majority in
Serb-ruled Kosovo.
	   In New York, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard spoke of ``heavy and
indiscriminate shelling'' of villages near the border with Albania.
He said U.N. workers could see heavy mortars being fired into the
villages.
	   Refugees said a 3-year-old child died en route to Albania.
	   Ethnic Albanian officials said 37 Albanians were killed over the
weekend. Twenty-seven died in clashes in Decani while 10 were
killed when Serb police stormed a village elsewhere, they said.
	   Two Serb policemen also died in the fighting around Decani, 45
miles west of Kosovo's capital, Pristina, Serb sources said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
	   The fierce fighting forced about 2,000 Kosovo Albanians _ mostly
women, children and the elderly _ across the border into Albania's
Tropoja (pronounced Tro-POH-yah) region on Sunday and Monday,
Albania said. They said more were arriving by the hour.
	   In Tropoja, some refugees said they had walked for up to 20
hours to reach the Albanian town. They said Serb tanks were
positioned inside Decani, and that Serb forces were besieging the
town.
	   Tropoja, although some three miles inside Albanian territory,
resembled a community under siege, with most of the men carrying
rifles or other weapons. Some men displayed the insignia of the
Kosovo Liberation Army, the militant Kosovo organization
spearheading the fight against Serbia.
	   Andrew Harper, a U.N. aid worker, said he purchased three tons
of flour, rice and other basics on the local market to provide for
the refugees, and more aid was expected from Tirana, the Albanian
capital, on Tuesday.
	   ``I am very worried about providing for all these people,'' said
Isa Memia, the town leader. ``We have grave (supply) problems
ourselves, but they are our kinsmen, and we will help them.''
	   Authorities in Serbia are using Serbian police and the Yugoslav
army to try to crush militants and maintain control over the
province, where 90 percent of the population of 2.2 million is
ethnic Albanian.
	   The conflict has killed more than 200 people in Kosovo since the
beginning of March. About half of the province is believed
controlled by militant Albanians and many regions are blocked off,
either by Serbs or Albanians.
	   The Kosovo Information Center, close to the ethnic Albanian
leadership, released the names of the 10 people it said were killed
Sunday when Serb police stormed the village of Poklek, 15 miles
west of Pristina. It said one had had his throat slit.
	   According to the ethnic Albanians' account, Serb police burst
into Poklek houses, pulled out villagers and told them to, ``Go to
Albania and never return.''
	   Afterward, Serb police allegedly set 26 homes ablaze.
	   Serbia is the dominant of two republics remaining in the
Yugoslav federation.
</TEXT>
