<SLUG> BC-Dutch Antilles-Government,0295 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New Dutch Antilles government sworn in 
</HEADLINE>
By NORMAN SERPHOS
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   WILLEMSTAD, Curacao (AP) _ After a five-month political
deadlock, a prime minister was sworn in Monday to head a new
government in the Netherlands Antilles.
	   Suzy Camelia-Romer, 38, is the youngest-ever prime minister of
the territory's five Caribbean islands: St. Maarten, St. Eustatius,
Saba, Bonaire and Curacao. Together, the islands are an autonomous
member of the Kingdom of the Netherlands.
	   Six political parties united to form the new government after
Jan. 30 elections failed to produce a clear winner.
	   The center-right Antillean Restructuring Party won four of 22
parliamentary seats in the elections, more than any other party but
not enough to govern. It was left out of the new coalition.
	   Camelia-Romer, a former justice minister, pledged to erase a
dlrs 70 million budget deficit and increase spending for the Dutch
Antilles Coast Guard, which is charged with stopping drug smugglers
from South America.
	   She and six Cabinet members were sworn in Monday by Gov. Jaime
Saleh in Willemstad.
	   The coalition government includes the Curacao-based Popular
Crusade Labor Party, which won three seats, the National Party of
the People, with two seats, and the May 30 Workers Liberation
Party, also with two seats.
	   It also includes the St. Maarten Democratic Party, with two
seats, the Bonaire Democratic Party with one seat and the Windward
Islands People's Movement from Saba with one seat.
	   Popular Crusade Labor Party leader Errol Cova was named
president of parliament, charged with control over movement of
legislation.
</TEXT>
