<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Ireland </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
British Prime Minister Blair invited to speak to Irish Parliament 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) _ British Prime Minister Tony Blair has
been invited to address the Irish Houses of Parliament, the first
British leader since Ireland won independence in 1921 to receive
such an invitation.
	   Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern confirmed the invitation
Monday evening when he met with Blair in the Irish capital to
discuss the Northern Ireland peace process and European Union
business ahead of an EU conference in Cardiff, south Wales, later
this month.
	   Blair said he would be ``honored and privileged'' to speak to
the parliament.
	   ``I believe a new era in UK-Irish relations is opening up,''
Blair said.
	   Previous world leaders to have spoken to lawmakers from the Dail
and Senate have included U.S. presidents John Kennedy, Ronald
Reagan and Bill Clinton, French President Francois Mitterrand and
Germany's Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
	   Blair is likely to make his historic address to the Dail and
Senate houses of the parliament in the autumn.
	   (rs/er) 	   
</TEXT>
