<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Greenhouse Gases </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Australia to become worst greenhouse gas emitter 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ Australia will be the world's worst
per capita greenhouse gases polluter within 12 years, a report
released Monday found.
	   Australia was one of only three developed countries which won
approval at the international conference on global warming in
Kyoto, Japan, last December to increase greenhouse gas emissions by
2010.
	   The outcome was hailed by the federal government as a major
victory for Australian industry, but an analysis of the Kyoto
agreement by the liberal think-tank the Australia Institute said
the victory may be at huge environmental cost.
	   The institute's report says Australia's per capita emissions
from energy consumption and industrial uses will rise from 21
(metric) tons per head to 26 tons in 2010, making Australia easily
the world's biggest greenhouse gas polluter.
	   Institute Executive Director Clive Hamilton said Australia had
tricked the rest of the world into giving it special treatment and
had seriously jeopardized attempts to involve developing nations in
future climate change agreements.
	   ``If they had been aware of the facts, other nations would not
have agreed to Australia's demand for an increase in emissions but
would have required us to cut our emissions by more than other
countries,'' Hamilton said. 	   
</TEXT>
