<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0780 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 0000. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and move
on this circuit in expanded form:
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Blue-chip stocks edged higher Monday, but
technology shares took another drubbing as the delay of the new
Intel chip compounded worries about the impact of a weak Asian
economy on computer industry profits. The Dow Jones industrial
average rose 22.42 points _ or 0.25 percent _ to 8,922.37 after
retreating from an 81-point advance to within 20 points of 9,000.
Broader indexes fell, with the technology-laden Nasdaq composite
plunging nearly 2 percent as the recent exodus from big
computer-related names picked up steam. (US-CLOSING STOCKS)
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ American Home Products Corp., a leading drug and
health care products concern, is buying biotechnology giant
Monsanto Co. for stock valued at about dlrs 33 billion. The deal
announced Monday would create a life sciences behemoth with dlrs 23
billion in annual sales, more financial muscle for research and
marketing and ambitions for getting products out faster in a
fiercely competitive market. American Home Products makes the pain
reliever Advil, Chap Stick lip balm and Robitussin cough syrup as
well as a range of prescription drugs and medical devices. Monsanto
makes ingredients for agricultural products, pharmaceuticals and
foods including the Lasso and Roundup herbicides and the Nutrasweet
sugar substitute. (US-MONSANTO-AMERICAN HOME)
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian stocks plunged more than 10 percent Monday
in a frenzy of selling by Russian banks and a cold shoulder from
foreign investors wary of the market's turmoil. The Russian Trading
System index closed 10.2 percent lower after late panic selling
gripped the market and reassuring comments from government
officials failed to calm jittery investors. Monday's close matched
the 10-percent fall last Wednesday, when hectic selling caused the
stock market to plummet and threatened a run on the national
currency, the ruble. The market has fallen 44 percent since the
beginning of May, making it the worst performing market in the
world, and there are fears of further losses before calm is
restored. (RUSSIA-ECONOMY)
	   PARIS (AP) _ In normal times, an Air France strike would merely
cause havoc. But the walkout by the carrier's pilots Monday was
worse: a deep embarrassment for a country preparing to host in just
nine days the world's biggest sporting event, the World Cup.
Despite pressure from leftist government ministers, most of the
state-run carrier's 3,200 pilots stayed out of their cockpits to
protest 500 million francs (dlrs 83 million) in annual pay cuts.
They are threatening to stay out for two weeks or more. That's well
into the World Cup, which begins June 10 and lasts a month. On just
the first day Monday, 100,000 passengers were sent scrambling. And
it could be only the beginning: French train workers were planning
to strike at the end of the week. (AIR FRANCE-STRIKE)
	   KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) _ The Karachi Stock Market hit a record
low on Monday falling 128.76 points to close at 911.44. ``There was
massive liquidation by foreign investors and this put immense
pressure on the market,'' said Hasan Davar, a trader with UBS
Securities. The Karachi Stock Exchange opened Monday for the first
time since Pakistan exploded five nuclear devices last Thursday and
a sixth one on Saturday, bringing global condemnation and threats
of economic sanctions. Within hours of the first five explosions,
Pakistan's president declared a state of emergency and froze all
foreign currency accounts to try to prevent a panic exodus of
foreign capital from the country. Pakistan's foreign reserves stand
at dlrs 1.2 billion, which is barely enough to pay for the next six
weeks of imports, say financial analysts. (PAKISTAN-STOCK MARKET)
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israel on Monday decided to retain ownership of
51 percent of the national air carrier El Al, despite
recommendations the unprofitable company be sold off. A statement
from the ministerial committee overseeing Israel's privatization
plans quoted Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu as saying the
decision ``will protect our national interests.'' Israel radio said
national security and emergency situations were key factors in the
decision to retain a majority share of the airline. The decision
ensures that El Al flights will continue to be grounded during the
Jewish Sabbath _ from Friday sundown to Saturday sundown. The
Sabbath groundings have been cited as a factor in the company's
losses. (ISRAEL-EL AL)
</TEXT>
