<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0612 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>

</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Thousands of refugees from Serbia's
Kosovo province streamed into neighboring Albania on Monday to
escape some of the deadliest fighting in months. Dozens of people
were reported killed. Albania appealed to the United States and
European Union to intervene. Reports from Serb and Albanian sources
often were contradictory and could not be independently verified.
But with 39 people reported killed over the weekend, and fighting
apparently continuing, the bloodshed appeared the worst since
March, when Serbian police killed more than 80 people in a
crackdown on militants among the ethnic Albanian majority in
Serb-ruled Kosovo. The latest fighting forced about 2,000 Kosovo
Albanians _ mostly women, children and the elderly _ across the
border into Albania's Tropoja region on Sunday and Monday, Albania
said. (YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO)
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ Iran will not build an atomic bomb despite
nuclear tests by Pakistan and India that have forced ``a new
security situation'' on the nearby Asian subcontinent, the defense
minister said in comments published Monday. India tested five
nuclear devices last month, which were followed by six explosions
by neighbor and rival Pakistan. Iran denies repeated U.S. and
Israeli allegations that it is close to building an atom bomb,
saying its nuclear program is peaceful. (IRAN-NUCLEAR)
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Facing increased pressure to clean up
past misdeeds, Indonesia's new government announced a broad-based
inquiry Monday into corruption under ex-President Suharto. However,
it stopped short of meeting demands by student protesters and
others who want the wealth of Suharto and his super-rich family
specifically targeted. Critics say the Suhartos blatantly used
their power and position to amass billions of dollars by dominating
the now ailing economy. Thousands of students staged peaceful
protests in several cities Monday calling for an end to both local
and national graft. (INDONESIA)
	   FAISABAD, Afghanistan (AP) _ Some hobbled on makeshift crutches,
a few carried stretchers and others broke into a run as helicopters
carrying emergency aid landed Monday in remote northern
Afghanistan, devastated by an earthquake that killed more than
3,000 people. On a small distant hillock, a woman cuddled her
infant, a toddler sat nearby wailing. Crouched behind, her head
buried in a bright orange shawl, a woman sobbed. The quake, which
hit Saturday with a preliminary magnitude of 6.9, flattened entire
villages, sliced mountains and triggered landslides. The estimates
of the dead vary from 3,000 to 5,000 people. Thousands more were
homeless and missing. Aftershocks lingered in the region Monday,
sending frightened residents scrambling outdoors.
(AFGHANISTAN-QUAKE)
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah arrived Monday
in Jordan for talks aimed at resolving differences between key Arab
leaders on a proposed summit on the Middle East peace process.
Abdullah came from Damascus where he met at least twice with Syrian
President Hafez Assad to persuade him to accept an open agenda at
the proposed summit, Arab diplomats said. Such a demand also has
been made by Jordan and some Gulf nations. But all agree that the
summit should forge a unified Arab position against Israel. Talaat
Hamid, spokesman for the 22-member Arab League, said in Cairo that
consultations were under way between Arab leaders over the time and
place for the summit. (ARABS-SUMMIT)
</TEXT>
