<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-People and Places,0840 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
People and places in the news meteorite sale, Geri Halliwell and Paul Gascoigne, and a noisy sign. Some items may also have moved as separates. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: Contains items on Hitler and potato chips, Jerry Seinfeld,
<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ An advertising agency apologized for
using Adolf Hitler's image to sell potato chips in Thailand, and
was talking with the chip-maker Monday over whether to pull the
ads.
	   The TV commercial for ``X'' potato chips shows Hitler giving a
Nazi salute and a shot of a swastika transformed into the ``X''
product logo.
	   Posters for the chips suggest that eating the snacks would
transform even Hitler himself into a fun-loving, likable character.
	   ``The commercial ... is designed to communicate that the world
would be a better place if happiness ruled. It was never intended
to offend and the agency apologizes to anyone who finds it
insensitive,'' the international ad agency, Leo Burnett Bangkok,
said in a statement Sunday, after Israeli diplomats complained.
	   Talks were under way Monday between the agency and the Thai
client, Food Processing Co.
	   ___
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ The array of snacks Jerry Seinfeld
reportedly requires backstage is idiosyncratic enough to inspire an
episode of the popular U.S. television show ``Seinfeld.''
	   The superstar comedian is scheduled to do eight live shows in
Australia this month, but only if he gets certain foods, according
to The Daily Telegraph.
	   The paper quotes an unnamed promoter as saying Seinfeld's
``essential backstage items'' include: 18 small bottles of water on
ice (any brand except Evian is fine), one bag of Rold Gold
pretzels, one vegetable tray for four people, one small jar of
mayonnaise, and a small amount of pasta salad _ hold the
mayonnaise.
	   ``By superstar standards, it's not that demanding a list,'' the
promoter told the Telegraph.
	   ___
	   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) _ Mark Lenney now owns a little piece of
Mars.
	   The engineer from Santa Clara, California, shelled out dlrs 700
for a Mars rock at an auction on Sunday that included dinosaur
bones, rare gems, minerals and several meteorites.
	   ``It was reasonably priced,'' said Lenney, who added that the
mystery of the universe propelled him to his first auction ``to be
in touch with the wonder of it all.''
	   Lenney also picked up a dlrs 450 slice of meteorite created at
the dawn of our solar system and a dlrs 325 rock from a 1969 meteor
shower that contains dozens of amino acids, the building blocks of
proteins.
	   The biggest seller at the auction was a 995-pound (450-kilo)
boulder that was part of a vast meteorite shower that fell on the
edge of the Kalahari Desert thousands of years ago. It sold for a
whopping dlrs 101,500.
	   Not to be outdone by more experienced collectors, 9-year-old
Caleb Kauffman of San Francisco won the bidding for a sample of
Sikholite-Alin meteorite, an iron specimen that fell on Siberia in
1947.
	   ___
	   LONDON (AP) _ It was all over the tabloids Monday, and the
quality papers, too. Questions were asked in the House of Commons:
Geri Spice is out. So's Gazza.
	   Geri Halliwell, 25, was the eldest member of the Spice Girls,
the inventor of ``girl power,'' the gorgeous pouting idol of
millions of pre-adolescent girls. She quit after a series of fights
with the other four members of the group _ and after earning a
reported dlrs 20 million in two years.
	   Paul Gascoigne, 31, was a sometimes brilliant soccer player who
won the nation's heart with his tears when he was ejected from the
1990 World Cup. But the nation often had to think again: Gazza
drunk, Gazza posing at a urinal on his wedding day, Gazza's wife
walking out of the marriage with a bruised face.
	   England manager Glen Hoddle dropped Gascoigne from the World Cup
squad because of his poor physicial condition.
	   In the House of Commons, Labor lawmaker Gareth Thomas urged the
government to encourage Geri ``to think again.''
	   Conservative lawmaker Anne McIntosh managed to work Gascoigne
sad situation into a discussion of the ``social exclusion'' of
Britain's down and out.
	   ``I wonder if you would like to comment on the impact on the
England football team of excluding Gazza from the squad?'' she
said, drawing laughter from her colleagues.
	   ___
	   WEST HAVEN, Connecticut (AP) _ The mayor has pulled the plug on
a flashing sign that warned people to keep quiet at the beach. It
was too loud.
	   The sign was turned on for the first time Friday, then
disconnected a few hours later because the generator used to power
it made enough noise to defeat the sign's purpose, said Mayor H.
Richard Borer Jr.
	   ``It wasn't that loud, but it was a generator,'' Borer said
Sunday. ``It makes noise.''
	   The sign stands about 10 feet (3 meters) off the ground flashes
a warning advising motorists driving into the city that the
beachfront road is a quiet zone.
	   Town workers may connect the sign to a nearby electrical outlet
for a quieter power source, the mayor said.
</TEXT>
