<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-06 20:32:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1739  wstm-
r i     BC-Britain-ProsecutionAg     06-01 0346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Prosecution Agency </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Britain's state prosecution agency faces major shake-up, government says 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ The government has said it will back proposals for
a shake-up of Britain's public prosecution organization _ which
would include the introduction of American-style district attorneys
_ in an effort to stop so many serious cases being dropped before
they get to court.
	   A damming report on the 12-year-old Crown Prosecution Service
issued Monday said it was too bureaucratic and centralized to do
its job, with lawyers spending too much time on paperwork and not
enough fighting cases.
	   ``Our assessment of the CPS is that it has the potential to
become a lively, successful and esteemed part of the criminal
justice system, but that, sadly, none of these adjectives applied
to the service as a whole at present,'' the report, written by
former judge Sir Iain Glidewell, said.
	   Glidewell said that prosecutors failed to pursue one in eight
cases, and that about a quarter of people charged with more serious
offenses had their prosecutions dropped.
	   In contrast, only 1 in 100 motoring offenses was dropped by the
CPS, the report said.
	   The service's critics, including police officers, say that has
happened because the service's lawyers prefer to pursue easy-to-win
cases and engage in plea-bargaining in more serious cases to avoid
the expense of going to court.
	   The report made 75 recommendations, including the establishing
of 42 new Chief Crown Prosecutors, one for each police force area
in England and Wales, which British newspapers reported Tuesday
would be modeled on the U.S. system of district attorneys. Scotland
has its own state prosecuting service.
	   ``The Government accepts the thrust of the report's proposals
for reordering CPS priorities to focus more on the core business of
prosecuting, greater separation of management from legal work,
greater autonomy for the areas, and better prospects for the
staff,'' Attorney General John Morris told the House of Commons on
Monday.
	   (rs/er)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Britain-Prosecution Agency; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
