w1742  wstm-
r i     BC-LatinAmericanBriefs     06-01 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs,0802 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Brazil, Mexico. 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: Contains items from Puerto Rico, Dominican Republic, Panama,
<TEXT>
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ A Puerto Rican separatist group
responsible for bombings in the 1970s and 1980s on Monday promised
to fight to prevent the sale of the public telephone utility to GTE
Corp. and other investors.
	   ``The sale of the Puerto Rico Telephone Company is nothing more
than a declaration of war,'' the People's Boricua Army said in a
letter sent to the Associated Press. ``Now they will know what war
is.'
	   Gov. Pedro Rossello announced a dlrs 1.9 billion deal last week
to sell part of the telephone company to investors and give GTE
control over management. The sale must be approved by the Puerto
Rican legislature.
	   The guerrilla group is also known as the Macheteros, or
``cane-cutters.'' Founded in 1978, it claimed responsibility for
several bombings and other attacks on U.S. government installations
through the early 1980s.
	   ___
	   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) _ A bomb exploded outside
the headquarters of the Dominican Republic's main anti-drug agency
early Monday, leaving a bucket-sized crater in the pavement but
causing no injuries.
	   Explosives experts took samples from the site Monday morning in
Santo Domingo, but nobody was immediately arrested.
	   The blast came days after a visit to Santo Domingo by Barry
McCaffrey, U.S. drug policy adviser to President Bill Clinton. The
explosion also followed cocaine seizures totaling 1,980 pounds (900
kilos). The cocaine was believed to have come from the Cali Cartel
in Colombia.
	   ___
	   PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) _ A major drug trafficking suspect who
was the focus of a political scandal in Panama has been extradited
to Florida, officials said Monday.
	   In a radio interview, Interior Minister Raul Montenegro said
Castrillon Henao, a Colombian, was flown to Florida on Sunday,
where he was also wanted on money laundering charges.
	   Local newspapers reported that Jose Castrillon Henao had
contributed to the 1994 campaign of President Ernesto Perez
Balladares. The president denied knowledge and vowed to tighten
rules on campaign financing and against money laundering.
	   Police arrested Castrillon Henao in April 1996, accusing him of
being head of the Cali drug cartel's operations in Panama.
	   ___
	   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) _ Brazilian drug stores saw brisk
sales of Viagra on Monday, the first day the anti-impotency drug
was legally sold in the country.
	   Pharmacies that had not yet received the drug reported waiting
lists with as many of 40 names. Several others had opened telephone
hot lines for home delivery of the drug.
	   By early afternoon, Gilberto Silvany, a Rio pharmacist, reported
his store had already sold out 80 percent of its stock.
	   ``I think we'd probably sell more but a lot of people are too
embarrassed to ask for a drug that affects them down there,''
Silvany said.
	   Although Monday marks the first day that Viagra was sold legally
in Brazil, it has been available for some time on the black market
for as much dlrs 22 a pill. In the drug stores, the drug sells for
about dlrs 48 for a box of four pills.
	   ___
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Mexicans continue to hold a generally
favorable image of President Ernesto Zedillo, despite skepticism
about the success of key policies, according to a poll published
Monday by the daily Reforma.
	   Asked the rate the president on a scale of one to 10, those
polled gave Zedillo an average rating of 6.4, down from 6.5 in
March and 6.7 in December, but higher than the ratings in his first
two years after taking office in December 1994.
	   The poll found that 54 percent approved of Zedillo's
performance, down from 59 percent in September 1997, while 39
percent disapproved, up from 32 percent in September.
	   However those polled overwhelmingly said the government had
achieved little success in halting corruption, solving the
rebellion in Chiapas, improving the economy, attacking pollution or
fighting drug trafficking.
	   Reforma said its polling unit surveyed 1,190 adults across
Mexico in late May. It gave a margin of error of plus or minus 3
percent.
	   ___
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Bandits blocked the road from Acapulco to
Zihuatanejo and robbed passengers aboard a luxury tourist bus of
more than dlrs 2,200, newspapers reported Monday.
	   The daily Reforma reported that one of the passengers, Isolina
Sanchez, was shot in the thigh during the incident and was being
treated at a hospital.
	   Federal Highway Police told Reforma that the incident occurred
at 3:30 a.m. Saturday on the outskirts of Acapulco.
	   Six heavily armed men blocked the highway and forced the driver
to leave the road. Passengers were then robbed of their belongings.
</TEXT>
