<SLUG> BC-Japan-Explosion </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Explosion destroys three buses near Tokyo airport, no injuries 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A pre-dawn explosion Tuesday at a bus depot just
outside Tokyo destroyed three buses, two of which were used for
shuttling passengers to Tokyo's main international airport, a
police spokesman said.
	   Atsushi Henmi of the Chiba Prefectural, or State, Police, said
the explosion occurred in the bus depot at the Matsudo office of
Keisei Electric Railway's motor vehicle department at around 3:30
a.m. (1830 GMT Monday).
	   The explosion set two limousine buses and one regular passenger
bus in the depot on fire, destroying them, Henmi said. There were
five bus company employees on night at the time of the explosion,
but none was hurt, Henmi said.
	   Police suspect anti-airport radicals may have been involved in
the explosion as fragments of lead cables and batteries were found
near the explosion site.
	   The airport at Narita, 65 kilometers (40 miles), east of Tokyo,
opened in 1978 with a single runway.
	   Left-wing activists, opposed to the expansion of the airport,
claim that the government has planned to use the airport for
military purposes.
	   In April, a pre-dawn explosion damaged the home of an official
at the airport, while in February the ultra-leftist Revolutionary
Workers Association claimed responsibility for three homemade
rockets fired into a cargo plane area at Narita airport.
	   One airport worker was injured in that attack, which came as
athletes and other officials were arriving at the airport for the
Winter Olympic Games in Nagano.
  (km)
</TEXT>
