<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-French Open,0771 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Can Venus and Hingis be the next Chris and Martina? 
</HEADLINE>
By JOCELYN NOVECK
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Could there be, finally, a rivalry to match Evert
vs. Navratilova? Surely that's what the tennis world hopes.
	   Not so fast, says Martina Hingis. She isn't ready to call Venus
Williams a true rival yet.
	   ``Everybody else is trying to make rivalries against me,'' she
says. ``Venus, she won Key Biscayne, but that's not a Grand Slam.''
	   ``I'm No. 1, I've won four Grand Slams. I have the
self-confidence.''
	   True. But Williams is playing so well at this year's French Open
that their match Tuesday is the most anticipated of the tournament.
	   Hingis and Williams will meet in the quarterfinals, but many see
it as worthy of the final.
	   Williams, seeded eighth at Roland Garros in just her fourth
event on clay, responded diplomatically to Hingis' comments.
	   ``I think that she's playing good tennis, and she has every
right to say what she wants to,'' Williams said.
	   Hingis holds a 5-2 record against Williams, including a 6-0, 6-4
win in the final of the U.S. Open last summer in their only
previous Grand Slam meeting.
	   They are 2-2 this year. But Hingis won their only career
encounter on clay, the final of the Italian Open in May.
	   ``It was a good victory for me there,'' Hingis said. ``I hope
she will remember that, too.''
	   Statistically speaking, the two have had an almost identical run
through the early rounds here. Hingis has lost just 14 games while
averaging 56 minutes per victory. Williams has lost 13 games and
averaged 58 minutes per match.
	   But stylistically speaking, they are totally different.
	   Hingis has a masterful touch, moving opponents around the court
with precise groundstrokes. Williams is pure power.
	   Power is what Marat Safin has, in spades. The 18-year-old
qualifier stormed his way through the first three rounds, but lost
in the fourth Monday, in five tough sets.
	   The French fans chanted wildly for his opponent, Frenchman
Cedric Pioline. ``Allez Cedric!'' they yelled.
	   But as the match wore on, there were growing chants of ``Ma-RAT!
Ma-RAT!''
	   It was in tribute to the remarkable run by the young Russian
playing his first Grand Slam event. He began the tournament ranked
116th, but won't be there much longer.
	   ``I think I can beat good players now,'' he said after Pioline
ended his run, 7-5, 4-6, 6-7 (5-7), 6-4, 6-4.
	   Safin's tournament started with three qualifying matches just to
get into the main draw.
	   Next up was Andre Agassi. With the American star hot on a
comeback, Safin wasn't given a chance. But he thwarted the
comeback, and then ousted defending champion Gustavo Kuerten,
ranked eighth in the world, in another five-setter.
	   In the third round, Safin, by now the story of the tournament,
had a slightly easier time _ a four-setter over Daniel Vacek of the
Czech Republic.
	   That set up the match with Pioline. The 28-year-old Frenchman is
erratic, but brilliant on occasion. He's reached the finals of
Wimbledon and the U.S. Open, both times losing to Pete Sampras.
	   Pioline has a reputation for choking at the end of matches. He's
reached 12 finals but has only two singles titles.
	   Safin knew nothing of that.
	   ``Nobody told me,'' he said.
	   It didn't matter. This time, Safin unraveled. Pioline broke
serve three times, including once in the fifth set. That was
enough.
	   Safin said he wasn't thrown by the 16,000 or so fans at Roland
Garros shouting for Pioline.
	   However, the presence of soccer star Ronaldo in the VIP box was
another matter. Asked if he'd been distracted by the Brazilian, in
town for the World Cup, Safin thought for a moment, then announced:
``Yes.''
	   ``I'd never seen Ronaldo so close up before,'' he explained.
	   Then again, maybe it was the presence next to Ronaldo of Anna
Kournikova, the blonde Russian teenager who also lost Monday.
	   ``She's so beautiful, unbelievable,'' Safin said.
	   Whatever the reason, Safin said he'd learned a lesson on center
court.
	   ``You have to be a little bit clever on the important points,''
he said. ``You can't lose your serve when you are 5-3 up.''
	   Olga Morozova, the former Russian champion, played with Safin's
mother, Rauza. She said Safin was the new great hope for Russian
tennis.
	   ``It's really quite unbelievable, what he did here,'' she said.
	   Safin himself was more down to earth. What makes him happy is
that he broke into the top 100 this week.
</TEXT>
