<SLUG> BC-UN-Kosovo,0532 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rugova calls for greater UN role, independence for Kosovo 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: RECAPS previous
By ROBERT H. REID
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ With violence escalating in Kosovo, the
head of the self-declared government of the Kosovo Albanians is
calling for an international civilian administration for the
Serb-ruled province as a first step toward independence.
	   ``The independence of Kosovo is the best solution,'' Ibrahim
Rugova told reporters Monday after meeting Secretary-General Kofi
Annan. He said he asked Annan for ``more support for Kosovo'' and
unspecified ``preventive measures'' to prevent further
deterioration and ``massacres and massive ethnic cleansing.''
	   Rugova said independence for Kosovo, which has a 90 percent
majority Albanian population, would help stabilize ``even Serbia,
although at this stage they think in a different way.''
	   Serbia rejects independence and considers Kosovo the cradle of
Serb culture. The United States and other major countries also
oppose independence but have called for self-rule for the Kosovo
Albanians within Serbian borders.
	   But Rugova said an independent Kosovo could guarantee the safety
of Serbs living within its borders. Pending independence, he
suggested creation of ``some kind of international civilian
administration, or a protectorate, as an interim measure.''
	   He also called for an end to Serb military and police operations
against Albanian separatists who have been fighting for
independence for the Albanian-majority region, which is now a
province of Serbia. Serbia, together with Montenegro, forms
Yugoslavia.
	   Rugova arrived in New York after a visit to Washington in which
he conferred with President Bill Clinton and U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright.
	   His visit coincided with a sharp escalation of violence in the
troubled province. Thousands of refugees streamed Monday into
neighboring Albania to escape some of the deadliest fighting in
months. Dozens of people were reported killed.
	   Albania appealed to the United States and European Union to
intervene in what it said was a ``massacre'' in Kosovo. ``This is
just the start of a war with tragic dimensions,'' the Albanian
government said in a statement.
	   The bloodshed appeared the worst since March, when Serb police
killed more than 80 people in a crackdown on militants among the
ethnic Albanian majority.
	   On Monday, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said 1,300 people arrived
Sunday at the Albanian border town of Tropoja, the largest number
in a single day. Eckhard said an undetermined number of others were
believed trapped by the fighting and unable to cross the border.
	   During the press conference, Rugova applauded U.S. mediation to
promote a dialogue between the Kosovo Albanians and President
Slobodan Milosevic. Milosevic revoked Kosovo's autonomy in 1989.
	   ``In order for the negotiations to be successful, it is critical
that police and military operations stop,'' Rugova said. ``Serb
police and military actions have been continuing, resulting in many
people killed.''
</TEXT>
