u f     BC-Japan-Markets     06-01 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar higher, stocks bounce back moderately in Tokyo 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar was higher in early trading Tuesday
from its levels late in Tokyo on Monday, though off record highs
reached overnight in New York. Tokyo stock prices rose moderately.
	   The dollar bought 139.42 yen in early trading, up 0.30 yen from
late Monday in Tokyo. In New York overnight, the dollar settled at
139.70 yen, its highest closing level since June 24, 1991, when it
reached 139.82 yen.
	   Traders said the dollar's retreat from its New York level came
on profit-taking after a Japanese newspaper said Tuesday that
officials from the major industrialized nations may meet as early
as this week to discuss the weakness of the yen.
	   The Yomiuri newspaper, quoting unnamed international sources,
said the deputies of the Group of Seven major nations may hold a
meeting to stem the yen's slide.
	   Japan's Finance Minister Hikaru Matsunaga, meanwhile, expressed
renewed concern about the current level of the yen against the
dollar.
	   ``In any case, I have strong concern about an excessively weak
yen, and we will take appropriate and decisive action against it,''
Matsunaga said at a regular news conference.
	   On the stock market, sentiment improved slightly after Monday's
announcement that Nikko Securities Co., a major Japanese brokerage,
and Travelers Group of the United States were planning an equity
tie-up.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 125.82
points, or 0.82 percent, to 15,446.85 in the first 30 minutes of
trading. On Monday, the index had lost 349.75 points, or 2.23
percent.
	   ``The market welcomed Nikko's alliance, as it will likely
trigger more Japanese financial institutions' tie-ups with foreign
institutions,'' said Masaru Arai, general manager of the stock
division at Ryoko Securities.
	   Deepening worries over the state of Japan's economy had
triggered Monday's fall.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 6.27 points, or 0.52 percent, to 1,202.97. The
TOPIX fell 24.79 points, or 2.03 percent on Monday.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond rose to 1.165 percent from Monday's record low
finish of 1.155 percent, driving its price down to 112.33 yen from
112.41 yen.
  (kgo-km-dj)
</TEXT>
