w1760  wstm-
r i     BC-AirFrance-Strike     06-01 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Air France-Strike,0656 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Talks set Tuesday, but can pilots be enticed to return to skies? 
</HEADLINE>
EDS: RECAPS previous
AP Photos PAR101,105,108.
By ELAINE GANLEY
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Air France, the official World Cup carrier, moved
into its second day of a strike Tuesday, setting talks to find
common ground with angry pilots and save face ahead of the soccer
championships next week.
	   The strike caused chaos for almost 100,000 passengers on its
first day Monday, worries for fans and teams attending the
month-long World Cup starting June 10 and embarrassment for all.
	   The state-run carrier's main pilots' union called the 15-day
action to protest against 500 million francs (dlrs 83 million) in
annual pay cuts. Most of the 3,200 Air France pilots did not work
Monday.
	   Departure screens at airports around the nation flashed the bad
news: ``annule'' and ``canceled'' next to list upon list of
flights. Air France planes, many decorated with giant paintings of
soccer players representing the 32 competing teams, sat idle.
	   Air France predicted a slight improvement in traffic Tuesday
with 15 percent of long-haul flights taking off, compared to 10
percent Monday, and up to 35 percent of short- and medium-haul
flights scheduled.
	   ``I think that all the French without exception, and naturally
the pilots ... hope the (World Cup) will be a great fete, a great
fete for world soccer and a great fete for France,'' said the
airline's president, Jean-Cyril Spinetta, in a television interview
Monday night.
	   ``And I don't see who would take responsibility to wreck this
great fete by a strike which can't be understood.''
	   Air France is committed to transporting teams to the 10
competition sites around France, and the company has said if the
strike continues it will probably use outside carriers to enable it
to meet its obligations.
	   Spinetta appeared to be counting in part on World Cup ardor to
convince pilots to return to the cockpit in talks set for 3:30 p.m
(1330 GMT) Tuesday -- the first since failed 11th hour talks last
Thursday.
	   But he gave no hint that Air France, which almost went bankrupt
in 1993, was ready to withdraw its controversial plan to cut
pilots' salaries in exchange for shares in Air France.
	   Pilots also want Air France to do away with salary cuts for
starting pilots, a system in force for the past year.
	   Nicolas Minvelle, waiting at Charles de Gaulle Airport for a
flight to Senegal, said it wasn't fair the pilots were striking
just before the World Cup.
	   ``They use an international event to bother everyone. It's too
bad,'' he said.
	   The airports in Lyon and Marseille, France's second and
third-largest cities, were virtually deserted. Rental car agencies
did brisk business.
	   The U.S. Soccer Federation, heading to France on Thursday, said
it is sending the U.S. team on an American Airlines flight to Paris
that connects to an Air France flight to Lyon. As a backup, the
Americans have rented buses for all their travel plans in France.
	   ``After the draw, everyone was scared,'' federation president
Alan Rothenberg said Monday. ``We've gone out and spent to set up
our own system ... to take care of ourselves.''
	   Passengers ``are being taken hostage,'' the French passenger
association ADUA said in a statement. It called the walkout by the
pilots, among the highest-paid in the world, ``a strike by the
privileged of the skies.''
	   Air France pilots earn around 60,000 francs (dlrs10,000) per
month, 20 to 30 percent more than pilots from other European
countries.
	   The walkout would be Air France's longest in 27 years if it
lasts the projected two weeks.
	   Christian Paris, spokesman for the main union, the SNPL,
admitted Monday the strike's consequences were ``disastrous.''
	   ``But when you're confronted by an attack you have no choice but
to defend yourself,'' he told French television.
</TEXT>
