<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Queensland Election </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Poll: Hanson splits conservatives, Labor Party to take Queensland 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BRISBANE, Australia (AP) _ A new poll released Tuesday predicted
Pauline Hanson's One Nation Party will split the conservative vote
in Queensland's June 13 election, lifting the opposition Labor
Party to power.
	   If Labor ousts conservative Premier Rob Borbidge's government,
it will be a bad omen for the nationwide chances of Prime Minister
John Howard and his conservatives in the federal election expected
later this year.
	   Whether or not Hanson's party, famous for its anti-gun control,
anti-Asian immigration, and anti-Aboriginal welfare policies wins
any seats itself, it would have made a major impact on Australia's
political landscape.
	   In an effort to win back potential One Nation voters, Borbidge
has been talking tough on crime, unveiling new legislation to make
sure violent criminals serve their entire sentence with new parole.
	   Labor and Borbidge's conservatives currently hold 44 seats each
in the state's 89-seat Parliament; Borbidge has governed only
because a single conservative independent member of Parliament has
voted with his side.
	   The Newspoll survey in The Australian newspaper shows support
for the governing conservative coalition in big-city Brisbane seats
dropped from 42 percent to 25 percent while Labor had soared from
49 to 54 percent.
	   The Newspoll showed support for Pauline Hanson's One Nation
Party had tripled to 15 percent in the past six months statewide,
and almost doubled to 7 percent nationally in the past two weeks.
	   In Queensland rural areas, support for the governing
conservatives had slumped from 54 percent to 41 percent.
	   Borbidge told Australian Broadcasting Corp. radio Tuesday that
it looked like his party was ``behind the eight ball.''
	   The poll was conducted last weekend by telephone to 1,007
Queensland households. Newspoll said the margin of error on various
questions ranged from 3 to 4.4 percent, depending on the number of
respondents.
	   The poll suggests the Labor Party under Peter Beattie would gain
enough seats to hold a comfortable majority even if One Nation
Party wins several seats on its own, thus denying Hanson the
balance of power. 	   
</TEXT>
