w1767  wstm-
r i     BC-Arabs-NuclearTests     06-01 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Arabs-Nuclear Tests,0669 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Arabs concerned about nuclear tests but blame the West With Pakistan-India, US-Pakistan-India 
</HEADLINE>
By VIJAY JOSHI
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Much of the Arab world greeted with concern
nuclear tests by India and Pakistan but blamed the arms race on the
West for turning a blind eye to Israel's secretive nuclear arsenal.
	   Echoing the worldwide condemnation of the tests last month by
the two South Asian enemies, several Arab nations urged them to
show restraint from now on and start a dialogue to end their
conflicts.
	   The Muslim world's main group, the Organization of the Islamic
Conference, issued a statement Monday expressing ``deep concern
over this serious development.''
	   India's five tests May 11-13 escalated the long-standing
Indo-Pakistan rivalry to the nuclear level. Pakistan reponded with
what it said were six detonations of its own; five on Friday and
one on Saturday.
	   Pakistan and India have fought three wars since they were carved
from the same British colony 50 years ago. They are divided by
religion _ Pakistan is officially Muslim and India is predominately
Hindu _ and a simmering territorial dispute over the Himalayan
region of Kashmir, which is divided between them and claimed by
both countries.
	   The world ``must seriously encourage'' India and Pakistan to
quickly sign a non-aggression treaty to prevent regional
instability, the OIC, a 55-nation group that includes Arab as well
as other countries such as Iran and Indonesia, said in a statement.
	   But the Arabs were quick to point out that Israel, located in
the center of a hostile Arab world, has most likely possessed
nuclear bombs for decades without facing any punishment from the
rest of the world.
	   Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi defended Pakistan's
tests, saying India left Pakistan no choice.
	   At a news conference during a visit to Pakistan on Monday,
Kharrazi also said Muslims in the Middle East long had worried
about Israel's nuclear capability and could now feel confident that
a fellow Islamic nation possessed similar abilities.
	   ``As a matter of its national security and to create a balance
in the region,'' Pakistan had to respond with its own nuclear
tests, he said.
	   The leader of a radical Palestinian guerrilla group also boasted
that the Muslims now have an Islamic bomb to counter Israel.
	   ``Pakistan's possession of nuclear power is to be considered an
asset to the Arab and Muslim nations,'' Sheik Ahmed Yassin, the
spiritual leader of Hamas movement, said.
	   But if other Arab nations felt any pride in that fact, they
didn't show it.
	   Kuwait, which has good relations with Pakistan and India, said
it expresses its ``extreme regret and worry about this arms race
... and its dangerous consequences on the security and stability of
the area.''
	   The Saudi Arabian government issued a statement Monday claiming
``double standards by the international community through excluding
Israel from nuclear inspections have encouraged the nuclear arms
race.
	   The United States imposed harsh sanctions on Libya, Iraq and
Iran _ and now on India and Pakistan _ for trying to acquire
weapons of mass destruction.
	   Similar statements were made earlier by the United Arab Emirates
and Lebanon.
	   Egypt, the Arab world's stalwart, criticized neither Pakistan
nor its traditional ally India. But Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
said their explosions have proved that an international treaty
banning nuclear tests ``has gone with the wind.''
	   Israel is believed to have 100 nuclear warheads. Successive
Israeli governments have refused to either confirm that or allow
the International Atomic Energy Agency, the U.N. nuclear watchdog,
to inspect its facilities.
	   Israel has warned that the Indian and Pakistani tests could
encourage Iran to follow suit.
	   But Kharrazi said his government has no intention of developing
a bomb and that its nuclear program is for peaceful purposes.
</TEXT>
