<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Briefs, 2 Takes,0853 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
dropping Gascoigne; Norway coach says Brazil vulnerable; Nigeria's goalkeeper problem; France's Armenian; Yugoslavia names final 22; German youth; Tunisia's 22; Germans hammer Colombia; Peruzzi on TV; Romania guns for semifinals 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: Includes items on Bierhoff challenging Ronaldo; Hoddle defends
<TEXT>
	   MILAN, Italy (AP) _ Oliver Bierhoff held off Brazilian star
Ronaldo in the race for the scoring champion in the just-concluded
Serie A season in Italy, and says he can do the same at the World
Cup.
	   ``I have always looked for a rival as a point of reference. Even
as a boy,'' the German told Gazzetta dello Sport on Monday. ``It
gave me the motivation to commit myself. Hopefully I can beat
Ronaldo again _ at the World Cup and in the league.''
	   Bierhoff tallied 27 goals for third-place Udinese this season,
while Ronaldo had 25 for runner-up Inter Milan. They'll be
neighbors next year, though, with Bierhoff having transferred to AC
Milan.
	   ___  
	   LA MANGA, Spain (AP) _ England coach Glenn Hoddle said Monday he
dropped controversial midfielder Paul Gascoigne from the final
22-man World Cup team solely because he wasn't fit.
	   On Sunday, Hoddle stunned England with his decision not to
include the 31-year-old Gascoigne, rated by some as the best
midfielder in English history.
	   The story was one of the biggest soccer items to hit England
since the team won its sole World Cup in 1966.
	   As well as Gascoigne, Hoddle also dropped five other players _
Tottenham goalkeeper Ian Walker, Manchester United's Phil Neville
and Nicky Butt, Coventry's Dion Dublin and Everton's Andy
Hinchcliffe _ to get down to the final 22-man team.
	   ___  
	   OSLO, Norway (AP) _ Brazil is favored to win its fifth World
Cup, but Norwegian Coach Egil ``Drillo'' Olsen said Monday there is
a chance the defending champions would not make it through Group A.
	   ``Brazil is not as good as the FIFA ranking suggests, and it is
not unthinkable that they will be beaten by two of the teams in
group A. But I don't think that will happen,'' Olsen said.
	   Brazil tops FIFA's ranking, Norway is seventh.
	   Brazil opens the World Cup against Scotland on June 10.
	   In May 1997, Olsen's team stunned the world beating Brazil 4-2
in Oslo.
	   ___  
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Nigeria, losers 3-0 on Friday to
Yugoslavia, may be looking for a new goalkeeper.
	   Radio talk shows and daily newspapers were filled Monday with
criticism of goalkeeper Abiodun Baruwa, who allowed in all three
goals in the Friday's loss.
	   Many fans called for the return of Peter Rufai, who plays for
Spanish side Deportivo La Cornua, to the No. 1 spot on Nigeria's
World Cup-bound squad.
	   Former national team captain Segun Odegbami said goalkeeping was
merely part of a larger problem _ growing team apathy.
	   ___  
	   PARIS (AP) _ French midfielder Youri Djorkaeff says France's
public recognition of the 1915 genocide of ethnic Armenians in
Turkey inspired his spectacular goal in a 2-2 draw against Morocco
last week.
	   Djorkaeff, whose mother is Armenian, said he came on as
substitute determined to score after hearing the news that
lawmakers had passed a motion recognizing as ``genocide'' the
deaths of 1.5 million Armenians.
	   ``It was a great day for me because France acknowledged the
genocide of Armenians,'' Djorkaeff said in an interview published
Monday with sports daily L'Equipe.
	   ``I thought of it as I went onto the pitch. I wanted to do
something special, and that's how goals like that are scored.''
	   ___  
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Yugoslav Coach Slobodan Santrac on
Monday dropped striker Anto Drobnjak and midfielder Albert Nadj
from Yugoslavia's 22-man World Cup squad.
	   Drobjak, of French champion's Lens, and Nadj, of Betis in Spain,
will not travel to France, where Yugoslavia faces the United
States, Germany and Iran in the preliminary rounds.
	   Nadj, angering Santrac, reportedly refused to start on defense
before Yugoslavia's friendly warm-up with Nigeria last Friday which
the Yugoslav team won 3-0.
	   Santrac had a large choice of strikers and Drobnjak lost his
place in competition with Predrag Mijatovic and Darko Kovacevic.
	   The Yugoslav team up front includes forwards Predrag Mijatovic,
Savo Milosevic, Darko Kovacevic, Perica Ognjenovic.
	   ___  
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ On Germany's team of oldies, whose
average age is over 30, one new face may have cracked the starting
lineup.
	   Defensive midfielder Jens Jeremies, the team's baby at 24,
turned in an outstanding performance in the European champion's 3-1
victory over Colombia Saturday.
	   ``Our best player was our youngster Jens,'' coach Berti Vogts
said. ``The way he worked for (offensive midfielders) Andreas
Moeller and Thomas Haessler, how he gave commands and stripped
players of the ball _ that impressed me a lot.''
	   Jeremies played for 1860 Munich last season and will transfer to
cross-town rival Bayern Munich next season.
	     MORE
</TEXT>
