<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Briefs, 1st Add,0459 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILAN, Italy: next season 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) _ Tunisian coach Henri Kasperczak Monday
announced his squad for the World Cup, including four
European-based players he hopes will give the team vital
international experience.
	   It will be the second time Tunisia has played in a World Cup,
coming 20 years after its debut in Argentina. Many observers say
the current squad is the most talented Tunisia has ever fielded.
	   Kasperczak, from Poland, chose four players from European
leagues: striker Adel Sellimi of Spanish second division team Jaen,
the Freiburg (Germany) duo of Zoubeir Beya and Mahdi Ben Slimane,
and France's Bastia goalkeeper Ali Bou Mnijel.
	   ___  
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Germany's players were ecstatic after
their convincing 3-1 win over Colombia Saturday, saying it revealed
the potential of their World Cup team.
	   ``We've very well prepared and we've got a good troop together _
now we want to prove it in France,'' said team captain Juergen
Klinsmann.
	   But Colombia coach Dario Gomez wasn't as happy with his players,
who seemed overwhelmed by Germany's pressure tactics. Within 16
minutes, the South Americans were down 2-0 on two Oliver Bierhoff
goals.
	   Before the match, Colombia's players chose to warm up in the
dressing rooms instead of on the field.
	   ``Germany unquestioningly has the potential to reach the
semifinals again _ but that showed how passive my players were,''
Gomez said.
	   ___  
	   ROME (AP) _ Angelo Peruzzi will be playing during the World Cup
_ playing a role in a TV ad, that is.
	   Italy's starting goalkeeper, out of France '98 with a calf
injury, is the star of an adverstisement for Gatorade. The spot is
centered on Peruzzi's thoughts before facing a penalty kick.
	   ``I am happy that my injury did not make them change their minds
about using the ad,'' said Peruzzi, who hurt himself while training
Sunday. ``It would have been a shame not to see the fruit of our
work.''
	   The ad will air for the first time Tuesday night, during Italy's
World Cup tuneup match at non-qualifier Sweden.
	   ___  
	   SAFTICA, Romania (AP) _ Romania's soccer team hopes to make it
into the semi-finals of this summer's World Cup in France, topping
its performance of four years ago, when it fell in the
quarter-finals.
	   ``We might qualify for semi-finals if we play well,'' said
Gheorghe Popescu, a key part of Romania's defense, who plays
professionally for Turkey's champion Galatasaray.
	   His teammate with Galatasaray, Gheorghe Hagi, known as ``the
Maradona of the Carpathians,'' said Romania's most difficult game
would be its first one, June 15 against Colombia.
</TEXT>
