<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-Quake,0604 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Aid trickles into quake-stricken Afghanistan 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: RECAPS previous
AP Photo ISL102
By PHIL GOODWIN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   FAISABAD, Afghanistan (AP) _ Aid organizations struggled to
deliver emergency supplies and treat injured survivors of an
earthquake in a remote region of northern Afghanistan that killed
at least 3,000 people and left thousands more homeless.
	   Landslides cut off roads to the hardest-hit areas, where 16
villages were destroyed, blocking aid trucks, Martin Griffiths,
U.N. deputy emergency relief coordinator, said Monday in New York.
	   ``This is a scenario from hell,'' Griffiths said. ``It's a
region which is extremely inaccessible.''
	   As aftershocks rumbled through the region Monday, frightened
residents scrambled out of the few homes still standing and refused
to go back inside.
	   The quake, which hit Saturday with a preliminary magnitude of
6.9, flattened entire villages, cracked mountains and unleashed
landslides across this rugged, remote region of struggling farmers.
Estimates of the dead ranged from 3,000 to 5,000.
	   Thousands more were missing or homeless. About 45,000 of the
area's 70,000 people have no shelter, Griffiths said.
	   The quake sent houses tumbling down mountainsides into the
valleys below. Up to 80 villages were estimated to be heavily
damaged, and another dozen obliterated.
	   In Chaujan, a village near the quake's epicenter, the scene was
horrific. Thousands of homes were gone. People wandered, dazed,
through the rubble.
	   In the middle of the devastation, a lone wooden door stood
erect, clumps of mud on it the only reminder of the home that once
stood. The family of four who lived there was dead.
	   Tending to the injured was a priority Monday. The International
Red Cross and the United Nations set up mobile medical units in
Shari Basurkh, 50 kilometers (30 miles) from Faisabad, the capital
of northern Badakhshan province.
	   Doctors Without Borders were operating a clinic there.
Helicopters ferried the wounded, many of them with broken bones,
most of them small children and the elderly.
	   Aid workers distributed blankets, tents and plastic sheeting.
	   Among the hardest-hit areas was Rostaq, the site of a Feb. 4
earthquake that killed as many as 2,300 people and left another
8,000 homeless.
	   Many residents were living in tents even before the quake,
having lost their homes in the February quake.
	   The region is in the control of an alliance fighting the Taliban
religious army, which holds the Afghan capital, Kabul. Anti-Taliban
soldiers say they have recovered 1,650 bodies, but added that
thousands more were dead.
	   Aid workers said people were traumatized, their eyes unfocused,
their hands automatically searching through the rubble. With poor
sanitation and recent rains, the risks of malaria, cholera and
hemorrhagic fever were rising as each day passed.
	   Many homes simply crumbled into dust in Saturday's violent
shaking, after being cracked by the February quake and pounded by
recent, relentless rains.
	   Cargo aircraft from neighboring Pakistan, packed with emergency
supplies, reached Faisabad on Monday. A U.N. disaster coordination
team was flying in Monday to help manage the aid operation.
	   France was sending about 35 tons of aid to Dushanbe, Tajikistan,
to be transported to the disaster area. Japan, the European Union,
and the Netherlands were also sending assistance.
	   ``The key here is to respond very, very quickly,'' Griffiths
said. ``The key thing we learned from the last time is to get air
transport in quickly.''
</TEXT>
