<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Child Labor,0504 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Child marchers breathe new life into old U.N. agency 
</HEADLINE>
By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ An exuberant group of children who have been
rescued from mines, sweatshops and servitude around the world
descended on Geneva Tuesday to breathe new life into an old U.N.
agency.
	   The children will be among the first speakers at the annual
meeting of the 174-nation International Labor Organization, which
is considering a new world convention aimed at abolishing the most
extreme forms of child labor.
	   The children, including a 15-year-old boy from Bangladesh who
lost a leg in a coal mine accident and an 11-year-old former
domestic servant from Nepal, are culminating a six-month campaign.
	   ``Go, go, global march,'' shouted the children Saturday as they
led more than 1,000 demonstrators through the streets of Geneva.
	   The campaign, sponsored by the ILO, the U.N. Children's Fund,
Scouts and other organizations, began last January in the
Philippines and has included marches in 62 countries in Asia,
Africa, North and South America and Europe.
	   Child labor tops the agenda of the annual two-week ILO meeting,
which brings together representatives of government, labor and
management. The ILO draws up and monitors conventions on a wide
range of labor issues.
	   The campaign against child labor was a boost for the ILO,
showing that the oldest U.N. agency stemming from the 1919 creation
of the former League of Nations is still needed to stop labor
abuses around the world.
	   The ILO has been singled out by the United States in its
campaign to reform the world organization. Some U.S. Republicans
have accused the ILO of being irrelevant.
	   Another visitor expected at the meeting was newly freed
Indonesian labor leader Muchtar Pakpahan, who was imprisoned from
1996 until last week on charges relating to civil unrest and
alleged subversion. Other speakers were to include U.N. human
rights chief Mary Robinson and Venezuelan President Rafael Caldera.
	   The meeting will work on a declaration committing countries to
work toward collective bargaining and the elimination of forced
labor. The new child labor convention would call for criminal
penalties, specify preventative measures and rehabilitation of
child victims, according to the organization.
	   The labor organization also has called for new international
legal standards on child labor that would halt slavery and
slavery-like practices, forced labor and debt bondage. The
standards also would prevent children being used in prostitution
and pornography or any activity likely to jeopardize their health
or morals.
	   ILO surveys have found that a quarter of all children ages 5-14
are economically active, with many of them doing hazardous jobs.
	   ``Children are employed simply because they are cheaper and more
compliant than adults,'' said Neal Kearney, general secretary of
the Brussels-based International Textile, Garment and Leather
Workers Federation.
</TEXT>
