<SLUG> BC-Australia-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Asian crisis fuels current account deficit, Aussie dollar slumps 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ The Asian currency crisis fueled a
massive U.S. dlrs 1.22 billion (2 billion Australian dollars) rise
in Australia's current account deficit in the first three months of
1998, the government said Tuesday.
	   While the figure was within the range of expectations, it is
edging closer to 6 percent of gross domestic product, a level that,
back in 1986, then-Treasurer Paul Keating said was indicative of a
``banana republic.''
	   The overall economic problems also undermined the Australian
dollar, which slumped to 61.15 U.S. cents, a 12-year low.
	   The slump in Asian prices for Australian products pushed the
current account deficit to a three-year high of U.S. dlrs 4.57
billion (7.5 billion Australian dollars), widening by 33 percent
since the December quarter, the Australian Bureau of Statistics
said.
	   Economists had predicted the blowout, blaming the Asian currency
crisis and struggling exports.
	   Net foreign debt rose to U.S. dlrs 137 billion (225 billion
Australian dollars), the Bureau said.
	   The All Ordinaries stock index lost 45 points, 1.6 percent of
its value, by midday Tuesday. 	   
</TEXT>
