<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Channel Tunnel </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Newspaper: Contracts to be signed for high-speed rail link to Channel Tunnel 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: RETRANSMIT to include slug
<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Contracts to build a 5.4 billion pound (dlrs 8.9
billion) high-speed rail link from London to the Channel Tunnel are
expected to be signed Tuesday, the Financial Times has reported.
	   The newspaper predicted Tuesday that Deputy Prime Minister John
Prescott would tell the House of Commons on Wednesday that his
search for new backers to rescue the troubled 68-mile
(110-kilometer) link has been successful.
	   A spokeswoman for Prescott's Department of Environment,
Transport and the Regions would not confirm the Financial Times
report.
	   ``The Deputy Prime Minister said he wanted to make an
announcement as soon as possible after the (Parliament) recess,''
said the spokeswoman, speaking on customary condition of anonymity.
``But I am not in a position to confirm any particular date at this
stage.''
	   London and Continental Railways Ltd., which won the contract to
build the link in February 1996, said in January that it was 1.2
billion pounds (dlrs 1.9 billion) short.
	   The government refused to provide the funds and said that unless
the money could be raised, the state would take over the project.
	   The government has already committed 1.8 billion pounds (dlrs
2.8 billion) to the link, which would carry trains at 300 kph (186
mph) through southeast England and is due for completion in 2003.
	   Currently, passengers who ride the Channel Tunnel trains from
Paris to London whiz at high speed through France, only to slow
down after they cross under the sea and amble along British
commuter tracks.
	   Under the reported deal, London  Continental Railways would
receive financial backing from rail infrastructure group Railtrack.
	   The Financial Times said the company would build the link in
stages, with Railtrack agreeing to buy the first phase _ from the
tunnel to Ebbsfleet in north Kent _ at a price reflecting
construction costs.
	   Railtrack would take an option over the later, more expensive
sections of the line into central London, the newspaper said.
	   (er)
</TEXT>
