<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Palestinians-Watchmen,0563 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Palestinian security firm patrols east Jerusalem 
</HEADLINE>
By IMAD MUSA
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ On their first night on the job, a team of
Palestinian security guards dressed in matching black jackets
bearing the company emblem _ the Dome of the Rock Mosque _ hit the
streets of east Jerusalem in search of trouble.
	   With crime on the upswing and no Palestinian police allowed in
the eastern sector of Jerusalem, a group of Arab residents decided
to take security into their own hands and turn a profit.
	   Abdul Razzaq Ghazzawi, co-owner of the newly founded Jerusalem
Security Services, and a former Israeli police officer said his
company could fill the niche. ``We will protect the property
here,'' he said.
	   In March, professional thieves broke into a bank by drilling
holes through three neighboring stores. And recently, robbers
managed to walk out of a building in the area's busiest street with
a giant safe.
	   The Israeli police, who have jurisdiction in the area are
investigating the crimes, but they maintain a small presence in
east Jerusalem and often do not receive the full cooperation of
Palestinians, distrustful of the Israelis who took over the area in
the 1967 Mideast war.
	   Israel annexed east Jerusalem shortly after the war, but the
Palestinians want it as the capital of a future state. Palestinian
leaders have for years been calling for a civilian Palestinian
police force.
	   Peace accords with Israel allowed Yasser Arafat's Palestinian
Authority to operate in all Palestinian cities, but prevented it
from working in Jerusalem and left the city's status open for
future negotiations.
	   The security company received verbal approval from Israeli
authorities to go ahead ``as long as it does not break the law or
establish relations with the Palestinian Authority,'' the company's
lawyer, Jawad Bulous, said.
	   That agreement is fine with the owners.
	   ``We will not get involved in politics. Already some of our
customers are afraid that the Israelis will close us down, and we
do not want that to happen,'' Ghazzawi said.
	   In the past, Israel has tried to prevent Palestinian security
forces connected to the Authority government from operating in
Jerusalem. Shmuel Ben Ruby, a spokesman for the Jerusalem police
said he was checking into the company's approvals.
	   The 25 young men of the security firm are armed with batons,
flashlights, stun guns and small mace canisters and only work at
night. Firearms were not provided however, ``to avoid any legal
wrangling with the Israeli police.''
	   On Monday, four guards rode on scooters past store fronts, while
others patrolled the unlit streets and winding stone alley ways on
foot. They received no formal training, but Ghazzawi said he gave
them two directives: Protect the stores and do not get involved in
police work.
	   The Palestinian Chamber of Commerce has already given the
company its blessing and sent out letters to over 1000 business in
east Jerusalem touting the new company's services.
	   Ali Tazziz, who chairs the chamber said it was Israel's
disregard of the traditionally Palestinian side of the city which
led to the need for the company.
	   ``The west side gets all the attention, protection and
services,'' Tazziz said. ``We were forced to do this because of
their neglect,'' he said.
</TEXT>
