<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar higher, stocks bounce back moderately in Tokyo 
</HEADLINE>
Eds: UPDATES with midday currency, stock and bond prices
<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar was higher in morning trading
Tuesday amid continuing pessimism about Japan's economy, though it
retreated from seven-year highs reached overnight in New York.
Tokyo stocks rose.
	   The dollar bought 139.53 yen in early trading, up 0.41 yen from
late Monday in Tokyo. In New York overnight, the dollar settled at
139.70 yen, its highest level since June 24, 1991.
	   The dollar has gained steadily in recent weeks against the yen
as sluggish consumer spending and the write-off of some 76 trillion
yen (dlrs 550 billion) in bad loans by the nation's banks cloud the
outlook for Japan's economy.
	   But the dollar ceded some of its gains in early Tokyo trading
amid a rising chorus of concern for the weakening yen by Japanese
finance officials.
	   Finance Minister Hikaru Matsunaga told reporters Tuesday the yen
is too weak and Japan will take decisive action to defend it. The
same day, Haruhiko Kuroda, head of the ministry's international
finance bureau, said the pace of the Japanese currency's decline is
too fast.
	   ``In any case, I have strong concern about an excessively weak
yen, and we will take appropriate and decisive action against it,''
Matsunaga said at a regular news conference.
	   On the stock market, sentiment improved slightly after Monday's
announcement that Nikko Securities Co., a major Japanese brokerage,
and Travelers Group of the United States were planning an equity
tie-up.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 120.58
points, or 0.79 percent, to 15,441.61 at the close of the morning
session. On Monday, the index had lost 349.75 points, or 2.23
percent.
	   ``The market welcomed Nikko's alliance, as it will likely
trigger more Japanese financial institutions' tie-ups with foreign
institutions,'' said Masaru Arai, general manager of the stock
division at Ryoko Securities.
	   Deepening worries over the state of Japan's economy had
triggered Monday's fall.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 9.33 points, or 0.78 percent, to 1,206.03. The
TOPIX fell 24.79 points, or 2.03 percent on Monday.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond fell to 1.130 percent from Monday's record low
finish of 1.155 percent, driving its price up to 112.59 yen from
112.41 yen. 	   
</TEXT>
