<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-France-Micromotoring,0652 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Forget gas guzzlers: kids, countryfolk drive lean and license-free 
</HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER BURNS
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   LES HERBIERS, France (AP) _ For landlocked countryfolk without
driver's licenses and chic Parisian teen-agers evading parental
chauffeuring, a tiny contraption has been a boon.
	   At first sight, it's cute as a bug and not much bigger. The
two-seat Microcar has to be to stay under the weight and speed
limits of a ``voiturette,'' or ``quadricycle.''
	   Owners don't seem to mind that it's like riding atop a
lawnmower. They like the legal loophole: you don't need a driver's
license.
	   Never mind that Americans are embracing gas guzzlers thanks to
rock-bottom prices at the pump. Europe's ``micro'' and larger
``mini'' car markets are benefiting from gasoline prices that can
top dlrs 1.10 a liter (dlrs 4 a gallon).
	   Microcar and eight other ``micro'' producers in France and Italy
expect to sell 25,000 units this year, up from about 16,000 last
year.
	   At the assembly plant in this village outside Nantes in western
France, lines of red, blue, gray and green Microcars hang from a
yellow overhead conveyor belt that cranks out about 30 a day.
	   A well-heeled subsidiary of the pleasure boating giant Jeanneau
_ bought out in 1995 by another yachting giant, Beneteau _ Microcar
glues together a featherweight body from nine pieces of reinforced
polyester, using parts from regular automakers. The cars are
limited to 350 kilograms (770 pounds).
	   The Yamaha diesel engine powers the car up to 43.5 kph (27 mph)
and uses 3.5 liters of gasoline per 100 kilometers (gets about 68
miles per gallon).
	   The micros aren't much cheaper than some of their slightly
larger competitors _ the minis like the Rover 100, Renault Twingo
and Fiat Cinquecento. Microcar's sticker price starts at about
50,000 francs (dlrs 8,300).
	   But the edge is, you don't need a license. Anyone 16 and over
can drive them.
	   ``I'm 16, and it's changed my life,'' says Emmanuelle Bousquet,
whose family lives in the upscale western Paris suburb of Boulogne.
``I don't have to depend on taxis, buses, the subway, my parents.''
	   With Mom and Dad's help, she's added electric windows and
leather upholstery to her trendy gray voiturette _ options Microcar
offers to attract the Gucci crowd.
	   Outside Orleans in the Loire Valley, Jacqueline Bourgeot has
been driving micros since 1984. As an epileptic, she can't get a
license.
	   ``I'm independent with this car. I'm not forced to wait for my
husband,'' said Bourgeot, 49, a nurse who works nights.
	   She doesn't deny her Microcar is a bit loud, ``but it makes less
noise than my Aixam and my Erade'' _ earlier versions of other
makes.
	   Microcar also makes a quiet electric version that looks like a
small beach buggy, and some hybrid models use electric and diesel
motors.
	   So far, European officials don't see micros as a road hazard.
They're already banned from freeways because they have to stay
under 45 kph (28 mph).
	   But it's anyone's guess how many owners may have lost their
licenses because of drunk driving or other offenses, and no
accident statistics are available.
	   Up to now, there's been no clamor to do away with the legal
loophole in France, Italy, Spain and a handful of other countries.
But Britain and the Netherlands are among those that require
licenses, and the European Union is studying how to standardize
regulations on licenses and safety.
	   The micros are part of the smaller-is-beautiful trend in
Europe's car market. Analysts expect Europe's overall subcompact
auto sales to rise more than 9 percent in 1998.
	   Of course, Emmanuelle dreams of her 18th birthday, when she
hopes to get a Volkswagen Golf. In the meantime, her parents can at
least be happy she's riding on four wheels.
	   ``A scooter is too dangerous for Paris,'' she says.
</TEXT>
