w1821  wstm-
r f     BC-FEA-US-PantyhosePanac     06-01 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-US-Pantyhose Panacea,0719 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
There may be help for harried hosiery users 
</HEADLINE>
AP Photo NY342
By LISA CORNWELL
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
	   AKRON, Ohio (AP) _ Suzanne Nesbit knows pantyhose problems.
	   Snags, runs, rips and tears _ always at the most inconvenient
times _ are always followed by the traditional quick fix with
smelly nail polish.
	   ``And when you do use nail polish ... it sticks to your leg and
you end up tearing off layers of skin when you try to take the hose
off,'' Nesbit said.
	   But Nesbit, a 36-year-old pharmacist who says she often snags
her hose on desk corners and other equipment at Akron General
Hospital, has found a new product that may be a boon to
long-suffering women.
	   RunFree Instant Hosiery Repair is an odor-free, colorless liquid
that comes in a small tube and is applied with a brush like nail
polish.
	   It was created by Robert Horning and Deborah Vollmer who are
betting that women are looking for better ways to patch their
stockings and cut down on their hosiery costs. Industry experts
believe it may be the first run-repair product of its kind.
	   Horning and Ms. Vollmer, both of Akron, were on a date at a
restaurant when she discovered she had a run in her stocking. She
borrowed some nail polish from a woman in the ladies room.
	   ``When I returned to the table, I told Bob I hoped the nail
polish odor wasn't too strong, and he wanted to know why I was
putting on nail polish in the middle of dinner,'' she said.
	   Horning said he couldn't believe there wasn't a product to
repair runs in women's hosiery. ``I guess, being a guy, I just
never had thought about it,'' Horning said.
	   They began brainstorming and decided they would give it a try.
After consulting with chemists and physicists and testing more than
400 compounds, RunFree was developed in 1994.
	   The next few years were spent working on packaging and
marketing, and in November 1997, RunFree went on the market,
retailing for dlrs 4.95 a bottle. A bottle will fix more than 60
runs and 100 snags.
	   The clear liquid has only slight scent for second or two when
first applied, then is odor-free. It can't be seen on hose the way
nail polish can, and doesn't become hard. It also seems to
withstand washings.
	   Ann Coburn, 65, likes it so much she ordered 15 tubes to give
out as party favors.
	   ``It's nice to have something you can use for quick repairs,
especially since you inevitably get runs and tears when you are
running late or on your way to something important,'' she said.
	   Susan Stromberg, manager of the Capezio Dance Theater Shop in
the Cleveland suburb of Lyndhurst, has sold about 30 bottles and is
on her second order.
	   ``I've sent samples to our stores in New York, Dallas and Boston
and it seems to be selling well if you bring it to customers'
attention,'' she said. ``We sell products for adult ballroom and
ballet dancers and for children in dance classes, and those
stockings and tights can be really expensive to replace, with some
costing as much as dlrs 23.''
	   Ms. Stromberg says her customers like RunFree because it can be
used before runs even start to reinforce toes and panty.
	   ``RunFree will outlive your pantyhose,'' she said. ``The threads
will eventually wear thin in other parts of the stockings before
the area with the run or snag treated with RunFree gives out.''
	   Sid Smith, president and chief executive officer of the National
Association of Hosiery Manufacturers, said women have tried a wide
range of techniques to extend the life of their stockings _ even
putting hosiery in the freezer with the hope that it will help
prevent runs.
	   But Smith knew of no other product aimed specifically at
patching runs. He said he hasn't taken a look at RunFree yet.
	   He did have an answer for the age-old question: Why can't
manufacturers make pantyhose that won't run?
	   ``Women would like pantyhose that don't run, but they also want
sheerness,'' said Smith. ``The strength of hosiery is directly
related to the size of the yarn, and the heavier yarn you use, the
less sheerness you are going to have.''
	   Smith said there is nothing on the horizon to suggest a no-run,
sheer pantyhose will be available in the near future.
	   And that, say the makers of RunFree, is what they are counting
on.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-FEA-US-Pantyhose Panacea; CT:f; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
