<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai inflation expected to fall by year's end, deputy premier says 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Thailand's soaring inflation rate is
likely to fall in the second half of the year and will be below IMF
targets by year's end, a deputy prime minister predicted.
	   Supachai Patichpakdi, who is also commerce minister, said in an
interview late Monday on the ITV television station that declining
inflation would allow high interest rates to fall as well.
	   ``That will benefit the entire economic system,'' Supachai said,
without giving any estimated figures.
	   High interest rates are crippling Thai businesses struggling to
survive the current recession, which the government said last week
will be far deeper and probably longer than previously expected.
	   The International Monetary Fund has demanded that Thailand keep
inflation at an average of 10.5 percent for the year as a condition
of receiving a dlrs 17.2 billion economic bailout package.
	   The economy has begun to stabilize under the administration of
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai, but new declines in the currency and
stock market this week on fears of a deeper recession underscored
how far the country still has to go.
	   The Commerce Ministry released data Monday that showed Thai
consumer prices rose 10.2 percent year-on-year in May, the worst
inflation in more than three years. It was the fifth consecutive
month this year that the index has risen.
	   Inflation has worsened steadily since July 1997, when Thailand
abandoned its fixed-exchange rate system under attacks by currency
speculators and triggered a chain reaction of crises across Asia.
</TEXT>
