r s     BC-Sports-Olympics-Sydne     06-01 0208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Olympics-Sydney-Homeless </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Premier rejects anti-loitering laws for Olympics 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ The state government has criticized a
push by Olympic mayors to clear the streets of hawkers, beggars and
loiterers before and during the 2000 Olympics.
	   The group of mayors representing Olympic areas has lodged a
submission for more powers to deal with loiterers with the state's
local government minister Ernie Page.
	   But New South Wales premier Bob Carr said ``unfortunates'' would
not be removed from Sydney streets just to create a good
impression.
	   ``Any idea that we behave like Hitler in 1936 by getting
unfortunate people off the streets to present a false image to the
world should not be embraced,'' Carr said Tuesday. ``It's not going
to be done as a special artificial, cosmetic measure for the
Olympics.''
	   Carr said it was wrong to make special loitering laws for the
games. Atlanta enacted such laws for the 1996 games.
	   ``I reject the notion that we ought to be doing anything special
in this respect for the Olympics,'' Carr said.
	   ``We ought to be meeting the problem of the homeless because
it's the good thing to do, not because it's related to the
Olympics.''
  (tjh)
</TEXT>
