r i     BC-Malaysia-Drought     06-01 0263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Drought </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Severe water rationing for parts of Kuala Lumpur 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Residents in large parts of the
Malaysian capital may get water only once every three days as a
severe draught forces authorities to consider drastic rationing, a
newspaper said Tuesday.
	   Rationing water may be the only way of stretching reserves that
have fallen sharply in the absence of rain, the Star newspaper said
quoting the Selangor Waterworks Department.
	   One major reservoir near Kuala Lumpur has only enough water to
supply city residents for another 10 days, the newspaper warned.
	   ``The dam level now is only 1.26 meters (4.1 feet) above the
critical level of 204.2 meters (673.8 feet),'' V. Subramaniam of
the department said. Below the critical level it is difficult to
pump water.
	   The dam that normally supplies 477 million liters a day to the
city was able to pump out only 191 million liters on Monday, the
daily said.
	   Three other dams that provide water to the city were also
depleted and pumping out far less water than usual.
	   Nearly two million or one-third of the population of Klang
Valley, as Kuala Lumpur and its suburbs are known, have been on
water rationing for three months.
	   Residents have to wait with pails, plastic containers, urns and
even bottles for water trucks to arrive.
	   The worst drought in decades is being blamed for the water
shortage in the city that depends mainly on rain-fed reservoirs.
But experts also say that indiscriminate logging has affected the
traditional rainfall in the area.
</TEXT>
