<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Currency </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan's finance minister hints of action to prop up yen 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's Finance Minister Hikaru Matsunaga expressed
``strong concern'' on Tuesday about the current level of the yen
against the U.S. dollar and warned Japan will take appropriate
action to stem its currency's fall.
	   Matsunaga declined to comment on what he sees as an appropriate
exchange rate for the American currency and the yen.
	   ``But in any case, I have strong concern about an excessively
weak yen, and we will take appropriate and decisive action against
it,'' Matsunaga told a regular news conference.
	   The dollar rose to its third straight seven-year high against
the yen in late New York overnight, trading at 139.70 yen. That's
its highest closing level since June 24, 1991, when it traded at
139.82 yen.
	   By late morning in Tokyo, Matsunaga's comments had helped push
the dollar back down to 139.53 yen.
	   While a stronger dollar makes Japan's exporters more competitive
by allowing them to cut prices overseas, it is also seen a vote of
no confidence in the Japanese economy. The dollar has gained in
recent sessions as investors sell yen to shift funds out of Japan's
moribund markets and into high-flying U.S. assets.
  (km-mef-dj)
</TEXT>
